<HEADLINE>
GRANT CALLS TRADE A BLESSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Horace Grant can't talk about his
relationship with Shaquille O'Neal without lapsing into hyperbole,
describing every chapter as either a mortal injury or a religious
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he feels that strongly about playing with the NBA's
greatest center.
</P>
<P>
   They were bosom-buddy Orlando Magic teammates for two seasons in
the mid-1990s, but a quick exit from the NBA Finals was followed by
O'Neal's exit from Florida. O'Neal defected to the Los Angeles
Lakers in 1996 and Grant took it hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like Lennox Lewis or Mike Tyson punched me in my
stomach,'' Grant recalled. ``I went home to Georgia and spent a
whole week there and thought about my life without Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   Four summers later, Grant is a Laker himself, courtesy of last
week's four-team blockbuster trade. Grant is thrilled with the
reunion and at age 35 just as thrilled to be in position to win a
championship alongside O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hope and pray, good things happen,'' Grant said
Wednesday, at a press conference at Lakers headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen,'' chimed in Greg Foster, who also came from Seattle to
the Lakers in the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, a lot of people were doing a lot of praying for this
deal _ from the players, to the Lakers brass who were desperate to
trade Glen Rice and acquire some big bodies, to O'Neal himself.
O'Neal has been clamoring for a physical power forward ever since
he arrived here and had openly lobbied for Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always had problems at the `four' spot. That will be no
more,'' O'Neal said in a separate interview. ``The nice thing about
Horace is, in Orlando when I played with Horace, when I wasn't in
position to get a rebound, most of the time he had it.''
</P>
<P>
   That, O'Neal said, will free him up to zip down the floor for a
fast-break outlet pass now and then _ ``That's an extra four to six
points on my average,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the 6-10, 245-pound Grant brings a physical
presence. He is a tough defender and rebounder who will relieve
some pressure from O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a big difference,'' O'Neal said. ``Me and Horace, we
played well together. Horace is very unselfish. Horace is one of
the greatest role players that I've played with. He doesn't worry
about scoring. He doesn't worry about a lot of stuff. But he knows
he's out there to defend and rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant averaged 7.8 rebounds last season, but that was as
Seattle's de facto (and undersized) center. He averaged nine
rebounds while playing alongside O'Neal in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won the championship last season despite using an
undersized power-forward tandem of A.C. Green and Robert Horry, but
there's no question where their Achilles' heel was located.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was on other teams, like Chicago and Orlando and
Seattle, you wanted to attack (the Lakers) at the power-forward
position,'' Grant said. ``Shaq is going to be Shaq. He just needed
a power forward to really sort of `get his back,' so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   These will be familiar surroundings for Grant, who also played
under coach Phil Jackson's staff for three championship seasons in
Chicago. Grant also was an Orlando teammate of guard Brian Shaw,
expected to re-sign with the team shortly.
</P>
<P>
   And his expectations are unabashedly high.
</P>
<P>
   ``My quote was, 'Size us up (for championship rings), because
we're going to be definitely hard to beat,' '' Grant said. ``I'm
looking for a few championships here.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no mistaking Foster's emotions, either. The former
UCLA Bruin (he transferred to UTEP after two seasons) called the
trade ``somewhat of a homecoming for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Foster's emotions once got him in trouble with the
Lakers. Two seasons ago, while playing for the Utah Jazz, he
enraged the Lakers with a now-infamous throat-slashing gesture,
drawing fire from O'Neal and an eventual payback takedown by Rick
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope there's no ill will,'' Foster said. ``It was just
all in fun for me. I'm an emotional-type player at times and I hope
I can bring that to this team also. It's all water under the bridge
as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two acquisitions in the trade, guard Emanual Davis and
forward Chuck Person, were not present. Davis is expected Monday
when the Lakers hold their annual media day. But Person is mulling
retirement, and with the Lakers deep at small forward, he's a long
shot to make the rotation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
