<HEADLINE>
CHAMPAGNE STILL ON ICE FOR YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Champagne will be flat by the time
the New York Yankees get around to clinching the American League
East. If they drag it out any longer, George Steinbrenner might
disgustedly tell his players to split a six-pack of beer.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' magic number remains frozen at one after the
last-place Tampa Bay Devil Rays crushed Denny Neagle and the
Yankees Wednesday night, 11-1 _ the Yankees' fifth loss by 10 or
more runs in the last two weeks, their third straight defeat and
their 11th in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost impossible for the Yankees to find a way to lose
the division race. They lead Toronto by 4 1/2 games and these are
all the things that would have to happen: The Red Sox and the Blue
Jays would have to win all of their remaining games, and the
Yankees would have to lose here Thursday, lose three in Baltimore
over the weekend, lose a makeup of a rainout against the Florida
Marlins on Monday and then lose an intradivision playoff game on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees have little chance to recoup the confidence they
built in August and early September, in taking 4 of 6 games from
Seattle and Oakland on a road trip and sweeping three games from
the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of the doubts that have grown over the last two
weeks _ about the bullpen, about an offense starved for hits, about
Neagle and his propensity for implosion _ are assured of carrying
over into the playoffs. And there is a strong chance that the
Yankees will open the postseason on the road, something they have
not done since 1981. At the moment their game concluded here
Wednesday night, the Yankees had the fourth-best record in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner lives in the Tampa area, and within the Yankees'
organization, it is widely accepted as fact that beating the Devil
Rays is only slightly less important than winning the World Series
and world peace. If there was one positive to be drawn from the
slump that began with a 3-2 loss to Toronto on Sept. 14, it was
that the Yankees were presented with the opportunity to come here
and obliterate the Devil Rays in Steinbrenner's neighborhood and
spray Champagne all over Tampa Bay property.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devil Rays edged the Yankees, 2-1, on Tuesday, and
Steinbrenner vacated his private box without stopping at the
clubhouse. He was here again Wednesday night to see Neagle, who
lasted three innings and took another giant stride in sabotaging
his chances of getting a serious contract offer from the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle, however, is only one symptom of a team malaise. The
Yankees want to know what it's like to win games again before the
playoffs start, but they are running out of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
