<HEADER>
A4506 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-TUBERCULOSIS-GRANT-SF     09-28 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUBERCULOSIS-GRANT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LIVERMORE LAB GETS GRANT TO FIGHT TB  &HT;     By BERNADETTE TANSEY 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory will receive a $4 million
research grant from the National Institutes of Health as part of a
drive to eradicate tuberculosis, the world's No. 1 infectious
disease threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Livermore lab is part of a consortium of 13 laboratories in
six nations awarded a total of $28 million to study the proteins
that help the tuberculosis bacterium invade cells, produce toxic
chemicals and hide from the human immune system. That information
will be provided free online to researchers and pharmaceutical
companies trying to design drugs to thwart the deadly infection,
which kills 2 million people a year.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the United States who are infected with the AIDS
virus actually die from complications of tuberculosis, which is
more dangerous to those with weakened immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year tuberculosis project will be coordinated by Los
Alamos National Laboratory, which will use genetic cloning
techniques to produce samples of 400 bacterial proteins for testing
by other labs.
</P>
<P>
   The $28 million grant is part of a larger $150 million
investment by the National Institutes of Health in seven pilot
studies that build on the discoveries of the government Human
Genome Project and other DNA sequencing research. Now that
scientists have uncovered the sequences of DNA that code for
proteins in human beings, bacteria and other life forms,
researchers can use that information to develop disease remedies
and other useful products.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory will receive $4 million
to determine the complex shapes of large tuberculosis proteins by
converting them into crystalline form and then using X-rays and
computer analysis to reveal their structure. Knowledge of the shape
of a protein helps medical researchers design drugs that bind to
the protein the way a key fits into a lock, allowing the drug to
block the protein from harming the body.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the University of California at Berkeley, also
part of the consortium, will receive $2 million during the
five-year program to study proteins used by tuberculosis bacteria
to copy and repair their DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other protein pilot studies funded by the National
Institutes of Health is a Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory
project to study bacteria that cause pneumonia and infections of
the human genital and respiratory tracts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
