A4507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-U.S.-CUBA-SANCTIONS-6     09-28 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CUBA-SANCTIONS-620&AMP;ADD--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL LEADERS APPROVE A DEAL TO ALLOW FOOD SALES TO CUBA
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House and Senate leadership Wednesday approved
a deal to allow the sale of U.S. food products to Cuba, clearing
the way for the most significant rollback of U.S. sanctions against
the island in four decades.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement on sales, which was brokered between farm-state
and anti-Castro lawmakers, was eagerly sought by U.S. farm groups
and first proposed this spring by Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash.
It would allow cash sales to Cuba and financing through third
countries but bar U.S. financing, lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   It would also add a new category to the designated groups of
Americans who are allowed to travel to Cuba, despite restrictions
on spending money there. U.S. exporters of grains and other food
products would be authorized to visit the island to promote sales,
just as scholars and journalists are currently allowed, the
lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement does not, however, allow for the sale of Cuban
products in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Washington first imposed a ban on trade with Cuba in 1962, after
the revolutionary government of President Fidel Castro appropriated
more than 6,000 U.S.-owned properties without paying compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo., brokered the deal between Nethercutt and
Rep. Jo Ann Emerson, R-Mo., on one hand, and Congress' two
Cuban-American lawmakers from Florida, Reps. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen
and Lincoln Diaz-Balart, both Republicans, on the other. Until now,
the two Cuban-Americans have opposed any easing of sanctions
against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Blunt, who said Republican leaders in Congress had approved the
deal, said in a telephone interview that it would open Cuban
markets to U.S. exporters of rice, pork and other staples. Cuba has
long sought to resume trade with the United States, arguing that
the trade embargo had forced it to pay a premium in shipping costs
from more distant nations. ``It provides a significant opening of
that market to U.S. agricultural products,'' Blunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations in recent weeks between the farm-state and the
anti-Castro lawmakers bogged down over the question of financing.
The Cuban-American lawmakers prevailed by ruling out U.S. credits
for the sales, but those favoring sales scored a victory by winning
an allowance for third-country financing.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba, which has been under an austerity program for a decade
since the breakup of the Soviet Union, its former patron, relies on
foreign banks for most of its imports.
</P>
<P>
   Once the new deal becomes law, it would in theory allow the
Havana government to turn to a Mexican bank, for example, to
finance a purchase. That bank would then notify a U.S. bank that a
transaction had been approved, and the U.S. bank would notify the
U.S. exporter to proceed with the sale, Blunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional sources close to the negotiations warned Wednesday
night that it could still fall apart, especially if pro-trade
Republican lawmakers, such as Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., object to
the restrictions against U.S. financing.
</P>
<P>
   But the drive toward greater openness with Cuba has been evident
in recent months, as lawmakers have steadily approved measures to
ease restrictions on trade and travel. The Clinton administration
has facilitated that effort, by approving visits throughout the
Midwest by Cuban diplomats and agricultural officials.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman did not immediately return a call for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The deal does not affect the sale of U.S. medicines to Cuba,
which is already authorized, provided that purchasers there can
demonstrate that the items are not misused or packaged for resale.
</P>
<P>
   The full House is expected to vote on the Cuba food bill as part
of a $75 billion agriculture funding bill next week, Blunt said,
with the Senate expected to follow later in the week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR;  &LR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The compromise was reached on Capitol Hill as eight prominent
Republicans released a joint statement calling for an end to the
embargo on food and medical sales to Cuba and a lifting of all
travel restrictions imposed on Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The group _ including Gov. George Ryan of Illinois, William P.
Clark, the national security adviser under President Reagan, and
Frank Carlucci, defense secretary in the Reagan administration _
said, ``Humanitarian trade should not be used for political
leverage.'' A lifting of sanctions would allow ``a flow of people,
commerce and ideas that would increase American influence,'' they
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement released through the Lexington Institute, a
conservative research group, the Republicans said the 1996
Helms-Burton Act, which tightened sanctions on Cuba had proved
ineffective. ``It has not brought political change,'' they said.
``It has not resolved property claims; it creates costly disputes
with major trading partners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
