<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETERSON-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARREST AT SHEA MAY PUT KILLER OF INFANT SON BACK IN JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., N.J., N.Y.)   By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYCKOFF, N.J. _ Since returning here in January after a prison
term for discarding the body of his newborn son in a motel trash
bin, Brian C. Peterson had compiled a spotless probation record.
But on Tuesday night, he and a friend from high school went to Shea
Stadium for a New York Mets game. Peterson left in handcuffs, his
eight months of good behavior tarnished and his future at risk.
</P>
<P>
   New York police say that Peterson's friend, Raymond Maniaci,
hurled a partly filled bottle at John Rocker, the outspoken relief
pitcher for the Atlanta Braves, as Rocker stood on the mound in the
eighth inning. The bottle landed about 10 feet from the pitcher,
and officers stationed near the first base box seats arrested
Maniaci. As they led him away, Peterson began interfering, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   A complaint filed Wednesday said that despite three warnings to
move away, Peterson followed the arresting officers and his friend
down a ramp and pushed through a cluster of fans, yelling, swearing
and flailing his arms, even as the officers arrested and tried to
handcuff him.
</P>
<P>
   Probation officials in Delaware _ where Peterson and his high
school sweetheart, Amy S. Grossberg, had pleaded guilty to
negligent manslaughter in the death of their newborn son there _
said Wednesday that Peterson's future would depend on the outcome
of the new case.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, 22, spent the night in a police lockup and was
arraigned Wednesday afternoon in Criminal Court in Queens on
charges of resisting arrest, disorderly conduct and harassment. He
said nothing as he appeared with his lawyer, Russell M. Gioiella,
before Judge Stephen Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the media reports are correct, I hope your client realizes
the stupidity of his actions,'' Knopf told Gioiella.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer responded, ``Nobody in Queens is more aware of the
stupidity of his actions than my client.'' After Peterson entered a
not-guilty plea, the judge ordered him to return for another
hearing on Oct. 10 and released him without bail.
</P>
<P>
   Maniaci, 22, of Wyckoff, who was a high school soccer teammate
of Peterson's, was charged with reckless endangerment, attempted
assault, harassment and disorderly conduct. Knopf also released him
without bail.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as reporters followed Peterson, and his mother, Barbara,
from the courthouse, Gioiella paused briefly and called the
incident ``very, very unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Welch, a spokeswoman for the Delaware Department of
Correction, which is supervising Peterson's two-year probation
term, said it was too early to determine what impact the arrest
would have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to date, he's not been a problem,'' Welch said. She said
Peterson was working, taking college courses and fulfilling a
requirement he serve 300 hours of community service by lecturing
teen-agers about his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``His record has been very good, and he's not broken any
rules,'' Welch said. She noted that before going to Shea Stadium,
Peterson had received permission from his probation officer to
travel outside New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   A conviction on the new charges could lead to revocation of his
probation or stiffer probation restrictions, Welch said. If he is
acquitted, he might avoid any change in his probation status, she
said. The ultimate decision will be made by Henry duPont Ridgely,
the Delaware judge who conducted pretrial proceedings against
Peterson and Grossberg, and in 1998 accepted their guilty pleas in
the death of their newborn son at a motel. The two were college
freshmen when the baby died.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson served 18 months of a two-year sentence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
