<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GOLDSCHMIDT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTHUR E. GOLDSCHMIDT, 90, U.N. ENVOY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Texas)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arthur E. Goldschmidt, a United Nations economist who became an
ambassador at the United Nations, died on Sept. 21 at a retirement
community in Haverford, Pa. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Goldschmidt was the U.S. representative at the U.N. Economic and
Social Council from 1967 to 1969 with the rank of ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Goldschmidt was born in San Antonio, grew up there and received
a bachelor's degree from Columbia University. He held government
posts in Washington and was chief of the Interior Department's
power division before going to work for the United Nations in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Elizabeth Wickenden; a
daughter, Ann Richardson of London; a son, Arthur Jr., of
University Park, Pa.; a brother, Walter, of Los Angeles; four
grandchildren and a great-grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
