<HEADER>
A4517 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHR     09-28 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH SCORES HITS IN SWING THROUGH CALIFORNIA  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush brought his campaign to
a South Central Los Angeles Catholic school Wednesday, buoyed by
rising poll numbers and looking ahead to next week's debate with
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP candidate scored some solid hits on his two-day
California swing. His appearance on ``Larry King Live'' with his
wife, Laura, gave him an extended chance to talk about his vision
for America. A Los Angeles Times editorial heaped praise on his
educational plan, while the paper's latest poll, released
Wednesday, showed him up by 6 points, 48 percent to 42 percent,
over Gore nationally.
</P>
<P>
   He also brought out big and enthusiastic crowds for fund-raising
events that brought in $1.4 million to the state Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   But even with all the good news, Bush ran into problems
Wednesday keeping his campaign's message on track.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself seemed to hint at the cause of the apparent
distraction when he ran into a fourth-grader Wednesday at Ascension
Catholic school and was asked if he had ever met Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to see him next Tuesday, when we have what's called
a debate,'' said Bush. ``I look forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming debate, widely viewed as a make-or-break event for
both candidates, at least partially overshadowed Bush's message
during the West Coast trip that ended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There were continuing stories about a pro-Gore ``mole'' who may
have infiltrated the Bush campaign and sent a debate preparation
video to the Democrats. Other stories dealt with the preparations
for the debates, even while Bush worked valiantly to stress
education and what he has called an ``education recession'' that he
believes has occurred under the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy and it didn't always work.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was scheduled Wednesday to highlight the efforts of
faith-based institutions to help kids and neighborhoods with a
visit to a Watts Catholic school _ which sits directly across the
street from Figueroa Elementary, the local public school.
</P>
<P>
   The venue could have made for a vivid explanation of why Bush
supports school vouchers, which he believes they could lend a
needed hand to low-income and minority parents, Latino and
African-American, struggling to provide kids a good education in
some of America's toughest neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the public school parents, many of them angry, stood on
the street because they weren't invited in to see the governor. A
group of Latino mothers, all with kids at the public school, said
they tended to like Bush and were curious about his voucher plan
for low-achieving schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the real poor. We can't afford the $300 a month
tuition'' at the Catholic school, said Irma Campos in Spanish.
``Ay, no, that's too much.'' And she added, ``If he wants to get
the Latino vote, he has to come where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids need books and materials,'' added Cecilia Serrano.
``And they need someone to watch over them ... why doesn't he come
over here to see us?''
</P>
<P>
   Inside Ascension school, where parents pay an average of $2,200
a year in tuition _ Bush talked up his recurring education themes:
the ``soft bigotry of low expectations'' and the need for
accountability and local control.
</P>
<P>
   He praised Catholic schools for their successes, saying he
appreciated the discipline and the policy of ``zero tolerance`` for
drugs and disruptions in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank you for allowing me to come to this little
haven of love,'' he told students.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has said he would be focusing on ``real people'' as he
campaigned, spoke only briefly to the invited crowd of about 50
parents, as a group of about two dozen students in plaid uniforms
sat behind him on the stage. He left without taking questions from
either the parents or the children.
</P>
<P>
   The governor occasionally jumbled words and phrases, shredding
his own message.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said America must provide teachers and principals ``with
strong tort reform legislation that protects our teachers from
doing what they need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about the formula for successful schools, he said,
``One of the common denominators I have found is that expectations
rise above that which is expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as some national reports suggested Bush will pull back from
the nation's most populous state _ where he lags by double digits
in recent polls _ the Texas governor repeatedly declared he will
win California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to win California. I am,'' Bush told Larry King on
Tuesday. ``I'm ... down in the polls (here), but who pays
attention, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Donors at an Atherton fund-raiser Tuesday were promised by state
campaign chair Gerry Parsky that when the debates are over, Bush
will return to California for more campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush lent little more than financial support to GOP hopefuls
in California. In his Bay Area appearances Tuesday, Bush gave
little more than a nod to Jim Cunneen, the GOP congressional
candidate facing a tough race against Democrat Mike Honda in the
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   And in Southern California, where Republicans face congressional
contests that could decide the balance of power in Congress, there
was no mention at all of other GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The governor now will head out to the crucial Midwest and then
hunker down in his home town of Austin to prepare for Tuesday's
debate in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
