<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MINI-MART'S BIG, NEW IDEAS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The world keeps getting better.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-Eleven people are giving a sneak preview Thursday of some
of their new products at the San Mateo County Expo (it's not too
late to phone in sick!).
</P>
<P>
   They call the event the University of 7-Eleven. Not to brag, but
I'm an alum, with a doctorate in cheese-like snacks.
</P>
<P>
   The new products include the Salad Gulp and the Fruit Gulp.
</P>
<P>
   Great products for what the kids call ``dashboard dining.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Salad and Fruit Gulps, I recommend you also
purchase the Dr. Henry Heimlich Ride-Along Robot ($14,000, but
watch for a ``two-fer'' sale), because I don't want to die in a
flaming car crash after being rear-ended by some guy trying to
dislodge a softball-size melon ball from his esophagus with a
chopstick that came with his 7-Eleven sushi (Raw Gulp).
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquitous mini-marts will also carry a new line of keen
teen jewelry, because studies show that a leading cause of teenage
depression is the lack of stuff to spend money on.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with all these great new goodies is that in
order to make room for them, other fine items must go. Some of the
traditional items that no longer will be stocked:
</P>
<P>
   _ Raccoon jerky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Janet Reno ``Back Off!'' mud flaps.
</P>
<P>
   _ Funyon snuff.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Widowmaker Lap-Scalder Cup o' Joe, known affectionately as
the Big Yelp.
</P>
<P>
   But some 7-Eleven traditions will remain intact. You can still
buy lottery tickets, using numbers based on the horoscope you
calculate right there at the checkout counter, especially if I'm in
line right behind you, late for work and trying to buy a quart of
malt liquor (Big Buzz) with the correct change.
</P>
<P>
   IN OTHER fake news, the 49ers have backed off their stand
against Terrell Owens' midfield celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Owens  &UR; will  &LR; be allowed to celebrate 49er touchdowns by running
to midfield and cavorting on the opposing team's logo. But he'll
have to do it in street clothes, and he'll have to buy his own
ticket to the game, and dodge security forces with dogs in order to
dash onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish him godspeed,'' one 49er official said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lacey says he hears that NFL fans have filed a
classless-action lawsuit against Owens.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Owens explained that what he was doing last Sunday in
Dallas was ``trying to provide my team with a positive spark.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Owens said that what he was doing was praying,
``thanking God for the ability that I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that changes things. Now we see that what Owens did was
the ultimate gesture of humility.
</P>
<P>
   CLIP THIS item and save it for when you can read it several
times. It is an explanation to policyholders in the Fremont
Compensation Insurance Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original insurer of this policy, Fremont Compensation
Insurance Company, no longer exists because it has been merged into
another insurance company member of the Fremont Compensation
Insurance Group, UNICARE Workers' Compensation Insurance Company,
also known as `UNICARE Insurance Company.' Immediately following
this merger, UNICARE's name was changed to Fremont Compensation
Insurance Company. Your workers' compensation insurance coverage is
now provided by Fremont Compensation Insurance Company, formerly
known `UNICARE Workers' Compensation Insurance Company', or
`UNICARE Insurance Company'.''
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up in the name-this-organization contest: Fremont
Unified Bureau of Ambulatory Rehabilitation (FUBAR).
</P>
<P>
   DESPERATE for reading material while riding a 27-Bryant Muni
bus, Robert Shepard picked up a Muni ``Destinations'' newsletter.
It was the August issue, a month behind, but at least it was August
of '00.
</P>
<P>
   One story told of the picturesque 29-Sunset line. ``It curls
between the Bayview/Hunter's Point community and 3Com Park, through
at least half The City's neighborhoods. ... It's like an old
European local train that wends its way through the marketplaces
and countryside.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would say a more appropriate comparison would be to the
Japanese Bullet Train.
</P>
<P>
   The 29 route wends through the S.F. State Campus, and
``Destinations'' writer Anita Hill writes: ``Sometimes the driver
hot-rods it around the campus and up Sunset Blvd. We're actually
happy when that occurs because it means we get home earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's fun to watch the pedestrians scatter like frightened
sheep on a European country lane.
</P>
<P>
   SEE THIS: ``Michael Jordan To the Max,'' the IMAX movie, now
playing at the San Jose Tech Museum.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a kid (or are a kid) who likes basketball, you have
to take him or her to this show. Dr. Naismith invented basketball
for Jordan, and Dr. Imax invented the monster movie screen for
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The nightly TV sports-highlight shows have trivialized the dunk,
but this is Jordan five stories high, dunking like Zeus. Even the
music is cool.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: Inspiring messages are presented.
</P>
<P>
   AN 87-YEAR-old S.F. woman fell. Her daughter couldn't lift her
up and so called 911, told the operator it was not an emergency but
she could use some help.
</P>
<P>
   An ambulance was dispatched, the woman was helped to her feet.
Then came the bill for $568, not covered by Medicare or Medi-Cal.
</P>
<P>
   So before you call, make sure it's an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Or send for my T-shirt: ``Help! I've fallen and I can't afford
to get up!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
