<SLUG> BC-MINNINGER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENNINGER CLINIC TO LEAVE TOPEKA FOR HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   TOPEKA _ In a blow to Kansas, the
Menninger Clinic announced plans Wednesday to move the
world-renowned mental health center to Houston to affiliate with
the Baylor College of Medicine and Methodist Health Care System.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Houston effort to attract the financially struggling
Menninger Clinic won out over the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center at Dallas and the University of Kansas Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mixed feelings, because we have a lot of roots here,''
said W. Walter Menninger, a psychiatrist and the Menninger Clinic's
president and chief executive officer, at an evening news
conference that followed a meeting by Menninger's board of
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we would not have chosen this to happen, we could not
continue to survive if we had continued to operate the same way in
the same setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Menninger, the third generation of his family to lead the
clinic, said the transition to Houston would be complete by 2002.
He said it was too early to say what would happen to Menninger's
242-acre Topeka campus, but he added that Menninger programs in the
Kansas City area probably would be phased out in four to six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger said the organization employed 1,162 persons _ 918 in
Topeka and 244 in the Kansas City area. About 50 are doctors. He
said that there would not be jobs for all the employees in Houston
but that it was too early to say how many would be offered jobs
there.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger disclosed few financial details of the relocation
agreement but said that Menninger, Baylor and Methodist together
would raise an endowment of more than $200 million to support joint
research, in addition to the existing Menninger endowment of about
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   A public-private consortium proposed an incentive package worth
as much as $100 million to persuade Menninger to stay in Kansas and
form a partnership with KU Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Donald F. Hagen, executive vice president of KU Medical Center,
said his institution would continue to press ahead with plans for a
neurosciences research center as part of a larger life sciences
development effort in the area ``and to fill any gaps that might
occur as a result of Menninger leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Building KU Medical Center's research programs in neurosciences
has long been a campus priority, and development of a neurosciences
institute has been under discussion by medical center officials for
more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed with the decision, but it doesn't lessen
our commitment to provide research, education and psychiatric care
for the people of Kansas,'' Hagen said. ``We thought Menninger was
such an important part of the history of Kansas, and we wanted them
to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas proposal included the establishment of a brain
research center near the medical center's Kansas City, Kan.,
campus, and possibly a freestanding mental health center. Gov. Bill
Graves had said he would ask legislators to increase the budget of
KU Medical Center to help create an alliance with Menninger.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Graves said he was saddened by the news but
appreciated the ``opportunity the Menninger board provided for
Kansas to develop and submit a proposal in hopes of maintaining
Menninger's presence in our state.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort to keep Menninger was mounted amid heightened
interest in life sciences research, propelled by the scheduled
opening of the Stowers Institute for Medical Research in Kansas
City around Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Baylor and Methodist calls for the three to
form an alliance to establish a national center for specialty
psychiatric services for the mentally ill and create a new brain
and behavior research center. The Menninger name will be
transferred to Houston, where Baylor and Methodist already have an
affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are enthusiastic and honored to form a partnership with the
highly acclaimed Menninger Clinic,'' Ralph D. Feigin, president and
chief executive officer of Baylor College of Medicine, said in a
news release.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision marks a turning point for Menninger,
founded in 1925 by C.F. Menninger and sons Will and Karl in a
Topeka-area farmhouse. It is still considered one of the nation's
top mental health centers, despite recent financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, tighter spending by managed-care companies and
government health programs, and new pharmaceutical treatments for
mental illness, have cut into longer, lucrative stays by patients
at mental health centers such as Menninger.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to remain financially viable, Menninger slashed
jobs, trained fewer psychiatrists, formed partnerships with care
providers to reach patients in their own communities and launched
research projects.
</P>
<P>
   But the financial losses have continued, and Menninger officials
said earlier this year that they were considering closing its
Topeka campus.
</P>
<P>
   John Leifer, a Kansas City area health-care consultant who has
done work for Menninger, said he was shocked by Menninger's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its roots run so deep in this community, and Menninger has
been working arduously to build a community psychiatric presence
within the Kansas City metroplex,'' Leifer said. ``I assume that
tremendous deliberation went into reaching this difficult decision,
and I'm saddened that Kansas will no longer be home to arguably the
greatest legacy in American psychiatry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
