<HEADER>
A4522 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-OPEC-SUMMIT-SFCRHON &LR;      09-28 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-SUMMIT-SFCRHON </SLUG>
  
 OIL LEADERS PRESS THEIR DEMANDS  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS _ Leaders of the world's top oil-producing nations
warned politely but firmly Wednesday that they intend to strike a
hard bargain in exchange for increased cooperation with the Western
countries that buy their crude.
</P>
<P>
   Heads of state and top officials of the 11-member Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries tried to allay the world's current
jitters over soaring oil prices, saying OPEC wants to help create a
system that sets ``fair'' prices, not high ones.
</P>
<P>
   But, in a remarkable display of unity, the leaders also made
clear that they sought a more equitable relationship with the more
powerful consuming nations. Speaker after speaker demanded that
Western countries reduce the taxes they levy on fuel, an issue that
prompted thousands of protesters to paralyze highways in Europe in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The summit's host, Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez, urged OPEC
leaders to not just stop there. Instead, he said, OPEC should use
its clout to pressure rich countries to give poorer nations more
favorable terms of financing and trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are asking for is justice,'' said Chavez, who has
built his political career on populist appeals.
</P>
<P>
   But the tone of the OPEC summit's opening day was generally
moderate, typified by Iranian President Mohammed Khatami, who said
the organization ``is willing to open a dialogue about finding a
reasonable price for crude and a mechanism to set it.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a sign that such a dialogue may indeed be emerging _
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin phoned Chavez Wednesday to
propose negotiations between the European Union and the oil
producers. The two agreed on the idea, but no date was set,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was plenty of resentment at the meeting over what
was described as the West's dominance of international trade.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez drew laughs from the assembled leaders when he compared
the $31 price for a barrel of oil with the per-barrel prices of
other internationally traded products: Coca-Cola, $78; shampoo,
$2,056; suntan lotion, $5,365.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let consuming nations blame us for high fuel
prices,'' Chavez said. ``We're victims of the unjust terms of
trade, in which we sell cheap and buy dear, yet get blamed for high
prices that aren't high.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has said he wants OPEC to step up pressure on consuming
countries, especially in Europe, to slash government taxes on fuel,
which account for as much as 75 percent of the cost to consumers in
some countries.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin's call for dialogue accompanies European governments'
growing nervousness about the domestic political costs of
high-priced fuel. His overture to Chavez suggests that he does not
want the issue to simmer until a scheduled meeting Nov. 18 in Saudi
Arabia between oil producers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The last meeting between consumers and producers was held two
years ago in Cape Town, South Africa, when oil prices were falling
toward their lowest level in 12 years, and consuming nations were
clearly in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, whose government has long taken a hard-line stand in
favor of keeping prices high, said OPEC will offer a quid pro quo:
production increases only in return for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are willing to raise production to keep prices stable, but
we are concerned about high taxes, and we ask for measures to
rectify this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also demanded concessions on environmental regulations, which
also add to the cost of gasoline, although he did not specify which
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah indicated that his nation, which has
close ties with the United States, will keep nudging fellow members
toward compromise, but he added that it too wants the world's most
powerful countries to address the problem of poverty in the Third
World.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been supporting dialogue, and we still support
dialogue, to reach comprehension and mutual effort,'' he said.
``(But it) should help end poverty and reach international
equilibrium for developing nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-isolated Iraq, which bears the greatest grudge against the
West, had its own demand.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan complained about the
U.S.-backed oil sanctions against his country, enforced by the
United Nations since the 1991 Gulf War. He indicated that Iraq will
insist that OPEC make lifting the sanctions a condition of any deal
on prices.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the spirit of the day, Yassin repeated some of the
other leaders' conciliatory rhetoric: ``If the embargo is lifted,
it will be conducive to reaching a long-term strategy that
guarantees oil producers fair prices while guaranteeing supplies to
consuming nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the leaders insisted that there is little
reason to increase the amount of oil they produce.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the United States starts releasing 30 million
barrels of oil from its strategic reserve, while OPEC will produce
an additional 800,000 barrels a day starting in October. Both
measures are expected to lower prices. ``I don't see why anybody
should worry,'' said Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   ``No deficit of crude exists,'' declared OPEC President Ali
Rodriguez. He said crude supply exceeds demand by 2 million barrels
a day _ and added that some European Union members are quietly
drawing from their own reserves.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to reveal which ones, saying, ``I know, but you have
to find out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
