<SLUG> BC-DOLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE INDUCTED INTO AGRICULTURE HALL OF HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   WASHINGTON _ Bob Dole was feted as an
American hero again Wednesday, this time right up there with Smokey
Bear.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture inducted the former senator
from Kansas, the bear and scientists George Washington Carver and
Hugh Hammond Bennett into its new Hall of Heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The waddling Smokey stole the show, but Dole seemed to expect no
less from the guardian of the nation's forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get Smokey to endorse me in 1996, and he wouldn't
do it,'' quipped Dole, a former Republican presidential nominee.
``That's probably why I lost.''
</P>
<P>
   One recent survey found that 98 percent of Americans over age 10
could identify Smokey by his picture, compared with 27 percent for
Dole, said Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   Dole had something going for him, though, said Glickman, another
former lawmaker from Kansas: ``Bob, you are the only one of these
inductees who is alive and who is not a bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Glickman got serious: ``Senator Dole was the author and or
principal co-sponsor of virtually every piece of farm legislation
passed by Congress in the past 35 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who has two Purple Hearts, a Bronze Star and the
Presidential Medal of Freedom, said being in the Hall of Heroes was
also a valued honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always loved the Department of Agriculture,'' Dole said.
``Agriculture is never partisan. We'd say, `You write this section,
and I'll write that section.' There is very little politics in
agriculture, so I'm proud to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Carver, a southwest Missouri native born into slavery in 1861,
was a teacher and scientist who developed industrial chemical
products from organic materials. Bennett crusaded for soil
conservation at the Department of Agriculture in the wake of the
Dust Bowl of the middle 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Smokey Bear was created as a cartoon character for the U.S.
Forest Service in 1944.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
