<HEADER>
A4531 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-GAMING-KAN &LR;      09-28 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMING-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Seven Station Casinos executives again ordered to testify  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ The chairman of the Missouri Gaming Commission has
ordered seven executives at the Las Vegas headquarters of Station
Casinos Inc. to appear and testify under oath at a special meeting
next month in Jefferson City.
</P>
<P>
   If they do not appear Oct. 10, Chairman L.G. Ullery said
Wednesday, the company's licenses to operate riverboat casinos in
Kansas City and St. Charles, Mo., may be in jeopardy when they
expire this winter _ or sooner.
</P>
<P>
   After noting the casinos' license expiration dates, Ullery said:
``This commission will shortly face the question of whether Station
Casino has proven by clear and convincing evidence its suitability
as to receive new excursion gambling boat licenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles German, Station's lawyer in Kansas City, said late
Wednesday that it hadn't been decided whether the seven executives
would appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission chairman's statement is something we will study
and that we take very seriously. We will respond to him before
October 10,'' German said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Station's Kansas City license expires Jan. 15, 2001,
and St. Charles on Dec. 27, Ullery also ordered commission
investigators to report at the commission's regular meeting later
in October on Station's general suitability to hold state gambling
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Ullery said that special staff report should emphasize ``the
institutional knowledge and control of Station Casinos' agents and
Station Casinos' ability to supervise activities of its agents.''
Under its rules, the commission can reopen a license hearing at any
time.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting Wednesday in Jefferson City, the commission also
proposed that Station Casino Kansas City be fined $50,000 for
displaying placards on its River King casino floor that advertised
incorrect payback percentages for a specific set of slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   A Station executive called the proposed fine ``excessive'' and
said he expected the company to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Station executives ordered to appear Oct. 10 refused to obey
commission subpoenas issued last month. The executives are Frank J.
Fertitta III, chairman and chief executive; Glenn C. Christenson,
executive vice president and chief financial officer; Scott
Nielson, executive vice president and general counsel; William W.
Warner, vice president of finance; Richard Haskins, associate
general counsel; John Pasqualotto, vice president of regulatory
compliance; and Marnie Hinrichs, executive secretary to Nielson.
</P>
<P>
   Warner is an investor in a spinoff company of Station insiders
proposing to buy the Kansas City and St. Charles casinos for $475
million.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's consideration of that sale is caught up in the
larger issue of license revocation and the escalating discord
between Station officials and state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted unanimously Aug. 31 to revoke Station's
Kansas City and St. Charles licenses for the seven executives'
refusal to honor subpoenas and testify under oath at a formal
inquiry that week in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   That inquiry centered on events surrounding the guilty plea in
federal court earlier this year of former Station outside counsel
Michael Lazaroff. The St. Louis lawyer admitted to multiple
felonies, including misappropriation of law firm funds that
included $500,000 in questionable bonus payments from Station.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaroff agreed to cooperate in the commission's investigation
while awaiting sentencing in exchange for leniency in his expected
27-month to 33-month prison sentence. Lazaroff is scheduled to be
sentenced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings were intended to reveal whether Lazaroff used bonus
money to improperly influence public officials on Station's behalf.
Instead, the commission's staff presented evidence that Lazaroff
spent all the money on himself.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry now appears to turn on Lazaroff's personal
relationship with former commission Chairman Robert L. Wolfson and
whether their prohibited private conversations over several years
gave Station an unfair advantage in winning its riverboat licenses
_ which Lazaroff testified it did.
</P>
<P>
   Station is expected to appeal the revocation decision and defend
itself at a public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is considering additional charges against Station
in connection with the Lazaroff-Wolfson relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Station said last month that it was refusing to participate in
what it termed an ``unfair, one-sided proceeding'' at which it
could not cross-examine witnesses. The company also has challenged
the commission's authority to issue subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed $50,000 fine against Station was approved by
commissioners Wednesday after staff investigators reported that the
company failed to ``honestly and fairly represent jackpot payouts
in its advertisements.''
</P>
<P>
   Station has 30 days to appeal the penalty or pay the fine.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, John F. Finamore, Station's Midwest
president, said the fine almost certainly would be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``$50,000 is extremely excessive,'' Finamore said. ``There was
no deliberate attempt by us to mislead the public. It was an honest
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Finamore said a bank of eight slot machines was replaced in May
with a set of 12 ``Eye of the Tiger'' $1 devices. But the roughly
20-inch square signs nearby promoting the payback rates of the old
slots were inadvertently left in place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just forgot those signs,'' he said. ``They were so small we
didn't even notice them.''
</P>
<P>
   The old machines paid back jackpots to players in excess of 97
percent of all coins played through them, and the sign advertised
that number.
</P>
<P>
   The linked-jackpot ``Tiger'' games, which are still in place,
pay 94.5 percent, plus an additional 2 percent to a pooled bonus
jackpot fund, Finamore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 0049EDT &QL; 
