<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4532 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-WINDFALL-OIL-SFCHRON(     09-28 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDFALL-OIL-SFCHRON(SIDEBAR </SLUG>
 TO OPEC)  
 CHAVEZ'S OIL WINDFALL  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS _ If money is power, Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez
suddenly has lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rise in oil prices, the government _ which
derives most of its revenues from Petroleos de Venezuela, the
state-owned oil company _ has seen its annual revenue increase by
$10 billion this year, a 60 percent jump over last year. Much of
the money is being put aside in a special ``stabilization fund'' _
essentially, a rainy-day fund for when oil prices fall.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Chavez announced his first major spending program.
The plan totals $2.1 billion, including $819 million for
infrastructure, $756 million for social programs, and the rest for
economic stimuli, technology and security. Only $84 million is to
be spent on the police and army.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chavez is a former army paratrooper and led a failed
military coup in 1992, he has surprised his critics and angered the
military officer corps by not increasing the budget for arms
purchases. Officials say little or nothing from the new package
will go to weapons spending.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the program will be administered by Plan Bolivar 2000, a
military-run social-service program that has won widespread public
praise. While officers resent being sent to supervise ditch-digging
and the like, ordinary Venezuelans are delighted by the program
because most believe the military is not corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez gained power because of public revulsion over decades of
graft, during which revenues from previous oil booms were stolen
and squandered.
</P>
<P>
   The worst damage occurred during the administrations of
Presidents Luis Herrera Campins, Jaime Lusinchi and Carlos Andres
Perez, which spanned 1974 to 1993. The losses during the period
were estimated last year by Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel at
$100 billion _ three times the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   The era was capped in 1994 by a crisis touched off by dishonest
bankers. Almost the entire private banking system had to be
nationalized, at a cost of $8.5 billion, the equivalent of
three-quarters of the federal budget. The bankers responsible
absconded with most of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of this history, Venezuelans will probably
love him forever if he can spend the proceeds of the current oil
boom honestly and efficiently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-STREISAND-CONCERT-REV     09-28 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREISAND-CONCERT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREISAND'S CONCERT A BIOGRAPHIC MUSICAL FAIRY TALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With STREISAND-CONCERT) 
(DUPLICATION WARING: The following story is also being sent with an
``e'' category code) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leave it to Barbra Streisand to turn her own life
into a musical fairy tale, one with a resoundingly happy ending.
That is the essence of the farewell show Streisand brought to
Madison Square Garden for two sold-out performances Wednesday and
Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   The personal story she tells in songs and anecdotes is a
variation on any number of myths in which a lonely, gifted child
who never knew her father dreams of finding and marrying a handsome
prince and living happily ever after. But before the blissful
fadeout into a heavenly sunset, she also becomes the queen of the
Hollywood dream factory with her spellbinding voice. That voice
lingers over the word ``love'' like no other. The ``l'' is
typically rolled voluptuously for an extra half beat, the ``o''
quivers with a tremulous anticipation, the ``v'' is soft and
inviting. Both the yearning for that love and its fulfillment are
built into the voice. Love of the most romantic kind is the magic
word that if you repeat it enough times can conjure up a romantic
savior.
</P>
<P>
   Streisand's show even includes a child version of herself (the
gifted young singer Lauren Frost) who is used to fine dramatic
effect playing the singer as an adolescent girl recording ``You'll
Never Know.'' Streisand eventually chimes in on the number, and the
two join voices on ``Something's Coming,'' the great
Bernstein-Sondheim ballad of romantic anticipation from ``West Side
Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the show, in the most effective of several video
sequences, Frost and Streisand rejoin voices with video images (two
live and one from the movie ``Yentl'') singing ``Papa Can You Hear
Me?'' The song is the touching musical climax to Streisand's
anecdote about being sent a love letter her father wrote to a woman
(not her mother) 60 years earlier when he was 19.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into possession of the letter, the singer said, made her
feel a mystical spiritual connection with him that helped her
through the rougher moments of making ``Yentl.''
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the show is a fairly straightforward career
retrospective that carries the singer from that early recording
session, to nightclubs, to Broadway, and finally to Hollywood and a
late-blooming fairy-tale romance and marriage to the actor James
Brolin. The closer it gets to the present, the more shamelessly
sentimental the show becomes. The love songs that accompany
Streisand's wedding and happily-ever-after pictures with Brolin are
pure greeting-card mush.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder is that Streisand's voice can make such sing-songy
romantic doggerel sound if not deep, at least deeply heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   What's most surprising about Streisand's show is that personal
happiness has lightened up her singing. She has always been better
in a relaxed, tender mode than in her steely stentorian one, In her
recordings, especially her more recent ones, Streisand's
perfectionist drive has tended to eradicate spontaneity in the
quest for an inhuman technical perfection. Again and again, the
singing conveyed a relaxed joy, a playful tenderness that rarely
makes it to Streisand's recordings nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many magical moments, some of the most memorable were
a wistful ``The Way We Were,'' a tender ``Something Wonderful,''
``Alfie,'' ``Send in the Clowns'' and ``Don't Like Goodbyes.''
Among misfires, only two seriously grated: The frantic disco hit
``The Main Event,'' and an awkward beyond-the-grave video duet with
Frank Sinatra on ``I've Got a Crush on You.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the concert reconfirmed Streisand's status as the
last (and possibly the greatest) true believer in the old romantic
myths that are vanishing from pop. She's living proof that
schoolgirl dreams really do come true, and happy endings aren't
just found in fairy tales. But if these are really her last
concerts, her happy ending is our loss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0023 </DOCNO>
