<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-CHAVEZ-PROFILE-SFCHRO     09-28 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAVEZ-PROFILE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA'S CHAVEZ MASTERMINDS AN OPEC COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  CARACAS _ The man who cavorted on the airport tarmac with his
honor guard, playfully ordering them here and there and cracking so
many jokes that they looked at each other in amazement, didn't seem
like the kind of figure who commands world attention.
<P>
   Yet there Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez was, breaking
red-carpet protocol at nearly every chance _ bounding up an
airplane stairway to give a bear hug to the emir of Qatar, kissing
Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, and kidding and flirting
with journalists who surrounded him at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's performance Tuesday as he welcomed leaders to the
summit meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
was typical of his strange magic.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, who almost single-handedly brought OPEC back from what
only a few years ago seemed like near-death status, is now trying
to make the organization a major world player again.
</P>
<P>
   In his frequent travels since he took office in February of last
year, Chavez has charmed and beguiled Middle Eastern sheiks, Wall
Street bankers and Cuba's Fidel Castro. When the occasion calls for
it, he can be serious and eloquent.
</P>
<P>
   But strangely enough, Chavez's informal shtick seems to work
well for the formal, often pompous circles of OPEC diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, for example, he phoned OPEC Secretary-General Rilwanu
Lukman, abruptly interrupting the Nigerian as he was giving a press
conference. Chavez _ who was holding his weekly call-in radio show
at the time _ put the startled official on the air live: ``OK,
Lukman, welcome to the country of Bolivar. We're glad you're
here,'' said Chavez in broken English, referring to independence
hero Simon Bolivar.
</P>
<P>
   Lukman paused, then grinned ear to ear, obviously tickled pink.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is unclear whether Chavez will succeed in keeping
OPEC unified. He has no real control over the group's underlying
divisions, rivalries and differences in national priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that Chavez has gotten away with what he has,''
said a Caracas-based diplomat, referring to OPEC's acquiescence in
his informal leadership role. ``He's riding high. But I wonder how
long it will last.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's current diplomatic success seems unreal after his
checkered past.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, after the then-army colonel led a failed coup against
the government, he was imprisoned and his career appeared to be
over. But his populist appeal _ based largely on his vow to stamp
out the flagrant corruption that plagued Venezuela for 30 years _
touched a nerve in the impoverished public, and the government was
forced to release him after two years.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's radical harangues against what he called the country's
``rancid oligarchy'' propelled him to power in the 1999 elections
and again in May.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in effect, a bloodless revolution. The leading political
parties, widely loathed for their tolerance of graft and cronyism
among the elite, have been virtually wiped off the map, while the
Congress, Supreme Court and constitution have been overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   Among the middle and upper classes, though, there is widespread
anti-Chavez sentiment. The wealthy, who are almost entirely white,
often look askance at the president's humble origins and dark,
mixed-race features.
</P>
<P>
   He has also irritated former colleagues in the military by
insisting that the institution participate in his popular Plan
Bolivar 2000 poverty-fighting program. This has saddled soldiers
with such unfamiliar tasks as repainting schools, cleaning
drainpipes and operating low-cost ``popular markets'' in poor
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's foreign-policy views often seem like echoes of Third
World anti-Americanism from an earlier era.
</P>
<P>
   He withdrew the Venezuelan military from regional naval
exercises in the Caribbean and refused to allow U.S. planes
monitoring drug trafficking to fly in Venezuelan airspace. He has
harshly criticized Washington's $1.3 billion aid program for
neighboring Colombia's war against leftist rebels and drug dealers,
saying it may lead to ``the Vietnamization of the entire Amazon
region,'' and he has expressed sympathy for the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Chavez defied Washington and world opinion in general
by becoming the first head of state to visit Iraq's Saddam Hussein
since the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   And he clearly sees Castro as a mentor, declaring last year that
Venezuela and Cuba are swimming together ``toward the same sea of
happiness and of real social justice and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Chavez, who calls himself a ``revolutionary,'' a new Castro
in the making?
</P>
<P>
   Rumors and accusations abound _ arms shipments to the Colombian
rebels, the infiltration of hundreds of Cuban security agents into
Venezuela _ but U.S. diplomats say they have found no proof yet.
The Clinton administration, in fact, has treated Chavez with
patience _ a far cry from bygone days when deviations from U.S.
policy lines drew bellicose responses from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There is more than a little in Chavez of the priest his mother
wanted him to become _ although he never rose higher than altar
boy, and his own dream was to be a U.S. major league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   He has a preacher's gift for oratory, and his speeches are
sprinkled with biblical references _ despite the fact that he once
told an interviewer he was ``not familiar with Christian doctrine,
nor do I practice it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most ordinary Venezuelans seem to find little to object to in
the comparisons Chavez often draws between himself and Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord sent him to us,'' said Emma Duran, a Caracas resident
who the president comforted recently after her slum dwelling was
partially destroyed by flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez hugged and kissed the 68-year-old widow and, after
speaking with her for several minutes despite being late for an
appointment, ordered his military aides to deal with the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the president's energy that it sometimes seems as if he
intends to solve the problems of the poor one-by-one and by
himself.
</P>
<P>
   It is a technique dismissed by critics as unsustainable
micro-management, and it is clearly no substitute for efficient
state institutions. Emma Duran's house still leaks, despite the
efforts of the construction gang sent by the president's men.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubting the impact Chavez has on the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez talks to people in their own language,'' said Teodoro
Petkoff, a former planning minister and editor of the opposition
newspaper TalCual. ``Politicians here stopped talking to people
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle Foreign Service correspondent Phil Gunson contributed
to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
