<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYWRES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDNER'S GOLDEN MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Growing up in Afton, Wyo., Rulon Gardner
wrestled eight siblings, heads of cattle and small-town
stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew his obscure background would provide the perfect
training ground to dethrone the most colossal of Greco-Roman
wrestlers?
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, 29, became the first man in 13 years to beat three-time
Olympic champion Aleksandr Karelin of Russia, in the heavyweight
gold-medal match Wednesday at the Sydney Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
   Karelin felt his grip loosen on his astounding streak in the
second period when, while battling for an advantageous position, he
broke his hold on Gardner, who was promptly awarded one point. That
would be the only score of the consequential match.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner's 1-0 win contrasted sharply with the result the only
other time the two wrestlers squared off. At the 1997 World
Championships, Karelin won 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   In six years of competing internationally, Gardner never had
notched an international title. He picked a heck of a stage for his
global breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up on a farm,'' Gardner said. ``As a kid, I could
barely pick up a bale of hay. By the time my senior year in high
school came around, I was grabbing four bales of hay at a time. I
always learned that when you work, you go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't actually think I could beat (Karelin), but I was
going to work as hard as I could. I just tried to push on him like
I push cows,'' Gardner added. ``I knew if he got a point on me,
he'd win the match. When I wrestled him the first time, in 1997, he
threw me on my head three times.''
</P>
<P>
   In Olympic competition, Karelin handled most of his opponents
like rag dolls. In 1988, Rangel Gerovski was the only one of
Karelin's five opponents to go the distance. Karelin came from
three points down in the final 30 seconds to beat Gerovski for the
gold medal 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1992 Summer Games, only one of Karelin's opponents
managed to last the full five minutes against him. Karelin needed a
total of 5 minutes, 32 seconds to pin the other four.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later in Atlanta, Karelin scored a one-point takedown
less than two minutes into his gold-medal match against American
Matt Ghaffari, repelling Ghaffari's best moves for the remainder of
the match and the ensuing overtime to become the first Olympic
wrestler to win the same division three times.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gardner has a streak to wrestle with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from a small town, I'm not used to this big-time stuff,''
Gardner said. ``It was incredible standing on the (victory) podium.
I won the gold medal, but I know nobody in wrestling will ever
forget (Karelin). He's a legend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
