A4560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-ROMANIAN-GYMNAST-     09-28 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ROMANIAN-GYMNAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARBITRATORS REJECT APPEAL BY ROMANIAN GYMNAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Less than a week after the charismatic
Romanian Andreea Raducan won the prestigious Olympic all-around
gold medal with a style some compared to Nadia Comaneci, she was
stripped of her medal on Tuesday after testing positive for a
banned drug.
</P>
<P>
   A Romanian team doctor administered the drug stimulant
pseudoephedrine to the 16-year-old Raducan in the form of a cold
medicine. Dr. Ioachin Oana was held responsible and expelled from
the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Raducan is the first gymnast to be stripped of a medal because
of a drug violation. She is the second athlete at these Games to
lose a gold, and it was the sixth positive drug case at the Sydney
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team physician should be able to read a bloody label on a
package,'' said Dick Pound, vice president of the International
Olympic Committee and head of the IOC's World Anti-Doping Agency.
``It was reckless on the part of the physician. His athlete tested
positive; and because of it, her medal was withdrawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Raducan, the first Romanian to win the gold in the all-around
since Comaneci, was allowed to keep the gold she won as a part of
the team competition and also the silver medal she won in the
vault. But with Raducan's disqualification, the Romanian sweep of
the all-around medals came to an end. The Romanian Simona Amanar
claims the gold in the individual all-around competition, and her
teammate, Maria Olaru, moves up from bronze to silver. Liu Xuan of
China, who placed fourth, is the bronze medalist.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement issued on Tuesday by the IOC's
executive board, the presence of the banned substance was detected
in the A urine sample. The Romanian delegation was informed of the
results on Monday, and they requested a B sample be tested. The
results were the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this case is completely irrelevant,'' Ion Tiriac,
the president of the Romanian National Olympic Committee, told The
Associated Press. ``The athlete is the best gymnast in the world at
this time _ she has proved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Raducan was part of a mighty Romanian gymnastics team. On
Thursday night, she stood atop her coach's shoulders and smiled
brightly after her dominating performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of them,'' said Bela Karolyi, the U.S. team
coordinator, who laid the groundwork for the Romanian program. ``I
feel good about what has happened to their program.''
</P>
<P>
   Raducan has been the sparkling ornament on the Romanian program.
She has steadily risen through the factory-like system in Romania
and become one of the elite gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Russian Svetlana Khorkina _ who was one of the
favorites for the gold, but saw that chance ruined by an error in
the vault measurement _ Raducan revealed herself to be the template
for the gymnastic pixie. At 4 feet 10 inches, and only 82 pounds,
she is the perfect size to impress the judges. She is also better
equipped to adjust on the fly. But now, after a team physician
administered Nurofen, an over-the-counter cold medicine with the
banned drug, Raducan has been stripped of her glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the physician is a moron, he should know what he is
giving an athlete,'' Pound said. ``If there is a presence of a
banned drug, he should be able to realize that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
