<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PLAYOFFS AGAIN, SO JOHNSON SET FOR FATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tonight might be the last time manager Davey
Johnson puts on the home uniform of the Dodgers, but he insists he
holds no ill will about how the process has gone down.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he understands when a payroll is $98 million, up
nearly 20 percent from 1999, and the team doesn't win, somebody
must fall. After all, pitching coach Charlie Hough met the same
fate last season when the Dodgers didn't live up to expectations
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have the payroll we have here and you don't win,
there's no question someone's going to take the brunt of it,'' said
Johnson, in his second season with the Dodgers. ``We just weren't
as good as the Giants. Basically, their starters pitched better
than our starters. Their starters are (23) games over .500. Their
offense generated more runs than ours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to win, you don't have any areas of weakness.
That's why you win. I think I have as much experience managing the
clubs that win divisions and get in postseason play as anybody in
baseball, and I think I would recognize a championship club and
what it takes to be a championship club.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club was actually overvalued last year, because I think
of the money spent. There were definitely deficiencies (in the)
bullpen and flexibility. We had a lot of injuries (this season) and
our starters, all five of them, have never been consistent at one
time. That's the difference in winning and losing, a championship
club.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the Dodgers' inability to get consistent,
even mediocre, outings from their fourth and fifth starters. That
part of the starting rotation was 10-25 with a 6.38 ERA heading
into Wednesday. That weighed heavily in the Dodgers' starting
pitchers going a combined 52-49 with a 4.33 ERA. By contrast, the
division-winning Giants saw their starters go 68-45 with a 4.35
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also didn't have a true leadoff hitter for four
months, had no dependable lefty in the bullpen and are the
second-worst fielding team in the major leagues with 135 errors.
But the pitching was the biggest thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some disastrous results, four and five,'' Johnson said.
``Not only those games, but there was an overriding effect in other
games because of what it did to my bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   But disappointment this season was set up by the terrible 1999
in which everyone associated with the Dodgers, from the moment
Kevin Brown signed a $105 million deal, talked about them competing
for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of money was spent and expectations go with a high
payroll, regardless of whether all the pieces are there or not,''
Johnson said. ``That's just part of it. Were we a championship club
last year? No. Were we better than our (77-85) record? I don't know
that either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we played pretty good this year? I think we've played
pretty good this year. I think it's been an improvement, a lot of
steps in the right direction. Could we have done more? Yeah, I'd
like to have done more. A lot of times we were restricted by
contracts, by personnel, lack of depth, lack of minor-league
support.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Tommy due in: Dodgers senior vice president Tommy Lasorda,
fresh off leading the United States baseball team to its first gold
medal, is expected to be at Dodger Stadium for tonight's home
finale. Lasorda and the team were due to arrive at LAX this
morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
