<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYTV-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER PRIME OPPORTUNITY MISSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How cool would that have been?
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Cuba baseball gold-medal game live at 1 in the morning
here, creating a buzz as the East Coasters woke up to see what some
have overzealously compared to the ``Miracle On Ice'' from 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   We could have even handled Tommy Lasorda's overexuberance, kinda
like the rooster's crow to start the day.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't have spoiled it for prime-time viewers later
Wednesday, right?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but that's where NBC compounded its blunder in its coverage
of what could be the Games' biggest event so far. It picked the
middle of the day Wednesday to show it on MSNBC. True, it got the
best uninterrupted time chunk, but so much for getting the most
eyeballs glued to the TV to America's so-called pastime.
</P>
<P>
   As for NBC's prime-untimeliness coverage, it didn't come until
past 9:30 p.m., when Lasorda went into the studio for an interview
with Bob Costas. At which point, when it aired here, Lasorda was
already on a plane heading home.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ratings roundup: Anchored by the mind-numbing fluff of the
gymnastics champions' gala exhibition and some really obese guys
lifting weights on an offday for track and field, Tuesday's
prime-time ratings stumbled in at 12.4 and a 21 share, the smallest
of the 12 days during NBC's coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The network spin, of course, was that it was 80 percent better
than the network's season-to-date Tuesday average of 7.5 with
``Frasier,'' ``Just Shoot Me,'' and ``Dateline NBC,'' while it
crushed that night's competition from Fox (4.4/7), CBS (4.8/8) and
ABC (7.8/13).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NBC has also figured out a way to manipulate and
boost ratings without messing with the overproduced programming.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has instructed Nielsen research to not include ratings on
the 7- to-7:30 p.m. portion of each night's telecast, which has
been about 40 percent lower than the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC spokesperson confirmed the move and said national
advertisements were moved to later in the broadcast. NBC has been
doing this nifty little trick the last five nights.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the overall 12-night rating of 14.6 (with a 25
share) is well under the 16.1 guaranteed to advertisers, 36 percent
off from Atlanta in '96 (22.7/43), and 19 percent off Barcelona in
'92 (18.1/34) and Seoul in '88 (18.0/32).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4566 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NAPSTER-INFLUENCE-SFC     09-28 1557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-INFLUENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NAPSTER MAY HAVE STARTED SOMETHING NO COURT RULING CAN STOP  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In Ian Clarke's view, it won't matter whether
Napster lives or dies in its big courtroom showdown next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is already filled with Napster-style programs,
including one Clarke wrote called Freenet. Each accomplishes the
same digital share-and-swap functions as Napster, yet won't be as
easy to slap down with a civil court summons.
</P>
<P>
   A host of new companies inspired by the wildfire success of
Napster are popping up with business plans that not only promise
legal uses of ``peer-to-peer'' file sharing, but could make the
technology even more widespread than Napster could ever accomplish
on its own.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, companies like Lightshare Inc. and Flycode _
started by two of Napster's original investors _ hope to take file
sharing far beyond free downloadable music. The technology could be
used to easily find company sales reports and expense forms, or
sell San Francisco Giants tickets, used motorcycles or even fully
licensed copies of Metallica songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peer-to-peer (technology) is gaining legitimacy aside from
being just a piracy tool, which was the very-early-2000 point of
view,'' said Clarke, 23, a computer programmer in London who has
just started his own company called Uprizer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of linking millions of decentralized computers to share
information rapidly could be the most powerful ``democratic
publishing model'' ever seen, said Doug Ross, chief technology
officer of BadBlue Corp., a Cincinnati peer-to-peer software
company that will launch Thursday. ``There's nothing you can do
about the free flow of information.''
</P>
<P>
   An unstoppable people's revolution was far from Northeastern
University student Shawn Fanning's mind when he wrote the Napster
program during January 1999. He simply wanted an easy way to share
digital MP3 music files with his friends, and named his creation
after the nickname he picked up after getting a short, nappy
haircut.
</P>
<P>
   The program soon begat a company, Napster Inc., which originally
set up shop in San Mateo, Calif., and is now based in Redwood City.
And with lightning speed, Napster became what company employees
have called an ``accidental empire'' of about 28 million registered
users, one of the fastest-growing software applications ever
unleashed.
</P>
<P>
   The Napster program enables music fans to connect their
computers via the Internet on a one-to-one basis. With millions of
computers, that peer-to-peer network forms a huge database of songs
not possible with a central computer server. Napster also became
popular because the program is easy to use and can find virtually
any song quickly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Copyright Lawsuit
</P>
<P>
   But the world's biggest record labels, which own the copyrights
to the majority of those songs, sued Napster on grounds that the
program serves only to promote illegal music piracy.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a U.S. District Court judge in San Francisco agreed,
slapping a preliminary injunction on Napster and ordering it to
halt the swapping of copyright songs. Two days later, however, the
U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco issued a stay of the
injunction, and a three-judge Appeals Court panel will hear oral
arguments in the case Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If Napster loses the case, it could be forced to shut down. A
similar suit by the Motion Picture Association of America could
eventually shut down a Beverly Hills company called Scour, which
created a similar program that enables users to find and share
digital music and movie files.
</P>
<P>
   But shutting down similar programs like Gnutella and Freenet
would be difficult because, unlike Napster or Scour, they do not
depend on any one company or central computer server to function.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who argue that new limits should be placed on copyright
law may get their way in the courts as intellectual property
holders push their cases,'' media analyst Malcolm Maclachlan said
in a recent report. ``Meanwhile, new peer-to-peer programs may make
any copyright law irrelevant by making them impossible to
enforce.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, there are dozens of freely distributed programs
available for download from the Internet with names like HackSter,
MyNapster, INapster, BeNapster, Macster, Gnapster, Snap, WebNap,
Gnotella and MyGnut. None, however, comes close to having the
number of users Napster claims.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Decentralized Network
</P>
<P>
   One of the most intriguing is Freenet, which provides a more
pure form of peer-to-peer computing than Napster. Clarke wrote the
program while earning a degree in computer science and artificial
intelligence from the University of Edinburgh in Scotland in 1999
and released it onto the Internet as an open-source program.
</P>
<P>
   A computer with the Freenet program installed becomes a ``node''
in a network connected by the Internet to other ``nodes.'' So
someone using Freenet to search for a particular MP3 music file has
one node contacting other nodes until that file is found and
anonymously relayed back to the originating computer. And each node
contacted learns where that file is stored, so subsequent searches
become easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's interesting about this technology is the fact that you
can design a system that does not have centralized controls and
that is scalable and efficient,'' Clarke said. ``And each time it
forwards information, it learns more.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarke said he didn't write Freenet to trade music or movie
files, but as a way to protect intellectual freedom on the
Internet. He wanted a way to disseminate information, whether it is
about controversial political views, alternative religions and
lifestyles, or whistle-blowing data on companies, even within
countries where governments censor such thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freenet is politically motivated as a tool to allow free,
anonymous speech,'' Clarke said. ``Ultimately, my aim is to make
censorship impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Freenet is a beta program that has been downloaded by
300,000 people. Clarke said it is intentionally designed to be
difficult for the average consumer to use because it is still a
beta, but there are programmers who are close to making it as easy
as the Netscape or Internet Explorer Web browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Freenet is already being touted as a way for people to keep
trading digital music files if Napster is shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, Freenet might start to play a significant role
when Napster is shut down because there is no legal remedy,''
Clarke said. ``We don't own Freenet, and we don't control it. I
don't even control it. Even if I was held personally liable for
so-called crimes due to Freenet it would not affect Freenet.''
</P>
<P>
   Free speech aside, Clarke is also moving into the world of free
enterprise. He has just incorporated a Los Angeles company called
Uprizer Inc. that is trying to steer clear of the sticky issues
surrounding digital copyrights, yet apply the Freenet technology to
corporate Intranet or wireless networks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the underground, power-to-the people mantra of Freenet,
Clarke describes Uprizer as a company with a very standard business
mission of being an ``application service provider,'' or ASP, that
helps companies easily share work documents and other files among
its employees or departments.
</P>
<P>
   BadBlue'sRoss said his company is also an ASP, with a
shrink-wrapped corporate software product, scheduled to premiere
during the fourth quarter of this year, that helps find documents
like expense forms and sales reports within a company. Eventually,
though, BadBlue hopes its peer-to-peer technology ``makes every
machine into a Web server.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said Napster's success with music leads to the question,
``What if every machine were a Web server?'' As for the legal
implications, ``we'll let the attorneys figure that out,'' he said.
``Our business model is we're moving digital bits around. They can
only legislate so much.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
P2P Commerce
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Kwan, chief executive officer and founder of Lightshare
Inc., said his Mountain View company is another ASP looking to a
day when peer-to-peer technology is used to buy and sell both
digital and physical goods, sort of a Napster-ized version of EBay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to make money without having to have a Web site or
a large server,'' Kwan said.
</P>
<P>
   Lightshare's business plan is to become the clearinghouse for
transactions set up by a Napster-style network. As an example, Kwan
said customers could search the entire network for Giants baseball
tickets, locate the best deal and arrange the sale, with Lightshare
providing the mechanism for the money exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Software, research papers, even CDs can be sold the same way,
Kwan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to transform this whole peer-to-peer concept, which
has gotten a bad rap,'' Kwan said.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is a proliferation of computers using peer-to-peer
programs, that will also make swapping of free digital files like
music and movies and e-books even easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were just Napster, I think the Recording Industry
Association of America would have a good chance of shutting it
down,'' Clarke said. ``Now there's a proliferation of Napster-like
systems that can't theoretically be shut down one by one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at bevangelista(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
