<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXODUS-WEBHOST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EXODUS COMMUNICATIONS PURSUING HOSTING BUSINESS  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Exodus Communications Inc. in Santa Clara,
Calif., which bid for Global Crossing Ltd.'s Web hosting business
in Sunnyvale two months ago, reportedly was negotiating furiously
Wednesday night to revive the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones News reported Wednesday that Exodus is in ``advanced
discussions'' to buy the GlobalCenter business for $6.5 billion and
said both boards were scheduled to consider the deal Wednesday
night. Unnamed sources told Bloomber News that a pact could be
announced as early as today.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company returned phone calls seeking comment. But
analysts said the deal could help Exodus meet its aggressive
expansion targets and bolster its position as one of the largest
Web hosting companies. Exodus, which has data centers around the
world, helps companies manage large Web sites and link them to the
Internet backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Adams Harkness &AMP; Hill analyst Alex Arnold said Exodus would be
giving up as much as 30 percent of its stock to grow by 20 percent.
But Arnold said the deal makes sense because it would enable Exodus
to grow far faster than it would on its own and give it access to
new customers and services.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said Exodus' data centers cover about 2.5 million square
feet, and it hopes to expand that to 3.9 million by year end. A
deal with Global Crossing would quickly give Exodus an additional
500,000 square feet _ putting it closer to its goal. ``This is an
interesting way of getting there,'' Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   Exodus reportedly lost out when WorldCom Inc. acquired another
Web hosting firm, Digex Inc., three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also benefits Global Crossing, which acquired its Web
hosting business as part of a $10 billion purchase of Frontier
Communications. It has already sold off its local phone service for
$3.6 billion. Should Global Crossing sell its Web hosting business
for $6.5 billion, it would essentially be allowed to get back its
entire purchase price for Frontier and keep teh long-distance
business and data networking for free.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the deal could also include a commitment from
Exodus to use Global Crossing's telecommunications network to carry
its data traffic _ a pledge worth $4 billion. The firms are also
considering pooling their efforts in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the deal wasn't final as of Wednesday afternoon. Word
of similar negotiations leaked out in July, only to be called off
over a dispute about the price.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the news sent investors scurrying to trade their shares
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Exodus plunged $2.75 to $53.25 during regular trading and
tumbled an additional $2.25 during after-hours trading on concerns
the price was too high and could dilute earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Global Crossings jumped $1.88 to $29.88 during
regular trading and rose an additional $1 during extended trading.
Both stocks were among the most actively traded during after-hours
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Both firms have a raft of competitors, ranging from other Web
hosting firms like Verio Inc. _ which typically manage other firm's
Web sites on their computers _ to companies like Equinix in Redwood
City, which runs ``telecom hotels,'' where Web site operators and
hosting companies can easily link to the Internet. Equinix's data
centers cover about 500,000 square feet, about the size of
GlobalCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Equinix chief executive Peter Van Camp said the recent deals
underscore the ``opportunity in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Exodus deal under discussion also outlines the
differences in their strategies. While Equinix is setting up data
centers around the country to give other firms a place to easily
offer their services and interconnect, Exodus prefers to offer
one-stop shopping for a wide suite of services to put companies
online.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag  &LR; Chronicle news services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at twallack(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
