<SLUG> BC-MTVI-LAYOFFS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV'S INTERNET UNIT CUTS STAFF, SETS ASIDE PLANS FOR
SPIN-OFF,  IPO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Attempting to cut costs in the increasingly
cutthroat dot-com market, MTV's Internet branch will lay off 25
percent of its staff, including some workers in San Francisco, the
company said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   MTVi also shelved plans for a spin-off and initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   More than one-third of the 105 layoffs will come as a result of
consolidating the music news divisions of MTV.com, VH1.com,
Sonicnet.com and Country.com, a spokesman said. As a result, the
four Web sites will share content.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to have four people reviewing the same album.
It just doesn't make sense,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   MTVi said the move is simply a shortcut to profitability and
does not reflect a change in strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The company this year expects to double last year's $20 million
in revenue, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet music analyst Stacey Herron suggested that the
company is following the industry trend away from content, where
profits have been elusive.
</P>
<P>
   MTVi may provide more interactivity and fewer articles on its
site, Herron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're evaluating how people are interacting with their site.
Are they smart to do this? Yes,'' Herron said.
</P>
<P>
   MTVi was formed in July 1999 when MTV bought San Francisco's
Sonicnet and merged it with MTV.com and VH1.com. The New York
company maintains Sonicnet's offices as its San Francisco branch,
where it employs about 60 people. MTVi would not disclose how many
San Francisco employees will be laid off. The local office will
remain open, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   MTVi, a unit of Viacom, filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission in February to sell 10 percent of its stock to the
public. But an unfavorable IPO market scotched that plan, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the online music entertainment space, Wall
Street is not looking at it as favorably as they were a year ago,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet spin-offs of large media companies have not fared
well. NBC Internet's stock has fallen from an IPO price of $76 to
close Wednesday at $7 a share, and the company laid off 20 percent
of its staff last month. Disney spin-off Go.com has fallen from
$35.44 on IPO day to Wednesday's $10.50.
</P>
<P>
   MTVi parent Viacom closed at $56.56 Wednesday, down 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
