<HEADER>
A4571 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA-FOST-SFCHRON &LR;      09-28 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-FOST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA BYTES: IMAGINE MEDIA'S BRITISH STOCK OPTIONS BETTER THAN
NO  OPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As Brisbane, Calif.'s Imagine Media has tried to
attract journalists to work for its magazines, one key competitive
edge is that it can offer options in a stock that's publicly traded
while many other magazines can't.
</P>
<P>
   But those options have turned out to be, in the words of one
employee, ``hollow gift boxes,'' because of a serious lag between
the time employees decide to sell and the time the stock is
actually sold.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Imagine _ which publishes such magazines as
Business 2.0, MacAddict and PC Gamer _ is owned by a British
company, the Future Network.
</P>
<P>
   With stock in the Future Network trading on the London Stock
Exchange, it can take several days to cash in options _ and in some
cases, it has even taken a month.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot can happen in a month.
</P>
<P>
   During the past month, for instance, Future's stock price
dropped from 7.4 pounds on Aug. 29 to 6.55 pounds Tuesday. Putting
that into U.S. dollars, that's a drop from $10.76 to $9.57 _ or a
one-month decline of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   From its high of 9.26 pounds (or $13.52) on Feb. 25, the stock
price is off 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident this summer, one journalist at the company
apparently suffered a paper loss of about $5,000, according to
employees. The worker was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, employees at TheStreet.com can exercise their
options and sell the stock all in one day, according to a company
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine's management is addressing the problem, but it will
still take at least several days to execute any stock sale,
according to the company's new president, former Times Mirror
executive Nancy O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does take a longer time with the London Stock Exchange than
it would on the Nasdaq,'' O'Neill said, citing ``longer settlement
times.'' ``They operate on different terms. The broker needs a
certain number of days to be able to effect the trade. ... We still
think this is reasonable, though.''
</P>
<P>
   From now on, once employees place their order, they will get
their money in 15 days, O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said some of the earlier problems had several causes.
Some of those were internal problems at Future Network and have
been fixed, either administratively or by patching up the software.
</P>
<P>
   Others were ``issues with our broker that were one-time
issues,'' O'Neill said. The brokers ``now understand how much
importance we place on this and how we want to make sure our
employees can exercise options in a timely manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The employees I spoke to did not want to be identified but said
that the issue has been raised in a virtual ``suggestion box'' on
the company's intranet. O'Neill said she has not had a chance to
alert employees to the changes but would soon.
</P>
<P>
   Employees have noted that Imagine's founder, Chris Anderson, has
used the stock options as a recruiting tool. Business 2.0, for
instance, competes for talent with magazines like Wired, the
Industry Standard, Fast Company, Upside and Red Herring _ none of
which are publicly traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me,'' one employee said, ``is that Imagine and
Anderson have said to employees that we have nice stock options.
Granted, at my level it's not a huge amount anyway, and I don't
think any of us are talking much about the stock or glaring at the
ticker symbol on our screens in anticipation of making the first
$20 million, but I think management has been selling us some hollow
gift boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said the irony was not lost on management.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly a value of ours,'' she said. ``We want people to
be able to share in the success of the enterprise. This is
something you try to do for employees to be an unusual benefit. You
don't want there to be a drag on it.''
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S IN THE NEWS: MarketWatch.com is in the News _ the New York
Daily News Express, that is. The Express is a free afternoon paper
that the News premiered earlier this month, and San Francisco's
MarketWatch.com is providing most of the business section coverage.
</P>
<P>
   MarketWatch Chief Executive Officer Larry Kramer has experience
with afternoon papers: He was once the executive editor of the San
Francisco Examiner. ``I'm back,'' he said last week, sitting on one
of the gaudy yellow leather chairs in his office. ``I can't believe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   MarketWatch doesn't get any money for its stories, but Kramer
says it's a great deal because it takes little extra work and it
gives the company promotion _ both by putting MarketWatch.com
bylines on the stories and by getting ads in the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   ``My board had said, `Promise us you won't go into print,'''
Kramer said. ``But this kind of print, there's no downside.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW NOT TO CRASH A PARTY: Salon.com is throwing a big bash
Thursday night at San Francisco's Yerba Buena Center for the Arts,
with Comedy Central's Ben Stein moderating a panel discussion
called ``From Degas to Dot-com.'' Actress Tracey Ullman, movie
critic Roger Ebert, comic-book artist Stan Lee, director Mike
Figgis, rocker Jerry Harrison and entrepreneur Brenda Laurel will
have a real-life salon on the fusion of art and technology.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 750 people have RSVPd. CEO Michael O'Donnell is worried
that even more will try to crash but he figures they won't be too
hard to stop. ``We found Web sites that tell you how to
successfully crash the parties,'' he said. ``The No. 1 way is to
tell them you're a venture capitalist.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell added his own tip: ``We said, `Tell them you're a
venture capitalist who's into content.' Then you're really not
believable.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I thought the era of big dot-com parties was over, but
O'Donnell said Salon found a way around that, too. He said Lexus, a
big sponsor on Salon's Web site, is footing the bill. (He wouldn't
say how much the party cost.)
</P>
<P>
   STAYING PUT: Employees at my old paper, the Marin Independent
Journal in Marin County, Calif., were sure the paper was being sold
recently when the publisher and advertising director left on the
same day.
</P>
<P>
   The paper was indeed sold, by Gannett Co. to ANG Newspapers. But
the ad boss, Marty Rubino, has had a change in circumstances, and
he is no longer moving. He was going to run the ad department at
the Fang-owned San Francisco Examiner, but now he is going to stick
with the IJ.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Dan Fost at dfost(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
