<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-RECRUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. CITY POLICE DEPT. RELAXES REQUIREMENTS FOR RECRUTIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Faced with a dwindling number of applicants for the
city's Police Academy, the Police Department relaxed its
eligibility requirements on Wednesday to allow younger recruits to
join the department and to admit more officers without two years of
college study.
</P>
<P>
   Under the changes, which Police Commissioner Bernard B. Kerik
said would take effect immediately, the department will accept
21-year-old applicants. For the last five years, the department set
22 as the minimum age, in the belief that officers younger than
that were more likely to become disciplinary problems during their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik also said the department would waive a requirement that
recruits have 60 college credits for two more categories of
applicants. The department already waives the requirement for those
with two or more years of honorable military service. Now the
education requirement will be waived for any of the city's 5,200
traffic enforcement and school safety agents who have at least two
years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new initiative is a creative way to enlarge our pool of
qualified applicants and attract city residents to a career in the
NYPD,'' Kerik said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were the department's clearest acknowledgment to
date of its struggle to find recruits for the 40,000-member force.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 31,000 people applied to take the department's
admission test. In 1999, fewer than half that number applied, and
this year the department has had to extend its application
deadlines to find even several thousand people willing to take the
test. Kerik said on Wednesday that the Oct. 6 deadline would be
extended to Oct. 27 to allow more people to apply. To date,
slightly more than 2,000 people have applied, police officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police and union officials have cited multiple problems in the
department's effort to attract new members, including the strong
private-sector economy and the relatively low starting pay _
roughly $31,500 _ for rookie officers, as well as the public outcry
surrounding several fatal shootings by the police of unarmed black
men.
</P>
<P>
   The problems have been severe enough to have become evident at
the Police Academy. The next class of recruits, set to begin
instruction on Friday, is roughly 300 short of its 1,589 planned
members, the first time in memory that the department has been
unable to meet its budgeted class size.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who appeared at a news conference with
Mr. Kerik to announce the changes, said the extension of the
education waiver to school safety and traffic agents would not
affect the quality of the applicants because these agents had been
monitored during their years of city employment. Kerik said that by
loosening the eligibility requirements for these employees, the
department gains a pool of 1,300 potential applicants, many of whom
are members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the changes run counter to some of the department's
previous thinking, and certainly to its public posture to date.
Since last year, when the drop in public interest in city police
careers became apparent, the department had steadfastly maintained
that it did not have a hiring problem, and said its stepped-up
recruiting efforts, including two $10 million advertising campaigns
since the spring of 1999, were aimed more at diversifying the ranks
than maintaining the department's size.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
