<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOBE-HIRING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ADOBE SYSTEMS PLANS TO ADD 1,000 WORKERS  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Spurred by growing demand for its software,
Adobe Systems unveiled plans Wednesday to expand its San Jose,
Calif., headquarters and hire 1,000 more employees.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, the largest manufacturer of software for online
publishing and graphic design, will add 250 workers each quarter
for the next year to meet the demand for products such as Acrobat
Reader, Photoshop and PageMaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expanding rapidly,'' said Kristin Fabos, a spokeswoman
for Adobe. ``The company is doing incredibly well. We need more
room to accommodate our new employees.''
</P>
<P>
   The hirings will increase Adobe's workforce by 40 percent to
3,500 from 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new jobs, ranging from marketing to engineering to
research and development, will be at the firm's downtown San Jose
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the growth, Adobe plans to add a third tower and
a parking garage to its campus.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the 17-story building, which will feature
hanging walkways to nearby towers, an employee cafe and large
sixth-floor patio, is scheduled to begin in spring 2001 and take
about 18 months to complete.
</P>
<P>
   The company also plans to expand its offices in Seattle, San
Diego, India and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe has prospered recently with increasing demand for its
software that has been fueled by the expansion of the Internet and
desktop publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has recorded five consecutive quarters of record
revenue, driving its stock up nearly threefold in the past year.
Wednesday, Adobe's stock closed down $2.94 at $148.38.
</P>
<P>
   The company earlier this month said it will split shares 2 for 1
in October. The firm also predicted 25 percent revenue growth for
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe is the world's third-biggest software manufacturer for
personal computers behind Microsoft and Novell. It has annual
revenues of more than $1 billion, the biggest part of which come
from sales of its photo editing software.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe's announcement Wednesday underscores its emergence from a
slump in the late 1990s, when the firm laid off 600 workers to
offset poor sales in Asia and to focus more on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It also fended off an unsolicited bid by Quark, a privately
owned softwaremaker in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Verne Kopytoff at vkopytoff(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
