 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: OLD COMPUTERS CAN BE DONATED  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The san Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I have upgraded my PC a couple of times and would like to donate
usable old parts to a good cause. What can you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Unfortunately, there isn't much call for components such as
small hard-disk drives and slow processors, which are the items
most often replaced during an upgrade. You would have a better
chance finding a home for a complete used PC.
</P>
<P>
   But even then, it would have to be Windows 95-capable for it to
be really useful to a school or nonprofit.
</P>
<P>
   Most metropolitan areas have a handful of organizations that
``recycle'' old PCs by sprucing them up and giving them away.
</P>
<P>
   You might try offering your old parts to one of those groups.
</P>
<P>
   And you can always donate them to Goodwill or the Salvation
Army, both of which renovate old computers and put them back into
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Lose the Lists
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm having no luck getting rid of the drop-down lists in a
couple of search engines that I use regularly. I went to the
options in Internet Explorer and cleared the History. That emptied
the drop-down list in the IE Address bar. But it didn't affect the
search engines. I still see a list of recent searches every time I
place my mouse pointer in the search box and hit the down arrow. Is
there any way to get rid of these lists?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Sure. Search engines use Internet Explorer's AutoComplete
feature to provide drop-down lists of searches you've previously
made. Specifically, they use the Forms aspect of AutoComplete.
That's the same technology that makes it easier to fill in online
forms by prompting you with names, addresses and other information
you've used in the past.
</P>
<P>
   To empty a drop-down list in a search engine, go to Internet
Options in the IE tools menu. Tab over to Content, click
AutoComplete and then choose Clear Forms. That should do the job.
If you never want to see a drop-down list in a search engine again,
remove the checkmark from the Forms Box.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind, though, that deleting the Forms history or
disabling the AutoComplete Forms function will affect all online
forms, not just the search engines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
More File Storage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I am trying to copy a 2.5-megabyte file to a floppy disk, but I
get a message that the file is too large. How much can you fit on a
floppy, anyway, and is there another way to save big files outside
of the computer?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: The capacity of a floppy is 1.44 MBs. Depending on what's in
your 2.5 MB file, you might be able to compress it with a Zip
program enough to fit it onto a floppy. (If you don't already have
a zipping software, you might try WinZip, a $29 program that you
can download from www.hotfiles.com or www.shareware.com.)
</P>
<P>
   If you have a lot of large files that you want to store, you
might consider getting an Iomega Zip drive. The newest models let
you store as much as 250 MBs on a single cartridge. Expect to pay
around $170 for the drive and about $20 per cartridge.
</P>
<P>
   You can also store files online through Web sites such as
www.driveway.com and www.idrive.com. I-Drive lets you store 50 megs
of PC files online for free.
</P>
<P>
   HACKER UPDATE: After I suggested that hacking PCs through a DSL
is rare, I got a flood of mail from folks who have installed
security software and claim that it shows a continual barrage by
outside computers looking for ways to access their systems. One guy
said he runs three different firewall programs ``and you would not
believe the high number of intrusion detection alarms I get all day
long from all three.'' Another person wanted to know if someone he
suspects of trying to tap his phone line could find a way to
monitor his online activity.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, nobody offered evidence of an actual hack attack
in which information in the PC was stolen or the system damaged. If
anyone has any stories of actual attacks, please send them along.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, if you want to keep your guard up, you can try
the personal firewall software from Norton or McAfee that I
mentioned last week (Norton Personal Firewall from Symantec Corp.
for about $50 and McAfee Personal Firewall, $30). Two other
programs that readers rave about are Black Ice Defender ($39.95
from www.networkice.com) and ZoneAlarm ($19.95 from
www.zonelabs.com). Safe surfing, you all.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK: Want to access a Web site without using your
mouse? In Internet Explorer, hold down the Alt key and press D.
Your cursor will jump right into the Address bar, where you can
enter a Web site's address. In America Online, press Ctrl + K, then
type the address into the Keyword box. In both cases, hit Enter to
go to the site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Einstein at computers(AT)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
