 SONY CAN'T DELIVER NUMBER OF PLAYSTATIONS IT PROMISED  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Only half as many PlayStation 2 video-game
consoles as expected will be available in North America for the
Oct. 26 launch date, Sony Corp. said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage will make PlayStation 2 this holiday season's
most-hyped toy, predicted Joe Funk, editor in chief of Electronic
Gamers Monthly magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see them selling for $500 on EBay,'' Funk
said. PlayStation 2 is to retail for $299.
</P>
<P>
   Sony will provide only 500,000 units to retail stores Oct. 26,
instead of the 1 million originally promised, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Unspecified component shortages have put production one month
behind schedule, the company said. Senior Vice President Andrew
House would say only that the missing components were not for the
console's DVD player.
</P>
<P>
   Sony plans to increase its production and release an additional
100,000 units every week after the launch, with a goal of shipping
1.3 million PlayStation 2s to North American stores by year end.
The company's previous target of shipping 3 million consoles for
the U.S. market by the March 2001 end of its fiscal year will not
be affected, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   PlayStation 2 was already expected to be in short supply this
holiday season. Retailers nationwide maintain customer waiting
lists for the game machine, and most stopped taking orders during
the summer, said Funk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more highly anticipated than any video game system
that's ever launched,'' Funk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think everyone who wants one will get one,'' said Sony
Senior Vice President Jack Tretton. ``The situation will improve
after the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   The supply reduction will be meted out evenly throughout U.S.
stores, Tretton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony also said that 25 or 26 game titles will be available for
the Oct. 26 launch, and 24 additional games will be released by the
holidays. Originally, Sony expected only 15 games to be released by
the launch.
</P>
<P>
   Funk said that having 50 games within a few months of launch is
unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that it will only make the people who didn't make
the list (to buy the console) even more bummed out,'' Funk said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby(AT)sfchronicle.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
