<SLUG> BC-MP3-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REVIEW: NOMAD JUKEBOX QUICKLY CLEARS MP3 CLUTTER  &HT;     By BECKY WARING 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you've been wondering what to do with all
those MP3 music files filling up your hard disk, Creative
Technology's new Nomad Jukebox is designed for you. Holding more
than 100 hours of music on a 6-gigabyte hard drive, this portable
player lets you take an entire music collection on the road, albeit
at a stiff price ($499 list, $450 street).
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Jukebox looks just like a CD player. Indeed, at
first I thought it played CDs, too, since several new combo MP3/CD
players have hit the streets recently. But the Nomad is an MP3-only
player.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomically, it's heavier than a CD player of the same size
(about 1 pound). It's portable, as on an airplane or in a car, but
not ``joggable.'' The rechargeable batteries (two sets are
included) last about three to four hours during playback, less when
connected to a PC. I recommend using the included AC adapter when
transferring files from your PC to the Jukebox. It's available in
your choice of metallic blue or silver.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that sets the Jukebox apart: It is one of the few MP3
players that supports both Windows and Mac platforms out of the
box. Creative bundles Casady &AMP; Greene's top-ranked SoundJam MP3
player for the Mac and its own Creative PlayCenter software for the
PC. Both packages do a fine job of organizing your MP3 collection,
creating playlists, and ``ripping'' audio CDs and converting CD
tracks into MP3 files.
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic sources of music for the Nomad: MP3 files
that you download from the Internet (from sites like MP3.com or by
using Napster), and those that you create yourself using an MP3
encoder. A large collection of music, both pop and classical, also
comes ready-to-go on the Nomad.
</P>
<P>
   Ripping favorite audio CDs will be the first task for most users
to fill up all that disk space. The usual route is to convert and
save CDs onto your PC or Mac, then transfer the resulting MP3 files
to the Jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   On the PC, you can also rip directly from CD to Jukebox,
bypassing your PC hard disk. The process is simple. Popping in a CD
on either platform brings up a list of tracks with the artist and
album names, thanks to an Internet CD database. You then decide
which tracks you want to convert and press a button.
</P>
<P>
   Using the default 128-Kbps settings with either SoundJam or
PlayCenter creates fine-sounding MP3 files, although you raise or
lower the quality level, depending on your preferences. For
portable audio, and using the supplied headphones, which aren't
very good, you don't need absolute CD quality.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to plug the Jukebox into your stereo system,
however, you might want to increase the quality level. High-quality
files (such as 192-Kbps) take more space though, so you won't be
able to fit as many albums.
</P>
<P>
   On my Mac PowerBook with DVD-ROM drive, CDs ripped at about four
times real time. That is, a one-hour CD was converted to
high-quality, variable bit-rate MP3 files in about 15 minutes. On
my desktop PC with CD-ROM drive, things were slightly faster.
Encoding time varies depending on drive and processor speeds, as
well as quality level. Older drives may not be able to encode
faster than real time.
</P>
<P>
   Once converted or downloaded, you transfer MP3 tracks to the
player by plugging it in to your computer's USB port and then
dragging files from one window to another. This is a deceptively
simple process. I found that if SoundJam on the Mac was playing an
MP3 at the same time as I was copying tracks onto the player (which
it seems to do by default), the system would hang in short order.
</P>
<P>
   x On the PC, transferring hundreds of files at once (my entire
MP3 collection) also caused me to have to reboot both system and
player. The problem was fixed on the Mac by turning off the player
and on the PC by copying fewer files at a time. It took just a few
minutes to transfer a couple hours' worth of music.
</P>
<P>
   uncx In the future, the Jukebox will play back other types of
music files, such as Windows Media Audio, through firmware upgrades
downloadable from the www.nomadworld.com site, but for now, only
MP3 is supported.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Nomad also lets you record hours of audio files
with a microphone input. Unfortunately, since there is no way to
save your place within an audio file or fast forward/rewind, the
audio feature is not very useful. But again, Creative hopes to
address these problems in upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   With the Jukebox all loaded up, it was time to start playing
things back. You can do this in two ways, via a small LCD screen
and control buttons on Jukebox, or via the PC/Mac software.
</P>
<P>
   Using the software was basically the same as playing back MP3s
on your computer: You create a playlist by dragging files, and then
press play. Very easy. With a big screen, navigating through the
hundreds or thousands of songs on the Jukebox is not a problem. You
can also save playlists for download to the Jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   Using the LCD screen for creating playlists is more difficult,
but adequate to the task. It has room for about seven lines of
data, pretty compact. Pressing the Library button brings up a
choice of album, artist, genre or playlist. You then click your way
to the tracks you want, adding them to your playback queue.
</P>
<P>
   Albums are stored in folders, so you can add a full album to the
queue by selecting the folder. Or you can choose to have things
played back randomly.
</P>
<P>
   As I mentioned before, the headphones are sadly lacking. They
are cheesy behind-the-head models that don't even adjust. I
immediately plugged in my own headphones, and also tried the line
outputs that plug into your stereo. It even supports quad-sound,
with dual outs, and has special effects like auditorium, playback
speedup and slowdown (useful for audio books), and parametric
equalization.
</P>
<P>
   One thing to note is that you can't use the Nomad to transfer
MP3s from one PC to another, even your own machines. This is
because of an agreement with the music industry, but also makes it
impossible to back up the Nomad directly. If you are concerned
about losing the data in your Jukebox (it is a hard drive, after
all, and hard drives crash), you'll need to be careful to keep all
your songs on your PC as well, or perhaps store them on writable
CDs.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going so far as to back up your MP3 collection on
CD-R/RW, you might consider getting a new combo CD/MP3 player, like
the aforementioned Philips model, that can play both regular CDs
and writable CDs with MP3s on them. A single CD-R disc can hold
about 150 MP3 songs, and the players sell for one-third the price
of the Nomad. They're also joggable.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting alternative to the Nomad is DigMedia's new
MusicStore. This jukebox is the same price as the Nomad, but
includes a CD player as well as a 5.4-GB hard disk and does not
require a PC to convert CDs to MP3s. It also has optional handheld
MP3 players that hook up to it, each holding one to three hours of
music.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear what types of players will take hold with the
market. The only certainties are that the MP3 market is growing
rapidly and that manufacturers will continue to come up with new
combos of storage, portability and playback capabilities. Cahner's
In-Stat Group predicts sales of players rising from $126 million in
1999 to $1.25 billion in 2002, a tenfold increase. The number of
manufacturers is also multiplying, from five last year to 50 this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the best way to carry around large amounts of MP3
music is the Nomad Jukebox. Aside from the audio-book deficiencies,
which should be addressed soon, my major complaint is that it takes
too long to start up, about 30 seconds. That can seem like an eon
when you're in the car dodging traffic. (It's easy to add adapters
that plug into your tape deck and cigarette lighter.) It's
expensive, but way cheaper than the same amount of storage in a
flash-card MP3 player, which typically sells for about $200 and
holds just an hour of music. The Nomad Jukebox has my vote!
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail Becky Waring at becky(AT)waring.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
