<HEADER>
A4586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-ROMANIAN-GYMNAST-     09-28 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ROMANIAN-GYMNAST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARBITRATORS REJECT APPEAL BY ROMANIAN GYMNAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout; subs byline)   By RICHARD SANDORMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The Court of Arbitration for Sport on
Thursday denied the Romanian gymnast Andreea Raducan's appeal to
regain the gold medal stripped from her by the International
Olympic Committee because she tested positive for a banned
substance.
</P>
<P>
   The three-member court ruled that it did not matter that the
drug pseudoephedrine was taken in the form of cold medicine or that
it did not enhance her performance at the individual all-around
event. What mattered, the panel decided, was that she committed a
doping offense in violation of the Olympic antidoping code.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strict liability test must thus be applied,'' the court said
in a statement, ``the consequence being automatic disqualification
as a matter of law and in fairness to all other athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the panel said factors such as her age, her
weight and her need for the medication were irrelevant. The panel
held that the ``presence of a prohibited substance in a
competitor's bodily fluid'' is the threshold issue, ``irrespective
of whether or not the competitor intended to ingest the prohibited
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC recognized that Raducan, who turns 17 on Saturday, did
not intentionally violate the code, but refused to make an
individual exception to the antidoping code for her. Jacques Rogge,
vice chairman of the IOC's medical commission, said that revoking
her gold medal ``was one of the worst experiences I have had in my
Olympic life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Having to strip the gold medal from the individual for
something she didn't intentionally do was very tough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Raducan, a 4-foot-10, 82-pound gymnast, performs with a
pixie-ish, crowd-pleasing style reminiscent of her legendary
Romanian predecessor, Nadia Comaneci. Raducan was the first
Romanian to win the gold in the all-around since Comaneci did it in
1976. Although Raducan was stripped of the all-around gold, she was
allowed to keep the gold she won as part of the team competition
and the silver medal she won in the vault.
</P>
<P>
   The court added that it is ``aware of the impact of its decision
on a fine, young, elite athlete. It finds, in balancing the
interests of Miss Raducan with the commitment of the Olympic
movement to drug-free sport, the anti-doping code must be enforced
without compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ioachin Oana, the Romanian team doctor who administered the
medication to Raducan, has been expelled from the Sydney Summer
Games, the 2002 Salt Lake City Winter Games and the 2004 Summer
Games in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, when the appeal was filed, there were reports that
Raducan's teammates, who were elevated to gold and silver medals,
would return them in protest. But Romanian national team officials
said on Thursday that they would not do that.
</P>
<P>
   Several IOC members sounded sympathetic toward Raducan, even
though they were the ones defending the decision to strip the
medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is with the athlete but it's a decision that stood
the test of arbitration, and everybody must live with that,'' Kevan
Gosper of Australia, an IOC executive board member, said after the
ruling. ``It's a decision that was put to the test. It's a
nonambiguous one, and it demonstrates we're serious about doping,
if anyone had any doubts.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the circumstances, Raducan tested positive for a banned
substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived the most humiliating moment of my life when I had to
turn in Andreea's medal,'' Octavian Belu, the coach of the Romanian
team, said on Wednesday. ``If they decide to give it back, I would
walk all the way to the Olympic village to bring the medal back to
its rightful owner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Arbitration for Sport is an independent,
international body created to resolve disputes over discipline and
contracts. Based in Lausanne, Switzerland, it establishes a branch
in the Olympic city during the Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
