<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4591 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-AZEVEDO-LADN-(SLA     09-28 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-AZEVEDO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT TIME FOR WATER POLO TEAM?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Tony Azevedo figures the folks back home are
worried. They shouldn't be, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people will look at this and say, `They've lost three
times and won only twice and they're out,' '' Azevedo said, ``But,
really, the tournament is just beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   And at just the right moment, it would seem, for Azevedo and the
U.S.men's water polo team.
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo, the 18-year-old polo prodigy out of Long Beach Wilson
High School, scored three goals as the Americans routed Greece 9-3
on Wednesday and secured a berth in the quarterfinals of the Sydney
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our next game is Russia, and that's a big one, because if we
win we're in medal contention,'' Azevedo said.
</P>
<P>
   His three goals Wednesday before a full house at Ryde Aquatic
Center gives him nine goals in the tournament, tying him for the
team lead withveterans Chris Humbert and Wolf Wigo.
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo said he and the U.S. team have made significant strides
sinceopening Olympic competition with a 10-7 loss to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think the first game I played really timid,'' he
said. ``It's the first game in the Olympics, something I've dreamed
about mywhole life, and I was timid. I played timid. I was out
there, and I wasnervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``But every game I've gotten better, every game I've calmed
myself down, and today I felt fine. There was no nervousness in me.
Our team is doing the same thing; we're progressing. We were timid
the first game, and with every game we're getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. won two of its last three group games, and lost by one
goal to world No.1-ranked Hungary in the other. The Yanks finished
fourth in Group B, and meet Group A champion Russia on Friday. From
here on out, one loss means elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo is not alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   `` I feel confident against Russia, and so does the team,'' he
said. ``The last time we played them was the FINA Cup, and we
needed to win itby three, and we won by three.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that pool play is complete, the Americans wonder whether
Group B was overloaded with good teams. The U.S. losses were to
Croatia, Yugoslavia and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three and us definitely could be the top four teams in
the tournament,'' Azevedo said. ``We've beaten (Group A qualifiers)
Russia, we've beaten Italy, we've beaten Spain, we beat
Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran two-meter man Kyle Kopp, former Long Beach State
standout, said Azevedo is comfortable with his first Olympic
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's handled it well,'' Kopp said. ``We carpool together, and
I've had a lot of time the last year-and-a-half to talk to him and
to preparehim for this -- the ups and downs of the tournament, the
chaos and everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been around the pool deck since he was 2 and 3 years old,
so he's been around it, he's seen it, and I think he's handling it
extremelywell.''
</P>
<P>
   Azevedo's confidence is high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling good about how I'm playing,'' he said. ``We're 0-0
in this tournament now, and we're ready to go get a medal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 0144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
