<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HOPES FOR POSTSEASON END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Twenty-five minutes before the Los Angeles Dodgers
took the field to be soundly beaten by San Francisco 4-0 Wednesday,
they had a chance to sit in the clubhouse and watch the Mets beat
Atlanta to end offcially the Dodgers' playoff fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers then played as if they had just had the last breath
stomped out of them _ you know, as they've played most of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we play for second place,'' Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw said.
``It'sofficial. We're out of the playoffs, but we still have
something to play for. Whether it be pride, second place, first
place, whatever, you always have something to play for.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Wednesday was a wonderful little parallel for the
season, especially since Luke Prokopec, in the No. 4 spot in the
rotation, took the loss.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers' top three starters have all had strong
seasons, anyone they've tried in the fourth and fifth spots has
experienced all sorts of difficulty. Entering Wednesday's game, the
fourth and fifth starters were a combined 10-25 with a 6.38 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Though Prokopec was solid in two other starts, he allowed four
runs in five innings against the Giants to further pad the brutal
numbers of the back end of the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   That glaring gap, which was insufficiently filled by Carlos
Perez, OrelHershiser, Mike Judd, Eric Gagne, Matt Herges, Ismael
Valdes and Prokopec, is the overwhelming reason the Dodgers'
postseason drought has hit four seasons. It also bears reminding
the Dodgers last won a postseason game in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough year,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``We
had some bad moments and some good moments. The Mets played better
than us. When you don't make it (to the playoffs), you don't feel
good about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
