<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4597 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-LASORDA-LADN-(SLA     09-28 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LASORDA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASORDA IN LIMELIGHT AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Cuba ran into Tommy Lasorda on Wednesday,
and it was a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   The world's biggest ham on the world's biggest sports stage?
C'mon, no contest.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy lives for the limelight. Basks in it. Shines in it. The
bigger the moment, the better he is. He was no more going to lose
to Cuba than take a job managing the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy's patchwork Yanks defeated mighty Cuba 4-0 Wednesday night
to win the gold medal in the Sydney Olympics, the first Olympic
baseball gold for the nation that invented the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I managed the Dodgers 20 years, but this is the greatest
moment of my life!'' Tommy bellowed. ``This is bigger than the
World Series because tonight everybody in the United States of
America is happy!''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, it was an upset victory, but did you honestly expect
any &QL;
</P>
<P>
   thing less with Tommy in the dugout mugging for the camera and
crying during the national anthem?
</P>
<P>
   You and I know Tommy is mostly full of beans. You hear one
``Great Dodger in the Sky,'' speech, you've heard them all. After a
dozen renditions of ``bleeding Dodger Blue,'' your eyes glaze over.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no denying Tommy has charisma, and USA Baseball's
choice of him as Olympic manager was inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy can motivate. No one denies that. Perhaps not over a
period of years, but put Tommy with the San Bernardino Stampede for
a month and they'll think they can beat the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   And the guys he had here were essentially the Stampede.
Minor-leaguers all, Triple-A and Double-A players not good enough
or seasoned enough for September callups to the big club.
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Doug Mientkiewicz, Adam Everett and Brad Wilker &QL;
</P>
<P>
   son. Ernie Young, Mike Neill and Mike Kinkade. John Cotton,
Brent Abernathy and Pat Borders.
</P>
<P>
   And those were Tommy's starters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they were enough to bring down Cuba, which has a player or
two wash up in Florida every month and go directly to the big
leagues. A Cubanteam that has dominated international baseball for
half a century.
</P>
<P>
   What Tommy did in a month with this American team was create the
Olympic version of the 1988 Dodgers. A modestly talented team with
spirit, cohe &QL;
</P>
<P>
   sion, an inspirational right fielder (Kirk Gibson, meet Ernie
Young) and a hot right-hander (Orel Hershiser, say hello to Ben
Sheets).
</P>
<P>
   It was a team that didn't scare anyone, and didn't overpower
much of anyone. But Tommy kept telling them how good they were, how
they were anelite, hand-picked bunch and, by gol &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ly, they bought that whopper.
</P>
<P>
   These 26 journeymen Joes, mostly career minor-leaguers, came to
believe they were something special. And, like Mickey Hatcher and
Franklin Stubbs 12 years ago, believing made it so.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were something special Wednesday night. They
fielded flawlessly. Neill banged a first-inning homer to give them
a lead. Young bounced a bases- loaded single up the middle to make
it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   And Sheets mowed down the Cubans who have terrorized U.S. teams
for more than a decade. Omar Linares, Orestes Kindelan, Antonio
Pacheco &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys could play in the major leagues right now!'' Tom &QL;
</P>
<P>
   my informed us. As could, he said, all three guys who pitched
against his team Wednesday. ``The first guy threw 93 (miles per
hour), the second guy threw 97 and the third threw 100!''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy credited the players with their success, but in his
egocentric little heart he believed he had a lot to do with it. And
he did.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great moment. Really, it was. Neill makes a sliding
catch inleft field to end the game, and Tommy bounces out of the
dugout like Gibson's homer has just reached the right-field
pavilion. (His vertical leap has declined in the 12 years since
1988, but Tommy is 73, as chubby as ever, and we'll cut him a
break.)
</P>
<P>
   It was a great moment because a warhorse put out to pasture
after a heart attack was given one more moment in the sun, a moment
he desperately wanted, and he seized it.
</P>
<P>
   He reminded us why he is a Hall of Fame manager. He wrung a
great Olympic moment out of modestly talented guys. He con &QL;
</P>
<P>
   vinced them they could win, and they did.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba never stood a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
