<P>
   &UR; KENTUCKY'S OLD CAVES GET A NEW LEASE ON LIFE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAVE-BIZ-KENTUCKY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HORSE CAVE AND PARK CITY, KY. _ More than 100 years ago, the
small town of Horse Cave became the second city in Kentucky to be
wired for electricity. It did this by harnessing the swooshing
waters of the Hidden River, an underground stream that briefly
opens to the sky in the center of town. After this great feat,
Hidden River cave remained unused for most of the 20th century _
except as a particularly nauseating open sewer. Now, once again, it
is the center of town. Caves are once again becoming big business
in central Kentucky. &QL;
</P>
