<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEHRAN EXTENDS A CAUTIOUS HAND TO SATAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOTIVES-IRAN-THAW-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEHRAN _ In recent weeks, high-ranking Iranian and American
dignitaries have begun to meet in intriguing ways. A number of
Iranian MPs, including Mehdi Karroubi, the speaker of the
parliament, ran into several American congressmen earlier this
month in New York at a reception at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
Mere coincidence, said Karroubi. Few believed him. All this
posturing and gesturing reveals that both sides in Iran, reformist
and conservative, would like to see an end to the 21-year rift in
relations. For the first time, the conservative establishment has
admitted what it once acknowledged only in private: that Iran can
no longer afford to snub the Great Satan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEATH IN DONGO: CONGO WAR SUDDENLY BECOMES SERIOUS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONGO-QUAGMIRE-UN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DONGO, THE CONGO _ His name was Kabwanga Makengo. Born
Lubumbashi, June 3, 1980. Private, 2nd Brigade of the army of the
Democratic Republic of Congo. Catholic. Unmarried. The photograph
shows a baby face startled by the camera. Makengo's muddied _ or
bloodied _ identity card lay in the trench where he is buried, next
to a smashed anti-aircraft gun. When the rebels of the Movement for
the Liberation of Congo (MLC) took this tiny trading post on the
Ubangi River on Sept. 7, they put the 34 dead government soldiers
in the trenches and covered them over. Suddenly, this war has
turned serious. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
