<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-IRAQ-ASSESS (United Nations) _ The Clinton administration
is about to strike a deal with Russia and France that would give
Iraq a larger share of the money from the oil for food program.
This comes at a time when the air embargo on Iraq is all but over,
as Iceland and Jordan join the countries that are sending flights
to Baghdad. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-NEW-TEACHER (New York) _ In July, Donna Moffett abandoned her
comfortable longtime job as a legal secretary near Wall Street to
be one of 320 ``teaching fellows'' _ people with little or no
teaching experience, hired by Schools Chancellor Harold Levy to
fill chronic vacancies in the system's most troubled schools. In
her first weeks of school, Moffett is learning that teaching is
only part of her job description _ for now, an achingly small part.
Already she is grappling with tardiness and discipline problems,
often spending far more time on ``classroom management,'' as
veteran teachers call it, than lessons. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHROPOLOGY-BOOK (Undated) _ A book about anthropologists who
worked with isolated Indians in Amazonia has touched off a storm in
the profession, reviving scholarly animosities, endangering
personal reputations and, some parties say, threatening to
undermine confidence in legitimate practices of anthropology. By
John Noble Wilford and Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   INSURE-POOR-KIDS (Undated) _ Three years ago, Congress provided
$4.2 billion to the states to provide health insurance for the
millions of children whose parents were too poor to afford
commercial plans but who earned too much money to qualify for
Medicaid. But a majority of the states are in danger of forfeiting
their share of the federal money, because they have not been able
to get their versions of the program up and running. What separates
those states that have managed to enroll children into health
insurance programs from those that did not in many ways defies
convenient leaps of logic and, in many cases, the expectations of
experts of the program. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PARTIES-SOFTMONEY (Undated) _ The national Republican and
Democratic party organizations are outspending both special
interest groups and the Bush and Gore campaigns on television in
the presidential election, a trend that political analysts say is
transforming the parties this year from supporting players into the
chief advertising agents for the candidates. In fact, this this
year, if the trend continues, the advertising campaigns will have
been financed largely by the unregulated soft money donated to the
parties by corporations and wealthy individuals. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-KIDS-PARENTS (Westland, Mich.) _ As they shopped for
milk at Kroger's, ate ice cream at the Westland Mall or sat in the
bleachers at the Westland Sports Arena, most of the parents
interviewed here agreed that it was their responsibility _ and not
that of the president, Congress or even Hollywood _ to filter what
reaches their children. The candidates, they suggested, should save
their breath for the economy and health care. Yet all of the
parents conceded that they regularly crossed or blurred the borders
between acceptable and unacceptable content. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GAS-PIPELINE (Inuvik, Northwest Territories) _ For three
decades, geologists probing beneath the Arctic Ocean near here and
offshore Alaska have mapped the largest known untapped reserves of
natural gas in North America _ 165 trillion cubic feet, seven times
as much as the United States will consume this year. But, with gas
prices low, indigenous opposition high and environmental issues
looming, energy companies never sought to build pipelines to send
the gas south to heat homes and to generate electricity. This is
changing as fast as it takes to read a home heating bill. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TAX (Paris) _ Europe is rushing to tear down borders, but
the Internet is toppling some of them even faster, making life
distinctly uncomfortable for European policy-makers. A big source
of that discomfort is the threat of lost tax revenue, because
European nations depend far more on taxes on consumption than the
United States does. So in contrast to the United States, European
officials are pushing hard to adopt a seemingly narrow but
potentially far-reaching proposal to ensure that digital products
bought in Europe over the Internet do not escape taxation. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-IMPORTS (Undated) _ If a bill allowing imports of
low-priced prescription drugs becomes law, drug companies will be
able to use a myriad of tactics to protect their profits, Wall
Street analysts said Wednesday, and keep the amount of the drugs to
a minimum. Consumer groups gave the plan a tepid thumbs-up, saying
they would continue to push elected officials to do more to rein in
drug prices, which are now the leading cause of the nation's rising
health care costs. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   BOSS-LARGESSE (Boston) _ Much has been made of the fringe
benefits of working for a dot-com company _ the free cappuccino,
the concierge services and the lucrative stock options. But, for
one day last week, working the production line for a company that
makes floor wax and carpet cleaner brought the perk of a lifetime.
Charlie Butcher, 84, the chairman of the family-owned Butcher Co.
in Marlboro, Mass., handed out bonus checks to his 325 employees
that totaled $18 million. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   SWAP-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ News Corp. and Liberty Media Group
confirmed Wednesday that they had agreed on a complex stock and
asset swap in which Liberty Media would increase its stake in News
Corp. and News Corp. would pick up Liberty's Gemstar-TV Guide
International holdings. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ George W. Bush has finally made
government the issue of the presidential campaign. After wasting
months focusing on Al Gore's character, he returned to what was
always the Republicans' meat and potatoes. As president, Gore would
give you big government, Bush now emphasizes. But if voters elect
him instead, Bush says, he would continue to tame Washington. Bush
is picking up, of course, from the legacy of President Reagan. By
Jeff Madrick.
</P>
<P>
   INTERPUBLIC-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ A seasoned executive with
experience in the account, creative and strategic realms of agency
operations is being named to a new top post at the Interpublic
Group of Cos. in New York. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-FUNDS-BRITAIN (London) _ As London is seeing the greatest
cultural expansion in its history _ a $600 million millennium
effort funded in part by England's National Lottery and in part by
private donations _ a list of many of the largest donors reads like
a who's who of American philanthropists. New galleries and
courtyards, libraries, reading rooms and additions are being
christened with names like Annenberg and Sackler. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICS-NAUGHTY-WORDS (Cambridge, Mass.) _ The publisher of the
Loeb Classical Library, the very proper series of Greek and Roman
literature for English-speaking readers, has been gradually putting
back the naughty bits it had been editing out of the books. By
Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   VIDAL-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Gore Vidal's ``The Golden Age,''
reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TALK (New York) _ Of the various newfangled epiphanies that
has smote book publishing lately, the most interesting is not the
future of the e-book or print-on-demand or on-line publishing.
Rather, it is that there is a large, and growing, citizenry of
black people who buy books and are greedy for reading material
relevant to them. By Martin Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bob Herbert writes about women and
their discontent in this campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire comments on the
gyrations of polls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN (Undated)_ With the late autumn of his career
upon him, Patrick Ewing, 38, with his 7-foot body battered but
still willing after 15 bruising seasons with the New York Knicks,
looked back on his professional basketball life. ``Athletically,''
he said, ``I'm not where I was back in my prime, but mentally I'm
much better. When I think about what I knew back then and what I
know now, I realize how great I could have been.'' By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN (Sydney, Australia) _ Regarding that form of
drug known as ``performance-enhancing,'' there is only one claim
George Vecsey says he would definitely believe from any athlete:
``Personally, Chief, I slurp 'em up like Corn Flakes. I can't wait
to finish talking to you so I can go get me some more.'' That
person I would believe. Sports column. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKO-RUSSIA (Sydney, Australia) _ To a former Russian
basketball coach who has seen it all, these are not good days. The
Americans, he says, are simply too skilled and strong for the
Russians to keep pace. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-AUSSIE-TOWN (Lithgow, Australia) _ Lithgow, population
15,000, lies at the end of the electrified railroad line from
Sydney, 90 miles to the west. It is not the sort of place the
writer Donald Horne was thinking of when he famously described
Australia as ``the lucky country.'' Remote, economically depressed,
and cursed with dreadful weather, Lithgow is worlds away from the
designer skyscrapers and sun-splashed beaches of Sydney. On a
recent weekday afternoon, a few cars rattled along Main Street,
barely outracing the fog that drifted down from the nearby
mountains. And yet, for all its hard-luck veneer, Lithgow is as
proud, as captivated, and as unabashedly excited about the Olympics
as Sydney. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN (Sydney, Australia) _ Sports column on the
Australian favorites in the men's doubles tennis final, the
Woodies, Mark Woodforde and Todd Woodbridge, who ended a
distinguished doubles career together with a silver medal before
their home crowd. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COLLEGES (Undated) _ The ins and outs, advantages and
disadvantages, of using the web to research colleges and apply for
admission. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WIRELESS-WEB (Undated) _ For some people, the wireless web
may replace the wired web. By Ian Austen.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sega Dreamcast games on the web.
By J.D. Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GEEK-NOTES (Undated) _ Internet appliance from Larry Ellison
company; portable email for the Gameboy; headphone technology from
Sony; study looks at Internet drop-outs.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING (Undated) _ On Hagglezone.com, a site for
bargaining with virtual hagglers. By Michelle Slatalla.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ What is an AGP port and what are PCI slots?
What is the meaning of the Windows error message ``This program has
performed an illegal operation and will be shut down''? By J.D.
Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CELLPHONE-ADS (Undated) _ Advertisers are beginning to tap
into the country's 101 million cell phones with text messages to
reach customers in a more direct and timely way. For marketers, a
wireless pitch is unlike any other because it can be aimed at
certain people and particular locations. By Jeffrey Selingo.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-D2-GAME (Undated) _ D2 is a game that is good at all the
extraneous elements of a video game but bad at the one central
necessity _ that it be entertaining to play. By Charles Herold.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-MTV (Undated) _ What primarily distinguishes ``Direct
Effect,'' MTV's new interactive show, from regular television fare
is that viewers not only watch it but also help direct it through
computers wired to MTV.com. By Michel Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-NEW-GRID (Undated) _ Researchers are developing an entirely
new kind of computer network to accommodate the data expected to
come from the next-generation particle accelerator scheduled to go
live in 2005 at the European Organization for Nuclear Research,
known by the French acronym CERN. Other scientific megaprojects
will also be served by the new system, and in time, the new network
_ GriPhyN (pronounced ``griffin''), for Grid Physics Network _ may
transform the Internet. By Robert Hercz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POOL-UPKEEP (Undated) _ The best thing about having a swimming
pool in your back yard is that it's there whenever you want to use
it. The worst thing is that it's still there even when you don't.
By Jay Romano.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN-REMODEL (New York ) _ In New York City, remodeling an
entire kitchen _ with new appliances in better locations, new
countertops, cabinets, floor and labor _ for less than $20,000 is
the equivalent of finding a two-bedroom apartment for $1,000 a
month. It's possible, but not very likely. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ZEN-FASHION (Corte Madera, Calif.) _ Zen is an upfront influence
at the office of ZoZa, a new fashion company set for its Web debut
in mid-October. Shoes are to be removed at the entrance and placed
in cabinets. A hefty Chinese gong stands ready to call meetings,
and there's a large empty swath of carpet for the staff's morning
yoga classes. By Peter Hellman.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-OBJECTS (Washington, D.C.) _ Hillwood, Marjorie
Merriweather Post's home-museum, is filled with a battalion of
royal objects. Her collection of imperial Russian art from the 18th
and 19th centuries is the greatest in the world outside Russia, and
her estate has one of the leading U.S. collections of Sevres
porcelain, much of it commissioned by Catherine the Great. By Irvin
Molotsky.
</P>
