<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORA-LEWIS-SEPT28-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINANCE OF ENGLISH CAN BE A HANDICAP  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 800-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of the FLORA LEWIS column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Flora Lewis  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   PARIS _ There is no longer any pretense of competition. An
international language has been accepted as valid for everyone, and
it is English.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, French which was the language of diplomacy and
international exchange well into the 20th century fought to remain
at least a rival. Now even that status is ceded.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a congress of teachers of French this summer, Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin said they were able to ``contribute to more
than one way of thinking.'' If French ``is no longer the language
of a power, it can be the language of a counter-power,'' he said,
``one of the languages expressing resistance to the uniformity of
the world and the refusal to diminish identity.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 900,000 French teachers and 82 million students of the
language, according to Le Monde. It is the World Wide Web which
finally, definitely defeated its aspiration to be everybody's
second language. But France is determined to keep it available
nonetheless, by supporting its use on ``la Toile'' (literally, the
Web), Jospin said.
</P>
<P>
   There is an attempt to keep up with the vocabulary of technology
by choosing specifically French words for the new names most people
simply accept in English (a chip is ``la puce,'' literally, the
flea, but marketing turned out to be irreplaceable. It is ``le
marketing.'')
</P>
<P>
   The resistance doesn't suceed very well. The English words
overwhelm usage, no matter what language is being spoken or
written, which therefore appears to confer a tremendous additional
advantage on native English speakers and to justify Americans'
disdain for learning other tongues.
</P>
<P>
   I would argue this is a deception that requires all the more
effort to undo because it isn't self-evident. It is going to be a
big disadvantage. Everyone else plugged into any kind of
international exchange will know at least two and often three or
four languages.
</P>
<P>
   American education has to a large extent abandoned foreign
language requirements for admission to college, which had led to
their often no longer being offered at lower levels.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent young Americans speak something besides English,
it is likely to be their mother tongue or that of their immigrant
parents, not something they learn in addition to everyday function.
</P>
<P>
   That means they don't need consciously to examine the different
ways ideas are formed. Learning another language isn't just finding
another word to say the same thing, it is learning another mode of
expression and even way of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   That is why computer translations are so flat and unhelpful.
They can do the part of equating one set of words with another that
is like mathematics, but they lose all the aura and usually the
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, that is exactly what is being talked about when the
need is expressed for dialogue, for understanding, for
communication with a substantive content. It is just the opposite
of homogenization, a recognition and appreciation of differences
rather than the process of compression which can be the other
result of globalized culture.
</P>
<P>
   As much as American fast food, and blue jeans, and movies and
pop music, as much as American business manners and calculations
are eagerly absorbed by the rest of the world, they build up a
resentment and feeling of abuse of power if all the influence and
intellectual effort go only one way.
</P>
<P>
   When others have learned through language and application to see
how Americans think, it is to put themselves in a position of
inferiority _ not superiority _ for Americans to know only
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Psychological studies reported to the annual meeting of the
American Psychological Association provide concrete evidence to
support the intuitive sense that different cultural approaches do
make people think differently. It had been supposed that logic and
use of categories were basic, universal human methods of thinking,
though culture made people think about different things.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nisbett and his colleagues at the University of Michigan
devised research projects which showed this was not true, that
there were indeed Asian and Western habits of thought that were
contrasting, the first more focused on context and relations with
more tolerance for contradiction, the second more analytic, reliant
on formal logic, serial.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing genetic about the difference.
Asian-Americans and Americans of European origin were
indistinguishable in the tests.
</P>
<P>
   These are things which can be learned and are of the greatest
value in dealing successfully with people from other backgrounds.
The key is learning other peoples' language.
</P>
<P>
   Even if everybody in the world can eavesdrop and know what they
are talking about, English-speakers confine themselves to a kind of
mental ghetto if they can't find their way on the linguistic turf
of others. It is self-deprivation, of pleasure as well as utility. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist
for The New York Times. She is the author of five books, including
``Europe: Road To Unity'' and ``Europe: A Tapestry of Nations.''
Her articles have appeared in the International Herald Tribune, The
New York Times Magazine, The Atlantic, The Economist, France-Soir,
Life, The London Observer, The New Yorker and many other
periodicals. Last year she won the Overseas Press Club's Award for
Lifetime Achievement.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the FLORA
LEWIS column and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
