<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-NYRA-PROBE-NYT &LR;      09-28 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NYRA-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SEARCH THE CASH BOXES OF BETTING CLERKS FOR EVIDENCE OF
MONEY LAUNDERING
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The state police went through the cash boxes of
scores of betting clerks at Belmont Park racecourse Wednesday as
part of an investigation into allegations that clerks at New York
tracks laundered money for a criminal organization, law enforcement
and racing officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are auditing the house,'' said Clem Imperato, a
consultant to the New York Racing Association, which owns the
tracks under a state franchise. ``That's really what they are
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The association's president, Terry Meyocks, issued a statement
after the state raids started, saying his organization was
``assisting federal authorities and providing them with certain
documents they need.'' The association ``is not the target of any
investigation, federal or state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation that led to the raids, first reported in The
New York Post, began about six months ago, law enforcement
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general's Organized Crime Task Force and the
state police have been examining allegations that people with links
to organized crime have been colluding with parimutuel clerks to
launder money.
</P>
<P>
   The clerks are believed to be, for a fee, exchanging large,
easily traceable bills for dozens of smaller, untraceable bills,
according to these officials, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known Wednesday where the large bills came from or
what sort of criminal organization might be involved. Cash from
drug sales tends to be in small denominations, while gambling money
and stolen cash is often in larger bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully anticipate to at some point soon come forward with
indictments and arrests, but we can't say when that will be,'' said
Darren Dopp, a spokesman for the attorney general, Eliot Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Racing officials were also served with federal subpoenas
Wednesday as part of an Internal Revenue Service investigation into
activities at the tracks, law enforcement officials said. It was
not clear whether the two investigations are related.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, dozens of state police officers raided the
betting departments at Belmont, Aqueduct and Saratoga, seizing
stacks of records, boxes of cashed winning tickets and cash boxes.
At Belmont, the police had to wait overnight for a time-locked safe
to open before they could examine the cash boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday , race track officials said, the state investigators
were poring over the contents of the boxes, which contain not only
large amounts of cash but also records of bets placed, winnings
paid out and money taken in.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said a number of mid-level and
low-level racing association employees were believed to be
involved. The number of parimutuel clerks varies from 125 to 500,
depending on the season, and they have about a dozen supervisors,
racing officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The parimutuel, or betting, department of the racing association
has been criticized for lax money-handling.
</P>
<P>
   The State Racing and Wagering Board, which oversees the racing
association, has been pressing for an independent audit of the
department since February 1999, but racing officials have resisted.
</P>
<P>
   The parimutuel clerks are given a sum of money at the beginning
of a track's racing season and are expected to keep their own
accounts straight until the end, when they must account for
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a clerk takes in more than a stated maximum, which
ranges from $2,000 to $10,000 depending on the size of the wager
that can be made at the clerk's window, the excess must be turned
over to a central ``money room,'' Imperato said.
</P>
<P>
   Imperato said supervisors opened and audited the clerks' boxes
at least once every 10 weeks, but usually more often. Most clerks
are audited once every three weeks, he said. Three to five clerks
were subjected to surprise audits every day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews Wednesday at Belmont, several clerks, speaking
on the condition of anonymity, said that typically they were
audited only three or four times a year. They said there were
plenty of opportunities for dishonest clerks to take money out for
their own uses, as long as it was returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I run my own store here,'' one clerk said.
</P>
</TEXT>
