<HEADER>
A4618 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a bc-SENATE-HOLLYWOOD-LADN     09-28 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-HOLLYWOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS WARN MOVIE EXECS
</HEADLINE>
bc-SENATE-HOLLYWOOD-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Bill Hillburg 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Under attack for marketing sex and violence to
kids, executives of Hollywood's major studios told Congress on
Wednesday they would clean up their act but failed to assuage
Republican lawmakers or derail the threat of congressional action.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the executives opened the Senate Commerce
Committee hearing by outlining their reform plans, Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., who chairs the panel, cut to the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you or will you not market R-rated films to children
under 17?'' asked McCain, who called a studio reform plan announced
Tuesday ``full of loopholes.'' He then pressed each executive for a
simple ``yes'' or ``no'' answer.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Harris, president of Sony Pictures Entertainment, and Stacy
Snider, chairwoman of Universal Pictures, gave qualified responses,
saying they would enact reforms but would continue to make
marketing decisions on their R-rated films on a movie-by-movie
basis.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was less equivocal from Rob Friedman, vice chairman
of the Paramount Motion Picture Group; Jim Gianopulos, chairman of
Fox Filmed Entertainment; Alan Horn, president of Warner Bros.;
Robert Iger, president of The Walt Disney Co.; Chris McGurk, vice
chairman of Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer; and Walter Parks, co-head of
production for DreamWorks SKG.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have gotten my attention,'' said Snider, who added that
Universal has already implemented changes announced Tuesday by the
Motion Picture Association of America and its president, Jack
Valenti.
</P>
<P>
   She cited ``Boyz N The Hood'' as an example of an R-rated film
that could have educational value for younger viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's question I cannot answer, sir,'' Harris told McCain.
Stressing that Sony will strictly adhere to MPAA's new rules, he
said each film project is unique and so are its marketing plans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he was disappointed by the responses, particularly
from Sony and Universal.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, issued a warning to the
executives, saying parents were frustrated and concerned by
marketing aimed at their kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sending a shot across your bow,'' she said. ``If you don't
try to really make this work, you're going to see some
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison also polled the executives on whether they would
support a federal law banning persons under 17 from access to
R-rated fare. All eight were opposed, citing First Amendment rights
and saying that strong self-regulation of their industry is
sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Several studios announced new reforms Wednesday, including Fox,
which will ban the showing of trailers for R-rated films in
conjunction with movies rated G and PG. The MPAA proposal covered
only G-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   Gianopulos also said that the Fox TV Network would not accept
any ads for R-rated films for its shows with a youth audience
measured at 35 percent or more, and would not advertise its R-rated
features on other networks' youth programs.
</P>
<P>
   Horn said that Warner Bros. would match Fox's efforts and would
also ban toy tie-ins with fast-food franchises for R-rated films,
as well as licensed products aimed at kids. He said Warner Bros.
was also expanding its movie rating system with more specific
designations of Rv to indicate violence, Rs for sex and Rl for
language.
</P>
<P>
   Iger said that Disney had, on several occasions, ``allowed
competitive zeal to overwhelm sound judgment and appropriate
standards in the marketing of some of our R-rated films'' but said
reforms were already in place.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Disney is leading an effort to set up a unified
ratings system for the movie, music and video game industries.
</P>
<P>
   Iger said he was referring to a report in Wednesday's New York
Times that Disney's Hollywood Pictures unit had tested the R-rated
``Judge Dredd'' with youngsters as young as 13 and that its
Touchstone Pictures had used kids 12-14 to screen the R-rated
``Enemy of the State.''
</P>
<P>
   The report cited documents included in the Federal Trade
Commission's Sept. 11 report on Hollywood's youth marketing
practices. The FTC study and report was ordered by President Bill
Clinton following the 1999 massacre at Columbine High School in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats were less critical of Hollywood's efforts,
including Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who said that media violence
was only one of many negative factors impacting the nation's youth.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne White, director of activist group The Lion and Lamb
Project, said she was unimpressed with Hollywood's latest reforms.
Members of White's suburban Washington-based group, including
parents and their kids, attended the Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need an independent ratings board, appointed by Congress
and reflecting a wide spectrum of society, to review movies, music
and video games,'' said White. ``With self-regulation, we have the
foxes guarding the henhouses.''
</P>
<P>
   L. Brent Bozell III, chairman of Parents Television Council, a
Los Angeles-based activist organization, was also critical of
Hollywood's cleanup efforts.
</P>
<P>
   PTC released its survey Wednesday of movie advertising on
network TV during the family hour, 8 to 9 p.m., for the period
Sept. 1-20. It found 45 of 54 spots touted R-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   ``When 83 percent of all movies marketed during the network
television family hour are R-rated, don't tell me that Hollywood
isn't marketing its trash fare to our children,'' Bozell said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
