<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4829 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-PRESIDENTIAL-T     09-28 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-PRESIDENTIAL-TELEVISION-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND GORE COURT THE TALKING HEADS OF TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use THURS., SEPT. 28, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Paar was a pioneer. He was the first entertainment-oriented
TV host who was able to convince presidential candidates that it
would be in their best interests if they crossed over to
entertainment television in order to prove they could swing with
the hipsters.
</P>
<P>
   Before Bill Clinton donned sunglasses and played a
sausage-fingered version of ``Heartbreak Hotel'' on the ``Arsenio
Hall Show'' in the summer of '92, even before the Madame
Tussaud-looking Republican contender Richard Nixon intoned, ``Sock
it to me?'' on ``Laugh-In'' in 1968, Paar played host to John F.
Kennedy and the ubiquitous Nixon in separate appearances on the
``Tonight Show'' in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   The fidgety, mercurial Paar saw it coming. He knew the idea of a
dignified presidential campaign, if it ever existed, would die hard
in the TV era. He knew these guys would do whatever it takes to
win, whether it meant dirty campaign tricks or phony-friendly chats
with their TV host.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, Nixon played the piano on Paar's show. (He
had more musical talent than his duplicitous spiritual stepson
Clinton.) Kennedy? He sang the ``Tonight, Tonight'' number from
``West Side Story'' with Marilyn Monroe. (Just kidding.)
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to the year 2000, when there's no longer any
question of whether a candidate will do ``soft'' talk shows. Now
the only questions are:
</P>
<P>
   A. How many shows will the candidate do?
</P>
<P>
   B. What are the limits for each appearance?
</P>
<P>
   So far the answers appear to be:
</P>
<P>
   A. Everything but ``Springer.''
</P>
<P>
   B. No yodeling.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, the desperate-to-appear-not-desperate
candidates seem willing to do just about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Will George W. Bush kiss Oprah when he visits her queendom, in
an obvious attempt to upstage Al Gore's polite-but-smoochless hello
to ``O'' the week before? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Is Gore willing to play the part of a cue card man for a Jay
Leno monologue on the ``Tonight Show''? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Will Joseph Lieberman break into a verse of ``My Way'' on ``Late
Night with Conan O'Brien''? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Is it OK with Bush if Susan Hawk, the trash-talking truck driver
from Wisconsin and ``Survivor'' semifinalist, sits in with Regis
Philbin during Bush's guest shot and grills him with irreverent
questions, as if he were running for game warden of her hometown?
Check.
</P>
<P>
   Are Gore and Lieberman willing to star in a wacky,
mock-documentary clip for the benefit of the ``Late Show,'' in
which Gore refers to David Letterman as a ``major-league (expletive
deleted)'' and Lieberman affirms, ``Big time,'' in a takeoff on
Bush's real-world comment about a New York Times reporter and Dick
Cheney's reaction? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Can we get Lieberman to guest with Conan O'Brien and do a hunk
of Jewish-related material, i.e., reading a list of jokey campaign
slogans such as, ``A Matzo Ball in Every Soup,'' and, ``No Bull, No
Pork,'' and telling Conan, ``Sometimes when my wife is out, I go
down to the family room, turn on the VCR and play the love scenes
from 'Yentl' over and over?'' Check!
</P>
<P>
   Will Hillary Clinton do a Top Ten List on Letterman's show?
Check. How about Gore? Check check.
</P>
<P>
   If Letterman asks Bush, ``Who likes interns better, you or John
McCain?'' will Bush shoot back, ``That's the wrong party?'' Check.
</P>
<P>
   Will Bush don a monochromatic shirt-and-tie ensemble, a la Regis
on ``Millionaire,'' when he does Reege's daytime show? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Will Gore, Lieberman, Bush and Cheney move in to the ``Big
Brother'' house this weekend, after the grand-prize winner is
declared on Friday night and the remaining mopes from that colossal
failure have been sent home?
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Far be it from me to give a sanctimonious lecture on how
presidential candidates should comport themselves with presidential
dignity. After all, I'm the guy who joshingly asked George Bush to
name the capital of Illinois, knowing full well he'd get the joke
and play along.
</P>
<P>
   If these guys are willing to stray from the heavily scripted,
carefully rehearsed campaign speech all the way over to the heavily
scripted, carefully rehearsed talk-show joke material, let 'em give
it a try.
</P>
<P>
   As long as they understand that, despite what the traveling
press corps may believe, it doesn't fool the average voter _ or
nonvoter. The candidates may think they seem cool and happening by
appearing on these shows and playing along with the gags, but to
the average voter, they're the political equivalent of the
corporate exec who tells a couple of jokes or sings a parody song
at the company Christmas party while we all roll our eyes and say,
``Nice try.''
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper and the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
