<P>
   SMART-MICROBE (San Francisco) _ Many of them are too small to
see, and through a microscope they resemble hairy water balloons or
wriggling, translucent blobs filled with lint. But they're not as
dumb as they look. Indeed, one type of microbe has enough primitive
intelligence to wend its way through a maze, Japanese researcher
Toshiyuki Nakagaki and two colleagues claim in this week's issue of
the journal Nature. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-IMMUNE (San Francisco) _ A promising new avenue of HIV
research _ priming the body's immune system to keep the virus in
check _ is getting a boost from a study of newly infected patients,
some of whom were able to fight off the infection much better after
an initial course of standard drug treatment. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
