<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN01-CO     09-28 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: How much to spend on the kiddies?
 &HT;    For release Oct. 1, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, the U.S. Census Bureau reported that the nation's
poverty rate hs fallen to its lowest level in two years. A few days
later, at the other end of the financial spectrum, billionaire
Warren Buffett complained that rich people are, ``leaving tons of
money to their kids, whose main achievement in life had been to
emerge from the right womb.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to this year's FAO Schwarz ``Ultimate Toy
Catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   Not yet ready for those barely poking their noses above the
poverty line but voraciously attuned to those Buffett is talking
about, and maybe those yearning at a slightly lower level, this
catalog would give any socialist a fatal heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   I can imagine only the MacCauley Culkin-played character in the
1994 movie ``Richie Rich'' leafing through its pages, saying ``I'll
have one of these, two of those, one of these...''
</P>
<P>
   And what I find so outrageous about buying outrageously priced
toys is that assembly is still required!
</P>
<P>
   I do not invent this allegation. Page 31 offers a children's
outdoor theater, quite impressive with a second-floor balcony. It
comes with a marquee that has changeable letters, a front ticket
window and, as the accompanying photo in the catalog shows, at
least five kids can get inside the thing. With an included 25-inch
TV, VCR and hardwood floors _ it doesn't say what the walls are
made of _ this nifty little gift for your child sells for $14,500.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's that caveat: Assembly required.
</P>
<P>
   If I had $14,500 for a toy for my kids, I'm sure I'd have plenty
more money to hire people to put it together. But it seems to me
that for $14,500, FAO Schwarz ought to be doing it.
</P>
<P>
   How many ``One-Of-A-Kind'' Monopoly sets do you think FAO
Schwarz will sell from its catalog? Likely, it's just one, as in
``One-Of-A-Kind.'' But who would buy the one? This is not your
ordinary, or even premium Monopoly set; it goes far beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   While not giving the amount, the blurb says the game comes with
``hard cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: Rosewood board, street names written in gold leaf,
emeralds around the Chance icon, sapphires around Community Chest,
rubies in the brake lights of the car on the Free Parking space; it
goes on and on, up to and including twelve 18-karat gold hotels and
thirty-two 18-karat gold houses.
</P>
<P>
   The price? $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Check and confirm: One hundred thousand dollars!
</P>
<P>
   Here's the rub: Freight costs extra.
</P>
<P>
   Man, that ticks me off!
</P>
<P>
   It's going to make the difference in whether I buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, we have become a wealthy population; well, a lot of us
have. We live in an era where people actually spend more than $100
a game to watch pro basketball, where theater tickets sell for $85
and up, where $350,000 homes are not uncommon, where automobiles
are purchased at $30,000 and up. Which brings me back to the FAO
Schwarz ``Ultimate Toy Catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   You can get a replicated Lamborghini, child-sized version, with
a four cycle, five horsepower engine, ``faux'' leather upholstery
(''faux'' means ``fake'') and a working horn (wow!) for $40,000;
also extra for the freight.
</P>
<P>
   As I look at the morning paper, $40,000 will get me three or
four real Chevys, even a utilitarian Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   Likely, Warren Buffett knows people who will use this catalog
for their Christmas shopping, and would be concerned about them
bestowing such outrageous gifts upon their Richie Rich kids. And
the news that the poor people aren't quite as poor as they were two
years ago does not portend that they now can choose their gifts
from anything more lavish than a Harriet Carter catalog.
</P>
<P>
   But it's nice to know those fancy things exist, that we can look
at them in catalogs _ and can dream.
</P>
<P>
   Always, we can dream; it's free. No freight, batteries or
assembly required.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
