<HEADER>
A4889 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0929-CO     09-28 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    I have done my small part to bring on the rain
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Fall is finally here, though rain is still
playing hide-and-seek, meaning the temperatures are tolerable, but
the land is still ridiculously dry even with a few showers. Forest
fires are still a fact of life, and anybody who is dumb enough to
burn outdoors or chunk a cigarette out a car window ought to be
horsewhipped.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I have taken the ultimate step to appease the rain gods.
I took the top off my Jeep last Sunday while the Big Strong
Boyfriends were in town to help.
</P>
<P>
   I'm beginning to love this boyfriend deal. At first I was a bit
uncomfortable with the ever-presence of the boys, as my wife and I
call them. The girls show up, and like Siamese twins, there are the
boyfriends, automatically doubling the number of young adults
eating my food.
</P>
<P>
   But then I was struck with a lightning bolt of inspiration. Put
them to work while they're here. Make them lift stuff. Since
they're falling all over themselves to stay in my good graces _ and
they're nice guys to boot _ they hop right up every time I enlist
their brawn.
</P>
<P>
   So the top came off the Jeep, replaced with a bikini top that
keeps the sun off but won't keep the rain out. It's a wonderful
feeling, wearing a jacket early in the cool morning while driving
to work as the sun rises. There's the toasted-wood smell of
International Paper, which pleasantly reminds me of a wood-burning
fireplace, the sounds of a small town waking up, delivery trucks
making their rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Even the diesel smell of school buses picking up kids perks me
up. I have to crank NPR up terribly loud to hear the news, but I do
so with a clear conscience, figuring it is an elevating experience
for those boom-boxers playing rap music with the bass turned way
up. Give them a dose of Bob Edwards' cigarette-deepened voice at
6:30 a.m. and maybe they'll forget about Eminem and contribute to
the pledge drive coming up, way I figure. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   Riding around in a vehicle without a roof, back windshield or
windows reminds me of my motorcycling days, which concluded a few
decades back after an unfortunate entaglement with a barbed-wire
fence. I had just bought a Honda Hawk and was heading home from the
insurance agent's office, sweeping through the S-curve on Pearl
Street in Nacogdoches, right behind La Hacienda. An old pickup in
front of me dropped a square bale of hay off the bed. I panicked,
made a hard right, jumped the curb and ended up flying over the
handlebars and through the barbed-wire fence.
</P>
<P>
   I still have the scars to prove it, from my shoulder down to my
waist. The bike was relatively unscathed, but I was cut up pretty
extensively, though nothing was life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   This was my third motorcycle wreck in four years, and somehow I
had managed each time to avoid an overnight stay in the hospital,
though emergency room personnel knew me by sight.
</P>
<P>
   Thus came an epiphany. God doesn't want me to ride a motorcycle,
much as I love them. I'm too short and stubby to keep anything
aloft much bigger than a Moped. A few months after that last wreck,
I sold the bike and have stuck with four-wheelers ever since. Know
your limits, I say.
</P>
<P>
   So in the 25 years since I've settled for rag tops of some type
or description, from an Austin Healy I drove each day from Austin
to Round Rock on I-35 - convinced an 18-wheeler was about to devour
me _ to the Fiat Spider I bought between marriages a few years back
and still kick myself for selling to buy a Ford Tempo. What was I
thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Now I have a Jeep that is loud, cranky, drives rough as a
carnival ride, is built to run over nearly anything, and can be
taken apart like an Erector Set project. You can take off the roof,
rip out the back seats, remove the doors and even take down the
windshield if you enjoy capturing bugs in your teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it keeps one occupied. The Jeep is not a motorcycle, but
when heading down the highway, the canvas top flapping loudly and
red dust wafting through the windows, it's a good feeling. And I
don't have to worry about dying if I hit a hay bale.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, once the top came off, a few days later the rain came,
a blessed sight. Unfortunately, the boyfriends had already headed
home to Austin, and I had to shanghai a co-worker to put it back
on.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)ccoxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
