r l BC-THE-MECHANIC0929-COX     09-28 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fuel, additives handle injector cleaning
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The question of whether to clean the ``self-cleaning''
Multec fuel injectors on a 1990 Camaro _ broached by R.P Borsody
last week _ prompted me to delve into an area for which I thought I
had a definitive answer.
</P>
<P>
   However, my research of real-world conditions revealed, as is
often the case, that the factory information I have believed to be
gospel contains some discrepancies.
</P>
<P>
   I am not completely disputing the original recommendation of GM
when it says in the vehicle service manual, ``DO NOT CLEAN Multec
injectors.'' I think the controversy can best be illustrated by
deferring to its history and usage.
</P>
<P>
   I happened to be working at a GM dealership in the mid-1980s,
when electronic port fuel injection engines began replacing their
carbureted predecessors. Thus I witnessed firsthand a transition,
one that suffered growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   A primary source of engine performance and driveability
complaints stemmed from the incompatibility of the fuel injector
design and the formulation of the gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   While we waited for the injector and fuel engineers to work out
a solution, we replaced injectors in droves.
</P>
<P>
   The Multec ``self-cleaning'' injector appeared on the scene in
1987, incorporating a completely different design than the
traditional ``pintle and seat'' depicted last week.
</P>
<P>
   GM's description states: ``It uses a stainless steel ball and
seat valve, finished to a near mirror smoothness to obtain a
positive seal. A director plate with six holes, which is
insensitive to fuel deposits, provides spray pattern control. As a
result, the Multec injector is less susceptible to plugging caused
by varnish buildup.'' Additional modifications included the
electrical wire windings and sealing of the injector.
</P>
<P>
   As technicians, we were warned that cleaning these injectors
could damage the insulation on the wire windings, causing them to
fail electrically. We were told that because of their design, they
didn't need cleaning, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the discrepancy lies.
</P>
<P>
   According to my research, there are areas both within the fuel
delivery system and the injectors themselves that can become gooked
up.
</P>
<P>
   As with conventional ``pintle and seat'' injectors, a mild to
moderate buildup can often be remedied by cleaning the injectors.
However, the mechanic's choice of chemicals and cleaning method can
make the difference between restored performance of the injectors
or a meltdown nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   If the cleaning solution is too harsh or used in the wrong
proportions, or if it is introduced into the system improperly,
disaster is in your future.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing that must be determined is, are the injectors at
fault?
</P>
<P>
   This can only be determined through a diagnostic test that
measures the fuel pressure drop of each injector.
</P>
<P>
   I have never seen all of the injectors go bad at the same time.
Yet because of the way the fuel delivery system is designed, all of
them will need to be cleaned. A single-line unit (bug
sprayer/canister type) is inferior to a dual-line cleaning unit.
</P>
<P>
   I do not adhere to fuel injection cleaning as preventive
maintenance. I do advocate the use of quality fuel containing the
additives to clean injectors, along with a bottle of Techron or 44K
added to a tank of gas every 5,000 miles or so.
</P>
<P>
   Note: More is not better. Oh, and stay clear of products
containing methanol.
</P>
<P>
   Intake or induction cleaning differs from injector cleaning in
that it cleans the air intake plate (throttle plate) intake
passages, intake valves and combustion chamber without going
through the fuel system.
</P>
<P>
   I have had very good success with intake cleaning, which I
recommend performing every 30,000 to 60,000 miles, depending on
driving habits.
</P>
<P>
   This procedure is not usually listed in the manufacturer's
vehicle maintenance schedule, and it can be a little costly. But I
feel it is well worth it in both performance and fuel economy. My
engine seems to like it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
