r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0929-COX     09-28 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abstinence-only isn't sex education; it's pacification
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Unwrap an arm's length of cotton gauze, wad it in
your mouth and experience what too many health educators say they
feel.
</P>
<P>
   When the subject is sex education. It comes out ``sez
nextonuthin.''
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely what many policy-makers want. Next to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Clarification: Next to nothing, they want full-throated
advisories against it.
</P>
<P>
   It? You know. It. Do I have to spell it out? S-E-X.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday two surveys came out showing overwhelming support for
something else, real sex education. The survey that got the most
attention came from the Kaiser Family Foundation. It showed parents
valued comprehensive sex education every bit as much as they valued
abstinence messages and coping skills. Bring it all on, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The other survey, by the Alan Guttmacher Institute, indicates
that nine of 10 health educators are frustrated with sex education
under abstinence-only restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and teachers seem to agree that comprehensive sex
education means discussing contraception: how to use it, how it
works.
</P>
<P>
   Onwafessum?
</P>
<P>
   No. Contraception.
</P>
<P>
   These findings are at odds with policy-makers' increasing
insistence on abstinence education which quite often, and quite
dangerously, serves as a school district's only sex education.
</P>
<P>
   Congress spends nearly $100 million a year on abstinence
education programs, which proponents and some school districts pose
in an either/or proposition: Either you teach abstinence or you're
promoting promiscuity.
</P>
<P>
   The nomenclature of abstinence funding has a strong whiff of
someone's ministry of propaganda. There's abstinence education and
there's ``mixed messages'' _ the abstinence-only term for
comprehensive sex education.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry line: Referring to contraception in any way other
than what it can't do _ it can't prevent pregnancy 100 percent of
the time, and condoms fail _ is tantamount to advocating teen sex.
</P>
<P>
   With abstinence-only programs like Teen Aid and Sex Respect, one
has the unfortunate condition of school policy-makers saying
they've done their job by providing sex education. In fact, with so
many questions and concerns that could be addressed in a classroom
setting, the districts simply have handed growing and nearly grown
children a lollipop to pacify.
</P>
<P>
   IMPORTANT THEME
</P>
<P>
   Who doesn't think abstinence should be the prevailing theme in
discussing sex with young people? I certainly think it should. So
should any self-respecting sex educator in the age of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser Family Foundation found that virtually all parents it
surveyed, 97 percent, wanted an abstinence theme to sex education.
But a vast majority say they want much more, even on the touchiest
subjects. Seventy-five percent of parents said they wanted
classroom treatment of subjects like homosexuality, abortion and
how to use birth control.
</P>
<P>
   Is this such an unusual request? Absolutely not. With today's
information and influences, what child does not have questions that
need dispassionate, factual explanations in keeping with an
abstinence theme? The facts certainly support the need for
abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one would hope that such answers would come from
home. Not in this world. Not in this life.
</P>
<P>
   The students' parents can supply the passion on the subject
matter if so desired. This is a matter of information.
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Parents want abstinence-based sex education that's
real sex education. It's not either/or.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
