 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, September
29, 2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMOTIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is available now. Art includes three color photographs
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0926: 2000 MAZDA PROTEGE _ The Mazda Protege is a
little sedan that isn't always near the top of the list when
price/content-minded buyers head out to look for a family car, but
it should be. (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes
a 4-column color photo of the 2000 Mazda Protege and a 2-column
color photo of the car's interior.
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 2000 Mazda Protege.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP DRIVING _ After 2,600 miles with a Hummer, I learned that
living with a Hummer is in many ways like a man lusting over a
gorgeous woman and finding out after he marries her that she can't
cook (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). Includes 1-column color
photograph of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA _ The number of hybrid-fuel vehicles
available to the public has just doubled.
</P>
<P>
   A hybrid is a vehicle that has more than one power source _ in
this case, a 44-horsepower electric motor and a 70-horsepower,
inline, four-cylinder gasoline motor. The newcomer, joining Honda's
Insight in the market place, is Toyota's Prius (pronounced pre-us).
(Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ ATLANTA _ The question of whether to clean the
``self-cleaning'' Multec fuel injectors on a 1990 Camaro _ broached
by R.P Borsody last week _ prompted me to delve into an area for
which I thought I had a definitive answer. However, my research of
real-world conditions revealed, as is often the case, that the
factory information I have believed to be gospel contains some
discrepancies. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-DRUG _ Manufacturing, distribution and legal troubles
have bogged down the process, but the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration is scheduled to approve mifepristone (ru486) _ with
some potential restrictions _ by Sept. 30. How easy will it be to
obtain the drug in Atlanta, will some doctors refuse to prescribe
it, what will it cost, including costs of followup ultrasound, what
do local antiabortion groups plan to do, if anything, what does
that mean for abortion clinics? We'll answer those questions.
(Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: With graphic on how RU486 works.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-CONFERENCE _ ATLANTA _ She struggles to put her fear into
words, but Mardis Andrews knows perhaps better than anyone what the
AIDS epidemic means to her and her children, an 11-year-old
daughter and a baby not yet born. ``I feel like I'm in a world
different from everybody else,'' the 33-year-old Atlanta mother
said. Truth is, Mardis Andrews isn't. She has never been. In
Georgia, 82 percent of women with AIDS are African-American, just
like her. And African-American children represent 62 percent of all
new HIV-AIDS cases in the United States, just like her daughter.
But if these numbers are lost on Andrews, they weigh heavy and wide
on the 3,300 representatives from HIV/AIDS advocacy groups and
service providers who are expected to meet here Sunday through
Wednesday for the U.S. Conference on AIDS. (Staples, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   FOAM _ ATLANTA _ Emory University professor Sidney Perkowitz is
nuts about foam. He looks at a cup of capuccino and sees the
structure of the early universe. Now he's written a book about it,
called, as one might expect, ``Universal Foam.'' (Earle, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   JEWS-AWE _ Jews in Atlanta and around the world begin the
observance of the 10-days of Awe tonight with Rosh HaShanah, the
Jewish New year. The holy period ends Oct. 9 with Yom Kippur, the
Day of Atonement. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   E-LIVING _ A daily column featuring the most useful Web sites
and live online events affecting arts, entertainment and leisure
activites. Today: (Footlick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   FALLTV-PREVIEW _ A look at all the new shows debuting on TV this
season. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News). 65.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FALLTV-TOP-PICKS _ FiveTV shows that should click this fall.
(Dempsey, Dayton Daily News). 25.
</P>
<P>
   FALLTV-CLIFFHANGERS _ A look at last season's cliffhangers and
when the series premieres are. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News). 11.
</P>
<P>
   FALLTV-NNAMES _ Some of the names of this year's new series
confuse us. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News). 4.
