<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHARP-COLUMN0929-COX     09-28 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-COLUMN0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toyota seeks niche in technology arena with hybrid-fuel Prius
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The number of hybrid-fuel vehicles available to the
public has just doubled.
</P>
<P>
   A hybrid is a vehicle that has more than one power source _ in
this case, a 44-horsepower electric motor and a 70-horsepower,
inline, four-cylinder gasoline motor.
</P>
<P>
   The newcomer, joining Honda's Insight in the market place, is
Toyota's Prius (pronounced pre-us).
</P>
<P>
   Typically when you quiz automotive consumers about which vehicle
first comes to mind when you think of safety, the response is
Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   When you ask about luxury, it may be Mercedes-Benz or Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   But what about if you were to ask about the one with the most
revolutionary technology?
</P>
<P>
   If it were a computer or Palm Pilot that you were referring to,
the answers from many people would be quick. But when it comes to
automobiles, there really is no accepted technology standard.
Toyota's goal is to claim that spot with its new Prius.
</P>
<P>
   The Toyota people don't see the Prius as an answer to all our
fuel and pollution problems, but rather as a beginning step. Toyota
hopes consumers 50 to 75 years from now think of the Prius in the
same way we currently think of the Model T.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, Toyota faces an uphill struggle to fill the
marketplace with its hybrid vehicle. The Japanese almost knocked
down dealers' doors to order the Prius, with now some 45,000 units
on the road. But the American consumer is going to be a harder
sell. Why?
</P>
<P>
   First, even with the rise in gas prices, consumers haven't
gotten that excited about high-mileage vehicles. If they had, they
wouldn't be buying SUVs like they were blue light specials at
Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   Second, since we really don't accept the fact that our air
quality is stinko, we typically aren't willing to adjust our
lifestyle to help to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   I spent an extended amount of time in the upper Midwest this
summer. Until then, I did not really understand just how bad
Atlanta's air has become and how much better my breathing could be
when I am in a less-polluted environment.
</P>
<P>
   The Prius does not get as good gas mileage as Honda's Insight,
but my guess is that it is going to be much more widely accepted,
because it has more traditional characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   It can carry five adults, it has a large trunk and it comes
standard with an automatic transmission and air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota says it gets 45 mpg on the highway and 52 mpg in the
city. No, I didn't reverse those numbers. At city speeds, the Prius
depends more on its electric motor capability than it does its
gasoline partner. Thus the better city mpg.
</P>
<P>
   How does it drive? Driving in downtown Miami, I found it
outjumped most cars at stoplights and cruised admirably on the
freeway. Bottom line, it didn't seem any different than a regular
vehicle, except that it was uncannily quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many automakers that have quietly resisted the
government's mandate to produce an acceptable alternative-fuel
vehicle, and therefore only put forth whatever minimal effort that
was necessary, Toyota is making a concentrated effort to get this
vehicle into the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   At a selling price of $20,450 _ or a three-year lease program
with 45,000 miles and a $298 monthly payment _ Toyota is heavily
subsidizing this effort.
</P>
<P>
   Actual production cost for the Prius is rumored to be around
$27,000.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota is so confident in the reliability of this new product
that it provides an eight-year, 100,000-mile warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is not a pure alternative-fuel vehicle, you will
spend a lot less time in your local gas station.
</P>
<P>
   And, more importantly, you will be doing something really good
not only for yourself but the rest of us as well, since the Prius
pollutes the air an impressive 90 percent less than any
conventional vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp's column is written exclusively for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
