<HEADER>
A4900 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-HEALTH-EYE-OPENER-MED     09-28 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-EYE-OPENER-MED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS A CLEAN T-SHIRT A SIGN OF A BAD HEART?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This premium feature from The New York Times Syndicate is
available without charge to clients of this news wire.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By SAM URETSKY  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Our mothers always told us to wear clean underwear in case we
had an accident and had to go to the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   But suppose you learned that wearing dingy underwear reduced
your risk of heart disease, what then?
</P>
<P>
   The June issue of Science of the Total Environment reports that
there may be a relationship between clean underwear and heart
problems. It's all in the water you drink and wash with.
</P>
<P>
   When Scottish researchers measured the amount of calcium in the
hair of 4,393 men, they found that those with the most calcium had
the lowest rate of heart disease. And those with the most calcium
in their hair lived in areas with the hardest water _ that is,
water with the most minerals in it, including calcium.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, measurements of water hardness and sun exposure
together were able to account for almost half the differences in
rates of heart disease in Scotland. Harder water and more sun were
better.
</P>
<P>
   The drawback, of course, is that clothes don't wash as well in
hard water. Maybe that's why people wear gray T-shirts to the gym.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT HEALTHSCOUT:
</P>
<P>
   HealthScout (http://www.healthscout.com) is a service of Rx
Remedy, Inc., a leader in the field of health information and
