<P>
   EDITORS: The following photos of the 2000 Summer Olympics have
moved as part of the New York Times News Service photo report for
Thursday, Sept. 28, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Additional photos will move as available.
</P>
<P>
   (OLY21) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 28, 2000 -- OLY-RUN-MEN-6 --
Erki Nool of Estonia with his country's flag after winning the gold
medal in the decathlon at the 2000 Summer Olympics, Thursday. Nool
won the gold with 8,641 points. Roman Sebrle of the Czech Republic
won silver with 8,606 and American Chris Huffins won bronze with
8,595. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY20) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 28, 2000 -- OLY-SOC-WOMEN-11
-- Brandi Chastain of the U.S. Olympic women's soccer team is
greeted by fans as she enters the players tunnel following the
team's loss to Norway, Thursday. In the 12th minute of sudden death
overtime, substitute Dagny Mellgren of Norway scored to give the
team a 3-2 victory over the Americans and an Olympic gold medal.
The U.S. team took the Silver. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY19) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 28, 2000 -- OLY-SOC-WOMEN-10
-- Norway's Olympic soccer coach, Per-Mathias Hagmo, is thrown into
the air by his players after they defeated the U.S. 3-2 in the
Olympic women's soccer finals match, Thursday. In the 12th minute
of sudden death overtime, substitute Dagny Mellgren scored to give
Norway a 3-2 victory Thursday over the Americans and an Olympic
gold medal. It also gave it the right to claim a spot next to the
United States as the top team of the past decade in major
international women's soccer. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY18) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 28, 2000 -- OLY-SOC-WOMEN-9
-- US Olympic soccer team players, from left, Mia Hamm ((NU)9),
goalkeeper Siri Mullinix ((NU)18), and Joy Fawcett watch as Norway
celebrates their overtime goal to win the finals match, Thursday.
In the 12th minute of sudden death overtime, substitute Dagny
Mellgren scored to give Norway a 3-2 victory Thursday over the
Americans and an Olympic gold medal. It also gave it the right to
claim a spot next to the United States as the top team of the past
decade in major international women's soccer. (Chang W. Lee/The New
York Times)
</P>
