<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4956 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-TV-TONIGHT-ADV02-NYTS     09-28 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TONIGHT-ADV02-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV02 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, OCT. 02, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Premiere week gets under way tonight with a slew of new shows
and season premieres, including the debut of NBC's drama series
``Deadline'' at 9. Oliver Platt stars as New York tabloid columnist
and college journalism teacher Wallace Benton. His newsroom
colleagues include Tom Conti, Bebe Neuwirth and Lili Taylor _ maybe
it's not an all-star cast, but they've got chops. And the producer
is none other than Dick Wolf of ``Law &AMP; Order.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's already plenty of grumbling among journalists that
this isn't exactly reality television.
</P>
<P>
   In the opener, Benton reopens a murder case in which he helped
put the accused killers on death row. Now he thinks he was wrong,
and he and his student acolytes get to work finding the real
killers before the wrong guys are executed. We, uh, won't tell you
how it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   This story line has led to suspicions that Benton is based on
Chicago journalism professor David Protess, who has a habit of
getting innocent men off death row with the help of his students.
The producers say not so _ their models are columnists like Jimmy
Breslin, Mike Royko and Mike McAlary. Now Breslin's half-seriously
talking about getting a lawyer, since those other guys are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Smart money says this one won't last as long as ``Law &AMP; Order,''
nor be as fondly remembered as ``Lou Grant.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``King of Queens,'' CBS at 8: Season premiere. Doug finds a new
way to turn Carrie on. Needless to say, he'll make a fool of
himself before he's done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddio,'' NBC at 8: Season premiere. Michael Chiklis stars in
this subpar sitcom. Donny Osmond guests as a former boss who
arrives with a job offer in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexiest Bachelor in America Pageant,'' Fox (who else) at 8:
What, you need more details?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' CBS at 9: Special hourlong
season-premiere episode finds Marie springing for an Italian
vacation for the whole family. Pasta and a fine whine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Dear,'' CBS at 8:30: Sitcom premiere about the different
parenting styles of two couples. The pilot episode was painfully
predictable. And the two male stars, comics Anthony Clark and Mike
O'Malley, were both less than successful in their previous sitcom
outings. Better catch this one quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tucker,'' NBC at 8:30: Another premiere. Tucker (Eli
Marienthal) and his newly divorced mother (Noelle Beck) are forced
by circumstances to move in with his awful aunt (Katey Sagal of
``Married with Children''). Tucker is sensitive and self-aware _
think ``Malcolm in the Middle'' _ but the pilot episode, at least,
is insensitive and stupid. Malcolm could pull off a long scene
about trying to conceal his, er, excitement, but here it just seems
smarmy. This one will race ``Yes, Dear'' to the cancellation line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football,'' ABC at 9: Seattle at Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roswell,'' WB at 9: Season premiere finds the alien high
schoolers and their friends facing new challenges, including the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hughleys,'' UPN at 9: Is a smutty Web site the way to
success?
</P>
<P>
   ``Girlfriends,'' UPN at 9:30: Is the Internet a place to find a
mate?
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Law,'' CBS at 10: Season premiere. Tony Danza joins the
cast as a street-smart lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third Watch,'' NBC at 10: Season premiere. One kidnapper is
dead, the other in a coma. Now where's the kidnappee?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventh Heaven,'' WB at 8: Season premiere of this family
drama. Eric and Annie disagree over work and school issues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF Raw'' and ``WWF War Zone,'' TNN at 9 and 10:
Ch-ch-changes. First, these two wrestling hits moved over to TNN
last week. And, at the same time, TNN dropped ``Nashville'' to
become The National Network. The biggest news is TNN now has a big
Monday-night ratings success on its hands _ last week these shows
got the cabler's best numbers ever.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Geena Davis
and Regis Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' CBS at 11:35: Pamela Anderson
and Christopher Titus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 1:05 a.m.:
TBA. (Note time after football.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35: TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: TBA.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
