<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLYMPICS-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      09-28 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn. Sports Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympic stories from The New York Times News Service for Friday,
Sept. 29:
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOC-WOMEN (Sydney) _ Dagny Mellgren's goal in overtime gives
Norway a 3-2 victory over the defending Olympic champion United
States in the women's soccer final. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TRACK (Sydney) _ The day's highlights: Marion Jones, already
the 100-meter champion, resumed her five-medal quest by adding the
200 title in 21.84 seconds, winning by almost a half-second. She
competes in the long jump final Friday. Ivan Pedroso of Cuba took
the men's long jump, reaching 28 feet, } inch on his final attempt.
Konstantinos Kenteris of Greece upset the favorites in the men's
200. China's Wang Liping won the women's 20-kilometer walk after
Australian Jane Saville was disqualified. Erki Nool of Estonia won
the Olympic decathlon, overtaking Chris Huffins of Indianapolis who
led through nine events. Huffins ended up third. Yanina Karolchik
of Belarus took the women's shot put. By Christopher Clarey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN (Sydney) _ Back in Norway, they heard
about the victory tour, the commercials, the sponsorships when the
United States won the Women's World Cup in 1999. ``The United
States has more money,'' said Silje Joergensen, who plays defense
for Norway. ``They are rich.'' The countries are different, the
cultures are different, the economies are different. And, in the
end, the two soccer foes need each other. Sports of The Times
column by George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Sydney) _ Sports of The Times column on
Marion Jones' gold medal-winning performance in the 200 meters. By
William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ARATON-COLUMN (Sydney) _ If you had put it to a vote, polled
the Olympic community, I suspect it would have been a landslide
Slobodan Milosevic couldn't ignore. By the time it was announced
that Andreea Raducan wasn't getting her gold medal back, people
just wished the cute little gymnast could wipe away the tears and
go home happily to Romania to claim her $30,000 victory prize. Not
to be. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DRUGS-RADUCAN (Sydney) _ Andreea Raducan still can't believe
her gold medal for winning the gymnastics individual all-around
competition was stripped from her for taking a cold medication that
contained a substance banned by the International Olympic
Committee. And even Thursday, as the Court of Arbitration upheld
the IOC's decision, the 16-year-old continued to be mystified that
taking an over-the-counter drug, pseudoephedrine, that was
administered by the Romanian team doctor, could result in such a
drastic outcome. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BOX (Sydney) _ Cuban boxers win four of five fights,
including bantamweight Guillermo Rigondeaux's victory over Clarence
Vinson of the United States. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BOX-KAZAHKSTAN (Sydney) _ Nurgali Safiullin, an Olympic
boxing coach of Kazakhstan: ``Kazakhstani people originated from a
very warrior tribe, the Kipchaki. They've always been fighters.
They know how to fight.'' At the 2000 Sydney Games, Kazakhstan is
proving its point. A nation of 14 million, it has four fighters in
the medal round of the boxing tournament. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKO-GAZE (Sydney) _ Andrew Gaze has led Australia's charge
into the men's basketball semifinals, where, after Thursday's
quarterfinal victory against Italy, it will face France. The United
States will play Lithuania. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DIV (Sydney) _ Two systems for developing divers were on
display at the Olympic Park Aquatic Center Thursday night, and the
results were as defining as Fu Mingxia's nearly flawless technique.
Fu won the women's 3-meter springboard title by surpassing her
Chinese teammate, Guo Jingjing, on the final two dives. With the
victory, she joined two Americans, Greg Louganis and Pat McCormick,
as the only divers to win four Olympic gold medals, and she became
the first female diver to win five career medals. She also
continued the Chinese dominance that has accounted for eight medals
so far in this diving competition. By Bill Brink.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SAIL (Sydney) _ In sight of the famous waterside Opera House
and the Olympic rings emblazoned across the Sydney Harbor Bridge,
the U.S. crews of J.J. Isler and Pease Glaser, and Paul Foerster
and Bob Merrick, raced to silver medals Thursday afternoon in the
waning days of the Olympic regatta. Competing in the men's and
women's divisions of the doublehanded 470 dinghy, the twin silvers
represented the best results for the U.S. sailing team in two
Olympiads. But, unfortunately for the Americans, it came on the
greatest day ever for the Australian Olympic sailing squad. By Herb
McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-VOL-WOMEN (Sydney) _ Russia ended the U.S. women's team's
unlikely run with a 5-set victory. The Americans, underdogs in the
tournament, will play Brazil for the bronze. Cuba will get a chance
to go for an unprecedented third straight gold medal against
Russia. By John Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TEN (Sydney) _ Venus and Serena Williams win the gold medal
in women's doubles. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TAE (Sydney) _ Patience and a penalty point helped propel
Steven Lopez of Sugar Land, Texas, to a gold medal Thursday in the
Korean martial art of taekwondo, 1-0. By Walter Barranger.
</P>
