<HEADLINE>
$ADV03 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, Oct. 03, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight offers your choice of hard-fought contests _ either a
presidential debate or an American League baseball playoff game. At
deadline, we only know the contestants in the debate. Baseball, if
that's what you're looking for, will be on NBC at 8.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, of arguably larger significance to the republic,
begins at 9 on ABC, CBS, PBS, C-Span and some, if not all, of the
cable news channels. Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George
W. Bush will meet at the University of Massachusetts in Boston for
90 minutes of questions and answers and rebuttals. PBS stalwart Jim
Lehrer moderates. The format is said to favor experienced debater
Gore, so the real battle here may be Al versus high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Building Big,'' PBS at 8: Premiere. The great explainer David
Macaulay (``The Way Things Work'') begins a series about
structures. Tonight, he crosses bridges, including, natch, the
Brooklyn and the Golden Gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jag,'' CBS at 8: Season premiere. Harm and the gang get
tangled up with Russian plotters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC at 8: Guess which network
will have the best debate ratings. Regis Philbin hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Angel,'' Fox at 9: Two-hour premiere of a cyber-noir
drama series from ``Titanic'' and ``Terminator'' director James
Cameron. Newcomer Jessica Alba is terrific as a bike messenger with
souped-up DNA trying to elude the shadowy government agency that
made her that way. Her main ally in post-apocalyptic Seattle is a
high-tech Internet muckraker (Michael Weatherly). It's a little
``Blade Runner,'' a little ``X-Files,'' a little ``Max Headroom.''
And Alba is more than a little sexy. But she can't be brooding atop
the Space Needle in every episode _ the budget can't be that big.
And we have to wonder how many people want their drama this dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show,'' Fox at 8: Season premiere. When last seen,
Hyde was taking a pot rap for Jackie, and now he's taking the
consequences, including getting thrown out of the Formans' house.
Once again this show looks set to score big laughs while touching
on a surprising amount of the confusion and pathos of 1970s teen
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' WB at 8: Buffy (Sarah Michelle
Gellar) and her ``new'' sister Dawn (Michelle Trachtenberg) get
tangled up with some vamps as well as some sisterly conflicts. And
no, we still don't know what's up with the whole ``new sister''
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angel,'' WB at 9: Mysteries of an abandoned hotel in Hollywood
carry ghosts of the McCarthy era.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We've never done a double entry before, but why not sit the kids
down tonight and watch the debate with them? It's probably a
homework assignment anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Bull,'' TNT at 10: Ryan O'Neal guests tonight as Ditto's
long-lost father. Repeats at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City,'' HBO at 11: Charlotte and Samantha get into
it. A repeat of Sunday's episode.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: The elegant
Christine Baranski, who happens to have a new show on CBS tomorrow
night, and punk rockers Green Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Yasmine Bleeth,
Jackie Chan and musical guest Phish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05 a.m.:
TBA. Presumably they'll hash over the debate, whoever they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35: Sylvester
Stallone, talking about ``Get Carter,'' we presume, and Heather
Page Kent, talking about her new CBS series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Andy Richter
returns for a visit, and the musical guests are The Corrs.
</P>
