<P>
   FDA-ABORTION-PILL (Undated) _ In a major victory for supporters
of abortion rights, the Food and Drug Administration ended an
18-year standoff and announced that it had approved the marketing
of an abortion-inducing pill, the first alternative to surgical
abortion approved in the United States. Political fallout is
expected. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ A growing percentage of women who
are treated for early-stage breast cancer are getting inappropriate
treatment, a new study has found. Researchers found that women who
are getting lumpectomies are not all getting radiation or having
lymph nodes examined, lapses that could lead to recurrence of
disease. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-CLIMATE (Washington) _ In anticipation of the next
round of global climate talks in The Hague, the Senate is holding a
hearing on the Kyoto climate accord. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   S.C.-SAUCE-RELIGION (Columbia, S.C.) _ Maurice Bessinger's
famous mustard BBQ sauce is being pulled from grocery shelves all
across South Carolina, and not because he refuses to use tomatoes.
Bessinger, who once waged a lawsuit to keep blacks segregated in
his restaurants, has been distributing religious tracts along with
his sandwiches that suggest slavery was biblically ordained, and
that slaves were better off than they were in Africa. By David
Firestone.
</P>
