   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news category)
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-AD-COLUMN (Sydney, Australia) _ Sydney has gone further
than any previous host city of the Olympics to protect its official
sponsors from being ambushed by rivals. Although non-sponsor
companies are visible here, Sydney has little of the flea-market
ambience that made the Atlanta Games a byword for crass
commercialism. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALLS (Dateline to come) _ Ford Motor Co. said it will
give consumers a choice of tires from three different companies _
Michelin, Goodyear and Bridgestone/Firestone _ for future versions
of the Explorer. (Byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Caracas, Venezuela) _ Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah
told leaders at the OPEC summit meeting that Saudi Arabia, the
world's biggest producer, is prepared to produce whatever amount of
oil is necessary to stabilize prices. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   BIOENGINEER-CORN (Plainview, Texas) _ It is a variety of
bioengineered corn supposedly fit only for animal feed. But somehow
it seems to have wound up in taco shells in stores nationwide.
Finding its source, somewhere in the Texas Panhandle, is proving to
be a challenge. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ An interview with German O. Gref,
Russia's 36-year-old economics minister, who is under orders from
President Vladimir Putin to cut taxes and bureaucracy to insure
long-term growth and restore faith among investors who have grown
cynical about Russia's future. By Sabrina Tavernise.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Short items on business news from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news category or as indicated)
