<P>
   RUSKIN-CENTENARY (New York) _ Much has been made of John Ruskin
(1819-1900) this year. It is the centenary of the death of this
artist, art and architectural critic extraordinaire, social
reformer, polymath lecturer, first official professor of art in
England (at Oxford University) and an admirer of little girls. The
Morgan Library has mounted its own show of Ruskiniana, a
biographical assemblage of 133 objects: letters, manuscripts,
photographs, drawings, paintings and artifacts. They were mined
entirely from the Morgan's own Ruskin collection, proclaimed by the
library to be one of the world's most comprehensive. By Grace
Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   BIOGRAPHY-THEATER (New York) _ The odds are you have never heard
of the star of ``Lifegame,'' the piquant, oddly touching new
offering from the ever-resourceful Improbable Theater. This latest
work from the young British troupe that turned Scotch tape into
ectoplasm in ``70 Hill Lane,'' the real-life haunted-house drama
that was their maiden outing in New York, is now turning instant
biography into instant, multiform theater. By Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   MOMA-2000 (New York) _ On ``Open Ends,'' the third and final leg
of ``MoMA2000,'' the millennium-marking group show that has taken
up every inch of gallery space at the Museum of Modern Art for the
last year. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   PELLEAS-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ On the Metropolitan Opera's
production of Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande.'' Reviewed by Paul
Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   GIRLFIGHT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Girlfight,'' Karyn Kusama's
sweet and fierce directorial debut, deals with the new phenomenon
of women who box by following a fairly standard sports melodrama
story line: We see a lot of hard training, a few triumphs and
setbacks, all on the way to the big fight at the end. Reviewed by
A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   FAITHLESS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Here's an unsettling thought:
The hardest lessons we learn in life (and maybe the only lessons we
truly absorb) are those learned too late. It is precisely this
sense of nagging regret and the compulsion to comb obsessively over
decisions we can't undo that haunts the characters in Liv Ullmann's
morose and profound film, ``Faithless.'' Reviewed by Stephen
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Martin Baumann or A Sure
Thing,'' by David Leavitt, Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
