   OLY-SOC-WOMEN (Sydney) _ Dagny Mellgren's goal in overtime gives
Norway a 3-2 victory over the defending Olympic champion United
States in the women's soccer final. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN (Sydney) _ Back in Norway, they heard
about the victory tour, the commercials, the sponsorships, when the
United States won the Women's World Cup in 1999. ``The United
States has more money,'' said Silje Joergensen, who plays defense
for Norway. ``They are rich.'' The countries are different, the
cultures are different, the economies are different. And, in the
end, the two soccer foes need each other. Sports of The Times
column by George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TRACK (Sydney) _ The day's highlights: Marion Jones, already
the 100-meter champion, resumed her five-medal quest by adding the
200 title in 21.84 seconds, winning by almost a half-second. She
competes in the long jump final Friday. Ivan Pedroso of Cuba took
the men's long jump. Konstantinos Kenteris of Greece upset the
favorites in the men's 200. China's Wang Liping won the women's
20-kilometer walk after Australian Jane Saville was disqualified.
Erki Nool of Estonia won the Olympic decathlon, overtaking Chris
Huffins of Indianapolis who led through nine events. Huffins ended
up third. Yanina Karolchik of Belarus took the women's shot put. By
Christopher Clarey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DRUGS-RADUCAN (Sydney) _ Andreea Raducan still can't believe
her gold medal for winning the gymnastics individual all-around
competition was stripped from her for taking a cold medication that
contained a substance banned by the International Olympic
Committee. And even Thursday, as the Court of Arbitration upheld
the IOC's decision, the 16-year-old continued to be mystified that
taking an over-the-counter drug, pseudoephedrine, that was
administered by the Romanian team doctor, could result in such a
drastic outcome. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BOX-KAZAHKSTAN (Sydney) _ Nurgali Safiullin, an Olympic
boxing coach of Kazakhstan: ``Kazakhstani people originated from a
very warrior tribe, the Kipchaki. They've always been fighters.
They know how to fight.'' At the 2000 Sydney Games, Kazakhstan is
proving its point. A nation of 14 million, it has four fighters in
the medal round of the boxing tournament. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-DIV (Sydney) _ Two systems for developing divers were on
display at the Olympic Park Aquatic Center Thursday night, and the
results were as defining as Fu Mingxia's nearly flawless technique.
Fu won the women's 3-meter springboard title by surpassing her
Chinese teammate, Guo Jingjing, on the final two dives. With the
victory, she joined two Americans, Greg Louganis and Pat McCormick,
as the only divers to win four Olympic gold medals, and she became
the first female diver to win five career medals. She also
continued the Chinese dominance that has accounted for eight medals
so far in this diving competition. By Bill Brink.
</P>
