<SLUG> BC-FILM-URBANIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNTANGLING `URBANIA' A CHORE WITH REWARDS ALONG THE WAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CHRISTOPHER KELLY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Urbania'' takes place in a dark and gloomy New York City where
something weird seems to be going on. Charlie (Dan Futterman), a
gay West Villager, is searching for a particular man. He goes to
the bar where the man is said to be a regular _ but he isn't there.
So Charlie heads out into the night where he has all sorts of
unusual encounters _ with a bisexual soap opera actor (Gabriel
Olds), an old friend who is dying of AIDS (Alan Cumming), and the
straight guy who lives in the apartment above his (Bill Sage).
Along the way, there are also some cryptic flashbacks _ to a
boyfriend (Matt Keeslar) Charlie seems to have once had, and to
some violent encounter involving a bunch of leather-jacket-clad
men.
</P>
<P>
   What's it all mean? The fun of these sorts of movies (think of
Quentin Tarantino's ``Reservoir Dogs'') is in piecing together what
bizarre thing has happened to justify all the erratic behavior on
display. The problem with them (Neil Jordan's
brilliant-but-maddening ``The Miracle'' comes to mind) is that when
the final twist turns out to be not quite the earth-shattering
revelation you were hoping for, the entire movie starts to seem
like much ado about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The concluding scenes of ``Urbania'' aren't quite that bad, but
they are a letdown. (As the film drags on into a sentimental
denouement set in a blindingly white apartment that I think is
supposed to be heaven, they also prove painfully mawkish.) The
director, Jon Shear, makes another mistake by stringing a
distracting and unnecessary subplot about urban legends through the
movie. (By the way, can we place a moratorium on the one _ also
seen in last week's ``Urban Legends: Final Cut'' _ about the person
who has sex with a stranger and then finds that his or her kidneys
have been removed?)
</P>
<P>
   And yet, ``Urbania,'' shot in dark blues and blacks on super 16,
and then blown up digitally to 35mm, has style to burn. The large
ensemble cast is uniformly compelling. And there's one scene that
offers the most convincing portrait of homosexual seduction I've
seen since Gregg Araki's 1992 ``The Living End'' _ with Charlie
going up to the soap opera actor's apartment, and the two of them
acting out an uncommonly menacing (and ultimately disastrous)
erotic ``pas de deux.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era when gay cinema is defined by candy-colored,
empty-headed cartoons about the beautiful and self-obsessed
(''Trick,'' ``Kiss Me,'' ``Guido''), such achievements should not
be taken lightly.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Urbania''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jon Shear
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Dan Futterman, Alan Cumming
</P>
<P>
   Length: 103 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, strong language and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Christopher Kelly is film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5010 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BEAUTIFUL-TEX     09-28 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BEAUTIFUL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINNIE DRIVER PLAYS UNPLEASANT CHARACTER IN `BEAUTIFUL'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minnie Driver has made a career of playing likable, plucky
women, in movies as diverse as 1995's ``Circle of Friends'' and
this year's ``Return to Me.'' Actors get bored, though, and it's
easy to understand their attempts to stretch or to resist being
pigeonholed by playing against type.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Beautiful,'' Driver overdoes it as Mona, a perpetual
beauty-pageant contestant whose attractive exterior masks a
self-absorbed and misanthropic interior. Actually, that might not
be totally fair to Driver, who plays the role passionately _ it's
really writer Jon Bernstein who overdoes it, by making Mona's
desire to win border on the sociopathic. Either way, she's such an
unpleasant character that only the most tolerant will be able to
embrace her.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein tries to justify Mona's behavior by contriving a bad
upbringing for her; her mother belittles Mona's frequent
beauty-pageant entries, and her stepfather appears to want to crawl
into bed with her. But the early scenes, with Colleen Rennison as a
12-year-old Mona, already portray her as so obnoxious that you may
find yourself siding with her mom. It's also curious how the movie
includes the sleazy near-molestation scene, only to never broach
the subject again.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of an unsupportive mother comes up again when Mona
gets pregnant and has her best friend (Joey Lauren Adams) adopt the
child (''Pepsi Girl'' Hallie Kate Eisenberg) because motherhood
would make Mona ineligible to enter beauty pageants (considering
how inconsequential men are to this movie, perhaps Mona should have
scored points by saying it was a virgin birth). The movie then
hinges on whether Mona will acknowledge that she's the real mom.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Sally Field makes her feature-directing debut with
``Beautiful,'' and it's an interesting choice for an actress who
had to win an Emmy and two Oscars before she believed that her
peers liked her. Field never finds a consistent tone, although the
movie is generally either irritating or cloying. It's usually the
latter during the soppy beauty-pageant finale, which seems to play
out in real time and results in a ``surprise'' ending that won't
fool anyone. And the overriding idea _ that beautiful people can be
very mean and that plain-looking ones can be very nice _ is both
familiar and shallow.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Beautiful''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Minnie Driver
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
