<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5027 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-AIDS-VICTIM-ART-BOS &LR;      09-28 1559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VICTIM-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 IN MAINE JAIL, A PRISONER OF LIFE SUFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ Dean Mallis is cold.
</P>
<P>
   His 65-pound frame writhes beneath a gray blanket. Empty milk
cartons are strewn on the floor of his cell. He nuzzles his face
into a gray plastic mattress, which is smeared with blood.
</P>
<P>
   A door clangs in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut up!'' he screams back.
</P>
<P>
   Mallis, 26, has late-stage AIDS. He will die soon. Of this,
there is no doubt. He is being held in the Cumberland County Jail
on charges of sexually abusing a mentally retarded man. But despite
his itinerant, sociopathic past, practically no one here _ not
local police, corrections officials, lawyers or doctors _ believes
he should die in this jail. He should be in a hospital, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But he remains behind bars, slowly dying.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely web of legal circumstances has left him stranded in
jail. Typically, dying inmates are taken to hospices or nursing
homes or hospitals. Many prisons have them in house. To a large
degree, the modern American penal system has come to embrace the
idea of death with dignity, no matter how distasteful the criminal.
</P>
<P>
   But Mallis, a lifelong drifter with no address and no family
support, is the exception. He continues to lie in his cell, fixated
on his slow descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you call a dying spot,'' he said in an interview
in his dank isolation cell.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Maine court system has essentially given up on trying
him, the judge in the case won't set bail because of Mallis's
history of violence. And Mallis has downright frightened officials
since his jailing in July: Almost daily, he would jab his arms with
pencils or gouge his thighs and try to smear deputies with his
HIV-infected blood.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Maine law prohibits the judge from sending him to a
hospital until a doctor confirms he is close to death. But the
state says it has been unable to find a doctor willing to examine
him. So, Mallis stays where he is.
</P>
<P>
   The case has saddened and frustrated everyone involved. Some
have been transformed: a handful of tough-talking sheriff's
deputies have become like gentle, doting nurses, laboring to
provide their patient with minimal comfort despite the abuse he
heaps on them.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, Dean Mallis's dilemma has left them all wondering
how a man's life could turn out so pitifully.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a human being,'' says deputy Ben Smith. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one touches Mallis anymore.
</P>
<P>
   A recent visitor had to don rubber gloves, goggles, a surgical
mask and a full-body smock before entering his cell. Aside from a
few deputies, who take similar precautions, no one is allowed in
his cell, not even his only supporter, Donald Goudreau, 58,
Mallis's lover of seven years.
</P>
<P>
   How are you feeling?
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrible. Like always,'' he said. ``I'll probably die. I don't
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallis's speech is more a mumble, his words interrupted by blood
and phlegm. No one is sure what he is dying of. HIV has decimated
his immune system but, because he has not been properly examined
and diagnosed, the infection killing him is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been sick for a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Mallis was at one time prescribed
a daily regimen of 35 protease inhibitor pills, the so-called AIDS
cocktail that has increased the life expectancy of many people with
HIV. But he refused to take the pills, according to the documents
and Goudreau.
</P>
<P>
   He has told Goudreau he was infected with HIV at age 6. He has
also said he was abandoned by family at the same age. No one is
really sure.
</P>
<P>
   Mallis's body is covered with lesions. He can only consume milk,
ice cream and, occasionally, junk food. When he was first jailed in
July he weighed 120 pounds. Now he may be just over half that.
</P>
<P>
   He can barely muster the strength to reach the silver metal
toilet on the wall of his cell, often relieving himself on the bed.
He has a chronic cough, sleeplessness and severe joint and muscle
pain, he said. He gets irregular doses of painkillers or sleeping
pills from the jail's small infirmary. No one is sure when he will
die, though most who care for him predict Mallis has but weeks
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be in a hospital. No doubt about it,'' said Smith,
who is charged with cleaning Mallis's cell twice weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The isolation cell is long and narrow, with gray cinder block
walls, a cold tile floor, and a thin window. Mallis's mattress is
in one corner, a toilet in another. A few hours after the cell is
cleaned, it is stained with blood, spit, urine and food again, said
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Mallis said he wants to die at his ``friend's house.'' But
Goudreau said he cannot care for Mallis. Goudreau said he would
check him into a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Mallis now assumes he will die alone in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't nothing anybody can do about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his mind has gone blank. He barely recalls his family.
He does not reflect on his life, though he said he has no regrets.
He does not think of God or an afterlife or anything remotely
spiritual. He is not sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Past is unclear &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not much is known about Mallis's life. He attended the Harbor
School in Newbury for emotionally troubled children, according to
the school's records, though the school would not specify when.
</P>
<P>
   Mallis and Goudreau hooked up seven years ago, after Goudreau's
former lover died of AIDS. They met in a restaurant, when Mallis
was 19. The two lived in a series of motels. Mallis's address on
court papers is listed as ``transient.''
</P>
<P>
   Goudreau said Mallis enjoyed watching football and wrestling,
listening to hard rock music, and especially cruising around in
Goudreau's car.
</P>
<P>
   But Mallis's court record reveals a far more volatile
personality.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he had a brief affair with a 69-year-old man in
Haverhill. A month after they moved in together, Mallis attacked
the man with a glass shard, stabbing him twice in the back and
breaking his nose, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   Then, standing over the wounded older man, Mallis tortured the
man's seven cats to death, one by one, depositing the carcasses on
his terrified victim, said police.
</P>
<P>
   Attempted murder charges against him were dropped, and he spent
4 1/2 months in a Massachusetts jail for assault and cruelty to
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last year came another violent outburst. Mallis was
charged with holding a mentally retarded 40-year-old drifter
hostage in a Kennebunk motel for nine days. There, he allegedly
repeatedly sexually assaulted the man, poured salad dressing on
him, and beat him with kitchen utensils, according to police. The
older man escaped and was found nervously jabbering to himself in
the motel lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Mallis was released on a reduced bail of $500, on charges of
reckless conduct with a dangerous weapon, aggravated assault,
unlawful sexual conduct and two charges of gross sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, he was found with knives while on a joyride. He was
arrested again. And again he was released, on the condition that he
find a permanent place to live and stay there unless he needed to
visit a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   He did none of this. Instead, one day, he allegedly showed up at
the AIDS Project, a counseling center in Portland, screaming
obscenities and threatening counselors. He was arrested again.
Frightened employees at the AIDS Project told police that Mallis
frequently harassed them, on occasion rubbing his bleeding sores on
their office equipment, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   He has been in jail since then. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
His last hope &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mallis's original trial date, in August, was postponed after he
threatened to bite or spit on court employees. York County Superior
Court Judge Andre Janelle indefinitely put off the case. Given his
declining health, the case will probably never come to trial, said
Mallis's court-appointed lawyer James R. Bushell.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Mallis's history of troublemaking, the judge
overseeing his case refuses to grant bail in order for him to be
sent to a hospital or nursing home. A second option would be to
declare him a public menace, in which case the Maine Department of
Human Services can take custody of him. Last week, it refused to do
so. The judge and DHS have not explained their reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   The only other option is to convince the judge that Mallis is
close to death. In that case, Maine law would allow him to be
transferred to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I need is a definitive, authoritative opinion saying,
`This man is so ill that it's a crime to keep him in jail,' '' said
Bushell.
</P>
<P>
   Bushell requested that DHS find an AIDS specialist to examine
Mallis. Last week, the agency said it was unable to.
</P>
<P>
   Bushell is attempting to get permission to have Mallis checked
out in early October at a once-a-week AIDS clinic run at the nearby
Maine Medical Center. This is Mallis's last hope for release.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things have come together and we can't seem to find a
way out of this,'' said Bushell. ``But I'd like to see him in a
hospice or a home dying with some dignity rather than all by
himself in a dark, dingy jail cell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
