<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-MEN-YOGA-ART-BOS &LR;      09-28 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEN-YOGA-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MANY MEN FINDING YOGA NOT JUST FOR WOMEN ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe the guys finally noticed that celebrities like Kareem
Abdul-Jabber, John McEnroe and Sting were doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it's because more mainstream health clubs began
offering it alongside aerobics and Nautilus, and dropped some of
the chanting and incense-burning that aliened those who think
sweat, not spiritualism, defines a good workout.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, yoga is showing a more masculine side these
days. Men almost equal women in some classes and more strenuous
forms of yoga _ often dubbed Power Yoga as opposed to its Sanskrit
name, Ashtanga Yoga _ are soaring in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jock mentality gets put off by all the funny-sounding
names and Eastern baggage,'' said Michael Preston, a yoga teacher
at the Mt. Auburn Athletic Club in Watertown, Mass. for the past 10
years. ``But it's all changing. Yoga is becoming more mainstream
for men.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoga's reputation as a New Age feminine haven is being
challenged by an influx of middle-age male enthusiasts, recently
humbled into realizing they don't have the body of a 20-year-old.
Even younger men, often more open to Eastern-style pursuits, are
crediting yoga with giving them the agility and strength to improve
their overall athletic life _ and incidentally too, a more relaxed
mindset.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Maca, 35, said he is a better hiker and surfer because of
yoga, and he has gone far beyond caring if yoga has any public
relations woes in the male world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem if people think this is a girlie thing,'' he
said while at the Baptiste Power Yoga Institute in Cambridge,
Mass., owned by the celebrity yoga teacher, Baron Baptiste.
</P>
<P>
   So mainstream has yoga become that many men are quick to say
it's a great way to meet women, and they give exaggerated sighs of
disappointment that hordes of men now carry yoga mats.
</P>
<P>
   Construction worker Patrick McAuliffe, 45, says co-workers give
him ``funny looks'' when he takes off his hard hat and boots to
attend yoga classes. But he wonders if yoga's benefits aren't
becoming clear on the job: McAuliffe said his back is usually agile
and pain-free when lifting heavy objects, ``while the younger
workers are full of aches.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ramani Rangan, a yoga teacher for more than 20 years, said
yoga may have an image problem that crosses both genders, as many
women also scoff at an activity that can often seem cult-like.
Voice-mail greetings at some yoga centers begin with ``Namaste,'' a
Sanskrit greeting that refers to a person's internal light greeting
another person's internal light.
</P>
<P>
   While national data is scarce, it's clear Americans are flocking
to yoga in great numbers. About 10 million people participated in
yoga at least a few times each week in 1998, about double the
number in 1994, according to Yoga Journal, a trade journal for yoga
centers.
</P>
<P>
   And men appear to be the fastest growing audience for yoga. In
1994, women _ mostly urban educated females _ represented 80
percent of yoga students. Men made up about 20 percent of classes
back then, but instructors today say the male numbers have gone up
dramatically, and some classes, particularly at health clubs, have
a nearly even male-female split.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kennedy, a physical therapist at the Boston Athletic
Club, said middle-aged men _ careful to avoid the Sensitive Male
image many of them ridicule _ will often reluctantly try yoga if
it's presented as a clinical referral of sorts, a form of physical
therapy to help an ailing back or torn tendon.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys want me to tell the yoga teacher that they're there
for a bad back,'' said Kennedy. ``It's like, `I'm only in this
class because my physical therapist made me go.'''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Kennedy said, these men get hooked on the physical and
mental benefits of this 5,000-year-old tradition from India.
</P>
<P>
   Yoga's benefits come at all ages, but physicians say adults
beyond age 30 may be helped the most because that's when they often
begin to notice the tightening of their tendons, ligaments and
muscles near their joints. The muscle tightening has largely to do
with the inactivity of adults as they get busy with jobs and
families, but also the natural loss of flexibility in supporting
tissues, just as elasticity is lost in aging skin.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Helene Feiler, a physician who specializes in sports
medicine, said yoga and other stretching exercises may help reverse
the tightening process that can lead to injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Celtics athletic trainer Ed Lacerte said he recalled that
legendary center Robert Parish credited Eastern-style exercise,
such as tai chi, with giving him the flexiblity to stay in the game
so long. Lacerte said today's Celtics players don't seem to have an
interest in these pursuits, but ``any way you get variety'' in
stretching is a good thing for any athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Winning men over to yoga hasn't been easy. Paula Kout, a yoga
teacher hired in October 1997 by then-Chicago Bulls coach Phil
Jackson to instruct the team, confronted the male skepticism on her
first day on the job. ``It was like being in a room full of
13-year-old adolescents,'' she recalled, noting that some were
there only because Jackson threatened to fine them otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Kout said any time she would do a ``correction'' on a player,
such as touch their legs or hips to adjust a position, there would
be a roar of laughter from the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to give yoga a more mainstream feel has also been a goal
at the Kripalu Center for Yoga and Health in Lenox, Mass., the
country's largest yoga center with about 20,000 visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Foust, its curriculum director, said in the past year,
the center has introduced new courses such as Yoga and Golf, Yoga
and Skiing, as well as Yoga and Canoeing, all of which appeal
largely to men.
</P>
<P>
   He said they are also more sensitive to the fact that yoga terms
can seem particularly alien to many Americans. For instance, the
Sanskrit term ``ujjayi'' refers to one of the main breathing
techniques in yoga. Now, he said, many teachers refer to them as
``centering breaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Few were more skeptical about yoga than Don Murray, 65, the
retired president of the union representing the Boston police
officers. He said it seemed like a passive activity meant for women
who like to meditate.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray now refers to himself playfully as a ``disciple'' of
yoga, after getting hooked in his first class three years ago at
his health club. He said yoga explains why he maintains his lean
frame of 5-feet, 11-inch and 168 pounds and runs the Boston
Marathon year after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone are the days when I just put my leg on a fence, bent over
and that was my stretching,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
