<HEADLINE>
&HT; 
SITE OF THE WEEK
</HEADLINE>
bc-DIGITAL-SITE
cc,78p3  (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
-Gigawit.com: A new comedy and publishing site headed by Tony
Hendra, the former National Lampoon editor who also played the band
manager in ``This Is Spinal Tap.'' &QL; 
-Where: www.gigawitt.com. &QL; 
-What's cool: Hendra pumped out ``The Gigawit Dictionary of the
E-nglish Language,'' a less-than-earnest spoof of the overly
earnest jargon that suffuses so much of the Web world. By
registering on the site, you can read the first chapter of the
dictionary, and of course, you can buy the book and much else
directly from the site. &QL; 
-Features: Hendra is selling other goodies, such as posters that
show a mountain scene defined, for the sake of cubicle-penned
geeks, as ``offline''; the chance to contribute to works in
progress, such as moderately sacrilegious ``Real Conversations With
God''; and some simple animation that has its moments.  &QL; 
-You'll like this if: You're getting tired of online humor pitched
at boys ages 16 to 24. The site's offerings are still thin, as
could be expected with a new site, but with time and audience
participation, could turn into something quite fun.  &QL;
</TEXT>
