<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY SAYS CALIFORNIA HOUSING SUPPLY TO REMAIN TIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's housing supply has lagged behind
the population influx from strong immigration and blazing job
growth, a problem that will be exacerbated in the next two decades,
according to a new forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration into California will approach the high levels of the
1980s, but the rate of home building is unlikely to keep pace,
according to the forecast by the University of California at Los
Angeles. Economists from the university study the long-term
economic trends for the state and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The planners and the politicians and major watchdog groups
have to sit down and work it out, starting now,'' said UCLA
economist Rajeev Dhawan, the author of the report. ``Otherwise,
there's a chance that growth will fizzle. Quality of life issues
are so important.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing permits in California are expected to average 187,000
per year over the next 20 years, a much slower pace compared with
the economic boom of 1985 to 1990, when building permits averaged
245,000 annually, the forecast said.
</P>
<P>
   The shortfall is all the more acute in the San Francisco Bay
Area, the epicenter of technology growth.
</P>
<P>
   Data from the Federal Home Finance Board show that home prices
for San Francisco, Oakland and San Jose in the second quarter of
the year averaged $389,000, or 98 percent higher than the national
average during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not rocket science to figure out the problem,'' said
Stephen Levy, executive director of the Center for the Continuing
Study of the California Economy, a think tank in Palo Alto. ``The
solution is to build more housing. It's the next biggest challenge;
it's not that somebody will invest in the next wave of technology
or that we'll go into recession.''
</P>
<P>
   The housing crunch is unlikely by itself to derail California's
growth, but could create a drag on the economy if high home prices
prompt residents to leave or dissuade newcomers from taking jobs
here, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Factors adding to the dilemma include a decline in housing
starts during the early 1990s recession, the strong fiscal
incentives for local governments that favor retail over housing
developments, and the growing income gap that allows wealthier
residents to bid up prices, said Dianne Spaulding, executive
director of the San Francisco-based Non-Profit Housing Association
of Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stuck, fighting over the scraps, landlords and
tenants,'' said Gabriel Metcalf, deputy director of the San
Francisco Planning and Urban Research Association (SPUR), a public
policy think tank. ``We need to get beyond zero-sum game and
increase housing.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting mismatch between supply and demand means many
people will have less living space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The luxury or dream of owning a three-bedroom house with a
yard, pool and two-car garage for a family of four is an American
icon that is coming under pressure even in land-rich states like
California,'' the UCLA report states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
