<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAPOR BARRIERS MAKE INSULATION EVEN BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Insulatian is the cheapest thing you can install in your house
to make it the most comfortable at the least cost. Fiberglass or
cellulose, and in some cases rigid materials, do indeed save you
big heating bucks.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not the be-all and end-all of saving heat; it is
important to have a vapor barrier wherever you have insulation.
And, the rule continues, vapor barriers should face the heated part
of the house, not the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Much insulation has a paper backing. This is the vapor barrier.
Anovapor barrier is polyethylene plastic. Rigid insulation is also
a vapor barrier.
</P>
<P>
   A vapor barrier stops the loss of air from the house to the
outdoors, therefore saving heat and making the insulation much more
effective. It also keeps water vapor from escaping.
</P>
<P>
   That's all well and good, but how do you get a vapor barrier in
an existing wall, or on the attic floor, or on the basement ceiling
where insulation is supposed to go?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy on the attic floor; just put in backed insulation,
with the paper facing down. For a basement ceiling, just the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   If there is insulation already between the joists on the attic
floor, and there is no vapor barrier, the only way to install one
is to take out the old insulation, install new insulation with
paper backing, or install polyethylene plastic, then put back the
old insulation or put in new, unbacked insulation.
</P>
<P>
   If that seems like too much, then forget it. While a vapor
barrier is good, it is not essential. Besides, the ceilings of
rooms below are painted, and most paints are vapor barriers of
varying degrees of effectiveness, so you do have some protection
from loss of air. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Yes, but in the walls? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, here's the biggest question: What do you do about walls?
Where insulation is blown in in old houses, there is no vapor
barrier and it is impossible to install one without tearing out the
walls, and let's not get into that chore.
</P>
<P>
   Never fear. Most wall paints are vapor barriers, and so are
vinyl-coated wallpapers and Walltex-Type coverings.
</P>
<P>
   What if you make the house too tight with all those vapor
barriers? Couldn't vapor and other pollutants build up in the house
where it has no place to go?
</P>
<P>
   That is impossible in an old house. You can do a lot in an old
house, but you cannot tighten it up that much without taking it
apart and rebuilding it.
</P>
<P>
   New houses are another matter. They can be built so tight that
you save a bundle in heating and air conditioning, but pay the
price by too much water vapor and other pollutants indoors. Water
vapor is a big hazard because it can condense inside the house into
water, and mold can grow.
</P>
<P>
   Also, water vapor buildup can peel paint right off the outdoor
siding. That is a common problem in New England and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   So, builders have developed an air-to-air heat exchanger, which
ventilates the house, releasing the vapor and other pollutants,
without losing heat.
</P>
<P>
   That solved, there are a couple of other things to consider when
insulating the house and making it tight and comfortable and cheap
to heat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Windows important, too &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of those things is windows, which can be a major heat loss.
Doors, reasonably tight and with storms, are less important because
they constitute such a small area (less than 5 percent) of your
house. The point is, there is less urgency to run out and buy one
or more steel insulated doors or any other kind.
</P>
<P>
   You may not have to run out to buy new windows, either. If your
ancient windows are weatherstripped, realatively tight and with
effecient storm windows, there is little need for new ones.
</P>
<P>
   But if for any reason you want new windows, consider replacing
just the sash, the movable parts. In a double hung window, the
sashes are the two pieces that slide up and down. In a casement
window, the sash is that part of the window that opens like a door.
</P>
<P>
   Most replacement companies install just the sash, avoiding
removal of the frame and casing, which do not need replacing
anyway. This can be done reasonably, at $150 to $250 per window.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to go with even less investment is to replace storm
windows with efficient ones. Such storms cost abut $100 each;
anything less expensive is not very efficient. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ventilate the attic . . . &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, now you really are snug as the proverbial bug. Anything
else?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes: ventilation. It has nothing to do with keeping the
house warm and saving fuel, but does help reduce and prevent
condensation of moisture anywhere indoors or out. Condensation is
not good, and especially on insulation, because water can destroy
insulation very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The most important areas for ventilation are the attic and
basement, where vents can be installed. In the attic, the best
vents are ridge vents that go along the entire length of the roof
ridge, and soffit vents, continuous two-inch-wide vents going the
full length of all soffits. The soffits, of course, are the under
parts of the roof overhang. If there is no overhang, you can
install ventilated drip edges.
</P>
<P>
   These vents are better than powered fans, and do more than just
pull out excessive water vapor. They also keep the attic cool in
summer and can be a major prevention of the dreaded ice dams of
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Attic vents should be left open at all times. &QL; 
 &QL; 
. . . and the basement, too &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ventilating the basement is important in summer, to remove
excessive water vapor and eliminate that dank, musty smell we are
so familiar with. Keep windows open, screen and secure them from
forced entry. If there are no windows, install vents. They can be
left open from April to October, closed in winter.
</P>
<P>
   One more place where ventilation is important to eliminate
condensation, is in cathedral ceilings, and other areas where there
is no attic above the living space.
</P>
<P>
   The ventilation is provided by a one-inch-thick air space
between insulation of a cathedral ceiling and the roof. This air
space must have moving air, so there must be vents at the top and
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Most new houses with cathedral ceilings have this air space, so
it should be of no concern to the homeowner.
</P>
<P>
   If you are building or installing a cathedal ceiling in an old
house, the air space is not just desired, it is essential.
</P>
<P>
   OK, your work is cut out for you. Let's do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
