<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-AUTHOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLIMBING THE LADDER MAY MEAN OVERTAKING THE BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tom Peters knows exactly what he doesn't want
his epitaph to say: ``He woulda done some really cool stuff, but
his boss wouldn't let him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sincerely believe that the biggest waste of time is selling
ideas up the chain of command,'' the best-selling business author
said recently. ``Anybody who ever made it into the history books
didn't ask their boss for permission to do a damn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Inept management and how to get around it were two themes hit
repeatedly by Peters, the author of ``In Search of Excellence'' and
many other business books, during a six-hour program that was part
of San Francisco State University's Lessons in Leadership series.
He said managers of many major businesses are out of touch when it
comes to competing in the Internet economy and expanding customer
base.
</P>
<P>
   Peters said many businesses are particularly clueless when it
comes to satisfying the largest economy on Earth: American women.
He also believes women will lead most companies within 20 years,
partly because so many male managers love rules and a tough chain
of command.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are crazy times and you have to be able to do 11 things
at a time,'' he said. ``And guys can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Women traditionally have been stronger than men at such things
as forming relationships, using intuition and not being threatened
by strong people, Peters said, and those are all qualities that
leaders need.
</P>
<P>
   He said companies often have an inadvertent form of corporate
suicide when they try to change themselves incrementally. That
makes it too easy for fresh, eager competitors to wipe them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ain't blowin' stuff up, then you ain't gonna create
stuff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peters pointed to the merger of NationsBank of Charlotte, N.C.,
and Bank of America of San Francisco. He said both companies were
already falling behind competitors in terms of innovation, and the
merger simply means they will spend years trying to combine two
out-of-date systems when they should be putting the energy into
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, Cisco Systems often handles mergers
adeptly, buying smaller companies with talented engineers and a
next-generation product. Cisco is buying talent, even if it costs
$3 million per engineer.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to how the European and U.S. economies changed from
1980 through 1998. The Europeans had few layoffs and added about 4
million jobs, mostly in government.
</P>
<P>
   During that same period, the United States wiped out 44 million
jobs. But, Peters quickly pointed out, it also created 73 million
jobs, for a net gain of 29 million _ more than seven times as many
new jobs as in Europe. He said all those jobs couldn't have been
added if companies weren't willing to lay off people and
restructure.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes workers who are ready for dramatic change are stuck
with bosses who are incrementalists. What do you do then? Peters
offers two suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Never accept an assignment as given.''
</P>
<P>
   There are usually ways to change it so that it accomplishes what
the company wants _ or at least most of it _ while allowing the
worker to feel challenged and innovative.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Create a personal University of Weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters calls it `F2F (freak to freak),'' hooking up with a peer
or someone else in the company who shares your vision. He said it's
often better if that person is as far away geographically as
possible, so that bosses are less likely to know what is going on
until you begin taking action.
</P>
<P>
   He said workers need to create or change projects so that they
fit into the category of ``wow!'' They need to find projects that
excite them, whether it's with their current company, a competitor
or on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you use words like `wow,' you will look at the world
through a different lens than if you use less passionate words,''
Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   Bosses often eliminate the chance for exciting projects because
they are so preoccupied with costs, he said. They don't realize how
much potential there can be if they have enthusiastic workers doing
exciting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Workers need to look at potential ``wow'' projects and think
about which ones will make a difference, and which ones will
involve raving fans _ people who share the enthusiasm for your idea
or work. They should talk about the idea with others who feel
passionately about it, then reduce it to five bullet points so it
comes into clear focus.
</P>
<P>
   Peters also said it's important for the workers to believe that
their projects are beautiful, not just functional. ``That's the
problem with most of them: They're competent, but they aren't
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
