<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON BACK WHERE HE WANTS TO BE: IN THE MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A lion without courage, a bee without its
sting, a boa that couldn't constrict . . . Ted Johnson without his
ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Johnson thought it was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to feel normal again,'' he said. ``My body is
starting to react the way it used to. My technique still needs
work, but physically I'm fine. I feel like I'm getting back up to
the speed of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And the toughness.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks back, when he was knocked on his rear 2 yards
down the field, Johnson didn't feel right. A couple of hits like
that got his competitive juices flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing to me when something like that happens,''
said Johnson. ``I'm known for being tough and aggressive and
getting the upper hand that way. That's my whole game. If I'm weak
in that area it affects the rest of it. I won't be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   After two torn biceps tendons, the mind game of `Will it happen
again?' has finally left him. He no longer thinks if he reaches
back to tackle a ballcarrier his season will be over. There's no
time to think about that when your team is 0-4 and you're facing
one of the best running games and offensive lines in football
Sunday in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   What a time for the ferocity to return. It couldn't have come
back at a better time for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell by watching Ted that he made a huge leap in
that game (last) Sunday,'' said tackle Chad Eaton. ``When Ted is
playing that way he makes everyone around him better. The rest of
us feed off of it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Johnson is back to his old self. One of
the things he is still getting used to is not calling the defensive
plays. That chore has fallen to Tedy Bruschi because Johnson missed
all of training camp and someone with experience, Bruschi, had to
take over.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the challenge of keeping up with Bill Belichick's
many defensive sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill changes them up every week,'' said Johnson. ``Sometimes I
find myself thinking about where I'm going to line up and thinking
about the technique I need to use. What I'm trying to guard against
is having all that affect my aggressiveness out there. Because it
can if you let it. You get so worried about being in the right
place and not making a mistake that you forget about what it is
that defines you as a player. I never want to lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd better not lose that. If he does the Patriots defense might
crumble. Stopping the run is critical to whether the Patriots will
be able to contain the high-powered Denver offense. The Patriots
know that Broncos quarterback Brian Griese has a shoulder problem
and it may affect his attempts to get the ball downfield to
receivers Rod Smith and Ed McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the entire team is focusing on getting one win,`` said
Johnson. ``We have to look at who we're playing, but not get caught
up in where we're playing or that it's hard to win where we're
playing. That's not even entering our minds right now. We all have
to do everything a little better. I know people are on our offense
right now, but if the defense can make some plays and help our
offense get to a place they need to be . . . that's the way we have
to approach it. I don't think anyone in this room has said we'll
never make it now. We're just not thinking that way. Nobody here is
demoralized like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson began his upswing two weeks ago against the Vikings when
he made 10 tackles. He backed it up last week with seven tackles
and a half-sack against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's finally reached the point where he's in game shape
and no longer has to motion to the sideline to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the fine-tuning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could get better at taking on blockers,'' said
Johnson, who in Belichick's one-gap system often is up against
guards. ``Sometimes I don't have the leverage that I need to shed
someone. I think that's the kind of stuff I would have gotten
accustomed to in training camp, but I didn't have training camp
(because of a pulled hamstring). I had to learn the stuff early in
the season, and I think now I'm making gradual improvement. Each
week I feel a little more comfortable with something.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said, ``Ted's done well in making up for lost time.
He's worked hard. From the Tampa Bay game on he hasn't missed any
practice time. I don't think he made as dramatic a leap from the
week before to last week as some would think. I think it's been a
gradual improvement and that's what you hope for from someone who
missed so much of camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has missed a lot of time the past two seasons, but now
that he's been hit a few times and, in Belichick's words, has seen
``how fast the treadmill is turning,'' Johnson appears up to the
task. The ferocity has returned. And Johnson isn't planning on
giving it up anytime soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
