<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BE CAREFUL HOW YOU CRITICIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nobody likes criticism, but sometimes it has to
be given, for the good of both the individual and the organization.
Good bosses critique employees regularly, mixing praise with
suggestions for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the person you want to criticize is a peer instead
of a subordinate?
</P>
<P>
   If workplaces came with a flashing yellow light, you would see
one about now. The best thing you could do is grab it and put it in
your mouth until the mood passes.
</P>
<P>
   You need to use extreme caution before criticizing a peer,
because the person most likely to get wounded is you. Still, there
are times when it has to be done, for the sake of your career, the
sake of the company or maybe even for the sake of the person being
criticized. Before you say anything, though, ask yourself these
questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Is criticism part of the culture?
</P>
<P>
   College newspapers often have staff meetings where they critique
each edition, with advisers and everyone else offering praise and
criticism for specific stories. It's all done in the open, and
students get used to it after a while.
</P>
<P>
   In those circumstances, the newspaper is encouraging peers to
criticize one another. But even then, the wrong kind of criticism
can backfire. A nasty comment about a one-time event _ ``that story
stunk'' _ causes embarrassment and resentment, but a constructive
suggestion about how the story could have been better is often
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   In another type of corporate culture, some managers just don't
listen to anything employees have to say. Maybe they say they will
listen, but all they do is stonewall every suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   If your company is like that, don't make the criticism. You are
taking a huge risk without any chance of being rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   _ Should you involve the boss?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to be seen as a back-stabber or tattletale if you go
running to the boss to resolve conflicts. Have you at least tried
to discuss the problem calmly with your co-worker? Have you checked
to see whether other peers have faced the same problem and managed
to resolve it?
</P>
<P>
   Once the boss gets involved, you are escalating the conflict.
You have made it a lot harder for your peer to just shrug, say
``OK, sure,'' and forget about the whole thing the next day.
</P>
<P>
   _ What do you hope to gain?
</P>
<P>
   Never criticize just for the sake of criticism. If someone is
driving you crazy, complain to a friend or a counselor or someone
else away from your office. Don't criticize a co-worker within the
office unless you have something substantial to gain.
</P>
<P>
   Are you part of a team, so that his performance reflects on you
and limits your chance for a raise or promotion? Do you have to
work longer hours because of his incompetence? Is he driving you so
crazy that you are ready to leave the company?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you can ease the situation by thinking a couple of moves
ahead. If your colleague is always making your team late, don't
wait until you are missing the deadline to speak up or it will
sound like finger-pointing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, give the boss an upbeat update a couple of days before
your deadline: ``The project is going great. As soon as we get the
research from Tom, we'll be all done.'' You are not criticizing Tom
because no mistake has been made, but you are letting the boss know
where the potential problem lies.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure, too, that you are not using your colleague as a
scapegoat. If your pay is tied to his performance, maybe you ought
to be arguing that the company has a pretty stupid policy instead
of faulting your co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do you have an accurate picture?
</P>
<P>
   In a lot of jobs, it's easy to think that you are a better
worker than you are because there aren't really any measurable
standards of performance. If you don't make sure your own
performance is solid before you go running to management, the whole
thing is liable to blow up in your face.
</P>
<P>
   You also need to understand your colleague's circumstances.
Maybe he has to answer to three departments, and management has
told him to give yours the short end. Make sure you have identified
the right target before you fire away.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can you phrase it another way?
</P>
<P>
   Think about how you would feel if someone made the same
criticism of you. Would you think it was a cheap shot?
</P>
<P>
   If you are talking to the person directly, you will get better
results if you say something like, ``Have you thought about doing
it this way?'' rather than pointing out weaknesses. Don't complain
unless you can suggest a solution.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the best way is to throw it in management's lap.
Rather than criticizing one of your techies, simply say, ``We'd be
a lot more productive if we had better technical support. All these
crashes are killing us.''
</P>
<P>
   For all you know, the techie might even agree with you. Maybe
he's been trying to get the company to upgrade its system, but
management has been blowing him off.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ignore the idea of damning someone with faint praise,
either. If you have three co-workers and you frequently praise the
other two, only a dolt of a boss will fail to get the message.
</P>
<P>
   _ Are you usually upbeat?
</P>
<P>
   If you complain once a year, it will get a lot more attention
than if you complain once a day. If you offer sincere praise from
time to time, the criticism also will carry more weight.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time for the moment of criticism, though, don't be
overly positive. Be understanding and do what you can to soften the
blow, but don't let the message get lost amid jokes, praise and
chatter. Do whatever you can to make the situation right, but make
sure it's clear there is a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: If your criticism doesn't solve the problem, it will
probably add to it. Proceed with caution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
