<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS PAIR OF ENDINGS IN NEED OF A REWRITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ This was not the way it was supposed to end for either
man. Carl Everett on crutches, unable to play. Pedro Martinez on
ice, with nothing left to pitch for.
</P>
<P>
   For both, so much accomplished. And yet, in terms of what both
players say matters most to them, so little achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no drive, you have no push,'' Martinez said,
explaining why there is no longer cause for him to test the limits
of his marvelous arm and swizzle-stick body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing to be going home, period, that's what's
disappointing,'' said Everett, who will accompany the team this
weekend to Tampa Bay, but will not see action after crumpling to
the ground Tuesday because of a tendon injury (peroneal tendon
subluxation) in his left ankle. ``I really don't have any personal
glory in going home. My whole thing is to get to the postseason, so
the entire season is a flop for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put up numbers, but if you don't go to the postseason
it means nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   While manager Jimy Williams admitted Tuesday that the prospect
of another rumble against the Devil Rays entered into the Sox'
thinking about whether Martinez would take his last turn in the
season finale Sunday, Martinez said that was only incidental to his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I wouldn't pitch against anybody,'' said Martinez, whose
five scoreless innings against the White Sox Tuesday put the
finishing touches on a season (18-6, 1.74 ERA, 284 strikeouts) that
will be rewarded with his third Cy Young Award, including the last
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be anybody. I don't really want to get into it (with
the Devil Rays). I'm not scared of going out there, but I don't
have anything to prove. What I had to prove, I proved it that day
to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect those players, even Gerald Williams, for what he
did. It's just part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That might come as a surprise to Dan Duquette, who labeled the
Devil Rays outfielder a ``thug'' for charging Martinez after he hit
Williams with a pitch leading off the game in Tropicana Field Aug.
29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just won't pitch,'' Martinez said, ``because I need to rest
more than I need to pitch that game.''
</P>
<P>
   While X-rays on his ankle were negative, Everett won't be taking
any more turns at the plate, either, after he took just a couple of
steps out of the batter's box Tuesday before falling while running
out a ground ball to short.
</P>
<P>
   He should have extra time to spend on the team dinner he is
planning to throw at a Tampa restaurant this weekend, though it
remains to be seen if the no-shows outnumber those who make use of
their invitations.
</P>
<P>
   Everett may have mixed his metaphors, but his message in an
interview with John Reyes, a 74-year-old Chicago radio personality,
had not strayed off course from what he has been saying in the last
sorry days of his first season in a Sox uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have rattled some feathers in this clubhouse,'' Everett told
Reyes, ``by speaking my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Another comment, made to a group of Boston reporters, probably
will not boost attendance at his party:
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been others who have spoken out,'' he said, ``that
probably shouldn't have spoken out without putting a name on it.
Those people, if you're going to say something, make sure your name
goes behind it. Only a coward runs and hides behind something.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone says something derogatory toward someone and
can't put their name behind it, then he's a coward.''
</P>
<P>
   Say this for Everett, who statistically did about all the Sox
expected when they traded for him: .300 average, 34 home runs, 70
extra-base hits, 108 RBIs in 137 games. He gave us advance warning
of what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why people change for other people,'' Everett was
quoted as saying in a Globe (sorry Carl, that paper) story April
11. ``If you don't like me for myself, I don't care. The guy I'm
going to give you is me, not somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett's ankle may be sore, but his persecution complex remains
intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should sum up the whole season, all the criticism has
been toward me,'' said Everett, who won't be calling Morrissey
Boulevard any time soon to place a subscription order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything said about me was a lie,'' he said. ``I'll always
stand behind that.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, here's something impossible to refute, regardless of whose
newsprint it appears on:
</P>
<P>
   In the last three months of the season Everett didn't hit close
to .300. He batted .262 with 3 home runs and 7 RBIs in a July
shortened by his 10-game suspension for bumping umpire Ron Kulpa.
He hit .275 with 6 home runs and 23 RBIs in August. And in just 74
at-bats in September, a month interrupted by a quadriceps injury
and now short-circuited by the ankle injury, Everett batted just
.270 with 2 home runs and 10 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   He hit 20 home runs in his first 49 games, 14 in his last 88. He
hit .329 with 24 homers and 69 RBIs before the break, .261 with 10
home runs and 39 RBIs after the break.
</P>
<P>
   And that's with Nomar Garciaparra, about to win his second
straight batting title, hitting behind him.
</P>
<P>
   If the bottom line is productivity, as his general manager
famously said last week, then maybe Everett should be the next one
asked to explain himself at lunch to CEO John Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Martinez, in an act of self-preservation at least as
sensible as skipping the Devil Rays, is steering clear of this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my little world,'' Martinez said. ``I don't stick my
nose out of it. I let Jimy do his job. I let my teammates do their
job. I help them go through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't stick my nose where it doesn't belong. I just keep
myself in my little world right here. If I talk, I talk to my
neighbor Ramon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
