<SLUG> BC-HASH-BROWNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEFTOVER POTATOES CAN SPROUT INTO ANOTHER MEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Hash browns do not have to come from the frozen
food section. Nor do they have to be time-consuming to make. Hash
browns, those wonderful breakfast potatoes, can be made quite
easily from a few leftover potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a chef's trick that's probably as old as dining out. Take
leftover potatoes and make them into another dish. It's also a good
way to use up some of those potatoes that are starting to age past
their prime.
</P>
<P>
   Got extra mashers? Make potato cakes, or duchesse potatoes or
shepherd's pie, or potato croquettes.
</P>
<P>
   Using leftover potatoes is limited only by your imagination.
But, there are a few basics to learn about potatoes first.
</P>
<P>
   Potatoes generally are divided into two groups: waxy and
starchy. Waxy potatoes include red-skinned potatoes, white
potatoes, blue potatoes, fingerlings and Yukon Golds. Starchy
potatoes include russets, also sold as ``Idaho'' or ``baking''
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Starchy potatoes are the best ones for mashed potatoes and for
baked potatoes. Their high-starch, low-sugar, low-moisture content
makes them cook up light, dry and mealy in texture, writes Wayne
Gisslen in ``Le Cordon Bleu Professional Cooking'' (Wiley, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Waxy potatoes, on the other hand, retain more moisture during
cooking and hold their shape well. Use these for parsleyed
potatoes, potato salads or other dishes where you'll be serving the
potatoes cut into chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever kind of potato you're using, look for spuds that are
firm and smooth. Avoid those that are soft, shriveled or have green
areas. Green patches, which have a bitter flavor, develop on
potatoes that have been stored improperly. Also avoid potatoes that
are sprouted as they are high in sugar. Instead, look for potatoes
with shallow eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking potatoes is a basic process, but you'll be surprised at
how much you don't know that could improve the results. Here are
several success tips gleaned from culinary textbooks:
</P>
<P>
   Baking:
</P>
<P>
   _ Scrub the potatoes and prick them with a fork before cooking,
but don't wrap them in foil. Foil-wrapping potatoes steams them
instead of baking them, a process not recommended with starchy
potatoes such as russets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Potatoes are quite beautiful but if you must hide them under a
layer of foil, wrap them just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you desire a crisp skin, rub the potato lightly with oil
before baking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bake at 400 degrees for about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Boiling:
</P>
<P>
   _ Peel and cut potatoes into uniform chunks so they will cook
evenly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Start potatoes in a pot of cold water since this also allows
for more even cooking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bring the potatoes to a boil, lower the heat and let simmer
until tender.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not cool potatoes in cold water, as they will become soggy.
</P>
<P>
   Mashing:
</P>
<P>
   _ Drain and allow the potatoes to steam dry in a colander or
return to pan and heat over the stove for a few minutes to dry for
fluffy potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heat your mashing or ricing tools by running them under hot
water to avoid cooling the potatoes and making them gummy.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the same reason, heat any milk, cream or butter prior to
adding them to the potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the potatoes as desired and then if there are leftovers,
use one of the recipes here to make a second potato dish.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   POTATO CAKES
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups leftover mashed potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 3/4 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, divide the leftover potatoes into 4 portions and
form each portion into a patty. Refrigerate the potato patties,
separated by wax paper and covered until ready to cook potato
cakes. Or, wrap the patties in wax paper and place in a freezer
bag. Freeze until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large skillet over medium-high heat. Add shortening and
wait until shortening is melted and smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully add potato patties to skillet, and fry on one side 3
minutes or until the bottoms of the cakes are golden. Turn
carefully and cook other side until golden, about 2 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from skillet and drain on paper towels before serving.
Season with salt and pepper as desired while still hot.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   HASH BROWNS
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 leftover potatoes, either baked or boiled and left whole
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Peel the potatoes and cut into cubes. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, heat oil over medium heat. Add potato cubes
and cook, stirring occasionally, until golden and heated through.
Remove from skillet with a slotted spoon, drain and season.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien potatoes: Cook 1/4 cup diced onion and 1/4 cup diced
green pepper in oil before adding potatoes. Remove from skillet,
drain and set aside. Place potatoes in skillet and cook as
directed. A minute or so before hash browns are done, add onions
and peppers. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DUCHESSE POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups leftover mashed potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, separated
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, combine leftover potatoes with egg yolk, butter,
salt, pepper and nutmeg. Place mixture in a pastry bag an pipe into
mounds into a baking sheet. If a pastry bag is not available,
simply spoon the potatoes into mounds.
</P>
<P>
   Place an inverted coffee cup on each corner of the baking pan.
Cover the pan with plastic or foil, using the coffee cups to
support the wrap. Refrigerate until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Gently brush each potato mound with egg white and bake until
lightly, browned, 3 to 5 minutes depending on the size of the
mounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adapted from ``Le Cordon Bleu Professional Cooking'' by Wayne
Gisslen (Wiley, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SHEPHERD'S PIE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 10 servings)
</P>
<P>
   5 cups cooked, chopped roast beef or pot roast
</P>
<P>
   1 cup onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cups thinly sliced carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 cup celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cups brown gravy
</P>
<P>
   1 beef bouillon cube
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons parsley flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sage
</P>
<P>
   3 large bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Margarine
</P>
<P>
   Mashed potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   Saute onions, celery and carrots in margarine in large skillet
just until tender. Combine with roast beef, gravy and spices and
simmer slowly for about 20 minutes. Remove bay leaves. Mixture
should be thicker than stew but not too runny. Add more gravy if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Put 3/4 cup hot beef mixture into small, round casserole dish.
Cover to edges with mashed potatoes, smoothing with knife. Mark
with tines of fork. Sprinkle middle of potatoes with about 2
tablespoons grated cheddar.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in 350 degrees oven for 15 minutes. Garnish with fresh
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   _ From The Newbury House, Rugby, Tenn., via the 1st Traveler's
Choice Internet Cookbook. (www.virtualcities.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
