<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OLYMPICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NO MEDAL FOR NBC'S HANDLING OF THE OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest problem with these four-season Olympics
(summer-into-fall in the United States, winter-into-spring in
Australia) hasn't been what NBC has televised.
</P>
<P>
   No, the biggest setback for NBC has been what the other
networks, and cable outlets, and Internet sites, haven't shown. And
that's still NBC's fault.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the Sydney Games, NBC made a strategic decision: All
441.5 hours of programming on the network and on its cable sisters
CNBC and MSNBC would be on tape delay.
</P>
<P>
   With a record 15- to 18-hour time difference between the host
city and the United States, the network knew that none of the prime
events would fall into prime time here. (Previously, the biggest
gap was 14 to 17 hours for the 1998 Nagano Winter Games and the
1988 Seoul Summer Olympics.)
</P>
<P>
   It was a business decision, and certainly a debatable one. It
makes sense to keep the marquee events in the time slot with the
highest viewership, but the network could have gained by showing
even a smattering of lesser events as they happened.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the network's biggest gaffe. This is: Despite the
fact that NBC paid more than $700 million for the right to
broadcast these Olympics, it should be giving some of the Games'
footage to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Free. Gratis. As in, ``It's on us, pal.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a deal would go against standard practice and all business
sense. But these Games _ held so far away, in the Southern
Hemisphere for the first time in 44 years, and pushing into the NFL
season and baseball's pennant chase _ aren't the norm.
</P>
<P>
   In paying the princely sum for the broadcast rights, NBC secured
the right to all moving pictures from these Australian Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Simply stated: Until it airs on NBC or its cable brethren _ and
even then only after the end of the broadcast day _ nobody else can
use footage, not even NBC affiliates. And even if all those
criteria are met, you can air only six minutes in a given day.
</P>
<P>
   As anybody in television news will tell you, if you don't have
the pictures, you don't have the story.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures that are 24 hours or more old are simply old news,
especially in the rapid-response Information Age. As a result, most
televised Olympic reports are nothing more than the winners, the
scores and the medal count against a solid backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   But if NBC allowed other outlets to show snippets of some of the
action _ 15 to 20 seconds, tops _ national and local sports anchors
would have the ``art'' they need to tell a more in-depth story.
</P>
<P>
   NBC then would be the beneficiary of something that's been
missing from these Games, something that's been turned into a
four-letter word at that network: buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter made a spectacular dunk the other night against
France. Have you seen it? Neither have I. Had you seen it on the
nightly news or sports wrap, you'd be drooling to see it again when
it (eventually) airs on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
