u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-28 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BIG ON BASHING BIG BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We found out this week that one of our kids needs braces, which
means that over the next year we will have to shell out big money
for orthodontia.
</P>
<P>
   We could have blamed the whole thing on bad luck or bad genes.
But if we were Al Gore, we would have taken a different tack. We
would have accused the orthodonist of price gouging, making
excessive profits, and being in cahoots with ``big dentistry'' or
``big teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get us wrong: We basically like Al Gore. We think he's
smart, capable, and probably wouldn't be a bad president.
</P>
<P>
   But as business columnists, with some faith in the free market,
we are having more and more trouble listening to Gore's attacks on
business. They strike us as disingenuous, bordering on dishonest.
</P>
<P>
   The latest evidence: Gore's recent attack on oil companies
(``big oil'' in Gorespeak). In a discussion of his energy policies,
Gore this week noted that oil company profits have skyrocketed, and
he called on big oil to stop ``profiteering.''
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing new for the vice president. In the spring, when
gasoline prices became an issue, he accused big oil of ``gouging''
consumers and called on the Federal Trade Commission to
investigate. This week, he took the rhetoric to a new level. ``I
will work for the day when we are free forever of the dominance of
big oil and foreign oil,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Implicit in Gore's remarks is the idea that the oil companies
have the power to drive up prices. But do they? If so, how do you
explain the fact that oil prices have been low for most of the past
15 years and that only two years ago they were at their lowest
point, adjusted for inflation, since World War II?
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that oil profits have soared this year, longer
term they are nothing to write home about. The same can be said of
oil stock prices. Over the past five years, the Amex oil index, a
sampling of oil stocks, has returned 106 percent, compared to 180
percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   And what was Gore thinking when he pledged to end our dependence
on big oil and foreign oil? The US gets 50 percent of its oil from
overseas, most of it delivered by big oil companies. Does Gore know
someome small and domestic who is going to take up the slack?
</P>
<P>
   HMOs are another favorite Gore target. In a recent speech on
Medicare, Gore said, ``The HMOs and insurance companies want to
measure your health and well-being on a spread sheet.'' He
routinely denounces ``bean counters'' making medical decisions, and
this week he vowed to crack down on HMOs that leave the Medicare
program.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a point here. Some HMOs have set up too many barriers
to care. But many of the worst abuses have either been corrected by
the industry or by state legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem in health care today is cost. Insurance
premiums are going up at a double-digit clip. Beating up on HMOs
and threatening them with penalties isn't going to solve the
problem. If we outlawed all HMOs tomorrow, someone would still have
to grapple with the tough choices involved in keeping health care
affordable.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for that sort of nuanced argument from Gore about
HMOs. Or about prescription drug companies, for that matter. Gore's
Web site is full of boasts about how he has stood up to the big
pharmaceutical companies, which charge ``absurdly high prices'' and
make excessive profits.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies do charge a lot. They are also very profitable.
But big profits _ Gore nothwithstanding _ actually play a vital
role in our economy. ``Profits are a reward for risk-taking and for
making the right decisions,'' said Nicholas Perna, an economic
consultant based in Connecticut. ``They are also an enticement for
taking future risks.''
</P>
<P>
   America can cut drug company profits _ maybe we will have to _
but if we do, we have to accept the fact that the drug companies
will take fewer risks and produce fewer drugs. In a capitalist
society, money and talent flow to where the rewards are greatest.
That's true in Hollywood, on the Internet, and in the
pharmaceutical business.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Gore's cartoonish view of big business does a
disservice both to him and to the American people. He knows life is
more complicated than he's letting on, and so do the rest of us.
With just six weeks left until Election Day, it would be nice to
hear Gore talk to us as if we were 21st century sophisticates, not
19th century farmers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it would be more than nice. It would be big.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
