<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AIR-DELAYS _ WASHINGTON _ A House Transporation subcommittee
holds a hearing on the causes of airline delays this summer. Ben
DeCosta, manager of the nation's busiest airport, Hartsfield
Internatonal in Atlanta, is among the witnesses. (Kumar, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-TITLE _ Down on their luck, some Florida residents head
to car title loan shops for a bit of cash. They surrender their
vehicle title to receive as little as $500. Then they're hit with
yearly interest of 264 percent. Like other borrowers throughout the
South, the object of their ire is Atlanta-based Title Loans of
America, one of the largest so-called ``fringe lending''
institutions in the country. Published reports say the owner, an
attorney in South Florida who owns a Miami restaurant, has ties to
organized crime. Title loans, say Florida Attorney General Bob
Butterworth, are nothing but legal loan sharking. (Manuel, The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-INSURANCE _ WASHINGTON Nearly 2 million previously
uninsured Americans gained health-care coverage last year, the
first time in 12 years that the number of people without health
insurance dropped. Analysts point to the country's low jobless rate
and broader health coverage plans by employers as contributing to
the turnaround. Still, the number of uninsured Americans,
particularly among the poor, remained high. The number of people
without health insurance declined by 1.7 million between 1998 and
1999, from 44.3 million to 42.6 million. (Holmes, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-HOMES _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Aging Committee holds a
hearing on the last three years of nursing home problems and the
difficulty of bringing about reform. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory Social
Issues
</P>
<P>
   FIRESTONE _ A Statesboro, Ga., lawyer is at the forefront of the
legal case against Firestone Tires. Rowe Brogdon represents the
family of a college football player who died after a blowout on
I-95. Their lawsuit was settled after Brogdon found a Firestone
engineer who knew of the tire problems. We also have a copy of the
whistleblower's deposition. (Chapman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
