<P>
   AIDS-CONFERENCE _ ATLANTA _ She struggles to put her fear into
words, but Mardis Andrews knows perhaps better than anyone what the
AIDS epidemic means to her and her children, an 11-year-old
daughter and a baby not yet born. ``I feel like I'm in a world
different from everybody else,'' the 33-year-old Atlanta mother
said. Truth is, Mardis Andrews isn't. She has never been. In
Georgia, 82 percent of women with AIDS are African-American, just
like her. And African-American children represent 62 percent of all
new HIV-AIDS cases in the United States, just like her daughter.
But if these numbers are lost on Andrews, they weigh heavy and wide
on the 3,300 representatives from HIV/AIDS advocacy groups and
service providers who are expected to meet here Sunday through
Wednesday for the U.S. Conference on AIDS. (Staples, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
