<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-OZAWA-ART-BOS &LR;      09-28 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OZAWA-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 OZAWA PLANS FIRSTS FOR THE BSO'S 100TH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Seiji Ozawa settled a little carefully into a corner of
the couch in the conductor's green room in Symphony Hall Tuesday.
The conductor is back in Boston, eager to launch the season-long
100th anniversary celebration of the Boston Symphony Orchestra's
great home.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, he returned to the hall he first entered in 1968
to lead a performance of Beethoven's ``Missa Solemnis,'' the same
work the orchestra chose for the Hall's opening night on Oct. 15,
1900.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa seemed satisfied with the progress of rehearsals, with the
condition of the orchestra, the promise and accomplishment of new
players, and the seriousness of purpose with which the Tanglewood
Festival Chorus has prepared the work.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa first conducted the ``Missa Solemnis'' 30 years ago, for
the opening of the NHK Orchestra's hall in Tokyo; his most recent
performance, last season, was also in Japan. He was so happy with
the soprano, Emiko Suga, that he engaged her for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Missa Solemnis is a very difficult piece, something very
strong and raw _ it doesn't have much to do with conventional
religion. The music insists, and Beethoven had something important
he wanted to say, very urgently.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa's season includes two major premieres, the Second Symphony
by John Corigliano in November and ``The Map,'' ``a multi-media
concerto for cello and orchestra'' in February. Neither score has
come in yet, which makes Ozawa a little nervous. But the
Corigliano, a 35-minute work for strings, harp and percussion is
reportedly complete.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa will also conduct a revised version of the Cello Concerto
that John Williams wrote for Yo-Yo Ma and the opening of Seiji
Ozawa Hall at Tanglewood. ``This is a very complicated piece,''
Ozawa says, ``and very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly happy to present the first local performances
of the late Toru Takemitsu's ``From me flows what you call Time''
in the second week of the season. This work was premiered by the
Boston Symphony in New York a decade ago, but there was no Boston
peformance because the piece had been jointly commissioned by
Carnegie Hall and Suntory Hall in Tokyo, and Carnegie Hall
naturally insisted on the premiere. One of Ozawa's closest musical
friendships was with Takemitsu, and the composer's widow and
daughter are flying to Boston for the performances. ``This piece
will sound wonderful in Symphony Hall,'' Ozawa says.
</P>
<P>
   Another Japanese artist that Ozawa will introduce in December is
the pianist Momo Kodama, who will play Tchaikovsky's First
Concerto. ``She is the sister-in-law of the conductor Kent Nagano,
and a very unusual and sensitive artist who lives in Paris now. I
have done the Tchaikovsky with her before, and her interpretation
is completely different and full of lightness.''
</P>
<P>
   In April and May, Ozawa returns for a Beethoven Piano Concerto
cycle with Alfred Brendel and his first performance, believe it or
not, of Shostakovich's Fifth Symphony, a work indelibly associated
with his mentor, Leonard Bernstein (whose famous recording with the
New York Philharmonic was made in Symphony Hall). ``I was supposed
to conduct the Shostakovich before, but after I heard Slava
(Rostropovich) do it with the National Symphony on tour in Symphony
Hall, I gave it up. The other piece I gave up was Debussy's `Jeux,'
which is the only major piece by Debussy I have never conducted,
but after I heard Pierre Boulez conduct it, I decided to stay
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendel has been a favorite colleague for 35 years. ``Herbert
von Karajan insisted that I make my debut at the Salzburg Festival
in 1964 or 1965, and Brendel played the Brahms Second Concerto _ he
was making his Salzburg Festival debut, too. We have played the
Beethoven concertos at Tanglewood and in Japan. He is wonderful in
the way he finds the character of each piece; each of the Beethoven
concertos has a fantasy life. This is something very rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa was last in the local news when he played the Good
Samaritan after the final performance of Verdi's ``Falstaff'' at
the Tanglewood Music Center. He was driving to his West Stockbridge
home after the performance and stopped to assist a driver whose car
was halfway off the road. He now thinks that during the incident he
may have pulled something in his back which is still bothering him
_ that's why he settled a little gingerly into position.
</P>
<P>
   There was no rest for Ozawa after his Tanglewood season. He went
directly to Japan to preside over the ninth annual Saito Kinen
Festival, where he led performances of Bach's B-Minor Mass with
several of the same soloists who will perform the work with him
here in February.
</P>
<P>
   There was no opera at Saito Kinen this season, but earlier this
year, Ozawa had led performances of Mozart's ``The Marriage of
Figaro'' in Japan with an important international cast and an
orchestra of the best young Japanese players. ``Robert Mann, who
led the Juilliard Quartet for 50 years, has been coming to Japan to
work with young string players on quartets, and this is an
outgrowth of that. I think playing opera with very good singers is
the best training for young musicians. We proved this at
Tanglewood, where all the good things about the Tanglewood Music
Center came out _ the talent and energy of the singers and the
instrumentalists. The experience was really wonderful. This kind of
experience is particularly important in Japan, where young
musicians have acquired a tremendous technique but sometimes are
afraid of involvement. Opera is so clear in the emotions that it is
good for musicians like these. Next, we will do `Cosi fan tutte'
and `Don Giovanni' with singers like Bryn Terfel.''
</P>
<P>
   After three days off following Saito Kinen, Ozawa traveled to
China to meet up with his old friend Mstislav Rostropovich.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa and Rostropovich have collaborated for decades on the
world's great concert stages. Less well-known are the regular
``caravans'' they undertake to bring music to underserved regions
of Japan and Russia. The musicians travel by bus and truck to
remote sites; the sides of the truck are lowered to create a
concert platform.
</P>
<P>
   The recent China trip came about because the BSO's
long-anticipated return last year was cancelled because of an
international crisis. Ozawa went on alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so impressed by the level of the music students that I
called up Slava and asked him to come with me this year to Shanghai
and Beijing for rehearsals, master classes, and performances. He
worked very hard _ he played both a Haydn Concerto and the Dvorak
Concerto. We rehearsed and gave two concerts in both cities, and
all of them were free. The orchestras played very well, and we were
very happy _ and he found three excellent cellists. Our next
caravan is in August, 2002, and we hope the cellists will come with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa was born in Hoten, Manchuria in 1935 and spent his
childhood years in Beijing. His mother, now 92, insisted on joining
him for this recent trip to Beijing. ``We went back to see the
house where I grew up. Once my brother borrowed a pistol from a
military policeman who was courting our maid and shot three holes
in the entranceway, and they are still there!''
</P>
<P>
   The Symphony Hall centennial found Ozawa in a reminiscent mood
about his introduction to the building. He came to conduct the BSO
in Boston for the first time in 1968 _ the program included
Bernstein's ``Age of Anxiety'' and the second suite from Ravel's
``Daphnis and Chloe.'' He remembers how he profited from the advice
of his mentor, former music director Charles Munch. ``It was the
last time I saw him. He heard the rehearsal and helped me with the
flute solo accompaniment _ I think I had a problem!''
</P>
<P>
   In the BSO's forthcoming coffee table book ``Symphony Hall: The
First Hundred Years,'' Ozawa's remarks about the hall at a press
conference last April are quoted. ``Nothing prepared me for the
sound of the Boston Symphony _ so warm and clear, and effortless. I
am convinced that what we know as the `Boston Symphony sound' has
been created by these acoustics. The orchestra never has to force
or push. The sound just flies.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa recalled the first time he conducted there. He and his
wife Vera were staying at the Eliot Hotel because it would accept
the family Yorkshire terrier. ``They told me I could walk to the
hall _ it was winter, dark and cold, and the neighborhood was not
so good back then. There were terrible Chinese restaurants. And
when I arrived here there was no sign on the big brick building,
and it didn't even look like a concert hall. But I walked inside,
and there was Symphony Hall . . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
