u e BC-BOOK-PERISH-BOS &LR;      09-28 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PERISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDALL IS AS SPENSER DOES, BUT NOT AS WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
Perish Twice 
By Robert B. Parker 
Putnam, 265 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunny Randall is not just Spenser in drag, wearing low boots and
the latest in cropped pants, black, and a black sweater with a
scoop neck and some nice silver jewelry, her natural blond hair
newly highlighted by the hairdresser. One can hardly imagine
Spenser saying ``eek'' the way Sunny does when someone lights up a
cigarette. Unlike Spenser, Sunny says she doesn't read poetry _ but
she does remember some, and quote it. Spenser probably wouldn't
wear coral tights and cutting-edge sneakers to the gym, the way
Sunny does.
</P>
<P>
   These differences apart, Sunny does sound pretty much like her
creator's most celebrated creation _ and now, not 25 years ago,
when he was her age. She thinks like Spenser, alternates
sensitivity and wisecracks like Spenser: ``I tried the derringer in
my bra. It was too heavy, it interfered with the bra's primary
duty, and it made me look like I was carrying a concealed
unicorn.'' She lavishes pages of sloppy wet kisses on a dog, like
Spenser, and acts on a code of honor, like Spenser.
</P>
<P>
   In Robert B. Parker's ``Perish Twice,'' Sunny is dismissed from
a case 60 pages into the book, but of course she won't give up _
she has to find out what has happened, and why someone has been
murdered, even though the police have officially closed the case
and she is no longer being paid. Sunny seems peculiarly
uninterested in money.
</P>
<P>
   The case is a messy one. Sunny has been approached by a militant
lesbian feminist named Mary Lou Goddard who believes she is being
stalked.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mary Lou knows she's being stalked, and who is stalking
her, and why _ though she does not choose to share this information
with Sunny. She just wants protection, which Sunny supplies. Before
long, a woman who resembles Mary Lou and works in her office is
murdered, and Sunny has been called off the case, in part because
she knows more than Mary Lou wants her to _ but not enough to make
sense of the events or of the cast of characters, which includes a
loser named Lawrence B. Reeves, vice lord Tony Marcus, superpimp
Jermaine Lister, the jittery shooter Ty-Bop, a nice whore named
Jewell, and a mysterious creature named Natalie who looks stylish
and speaks with elegance when she isn't screaming. Jewell has a
habit, and as she scans the street for the candy man, Sunny sagely
observes that she is waiting for Godot.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny devotes about a third of her time in ``Perish Twice'' to
these people and the tangle of their sex lives. Another third goes
to her hopelessly out-of-it sister Elizabeth and her messed-up sex
life. And the rest goes to sisterly conversations over white wine
with her best friend Julie, the therapist, who is determined to
mess up her own sex life.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much about Sunny's sex life, but her ex-husband, the
straight member of an Irish mob family, is still around; they have
dinner once a week and sometimes sleep together.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny manages to sort out the main case, with a little help from
her friends, including the gay bistro owner and karate expert
Spike; her ex-husband and his family; and a police officer familiar
from the Spenser series. For a feisty protofeminist, Sunny is
perhaps a little too dependent on her friends _ she manages to
assemble a lot of information but cannot see the patterns,
meanwhile placing herself in the kind of physical danger that
requires gallant male protection. Meanwhile Elizabeth and Julie
tediously muddle through to somewhat more sensible destinies than
the ones they seem to be headed for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perish Twice'' has a big theme: It's about sex, and how sex
intersects both with love and with hate, with fire and with ice, to
quote a poem by Robert Frost that Julie shares with Sunny. Parker
has engaged this theme before, more effectively. Here he has
trouble focusing. All the familiar mannerisms appear _ the
restaurants, the local traffic patterns, the awfulness of
pretentious people, and the fundamental decency of the little guy
and of the whore with the heart of gold; the Boston brand names _
but the energy level is low. The mystery, such as it is, is solved,
not settled, and self-knowledge seems more elusive than ever. It
would be nice to think that was the point, but as early as her
second adventure, much of which repeats her first, Parker seems
tired of Sunny, and it's hard not to share the feeling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
