<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACTORING IN BILL O'REILLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like Rodney Dangerfield, Bill O'Reilly gets no respect. At least
among mainstream media poobahs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the hottest news show in the country, and now I have
the hottest book in the country, and I can't get on these shows,''
says the host of Fox News Channel's ``The O'Reilly Factor,''
complaining that some influential TV outlets are ignoring his book
tour because ``I'm a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his claims, well, he is hot. Nielsen numbers _ comparing
August 1999 ratings to August 2000 ratings _ show ``The O'Reilly
Factor'' still trails CNN rival Larry King's show by more than a 2
to 1 ratio. But while King's audience has dropped by nearly 20
percent in that period, O'Reilly's viewership has grown by nearly
50 percent. And his new book _ unsurprisingly titled ``The O'Reilly
Factor: The Good, the Bad, and the Completely Ridiculous in
American Life'' _ is a lofty number seven on The New York Times
bestseller list. That news may be leavened, however, by the fact
that it is still three places behind psychic Sylvia Browne's
``guided tour of the afterlife.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the success of a book that claims to deliver the
straight skinny on America's fundamental truths, O'Reilly goes into
full Frank Capra mode. ``People believe what I'm saying is true,''
he says in an interview. ``And I trust the folks.'' (Or, as he
writes in the book: ``I will get to the pith quickly and
undiplomatically _ even if the pith piths you off.'')
</P>
<P>
   For much of his career, O'Reilly was a conventional journalist,
working in local TV news, at CBS and ABC, and spending a lot of
time in tweedy, tradition-bound Boston. He attended Boston
University, worked at WCVB-TV (Channel 5) and WHDH-TV (Channel 7),
and developed the idea for his current show while getting a
master's degree from Harvard, where he landed after leaving his gig
as host of ``Inside Edition.'' In his book, O'Reilly conveniently
describes `Inside Edition'' as a forerunner of such shows as
``Dateline'' and ``48 Hours,'' instead of as a kissin' cousin of
such tabloid fare as ``Current Affair'' or ``Hard Copy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we did Madonna and Michael Jackson'' on ``Inside
Edition,'' he admits. ``Because you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly says Fox News chairman Roger Ailes bought the concept
of ``The O'Reilly Factor'' without even hearing the details.
(``Ailes just stays out of my way,'' he adds.) And today, its
feisty star is a poster boy for the Fox News Channel, where growing
ratings recently inspired a New York Times story.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it's easier to define the Fox News Channel by what
it's against than what it is. Its clever slogan, ``We Report, You
Decide,'' reflects its self-proclaimed niche as the antidote to
pervasive liberal bias in the media. When asked to expound on that
issue, O'Reilly turns diplomatic, suggesting the problem with other
networks is ``more censorship than bias.'' But he offers other
vocal criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with television news in the year 2000 is that it's
no longer necessary,'' he says. ``The network chiefs don't
understand that . . . It's over for the Establishment, that's for
sure. It's like the last days of Pompeii.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks' philosophy is that we're going to decide what
information is important,'' he continues. At Fox News Channel,
``we're not gonna do that. We're going to give you all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the words of a committed populist and
anti-gatekeeper journalist. Until you ask O'Reilly to define his
role. ``I'm an analyst,'' he says crisply. ``I look at the news of
the day, and I figure out what's more relevant to people, and I try
to bring out the real truth of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it must be working. As the never immodest O'Reilly is proud
to proclaim, the show generates 10,000 letters a week or ``more
than Oprah Winfrey.''
</P>
<P>
   So who needs the adulation of the mainstream media?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Jurkowitz writes about the media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
