<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5063 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-28 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARCE IN THE COURTROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A week after the second Reggie Lewis trial ended in a verdict
against his widow last May, attorney Neil Rossman had a talk with
his client, Donna Harris-Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict that Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. was not culpable in
the death of the former Celtics captain Reggie Lewis was likely
final, he told her. There were no legal grounds for an appeal. They
had received a fair trial; they had simply lost.
</P>
<P>
   When Harris-Lewis told Rossman she intended to appeal the
verdict regardless of his opinion, he asked her what she thought
her grounds might be.
</P>
<P>
   She informed him that she was going to appeal based on the
racial makeup of the jury, as well as the fact that Judge Thayer
Fremont-Smith had refused to have portions of the transcript read
back to the jury. Rossman said those were not grounds for appeal
and that he would not represent her. He was particularly
uncomfortable with the idea that race would be the foundation of
her appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Rosssman's refusal to handle what he correctly branded an
``intellectually bankrupt'' appeal landed him in a strange position
this week, unfamiliar even for someone who has spent close to 29
years in courtrooms, as he has.
</P>
<P>
   He was on the stand in Suffolk Superior Court testifying under
oath, every shred of the time-honored bond between attorney and
client breached. Harris-Lewis is pursuing a third trial. Rossman
stands accused, in effect, of not protecting his client's rights,
by allowing Mudge's motion for a dismissal of the appeal to go
unchallenged. Under questioning from his former adversary, William
J. Dailey Jr., and his onetime client's new lawyer, Pamela
Harris-Daley, Rossman insisted that he was not at fault for the
failure to contest the motion.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was a joke. Around and around the lawyers went on
matters of legal minutiae _ when memos were sent, when faxes were
sent, even whether a filing by Mudge had been faxed with a cover
letter, or without. It had little to do with law and nothing to do
with justice. It was all about how to work the system, how to get
another roll of the dice.
</P>
<P>
   After three hours on the witness stand, Rossman talked with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a fair trial and an attentive jury and I tried the case
that I wanted to try,'' Rossman said. ``It was just a (complicated)
case and we couldn't convince that jury that our position was the
correct position. It had nothing to do with race. It has to do with
medicine and medical testimony. Another jury could have come out
with another conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was telling Harris-Lewis he would not handle her
appeal, Rossman told her something else.
</P>
<P>
   He said he told her she could always find a lawyer to take
$100,000 of her money, go through the trial record, and tell her
there were no grounds for appeal. Or to write a brief for an appeal
going nowhere. Some lawyer would gladly take advantage of her. He
urged her instead to think of her reputation, her two children, and
the Reggie Lewis Foundation. He scheduled two meetings to try to
prevail on her, in person, to finally let it go. Harris-Lewis, he
testified, canceled both. Too bad. It was good advice.
</P>
<P>
   This case was tragic, then it was just sad. Now it has entered
the realm of farce. It has been tried and retried, and the
consensus of those who watched it was that Harris-Lewis enjoyed
stellar representation in the second trial in particular. Two
juries have failed to conclude that Mudge's care killed Lewis.
That's just the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, as Harris-Daley was claiming to find deep meaning
in yet another irrelevant piece of correspondence, she came
uncomfortably close to the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Rossman, glasses perched atop his forehead, objected.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're making me dizzy,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   After two trials, two verdicts, and the prospect of more to
come, Rossman could have been speaking for a lot of us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-GYM-RADUCAN-NYT &LR;      09-28 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-RADUCAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANIAN GYMNAST'S APPEAL IS REJECTED BY IOC COURT OF ARBITRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Andreea Raducan still cannot believe her
gold medal for winning the gymnastics individual all-around
competition was stripped from her for taking a cold medication that
contained a substance banned by the International Olympic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   And even Thursday, as the Court of Arbitration upheld the IOC's
decision, the 16-year-old continued to be mystified that taking an
over-the-counter drug, pseudoephedrine, that was administered by
the Romanian team doctor, could result in such a drastic outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took an innocent pill because I wasn't feeling well,'' she
said through a translator. ``It didn't help me to compete but gave
me some dizziness that impeded my competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed,'' she added. ``It's not for me to judge the
decision, but I am convinced and my heart is at peace that I did
everything right and competed fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Raducan won the all-around event on September 21, but a
subsequent urine sample detected traces of pseudoephedrine, leading
the IOC to take back her gold medal. On Wednesday, the Court of
Arbitration heard her appeal during a 4{-hour hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The three-member panel acknowledged that pseudoephedrine did not
enhance Raducan's performance, but ruled that the positive drug
offense violated the Olympic anti-doping code.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strict liability test must thus be applied,'' the court said
in a brief opinion, ``the consequence being automatic
disqualification as a matter of law and in fairness to all other
athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   The court held that the ``presence of a prohibited substance in
a competitor's bodily fluid'' is the threshold issue, not whether
Raducan intended to ``ingest the prohibited substance.'' As a
result, it said, the anti-doping code ``must be enforced without
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who defended Raducan at the hearing sought an exception to
the zero-tolerance policy, precisely because there was no sinister
intent and because of her confidence that her doctor would not give
her a banned substance. But to the court, ignorance of the code was
not a defense.
</P>
<P>
   Nadia Comaneci, who won three gold medals in the 1976 Summer
Olympics, including one in the individual all-around event, said,
``It's difficult for me to explain to her that she is innocent but
she's having the medal taken from her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ion Tiriac, the president of the Romanian Olympic Committee,
criticized the court of arbitration for being less interested in
the law than it should have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always believed it was a court of law and nothing about
sports and it would look at every case for its merits where
somebody has to be proved guilty beyond any other doubt,
particularly with this case,'' he said. ``We're talking about
aspirin, not drugs.'' Regarding the IOC, he said, ``They don't have
the courage to say in this case they might have been mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiriac said he will resign his position rather than enforce
against Raducan his blanket policy of banning for life all Romanian
athletes from competing in the Olympics if they test positive for
drugs. ``I could not look her in the eyes and for an aspirin ban
her for life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiriac defended the doctor who gave Raducan the medication yet
blamed him for his apparent ignorance about the banned substance.
The doctor, Ioachin Oana, was expelled for the remainder of the
Summer Games and banned from the 2002 Winter and 2004 Summer
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man, but he will be the devil from now on,''
Tiriac said. ``He does his best, but he uses what's on hand.. He's
experienced but not really Olympic-experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiriac added: ``He didn't study every cold remedy, but may have
known it was on the banned list.''
</P>
<P>
   The beneficiaries of the revocation of Raducan's gold medal were
her Romanian teammates: Simona Amanar moved up from the silver, and
Maria Olaru swapped bronze for silver. The fourth-place finisher
Liu Xuan of China gets the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the medal doesn't mean anything,'' Amanar said. ``I'm
going to accept it because it belongs to Romania. But I didn't win
it. The Olympic champion that day was Andreea, not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Raducan lost the all-around gold, she was allowed to
keep the gold she won as part of the team competition and the
silver medal she won in the vault.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole dream in my life was to come to the Olympics and
maybe win a medal,'' Raducan said. ``I did that. But life goes on
and I just have to get over this as soon as I can. We did a good
job here. I lost a medal, maybe, but in my soul, I know it was my
place.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
