<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIT ON DRILL BITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. You have written about a new drill bit for drilling ceramic
tile and glass. Could such a bit be used to drill a hole in a
ceramic soap dish that is much thicker than tile, to allow
drainage?
</P>
<P>
   JASON ALBANO, Lynnfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. In a word, yes. You don't have to use that special bit (made
by Black &AMP; Decker) either, but it will not hurt. The main secret to
success is to go slow and easy. Use a variable-speed drill and take
your time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a number of pressboard shelves that are giving off
formaldehyde. I replaced most of them with wood, but I can't get to
some of them to replace them. What can I use to seal in that
formaldehyde?
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS EVANS, Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Prime the pressboard shelves on all surfaces with an
oil-based interior primer, and finish with a latex enamel or latex
eggshell finish paint. Or, use two coats of an oil-based
polyurethane varnish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's one for the books: A fungus, similar to mold or even an
evil mushroom, one that lurks in wood and bark mulch, fires a spore
as high as 15 feet, making a dark spot on your siding, all
resistant to bleach.
</P>
<P>
   That is what H.L. of Newton, Mass. had when he called the
handyman with a fervent ``Help!''
</P>
<P>
   H.L. found out about the spore from the Massachusetts
Horticultural Society, which put him in touch with scientists at
Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   The fungus is called, not surprisingly, the artillery fungus,
and is common on both the east and west coasts.
</P>
<P>
   The spores not only make a mess on house siding, but they are
resistant to bleach and virtually impossible to remove. Actually,
soaking with detergent, and scrubbing, and scraping, and sanding
will eventually remove them. Untreated, they can live up to 10 or
11 years.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure, but there is a way to prevent future
bombardments. H.L. simply removed all the mulch and replaced it
with black plastic and crushed stone.
</P>
<P>
   -------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My new house has four bathrooms with top-of-the-line
fixtures. In some sinks, I get a smell of rotten eggs when I turn
on the cold water. After a short time, it stops. How can I elminate
that odor?D.L., Randolph, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The odor is caused by hydrgen sulphide dissolved in the
water. It may be occurring naturally or could be due to a buildup
of bacteria. Sometimes aeration will help; that is what you did
when you turned on the water and let it run. Sometimes you may need
special filters; consult your local water department for advice.
Sometimes the water, especially if it is well water, will need
chlorination.
</P>
<P>
   If it is from a bacterial buildup, it may be due to a dirty
filter, which could be replaced. Check the faucet aerator, too, the
gizmo that screws on the end of the tap. Filters and aerators can
collect a lot of bacteria. Replace filters as necessary. Unscrew
the aerator, take out the gaskets and washers, clean them
thoroughly, and put everything back together. A new house should
not have dirty filters or blocked aerators, but that depends on
what is meant by ``new.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My baseboard heating fins are very dirty, caked with crud and
dusty. Is there an outfit that could clean them, for a fee? The
fins are under a removable metal cover.
</P>
<P>
   M.E.K., Lynnfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Hmm. There are plenty of duct cleaners for hot-air ducts out
there; that has been all the rage in the past 10 years or so. But I
have never heard of fin cleaners. Fins should be cleaned because
when they get caked up, they lose a great deal of their efficiency.
You might call a duct cleaner to see if he could do the fins, but
that would require different tools.
</P>
<P>
   So, it may boil down to cleaning your own fins. Use a soft brush
on your vacuum to remove loose dust. Then you may have to scrape
between the fins with a dull knife or even an old credit card,
being careful not to bend the fins. After scraping, use the vacuum
again to pick up the spillage.
</P>
<P>
   If you can develop a fast, efficient way to clean the fins
safely, you could start your own fin-cleaning business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter C. Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or
e-mail him at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
