<SLUG> BC-HOME-FABRIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO REALLY MAKE A ROOM SPARKLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine yourself a dot-com millionaire living in a stylin' loft
with soaring windows. What do you cover them with? Chintz, perhaps?
Too much like mother. Moire? Too much like grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   How about fiber optics? Very motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   A Swiss company, Creation Baumann, has launched a line of
``cyber fabrics,'' wall-sized mesh and cotton panels entwined with
state-of-the art touches like strands of copper and aluminum,
metallic paper, and even razor-thin fiber optic cables that glow
blue when the panel is plugged in. They're aimed at
design-conscious techies who want the most modern touches in their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Gen X computer kids who have their parents' antiques
passed down to them, but want to jazz them up with something very
new,'' said Julie Mullin, manager of Furn &AMP; Co. at the Boston
Design Center, ``something they know they're not going to see
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10-foot panels are used as curtains, duvet covers, room
dividers, motorized screens, and shower curtains. The copper and
aluminum mix combines with flexible mesh to give the fabrics a
crinkly texture and shimmery glow. A balloon shade made from the
pliable fabric is not raised by string to let in the sunshine, but
scrunched into shape.
</P>
<P>
   Stiffer metallic papers (also being used on fashion runways for
jackets a la Judy Jetson) are two-toned (think silver and copper)
with high sheen.
</P>
<P>
   Laser technology is used to cut out girly swirls on one white
cotton panel, a new twist on the lacy eyelet of old, and to create
lifelike and boldly colored flowers, vegetables, and cutlery on
another.
</P>
<P>
   One white panel is bedecked in plastic butterflies, beetles, and
blades of grass that glow in the dark once they're exposed to
light.
</P>
<P>
   The piece de resistance, though, is a two-sided white mesh panel
that looks like a bridal veil. Yards and yards of transparent fiber
optics are sandwiched between the layers, all with twinkling blue
lights at their tips, forming the shapes of the constellations.
Clear glass orbs, made by the glassmasters of Murano, Italy, are
sewn on randomly to intensify the sparkle.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by a German bride who wanted her train to light up the
night sky when she walked down the aisle, (and had a battery pack
tucked into her gown to pull it off), the ethereal panel evokes the
heavens and has a price tag that's sky high: $1,559.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said a Saudi Arabian prince recently purchased two of the
panels to hang from the black ceiling of his media room, so it
would glitter with the magic of night. Local royalty, however, have
been slower in placing their orders, Mullin said, because ``Boston
is still pretty traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   Creation Baumann sells only to the trade, and Furn &AMP; Co. is the
only design shop in Boston carrying the fabrics. So, anyone
interested in seeing or purchasing the fabrics must work through a
designer or decorator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
