<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CHIMNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE GETTING COZY, CHECK THE CHIMNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Lynette Smith and Richard Bohmer were house hunting last
year, finding a home with a fireplace or two was a top priority.
Originally from New Zealand, the Smiths heated their previous homes
by burning wood in the fireplace, and wanted the same ambiance and
warmth in their American abode.
</P>
<P>
   When they finally purchased a 50-year-old Cape with two
fireplaces in Wellesley, Mass., they immediately scheduled a
chimney sweep, and last week had a second inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some friends had a fire in their chimney that wasn't major,
but it left us with a healthy respect for fire,'' Smith said. ``We
sit in front of the fire almost every night reading stories to the
kids and we want to be sure it's safe.''
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, when homeowners' fancies turn to cozying up
by the hearth, fire-protection specialists warn they should cozy up
to a chimney sweep first and make certain the fireplace flues have
not accumulated a dangerous layer of creosote, a wood and smoke
residue that clings to the inside of the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   If left untreated for too long, creosote can combust and cause
serious damage. According to the National Fire Protection Agency in
Quincy, Mass., there were 9,900 chimney fires in the United States
in 1997 (the most recent data available), causing eight deaths and
$57.7 million in property losses.
</P>
<P>
   There were 132 chimney fires in Massachusetts in 1998, resulting
in four injuries, according to the state fire marshal's office.
Thirty-six percent of those fires were caused by creosote buildup
and lack of chimney maintenance, according to the office.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Dubay, a fire-protection engineer with the NFP, said
the agency recommends chimneys be inspected annually for creosote
as well as cracks in the lining, nests, animals, leaks, and other
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are actively using your chimney for burning wood or
coal, you must have it inspected once a year,'' he said. ``That
also goes for wood-burning stoves. An inspection will quickly tell
you whether you have problems before you start your first fire of
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   He said homeowners should invest in caps for their chimneys to
prevent debris and critters from getting inside, and keep the
dampers closed when the fireplace is not in use. He warned that
when a fire is burning, all household materials should be kept at
least 3 feet from the flames. He said screens or glass doors should
be used to block sparks from jumping out of the fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not complicated stuff,'' Dubay said. ``The average
homeowner uses their fireplace for romance, not heating, so we're
not talking about extreme fires. But caution should always be
used.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are several self-cleaning tools on the market,
Dubay recommended that homeowners hire a professional chimney sweep
company rather than attempt the sooty task themselves.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Bill Heffernan, owner of Master Chimney Sweepers in
Natick, Mass., acknowledged that chimney sweeping is dirty work,
but only for the chimney sweep. He said that his workers take great
care to set down drop cloths, use industrial vacuums, and not touch
anything once they are inside the home.
</P>
<P>
   The job is still generally done the old-fashioned way, from the
firebox up, not the top of the chimney down, with long brushes for
scraping and flexible mirrors and lights for examining every
crevice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get people telling us all the time they didn't want to call
a chimney sweep because they thought we'd ruin the carpet,'' he
said. ``People shouldn't fear their homes getting dirty. That's as
important to us as anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Heffernan said people whose chimneys are more than 20 years old
should be extra vigilant about keeping them clean and clear, since
age and deterioration go hand-in-hand.
</P>
<P>
   He and Dubay also recommended an annual inspection of the
furnace flue to make sure it is venting properly. Clogging or
damage could lead to carbon monoxide leakage, and poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   While the chimney-sweeping process has remained relatively
unchanged for centuries (Charles Dickens' street scenes leap to
mind), there are some new products and technologies available.
ChimScan is a specially designed video camera some professionals
send up into the chimney for a closer view of the flue. Typically,
there is no extra charge for the use of ChimScan, but homeowners
are advised to inquire first.
</P>
<P>
   New to the market this season is the Sweeping Log, a mineral
compound made by Securiflame that you sprinkle onto a wood fire. It
promises to reduce and shake loose deposits of tar and creosote
from inside the chimney. It is not intended to be used in place of
an inspection by a professional, said Sweeping Log spokeswoman
Suzanne Hart, but ``in conjunction with'' one. It is available only
on the Internet at www.sweepinglog.com for $24.95 per log.
</P>
<P>
   Dubay said the best way to find a reliable chimney sweep is to
ask friends or call your local fire department for referrals.
Heffernan, who charges $169 for cleaning one flue, said consumers
should look for sweeps who are accredited by the Chimney Safety
Institute of America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
