<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5079 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-TITANS-TEX     09-28 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TITANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CLICHE ZONE: PREACHY `TITANS' DROPS THE BALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CHRISTOPHER KELLY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its cast of bland-faced, buff-bodied young actors, its
shimmeringly photographed Southern landscapes, and a tendency to
resolve racial conflicts with pithy two-sentence speeches that
sound as if they were written by ad-copy men, ``Remember the
Titans'' is certainly something to behold _ it's like a filmed
adaptation of the Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch catalog, except this catalog
has, like, really weighty themes, dude.
</P>
<P>
   In this football melodrama set in Virginia during a team's first
season of school desegregation, Denzel Washington plays an
African-American coach trying to integrate black and white players
who want nothing to do with one another. In other words, sanctimony
and sentimentality battle it out for two hours before finally
declaring a draw. (The only loser is the audience.)
</P>
<P>
   One senses trouble even before the first frame, when the logo
for Walt Disney Pictures appears on the screen. Do we really need
civics lessons from Mickey Mouse and Co.? It's not just that Disney
has displayed its own share of racial insensitivity over the years,
particularly in its cartoons like ``Song of the South,'' ``Dumbo,''
and ``Aladdin.'' It's that the Disney logo implies something
starched, uncomplicated and uplifting _ everything the issue of
school desegregation is not.
</P>
<P>
   So here we have a racial-conflict movie that paints everything
in the broadest and most obvious terms imaginable. Coach Boone
(Washington), relocated to Virginia from South Carolina and the
just-named head coach of the T.C. Williams High Titans football
team, is prickly, difficult and demanding _ but all in the service
of making his black and white charges come together as a team. Bill
Yoast (Will Patton), the white coach in line for the promotion that
went to Boone, harbors resentment, and maybe even racism _ but he
will come to respect Boone's integrity and commitment. The players,
black and white, are all stubborn and suspicious, but that's only
because they haven't had a chance to learn about one another. Once
they do, they can teach the disgruntled citizenry of Alexandria
that skin color doesn't matter _ it's what's inside a person that
matters most.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew the American racial divide could be so easily bridged?
Let's all link arms and sing ``Kum-Bah-Yah.'' (There is,
incidentally, much group singing of Motown classics on the part of
the football team, all of it cringe-inducing.) But before we get
too excited, let us ask this: Do the filmmakers think they're doing
anyone a service? The PG rating suggests that ``Titans'' is being
targeted at younger kids, but I imagine even the most naive will
sense something fishy about this picture's formulations: that
blacks and whites can find common ground by making ``Yo' mama''
jokes; that only the whites in the film would have trouble
accepting integrated schools and busing; that deep-rooted
prejudices can be assuaged by Washington periodically silencing
everyone and gravely intoning things like, ``If we don't come
together, right here, on this hallowed ground, we, too, will be
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest I've made ``Remember the Titans'' sound overly didactic,
rest assured that the film has also been conceived as cynically as
all of producer Jerry (''Gone in 60 Seconds,'' ``Armageddon'')
Bruckheimer's other films _ with the grandstanding interrupted
regularly with lots and lots of crowd-pleasing slop. The film
purports to be based on a true story _ but I don't think real life
often fits into the regularly repeated patterns on display here.
The boys engage in kooky antics; Washington pontificates; the team
almost loses but ultimately pulls out a victory. The only variation
is a final-act, tear-jerky twist that you can see coming about a
half-hour away.
</P>
<P>
   There is a great deal of talent behind ``Remember the Titans,''
but, frankly, they all should be ashamed of themselves. The
extraordinary cinematographer Philippe Rousselot (''Interview With
the Vampire,'' ``Henry &AMP; June,'' ``Hope and Glory'') shoots every
frame of ``Titans'' like a dream. But the pretty picture-making
makes no sense in the context of the gritty drama that's supposed
to be unfolding. The director, Boaz Yakin, has done some sharp,
original work himself (''Fresh,'' ``A Price Above Rubies''), but
his directing here seems to involve standing out of the way as the
script's melodrama plays out.
</P>
<P>
   And what is going on with Denzel Washington? This vital,
immensely talented actor has been playing virtually the same part
for the past 15 years _ a proud, blustery African-American who must
instruct whites with his upstanding behavior. At times he is
brilliant, as in last year's ``The Hurricane.'' But Washington long
ago gave up trying to challenge himself; and when he's on
autopilot, as he is here, the sight of him huffing, puffing and
threatening to blow everyone's house down is exasperating. Like
everything else about ``Remember the Titans,'' he's all hot (and
exceedingly stale) air.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Remember the Titans''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Boaz Yakin
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Denzel Washington, Will Patton
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ mild violence and even milder intelligence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Christopher Kelly is film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
