<HEADER>
A5082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-BOX-KAZAKHSTAN-NY     09-28 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOX-KAZAKHSTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAZAKHSTAN'S BOXERS FIGHT IN ONE DIRECTION _ FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ During the 1950s and 1960s, the Soviet Union
sent settlers to the ``virgin lands'' of the Kazakh Soviet
Socialist Republic, a landlocked area roughly four times the size
of Texas just northwest of China. The newcomers, who were mostly
Russians, brought with them the lessons of a centralized sports
system, and in the sport of boxing, a specific technique.
</P>
<P>
   It was an upright, rigid style, and standoffish with an emphasis
on shrewd ring maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   But as Nurgali Safiullin, an Olympic boxing coach of Kazakhstan,
a country formed after the breakup of the Soviet Union, said
Thursday: ``It's our thinking that battles should be won nose to
nose. It's close combat. We don't like to rely on judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kazakhstani people originated from a very warrior tribe, the
Kipchaki. They've always been fighters. They know how to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   At the 2000 Sydney Games, Kazakhstan is proving its point. A
nation of 14 million _ ``There used to be 2 million more, but a lot
of Russians have gone back since the Soviet breakup,'' Safiullin
said _ it has four fighters in the medal round of the boxing
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in other terms, a country with a population approximately
equal to that of Florida has as many fighters in the medal round as
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very exciting; our four fighters have already gotten
telegrams from our president,'' Safiullin said. ``The telegram
read, `Fight to the end.'''
</P>
<P>
   There is other motivation. Any Kazakh fighter winning a gold
medal will receive the equivalent of $100,000 from the government,
Safiullin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our men will fight hard anyway,'' Safiullin said. ``It's the
only way they know.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighters of Kazakhstan _ where 35 percent of the people live
below the poverty level (about $40 a month) and the average life
expectancy of males is 58 years _ fight with an uncompromising
relentlessness that has made them crowd favorites at the Sydney
boxing tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Kazakhs fight in one direction, forward, and will walk
through dozens of stiff punches to throw their own from close
range. Of their four fighters competing in Friday's semifinals, the
featherweight Bekzat Sattarkhanov is a student, the flyweight Bulat
Jumadilov and the middleweight Yermakhan Ibraimov are police
officers, and the superheavyweight Mukhtarkhan Dildabekov is in the
military.
</P>
<P>
   While they are resolutely aggressive, the four are thinking
fighters with good footwork. Their defense is solid since they hold
their hands high, a technique learned under the Soviet system,
Safiullin said. But they are hardly alike.
</P>
<P>
   Jumadilov, 27, said he liked to drive fast cars and considered
Muhammad Ali his favorite athlete. In the ring, he has fast hands
and scores points with punches in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about superstitions, Jumadilov, the flyweight world
champion, answered, ``Before competitions, I don't like to talk to
stupid people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibraimov, 28, lists Mike Tyson as his favorite athlete because
Tyson is ``a boxer who doesn't like to lose.'' Ibraimov fights as
if he hates to lose, too. On Wednesday, he upset Cuba's Juan
Hernandez, a reigning world champion. Ibraimov neutralized
Hernandez's power and had the 31-year-old Hernandez, a three-time
Olympian and silver medalist four years ago, suddenly looking very
old.
</P>
<P>
   After his victory, Ibraimov joined the several dozen Kazakh
rooters and officials in the grandstand. His countrymen took turns
having their picture taken with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are national heroes,'' Safiullin said through a
translator. ``Our boxing program is the only national sports
program that is totally supported by the government. Even during
the breakup of the Soviet Union, because of our past successes the
government didn't let it fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan has vast untapped fossil fuel resources as well as
reserves of minerals and metals, but market reform has been slow
and the process by which licenses are awarded to Western companies
by the ruling elite is murky. Once the home of defense industries
and test ranges, its radioactive and toxic chemical sites pose
significant pollution problems. There are significant ethnic and
religious differences because natives of the old Kazakh republic _
predominantly Muslim _ now outnumber the Russian immigrants when
the opposite was true 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, the national boxing program flourishes,
Safiullin said, with some challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is ever perfect anywhere,'' he said. ``There are
always some problems, but we get sponsors and things are going
well.''
</P>
<P>
   In the worldwide boxing community, Kazakhstan's presence
continues to grow with its boxing leaders serving as high-ranking
members of the Amateur International Boxing Association, the body
that governs Olympic boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan's success in Sydney has the American coach, Tom
Mustin, trying to get the Kazakh fighters to come to the United
States for a dual meet next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot to learn from them,'' Mustin said. ``They're
extra strong; they know how to brawl and roughhouse. They must do
neck exercises because punches don't seem to affect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan won a gold, a silver and two bronze medals at the
1996 Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do better this time,'' Safiullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Told that the U.S. coach wondered what exercises his team does
to withstand the torrent of punches they customarily see, Safiullin
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him they go back centuries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
