<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     09-28 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS OF THE TIMES: SAME SOB STORY, DIFFERENT SOBBER 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ If you had put it to a vote, polled the
Olympic community, I suspect it would have been a landslide
Slobodan Milosevic couldn't ignore. By the time it was announced
Thursday that Andreea Raducan wasn't getting her gold medal back,
people just wished the cute little gymnast could wipe away the
tears and go home happily to Romania to claim her $30,000 victory
prize.
</P>
<P>
   And that was before Ion Tiriac apologized for English that is
``not Shakespearean,'' and played host to an Oprah-like panel that
included the victimized Raducan and the Romanian gymnastic
matriarch, Nadia Comaneci.
</P>
<P>
   ``An aspirin is doping?'' said Tiriac, the whiskered president
of the Romanian Olympic Committee. ``OK, we are machines. We have
to act like machines.''
</P>
<P>
   The one-time career guide for Boris Becker has always been an
entertaining fellow, dramatic and bold with his pronunciations.
Just recently, back in more familiar territory, he reportedly said,
on the eve of Marat Safin's blowout of Pete Sampras in the U.S.
Open final: ``Sampras is out of gas. His tank is empty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic sport of doping is apparently more difficult to
handicap. With expectation growing that common sense and plain
sentiment would prevail, the opposite occurred. Tiriac apparently
believed he had successfully argued Raducan's case in a Wednesday
hearing. But before the Romanians gave Thursday's public defense,
an unsmiling bureaucrat from the International Court of Arbitration
for Sport read a statement that said, in effect: Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   And no questions from the news media would be answered either.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cold ending, no pun intended, leaving Raducan to seek
comfort in the arms of Comaneci, star of the 1976 Montreal Games.
Tiriac, meanwhile, lamented that the International Olympic
Committee, besieged as it is with drug scandals here, ``didn't have
the courage, in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, given the imagery of a weepy 4-foot-10-inch, 82-pound
pixie, the IOC demonstrated an intrepid resolve that was sure to
bring it additional scorn. Especially after its own inadvisable
assertion that Raducan had done nothing wrong by accepting a cold
pill from a team doctor that contained a banned substance,
pseudoephedrine, before the all-around event swept by the Romanians
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely as it seems that some competitive advantage was being
sought, what qualifies the IOC to know beyond a doubt what the
Romanians were up to? The same day Tiriac was appealing the Raducan
decision, the International Amateur Athletic Federation was
scoffing at C.J. Hunter's explanation for why he tested positive
for the anabolic steroid nandrolone last July. It was pretty much
the same sob story: He took a dietary supplement without knowing
what was in it.
</P>
<P>
   If it had been some Romanian weight lifter in the position
Raducan was in, would anyone have cared at all?
</P>
<P>
   All of these sports have their own peculiar cultures. Female
gymnasts don't bulk up, for obvious reasons, but most of them look
no more natural than the weight lifters. And that's usually the
problem with these cases, how they are defended, adjudicated and
publicly digested. Few of us know what the stimulants and drugs
even do, and at what levels they become significant. No one ever
knows for certain what the athletes were thinking, and sometimes,
neither do they.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when Tom Gugliotta, the Phoenix Suns' forward, had a
seizure on the team bus last season? He went on television the
following week and said he had taken a supplement that had been
recommended by a friend. Why did he take it? He couldn't say. What
was it supposed to do for him? He didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Tiriac knew little about the particulars of this story, only
that he ``couldn't look himself in the mirror'' if he hadn't fought
to get Raducan's medal returned. After vowing to suspend any
Romanian doper for life and claiming everyone on the Olympic team
was tested before the Games, he may wish to comb his hair with his
eyes closed. Two Romanian weight lifters were thrown out last week
and its world-record holder in the hammer throw, Mihaela Melinte,
was pulled off the field Wednesday for failing an IAAF test last
June.
</P>
<P>
   According to the track federation, the Romanians were informed
of the test two days earlier, and did nothing. You might say
Tiriac's track record doesn't exactly support his outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight years ago, an American swimmer, 16-year-old Rick
DeMont, was stripped of his 400-meter freestyle medal in Munich,
after taking an asthma medication that contained a banned
substance. DeMont wound up suing the U.S. Olympic Committee for
breach of fiduciary duty. Considering the tragedy of those
Olympics, the slaying of 11 Israeli athletes by terrorists,
DeMont's case was not exactly cause for international dishonor.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is this one, no matter how frail and sad-eyed the tiny
gymnast looked, sitting with her hands folded Thursday, as she
explained, ``I've done nothing wrong.'' It's entirely possible she
didn't, but then, who can definitively say that Hunter willfully
took the steroids he is accused of taking?
</P>
<P>
   Tiriac's little show Thursday came off no less contrived than
Hunter's. He said Raducan, who turns 17 Saturday, would get her
$30,000 prize. The Romanian who backed into the gold, Simona
Amanar, said she was accepting the medal because ``it belongs to
Romania. The winner that day was Andreea, not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Amanar should give Raducan back the medal when they get
home, and leave it at that. As Tom Hanks said, there's no crying in
the uneven parallel bars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
