<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Sept. 29:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ An Indonesian court
dismissed all charges against Suharto, the former president, and
abandoned his landmark corruption trial after doctors found him to
be too sick to face corruption charges. One Suharto supporter died
in riots as hundreds of Suharto opponents took to the streets.
These events followed by one day the sentencing of Suharto's son,
Tommy, to 18 months on corruption charges. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTIONS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Post-election
developments. Opponents threatened a general strike that would shut
down schools, offices and all institutions until Slobodan Milosevic
recognized their election victory. Montenegro and the Serbian
Orthodox Church were reported to have recognized Kostunica's
victory. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-MONTENEGRO (Dateline TK) _ What the vote in Yugoslavia
means to the people of Montenegro. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-UNREST (Jerusalem) _ On Thursday, Israel's opposition
leader, Ariel Sharon, visited Temple Mount, a shrine that is at the
center of peace talks, and clashes immediately broke out. Riot
police fired rubber bullets at 200 Palestinians. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK-EURO (Copenhagen, Denmark) _ Exit polls from Thursday's
vote showed that the Danes were moving toward rejecting the euro.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-POLITICS (Washington) _ President Alberto Fujimori of Peru
arrived in Washington Thursday for meetings with officials from the
Organization for American states, and requested to meet with
``high-level'' U.S. officials. (Byline TK)
</P>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE-TRIAL (Camp Zeist, Netherlands) _ The defense
continued to dismantle the testimony of the prosecution's star
witness in the trial in the bombing of PanAm Flight 103. By Donald
G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ President-elect Vicente Fox
promises to create a ``Transparency Commission'' when he takes
office nine weeks from now. It could be a window into a panorama of
secrets. The commission would have to confront Mexico's biggest
unsolved mysteries. What became of billions of dollars spent
bailing out banks in 1995? Was the killing of the ruling party's
presidential candidate in 1994 a political assassination? By Tim
Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-POLITICS (London) _ Tony Blair's law-and-order program
has been so tough _ on concerns ranging from drunkenness in the
streets to antisocial behavior in public housing developments _
that the stern Conservatives have at times been able to argue, with
straight faces, that they are the civil libertarians in the
political equation. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   FDA-ABORTION-PILL (Undated) _ In a major victory for supporters
of abortion rights, the Food and Drug Administration ended an
18-year standoff and announced that it had approved the marketing
of an abortion-inducing pill, the first alternative to surgical
abortion approved in the United States. Political fallout was
expected. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-INSURE (Washington) _ The number of Americans without
health insurance declined substantially last year, to 42.6 million,
reversing a 12-year trend. The number of uninsured had been growing
steadily by more than a million a year. It fell by 1.7 million in
1999, mostly because of an increase in coverage provided by
employers _ and perhaps because of a new program for children. By
Robert Pear.  &UR; Embargoed for electronic use until midnight &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   SC-SAUCE-RELIGION (Columbia, S.C.) _ Maurice Bessinger's famous
mustard BBQ sauce is being pulled from grocery shelves all across
South Carolina, and not because he refuses to use tomatoes.
Bessinger, who once waged a lawsuit to keep blacks segregated in
his restaurants, has been distributing religious tracts along with
his sandwiches, tracts that suggest that slavery was biblically
ordained, and that slaves were better off in the United States than
they were in Africa. He's also been flying a huge Confederate Flag
on his main store. Six major grocery chains, including Kroger and
Wal-Mart, are refusing to sell his sauce, and residents are either
infuriated or pleased, depending on their politics. Bessinger says
his religious freedom has been violated, and his business seriously
damaged. But he's hardly apologizing. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ A growing percentage of women who
are treated for early-stage breast cancer are getting inappropriate
treatment, a new study has found. Researchers found that women who
are getting lumpectomies are not all getting radiation or having
lymph nodes examined, lapses that could lead to recurrence of
disease. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-CLIMATE (Washington) _ In anticipation of the next
round of global climate talks in The Hague, Netherlands, the Senate
is holding a hearing on the Kyoto climate accord. By Andrew C.
Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-SPEND (Washington) _ The Senate was expected to vote on a
stop-gap spending measure that would keep government agencies
functioning until Oct. 6. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEBATE (Austin, Texas) _ It is impossible to know which
incarnation of George W. Bush will show up at the first debate
between Bush and Vice President Al Gore in Boston next week. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-CAMPAIGN (Dateline TK) _ Battleground report from Michigan,
with fresh poll numbers. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GORE-ENERGY (Washington) _ A look at the energy policies of
Bush and Gore. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEYS (Dateline TK) _ As campaign props, political spouses and
children have long held a place somewhere beside red, white and
blue bunting, yard signs, buttons and balloons. But this year,
perhaps more than most, presidential politics is a family affair.
There was Laura Bush at the Republican convention. There was the
little matter of that kiss that Al Gore planted on his wife,
Tipper, at the Democratic National Convention. But the hardest
working family in this election cycle may be that of the Republican
vice presidential nominee, Dick Cheney. By Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-CONGRESS (Waukegan, Ill.) _ A report on the race in
Illinois' 10th District. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Dateline TK) _ George W. Bush's campaign day. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline TK) _ Al Gore's campaign day. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-AD-COLUMN (Sydney, Australia) _ Sydney has gone further
than any previous host city of the Olympics to protect its official
sponsors from being ambushed by rivals. Although nonsponsor
companies are visible here, Sydney has little of the flea-market
ambience that made the Atlanta Games a byword for crass
commercialism. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALLS (Dateline TK) _ Ford Motor Co. said it will give
consumers a choice of tires from three different companies _
Michelin, Goodyear and Bridgestone/Firestone _ for future versions
of the Explorer. (Byline TK)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Caracas, Venezuela) _ Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah
told leaders at the OPEC summit meeting that Saudi Arabia, the
world's biggest oil producer, is prepared to produce whatever
amount of oil is necessary to stabilize prices. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   BIOENGINEER-CORN (Plainview, Texas) _ It is a variety of
bioengineered corn supposedly fit only for animal feed. But somehow
it seems to have wound up in taco shells in stores nationwide.
Finding its source, somewhere in the Texas Panhandle, is proving to
be a challenge. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ An interview with German O. Gref,
Russia's 36-year-old economics minister, who is under orders from
President Vladimir Putin to cut taxes and bureaucracy to insure
long-term growth and restore faith among investors, who have grown
cynical about Russia's future. By Sabrina Tavernise.
</P>
