<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN BOXERS BACK ON COURSE AFTER EARLY SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The evening did not start out well for the
celebrated Cuban boxing team Thursday when their light flyweight
Maikro Romero lost a controversial decision to Brahim Asloum of
France. It was the fifth consecutive defeat for a Cuban boxer in
the Olympic tournament going back to Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's coach, Alcides Sagarra, who a month ago had suggested
that his team could medal in all 12 weight classifications, waved
his hands disdainfully at the judges when the Romero decision was
announced, then stormed from the ring with a few angry shouts.
</P>
<P>
   But less than 30 minutes later, Sagarra was escorting his
bantamweight Guillermo Rigondeaux into the same ring. Rigondeaux
would dominate the American Clarence Vinson, winning easily on
points, 18-6. It began a streak of four successive victories for
the Cubans, the last another comfortable victory for the
heavyweight Felix Savon.
</P>
<P>
   So the Cubans have four boxers, including the lightweight Mario
Kindelan and the middleweight Jorge Gutierrez, fighting for gold
medals Saturday. Diogenes Luna, a light welterweight, will try to
make it five Cubans in the finals when he faces the American
Ricardo Williams Jr. on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson was never in Thursday night's fight, being beaten to the
punch by the fluid, powerful Rigondeaux from the earliest moments
of the bout. Rigondeaux, who fights left-handed, is 4 inches taller
than the 5-foot-2-inch Vinson and used his reach and graceful
footwork to ward off Vinson's many advances and to score
repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mustin, the U.S. coach, said Vinson has always had trouble
against left-handed fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this guy was strong and moved great side to side,'' Mustin
said of Rigondeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson will win a bronze medal because the losers of both
semifinals are awarded bronze medals in boxing. Vinson fought with
heart, as he kept trying to force the attack against Rigondeaux
even though he trailed by several points. But Vinson could not
routinely get close enough to his target, and Rigondeaux has a
mighty left hand he knows how to use. Rigondeaux stopped Vinson for
a count of 8 with one straight left hand to the face in the third
round, and he knocked Vinson down a few moments later with another
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little flat today and he fought very well,'' said
Vinson, who now plans to turn professional. ``He was a better
fighter today. You win some; you lose some. I'll take the bitter
with the sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Savon advanced easily, though he didn't look sharp in his 14-8
victory on points against Germany's Sebastian Kober. Savon even
briefly trailed during the fight's first round, but he rallied to
build a cushy lead. But even the slower, plodding Kober was able to
hit Savon.
</P>
<P>
   Savon, 33, will be a favorite to win his third gold medal
Saturday when he faces Sultanahmed Ibzagimov of Russia, who
defeated Vladimir Tchantouria of Georgia. The Ibzagimov-Tchantouria
bout had the Sydney crowd alternately booing, hooting and laughing,
it was so comically slapstick. The two wrestled each other to the
canvas at one point and spent four rounds otherwise wildly missing
with clumsy punches.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins, Savon would become the second boxer to win three
Olympic gold medals in one weight class, equaling his countryman
Teofilo Stevenson's mark.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Williams, the Americans Jermain Taylor and Ricardo
Juarez fight in Friday night semifinal bouts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
