<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATEBOARD-PRO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AGE NO BARRIER TO A SAGE OF SKATEBOARDING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RENE A. GUZMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 32, Tony Hawk could be considered the elder statesman of
skateboarding. Just don't tell the skating legend to give up his
board for a ``grown-up job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like there's always been a stigma attached to skating
that it's just for kids,'' Hawk said in a telephone interview from
his home in Carlsbad, Calif. ``As I grew up in the '80s and skated
into my 20s, I felt I kept improving at it. Suddenly, (pro skaters
my age) realized we were pushing the age limit boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the aerial boundaries, too. Last year, Hawk made
skateboarding history when he sank his claws into the world's first
``900'' _ a two-and-a-half midair rotation above a plywood ramp. It
would be just another dizzying exclamation point in Hawk's 20 years
as a pro skater, a run that includes more than 80 original skating
tricks and 70-plus major contest victories.
</P>
<P>
   Now the ``Michael Jordan of skateboarding'' is once again
soaring to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   Though retired from competition, Hawk still sees plenty of
airtime at world-touring exhibitions, most courtesy of ESPN's
popular ``X Games.'' He recently released an upbeat biography,
``Hawk: Occupation: Skateboarder'' (Regan Books, $23). And now
everybody can fly like a Hawk in ``Tony Hawk's Pro Skater 2,''
Activision's highly-anticipated video game sequel that just aired
onto store shelves this week .
</P>
<P>
   So in case you thought the up-and-down world of skateboarding
was in the midst of another tailspin, take it from the non-sport's
ultimate ambassador: As long as it sticks to its subculture roots,
skating will always have plenty of fans eager to hop on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that (skating) attitude has changed at all,''
Hawk said. ``I'd like to think that has been appreciated most. If
you don't want to worry about teams or practice schedules, here's
something you can do at your own pace and on your own terms. An
activity like skateboarding is exactly what some people are looking
for but never knew it was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawk's video games have certainly filled the ranks with the
newly converted. Last year's critically lauded ``Tony Hawk's Pro
Skater'' was one of the best-selling PlayStation game console
titles ever. The new ``Pro Skater 2'' sports even more intense
skater graphics, dead-on trick capabilities and enough high-rolling
terrain to amaze hardcore skaters and cursory fans alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us only anticipated the game to be popular among
skaters,'' Hawk said. ``We didn't think this would be a platform
for all kinds of video gamers. It was a great surprise, and has
helped to bring recognition to skating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, all these kids are experts at tricks and
difficulties and names,'' he said, ``which has always been one of
the hardest things for people to understand. They don't realize how
technical it is, and now (through the video games) they can see
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ``Pro Skater'' games aren't the only action-packed
Cliffs Notes for non-skaters. Since 1995, ESPN's ``X Games'' have
entertained and educated more armchair fans in the delicate nuances
of an ollie (popping the board's tail or nose while riding to
``hop'' into the air) and skating's other complex maneuvers, which
often make gymnastics look like a dull game of Twister.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The `X Games') have become a lot truer to representing
skating to how we approach it,'' Hawk said. ``The first year, it
was how `they' see `us.' Now, it's much more about what we want to
convey and how do we want to convey ourselves. I think through that
skewed programming in the beginning, the attitude and passion
shined through. Now they appreciate our opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   And that opinion has long been that skateboarding is about
having fun, not winning trophies. Even a self-professed competitor
like Hawk admits that the only guy on the ramp he ever really
fought against was himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking at skating in general, there are so many
skaters who never compete and are successful,'' said Hawk, citing
skating greats such as Steve Caballero, Eric Koston and Rodney
Mullen (who are all featured in ``Pro Skater 2''). ``They perform,
but not in a competition arena. That's never really been an issue
in skating.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days, Hawk focuses his self-improvement skills toward
parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   The father of two sons (Riley, 7, and Spencer, 18 months), Hawk
said that his hectic touring schedule is sometimes tough on his
children and his wife Erin, 28. Still, the family doesn't fault him
for spreading the gospel of skateboarding as a noncompetitive means
of self-expression.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's a fun job and Hawk still excels at it _ whether
it's on his board, in a book or on a video game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure skating will improve and may get bigger,'' he
predicted. ``But even if it doesn't grow there's now a foundation.
It's going to have much more longevity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
