</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-PILL (Washington) _ The government's approval of the
abortion pill RU-486 is hailed by pro-choice advocates and
denounced by anti-abortion activists. The proponents say it will
allow women to end their pregnancies privately at home, but
opponents predict few gynecologists will prescribe the pill. By
JENNIFER A. DLOUHY.
</P>
<P>
   FLIGHT-DELAYS (Washington) _ American Airlines Chairman Donald
J. Carty warns a House panel that flight delays will worsen next
year unless Congress intervenes to limit the burgeoning number of
flights at major airports. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-KILLING (Washington) _ Religious leaders and civil rights
advocates urge Congress to pass the pending hate crime bill
following the shooting death last week in a Roanoke, Va., gay bar
by a gunman who announced he was there to ``waste fags.'' By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President
Al Gore trade shots on who would be the better long-term custodian
of the nation's economy. At a rally in Green Bay, Wis., Bush paints
Gore as a big spender who would jeopardize budget surpluses. In
Washington, Gore says Bush's proposed tax cuts would give ``too
much to too few at the expense of too many.'' By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The myth is now frozen that the way
to woo female voters is to master the art of the smooch and chatter
about silly things like peanut butter sandwiches, as Al Gore and
George W. Bush are doing. The myth is as misleading as it is
patronizing. Women don't vote for president solely out of emotion
any more than men vote entirely by intellect. In any case we are
not a monolith. All the political talk about how to get the female
vote is just that _ talk. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES (Washington) _ In the first of the presidential debates
Tuesday night, George W. Bush hopes to bolster his aw-shucks appeal
with detailed knowledge of the issues while Al Gore tries to
connect personally with TV-viewers and avoid policy-wonk preaching.
The two are squaring off in the first of three showdowns that could
sway the outcome of the closest presidential election in 20 years.
By STEWART M. POWELL
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-ELECTION (Washington) _ Al Gore and George W. Bush are
knocking themselves out trying to one-up the other on education, an
issue at the top of voters' concerns. Each would dramatically boost
federal education spending, and each has a plan to raise student
achievement, but they are polar opposites on the controversial idea
of vouchers. We compare and contrast the two candidates' plans. By
DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PREVIEW (Washington) _ After tackling such volatile issues
as gay rights and late-term abortion in its last term, the Supreme
Court starts a new session Monday with a wide-ranging docket of
cases involving police searches, immigration law, soccer moms,
high-school athletes, migrating birds and smog. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   PEARL-HARBOR (Washington) _ Congress appears poised to exonerate
the U.S. commanders at Pearl Harbor at the time of the surprise
Japanese attack on Dec. 7, 1941. Legislation approved by both the
House and Senate would absolve Rear Admiral Husband Kimmel and Maj.
Gen. Walter Short of blame for the disaster, saying both officers
were ``professional and competent.'' By CHARLES J. LEWIS and ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
