<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5102 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-CARAMELIZATION-HNS &LR;      09-28 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARAMELIZATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAKING CARAMELIZATION WORK FOR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some classic dishes, such as caramel apples, sticky buns and
creme brulee, rely on caramelization for their complex flavors.
Newer dishes also make use of the technique.
</P>
<P>
   MICROWAVE CARAMEL
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 3/4 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   4 or 5 drops lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon water, if needed
</P>
<P>
   Place sugar in a 2-cup glass measure. Add corn syrup and lemon
juice. Stir until no white patches of dry sugar remain. Add a
tablespoon of water if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Place the dampened sugar in the microwave and cook, on high
power, until bubbles start piling on top of each other; time will
depend on the amount of sugar and the power of the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   The second you see a color change begin to occur _ melted sugar
turning to pale tan _ be on the alert. let the color darken only
slightly, them remove caramel from oven and let stand. Caramel will
continue to darken. If the mixture does not get as dark as desired,
microwave on high for 10 seconds more, then let stand again.
</P>
<P>
   Uses: Pour the caramel in ramekins and swirl to coat evenly to
use as the base for flan. Spoon on top of baked, chilled creme
brulee and swirl to make a seamless topping. Use it to coat the
bottom of a baking dish and then bake your favorite bread pudding
recipe in the dish. Pour into muffin cups then top with
refrigerator biscuits cut into pieces. Bake as directed on package.
Remove from oven, let cool 5 minutes then invert onto a serving
plate for fast sticky buns.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Cookwise'' by Shirley O. Corriher (Morrow, 1997)
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   CREME BRULEE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 8)
</P>
<P>
   10 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 quart heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Sugar for topping
</P>
<P>
   Line a baking pan, large enough to hold 8 ramekins or flameproof
custard cups, with a dish towel. Set a kettle of water on to boil.
Heat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg yolks thoroughly. Add cream, vanilla and sugar and
whisk until well combined. Pour custard mixture into ramekins and
place in prepared baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Place baking on rack in center of oven. Pour boiling water into
baking pan until the water comes halfway up the sides of the
ramekins. Cover baking pan with foil and punch holes in foil to
allow the steam to escape. Bake until a spot about the size of a
quarter is still wiggly in the center of each custard, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove ramekins from water bath and let cool. Refrigerate until
thoroughly chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, heat broiler. Sprinkle the top of each
custard very lightly with granulated sugar. (We sifted the sugar
through a fine mesh strainer onto the custards to remove any
lumps).
</P>
<P>
   Place custards on a sheet pan under broiler. Broil just long
enough to caramelize sugar, 1 to 2 minutes, watching closely to
make sure the sugar doesn't burn.
</P>
<P>
   _ From Coastal Grill restaurant, Virginia Beach, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   UNION SQUARE CAFE'S CARAMEL BANANA TART
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 6)
</P>
<P>
   CRUST:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   BANANA TOPPING:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 1 tablespoon sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   4 large, ripe bananas, thinly sliced on the diagonal
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped macadamia nuts (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream, optional
</P>
<P>
   CRUST:
</P>
<P>
   Beat the butter and the sugar in a large bowl with a mixer. Beat
in the egg yolk, vanilla, salt and blend well. Add the flour and
beat until moist clumps begin to form. Press the dough with your
hands into the bottom of a 9-inch tart pan with a removable bottom.
Pierce with a fork in a few places, about 2 inches apart.
Refrigerate 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 450, Bake crust until golden, 15 minutes. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   TOPPING:
</P>
<P>
   Place a large baking pan half filled with cold water and ice
cubes next to the stove. Combine 1/2 cup of the sugar, the corn
syrup, and 1 tablespoon of the melted butter in a small saucepan
over medium heat. Heat the mixture until the sugar dissolves and it
comes to a boil. Boil the mixture, without stirring but swirling
the pan occasionally so that it brown evenly, until it turns a
medium amber color, 7 minutes. Place the pan in the ice water to
prevent further cooking and to cool it to lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oven to 375 degrees. Arrange the banana slices,
overlapping them slightly, in a concentric circle beginning at the
crust edge and working your way in so that the crust is completely
covered. Brush the remaining tablespoon of butter over the bananas
and sprinkle with the remaining tablespoon of sugar. Bake until the
tart is just warmed through, 3 to 5 minutes. Rewarm the caramel
topping over low heat, stirring occasionally. Remove the tart from
the oven. Dip a spoon into the caramel and drizzle it back and
forth in squiggly lines over the bananas. Remove the pan bottom and
place the tart on a platter. Scatter nuts over top and serve.
</P>
<P>
   _ From Union Square Cafi, Albany, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1422EDT &QL; 
