<HEADER>
A5132 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-RECALLEDTIRES-SPARES-     09-28 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECALLEDTIRES-SPARES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCKS USE RECALLED TIRE TYPE AS SPARES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KELLY MELHART 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Firestone tires being used as spares on Ford's new Ranger Edge
pickups are identical, except for some markings, to the model
recalled last month after being linked to fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Firestone officials emphasized Wednesday that the spare
tires are safe if used at speeds of less than 50 mph and distances
of less than 50 miles. The Firestone ATX tires are embossed with
the words ``temporary only'' and ``Max speed 50 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   The temporary tires are not part of the recall, Ford and
Firestone officials said Wednesday. But other than the warnings,
the spares are identical to the recalled tires, said Joe Quinn,
Firestone spokesman in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Various dealers in Fort Worth-Dallas, apparently confused by
information from Ford, are handling the tire recalls differently,
they said. Some are replacing the spares, and others are not.
</P>
<P>
   The tires were found as spares on eight new Ranger Edge pickups
during a spot-check of dealerships Wednesday in the Metroplex.
Dealership managers said the pickups arrived from assembly plants
with the ATX spares.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary tires have been standard equipment on Ranger
trucks for at least a year, Ford spokesman Mike Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not the same as recall tires,'' Vaughn said from his
Detroit office. ``They are designed for temporary use to get you to
a repair facility to get the tire fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration said Wednesday that they were talking to
Bridgestone/Firestone and Ford Motor Co. about the tires after
learning about them from the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. They said
they could not make a statement. The administration has received no
complaints about the temporary tires, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Rolls, a Maryland resident who founded Tire Action Group to
try to persuade Firestone to recall all ATX and Wilderness tires,
said the spares should be recalled until more questions are
answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a flat tire and you put on a spare, and then your life
is riding around on a spare,'' said Rolls, who founded the group
after his Ford Explorer tires, which were not part of the recall,
began to fail. ``All these ATX and Wilderness tires ought to go.
Everyone who is riding around on them is riding around on four
tragedies.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not have specific reports about the quality of
Ranger spare tires, Rolls said he has heard from drivers of other
Ford vehicles whose spares are ``failing with less than 300 miles
on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth resident Tom Shafer insisted on five replacement
tires for his 2001 Ranger Edge after he found an ATX temporary tire
beneath the truck bed Tuesday night. Shafer said he matched the
code on his spare to the P235/75R15 code on the recalled ATX tires.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Firestone officials said the 15-inch tires marked
``temporary'' are not part of the recall, regardless of the code.
</P>
<P>
   Shafer, who bought the truck Sept. 15, said that doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a spare until a tire blows, then where is it?'' he
said. ``This is not about me, it's about (Ford's) president on
national TV saying his company is doing everything in its power to
ensure the safety of its customers _ his words, not mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Shafer's five Firestone tires were replaced with those of a
competitor Wednesday at the Five Star Ford dealership in North
Richland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The P235/75R15 radial ATX tire is one of three Firestone tire
types recalled by the company Aug. 9 after reports that their tread
peels off while the vehicle is traveling. The safety administration
is investigating reports of 101 deaths and more than 400 injuries
linked to tire problems.
</P>
<P>
   Other problem tires are the Wilderness AT types produced at the
company's Decatur, Ill., plant and all of the standard P235/75R15
radial ATX II types.
</P>
<P>
   Federal standards differ for regular tires and spares.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the standard ATX tires and the temporary
ones is how they are tested and how they are expected to be used,
Firestone spokesman Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel confident in our tires, and we believe temporary
tires, if used properly, will be safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone spare tire guidelines include driving less than 50 mph
and less than 50 miles, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Temporary spares are exactly what they say they are. They are
what you use when you have a flat,'' Ford spokesman Vaughn said.
``The tread separations, apparently they happen at higher mileages
and higher speeds and higher temperatures. All of those seem to be
aggravating factors. This is a temporary spare meant to be used at
a lower speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Recall literature from Ford has conflicting information. Some
advertisements state that all Firestone ATX and ATX II tires with
the P235/75R15 designation are affected, but some brochures state
that the temporary tires are not included in the recall regardless
of the designation. So some dealerships and tire retailers swap
spares, and others do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's on the recall list, it's being recalled,'' said Tim
Barnette, service manager for Texas Motors Ford in west Fort Worth.
``There's no documentation I have that says they (spare tires) are
not part of the recall.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wilson, finance director at Westway Ford, said the
dealership had replaced numerous spare tires at customers'
requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have checked them all,'' he said. ``If they've been in the
recall, we've replaced them. We've had hundreds of calls. I'd like
to be able to replace every Firestone out there, but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson said he was not sure whether the Ranger spare tire is
subject to the recall.
</P>
<P>
   He said a portion of the Ford recall notice states that the
Firestone Wilderness AT tire must have ``DOT VDHL'' on the sidewall
to be subject to the recall. He said he believed that the ATX and
ATX II models also needed those markings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it has that number, it's in the recall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Ford and Firestone officials have said that the ``DOT
VDHL'' marking applies only to the Wilderness AT model.
</P>
<P>
   In North Richland Hills, Five-Star Ford general manager Gary
Brophy cited a Ford internal memo that states that the temporary
tires are not part of the recall, although all other ATX and ATX II
tires with the P235/75R15 designation are. Brophy said his
dealership replaced Shafer's tires to allay his concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Black, service director at Grand Prairie Ford, said he
does not believe that there is a problem with ATX temporary tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as any different than putting a doughnut
(spare) on a Taurus,'' Black said. ``This is completely different
than a main service tire. This is for emergency use only.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to warnings on temporary tires, the owner's manual
also spells out how they should be used, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
