<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-YOUTHVOTE-INTERNET-10     09-28 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTHVOTE-INTERNET-1001-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET SPURS YOUTH INVOLVEMENT IN ELECTORAL PROCESS
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 1
 &HT;    By MEGAN K. DOYLE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After working a 13 hour day, Alexis Rice spends
another four hours on her computer working toward her real goal _
involving today's youth in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, 22, launched a non-profit, non-partisan Web site in July
aimed at educating young people about the upcoming presidential
election: www.generationvote.com.
</P>
<P>
   A native of West Palm Beach, Fla., Rice and a handful of other
founders rely on a nationwide network of young volunteers to
provide articles and opinion columns about the major issues in the
2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to educate, motivate and encourage young people to
become politically active,'' Rice said. ``I started this site
because I felt that there was nothing out there, as far as
political news goes, that spoke specifically to young voters. I
didn't see anything for my generation, to give them information
about the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   For Rice, the reasons for using the Internet to reach today's
youth are clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most young people have fast, easily available connections to
the Internet through their schools or jobs,'' Rice said. ``They're
used to using it for research, for fun, for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice began thinking about the site in March. She sent e-mails
and press releases to young activist groups and colleges across the
country. She posted information about her idea on the Web, looking
for people to help with the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most sites spend hundreds of thousands on design,'' Rice said.
``We're not funded by any corporation, we're just young people
encouraging youth to go out and vote. So we had to find designers
and writers who believed in the project and would work for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that generationvote.com is operational, staffers spend their
weekends and evenings keeping it updated. The Web is the one place
Rice said she can make a difference for youth voters.
</P>
<P>
   She is not alone. Since the 1996 election, many organizations
have gone to the Internet to reach young people.
</P>
<P>
   Even the presidential candidates are going on-line in efforts to
grab the youth vote. Both Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore offer pages on their campaign Web sites aimed at
today's youth.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's site, www.georgewbush.com, features pages where children
and college students can learn about the election and get involved
in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is more central to young voters today than in any
previous election,'' said Tucker Eskew, senior communications
advisor for the Bush-Cheney campaign. ``It's absolute political
dynamite for young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's site, www.algore2000.com, includes pages that encourage
children, college students, and young professionals to participate
in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young voters are Internet savvy,'' said Jano Cabrera, deputy
national spokesman for the Gore-Lieberman campaign. ``If they have
a question on a particular issue, they go to the Web site. If they
can't find the answer, they know they can ask the question on-line
and they'll get an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns said the amount of information available on the
Web will have a substantial impact on this and future elections.
</P>
<P>
   Web-based information already has affected some voters.
According to a 1998 study by the Pew Research Center, 34 percent of
people who used the Web for political purposes said their vote in
1998 was influenced by information they found on the Internet.
Another Pew study found that Americans under 30 are half as likely
to use the Internet for election news as a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Many sites see the Internet as a way to make the voting process
more accessible to today's youth. Through a partnership with
www.election.com, visitors to generationvote.com can register to
vote and request an absentee ballot on-line.
</P>
<P>
   Election.com has registered more than 300,000 people to vote
from their Web site through such partnerships, including one with
the American Association of Retired Persons, a group whose members
are 50 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Election.com also seeks to make lifelong voters out of today's
students through a program called Youth-e-Vote. The program works
with elementary and secondary schools to educate students about
issues and candidates, then urges the students to vote on-line a
week before the national election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people are the future of this country,'' said Julia
Glidden, vice president of public affairs at election.com. ``If
they're not engaged politically, we will all suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kids Voting USA is another organization trying to encourage
involvement in the electoral process. Kids Voting USA urges parents
to take their children to the polls on Election Day. Formed in
1991, the organization just went on-line a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw it as an opportunity to reach more people than we could
otherwise, especially because our program is so grass-roots
(oriented) and located in very specific areas,'' said Paula Case,
public relations coordinator at Kids Voting USA.
</P>
<P>
   The organization prepares children to vote through specific
civics courses taught in participating schools. Case cited the
ability to create an on-line curriculum that would be accessible
only to teachers as another major advantage of the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Kids Voting USA has seen some success. In 1996, Kids Voting
communities in Kansas had an 8 percent higher rate of turnout among
first-time voters than non-participating communities, according to
the Kansas secretary of state's office.
</P>
<P>
   Rock the Vote, a group dedicated to helping young people change
their communities, has also used the Internet to increase its
effectiveness. As a non-profit group, the organization finds it
easier to get its message out on the Web than through traditional
media where it has to rely on free advertising space and public
service announcements.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site is a place where young people can ``go a little
further'' by registering to vote, finding information about the
issues or speaking out on bulletin boards, according to Alison
Byrne Fields, creative director and chief strategist for Rock the
Vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the site, we get a lot of simple questions from young
people that maybe they're hesitant to ask for fear of looking
stupid, such as how to register to vote,'' Byrne Fields (CQ) said.
``The Web site enables them to do this anonymously.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of young people who don't vote cite unfamiliarity
with the candidates as the reason, according to a survey released
Monday by the Kaiser Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people feel uninformed and don't always feel that the
information out there is for them, but they feel a greater sense of
ownership over the Web,'' Byrne Fields (CQ) said. ``I think it
breaks down a lot of barriers for them. I think they know the Rock
the Vote site is for them, that it's a young people's site.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice said her struggle to create a young people's site has
already proven successful, as more and more young people volunteer
to write for the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were nights in the beginning working until three a.m.
when I had to be at work by nine, but it was worth it,'' Rice said.
``I can't think of anything better to do with my time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   GenerationVote.com: www.generationvote.com
</P>
<P>
   Rock the Vote: www.rockthevote.org
</P>
<P>
   Election.com: www.election.com
</P>
<P>
   Kids Voting USA: www.kidsvotingusa.org
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush campaign: www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore campaign: www.algore2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Youth-e-Vote: www.youthevote.net
</P>
<P>
   Youth Vote 2000: www.youthvote2000.org
</P>
<P>
   SpeakOut.com: www.speakout.com
</P>
<P>
   Pew Research Center: www.people-press.org
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Family Foundation: www.kff.org
</P>
<P>
   Megan K. Doyle's e-mail address is: mdoyle(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
