<SLUG> BC-EYE-EXPERIMENTS-DISCOVER-$ADV19-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE VISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., Sept. 19, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 (Color art is available.) 
 By ERIC HASELTINE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A large organization works most efficiently when a job gets
divided up among specialists, each of whom does a limited set of
things exceptionally well.
 &HT;    The same holds true for the human nervous system. Such division
of labor is especially prominent in the eye, home to two highly
distinct networks of light processing neurons.
 &HT;    In one network, visual nerve cells activated by rod-shaped
receptors are exquisitely sensitive to dim light and motion, but
hopeless at resolving colors and small contours.
 &HT;    The other network, driven by receptors shaped like cones, is
very proficient at discerning colors and fine details, but
relatively inept at detecting faint light or subtle movement.
 &HT;    Despite their individual weaknesses, the rod and cone systems
make a great team, working together like two army scouts who've
agreed that one will scan the landscape for movement but hand off
to his partner the job of determining what it is that's moving.
 &HT;    We don't notice that we have two receptor systems because our
brains seamlessly combine their outputs. But with these tests you
can tease them apart.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    EXPERIMENT 1
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Compare the brightness of these two color patches. In strong
light, the red should look a little punchier. But if you turn down
the lights until the gap in the C above the colors is barely
discernible, the red should be the dimmer of the two hues.
 &HT;    That's because the cone system, which dominates vision in
daytime, responds well to red light, whereas the rod system, which
rules the night, can hardly see red at all.
 &HT;    This change in relative color brightness from day to night is
called the Purkinje shift, after Jan Evangelista Purkinje, the
Czech scientist who first described it.
 &HT;    The proportion of rods to cones is greater away from the center
of the retina where you fix your gaze, so the red splotch will look
even darker if you move it into rod territory by staring at the C
instead of directly at the colors.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    EXPERIMENT 2
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Make an artificial star by taping a piece of cardboard over the
lens of a flashlight and then pricking a tiny hole in the
cardboard.
 &HT;    Ensuring that no light escapes except through the pinhole, put
the flashlight on a flat surface in a dark room, and angle the
light so you're not looking straight into it. Move 10 feet away and
you'll notice that the star is brighter when you look away from it
than it is when you look directly at it.
 &HT;    This provides more evidence that rods, which are most populous
in the periphery of vision, have greater sensitivity than the cones
that inhabit the center of the retina.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    EXPERIMENT 3
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Hold up your right index finger about 90 degrees from your
center of gaze. Now wiggle the finger vigorously, and notice how it
becomes much more visible while moving.
 &HT;    But if you look right at the same finger, it's just about as
noticeable moving as it is stationary. The reason: Rod-based
peripheral vision is vastly more sensitive to movement than it is
to small details, while the cone-based central vision is less
responsive to movement and more acute.
 &HT;    Remembering the physiological differences between your night and
day eyes can come in handy at times. For example, now you'll avoid
wearing red if you want friends to find you while you're scanning
the night sky with your peripheral vision, seeking out both faint
stars and the kind that you wish upon.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Eric Haseltine is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 c.2000 Discover magazine 
