r a BC-SMART-MICROBE-HNS &LR;      09-28 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-MICROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCIENTISTS IDENTIFY MICROBE WITH SOME INTELLIGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Many of the microbes are too small to see, and
through a microscope they resemble wriggling, translucent blobs
filled with lint.
</P>
<P>
   But they may not be as dumb as they look.
</P>
<P>
   One type of microbe has enough primitive intelligence to wend
its way through a maze, Japanese researcher Toshiyuki Nakagaki and
two colleagues report in Thursday's issue of the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The microbe, a slime mold named Physarum polycephalum, can
figure out the shortest distance between two points in a maze, as
if it were a little computer, the Japanese scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This remarkable process of cellular computation implies that
cellular materials can show a primitive intelligence,'' Nakagaki
and his team write.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts scoff at the idea that microbes possess
intelligence, even primitive. They say the microbe's behavior is
just an unthinking reflex action.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some critics acknowledge, the maze-running microbe
dramatizes that microbes aren't as passive and helpless as they
appear.
</P>
<P>
   Some microbes can engage in surprisingly complex behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're observing sounds real. But it's the
interpretation of the results that I question. The use of the word
intelligence might be stretching it,'' said Dennis Miller, an
associate professor of biology at the University of Iowa. Miller
frequently works with Physarum polycephalum in his research.
</P>
<P>
   In Nakagaki's experiment, the microbe was able to navigate its
way through the maze until it found the shortest _ and, hence, most
energy-efficient _ route between two blocks of microbe food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intelligence is a little bit strong as a statement (of the
microbe's behavior), but otherwise it's a nice little story,'' said
Steven Lindow, chairman of the division of microbial biology at the
University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Physarum polycephalum is a single giant cell, but it contains
multiple nuclei (gene-carrying materials). A typical cell contains
just one nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   A single Physarum polycephalum can spread several inches across,
as big as a Petri dish.
</P>
<P>
   Nakagaki works at the Bio-Mimetic Control Research Center in
Nagoya, Japan. His colleagues in the experiment were Hiroyasu
Yamada of Hokkaido University and Agota Toth of the University of
Szeged in Hungary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
