<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5207 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-NYDIA-ROJAS-HNS &LR;      09-28 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYDIA-ROJAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RANCHERO SINGER ROJAS REACHES NEW HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUSTINO AGUILA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ It wasn't even a week after her appendectomy,
but Nydia Rojas was ready to belt out her signature ranchero songs
for a PBS television show in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Still tender from the surgery, the 20-year-old then flew here
for another concert at an outdoor theater with about 300 people
watching her every delicate move. No problem.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Best Ranchero Performance nominee was headed
back to L.A. for the Latin Grammys at the Staples Center, where she
was seen by millions in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   After years of singing at everything from quinceaeras to
weddings and restaurants, where she made $40 for each appearance,
Rojas is finally reaching a new height in her career. On Saturday
at San Jose Arena she will begin a dream tour: appearing on the
same bill as legendary Mexican singers Juan Gabriel and Ana
Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be totally good at a different level,'' Rojas
said recently over a chicken ensalada at a Mexican restaurant.
``It's going to be instant credibility because of the name _ and
he's helping me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Crooner Juan Gabriel, who has amassed a musical empire worth
millions by writing, producing and performing his music since the
late '60s, is personally mentoring Rojas. Gabriel, who has written
hundreds of songs, is part of Hauser Entertainment, Inc., a
management group representing an A-list roster of Latino singers
including Rocio Durcal, Vicente Fernandez, his heartthrob son,
Alejandro Fernandez, and Joan Sebastian.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Rojas was asked to join the elite circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought she'd be a vital part of our company,`` said Ralph
Hauser. ``She has a good voice, she has a good work ethic and
crossover ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauser, who first met Rojas when she was about 16, watched her
grow up and was concerned about her voice changing, but it only got
better, he said. He added that he has asked Juan Gabriel ``if he
could help me in cultivating her in her growth. He's very
diversified. He's taken her under his wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas was born in Whittier, Calif., and raised in Guadalajara,
Mexico, where she took up mariachi music as a 2-year-old singing
Pedro Infante's ``Amorcito Corazon (Little Love, My Heart).''
</P>
<P>
   As a little girl she heard a boy in Mexico singing mariachi
music. It captivated her so much that she told her mother she
wanted to pursue mariachi singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was to say no,'' said Olivia Rojas, Nydia's
mother. ``I didn't want my daughter to sing love songs of
heartbreak that drunk men sing to women. Besides, it's not an easy
career, or lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother and daughter eventually forged an agreement. Nydia would
be allowed to sing as long as she studied music and kept up her
grades. She did.
</P>
<P>
   By age 11, Rojas had her first paying job as a mariachi musician
singing in a local L.A. restaurant. Years later she joined the
country's first all-female mariachi, Mariachi Reyna de Los Angeles.
By 15, she had gone solo and recorded her first album for Arista
Records.
</P>
<P>
   Today she has already recorded her third album, ``Si me
conocieras (If You Knew Me)'' on Hollywood Records and has played
for crowds reaching nearly 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   During the tour Rojas will be performing new music. She's
dropping the mariachi look and will add more pop. She will also be
moving around a lot more on stage. ``I will do a touch of mariachi
music (so as not to) leave my roots behind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican music typically uses trumpets, violins, a vihuela (small
guitar) and a guitarron (a big guitar) to convey the music's
passionate plea to love. The svelte singer, who often wears the
traditional embroidered costume known as a charro, knows how to
play all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas said she sees herself studying more, and not just music.
Between performances she takes classes at a junior college and said
she plans to transfer to a university to earn an MBA.
</P>
</TEXT>
