<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SOC-WOMEN-ART-500     09-28 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOC-WOMEN-ART-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CLASH OF SOCCER TITANS, NORWAY DEFEATS U.S. WOMEN FOR GOLD
MEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Norway) 
(ART ADV: Photos OLY 1,2,10,11,12,13,14,15 are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ No matter how many international tournaments
the United States has won, Norway has always played the role of
asterisk in the American domination of women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   It is the one nation with a winning record against the United
States, the one team with the same unyielding resolve and
expectation of victory. Norway did not capitulate Thursday night
when overtime of the Olympic gold medal came in the most
excruciating of ways, Tiffeny Milbrett heading a brilliant cross
from Mia Hamm into the net half a minute from the end of
regulation. The Norwegians grew angry, not discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got mad,'' defender Gro Espeseth said. ``I said: `No, we are
going to win this. We don't want them to do this again.' It was our
turn. We weren't going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3-2 Norwegian victory over the United States, before a crowd
of 22,848 at Sydney Football Stadium, will be remembered as one of
the greatest women's games ever played, wide open and full of wild
swings, breathless creativity, stirring defense, rapturous victory
and inconsolable defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive play developed 12 minutes into sudden death, when
midfielder Hege Riise sent a long, arcing pass into the penalty
area. Joy Fawcett got her head on the ball but could not control it
for the U.S. defense. The ball ricocheted off the upper left arm of
forward Dagny Mellgren and bounced free and unobstructed toward the
goal. Mellgren reached it and pushed a shot from 14 yards past the
diving U.S. goalkeeper Siri Mullinix, sending Norway into ecstatic
celebration and leaving the U.S. team in stunned silence, hands on
their hips, silver medals around their necks when they had expected
gold.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the game will be widely debated because of the
potential for a hand ball to have been called on Mellgren's winning
goal. The rules say that a violation occurs if a player touches the
ball on purpose or gains an advantage from the contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it was hitting me,'' Mellgren said. ``I didn't
see it. I didn't do it on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Chastain, the U.S. defender, said she was satisfied that,
unlike the NFL, international soccer does not rely on videotaped
replays to confirm or contradict a referee's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The referee is part of the game, for good calls and bad,''
Chastain said. ``I'd prefer her to make the call in that instant
than to rely on videotape.''
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett said she was uncertain what happened in the chaos of the
moment. Afterward, Julie Foudy, the U.S. captain, sought an
explanation from referee Sonia Denoncourt of Canada. The referee
put up her hand and said, ``Don't do this to me, Jules,'' said
Foudy, who added that Denoncourt thought the ball had hit
Mellgren's chest.
</P>
<P>
   The referee did not speak to reporters, but the U.S. team did
not challenge the decision, remaining gracious in defeat, calling
the loss shocking but not unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to focus on that,'' Foudy said. ``I think we need
to applaud Norway for a great game.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Norway has built a 15-13-2 overall record against the United
States, winning four and tying one of their eight matches this
year. It was Norway that handed the U.S. team their most bitter
defeat, a 1-0 loss in the semifinals of the 1995 Women's World Cup,
infuriating the United States when Riise and her teammates crawled
on their knees across the field in a celebration ritual called
``the train.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the United States defeated Norway in overtime of
the 1996 Olympic semifinals. The Americans opened the Sydney Games
with a 2-0 victory, dominating a Norwegian team that seemed slow
and listless. Thursday night, however, a rejuvenated Norwegian
squad prevailed on tactical resourcefulness, fresher legs and more
reliable goalkeeping.
</P>
<P>
   The United States scored in the first five minutes when Mia Hamm
elbowed her way around the defender Goeril Kringen and crossed a
pass to Tiffeny Milbrett, who chipped it into the net from 6 yards.
</P>
<P>
   `Oh, no, not again,'' Espeseth told herself in the Norwegian
defense. ``Why should they win again and again and again?''
</P>
<P>
   She would not let them. A minute before halftime, Riise lifted a
corner kick from the right side and Espeseth outjumped the U.S.
defender Kate Sobrero, flicking the ball with her head. Guarding
the left goal post, Shannon MacMillan raised her left leg, but the
ball deflected into the net for a 1-1 tie. A minute before
halftime, the United States had given a dormant team new life and
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a momentum crusher,'' Foudy said.
</P>
<P>
   Norway had opened the game in a 4-4-2 alignment with four
defenders, four midfielders and two forwards. After halftime, it
switched to five midfielders and began to pressure the United
States, closing space that had been wide open. In the 78th minute,
Mullinix rushed 12 yards off her line to punch away a long pass,
but instead collided with Fawcett, knocking her off the ball.
Ragnhild Gulbrandsen's header bounded into the empty net and put
Norway up, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Roaming the penalty area had made Mullinix an assertive
goalkeeper this year in replacement of an injured Briana Scurry,
but it also made her a risky last line of defense. She did not do
the one thing that is mandatory when she strayed from the goal
mouth: get her hands on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was a lack of experience,'' Mullinix said.
``That's my style. I'm not going to not play my style.''
</P>
<P>
   Seldom behind in any international tournament, the U.S. team
remained composed, and only 30 seconds before the end of
regulation, Hamm floated a crossing pass from the right flank to
the 5-foot-2 Milbrett, who outjumped a Norwegian defender and
headed in the tying goal. Criticized because she did not score in
the knockout round of the 1999 Women's World Cup, Hamm finished the
Sydney Games with the clever, dependable, relentless play that is
to be expected from someone with her reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just looked up to heaven and said, `Thank you,''' Hamm said
of the tying goal. ``I didn't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway might have folded at this point, but as it gathered
before overtime, Espeseth said her teammates were telling one
another: ``This is our Olympics. We're not going to lose.''
Mellgren had entered the game only 12 minutes earlier. While Hamm
and Milbrett had been running up and down nonstop, the Norwegian
forward had rested legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the Americans would be tired at the end, and we had
fresh legs to put in,'' Norway coach Per-Mathias Hagmo said.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve minutes into the overtime, Mellgren ran onto Riise's long
pass, lifted her arm slightly toward the ball, let it bounce and
fired a shot toward Mullinix. The U.S. goalkeeper lunged to her
left and got a hand on the ball but could not stop it. Norway had
won. Goalkeeping provided victory for the United States at the 1999
Women's World Cup, but Thursday night it was not steady enough to
prevent defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enormous will on our team,'' Mellgren said. ``We are
strong mentally and physically. We decided to win against every
team. I knew that if we kept going, we'd score a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mellgren's winning goal, Hamm knelt down and put her face
in her hands. Several of her teammates stood in disbelief. Others
hugged and cried in each other's arms. ``I was in shock until I got
to the locker room,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Having won a pair of World Cups and the gold medal at the
Atlanta Olympics in 1996, the U.S. team had changed the way women's
sports were viewed. They drew 90,000 fans to the Rose Bowl for the
1999 World Cup final, and 40 million television viewers in the
United States. No longer could anyone say that people would not pay
in large numbers to watch women play sports.
</P>
<P>
   A professional women's soccer league will start next April. The
players will finally be able to make a living at their sport
playing in their home country. But the U.S. squad wanted this
Olympic tournament as validation of their greatness, a confirmation
that they could win a major tournament outside the United States, a
final victory before many of the players considered retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted so badly to do it for this group,'' Foudy said.
``It's possibly our last time together. It's irreplaceable, this
bond.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, there were no excuses. Chastain, ever a
student of the sport, said defeat, as bitter as it was, was
tempered by the magnificence of Thursday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the greatest game I've ever been part of,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
