<HEADER>
A5223 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SALLYFIELD-INTERVIEW-     09-28 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALLYFIELD-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIELD FLIES OFF IN A NEW DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Sally Field appears to be eager to please. She's
sitting on the edge of a sofa in a cavernous suite in a Dallas
hotel, leaning into every question and comment as she discusses
``Beautiful,'' her feature-directing debut. She could be the
opposite of Mona, the ambitious beauty queen played by Minnie
Driver in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Field is affable; Mona is, well, kind of hard to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should be hard to take,'' Field says. ``I love that. I
love not knowing from the moment that you see someone on screen
that you're going to end up caring about their journey. Especially
when they're not coming onscreen with that, `You're going to have a
nice time with me because I'm going to be easy to take; I'm going
to be pleasant.' People aren't (pleasant). Things aren't. Life's
not.''
</P>
<P>
   If this doesn't sound like the winner of two Oscars and an Emmy
talking, recall that Field, who turns 54 in November, had been in
the biz more than a decade before she earned respect _ and her
first Emmy _ by playing a woman with 16 personalities in the 1976
TV movie ``Sybil.'' Recall that she had two Oscars before she
appeared to believe that she'd earned the respect. Recall that she
has been twice divorced, and that she's a single mother whose
primary focus these days is her youngest son, who's entering junior
high. Recall that she chooses her work carefully because she
believes it's still hard for a woman to earn respect in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   For her, it's especially hard to find a story that she can
relate to as a woman _ which is what drew her to ``Beautiful.'' Men
are inconsequential to ``Beautiful,'' which tells the story of a
woman who seeks redemption from an unhappy childhood by trying to
win beauty pageants. Mona, the protagonist, is so obsessed with
this process that she even pretends to be the aunt of her own
daughter _ because acknowledging the child would make her
ineligible for beauty contests.
</P>
<P>
   It's not Field's first directing assignment; she also handled a
1996 TV movie called ``The Christmas Tree'' and did a segment of
the Tom Hanks-produced HBO miniseries ``From the Earth to the
Moon.'' But it is her first shot at making a film for the big
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, primarily, I wanted to see if I wanted to do it
because I am a storyteller,'' Field says. ``As an actor, I'm a
storyteller, and that's what I've always liked about acting. I
thought, `You know, if I could translate this _ my love of acting
and my history with acting _ if I could translate it to directing,
if I ever could have any skill at it at all, then I could tell so
many more stories than I could as an actor, because as an actor I'm
locked into me. I can only tell stories about a woman my height,
approximately my age and my gender, my race.' I just was feeling
that really, I had more things to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Field started her storytelling relatively early. She entered
acting at age 18 when she enrolled in an actors workshop, which led
to a role in the 1965-66 TV series surf sitcom ``Gidget.'' As early
as 1967's ``The Flying Nun,'' she began studying under prominent
acting coach Lee Strasberg, and stayed with him off and on for
several years after the show was canceled in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Although she had done a handful of theatrical movies before
``Sybil,'' her Emmy _ and a relationship with Burt Reynolds _
helped her leap to big-screen stardom. She sealed the deal with
Oscars for playing a labor-union organizer in 1979's ``Norma Rae''
and for playing a Depression-era farm widow in 1984's ``Places in
the Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite growing up in public, Field doesn't believe that she's
unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really got the opportunity to have most of my childhood,''
she says. ``Certainly, I have been through so much that my
generation of women has been through. I was raised in the '50s and
early '60s, and watched all hell break loose, and had never been a
leader in it. I've really been very comfortable to be a sheep. It's
hard for me because I find it much more comfortable to be in the
middle of the flock.''
</P>
<P>
   Field says that acting helped her concentrate not so much on
leading or following, but on being herself and not caring so much
about what others thought. She's aware that ``Beautiful'' might not
be for everyone, but that's all right, because it worked for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outside of my hands,'' she says of the movie's box-office
fate, ``so I'm not having a major anxiety attack, because there's
nothing I can do. I set out to do what I wanted to do, and that is
I have this little story to tell _ and I did that. Certainly I
wanted to be still alive afterward, and I'm still alive, and
really, I did the very best that I was capable of doing at the
time. There's really nothing else that I can ask of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
