<HEADER>
A5229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-LARSEN-TITANS29-COX     09-28 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LARSEN-TITANS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Titans' scores points with simplistic game plan
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Remember the Titans'' is a well-intentioned racial drama
that's drawn in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the true story of a Virginia high school football team
that in 1971 was forced to integrate, the earnest Disney film
presents an inspirational tale about putting aside differences to
unite for a common goal _ in this case, scoring touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring a charismatic performance by Denzel Washington, the
feel-good film is an entertaining crowd pleaser. However, its
approach to the civil rights struggle is almost cartoonishly
simple.
</P>
<P>
   Washington stars as Herman Boone, who was brought up to
Alexandria, Va., from South Carolina to coach the T.C. Williams
High Titans over Bill Yoast (Will Patton), a potential hall of fame
candidate with more seniority and staunch local support.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their combative meeting, Yoast agrees to act as Boone's
subordinate to keep the white players from sitting out the season
with him _ coaching the defense while Boone, a ``race man'' who
marched with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., takes the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between the two coaches and their racially divided
staffs extends to the players, who previously attended all-white or
all-black schools. Racial brawls frequently erupt as the tough,
aggressive youths are packed off to a two-week summer training
camp, where Boone amusingly puts them through their paces like a
military drill sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   A pre-dawn run leads the team to the Gettysburg battleground,
where Boone delivers a stirring speech that puts the team's
conflict into historical perspective. ``If we don't come together
right now on this hallowed ground, we, too, will be destroyed,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans almost immediately pull together, but when they
return home to start school, the players find that their families
and friends don't share their newfound sense of harmony. Adding to
the strain, Boone learns that he will be fired if he loses a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the Titans'' is remarkably high-minded fare for
producer Jerry Bruckheimer, who this summer gave us the
dumb-and-dumber duo of ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' and ``Coyote Ugly.''
Directed by Boaz Yakin (''Fresh''), the socially conscious drama is
the first release from Bruckheimer's Technical Black banner, which
will produce smaller films ``that explore issues not generally seen
in mainstream filmmaking,'' according to the media notes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the film's heart is in the right place, its story lacks
complexity. The screenplay by former television writer Gregory
Allen Howard is broadly devised, with obvious heroes and villains,
and has all of the depth of a made-for-television movie.
</P>
<P>
   Washington clearly relishes his role, but his dialogue is
littered with platitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at family audiences, the uplifting film features no
profanity and steers clear of harsher racial epithets.
</P>
<P>
   The likable gridiron ensemble includes lead defensive end Julius
Campbell (Wood Harris) and defensive linebacker and team captain
Gerry Bertier (Ryan Hurst) _ opposing rivals who cross the color
line to become close friends.
</P>
<P>
   Hefty lineman Lewis Lastik (Ethan Suplee) doesn't care about
race, being a white kid from the poor section of town, and provides
comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   California transfer student Ronnie ``Sunshine'' Bass (Kip
Pardue), a long-haired quarterback, experiences the same
discrimination as his black teammates for being a hippie.
</P>
<P>
   Yoast's daughter, Sheryl (Hayden Panettiere), is a precocious
9-year-old tomboy who knows as much about football as any of the
men. Her lighthearted counterpart is Boone's prissy daughter, Nicky
(Krysten Leigh Jones), who prefers ``accessorizing'' dolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the Titans'' is a enjoyable effort, even though it
tackles major issues in a naive and shallow manner.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
