<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MCDORMAND-PROFILE29-C     09-28 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDORMAND-PROFILE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Actress rocked by character
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Frances McDormand sits down for an interview in a posh
Toronto hotel suite wearing a black Led Zeppelin T-shirt, jeans and
a denim jacket. The Oscar-winner's rock 'n' roll ensemble is in
stark contrast to the character she plays in Cameron Crowe's
``Almost Famous'' _ a somewhat eccentric, intellectual mother who
doesn't allow rock music to be played in her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be me,'' McDormand said, visually separating
herself from the role.
</P>
<P>
   McDormand, who won the Academy Award for best actress in 1996
for her performance as pregnant police chief Marge Gunderson in
``Fargo'', is drawing Oscar buzz again for ``Almost Famous''. Set
in 1973, the coming-of-age drama casts her as Elaine Miller, the
controlling mother of 15-year-old rock journalist William Miller,
played by newcomer Patrick Fugit, who is assigned to interview the
up-and-coming band Stillwater for Rolling Stone magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost Famous'' premiered at the Toronto International Film
Festival and expanded to wide release last weekend, grossing $6.9
million on only 1,193 screens, for an average of $5,806 per screen.
DreamWorks today added another 500 screens.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe, the Oscar-nominated writer-director of ``Jerry Maguire'',
based the heartfelt, funny film on his experiences as a teen-age
reporter for Rolling Stone touring with Led Zeppelin, Lynyrd
Skynyrd, the Allman Brothers Band and the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine is inspired by Crowe's mother, Alice. Like McDormand's
character, Alice was a college professor who abhorred rock music
and wanted her son to grow up to be a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The complex and colorful role leapt out at McDormand, who being
42 and female finds her acting choices in Hollywood limited to
wife, mother or aunt. ``If I play mothers, I would like them to be
like Elaine,'' she said. ``I would like them to be people first.''
</P>
<P>
   McDormand would have pursued Crowe for the role, had he not
offered it to her first.
</P>
<P>
   ``She quotes Goethe, for God's sake,'' the actress said. ``I
mean _ male, female, who cares _ if they quote Goethe, go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Illinois, McDormand received her stage training at the
Yale Drama School. The versatile performer earned a Tony Award
nomination as Stella in a Broadway revival of ``A Streetcar Named
Desire'' and made her screen debut in 1984 in the Coen brothers'
``Blood Simple''.
</P>
<P>
   McDormand married director Joel Coen, for whom she has also
appeared in ``Raising Arizona'' and ``Fargo''.
</P>
<P>
   McDormand recently finished shooting the upcoming Coen brothers
film, currently titled ``The Barber Project'', in which she stars
opposite Billy Bob Thornton. ``Black-and-white, film noir, takes
place in the '40s,'' she said. ``It's absolutely gorgeous.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Coen live in New York City and have an adopted
6-year-old son, Pedro McDormand Coen. How would McDormand feel if
her son went on the road with a rock band, like William Miller in
``Almost Famous''?
</P>
<P>
   ``My son lives with a rock band,'' McDormand said.
``Comparatively speaking, he doesn't live with a conventional
family. So it wouldn't be my worry that he would go with a rock
band _ in fact, I would like him to play bass some day. My concern
would be if he chose the military.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress fears that she wouldn't have given her son the
necessary tools to prepare for such a life. ``That would be
terrifying to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a media conference at the film festival, Crowe said
that McDormand ``probably had to travel the greatest distance'' of
all of his cast members, ``acting like she didn't love Black
Sabbath when she does.''
</P>
<P>
   McDormand surprised her younger cast mates _ who also include
Billy Crudup, Kate Hudson, Philip Seymour Hoffman and Jason Lee _
by breaking into an air-guitar rendition of Black Sabbath's Iron
Man when Crowe played the song between takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my music,'' she said. ``In fact, it's more my music
than it is theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   McDormand said she didn't have to sublimate her love of rock
music to play Elaine.
</P>
<P>
   What connects the characters is their passion, she said.
William's is for music, which unites him with the musicians and
groupies who become his makeshift family, while his mom Elaine has
a passion for literature and human behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't get to know what kind of music that she listened
to, but I'm sure it was Wagner with maybe a little Peggy Lee on the
side,'' McDormand said. ``But it was just a different generation.
She simply didn't have the exposure to the same kind of rock 'n'
roll that her son did. But it wasn't that they didn't share an
intellectual passion. They certainly did.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine stays in constant touch with William via the telephone
after he runs off to join the rock 'n' roll circus _ usually at
comically inopportune moments, such as when his hotel room is
overrun by groupies or when someone within earshot backstage is
loudly searching for drugs. Through these calls, Elaine develops an
unexpected bond with Stillwater guitarist Russell Hammond.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond is played by Crudup, a stage-trained actor with whom
McDormand appeared as mother and son in the off-Broadway production
of Oedipus.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone scenes presented an interesting technical
challenge, she said. ``That last phone call with Russell, it's a
two-person scene, but it's also a really well-written monologue.''
</P>
<P>
   Directing McDormand took on a surreal quality for Crowe when his
mother visited the set, but the actress said that she gained more
insight into the director than her character from Alice's presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was with a man who was really well-raised and had a really
extraordinary relationship with his parent,'' McDormand said. ``So
that's the way it affected me. But in terms of observing her
behavior or anything, it wasn't necessary because I was playing
Elaine. And it was so well-written that's all I needed.''
</P>
<P>
   That, and a little Black Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
