<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5231 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-SEX29-COX     09-28 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SEX29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A charming exploration of 'Love &AMP; Sex'
 &HT;    By Alison Macor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer-director Valerie Breiman claims to be an ``equal
opportunity exploiter'' when it comes to depicting the foibles of
men and women on-screen, and she succeeds charmingly in ``Love &AMP;
Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicling the rocky long-term romance between journalist Kate
Welles (Famke Janssen) and painter Adam Levy (Jon Favreau), ``Love
&AMP; Sex'' captures many of the couple's highs and lows with comic
deftness and poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   What it fails to do, however, is flesh out the story around
these two characters. Their prickly relationship is served up like
an astronaut's breakfast, vacuum-packed and oddly sealed off from
the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, colleagues and former flames parade across the screen
like cardboard cutouts, which puts a lot of pressure on the leads _
particularly Janssen _ to carry the story. The disarmingly sexy
Favreau (``Swingers'') clearly has the chops to drive the story,
but the weight of the tale falls to Janssen, who has worked
diligently in movies as diverse as ``Rounders'' and ``X-Men'' to
transcend her former Bond girl status. Janssen's skills as a comic
actress are appealing, but her performance during ``Love &AMP; Sex's''
dramatic moments doesn't ring true.
</P>
<P>
   Kate first experience-- the heady intoxication of new love in
the fourth grade, when Bobby Morton strut-- over, Steve
McQueen-like, and slugs her in the arm. Later, away from the
schoolyard jeering of his pals, Bobby leans his forehead against
hers and stares soulfully into her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at you like this, it looks like you only have one
eye,'' Bobby says dreamily.
</P>
<P>
   Kate spends the next two decades choosing men who are variations
on her idealized fourth-grade boyfriend. While their romantic
murmurings have evolved somewhat, their ability to relate to Kate
on an intellectual and emotional level hasn't progressed much
beyond Bobby's primitive gestures.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Love &AMP; Sex'' isn't a movie about what jerks men can be.
More often than not, Kate is equally implicated in her past
relationship debacles, and the film is as much about the viability
of long-term monogamy as it is an affectionate _ if myopic _
examination of the idiosyncratic ways in which one couple connects.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-GIRLFIGHT29-CO     09-28 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GIRLFIGHT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A body blow to the heart
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Only fools and sportswriters can tease poetry
from fists thrashing flesh and bone. Fortunately, filmmaker Karyn
Kusama is neither. But she is a boxer, and in her brawny urban
melodrama ``Girlfight'' Kusama dresses the sport up in the attire
an insider would _ none at all. She strips boxing to its essence _
a prosaic contest of strength, drive and skill _ highlighting the
craft of calculated pummeling.
</P>
<P>
   Kusama's storytelling is equally bareknuckled, and fresh.
``Girlfight,'' which shared top honors at this year's Sundance Film
Festival, is lean and lithe, yet peppered with surprising emotion
drawn not from victories in the ring but from the triumph of love.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a boxing love story, one whose romantic heart beats
louder and truer than Rocky Balboa's plaintive yelps of ``Adrian!''
Kusama's unlikely pugilist is a teen-age girl, who parlays her
molten temper into boxing dynamite. Michelle Rodriguez, cutting a
dazzling figure in her first acting role, plays Diana Guzman, a raw
product of a broken family in the Brooklyn projects. Despair and
anger find articulation in her sharpshooting fists.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't go over well at school, where Diana's a repeat
offender, force-feeding chumps knuckle sandwiches when ordered. And
troubles at home are simmering, ready to boil. Diana has nothing
but resentment for her dead-end father (the fine Paul Calderon),
who drove her mother to suicide with abuse. In her unyielding
glare, he can do no right. She rebuffs his wan attempts at parental
guidance and keeps her little brother Tiny (Ray Santiago) under her
wing.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny is her link to the boxing world. Watching him train at a
Brooklyn Athletic Club gym, she spies an outlet for her errant
pugnacity. Opposition to her donning gloves is perfunctory, and
that's a strength in Kusama's mindful script. Grizzled regulars
razz Diana (``Why not aerobics?'' one slob chimes in), but she's
soon being trained by Tiny's coach, Hector (Jaime Tirelli). Her
eventual ``gender-blind'' fights are wrapped in others'
reservations, but her chops make her a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got guys hittin' you in the face?'' asks a shocked school
friend. The deepest dismay lies with her father, who storms out of
a match when he realizes it's his daughter poppin' a boy in the
ring. (When she later cold-cocks her dad, there's a sense of cheap
catharsis, but the scene is fraught with narrative urgency.)
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez trained 4 1/2 months for the role, so each hook and
jab is punishingly real. She's an intimidatingly alive actor,
stoking a guarded naturalism with feral fire.
</P>
<P>
   She possesses a complicated beauty _ part thug, part bombshell.
Her hard gaze is a slow burn, her swagger all tomboy. In glimmers,
though, she reveals a winning girlishness. Enough to captivate the
handsome young boxer Adrian (Santiago Douglas), who's pinned his
future on punching his way out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Kusama depicts the courtship as sweetly tentative, as adolescent
love is. And the corker she throws into the relationship _
inevitable as it is, I won't reveal it _ pushes ``Girlfight'' even
farther from formula.
</P>
<P>
   The film works much better than it should. If any movie genre
invites weak-kneed platitudes, it's sports movies, where moral
conflicts are untangled in the ring, on the diamond or on the
gridiron. ``Girlfight'' honors the boxing-as-salvation metaphor and
occasionally lapses into sports-flick boilerplate about dreams and
``what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's forgiven for not romanticizing Diana's quest. Boxing
here is a spiritual palliative, not a cure. After a key win,
there's no champagne; Diana returns to the mildewed janitor closet
that is her ``locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusama keeps it real. The film has urban bite and tattered
edges; it looks slightly bruised. The fights are shot with few
tricks _ some slo-mo and lens-punches _ without the stylized
carnage of, say, ``Raging Bull,'' where violence was an overriding
theme. Kusama tastefully showcases Theodore Shapiro's vibrant and
eclectic soundtrack. Percussive flamenco clatters to the beat of
contacting fists.
</P>
<P>
   Kusama's remarkable debut feature startles and moves in equal
measures. ``Girlfight'' is heavy-hitting, but never heavy-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
