<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-FALLTV-STARS29-COX     09-28 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLTV-STARS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Season-ending shows left many hanging, so here's a recap
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be that movie stars disdained TV and TV stars knew
it, which is why they were always aspiring to the big screen. There
was a distinct line between the two types of actors, but that
divider exists no longer _ good material is good material, and
steady work is its own reward.
</P>
<P>
   This season, lots of big-screen names are coming right into our
living rooms, and nobody's apologizing or feeling a bit washed-up.
</P>
<P>
   Bette Midler's Bette, boldly based on herself, likens a
television series to suicide, but there she is, playing herself in
a TV series and yukking it up. We get the joke.
</P>
<P>
   Geena Davis is playing it straight in The Geena Davis Show,
where she's a hot young thing engaged to a hot young widower with
kids. Davis' career needs a jump-start _ last year's Oscar gig left
us cold, and this year's Emmy near-nakedness left us colder. She's
undoubtedly hoping a sweet series will make people like her.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of liking her, Sally Field comes to series TV with
a recurring role on ER as Maura Tierney's mom, of all things.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Platt, a familiar supporting film actor, gets his own
scenery to chew in his new series, Deadline, where he plays a
crusading columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Wiest, one of Woody Allen's go-to pros, is taking over
the county DA's office on Law &AMP; Order, and Robert Patrick _ yup,
the Terminator guy _ is moving in on Mulder territory as David
Duchovny whittles his X-Files burden to 11 episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Byrne and Charlie Sheen are new TV names we're used to
seeing on marquees. Byrne's Madigan Men is tailored to his Irish
charm, but Sheen has his work cut out, filling the shoes Michael J.
Fox left empty on Spin City.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Downey Jr. was a movie-guy until prison intervened; now
he's happy to take a recurring role as a romantic interest for Ally
McBeal.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? A job is a job, box office or not.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5239 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-BRIDGE29-COX     09-28 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BRIDGE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It has knives, it has sex - but it's not about the knives
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to the French to clarify the parallels between
knife-throwing and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is just that director Patrice Leconte can make any
unlikely activity seem erotic, but the razor-sharp variety act at
the heart of his delightfully tongue-in-cheek romantic comedy,
``Girl on the Bridge'', is positively steamy.
</P>
<P>
   Although it begins with the imminent threat of suicide and
continues on to knife-throwing's imminent threat of homicide, this
is the breeziest, most entertaining foreign film to hit our shores
since Run, Lola, Run ran herself ragged. It stars pop singer
Vanessa Paradis as Adele, the target of Daniel Auteuil's knives and
his ardor. While her acting range seems limited, she is so
perfectly cast and so appealing, I defy any red-blooded
heterosexual male moviegoer not to fall in love with her.
</P>
<P>
   In our earliest encounter with Adele, she is standing on the
edge of a Paris foot bridge, inching closer to plummeting into the
River Seine. Unlucky in love and unable to keep from choosing
badly, she wonders what the point is of continuing her miserable
life. Fortunately, Gabor happens along. He tries to talk her to
safety, but gallantly jumps in and rescues her when she makes good
her threat.
</P>
<P>
   In a hospital, following their treatment for hypothermia, Gabor
demonstrates his psychic powers (and Leconte shows his cinematic
flair with a shot from an airborne fly's point-of-view). Gabor
persuades Adele to become his assistant in his knife-throwing act,
arguing that if he slips and misses, she will be no worse off than
when he first met her.
</P>
<P>
   They not only become a hit from the hotels of the French Riviera
to the cruise ships of Italy, but they discover a telepathic bond
and an uncanny streak of luck that nets them financial rewards in
the casino. Still, such good fortune does not buy happiness, for
Adele cannot keep her hands off each passing (and pass-making)
waiter or sailor. Apart, Adele and Gabor find their luck quickly
evaporates. Perhaps, although they kept their feelings to
themselves, they are made for each other.
</P>
<P>
   Those who insist on deep meaning with their subtitled French
movies can contemplate the cosmos and the nature of destiny in
``Girl on the Bridge''. The rest of us can simply kick back and
have a good time. Were this story to be made by Hollywood _ which
looms as a possibility _ it would be a most mainstream romantic
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it has the patina of art houses, largely because
Leconte filmed it in a moody black-and-white and the characters
happen to speak French. The only drawback of Jean-Marie Dreujou's
lush cinematography is the annoying habit of the subtitles to
disappear into the background tones.
</P>
<P>
   So ignore the dialogue every now and again and lose yourself in
Paradis' wide waifish eyes. Auteuil is Pygmalion to her Galatea,
supervising her transformation to human show business prop,
dictating her new chic haircut, the clothes she buys, her stance
and demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, Adele writhes, swoons and utters little orgasmic gasps
as Gabor hurls his steely-cold knives at her in invasive thrusts.
The sexual subtext is obvious and most amusing.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins with a delicious character-establishing
monologue by Adele, in which she recounts her many mishaps with
men. Explaining how she got herself into one such dilemma, she
shrugs her delicate shoulder and says, ``I went to his head, like
Cointreau.'' ``Girl on the Bridge'' should have a similar
intoxicating effect on audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1552EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5246 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-FALLTV-PREVIEW-COX     09-28 2745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLTV-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Most of the new fall TV programming _ not bad
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's shaping up to be a year of some tough choices for the
discerning television viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 new shows offered up by ABC, NBC, CBS, WB and UPN,
only a few are outright dogs _ The Trouble with Normal, a sitcom
about paranoids, comes to mind. Some movie names are squeezing
themselves into the small screen, and some of the medium's biggest
behind-the-scenes names have new stuff.
</P>
<P>
   David E. Kelley _ Picket Fences, Ally McBeal, The Practice _ is
taking a shot at our school system with Boston Public. Darren Star,
who gave us Sex and the City, is the brain behind Grosse Pointe, a
comedy about a show within a show, and The Street, a drama focusing
on Wall Street's hot young things.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Wolf, Law &AMP; Order's main man, got himself a newspaper show
in Deadline. David Letterman's production company, Worldwide Pants,
brings us Ed and Welcome to New York, both about sweetly goofy guys
from the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   And Aaron Spelling, who knows that trash is never trashier than
when it's dressed well, offers Titans, in which Baywatch babe
Yasmine Bleeth marries the father of her ex-lover.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is packed and most of it's good. So find the remote
and sit back down.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ed (8 p.m., ET , ET , NBC, premieres Oct. 8): It's a sleeper,
like its title character, a New York lawyer who got fired and
caught his wife in bed with the mailman all on the same day. Worst
day of his life? Nope _ best day of his life: Ed headed home to
Stuckeyville, Ohio, and bought a bowling alley. Tom Cavanaugh plays
Ed, an irresistible combination of confusion, confidence and charm.
Love interest is found in the girl who ignored him in high school;
comic relief is all over the bowling alley, which entices customers
by offering free legal advice with every three games.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hype (9 p.m., ET , WB, premieres Oct. 8): This is the only new
show that's not a running series and is already getting heat for
its racy content. It's a half-hour sketch comedy featuring 10 young
actor/comedians. Brought to us by the folks from Mad TV, it's got
promise if it rises from the gutter at least occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nikki (9:30 p.m., ET , WB, premieres Oct. 8): Nikki Cox may be
the only thing anybody remembers from Unhappily Ever After, and the
only thing anybody remembers about Nikki Cox is the way she's
built. Nikki's premise is bizarre: Cox is a dancer who dreams of
hitting it big in Las Vegas; newcomer Nick von Esmarch is the
college-bound boy she sidetracks and convinces to give up school to
chase his dream of becoming a big-time wrestler. They marry, and
the mother-in-law is a problem. Surprisingly, this show has some
trashy charm working for it, and Cox is more than the sum of her
curvy parts.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Yes, Dear (CBS, 8 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 2) Anthony Clark
(Boston Common) has yet to find his niche. This absolutely dreadful
show sets him back a few thousand steps, with its predictable setup
and stale jokes. Clark and Jean Louisa Kelly play new parents who
fret over baby's every breath and make cute ugly faces when they
eat baby food. Supported by Liza Snyder (Jesse) and Mike O'Malley
(The Mike O'Malley Show), who play some less-stressed in-laws who
believe TV is the best baby sitter, it's a good lineup. If only
they had some real jokes to work with.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tucker (CBS, 8:30 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 2): Another sitcom
staple _ the wacky blended family _ rears its weary head. Tucker is
being billed as some sort of coming-of-age series, and the absence
of a laugh track gives it more weight than it deserves. Starring
Eli Marienthal as befuddled 14-year-old Tucker, who moves with his
newly divorced mom (Noelle Beck) to his sister Claire's (Katie
Sagal) house. Tucker now shares a room with weird cousin Leon and
hates his new life, until he sees a foxy neighbor. Hormones in the
hands of television writers? Expect lots of below-the-belt
punchlines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Deadline (NBC, 9 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 2): Law &AMP; Order
brain Dick Wolf stretches our capacity for suspending disbelief
with this series about a newspaper columnist who takes graduate
students on missions of truth and justice. Oliver Platt is the man
for the job: He's Wallace Benton, who's big and puffy with
seductive floppy hair and a huge gob of brainy passion for his
work. Check out the other players: Bebe Neuwirth as his managing
editor; Lili Taylor as a gossip columnist; and Tom Conti (where
have you been?) as the paper's mogulish owner. These old faces are
balanced by some great new ones _ it's a smart show, so pay
attention.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boston Public (Fox, 8 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 23): TV's
other reigning brain, David E. Kelly (Ally McBeal), tries high
school in this all-over-the-place drama with laughs about teachers
at the title school. Fyvush Finkel comes back from Picket Fences,
and Chi McBride may be able to make up for last season's famously
infamous The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer. Kelley's record is
spotty, so we'll see if Boston Public is weird, wonderful or
weirdly wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Girlfriends (UPN, 9:30 p.m., ET , began Sept. 11): It worked
for HBO and Sex and the City, so why not here? Four black women,
fast friends, talk about life _ the ups, the downs, the way men
obsess about cup size. The cast is spunky, if mostly unknown
(Tracee Ellis Ross _ who's Diana Ross' daughter _ Jill Marie Jones,
Persia White, Golden Brooks).
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Geena Davis Show (ABC, 9:30 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 24):
This show is dead in the water. Even Peter Horton (thirtysomething
) can't pull this one out of the toilet. Horton plays a widower
named Max with kids, who sweeps Davis, cutely named Teddie (maybe
because she'll be wearing a lot of them) off her feet. Hilarity
doesn't ensue as she, tattoo, short T-shirts and all, tries to fit
in to his family life. Pity the children.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Michael Richards Show (NBC, 8 p.m., ET , Oct. 24): Sure,
he's got three supporting Emmys, but can he take the lead? Michael
Richards is now gainfully employed as a rule-bending private
investigator. The smart money hasn't been bet, as this show has
undergone some serious retooling. But Richards has more depth than
his turn as Seinfeld's Cosmo Kramer would indicate. Tim Meadows and
William Devane are part of the ensemble. Wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DAG (NBC, 9:30 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 31): The title stands
for David Alan Grier, the series star, and his character's name,
which is Dagget. OK, that's settled. Grier is a Secret Service
agent who dove out of the line of fire and became a national
laughing stock. He's reassigned to the first lady and daughter,
played by the great Delta Burke (Designing Women) and Lea Moreno
Young. Grier and Burke are sitcom pros and there's chemistry here.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dark Angel (Fox, 9 p.m., ET , Tuesday): OK, screen size
doesn't matter to James Cameron, who directed Titanic and
Terminator. He still has the buzz on his side with this tale of the
bad, scary future. Already, star Jessica Alba has been named the
next big thing and she is hot as Max, genetically altered
(enhanced, obviously) and on the run from an evil military man
(John Savage). Max has superhuman skills and an ally in Logan
(Michael Weatherly), who works with her to fight for truth and
justice. She's also got a bar code on her neck, which may also
become the next big thing.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gideon's Crossing (ABC, 10 p.m., ET , previews Oct 10,
premieres Oct 18): Andre Braugher takes charge as a doctor who
specializes in experimental medicine, who navigates a moral and
ethical maze at work while dealing with big personal issues at
home. He's got a great partner in the earthily soulful psychiatrist
Max Cabranes (Ruben Blades), who listens and councils with
brilliant one-liners: ``You're angry? Get angry with God! Pick on
somebody your own size.'' Braugher, who left Homicide: Life on the
Street about the time everybody was falling in love with him, takes
the weight of the series on his shoulders _ do we doubt he can
handle it? Nope. Just give him good stories, and we'll be there.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bette (CBS, 8 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 11): Who'd have
thought? Bette Midler plays a diva based on someone a lot like a
Divine Miss M we once knew. What's great about this is that many of
the jokes are at her own expense, and her support system _ husband
Roy (Kevin Dunn), daughter Rose (Lindsay Lohan), manager (Joanna
Gleason) and accompanist Oscar (James Dreyfus) _ is tolerant and
adoring. They ground and balance Midler's outrageousness, giving
this series a surprising warmth. You've got to love a big star who
commits to a series where her character says, ``Pretty soon I'll
have my own series and then I might as well kill myself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Titans (NBC, 8 p.m., ET , premieres Wednesday): Trash at its
best, with Victoria Principal back in low-cut designer dresses,
right where she belongs. Yasmine Bleeth is the young, nubile babe
who agrees to marry Perry King, not knowing she bedded and broke
the heart of his son (Casper Van Dien). Principal plays King's
ex-wife, who lives in the mansion across the street and runs a hot
disco. The family's other children have problems with alcohol,
control and, not surprisingly, Yasmine. Camp it up, kids.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Normal, Ohio (NBC, 8:30 p.m., ET , premieres Nov. 1): Another
wacky family blend: John Goodman plays a newly out gay dad who runs
home to Ohio and his sister. Producers Bonnie and Terry Turner gave
us That '70s Show and Third Rock From the Sun, so here's hoping
they bring the same fresh sensibility to this one. At least they've
got Goodman, and that can't be bad, but this show _ like Michael
Richards' _ was being reworked at the last minute, and that can be
bad.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Welcome to New York (CBS, 8:30 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 11):
Nerd-out-of-water Jim Gaffigan plays a guy named, of all things,
Jim Gaffigan. From Indiana. Who's wooed to New York by Marsha
Bickner (Christine Baranski, late of Cybil), who produces a morning
show. His Hoosier roots are showing, but this hick is going to make
it on his own. Great sidekicks are all over the TV station,
especially in vain, stupid anchorman Adrian, played by a
scene-stealing Rocky Carroll (Chicago Hope).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Street (Fox, 9 p.m., ET , premieres Nov. 1): Hot stuff
from stock traders, or so the story goes. Tom Everett Scott is one
of the high-living players who populate this place, where boys will
be boys, even when they're trying to be men.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gilmore Girls (WB, 8 p.m., ET , premieres Thursday): One's a
woman, mother of the other, who gave up a life of privilege and all
its shackles when she had her namesake child. Lauren Graham is
32-year-old Lorelai; Alexis Bledel is her 16-year-old daughter _
call her Rory, please. They're growing up together, and we get to
watch. Edward Hermann and Kelly Bishop play the old-money parents;
Hermann turns reading the newspaper into the ultimate act of
passive aggression. A nice show, quiet and sweet, yet real and
pleasantly quirky. And on the WB, of all places.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cursed (NBC, 8:30 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 12): Yes, we love
Steven Weber (Wings), but not in this mess. Here he's is an ad man
who's hit _ literally _ with a hex from a bad blind date. Chris
Elliott does another turn as an eccentric best friend. No go, even
between Friends and Will &AMP; Grace.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Freedom (UPN, 8 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 27): This is another
hard-bodied fight for the American Way. Four folks, convicted of
treason after a military coup disrupts our own United States, put
the pedal to the metal. It's not WWF Smackdown!, but it's fast and
full of energy, and it stars Bodhi Elfman, who's married to Jenna
(Dharma &AMP; Greg) Elfman, in case anybody cares.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Fugitive (CBS, 8 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 6): Yes, we
love Tim Daly (Wings), but not with blond hair. Other than that,
The Fugitive has a big, expensive shot at series success. We all
know the story _ a nice doctor, unjustly convicted of wife's
murder, escapes and spends an hour each week chasing the one-armed
real killer. Mykelti Williamson is the cop on his tail. It worked
once with David Janssen; it worked again with Harrison Ford _ go
with three strikes and/or third time's a charm. We'll be the judge.
A cute trick: The plan is to shoot the show on the run, all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Grosse Pointe (WB, 8:30 p.m., ET , premiered Sept. 22): Grosse
Pointe is the show within the show, giving some young actors a
chance to act really cheesy, then change their hair and act really
real. The pilot wasn't funny, but don't give up: The cast is
appealing and it's always fun to be on the inside. This show's been
in the news already, after Aaron Spelling objected to one
character's too-close-for-comfort resemblance to his daughter,
Tori.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Trouble with Normal (ABC, 8:30 p.m., ET , premieres
Friday): The old line _ you're not really paranoid if they are
after you _ has become a sitcom. No, really. The support group for
paranoids doesn't help, and neither does living next to another
paranoid. Then the therapist's boyfriend walks in and makes fun of
everybody; then the paranoid gang drops in on her at home and
barely blinks. In fact, she goes on a group blind date with them.
If you're saying, ``Huh?'' you're not alone. Stars David Krumholtz
and Jon Cryer, who do the best they can with really bad stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  C.S.I. (CBS, 9 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 6): Old toenails and
hair fibers fascinate some folks, and when they're evidence in a
crime, at least they serve a purpose. The crime-scene folks at the
heart of this series (known as the ``Nerd Squad'') get deep into
the details, lots of them kinky, lots requiring strong stomachs.
William Petersen is boss; Marg Helgenberger is a single mom who
loves her job and loves her daughter _ a prescription for a
guilt-cliche cocktail. Maybe Jack Klugman's Quincy will drop by
sometime. Couldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Freakylinks (Fox, 9 p.m., ET , premieres Friday): One of the
Blair Witch guys was in on this, which stars Ethan Embry as Derek
Barnes, who uses a Web site to work some Scooby Doo magic. Derek's
brother, Adam, died a bizarre death, yet he's starting to turn up
on the Web. The truth is in there, somewhere, and it's spelled with
a www and a nice dot-com. OK, now scare us.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Level 9 (UPN, 9 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 27): Another nerd
alert for this super-secret team that takes high tech up a notch in
its quest to squash cybercrime. These guys are generic and the show
is, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Madigan Men (ABC, 9:30 p.m., ET , premieres Friday): They're
men and they're Irish, led by Gabriel Byrne, who plays Benjamin
Madigan with charm to spare. There's something for everybody:
Grandad Seamus (Roy Dotrice) and son Luke (John C. Hensley) bookend
Byrne as the three guys represent the old country, the immigrant
and the young Celtic turk. Grant Shaud (Murphy Brown) is a great
business-partner buddy. The only thing that could bring this one
down is an overload of blarney, but we'll take our chances.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  That's Life (CBS, 8 p.m., ET , premieres this Sunday then
moves to its regular time slot): This show has almost everything:
An appealing not-too-young lead in Heather Paige Kent, great
sidekick friends (Debi Mazar and Kristin Bauer), and overbearing
parents (Ellen Burstyn and Paul Sorvino). What it needs is a love
interest for spunky Lydia (Kent), who dumps her lout of a fiance
and heads back to college, where she's smarter than she knows. And
she knows she's pretty smart. So's the show, even if the
Italian-family thing has been done to death. Eat takeout Chinese to
balance the meatballs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The District (CBS, 10 p.m., ET , premieres Oct. 7): The
District has been taking serious heat from some, who bristle at the
premise: Hot-shot Jack Mannon (Craig T. Nelson) comes to
Washington, D.C., as its new police commissioner. His chest is all
puffed out as he begins to deliver on a promise to really cut
crime. Mannon is up against a legally challenged mayor and
butt-covering police chief. But the series doesn't shy from this or
many other issues, and Nelson is one actor able to play a bigger
than life eccentric who truly knows his stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact Laura Dempsey at 225-2403 or by e-mail at
lauradempsey(at)coxohio.com
</P>
