<HEADER>
A5254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBN-BONDS-HNS &LR;      09-28 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BONDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BONDS WANTS A WORLD SERIES RING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN SHEA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Barry Bonds was named one of three finalists for a
player-of-the-year award sponsored by the players' union. When
informed of the news before the San Francisco Giants' 4-0 victory
over the Los Angeles Dodgers Wednesday night, he didn't flinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment about that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about that stuff. I've been winning individual
awards since Little League. I need a (World Series) ring. I don't
need any more individual awards. That's not going to signify
anything more in my career. You win awards, and you take them. But
I still haven't won a World Series yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, this is a stale story. The questions aren't new: Will
Bonds finally play in a World Series? Will this be the year he
breaks his oh-fer string? Will he go home early again?
</P>
<P>
   But in a way, it's not a stale story. Bonds is 36, and it's been
uttered more than once in the clubhouse (not by Bonds) that this
could be the final chance for certain players to shoot for
baseball's grand prize.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds would never admit it. He seems to have the pride (and the
body) to play through age 40, if that's his intent. But how many
chances like this do you get in a career?
</P>
<P>
   For Bonds, this will be No. 5. Three with Pittsburgh ('90, '91,
'92) and two with the Giants ('97, '00). In the first four, Bonds'
teams were wiped out in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The closest he came to the World Series was '92, when the
Pirates were one out from winning the National League Championship
Series. They owned a 2-1 lead in Game 7, but Francisco Cabrera's
two-out pinch single in the ninth inning scored the tying and
winning runs.
</P>
<P>
   When Sid Bream slid safely into the plate, ahead of Bonds'
throw, the Braves were going to the World Series. Bonds was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best team wins the World Series,'' Bonds said. ``All the
rest of them, it's try again next year. A team might be better on
paper, but it doesn't always work out that way on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Bonds more excited about his chances of reaching the World
Series this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just as excited the first time,'' he said. ``And the
second time. And the third time. And the fourth time.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief pitcher Doug Henry goes back further with Bonds than any
other Giants player. They knew each other in high school in
California. They were teammates at Arizona State and with the '97
Giants. In July, the Giants reacquired Henry from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were still on the outside, I'd be rooting for him to get
to the World Series,'' Henry said. ``But now that I'm here, I'm
rooting for all of us to get there. He's not the sole reason we all
want to get there. We're all looking for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could do his part, but he can't carry us. One guy can stand
out, but he can't carry a team. The rest of us have got to do our
part, too. The whole team has to do the job, or it's not going to
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
