<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK GIVES FINE ACCOUNT OF TWISTS AND TURNS OF MICROSOFT ANTI-TRUST
TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CECIL JOHNSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. v. Microsoft''
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Brinkley and Steve Lohr
</P>
<P>
   McGraw-Hill, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Discussing his findings of fact in the lawsuit brought against
Microsoft by the Justice Department and 19 state attorneys general,
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson summoned up that familiar anecdote
about a man using a two-by-four in training a mule.
</P>
<P>
   As a prelude to the training, the man hit the mule in the head
with the piece of lumber to get its attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I've got Microsoft's attention,'' Jackson is quoted as
having said in ``U.S. v. Microsoft,'' by Joel Brinkley and Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that Jackson has done that _ and more. In effect, he
has performed an enormous service for the nation by establishing an
important precedent in applying the Sherman Antitrust Act to
information age monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley and Lohr, reporters for The New York Times, do a
splendid job of presenting the two-year courtroom melodrama that
led up to Jackson's rulings of fact and law and his ultimate order
for the breakup of the software Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   Their account is sufficiently lucid to hold the attention of
those not schooled in the metalanguages of computer programming
without insulting the intellects of those who are.
</P>
<P>
   The organization of the book is really what makes it work.
</P>
<P>
   Each important turn in the trial is summarized clearly and is
followed by reprises of news stories that narrated those
developments, stories whose significance many readers may not have
grasped at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The portraits of Jackson, Bill Gates, the attorneys for the
government and Microsoft and the witnesses are well-drawn,
humanizing the book and enhancing its readability. Besides
Jackson's and Gates', the memorable portraits are these:
</P>
<P>
   _ David Boies, the brilliant litigator who led the federal
courtroom team. In his cross-examinations, Boies so thoroughly
discredited most Microsoft witnesses that Jackson said afterward
that he found them unbelievable. On Boies' skill at making
Microsoft witnesses contradict themselves, Brinkley and Lohr write:
``For Microsoft witnesses, a few simple words of introduction
became deeply unnerving. `My name is David Boies, and I represent
the United States.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Netscape Chairman Jim Barksdale, who triggered the federal
investigation of Microsoft by having a company lawyer prepare a
white paper describing the tactics Microsoft used to try to exclude
Netscape from the browser market.
</P>
<P>
   _ James Gosling of Sun Microsystems, who was the lead engineer
in the development of Java, an Internet programming language that
Sun developed to allow applications to run on any operating system.
Microsoft developed its own version of Java, restricting software
applications to Microsoft's operating system. Brinkley and Lohr
describe Gosling as ``that rare computer programmer who is also
extremely articulate in English.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosling asserted that Microsoft was preventing the more
effective operation of programs used by most of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has this basic strategy they call `embrace and
extend,' which some people call `disgrace and distend,' '' Gosling
said. ``But it's all about making it easy, so that people can get
on the Microsoft platform. And then they screw around with it so
that going the other direction is really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates, in absentia, was a continuing presence in the courtroom
because the government team repeatedly used a videotaped deposition
he had given.
</P>
<P>
   In that deposition, Gates came across as arrogant and
uncommunicative. He indicated that he knew nothing of any
monopolistic tactics that Microsoft is said to have used to force
computer companies to accept Microsoft Explorer as its default
browser and shut the door to Netscape's Navigator browser.
</P>
<P>
   But his testimony was contradicted by intracompany e-mail
messages indicating that he was orchestrating the machinations.
Those thousands of e-mails also are used to discredit the testimony
of other Microsoft witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Jackson found in favor of the government, asserting
that Microsoft had used its monopoly power to impede innovation,
discourage competition and harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most harmful of all is the message that Microsoft's actions
have conveyed to every enterprise with the potential to innovate in
the computer industry,'' Jackson wrote in his 207 pages of findings
of fact.
</P>
<P>
   He held off on issuing his findings of law to allow the parties
an opportunity to reach a settlement through mediation. When that
failed, Jackson
</P>
<P>
   ruled in April that Microsoft had violated anti-trust laws. In
June, he ordered that Microsoft be split into two companies _ one
for its Windows operating system and another for its other computer
programs and Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also imposed a long list of restrictions on Microsoft's
business practices, then suspended the imposition of his order in a
move to put it on the fast track to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The reader will come away from ``U.S. v. Microsoft'' with the
understanding that Microsoft has been severely chastened. Even if
Jackson's ruling is overturned, Microsoft will have to change its
monopolistic ways.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-SACREDCHIMAYO-TEX     09-28 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SACREDCHIMAYO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH, CURIOSITY STEER VISITORS TO NEW MEXICO'S SCENIC CHIMAYO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIMAYO, New Mexico _ The line stretches halfway through the
sanctuary, past rows of families kneeling and praying in simple
wooden pews, past the colorful, primitive-style paintings
surrounding the gold-embellished altar. Nearly everyone waiting
patiently in line carries two things: a rosary and a small plastic
bag.
</P>
<P>
   The rosary's purpose is obvious; the reason for the plastic bag
becomes clear the closer you get to the destination, a tiny room
off the Santuario de Chimayo. It contains a small, shallow pit
called ``el posito,'' or Little Healing Well. And it is because of
this room, with its makeshift altar and dirt floor, that this
200-year-old adobe church is sometimes called the American Lourdes.
</P>
<P>
   Like that French shrine, the Santuario has become known as a
place of healing. Legend has it that because the church was
expressly built on land where a crucifix mysteriously appeared
nearly 200 years ago, its dirt is sacred. Ever since, people have
believed that touching this dirt, rubbing it on a wound or an
affliction, could bring about a cure.
</P>
<P>
   For years, this was largely a local place, somewhere people had
to be told about by a friend or a family member, or stumble across
by accident while driving the back roads. But today, like so many
places in New Mexico, its fame has spread. Only 45 minutes north of
Santa Fe on a road touted as a scenic route to Taos, it attracts
the devout, and the merely curious, from all over. Visitors on this
recent sunny Saturday afternoon include tourists from Germany, New
York and France, plus two busloads of Roman Catholic pilgrims from
Albuquerque, two hours south.
</P>
<P>
   All seem to have immediately grasped the procedure. After
waiting for as long as 30 minutes, the pilgrims enter the tiny room
two or three at a time, kneel beside the shallow pit, and use a
metal cup to scoop dirt into the plastic bags. (Some use their
hands instead.) Some stop briefly to pray; a few immediately rub
the dirt on an arthritic hand or a sore foot.
</P>
<P>
   Does it work? The long room leading to the healing room is lined
with old crutches and canes cast off by the cured, and its walls
are covered with pictures, crosses, statues and handwritten
testimonials and prayers of thanks. And many tourists and locals
seem convinced the site is sacred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen people walk out of there blessed, yes,'' says Lolo
Medina, who sells family-grown chile powder and spice mixes at his
stand across the street from the church. ``It's about faith, that's
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither pilgrims nor locals, however, want to answer other, more
nagging questions _ such as, why there seems to be an unending
supply of soft, loose dirt in the pit, no matter how many people
line up to take some away.
</P>
<P>
   Not that skeptics can't enjoy a day trip to Chimayo as well. The
drive alone is worth the time spent, particularly if you take the
roundabout way through Nambe, with its rust-colored adobe church
perched picture-perfect on the side of a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Many plan trips around lunch at Restaurante Rancho de Chimayo, a
sprawling hacienda turned restaurant that might remind Texans of
Joe T. Garcia's. The New Mexican food is fine, but people really
come for the beautiful gardens and warm setting.
</P>
<P>
   Others come to shop, particularly for the locally made weavings,
which families have produced in the area for hundreds of years,
passing the techniques from generation to generation. There are
fine selections of wool blankets, vests, purses, coats, pillows and
wall hangings at several galleries; the rugs are particularly
gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   And others come to see New Mexico as it once was, and still is
in a few isolated places. One of the best spots for that is Plaza
del Cerro, built about 300 years ago by Spanish settlers.
Constantly at war with the native American Indian settlements, the
Spaniards built their simple adobes right next to each other,
forming a solid adobe rectangle with a large, grassy plaza in the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   The plaza was the center of the community then, says Chris
Brown, the part-time curator of the small museum just off the
plaza. It is operated by the Chimayo Cultural Preservation
Association. People raised vegetables there, kept chickens there,
gathered there to talk and celebrate, Brown says.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the plaza is still home to a handful of people, although
one side, the site of the former chapel, is somewhat dilapidated
and forlorn, its adobe bricks crumbling and its roof caving in. But
other homes are well-maintained and obviously lived in. This
includes a corner ominously posted with ``no tours'' signs, warning
visitors not to get too close.
</P>
<P>
   Like so much in Chimayo, there's a story there, too.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen years ago, Robert Redford wanted to film part of ``The
Milagro Beanfield War'' on this plaza. Most locals were receptive,
but a few didn't like the idea and fought it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said all the attention would turn this into Disneyland,''
Brown says, smiling. ``So he went to Truchas (a nearby village)
instead. And it's exactly the same today as it was then. So it
probably wouldn't have made any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, why take the risk? In Chimayo, there's something to
be said for tradition.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: Chimayo is a scenic 45-minute drive from Santa
Fe; take Highway 85/284 north from Santa Fe, then head east at
Espanola on Route 76. An alternate route is to take Route 503 off
Highway 85/284 before getting to Espanola; this takes you through
Nambe and past its lovely adobe church, with a perfect setting
overlooking the high desert. Turn north on County Road 98 to
continue into Chimayo.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO DO: Santuario de Chimayo is open daily for prayer and
pilgrimages; it's on the main plaza in town, off County Road 98.
</P>
<P>
   The Chimayo Cultural Preservation Association maintains the
small Chimayo History Museum, with displays on weaving and local
history, located just off Route 76 and Plaza del Cerro. Hours vary,
but it's usually open Thursday through Sunday. (505) 351-0945.
</P>
<P>
   EATING: Restaurante Rancho de Chimayo ( (505) 351-4444) is the
most popular tourist spot for lunch and dinner, run for generations
by the Jaramillo family. Specializing in traditional New Mexican
dishes like chile rellenos and sopaipillas, it also serves
breakfast on the weekends. A gift shop selling pottery, jewelry and
textiles is attached; the extended family also runs a
bed-and-breakfast in the restored adobe home across the road.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
