<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5272 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-HELPING-FLAWED-STAR-E     09-28 2129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELPING-FLAWED-STAR-EMPLOYEES-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGING AWAY BAD HABITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Monday., Sept. 25, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is from HARVARD BUSINESS
REVIEW, the premiere source of information on the art and science
of business and management. For information about purchasing this
article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or about The Syndicate's new
offerings from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL PUBLISHING _ contact one of
the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the
end of the text.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: The full-length, 5,500-word version of this article
is available upon request.)
 By JAMES WALDROOP and TIMOTHY BUTLER  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've all worked with people who are star performers but have
one serious personality shortcoming that makes life difficult for
everyone, limits their effectiveness and often proves to be their
professional undoing.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of one executive we worked with, such people are
''95 percent brilliant, 5 percent disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tactics that you can use to help these otherwise
valuable people get beyond their psychological limitations.
</P>
<P>
   THE HERO
</P>
<P>
   The hero is often the last person a manager wants to change.
After all, why would you want to tamper with someone who gets more
done in a day than others do in a week?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that over the long term, the hero's constant
pushing adds real costs to the bottom line even if those costs are
obscured by short-term results.
</P>
<P>
   If you look carefully at the hero's trail, you'll probably find
the footprints of valuable people who left the company after trying
to keep up with the hero's superhuman exertions. Within the
company, you'll find burned-out co-workers. And the hero himself
may be thoroughly spent, too.
</P>
<P>
   Some heroes become addicted to success at an early age; others
push as a way of dealing with their own shaky self-esteem. An ``I'm
gonna show them'' mentality. Clearly, heroes lack the empathy
needed to understand what others are going through to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   To change a hero's behavior, express your appreciation for his
accomplishments. Then quickly segue into a discussion about the
costs of burnout _ in himself and in his team members.
</P>
<P>
   The hero must learn to take regular readings of his team's
temperature and to pay attention to body language, facial
expressions and energy levels that subtly indicate resistance or
dismay.
</P>
<P>
   As the hero's manager, you may want to help him make a checklist
of warning signs that the temperature is getting too hot: for
example, the times that he and others are leaving voice messages
and e-mails, the rising levels of illness among employees and
reports of marital troubles. The hero should fill out the list
weekly and discuss it with you.
</P>
<P>
   Heroes have to think more about winning the war and less about
the individual battles. Emphasize that you need your hero to make
strategic decisions; he should delegate the implementation whenever
possible. You might even encourage him to hire an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it is essential that someone take on the official role
of observing the hero. The goal is to turn down the volume without
switching it off. You could do this yourself, or help your hero
choose a trusted co-worker to carry out this task.
</P>
<P>
   THE MERITOCRAT
</P>
<P>
   Meritocrats believe that the world is a fair market in which the
best ideas will always win on their own merit. Such people
typically excelled at school and were consistently rewarded for
getting the highest score. Thus they have a naive reliance on the
authority of objective, measurable facts. They never accepted that
in the real world, ideas have to be sold, negotiated and shaped to
meet political and organizational realities.
</P>
<P>
   To help a meritocrat, you should first offer sympathy. Agree
that it's really an awful waste of time to have to persuade people
to support ideas of clear merit.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to raise a very difficult question: ``How
effective do you want to be?'' We've done this ourselves by using
Jimmy Carter as an example. Carter, we say, was a highly principled
and intelligent president who stayed unswervingly true to his
ideals. And yet even the most die-hard Democrat would agree that
Ronald Reagan was more effective than Carter at winning
congressional and public support for his agenda. We ask, ``Do you
want to be 100 percent pure, like Carter, or do you want to be
effective, like Reagan? You must choose one or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   A manager needs to help them see that it is possible to operate
in gray areas, accomplish a great deal and still emerge relatively
unsullied.
</P>
<P>
   Like the hero, the meritocrat has to learn much more about his
team. For each member, he needs to ask himself: What does this
person work for _ big money, prestige, intellectual challenge,
acquisition of power? Only when the meritocrat understands and
takes into account individual differences can he figure out how to
get people to support his goals and make their strongest
contribution to a project.
</P>
<P>
   THE BULLDOZER
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozers are people who decided early on that the world is a
hostile place where you should do unto others before they do unto
you _ plus 10 percent. They don't trust others, and others don't
trust them. At the same time, they're extremely loyal to their
bosses, and they get things done _ which is why they're worth
trying to help.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozers are often reluctant to change a style that, by their
lights, is highly effective. So to change a bulldozer, you have to
become one yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Start by asking him if he has any idea how many enemies he has
created within the company. Follow this with a powerful line we've
used in our consulting: ``If I put it to a vote, there's no
question _ you'd be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat of being fired is usually quite motivating. If the
bulldozer says he's willing to listen, the next step is to begin a
campaign of rapprochement. Tell him to make a list of his victims.
Then the two of you should script out an apology for each one.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate goal, of course, is to get the bulldozer to avoid
causing damage in the first place. To do that, he has to become
more aware of when he is about to roll over someone so he can stop
himself.
</P>
<P>
   As with a hero, it's a good idea at the beginning to agree on
someone the bulldozer trusts to monitor his behavior. If the
bulldozer shows a willingness to change, he'll be able to build
roads for you without flattening people in his way.
</P>
<P>
   THE PESSIMIST
</P>
<P>
   Pessimists' worries are sometimes justified _ they're based on a
knowledge of mistakes that others have made. More frequently,
though, pessimists simply stifle creativity and block fruitful
opportunities. They also tend to micromanage, looking over
everyone's shoulders lest a mistake be made.
</P>
<P>
   Pessimists are motivated primarily by a fear of shame of being
wrong or inadequate. And avoidance of shame can spread insidiously
throughout an organization's culture, destroying the company's
capacity to innovate and take risks.
</P>
<P>
   Tell the pessimist that you're on his side in looking at
proposals for change with appropriate caution. That positioning
lets you avoid a pointless wrangle over the pros and cons of any
particular initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Then point out that you're afraid that the impact of his alarms
is diminishing. Moreover, he's giving the other members of his
group a free ride: ``They don't have to worry and express their
reservations. You do that.'' The message: It's OK to worry, but
your fears must do more than guard the status quo; they should have
a constructive edge.
</P>
<P>
   Teach him how to evaluate risk better. Tell your pessimist that
when a change initiative is proposed, he must consider the pros and
cons of making the change as well as the pros and cons of doing
nothing. This way, he will be forced into a more objective risk
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   THE REBEL
</P>
<P>
   Although they fancy themselves as revolutionaries, rebels'
protests against ``the system'' don't go beyond simple grousing.
They're the ones who ask the inappropriate questions in meetings,
make jokes about the company's management and publicly question the
motives behind any major change.
</P>
<P>
   What rebels enjoy most is a game of tug of war. So your first
tactic is to refuse to play.
</P>
<P>
   Co-opt the rebel by making him responsible for a relatively
high-profile task that requires him to win the cooperation of
others. In essence, you pull him out of the heckling audience and
push him into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Another approach is to begin by asking the rebel, in a neutral
tone, if he's thinking about quitting. When he says no (with
surprise), tell him that you were wondering because he always seems
to be butting up against the limits and putting the organization
down. If he says, ``No, I'm only kidding around,'' come back
forcefully: ``I don't buy that. And in any event, the things you
say hurt people and the morale of the group. That must stop!''
</P>
<P>
   Then shift to a different gear: ``But more to the point, you
seem to think that a lot of things around here should be changed.
True? Well, right now you're about as effective a revolutionary as
a 3-year-old. If you're going to battle the counterproductive
aspects of the `regime,' why not do it effectively?''
</P>
<P>
   Now you have the chance to help your rebel become a real leader
of change. His first assignment should be to spend a week as a
cultural anthropologist, noting all the subtle elements of your
organization's culture: what people reveal about their personal
lives; how they align in groups; how decisions are made officially
and how they are really made; and so on. You should require him to
hand you a written report.
</P>
<P>
   Then ask: ``If you were a real revolutionary fighting somewhere
against a dictatorship, would it be better to stand out or to blend
in?'' The answer is clear, so push the rebel to the logical
conclusion. ``You have a choice. You can work to change things here
or you can follow your old pattern and just be an irritant. If you
choose the latter, your career will stall. We need people like you
to help improve this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being negative just for its own sake, he'll turn his
energies toward constructive criticism and the building of a better
company.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOME RUN HITTER
</P>
<P>
   The home run hitter is always imagining the roar of the crowd
when the ball clears the outfield fence. However, he tends to
strike out a lot, swinging for the fence when a simple base hit
would have helped the team. Put simply, home run hitters focus on
things that are too big too soon.
</P>
<P>
   As a home run hitter's manager, you need to deliver two
messages: (1) you appreciate his drive, ambition and
self-confidence; and (2) you want to move him up the curve as
quickly as possible but at a pace that ensures his steady progress
_ he must stay with the program.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to explain just what the program, be it
spending time overseas or working more with particular clients.
Look at people in positions that he aspires to and explain their
career trajectories; that way, he'll understand that they didn't
just walk in and take over.
</P>
<P>
   Home run hitters worry that they'll never get ahead, and they
feel that their strenuous efforts go unappreciated. Therefore, talk
with them often about their career progression and praise them
frequently. This will help reassure your home run hitter that,
given a little time, he'll have his shot at the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tactics we recommend here won't work in every case,
they can help turn some of your brilliantly flawed performers into
spectacular achievers _ to the benefit of themselves and your
company.
</P>
<P>
   (James Waldroop and Timothy Butler, both psychologists, are
principals at Peregrine Partners, a Brookline, Mass.-based
consulting firm that specializes in executive development and
employee retention.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on offerings
from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
