u s BC-BBN-METS-STUMBLE-NYT &LR;      09-28 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-STUMBLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE METS VS. THE THING: A NONMUSICAL SEQUEL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a character in the musical ``Phantom of the
Opera'' tries to explain away mysterious mishaps by saying ``these
things happen,'' another character says emphatically, ``These
things do not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips acknowledged that there is a thing that happens
to the Mets when they play the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Without putting the words to music, Phillips, the Mets' general
manager, said: ``We have a thing. We've got to try to figure out
what it is and why it is and how we're going to overcome it.
There's no ignoring that there's a thing. It's silly to say `Oh no,
it's just baseball.' It's something we have to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Braves defeated the Mets in the last three games of
the season, knocking them out of a chance for the wild-card spot in
the playoffs. Last September, the Mets went to Atlanta a mere game
behind the Braves and lost all three games there, then lost two of
three in New York. Last week's trip to Atlanta resulted in two
losses in three games. And then Tuesday night at Shea Stadium the
Braves heaped insult upon the Mets' inability to beat them by
clinching their ninth consecutive division championship.
</P>
<P>
   It was as in your face as it gets in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be like this for the next 20 years,''
Phillips said. ``Sooner or later it's going to turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to turn it one step at a time, the Mets beat the Braves,
6-2, Wednesday night and advanced to the National League playoffs
as the wild card for the second successive season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Despite a month in which they have won only 11 of 25 games,
the Mets gained the postseason more easily than a year ago. And if
they want to embellish baseball's version of the consolation prize,
the Mets can congratulate themselves for qualifying for the
playoffs sooner than the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have been stoic about their fate. And maybe just a bit
disingenuous. What's the difference, they proclaimed, if they
finished first or finished second and won the wild-card
distinction? Either way they would be in the playoffs, and any team
in the playoffs is eligible to make it all the way to the World
Series and win it. Why, just look at the 1997 Florida Marlins, they
have said. Look at Al Leiter over there. He has a ring from that
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday night's game, Bobby Valentine addressed the
issue of being the wild-card team, and he sounded downright
defensive about it. He chose to compare his team with the St. Louis
Cardinals, who had already clinched the National League Central
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Louis has won one more game in every 50 than we have,''
Valentine said, ``and in their city they're supposed to feel like
the kings and in our city people think that we should run away and
hide and be embarrassed about entering the playoffs. I don't get
it. And neither do my guys, so I tell them I don't get it either.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, relating a comment one of his players had made to him, the
manager added: ``One of my guys said which person is it who they
were supposed to go over and apologize to when they made the
playoffs. I said I don't get this whole thing. I said let's play
the game, win the game and not worry about the nonsense. Even those
who make something out of nothing will make nonsense a major
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, a veteran manager with tenures in Texas and New York,
has long been obsessed with the news media. It is important for him
to have supporters in that area. He doesn't care for critics. He
could avoid some of the attention he gets, but he brings it on
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, as the Mets were struggling to win that
wild-card slot, he was interviewed by Sports Illustrated and said
he had ``five losers'' among the players in his clubhouse and said
other managers would be afraid to appear on a panel with him
because he would make them look bad.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he was interviewed by New York magazine and even
brought up the 1999 Sports Illustrated article, which caused a ton
of angst in the Mets' hierarchy. Valentine didn't utter any
similarly inflammatory comments, but he deplored the idea of a
magazine doing such a piece with the Mets in such a position (of
course, he could have declined the interview) and he referred to
``a couple of clowns'' in the New York area who he said didn't give
him the credit he deserved.
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves in their division _ and maybe someday they won't
be if the National League becomes a four-division league _ the Mets
can't be expected to finish first. But they could beat the Braves
more often at critical times, and they could wrap up the wild card
more easily than they have the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But as the wild card, the Mets could have another opportunity to
knock off the Braves. Not that they should be dwelling on the
Braves when they play St. Louis or San Francisco in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time we should think about the Braves,'' Phillips
said, ``is tonight and tomorrow. After that, we shouldn't think
about them again until we're facing them in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   But just in case they do, the general manager dipped into the
past for an example the Mets could use in their attempt to change
their fortunes with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the ``thing'' the Mets have with Atlanta, Phillips
said, ``The Dodgers seemed to overcome it in '88 against the Mets
so it can be done.'' The Dodgers lost 10 of 11 games to the Mets
that season but beat the Mets in the league series. But they were
the Mets. This is the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
