<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX IN POSITION TO OWN OCTOBER 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1996 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ If NBC's Bob Costas wants to call a baseball
game on broadcast television during the next six seasons, he will
have to ring up Fox Sports.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's rejection on Tuesday of Major League Baseball's demand to
renew the contract it has had since 1996 allowed Fox to swoop in
with a $2.5 billion contract to merge its package with NBC's.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started Fox Sports, we said: `Where should we go?
Which sports did we want?''' said David Hill, the chairman of the
Fox Television Sports Group. ``We wanted and got the National
Football League, we wanted NASCAR and we wanted baseball. And we
said, `Wouldn't it be great to have the World Series year in and
year out?'''
</P>
<P>
   Starting next year, that is what Fox will get. In addition to
six guaranteed years of the World Series, it will retain the
Saturday Game of the Week, carry every All-Star Game through 2006,
and every league championship series and division series. The
division series games will most likely be shown on cable on Fox
Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have taken place over several months, with baseball
initially wanting to triple what Fox and NBC were paying to renew
their deals. Both rejected the demands, as did ESPN, which was
paying about $43 million a year to carry division series games. ABC
and CBS passed on assuming NBC's package, which had only been for
the postseason and three All-Star Games. Fox made its offer to
baseball nearly three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's $417 million annual rights fee under its new deal
represents a 44 percent jump over the $290 million paid for the
same group of packages by Fox, NBC and ESPN since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best deal baseball could make,'' said Neal Pilson,
an industry consultant and former president of CBS Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball didn't have the leverage or competitive market going
for it. They asked for a tripling and got less than 50 percent.
This is the market. You get what the market says you're worth, not
what you say you're worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox is assuming the largest load of sports network rights since
CBS owned a similar package from 1990 to 1993, minus the division
series, which had not yet been created. Hill insisted that Fox was
not destined to suffer a fate similar to that of CBS, which lost
nearly half of its four-year, $1.06 billion investment.
</P>
<P>
   Pilson, who made that deal, recalled that CBS was bedeviled by a
recession, the Gulf War and World Series featuring Toronto, a
market that is not included in the Nielsen ratings. ``But the
market is better now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said one of the crucial elements to making the new deal was
the growth of its owned and operated stations division. Fox owns 23
televisions stations and recently acquired 10 more.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Fox's new deal includes a renewal of its cable
rights on Fox Sports Net and Fx, spreading the financial burden
beyond the broadcast network. CBS did not have any cable properties
on which to show baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he was not worried that ABC, NBC and CBS would load up
their best first-run and event programming to counter the league
championship series and World Series on Fox. Rather, he points to
how Fox can now set its own advertising rates without being
tethered to NBC's pricing, and package multiple World Series deals
with advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Pilson said that having the postseason is a bigger ratings boost
for Fox, which ranks fourth in the ratings race, than for any other
network. The World Series, which has rated between a 14.1 and a
17.4 since 1996, is still a marquee event, but it is a much better
prime-time alternative to entertainment programming for Fox than
for NBC, ABC or CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Series was good for Fox and NBC, but dramatically
better for Fox,'' he said. ``But the issue is the impact it will
have on its prime-time schedule. ABC and CBS wouldn't make this
deal because it would have such an impact on launching its fall
prime-time schedule. It may not have as much an impact on Fox's
prime time as Fox thinks it will have.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC, without the NFL and, starting next season, baseball, is now
focused on the NBA; NASCAR (starting next season); the Olympics
through 2008; Notre Dame football; golf; the Wimbledon and French
Open tennis tournaments; launching the fledgling XFL with the World
Wrestling Federation; and, starting next year, the Triple Crown
horse races.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
