<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN     09-28 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TWO 'ENEMIES' WHO MAKE MUSIC BY PLAYING EACH OTHER
SO HARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos OLY 1,2,10,11,12,13,14,15 are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Back in Norway, they heard about the victory
tour, the commercials, the sponsorships, when the United States won
the Women's World Cup in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has more money,'' said Silje Joergensen, who
plays defense for Norway. ``They are rich.''
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian players did not sulk about losing to the Americans
as they went back to their jobs, playing for local clubs for a few
extra kroner. The countries are different. The cultures are
different. The economies are different.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, the Norwegians have been known to beat the United
States more than occasionally _ and even ticked off the Yanks with
a choreographed choo-choo train celebration after winning in their
semifinal of the 1995 World Cup in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archenemies'' is the word Tiffeny Milbrett once used to
describe the Norwegians, although Thursday night the effervescent
Milbrett was saying, ``Gosh, you've got to give them credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing word of the way corporate and hometown America fell for
the women last summer, the Norwegians could only remind themselves
that their time would come around again.
</P>
<P>
   It arrived in the final of the Summer Games Thursday night when
Norway outlasted the United States, 3-2, in sudden death. Norway is
the only nation to hold an advantage over the Americans, 15
victories to 13 losses with two ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not everything,'' Joergensen said. ``We showed that
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The two old rivals, who have been storing up bruises and cuts,
grudges and resentments, in the decade and a half of this sport in
the Olympics, staged a classic game, as good as sport gets. The
United States tied the game in the dying seconds of regulation
time, and then Norway clutched the victory in the 12th minute of
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The leaping header by the 5-foot-2-inch Milbrett was as stunning
as Mookie Wilson's eccentric at-bat in the 1986 World Series,
during which a wild pitch by Red Sox pitcher Bob Stanley and a
ground ball that went through legs of Bill Buckner led to a Mets
victory. And the stunning overtime goal was as dramatic as Bill
Mazeroski's home run that ended the seventh game of the 1960 World
Series _ and more controversial because it involved a potential
hand ball by a Norwegian forward.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will debate how Hege Riise's perfect lofting pass was
touched by Joy Fawcett and then bounced onto the
chest/shoulder/upper arm of Norway's Dagny Mellgren, who lashed a
grass-cutter under the fingers of Siri Mullinix.
</P>
<P>
   The referee, Sonia Denoncourt of Canada, showed common sense in
deciding that Mellgren had not blatantly positioned her upper arm
to control the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Would the call have gone that way in the jingoistic confines of
the Rose Bowl in 1999? The Yanks got the benefit of the doubt when
goalkeeper Briana Scurry leaped forward _ in violation of the rule
_ to smother a Chinese penalty kick. Thursday night, Norway won on
neutral turf, with many Norwegians sprouting Viking horns and
painting their faces red.
</P>
<P>
   These Americans and the Norwegians have become the Fraziers and
the Alis of women's sport. When they become grumpy old women, they
will still remember the mutual testiness.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 the Yanks beat Norway, 2-1, in China to win the first
World Cup. In 1995 the Yanks were offended when the Norwegians
crawled around the field clutching the ankles of the players in
front of them. And the Norwegians were not thrilled when the Yanks
beat them, 2-1, in overtime in the semifinals of the 1996 Summer
Games in Athens, Ga. But they usually come back.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations have produced the greatest offensive and
defensive players in the history of the sport, Michelle Akers and
Linda Medalen, the latter a detective who treated the Americans
like suspected perps.
</P>
<P>
   Without them, the legend grows. Gro Espeseth, Norway's defender,
who missed the 1999 World Cup because of knee surgery, was back
Thursday night, scoring on a header off the desperate flying foot
of Shannon MacMillan. That goal gave the Norwegians a reprieve at
1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we wanted it more,'' said Marianne Pettersen of
Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett conceded that the Yanks have a problem when they play
Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ``With every other team, we play the way we want, but they know
how to beat us,` Milbrett said. ``We just played the best game of
the tournament, and we're going home with a silver medal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are also going home to a professional league that
begins next April. And, yes, the Norwegians have heard about the
chunk of change being spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play soccer because I love it,'' said Joergensen, who is
attending college to learn to teach retarded children. ``I would
love to play soccer for money. I would go to the United States to
play in that league.''
</P>
<P>
   She would be welcome. And she would be gracious enough to not
mention the status of the Norwegian-American rivalry, at least not
very often.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
