<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ESCHER-NYT &LR;      09-28 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ESCHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARTIST THE WEB WAS MADE FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You would think that art and the Internet were made for each
other. But all artists are not equal on the Web. There are
reproductions, to be sure, but what about ``appreciation''? Some
renowned artists are represented by little more than a few capsule
biographies and a lot of dealers, with precious little commentary
or insight, even from museums.
</P>
<P>
   For an Internet art feast, try Maurits Cornelis Escher
(1898-1972), the Dutch graphic artist. His experiments in
perspective, his mathematically grounded lithographs and his
spatial illusions have struck a chord with several Web audiences:
art lovers, math and science students and fans of the fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   Escher is known for drawings, woodcuts and lithographs of things
like steps that go up and down at the same time, waterfalls that
replenish themselves, hands that draw each other and repeating
patterns, known mathematically as tessellations, of lizards, birds
and other shapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long before the first computer-generated 3-D images were
thrilling the public, Escher was a master of the third dimension,''
notes a page from the World of Escher (www.worldofescher.com), a
Texas company founded in 1993. Its five-year-old Web site includes
an Escher gallery, a bibliography and a selection of Escher
quotations and essays by and about him. It also offers posters,
neckties, T-shirts, CD-ROMs, jigsaw puzzles and _ in a tie-in with
its graphic-design merchandise _ a series of contests for students
who would like to try their hand at creating their own Escher-style
tessellations.
</P>
<P>
   The site draws 30,000 visitors a month, and it has received more
than 1,700 entries from students around the world since June 1995,
said Paul Schofield, the site's Webmaster, in an e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   In an online essay, a past editor of the site, Tom Litchfield,
asks, ``Can you imagine his thoughts on computer programs that
automatically generate tessellations; would he be excited or
woefully disappointed?''
</P>
<P>
   He also wonders what Escher would think about all the
merchandise. The site reprints a 1969 letter by Escher in which he
complained to his son that ``the hippies of San Francisco continue
to print my work illegally.'' He hated ``virulently colored
posters,'' he added. But Litchfield surmises that Escher would have
eventually accepted and approved of his work's popularization.
</P>
<P>
   Totally Tessellated (library.thinkquest.org/16661) won a 1998
ThinkQuest Internet Challenge contest sponsored by a company called
Advanced Network and Services, which invites students and their
academic coaches to form teams to design educational Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   It has an extensive discussion of tessellations, those repeating
figures that fill two dimensions, as well as a series of hands-on
activities. The site's many pages explore the history of
tessellation as an artistic concept. It includes the Moorish motifs
in the Alhambra in Spain, which Escher visited and which profoundly
influenced him.
</P>
<P>
   The site has a large Escher section, with a lavishly illustrated
biography that shows examples of Escher's explorations of infinity,
knots, perspective and impossible architecture as well as
tessellations. There are also sections on related art movements,
like Cubism, and mathematical topics.
</P>
<P>
   Another teaching site, from IProject Online
(www.iproject.com/escher/teaching/teaching.html), offers a number
of lesson plans and classroom suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   On the official M.C. Escher Web site (www.mcescher.com), a
biography of Escher points out that in addition to his famous
impossible figures, he designed postage stamps and tapestries,
illustrated books and sometimes worked in three dimensions, carving
wooden spheres. Viewers can download a free interactive game. The
site's news section warns about fake Escher prints being offered on
eBay.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the site is a 3-D multimedia section that flies
a viewer around and through three of Escher's most famous works. It
was developed for a 1998 exhibition in Rotterdam, Netherlands,
where, the site says, visitors stood for two hours to watch what
can now be seen online: a vivid unraveling of how Escher fooled the
eye by compressing multiple viewpoints into one.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Escher quotations on the site is this one: ``I walk
around in mysteries. Each time, youngsters say, You make Op Art,
too. I don't know what that is, Op Art. This work I have been
making for the past 30 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
