<HEADER>
A5309 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-OKLAHOMACITY-1000(2Ta     09-28 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLAHOMACITY-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA CITY IS SHEDDING ITS DULL AND DUSTY IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ This is a city that hasn't gotten much respect,
from the outside world or even from itself.
</P>
<P>
   Bisected by the Canadian River (which locals joke is the only
river that needs mowing three times a year), its economy dominated
by the cattle industry (step outside a downtown building, and some
days you can smell the evidence of the giant stockyards operation
just west of downtown), it has been hammered for being dull and
dusty, unsophisticated and unattractive. Even Tulsa looked down on
it.
</P>
<P>
   But the final straw came in the early '90s, when Oklahoma City
lost out on attracting a major out-of-town employer that had
promised to create up to 7,000 jobs. The company told Oklahoma City
that it just didn't have the ``quality of life'' that the winning
city offered. The mecca of culture that won the employer over?
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   That, apparently, was the wake-up call that Oklahoma City
needed. In the mid-'90s, the city launched a $700 million downtown
building spree, made possible by a five-year, 1-cent city sales tax
overwhelmingly approved by citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with only about half the projects finished, Oklahoma City
already looks like a new place, living up to its self-proclaimed
title, the Newest City in the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new 12,000-seat minor-league ballpark, a replica of
the vintage-style baseball fields so beloved in Arlington and
Baltimore. There's an expanded, renovated convention center, with a
shiny new Marriott Renaissance hotel tower across the street.
There's Bricktown, a bustling warehouse district of clubs and
restaurants. Its piece de resistance? The new Bricktown Canal, a
mile-long waterway lined with restaurants and plied by water taxis;
it is eventually supposed to hook up with the long-scorned Canadian
River in another ambitious redevelopment plan.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to come, including a downtown arena that will house
minor-league hockey and arena football, and a rebuilt music hall
and a new library. The building spurt has been accompanied by
expansion by businesses and museums _ and by a boom in civic pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internally, the biggest change is that people no longer
apologize for being from Oklahoma City,'' says Sandy Pantlik,
communications director for the city's tourism office. ``I think
the locals are really excited about the changes. It's an exciting
time for Oklahoma City. ''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   They rise like twin modernistic Arc de Triomphes, golden and
simple, at once majestic and unspeakably sad, marking a different
kind of victory _ that of a city that has weathered catastrophe and
rebuilt itself in a new image.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the two bronze gates, at each end of the Oklahoma City
National Memorial, is engraved with a time of day: 9:01 on one,
9:03 on the other, framing the time on April 19, 1995, that
Oklahoma City changed forever. It was at 9:02 a.m. that day that a
terrorist bomb went off at the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building
downtown, killing 168 and injuring hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than reconstruct the building, or erect a simple statue
or plaque, residents led the charge for a monument more fitting to
the memory of the United States' worst act of domestic terrorism.
In April, on the fifth anniversary of the bombing, President
Clinton dedicated the memorial, a $30 million project imposing in
its simplicity and funded by the federal government and private
donations.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial has already become one of the must-see destinations
for tourists. They walk through the gates, separated by a shallow
granite reflecting pool; they photograph the field of empty chairs,
168 stone-and-bronze structures, each with a base of illuminated
glass, etched with the name of a victim, symbolizing the lives
lost. They scan the pictures and poems and teddy bears and wreaths
left on the Memorial Fence, pieces of the original chain-link fence
that contained the rubble, where the community left its heartfelt
tributes.
</P>
<P>
   They gaze at the few remaining fragments of the federal building
walls, etched with the names of every survivor; they sit under the
Survivor Tree, a giant 75-year-old elm that somehow, miraculously,
escaped the carnage. Those two aspects underscore the city's hope
that the memorial convey not just the city's great loss, but
celebrate its survival. A memorial center and museum, initially set
to open this year but now scheduled for a February debut, will
further that theme, with interactive displays and firsthand
retellings of the bombing and the rebuilding process.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing has become so etched in the national consciousness
that it's often the first thing people think about when Oklahoma
City is mentioned. Many also believe that it spurred the downtown
redevelopment, which, of course, was already planned at the time of
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY: of the bombing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City residents understand they can't change that
perception. But they are valiantly trying to shed other outdated
perceptions of their hometown _ namely, that there's no culture, no
nightlife and nothing much to do.
</P>
<P>
   To be perfectly honest, North Texans ought to feel right at home
in Oklahoma City, as it bears more than a passing resemblance to
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City, too, has historic stockyards. (Theirs, however,
still comprise a working cattle district, with steakhouses and
diners geared to ranchers and cattle buyers attending the huge
weekly auctions.)
</P>
<P>
   Its Cowboy Hall of Fame and Western Heritage Center, with its
fine galleries of western art, its interactive, kid-friendly Old
West exhibits, and its lovely native-plant gardens, would fit
nicely in Fort Worth's museum district. (In fact, it seems like a
mondo combination of our Amon Carter and science and history
museums.)
</P>
<P>
   Its old-fashioned-looking red-brick Bricktown Ballpark is home
to the Oklahoma 89ers _ one of the Texas Rangers' minor-league
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   And its downtown is clean and safe, with a district of clubs and
restaurants that seems reminiscent of Sundance Square.
</P>
<P>
   The linchpin of downtown is Bricktown, an entertainment district
that looks like the love child of Dallas' West End and San
Antonio's River Walk, though it's not as big, commercial or crowded
as either of those. On weekend nights, young professionals and
date-night couples fill bars like Tapwerks, a sophisticated version
of the Flying Saucer beer joints popular in Texas. Families stroll
the sidewalks framing the canal and spill onto the patios of the
ubiquitous Tex-Mex restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The rebirth hasn't been without problems. Some folks, for
instance, have complained that the mile-long Bricktown canal was
little more than a chintzy imitation of San Antonio's historic
River Walk; indeed, development is still a bit sparse along the
waterfront. Overall, the level of sophistication doesn't always
match the ambition: For instance, one restaurant's frittata wasn't
the traditional Italian baked-egg dish, but rather a flat omelet
with asparagus and goat cheese piled on top. And the hottest dance
club seemed to play nothing but Madonna _ the '80s version at that
_ on a recent Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But growth, and new developments such as a planned movie theater
complex, ought to take care of some of that. In the meantime, those
who consider downtown limiting can find plenty to do elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The city's premier museum is the somewhat misleadingly named
Cowboy Hall of Fame and Western Heritage Museum, with a terrific
collection of contemporary western art in its elegant galleries.
The 40-year-old museum has been on a growth spurt in the past six
years, with $50 million worth of new construction, renovation and
exhibits. Kids will love the interactive exhibits about rodeos and
cowboys, as well as Prosperity Junction, a life-size replica of an
Old West town, with livery stable, bank, saddle shop, train depot,
schoolhouse and marshal's office.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, there's the makings of a museum district, with several
special-interest institutions. There's the Firefighters Museum; the
Omniplex, with a planetarium and an American Indian center; the
National Softball Hall of Fame; and the 45th Infantry Division
Museum, with an eclectic collection of war memorabilia including
tanks, planes, cartoons, weapons and Nazi-era artifacts looted by
American GIs, such as pieces of silver, linens and china once used
by Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles west, adventurous diners ought to explore a
neighborhood sometimes called Little Saigon. More than 20 years
ago, Oklahomans sponsored a number of Asian refugees, who largely
settled in a rundown neighborhood west of the state capitol. Now
it's grown into a bustling community, filled with small groceries,
jewelers, video stores, tailors, nail salons and more than a dozen
restaurants, from tiny noodle shops and pho (soup) houses to big
Chinese buffets.
</P>
<P>
   The businesses initially may have been supported mainly by
immigrants, but now they draw from all over the city, and beyond:
Mick Jagger got takeout from Sala-Thai, an unpretentious but
deliciously authentic Thai restaurant, the last time the Rolling
Stones played in the area. The boys' autographed picture, with a
handwritten thank-you note from the band's manager, is posted
proudly but unobtrusively near the front door.
</P>
<P>
   That's classic Oklahoma City for you. Look closely, and it just
might surprise you.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
