<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5323 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MARTIN-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     09-28 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTIN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARTIN BAUMAN': THE WRITING LIFE NEVER UNEXAMINED, OFTEN NASTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martin Bauman, the title hero of David Leavitt's new novel,
bears more than a passing resemblance to his creator. Like Leavitt,
he grew up on the West Coast and came east to attend an Ivy League
college. Like Leavitt, he published a story while still in his
early 20s in The New Yorker (or, in Martin's case, a magazine much
like The New Yorker), worked briefly at a publishing house and went
on to achieve a measure of renown as a novelist and short-story
writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Bauman; Or, a Sure Thing'' is told in the first person
and set down in an intimate, confessional voice reminiscent at once
of Philip Roth's ``Ghost Writer'' and Evelyn Waugh's ``Brideshead
Revisited'': a voice inclined toward nostalgia and rumination, a
voice sure to remind readers at times of the supple sonorities of
Leavitt's brilliant debut collection of stories, ``Family Dancing''
(1984).
</P>
<P>
   This novel, however, divides peculiarly into two halves. The
first, both heartfelt and polished, stands as a classic
Bildungsroman about a young man's coming of age and provides as
poignant and funny an account of literary apprenticeship as that
found in the opening pages of William Styron's ``Sophie's Choice.''
It focuses on Martin's contentious relationship with his former
writing teacher, the irascible Stanley Flint, and his subsequent
efforts to achieve independence from his onetime mentor.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of ``Martin Bauman'' is an altogether messier,
more haphazard production _ a rambling, self-indulgent chronicle of
Martin's romantic difficulties and the intramural squabblings of
his best friends. These latter pages, like the slush-pile
manuscripts Martin reads at the publishing house, echo ``in their
coarse sincerity'' the ``confessional talk shows'' of the '90s:
Martin rambles on here at wearying length about everything from his
endless sessions of television-watching to his medical treatment
for genital warts.
</P>
<P>
   We feel as i Leavitt were allowing us to eavesdrop on Martin's
whining therapy sessions instead of giving us a shapely account of
his hero's travails. It's a criticism echoed by Martin's friend
Seamus, who says he wishes Martin would ``get over his obsession
with stupid little picayune domestic details.'' Did Tolstoy write
about masturbation? Seamus wonders. Did Shakespeare?
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, these later sections of the novel
illustrate some of the very things that an editor criticizes in
Martin's stories: The ``tone is sometimes condescending'' and
``there aren't any likable characters'' _ that is, ``characters
with whom we can sympathize, whose points of view we want to
share.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's warmly observed portrait of his mother and the comical
portraits of his roommates give way, as the book progresses, to
carping descriptions of people the reader has no reason to want to
get to know.
</P>
<P>
   Martin portrays his boyfriend, Eli, as a grievance-hoarding
hothead and dogmatic gay ideologue who won't even go to his best
friend's wedding because she is marrying a man instead of a woman,
and he depicts their mutual friend Liza as a self-absorbed
careerist who does little but obsess about her sex life. Their
acquaintances in the literary world are equally tiresome: a
collection of phonies, self-promoters and hypocrites, who seem more
interested in gossip and in social climbing than in writing.
</P>
<P>
   As for Martin himself, he evolves from a callow young man,
likable in his bumbling efforts to excel, into an openly ambitious,
even opportunistic fellow who clearly tries the patience of just
about everyone, including the author. He is needy and possessive in
his relationship with Eli, throwing a histrionic fit when Eli
spends an evening comforting a distraught friend instead of staying
home with him; later, he will cavalierly cheat on Eli with an
assortment of other men.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to his career, Martin can be similarly
self-serving, courting literary success the same way he once strove
to get straight As in school. When Flint speaks disparagingly of
Martin's novel in progress, Martin tries to get his former teacher
in trouble by ratting him out to his boss, suggesting that Flint's
womanizing may be cause for dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   It is Martin's relationship with Flint that serves as the
primary motor behind this book. Flint not only represents a father
figure whose blessings signify the approval of the grown-up world
that the young Martin so desperately craves, but he also embodies
all the glamour and sophistication that Martin projects onto the
literary world in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening sections of the book, Leavitt does a dexterous
job of delineating Flint's aura: his mythic reputation among young
writers; his use of cruel put-downs and over-the-top praise to
maintain a hold over his students; his rigorous, unforgiving
aesthetic. He also uses Flint's contentious, emotionally fraught
relationship with Martin _ much the way he used the relationship
between the concert pianist Richard Kennington and his protege,
Paul Porterfield, in ``The Page Turner'' (1998) _ to show his
hero's ambivalent progress toward adulthood and autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   When Flint recedes into the background in the second half of the
book, much of the novel's energy is lost, as the reader is
abandoned to the narcissistic navel-gazing of Martin and his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   While this portion of ``Martin Bauman'' is sorely in need of
some editing, while this part of the book points up Leavitt's
difficulties with the long-distance form of the novel, the voice he
uses in much of this volume _ confiding, meditative and pliant _
marks his rediscovery of one of his greatest strengths as a writer,
and it points the way toward more satisfying achievements.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MARTIN BAUMAN: OR, A SURE THING'
</P>
<P>
   By David Leavitt
</P>
<P>
   387 pages. Houghton Mifflin. $26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
