<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUNICATION-BREAKDOWN-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNICATION BREAKDOWN: EIGHT MISTAKES MANAGERS MAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Tue., Sept. 26, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 FROM: THE HARVARD MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION LETTER  
 By STEVE ROBBINS  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How can management communications be screwed up? Let us count
the ways.
</P>
<P>
   Some can be traced to the idiosyncrasies of leaders _ for
example, Howard Hughes, who had a deathly fear of germs,
communicated with employees solely by notes or by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   But then there are the common foul-ups that every company falls
prey to at one time or another. Here are eight typical blunders and
how to avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNICATION WITHOUT GROUND WORK
</P>
<P>
   Any controversial decision can engender scheming, plots and
politics. So rather than announcing a controversial decision to an
entire group, prep people one-on-one. By doing so, you can build an
alliance around the process, even if people disagree about the
content.
</P>
<P>
   Topics involving change are the most charged _ especially
reorganizations, changing goals and the departure of key employees.
</P>
<P>
   One way to cope is to name the emotion. ``This reorganization is
scary.'' Then address the concerns. Share the scenario you expect
to unfold. Demonstrate with your voice and body that you get it.
</P>
<P>
   LYING
</P>
<P>
   Certain topics must remain confidential while they're under
discussion. But be careful how you keep secrets. If people know
you've lied, you will lose their trust forever.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than lie, train yourself to respond, ``No comment'' or
``I can't answer that fully right now'' when asked about sticky
topics. Consistency is important. Warren Buffet never discusses his
investments, even with shareholders. As a result, his silence on a
particular deal gives away nothing.
</P>
<P>
   BELIEVING THAT WORDS CAN OVERCOME ACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   We want to believe that logic and discussion are the stuff of
persuasion, but in the end, actions win every time. If you say you
value everyone equally, but the executives have special parking
privileges, the message is clear: Status and title matter. If you
say you want feedback but explode when the feedback is negative,
the message is clear: You want to hear only about the good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Before communicating standards of behavior, values or goals,
look carefully in the mirror. Review your recent decisions, and ask
whether the decisions support the values you're espousing. If not,
change your behavior.
</P>
<P>
   IGNORING THE REALITIES OF POWER
</P>
<P>
   Surprised that you never hear bad news until it's too late?
Don't be. The more power you have, the less you'll hear problems.
</P>
<P>
   For an honest assessment of a problem, seek out bad news. And
when it comes, appreciate it (visibly!).
</P>
<P>
   However, messages are magnified as they travel down the
hierarchy. For example, if you look pained during a presentation,
everyone will ``know'' you hated the presentation (or worse _ the
presenter).
</P>
<P>
   To prevent rumors, use plain, simple language. End meetings by
reviewing your reactions and next steps. ``I enjoyed your analysis,
Chris. The sales trend is disturbing _ let's follow up on
Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   MIXING BUSINESS AND FRIENDSHIP COMMUNICATION
</P>
<P>
   Confine friendship and business interactions to separate
meetings. If you must mix them, make the boundary clear. ``Let's
stop talking business for a minute and just talk as friends.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to contentious topics, keep it 100 percent
business in the office. An executive remarked to a friend at a
trade show that a new hire was extremely capable _ and good-looking
too. Bad move. Such comments at work can hurt credibility or turn
into a discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERESTIMATING YOUR AUDIENCE'S INTELLIGENCE
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to gloss over issues because ``people won't
understand.'' Why explain a reorganization when you can simply say,
``Here's the new org chart''?
</P>
<P>
   But that's a cop-out. Frontline employees may not be masters of
organizational design, but they deserve to know the rationale
behind changes that affect their lives. It's your job to help them
understand.
</P>
<P>
   CONFUSING PROCESS WITH OUTCOME
</P>
<P>
   In goal-setting, compensation and evaluation, it's easy to
confuse process with outcome. For example, you promise your team a
10 percent raise, but then the board caps raises at 5 percent. You
fight to raise the number, and compromise on 7 percent. But your
people don't appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   You want your team to honor how hard you tried _ to love you for
your process, not for your outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   When setting goals or evaluation criteria, communicate and
measure both the outcomes and processes involved. Motivation comes
from setting ambitious goals, especially if people are free to
choose how to reach them. To build a strong organization, however,
evaluation should include effort, learning and improvement _ all
process measurements _ to reinforce effective behavior.
</P>
<P>
   USING INAPPROPRIATE FORMS OF COMMUNICATION
</P>
<P>
   Different communication channels work best for different topics.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is great for conveying information, but don't use it for
emotional issues; e-mail messages are too easy to misconstrue.
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls and face-to-face meetings are inefficient media for
disseminating information, but great for discussing emotional
topics. You can handle the listener's reaction, and you can use
your tone of voice and facial expressions to control your message.
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Robbins is president of VentureCoach.com, a Cambridge,
Mass.-based entrepreneurial coaching service.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on HARVARD
BUSINESS PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
