r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-28 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH POLE HAS BEEN GETTING MORE THAN SNOW RECENTLY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CECIL JOHNSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine the hole in Texas Stadium expanded to a size sufficient
to encompass all of North America, and the sun's rays blitzing
down, as football officials say, ``unabated'' to the turf below.
</P>
<P>
   Got the picture? Well, that's how big the World Meteorological
Organization says the Antarctic ozone hole is this year.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the ozone hole? A few years ago there was plenty of
excitement about it. In fact, the concern almost escalated to a
the-sky-is-falling kind of intensity.
</P>
<P>
   What scared folks who were knowledgeable about the ozone layer's
role in the environmental scheme of things was that its depletion
could lead to increased smog, damage to food crops and marine
ecosystems, as well as increases in skin cancer and cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   That could happen, and may be happening, because the ozone layer
screens the Earth from the sun's ultraviolet radiation. Such
worries, along with fears of global warming, prompted most of the
major nations of the world to send representatives to Kyoto, Japan,
in 1997 to make some serious commitments to take remedial action to
combat those interconnected environmental threats.
</P>
<P>
   The same greenhouse gases that contribute to global warming play
an important role in depleting the Earth's protective layer of
stratospheric ozone. Compounds called chlorofluorocarbons, the
stuff that used to be contained in most aerosol propellants and the
refrigerants in refrigerators and home and automobile air
conditioners, also eat away at the ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, scientists involved in an Antarctic expedition warned
that there might be a hole in the layer. And in 1985, a U.S.
weather satellite confirmed the existence of one.
</P>
<P>
   Other satellites also discovered a hole at the Earth's other
polar area. But the Arctic hole is smaller. The difference is said
to have something to do with the action of polar stratospheric
clouds at the South Pole that increase in winter and exacerbate the
destruction of ozone in the Antarctic.
</P>
<P>
   WMO scientists say the southern ozone hole is larger this year
than it has ever been and that ozone levels are 50 to 70 percent
below what they were when the hole was first detected. National
Aeronautics and Space Administration officials say it is spread
over 11 million square miles, extending over all of Antarctica and
reaching the southern tip of South America, an area three times
greater than the U.S. mainland.
</P>
<P>
   One wouldn't expect the hole to continue to grow in light of
actions that governments and businesses have taken or promised to
take to prevent it. In the United States, many ozone-depleting
substances have been phased out, and stringent regulations have
been imposed to control the release of refrigerants while servicing
or disposing of air-conditioning and refrigeration equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The layman, then, might logically expect the ozone holes to be
getting smaller instead of larger. But some scientists say there is
cause to become fatalistic about ozone depletion. They say the
growth in the holes is the result of ozone-destroying substances
that were realized years ago because that stuff takes a long time
to get up to the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   That means the effects of efforts to keep more
chlorofluorocarbons from getting up to the layer will not show up
for years to come. That's comforting. But there could be another
reason for the size of the 2000 Antarctic hole.
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is a presidential election year. And there is
an extraordinary amount of hot air being emitted on the hustings.
That stuff travels fast because most it lacks any real substance.
That means it shouldn't take it long to get up there and do as much
damage to the stratosphere as it is wreaking upon the credibility
of the process by which Americans choose their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a former columnist and editorial writer for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
