<HEADER>
A5350 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-BEAUTIFUL-REVIEW     09-28 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BEAUTIFUL-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEAUTIFUL': NOT SO PRETTY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
On the wall beside the full-length mirror in Mona Hibbard's bedroom
is a motto to live by.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Beauty is as beauty does.''
</P>
<P>
   When people get to know Mona, a different maxim comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty is only skin deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Mona (Minnie Driver) is a beauty pageant contestant with one
goal: winning. If that means gluing an opponent's hand to a flaming
baton, well, it's all for a good cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful,'' directed by Sally Field from a script by Jon
Bernstein, takes a satirical and gentle _ but decidedly negative _
view of beauty contests and the driven women who claw their way to
victory.
</P>
<P>
   From as far back as she can remember, Mona has been obsessed
with winning pageants. As a child _ in the movie's early scenes _
she saves money to join local contests, though she never comes
close to winning.
</P>
<P>
   But she grows up, turns pretty and learns to dress, talk and act
like a beauty queen. She also learns to walk over people who get in
her way and to use those who try to help her.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many judges did you do to win this?'' a runner-up whispers
to Mona when crowning her in a local contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone except your dad,'' Mona says through a beatific
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she's reached her 20s, with a real crack at winning the
Miss American Miss pageant, Mona has mastered the tricks of her
chosen trade but lost sight of the inner beauty the contest was
once supposed to represent.
</P>
<P>
   She is, in a word, a shrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful'' is a film with real problems. It's unimaginatively
directed and has a major imbalance between its dramatic and comic
elements. (Like an elderly woman committing suicide, and an
innocent person going to jail for her ``murder.'') It drags in the
middle. And the central character is unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   But like a pageant contestant who flops in talent but scores
well in the inspirational speech, there are elements and nuances
that save the movie from total washout.
</P>
<P>
   It touches, even if only glancingly, on a host of feminist
issues and interests, and presents them from a woman's viewpoint
(though writer Bernstein is male). The few men who pass through
this movie are irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Some of its problems are really assets. American audiences tend
to be unforgiving to female characters who aren't flawlessly sweet.
Yet Mona's unpleasant nature, though sometimes annoying, gives her
character and the film weight. And there are occasional hints that
somewhere, way deep inside, there's a good person who just got
misguided.
</P>
<P>
   Giving the film dimension are relationships between Mona and two
other females whom she uses and abuses on her blinkered quest for
the sacred grail.
</P>
<P>
   One is her best friend, totally accepting Ruby (Joey Lauren
Adams of ``Big Daddy'' and ``Chasing Amy''). Since childhood, Ruby
has been Mona's unquestioning helper, seeing that Mona got to mall
openings on time or making sure her new gown is clean.
</P>
<P>
   The other is Vanessa (Hallie Kate Eisenberg of ``The Insider''
and ``Bicentennial Man''). Vanessa is Mona's daughter, but since
that would disqualify Mona from most beauty contests, Mona and Ruby
have always pretended Vanessa is Ruby's child. Even Vanessa doesn't
know the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway along, the movie refocuses from Mona's back-biting to
her refusal to acknowledge Vanessa's needs. We're pretty sure that
somewhere around crunch time, Mona will be forced to decide between
what she's always thought she wanted most and what her daughter
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Driver deserves some kind of crown for risking such an
unappealing role. And also for her outrageous ``talent''
performance in the big pageant: It packs in every stagey cliche
movement possible but remains scarily believable.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, as Ruby, supplies the niceness missing from Mona, in a
voice somewhere between Jennifer Tilly's and Ashley Judd's. As
Vanessa, Eisenberg is appealing and sassy without gagging us on
cute.
</P>
<P>
   The ending is nicely handled. It's satisfying without being
overly sentimental and without Mona doing something too out of
character.
</P>
<P>
   Field's direction can most charitably be described as
workmanlike. It doesn't add any pizazz to the proceedings, and has
no comedy timing, but at least it doesn't distract with forced
artiness. Bernstein's script, decidedly sensitive to women's issues
and point of view, would have benefited from a smoother touch.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has bite, although not enough to leave teeth marks. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Beautiful'' &QL; 
Starring: Minnie Driver, Joey Lauren Adams, Hallie Kate Eisenberg &QL; 
Director: Sally Field &QL; 
Screenwriter: Jon Bernstein &QL; 
Opening: today at area theaters &QL; 
Rating: PG-13, for language and thematic elements &QL; 
Running time: 113 minutes &QL; 
Grade: C &QL; 
X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
