<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GIRLFIGHT-FILM-REVIEW     09-28 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLFIGHT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIRLFIGHT': FLOATING LIKE A BUTTERFLY, STINGING LIKE A BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We first see Diana Guzman, the heroine of ``Girlfight,'' Karyn
Kusama's sweet and fierce directorial debut, through a crowd of
teen-agers stampeding through the halls of a Brooklyn high school.
She's leaning against a locker, head down, her black hair in
cornrows along her scalp. Then she slowly raises her eyes, throwing
out a glower as fearsome as Robert De Niro's in ``Raging Bull.''
It's a riveting, iconic moment, a glimpse into the soul of an
angry, proud young woman. The shot also introduces a powerful,
extraordinarily gifted young actress: Michelle Rodriguez. Remember
the name.
</P>
<P>
   The first few scenes, which Kusama directs with fluid
efficiency, establish the basic facts of Diana's temperament and
her circumstances. She moves through life in a coiled sulk, ready
at the slightest provocation to explode out of quiet truculence
into rage _ the kind of adolescent that education professionals
would label ``at risk.'' Actually, when Diana's mad, everyone else
is at risk, from a stuck-up schoolmate to her own father.
</P>
<P>
   She's quick with her fists, but her most potent weapon is that
stare. When Diana shows up at a run-down gym hoping to sign up for
boxing lessons, one of the trainers sneeringly asks if aerobics
wouldn't be more suitable. She turns her head slowly and freezes
him with a look of pure contempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I talking to you?'' she asks. Not many 18-year-old girls
can make a grown man cower like a beaten dog.
</P>
<P>
   Diana lives in the Red Hook housing projects with her father,
Sandro (Paul Calderon), and her younger brother, Tiny (Ray
Santiago), who dreams of becoming an artist. To Kusama's credit,
she doesn't load the family down with melodrama _ at least not
until the end of the movie, when a final confrontation between
Sandro and Diana tips over into sensationalism.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a pervasive feeling of dread and disconnection in
the scenes that take place around the table in the family's tiny
kitchen. Sandro is sullen and a bully, and yet Calderon's
performance is also full of sorrow and unexpressed tenderness.
Sandro is crushing his daughter _ forbidding her to box, walking
out in disgust when he sees her in the ring _ but also trying,
clumsily, to protect her. The movie's main locus of unresolved pain
is in this relationship, between two people who are so much alike
and yet fail utterly to reach each other.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it deals with the new phenomenon of women who box,
``Girlfight'' follows a fairly standard sports melodrama story
line: We see a lot of hard training, a few triumphs and setbacks,
all on the way to the big fight at the end. Diana is grudgingly
admitted to the macho subculture of amateur boxing. Her big break
comes when the state declares that amateur bouts and tournaments
must henceforth include men and women fighting each other. Although
in real life there has so far been only one known, officially
sanctioned fight between a man and a woman, the movie does not make
mixed-gender boxing seem outlandish. The plot takes some unexpected
_ if occasionally contrived _ turns. At the gym, Diana meets Adrian
(boxing-movie fans will note that this was also the name of the
love interest in the ``Rocky'' movies), a handsome young
featherweight played by Santiago Douglas. Their friendship soon
edges toward a very tender, believable romance (featuring a
wonderful first kiss), and before you know it, they're scheduled to
meet in the ring, an event foreshadowed by an early sparring
session, in which Diana rocks Adrian with a right cross to the
temple and then says, for the first time, ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this all a bit much? Maybe, but by the time the first bell
rings, you'll be in no mood to complain.
</P>
<P>
   Kusama's unassuming script and Patrick Cady's fine, gritty
cinematography keep ``Girlfight'' anchored in unpretentious
realism. Diana and her young male sparring partners and opponents
look good, but not too good; they flail with the energy of the
youthful amateurs they're meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girlfight'' sparkles with nice, small touches: a splendidly
punch-drunk rendition of ``The Star-Spangled Banner''; the
inspirational slogans, hand-lettered on cardboard, hung on the
walls of the gym; the sly banter between the wizened trainers.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting cast brings dimension to Diana's world.
Calderon's eyes and face suggest, more than the few lines he
speaks, the suffering behind his brutality. Douglas brings warmth
to his scenes with Rodriguez, and Jaime Tirelli _ as her gruff,
kindly trainer, Hector _ has the loose good humor that this role,
hardly the freshest in the fight-picture repertory, requires.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie belongs to Rodriguez. With her slightly crooked
nose and her glum, sensual mouth, she looks a little like Marlon
Brando in his smoldering prime, and she has some of his slow,
intense physicality. She doesn't so much transcend gender as
redefine it.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, athletes like Venus Williams, Rebecca Lobo and
Marion Jones have given the world a new, intoxicating image of
female beauty rooted in power and confidence as well as grace.
Rodriguez is the first movie star _ and she is, without question, a
movie star _ to embody this new ideal. Allow me one lame sports
metaphor (after all, this is a review of a boxing movie): she'll
knock you out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girlfight'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It includes profanity and some violent scenes.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `GIRLFIGHT'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Karyn Kusama; director of photography,
Patrick Cady; edited by Plummy Tucker; music by Theodore Shapiro;
production designer, Stephen Beatrice; produced by Sarah Green,
Martha Griffin and Maggie Renzi; released by Screen Gems. Running
time: 90 minutes. This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Michelle Rodriguez (Diana), Jaime Tirelli (Hector), Paul
Calderon (Sandro), Santiago Douglas (Adrian) and Ray Santiago
(Tiny).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
