<HEADER>
A5361 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NURSING-HOMES-0929-CO     09-28 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES-0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    OFFICIALS TELL OF LAX ENFORCEMENT OF NURSING HOME STANDARDS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years after headline-grabbing disclosures of
life-threatening conditions in many nursing homes, enforcement of
federal standards continues to be uneven and sometimes toothless, a
Senate hearing was told Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prevalence of poor care has not declined,'' said William
Scanlon, who led a U.S. General Accounting Office assessment of a
1998 nursing home initiative announced by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of new efforts, including more ``surprise''
inspections of the nation's 17,000 nursing homes, have yet to make
a difference, Scanlon told the Senate Special Committee on Aging in
describing the latest report card by the GAO, the investigative arm
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 Americans, most of them frail elders who cannot
speak for themselves, live in facilities where care is substandard,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials painted a picture of serious problems within
their nursing home inspection and enforcement systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes years for penalties to be imposed,'' said Claire C.
McCaskill, state auditor for Missouri, who recently completed a
scathing investigation that revealed some fines in Missouri were
unpaid after four years of repeat visits, grace periods and
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill compared the current system with a mother telling her
son to remove unsanitary food from his room and, then, after
several days without improvement, telling him that he would be
punished _ but not until years later.
</P>
<P>
   Her audit also turned up major problems in the Missouri
inspection system. The state's inspectors rated 34 nursing homes
``deficiency free,'' but when federal inspectors rechecked them,
they found 22 of the homes had ``substantiated'' complaints from
residents and their families. In one of these homes, federal
officials found 39 complaints and 17 violations involving ``actual
harm'' to residents.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill urged that states be allowed to focus more on consumer
complaints at nursing homes, instead of requiring a thorough annual
inspection of each facility, as is now mandated by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   That idea was seconded by Maryland's director of nursing home
surveyors, Carol Benner, who represented a national association of
more than 5,000 inspectors. The survey teams are stretched too
thin, Benner told the senators.
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal government is spending nearly $40 billion
this year on skilled nursing home care through Medicaid and
Medicare, only about $200 million _ a thimble full by comparison _
goes for enforcing standards laid out in a 1987 law, whose
standards have never been fully enforced.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA), which oversees
nursing homes, cited stepped up efforts during the past two years,
including more surveys conducted at night or on weekends, more
citations for substandard care, and more immediate sanctions for
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, HCFA now makes inspection results for specific homes
available on an Internet site at www.medicare.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, HCFA deputy administrator Michael Hash, conceded
shortcomings. A third of the states fail to investigate serious
complaints within 10 days as required and about the same number of
states fail to inspect every facility within the 15 months maximum
allowed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A HCFA fact sheet acknowledged, ``Currently, nursing homes can
delay paying a fine for years while they appeal the penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles E. Grassley, the chairman of the Senate Special
Committee on Aging who raised the profile of the plight of nursing
home residents with hearings in July of 1998, promised to keep the
spotlight on the problem as the next president takes over.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley, an Iowa Republican, said he was joining in a Clinton
effort to provide modest funding to increase staffing at some
nursing homes. The senator said he wants recommendations next year
for setting national standards for the ratio of nursing staff at
facilities, most of which have severe staff shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Such efforts hardly satisfy critics of the nursing home
industry, including the Texas Advocates for Nursing Home Reform.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Grassley timed for the hearing, Marie B. Wisdom,
president of the Austin-based group, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely weary of all of the so called 'attempts' by
Congress, presidents, (and) state legislators who say a lot but in
the long run, do nothing to create better environments in our
nation's nursing homes.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Senate Special Committee on Aging:
http://aging.senate.gov
</P>
<P>
   Health Care Financing Administration: http://www.hcfa.gov
</P>
<P>
   julia malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
