<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5367 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-EXORCIST29-COX     09-28 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-EXORCIST29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nothing shocking about additional `Exorcist' scenes
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't say Lucifer made them do it, but lucre might have
spurred director William Friedkin and writer-producer William Peter
Blatty to tinker with their supernatural classic, ``The Exorcist.''
Ranking second place at last week's national box office, based on a
limited screening, the 1973 flick opens wider today in a version
adding scenes and digital effects that actually reduce the
shocker's impact.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 minutes of new footage include one good addition. It's a
sequence showing distraught Hollywood star and single mom Chris
MacNeil (Ellen Burstyn) taking 12-year-old daughter Regan (Linda
Blair) for the first time to a doctor, after the girl's
increasingly weird behavior and complaints that her bed is shaking.
The scene adds to the movie's slow-building dread, before it
accelerates toward the head-spinning, soup-puking possession
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   There are also a couple of nice added grace notes that expand
Max Von Sydow's role as Father Merrin, the senior priest who aids
Father Karras (Jason Miller) in the climactic exorcism.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the bad stuff. We get a useless shot of the MacNeil
house in Georgetown, and a statue of the Virgin Mary before the
traditional opening in Iraq. The ``spider walk'' scene of Regan
coming downstairs upside down on all fours is included. It doesn't
work. Plus, the movie tacks on a more upbeat (and awkward) ending,
a scene of bantering between Father Dyer (the Rev. William
O'Malley) and Detective Kinderman (Lee J. Cobb).
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all are the digital additions _ superimposed flashes of
a demon face and the ancient statue first seen in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The demon face was supremely effective in the original
incarnation of the film because it flashed onscreen only two or
three times _ shock cuts that verged on subliminal, burning the
features into our minds. In the new version, the scamp shows up so
many times he's virtually a supporting character. (The movie's low
point comes when the face appears for a split second on the exhaust
hood of the MacNeil oven, apparently upholding the well-known
tradition of diabolical kitchen activity.)
</P>
<P>
   Do the tweaks and additions ruin the film? No. Its brooding,
ominous first half retains much of its power. And the over-the-top,
oozy shock effects in the second half still pack a wallop. But the
new version's amendments, for the most part, are distracting and
sometimes unintentionally funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Exorcist''
</P>
<P>
   Grade (for the 1973
</P>
<P>
   original): A-
</P>
<P>
   Grade (for the 2000
</P>
<P>
   remix): C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ellen Burstyn, Jason Miller and Linda Blair. Rated R
for strong profanity and disturbing images. 2 hours, 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A revamped classic, made scary in the worst ways.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
