<HEADER>
A5369 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-LOVESLABORS29-     09-28 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-LOVESLABORS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Branagh as Busby Berkeley to the Bard
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turning ``Love's Labour's Lost'' into a musical comedy may have
been a labor of love for Kenneth Branagh, but what's onscreen,
unfortunately, is often a labor to sit through.
</P>
<P>
   It must've looked good on paper. Take one of the Bard's least
performed works _ at best, the play is generally regarded a a kind
of warm-up for the infinitely superior ``Much Ado About Nothing'' _
and treat the plot the way those lavish MGM musicals from the '30s
treated their story lines. That is, as a lightweight necessary evil
around which to arrange all the sparkling musical numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Branagh gets into the frothy spirit from the start with an
old-fashioned credit sequence featuring cameo introductions of the
cast against a lush red-satin background. Next comes an artfully
reproduced newsreel purporting to catch us up on the news of
Navarre, a tiny kingdom that, like the rest of Europe circa 1939
(the movie's setting), is teetering on the brink of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Battle, however, is the last thing on the mind of the youthful
King of Navarre (Alessandro Nivola). So, he insists, is romance.
Rather, he and his three comrades _ Berowne (Branagh), Longaville
(Matthew Lillard) and Dumaine (Adrian Lester) _ have sworn to
devote the next three years to study and meditation. They will
``sleep little, eat and drink less and eschew all contact with
women.''
</P>
<P>
   His Majesty, however, has forgotten one little item on the royal
schedule: a visit by the Princess of France (Alicia Silvestone) and
her ladies in waiting _ Rosaline (Natascha McElhone), Maria (Carmen
Ejogo) and Katherine (Emily Mortimer). The oath goes out the window
as soon as the king and his pals meet the princess and her court.
</P>
<P>
   It's your basic boy-meets-girl plot, quadrupled by Shakespeare,
then dressed up by Branagh in Gershwin, Porter and Berlin as the
characters break off from speaking verse and break into song (and,
usually, dance).
</P>
<P>
   In theory, this tune-filled divertissement should be a delight.
In practice, well, let's just say it's marginally better than Burt
Reynolds' ``At Long Last Love'' or Woody Allen's ``Everyone Says I
Love You.''
</P>
<P>
   Branagh is trying to make an all-singing, all-dancing silk purse
out of a sow's ear, and the strain shows. Essentially, he's left
himself vulnerable on two fronts. We're faced with actors who, for
the most part, aren't entirely at home with Shakespeare. At the
same time, most of the cast _ with the exception of Lester, who can
dance, and Nathan Lane, who applies his vaudevillian skills to
Costad, one of the low-comedy clowns in the play's subplot _ can't
sing or dance (don't ask them). The movie comes off as a kind of
jocular amateur theatrical, neither fish nor fowl.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there aren't some inspired moments _ a Branagh
monologue that melts into Berlin's ``Cheek to Cheek'' shows us what
the director apparently had in mind. But that synergy happens all
too rarely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love's Labour's Lost''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kenneth Branagh, Alicia Silverstone and Nathan Lane.
Directed by Branagh. Rated PG for mild sexual themes. 1 hour, 33
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A lost cause, methinks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
