<P>
   SALLY FIELD-INTERVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Sally Field appears to be eager to please. She's
sitting on the edge of a sofa in a cavernous suite in a Dallas
hotel, leaning into every question and comment as she discusses
``Beautiful,'' her feature-directing debut. She could be the
opposite of Mona, the ambitious beauty queen played by Minnie
Driver in the movie. Field is affable; Mona is, well, kind of hard
to take. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TITANS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In this football melodrama set in Virginia during a
team's first season of school desegregation, Denzel Washington
plays an African-American coach trying to integrate black and white
players who want nothing to do with one another. In other words,
sanctimony and sentimentality battle it out for two hours before
finally declaring a draw. (The only loser is the audience.) By
CHRISTOPHER KELLY. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BEAUTIFUL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Minnie Driver has made a career of playing likable,
plucky women, in movies as diverse as 1995's ``Circle of Friends''
and this year's ``Return to Me.'' Actors get bored, though, and
it's easy to understand their attempts to stretch or to resist
being pigeonholed by playing against type. But in ``Beautiful,''
Driver overdoes it as Mona, a perpetual beauty-pageant contestant
whose attractive exterior masks a self-absorbed and misanthropic
interior. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GIRLFIGHT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ What makes ``Girlfight'' such a chore to watch is that
it isn't content to wallow in its own shamelessness; indeed, anyone
who has gorged on such late-night USA Network classics as ``The
Next Karate Kid'' (the movie Hilary Swank made before ``Boys Don't
Cry'') or the Helen Hunt TV movie ``Quarterback Princess,'' can
only sit back and wonder: Does the director really expect us to
take this stuff seriously? By CHRISTOPHER KELLY. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
