<HEADER>
A5374 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS28-     09-28 3091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adventures in Wild California''
</P>
<P>
   An Imax film.
</P>
<P>
   Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Review: You've got to hand it to the makers of the Imax movie
``Adventures in Wild California.'' Their movie will keep kids
slack-mouthed with excitement as they watch the extreme-sport
antics of athletic daredevils: tree climbers, snowboarders, skiers
and surfers. (SM) 40 minutes. Through March 4. Fernbank Museum of
Natural History, 767 Clifton Road N.E. 404-929-6400.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost Famous''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Patrick Fugit, Billy Crudup and Kate Hudson. R
(profanity, sexual situations, substance abuse)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Cameron Crowe's (``Jerry Maguire'') exuberant and
knowing movie grabs the soul of rock 'n' roll and blissfully
re-creates the early '70s, a time poised between one water sign
(the Age of Aquarius) and another (Watergate). Drawing on his own
experiences, Crowe gives us a 15-year-old rock fan (Patrick Fugit)
who, in 1973, convinces Rolling Stone magazine to send him on the
road with an emerging group called Stillwater. He learns about sex,
drugs, rock 'n' roll and stomach pumps. He also learns why the
music matters _ and always will matter. (ERG)2 hours. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Bait''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jamie Foxx, David Morse and Kimberly Elise.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R (profanity, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Review: May not hook you completely, but give it a chance.
Underneath the usual action-comedy trappings is an entertaining
and, on occasion, clever movie. Jamie Foxx stars as a small-time
crook who, without his knowledge, is released from jail with a
tracking device planted on him. The scheme, hatched by some federal
agents, is to lure a high-tech criminal out of hiding. A bit of
``The Truman Show'' emerges as the agents watching Foxx come to
care about him. Foxx, who provides the box-office bait, delivers a
fresh and charming performance reminiscent of early Eddie Murphy.
(ERG) 1 hour, 50 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Minnie Driver. Rated PG-13 (profanity and adult themes)
</P>
<P>
   Review: It isn't. Nor is it entertaining, incisive, amusing or
instructive. Minnie Driver stars as a woman who makes up for her
neglected childhood by competing in beauty pageants _ even if that
means handing over her young daughter (Hallie Kate Eisenberg, the
brat _ er, tyke _ in those ubiquitous Pepsi commercials) to her
best friend (Joey Lauren Adams) to raise as her own. Directed by
Sally Field, it seems that all the intelligence and craft in her
acting has deserted in her directing. (ERG) At metro theaters. 1
hour, 52 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``Bless the Child''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kim Basinger and Jimmy Smits.
</P>
<P>
   R (violence, drug content, brief profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: A junky would-be religious thriller about a little girl
with special powers. The latest cinematic struggle of good vs.
evil, the film swipes everything it can from ``The Omen,'' ``The
Exorcist,'' ``End of Days,'' ``Stigmata'' and other
Catholic/satanic epics, all while managing to bore the pants off
you. (SM)1 hour, 50 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring It On''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kirsten Dunst. PG-13
</P>
<P>
   (sex-related material, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Kirsten Dunst stars in a comedy that pits two rival high
schools' cheerleading squads in a we-hate-you showdown at the
national cheerleading championships. Pretty much all the jokes fall
flat. Actually, the funniest bit involves projectile vomiting. And
what does that say about this movie? (BL)
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 33 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cell''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jennifer Lopez, Vince Vaughn and Vincent D'Onofrio.
</P>
<P>
   R (violence, language, nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Don't get trapped in this one. Jennifer Lopez plays an
intrepid child therapist who, through an experimental sci-fi
technique, can enter the minds of others. A detective (Vince
Vaughn) asks her to stroll through the brain of a serial killer
(Vincent D'Onofrio) so he can find where he's stashed his latest
victim. Visually provocative, narratively impaired, it's like ``The
Silence of the Lambs'' without the compelling characters. (ERG) 1
hour, 52 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Coyote Ugly''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Piper Perabo, Adam Garcia, Maria Bello and
</P>
<P>
   John Goodman. PG-13 (sensuality)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Dog-face hideous. The come-on is five hot chicks serving
liquor in a rowdy fun-time saloon (they splash whiskey across the
bar and set it afire; they douse each others' T-shirts with big
pitchers of water). But it's really the slapdash story of a young
waif, a struggling songwriter aching for stardom in New York City.
``Coyote'' is profoundly stupid and earnestly inept at conveying a
story. (BL) 1 hour, 34 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crew''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Richard Dreyfuss and Burt Reynolds. PG-13
</P>
<P>
   (sexual content, violence, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: It stereotypes Jews and Hispanics and belittles the
group it's supposed to be celebrating, retirement-age Americans.
Even worse, the movie's not even funny. The stars are old mafia
wiseguys trying to fight a rent increase in their Miami hotel. Lame
plot twists and accidents ensue. (SM) 1 hour, 28 minutes. F
</P>
<P>
   ``Croupier''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Clive Owen and Alex Kingston. Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Review: This 1998 film involves a struggling author who takes a
job at a casino running a roulette wheel to look for writing
inspiration. Soon he's convinced to join a robbery scheme.
``Croupier'' has more on its mind than danger and plot twists. It's
a fascinating, hard-edged portrait of a man who swears he doesn't
gamble. (SM) 1 hour, 31 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Days''
</P>
<P>
   A documentary directed by Marc Singer. Unrated (but there are
adult themes) Review: Here's the real urban-legends movie worth
checking out. And there's not a slasher in sight. Marc Singer spent
two years chronicling the daily routines of some homeless people
who live underground in an Amtrak tunnel on Manhattan's West Side.
The documentary can be monotonous, but it's a fascinating record of
how these people create a community out of society's discards
(themselves included). (ERG) 1 hour, 24 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Duets''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Gwyneth Paltrow, Andre Braugher and Huey Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R (profanity, brief sex)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Off-key. Gwyneth Paltrow, Andre Braugher and Huey Lewis
are among six characters, each caught up in a personal drama,
headed for a big karaoke contest in Omaha. Sort of like a ``Love
Boat'' episode, only longer. And why, you might wonder, is an
A-list Oscar winner appearing in a dismal little movie about
karaoke? Check out the name of the director/producer. It's Bruce
Paltrow, as in father of ... (ERG)1 hour, 53 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``The Exorcist''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ellen Burstyn, Jason Miller and Linda Blair. Rated R
(strong profanity and disturbing images)
</P>
<P>
   Review: You can't say Lucifer made them do it, but lucre might
have spurred director William Friedkin and writer-producer William
Peter Blatty to tinker with their supernatural 1973 classic (in my
book, the original gets a grade of A-). The 11 minutes of new
footage include one good addition (an early doctor visit) and a few
nice grace notes expanding Max Von Sydow's priest role. But at its
worst are new multiple superimposed flashes of a demon face (on a
stove vent, no less). It doesn't ruin the film, but new stuff is
sometimes distracting. (SM) 2 hours, 12 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Girlfight''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michelle Rodriguez and Santiago Douglas. Rated R
(profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Grand jury prize winner at Sundance, it's a mix of clean
storytelling, tough edge and gritty urban texture. In
writer-director Karyn Kusama's rousing debut, a trigger-tempered
teen girl, only one fistfight away from getting expelled from
school, decides to channel her anger into boxing lessons at the
gym. It's a crowdpleaser that never sacrifices its brain to the
sucker-punch tricks of so many Hollywood films. (SM) 1 hour, 50
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Gladiator''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Russell Crowe.
</P>
<P>
   R (extreme violence, perverse sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Two thousand _ or, if you want to add computer effects,
200,000 _ thumbs up for Ridley Scott's spectacle starring Russell
Crowe as a Roman general, who returns to the Colosseum to take
revenge on the odious Emperor Commodus (Joaquin Phoenix). The
battles staged before the mob of mindless ancient Romans are the
film's centerpieces, but its brave heart (so to speak) is Crowe.
(ERG) 2 hours, 33 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollow Man''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Bacon and Elisabeth Shue.
</P>
<P>
   R (graphic violence, nudity, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: A high-tech fusion of ``The Invisible Man'' and ``Dr.
Jekyll and Mr. Hyde,'' it lets director Paul Verhoeven (``Starship
Troopers,'' ``Total Recall'') show off some gruesome,
state-of-the-art computer effects and exercise his gleeful brand of
brutal action. But his filmmaking energy is wasted on a weak script
and characters so two-dimensional, they're virtually all
transparent. (SM) 1 hour, 54 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life and Times of Hank Greenberg''
</P>
<P>
   A documentary about baseball player Hank Greenberg. Not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Review: Aviva Kempner's documentary is a rare film indeed _ a
celebration of Hank Greenberg, a pro baseball player in the 1930s
and '40s who became the first Jewish sports superstar. Greenberg
broke records, was voted most valuable player twice and led his
team, the Detroit Tigers, to two World Series _ even as he was
being subjected to anti-Semitic baiting by fans, rivals and,
sometimes, his own teammates. (ERG)1 hour, 35 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Love's Labour's Lost''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kenneth Branagh, Alicia Silverstone and Nathan Lane.
Rated PG
</P>
<P>
   Review: A lost cause, methinks. Kenneth Branagh's song-and-dance
version of Shakespeare's play about a king and his comrades whose
monastic oath to embrace study and eschew romance is up-ended by
the arrival of the Princess of France and her court must've looked
good on paper. The cast, led by Branagh and Alicia Silverstone,
mostly can't sing or dance and, with a few exceptions, can't handle
the verse either. (ERG) 1 hour, 33 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Renee Zellweger, Morgan Freeman, Chris Rock and Greg
Kinnear. Rated R (violence, language)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Renee Zellweger's otherworldly sweetness is used to
great effect in ``Nurse Betty,'' a dark fantasy. Like a collision
between ``Being There,'' ``The Wizard of Oz'' and early Coen
brothers, you've seen it before, but you've never seen anything
quite like this. Zellweger plays a waitress nurse in search of her
long-lost love, a soap opera character named Dr. David Ravell, and
steals a Buick to find him. Two problems. The Buick is full of
drugs, and hitmen Charlie (Morgan Freeman) and Wesley (Chris Rock)
are soon on her trail. (ERG) 1 hour, 48 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutty Professor 2: The Klumps''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Eddie Murphy and Janet Jackson. PG-13 (crude humor and
sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Review: The big problem in ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'' is
the nutty professor. This sequel to the 1996 hit seems designed for
video: You want to fast-forward through all the parts focused on
tubby scientist Sherman (Eddie Murphy) so you can get back to the
rest of his family (played by Murphy, Murphy, Murphy and Murphy,
plus a fat kidCQ all the Murphy references). Murphy is
jaw-droppingly funny. But the script is simply not nutty enough.
(SM) 1 hour, 45 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Original Kings of Comedy''
</P>
<P>
   Featuring Steve Harvey, Cedric the Entertainer, D.L. Hughley and
Bernie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   R (language, sex-related humor)
</P>
<P>
   Review: There's nothing that original. It's just a lot of funny
stuff knocked out by four sharp stand-up comics. And under Spike
Lee's direction, it's one of the liveliest concert films in years.
(SM) 1 hour, 57 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perfect Storm''
</P>
<P>
   Starring George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg and Diane Lane. PG-13
(profanity, scenes of peril)
</P>
<P>
   Review: The fishermen of the Andrea Gail take a pounding, and so
does the audience in the latest movie directed by Wolfgang
Petersen. Based on Sebastian Junger's best seller, it re-creates
the collision of three weather systems in the fall of 1991 _ and
the battle of men (George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg) and women (Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio) trying to survive the monstrous sea. (SM) 2
hours, 15 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Personals''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Malik Yoba, Stacey Dash and Sheryl Lee Ralph. Unrated
(contains adult themes, profanity).
</P>
<P>
   Part of BlackFilmFestAmerica's independent movie tour.
</P>
<P>
   Review: A sometimes witty, but thoroughly slow-going
relationship comedy. Malik Yoba (TV's ``New York Undercover'')
plays Keith, a New York journalist juggling a few too many personal
items. Like two girlfriends, a boss who wants to fire him, and
friends who see all too clearly through Keith's ``I'm OK'' veneer.
His saving grace may be his final assignment: date 30 women in 30
days for an article about the personal ads. (BL)
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 32 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember The Titans''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Denzel Washington. Rated PG (profanity, mild violence
and adult themes)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Go Titans! This filmed-in-Atlanta crowd-pleaser with a
conscience is loosely based on a true story from the civil rights
era. In 1971, the football players at a newly-integrated high
school in Alexandria, Va., learn to come together as a team. Denzel
Washington shines as the team's new coach. So do Will Patton as his
passed-over assistant and Kip Pardue, Wood Harris and Ryan Hurst as
players. True, there's not much subtle here, but as a
good-for-you-movie disguised as a feel-good flick, it's very
effective. (ERG) 1 hour, 53 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Replacements''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Keanu Reeves and Gene Hackman.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (some crude sexual humor, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: It's got it all. Bone-crunching football plays.
Boneheaded comedy (the team kicker, a wire-thin Welsh soccer
player, puffs cigs while booting field goals). And a dumb-as-dirt
pep squad whose sideline lap-dance cheers cause the opposition to
fumble a lot. Keanu Reeves and Gene Hackman star in this dumb romp
about adult scabs taking over for striking pro players. (BL) 1
hour, 58 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Scary Movie''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Anna Faris, Jon Abrahams, Shawn Wayans and Marlon
Wayans. Rated R (strong crude sexual humor, profanity, drug use,
violence)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Propped up by the Wayans brothers _ Keenen
(writer/director), Shawn (writer/actor) and Marlon (writer/actor);
and they are a talented bunch _ ``Scary Movie'' is a parody of teen
horror flicks.(BL) 1 hour, 28 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Clint Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones, James Garner and
Donald Sutherland. PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Review: The right stuff. Geezer chic gets a grand showcase in
Clint Eastwood's shamelessly crowd-pleasing comedy-thriller. When a
decrepit Russian satellite threatens to crash to Earth, four aging
astronauts who were axed from the NASA program in the '50s are
summoned into service to repair the thing. The best part of the
film is watching these veterans play off each other like seasoned
pros on the Senior Tour. (ERG) 2 hours, 15 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn It Up''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Pras, Ja Rule, Vondie Curtis-Hall. Rated R
</P>
<P>
   (strong violence, language, some drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Based on ``Ghetto Supastar,'' both the CD and
young-adult novel by hip-hop star Pras (aka the Fugees' Prakerzel
Michel), ``Turn It Up'' is a flashy, loud urban thriller that wants
to critique the guns-and-bullets world of thug life, while at the
same time reveling in its perks. It's a cautionary tale that isn't
quite sure what it wants to caution the audience about. (SM) 1
hour, 23 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Urban Legends: Final Cut''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jennifer Morrison and Matthew Davis. Rated R (violence,
gore, language, some sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Please let it be final. University film students get
whacked in this slasher film with loose connections to ``Urban
Legend.'' The characters are all interchangeably gorgeous and
equally shallow. First-time director John Ottman manages to crank
some suspense out of chase scenes, but he can't bring life to a
movie formula that is dead dead dead. (SM) 1 hour, 34 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Watcher''
</P>
<P>
   Starring James Spader, Keanu Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R (violence, language)
</P>
<P>
   Review: There's a resonant 21st-century theme in ``The
Watcher,'' an otherwise standard serial-killer thriller. A sicko
named Griffin (Keanu Reeves) stalks pretty women and uses a burnt
out detective, named Campbell (James Spader), as his main pawn.
Debut director Joe Charbanic manages to wring some suspense out of
stock situations. Too often, though, he falls back on cliches,
including heavy breathing on the soundtrack, and an arty reliance
on blurry slo-mo flashbacks. (SM)1 hour, 33 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way of the Gun''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ryan Phillippe, Benicio Del Toro
</P>
<P>
   and Juliette Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R (violence, gore, language, some sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Review: An Oscar winner for his ``Usual Suspects'' screenplay,
Christopher McQuarrie makes a sluggishly paced directing debut in
the tale of a couple of lowlifes named Parker (Ryan Phillippe) and
Longbaugh (Benicio Del Toro). Though it's not exactly original, the
movie is so intent on an air of existential grunge, it becomes
suffocating and pretentious. (SM) 2 hours. D
</P>
<P>
   ``What Lies Beneath''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michelle Pfeiffer and Harrison Ford. PG-13 (terror,
violence, sensuality, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Review: What lies beneath this film is a script that could have
come from a 1970s TV movie. Narratively old-fashioned, but boosted
by star performances from Michelle Pfeiffer and Harrison Ford and
suspenseful direction, it's a lovingly crafted throwback to
haunted-house movies that relied more on suggestion and slowly
building creepiness than great effects. (SM) 2 hours, 10 minutes.
B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Woman on Top''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Penelope Cruz and Murilo Benicio.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R (some strong sexuality, language)
</P>
<P>
   Review: Despite some tasty ingredients, it's a screen confection
that never quite gels. Mix together the stories of Gabriel Garcia
Marquez, ``Like Water for Chocolate,'' a few Food Network series
and lots of dreamy samba and you'll get the recipe. Call it Magic
Realism Lite. Though it's packed with cooking scenes and shots of
steaming food, the movie's spiciest ingredient _ and the main
reason to see it _ is Spanish actress Penelope Cruz. (SM) 1 hour,
33 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
