<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACETRACKS-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK RACETRACKS UNDER INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DENNIS YUSKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ A state attorney general's
investigation into the Saratoga Race Course and the state's two
other thoroughbred racetracks run by the New York Racing
Association is focusing on mutuel clerks who may have knowingly
laundered money for organized crime, a source close to the
investigation said.
</P>
<P>
   The source also said that a separate federal investigation has
been launched by the Internal Revenue Service, but that could not
be immediately confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators raided the three NYRA tracks early Tuesday,
seizing about 300 boxes of financial records.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Violette, a spokesman for Attorney General Eliot Spitzer's
office, said an ``ongoing investigation'' conducted by the office's
Organized Crime Task Force prompted the morning sweeps of Belmont
Park in Elmont; Aqueduct Racetrack in Queens; and Saratoga Race
Course, from which State Police and other law enforcement
authorities removed boxes of cashed mutuel tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the investigation said that it focuses in part
on the mutuel clerks who work the tracks' betting windows and may
have knowingly exchanged marked money involved in past crimes for
``clean'' money collected at the windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``NYRA as a corporation is not a target of the investigation. At
the request of the state, we can't comment further,'' said NYRA
spokesman Glen Mathes.
</P>
<P>
   The case is not targeting specific clerks, but a person close to
the investigation suspects ``there may be some dirty clerks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next process, we'll be able to eliminate scores of
window tellers and start focusing in on a select handful,'' said
the source, who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   NYRA President Terry Meyocks said the organization plans to
cooperate fully with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always looking to protect the integrity of the industry
and NYRA. Integrity is our major goal. We won't let the actions of
anybody get in the way of that,'' Meyocks said.
</P>
<P>
   The raids targeted financial documents and records, Violette
said. ``We now begin the process of sifting through them, analyzing
them and putting together a paper trail.''
</P>
<P>
   He would neither confirm nor deny whether they are investigating
the possibility of a conspiracy involving money laundering, but
stated that the main duty of the office's Organized Crime Task
Force was to get ``involved in tracking down and halting crimes
that are undertaken by organized criminals.'' The raids were the
result of a ``months-long'' investigation, Violette said. No one
was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The State Police executed search warrants at the three tracks
and NYRA cooperated fully,'' Mathes said.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, the State Police raided the main section of the
grandstand at Saratoga Race Course and removed boxes of cashed
mutuel tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they conducted the three sweeps
simultaneously on Tuesday, a dark day for racing, so they wouldn't
interrupt business at Belmont Park, which started racing after the
Saratoga meet ended Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   While the sweeps went smoothly at Saratoga and Aqueduct, the
vaults at Belmont that authorities needed to access were
time-locked with set devices that did not unlock again until
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officers who made the Belmont raid were forced to guard the
vault overnight until its opening early Wednesday, according to
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   State Police from the Albany area, White Plains and New York
City were involved in the raids, Violette said.
</P>
<P>
   NYRA employs up to 500 mutuel clerks at Saratoga Race Course,
Mathes said. Their duty it is to accept wagers and collect money.
</P>
<P>
   NYRA is a private not-for-profit company. It has a franchise to
manage the state's three tracks through 2007.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
