<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN     09-28 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A NIGHT OF COMPETING ASPIRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sports of the Times) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Some Olympic days are more defining than
others. Thursday was one of those days _ and one of those nights _
of clarity that brings fleeting insight into the essence of the
Olympic spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Not of the spirit that the International Olympic Committee
shamelessly sells and parcels out. Not of the spirit that compels
some athletes to load up with drugs. This was a glimpse into the
spirit of competition, of what the Australians call the ``fair
go.'' This is what you don't see when watching the television
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   This was the evening of Day 14, a night when Marion Jones won
her second gold medal, a night when Konstantinos Kenteris became
the first Greek man to win a gold in a running event, the 200
meters, since 1896, a night when Cuba's men broke the American
domination in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   Jones cruised home in the 200 with the fastest time in the world
this year, 21.84 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The silver medalist, Pauline Davis-Thompson of the Bahamas, was
so into the moment that she began crying tears of joy as soon as
she realized that she had finished second. When she stepped up to
get her medal, her mind was exploding with the names and faces of
all the people who helped get her there.
</P>
<P>
   This was a night when you learned a little more about Jones,
whose husband, C.J. Hunter, is involved in a controversy concerning
his failed tests for a performance-enhancing drug.
</P>
<P>
   Jones puts on the good public face and seems authentic.
</P>
<P>
   When the stadium announcer made a mistake before the 200-meter
final and introduced her as an athlete from the Bahamas, Jones
shrugged her shoulders and smiled. Then she went out and beat
everyone by 13 feet. She ran one race and the rest of the field ran
another.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, someone asked Jones if, in light of the news about
Hunter, she was afraid people might think she wasn't clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't have that fear,'' she said evenly. ``The people
that know me, the people that support me, train with me and coach
me, know that I'm a clean athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone else asked about the source of her focus, her ability to
block out distractions. She said her goals give her the focus she
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to prove to myself that it's possible to walk away
from Sydney with five gold medals,'' she said. ``This has been a
dream of mine for a lot of years, and so to let one event ruin your
life, as dramatic as it might be, that wouldn't be worth it at all.
All the days my mother would travel four or five hours to take me
to a track. To let one event ruin it _ no way. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   During the interviews, Jones accepted good-natured teasing and
gave it back.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis-Thompson said, in one of her extended answers, ``I'm
outspoken,'' Jones grabbed the microphone and said with mock
surprise, ``Noooo!''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the subject of the women's 400-meter relay came up,
Davis-Thompson said: ``We are still the underdogs and we love being
in that spot. It's going to make our victory just a little bit
sweeter, Marion.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she added: ``I know you have a little bit of Caribbean
blood in you, too, Marion'' _ alluding to Jones' mother's Belizean
heritage _ ``so you're almost like one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The room broke up and Jones lowered her head and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Grace and ease.
</P>
<P>
   Davis-Thompson was asked to compare Jones with the late Florence
Griffith-Joyner, since she had run against both of them. ``They're
both very dominant,'' she said. ``Marion seems more down to
earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the women's 200, I had been to the tennis site to
listen to Serena and Venus talk about their gold medal performance
in doubles. Serena spoke of walking around and watching the
performances of other great athletes, and how it enabled her to see
herself, and her accomplishments, in a larger context.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that context is what makes this more than a mere
track meet, more than a tennis tournament where athletes are
sequestered in their own worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just getting a chance to meet fellow American athletes who I
have never met and probably will never meet again, from rowers to
judo experts, from everyone,'' she said. ``Even the big stars, the
men's basketball team, the women's basketball team. Venus, Serena,
Monica, Lindsay. To see how humble they were really puts this whole
thing in perspective.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the news conference broke up, the other sprinters stayed
and chatted. Jones sprang up, and the soft smile gave way to an
all-business gaze. In an instant she was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what Days 15 to 18 hold.
</P>
<P>
   Day 14, off camera, was pretty impressive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
