<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of  &UR; FRIDAY &LR; , Sept.
29.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOMA-2000 (New York) _ The Museum of Modern Art has got to be in
an enough-already frame of mind. Te staff has just come through a
grueling strike. Construction on a new wing has reduced the
sculpture garden to rubble. Now all hands are on deck for ``Open
Ends,'' the third and final leg of ``MoMA2000,'' the
millennium-marking group show that has taken up every inch of
gallery space for the last year. By Holland Carter.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-VANCOUVER (Vancouver, British Columbia) _ Conspire to
arrive by ship. Like Naples, like New York and Cape Town, Vancouver
looks its best from the water, its shiny glass towers rising like
Xanadu against a backdrop of indigo peaks whose foothills dip their
toes in the harbor. Clean and leafy, blessed with a temperate
climate marred only by rainy winters, a model of municipal
etiquette, Vancouver seems to have it all. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NONPROFIT-THEATER (New York) _ A nonprofit theater's season
planning is a craft all its own, one of mundane logistical
maneuvering as well as lofty creative ambition; of sleepless-night
angst and pride-swelling triumph; of big-picture matters like
building audiences and details as precise as choosing a hat. It's a
balancing act of egos, schedules, budgets and creative visions. By
Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   BIOGRAPHY-THEATER (New York) _ The odds are you have never heard
of the star of ``Lifegame,'' the piquant, oddly touching new
offering from the ever-resourceful Improbable Theater. This latest
work from the young British troupe that turned Scotch tape into
ectoplasm in ``70 Hill Lane,'' the real-life haunted-house drama
that was their maiden outing in New York, is now turning instant
biography into instant, multiform theater. By Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSKIN-CENTENARY (New York) _ Much has been made of John Ruskin
(1819-1900) this year. It is the centenary of the death of this
artist, art and architectural critic extraordinaire, social
reformer, polymath lecturer, first official professor of art in
England (at Oxford University) and an admirer of little girls. The
Morgan Library has mounted its own show of Ruskiniana, a
biographical assemblage of 133 objects: letters, manuscripts,
photographs, drawings, paintings and artifacts. They were mined
entirely from the Morgan's own Ruskin collection, proclaimed by the
library to be one of the world's most comprehensive. By Grace
Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GIRLFIGHT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Girlfight,'' Karyn Kusama's
sweet and fierce directorial debut, deals with the new phenomenon
of women who box by following a fairly standard sports melodrama
story line: We see a lot of hard training, a few triumphs and
setbacks, all on the way to the big fight at the end. Reviewed by
A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   FAITHLESS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Here's an unsettling thought:
The hardest lessons we learn in life (and maybe the only lessons we
truly absorb) are those learned too late. It is precisely this
sense of nagging regret and the compulsion to comb obsessively over
decisions we can't undo that haunts the characters in Liv Ullmann's
morose and profound film, ``Faithless.'' Reviewed by Stephen
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   AT-THE-MOVIES (Hollywood) _ News of the silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-IN-BRIEF (Undated) _ Capsule reviews by New York Times
critics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND (Undated) _ Watching ``Big Brother'' has been as
exciting as watching vegetables grow. More precisely, it has been
as exciting as watching people put together a jigsaw puzzle, one of
the many inane tasks assigned to the 10 contestants who agreed to
live in a house for three months with cameras on them 24 hours a
day. You may be wondering why producers would even imagine that
watching people set up dominoes or ride a stationary bike would
create dynamic television, but it turns out that such stupid human
tricks are not to blame for the show's failure. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE-ART (Undated) _ A major gift has transformed the
University of Oklahoma into a repository of Impressionist and
