<HEADER>
A5386 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-LISTSERVE29     09-28 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-LISTSERVE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The day the typing died for a faceless e-community
 &HT;    By Jerry Gentry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Internet listserv creates an e-community of screen-readers
and typers, all sharing an interest: a political cause, a music
group or perhaps an antique car of which only 200 exist.
</P>
<P>
   The relationships consist entirely of electronically delivered
words. Faces are rarely seen, voices rarely heard. So what happens
when someone on the list dies?
</P>
<P>
   I am a member of a listserv for fans of the University of
Louisville. We e-mail to one address our complaints, cheers or
exasperations, and the messages are automatically sent to all on
the list. Some want the coach replaced; some want him retained. We
win, and we celebrate; we lose, and we sulk _ together, by reading
each other's words. We don't slouch out of an arena together or
smack high-fives; we type.
</P>
<P>
   One list member, a Louisville lawyer named Les Terry, sent
witty, concise and courteous messages. I particularly enjoyed his
lighthearted reports on alumni trips to road games. When the list
rhetoric overheated, he sent calm, rational messages that deflated
the hype. His e-mails were among the few that I clicked on eagerly.
His words reminded me of a favorite uncle who told funny stories
and hugged with big strong arms. He signed off with a simple
``Regards,'' a small touch that communicated respect and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the list received an e-mail with the ominous subject
heading, ``Listmember Les Terry.'' Like a phone ringing deep into
the night, the heading signaled bad news. Sure enough, the e-mail
from someone who knew Les said he had died of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, I sensed a somber mood on the list, even though ``on the
list'' meant only reading messages on my computer in my office. I,
a solitary person reading pixels, experienced a shared loss. The
Louisville football team had just trounced its opponent, but not
one single e-mail celebrated the victory. All of us, apparently,
looked at our screens and knew something was missing.
</P>
<P>
   I knew Les only through typed words, but I felt sad. It was a
strange sadness, over the loss of a personality attached to no
person with whom I was physically familiar. Yet that personality
felt vivid to me. When someone we know dies, for a while, we
instinctively expect that person to walk in the room.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing disappointment makes the loss more real. I began
expecting e-mails that didn't come.
</P>
<P>
   Many listmembers sent condolences, and several, including me,
said how much Les will be missed and speculated on what a
delightful man he must have been. Les's family members were
forwarded all our e-mails, and they responded that our impressions
of Les were correct. How remarkable is human language. Via his
words alone, his presence had passed electronically, accurately,
through wires onto a screen and into my heart.
</P>
<P>
   Through words flow one's character, one's demeanor. Because of
Les's words, his legacy is that of a warm, decent, jovial person.
Sports blather and hot-headed harangues do not last; respectful
dialogue and reasonable reflection do. Words flicker with our very
souls.
</P>
<P>
   Regards.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Gentry, author of ``Grady Baby: A Year in the Life of
Atlanta's Grady Hospital,'' teaches English composition at Mercer
University and lives in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in The Atlanta Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
