<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SAIL-NYT &LR;      09-28 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN DUOS CAPTURE GOLD OVER U.S. CREWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERB McCORMICK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ In sight of the famous waterside Opera House
and the Olympic rings emblazoned across the Sydney Harbor Bridge,
the U.S. crews of J.J. Isler and Pease Glaser, and Paul Foerster
and Bob Merrick, raced to silver medals Thursday afternoon in the
waning days of the Olympic regatta.
</P>
<P>
   Competing in the women's and men's divisions of the
double-handed 470 dinghy, the twin silvers represented the best
results for the U.S. sailing team in two Olympiads. But if their
performance was exhilarating for the Americans, the day was
positively euphoric for the home team, which delivered the greatest
day ever by an Australian Olympic sailing squad.
</P>
<P>
   With helicopters wheeling overhead, dozens of spectator boats
cordoned off alongside the race course, and large crowds craning
seaward from shoreline vantage points, the Australian duos of Tom
King and Mark Turnbull, and Jenny Armstrong and Belinda Stowell,
capped off strong, consistent regattas to capture the respective
470 gold medals. It had been 28 years since Australia's last
sailing gold.
</P>
<P>
   Both U.S. pairs started the day off with golden possibilities,
but their destinies were not entirely in their own hands. Isler and
Glaser, in third place after 10 races, were nine points behind the
Australians. Theoretically, a race victory coupled with a poor
finish by the Australians could propel them to first. But, in the
points, a bad race could have dropped the U.S. sailors from medal
contention.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Foerster and Merrick began the day in second, five
points behind the Australians. A race victory coupled with an
Australian finish of sixth or worse would have earned the Americans
the gold.
</P>
<P>
   The women's race went off first. The American boat got off to an
inauspicious beginning. `'The breeze came in very quickly,'' Isler
said, ``and we didn't get off the line very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the race, Isler and Glaser were mired in ninth
place and sailing astern of the Australians, Israelis and
Ukrainians, who were directly in their path to the medal podium. It
appeared that the U.S. pair was out of the running. But on the
second-to-last downwind leg, Isler noticed a stream of wind pulsing
off Bradley's Head, a promontory lined with spectators. Among them
was her husband, Peter, like his wife a veteran of the America's
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of boats passed us by going really close to the
headland and getting a big puff,'' Isler said. She made a mental
note of exactly where.
</P>
<P>
   It paid off on the final leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that last run, we saw the same kind of puff developing, so
we kind of reached up for it,'' Isler said, ``and the next thing we
knew we were crossing the Israelis.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Isler, running along the coastline, noticed it, too.
``There was a sweet spot right at the point, and they also got a
nice ride from a powerboat wake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They were also passing several boats, and their sixth-place
finish in the race _ the Aussies, to raucous cheers from the Manly
Ferry, were first _ propelled the Americans to the silver medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy,'' J.J. Isler said. ``Our best international
finish coming into this regatta was a seventh. This is all we could
ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the women's team, the men's team, featuring Foerster, a
silver medalist in 1992, and Merrick, came into the Olympics as one
of the favorites. And on the final day, sailing a near-flawless
race, they almost earned the top prize. ``We got a good start,''
Merrick said. ``We were able to go exactly where we wanted to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Isler and Glaser, the men realized that the point off
Bradley's Head was paying huge dividends, and sailed directly for
it. They rounded the top mark in first, with the Aussies a distant
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd seen them earlier and knew they were a few back,''
Merrick said. ``But they're great sailors. From our point of view,
they really needed to be about 15th at that point to not be able to
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the Australians did come back, rolling through the fleet to
camp right behind the Americans. The U.S. team hung on to win the
battle, but the Australians, with their second-place finish, won
the war, and the gold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
