<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, Sept. 29. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ An Indonesian court
dismissed all charges against Suharto, the former president, and
abandoned his landmark corruption trial after doctors found him to
be too sick to face corruption charges. One Suharto supporter died
in riots as hundreds of Suharto opponents took to the streets.
These events followed by one day the sentencing of Suharto's son,
Tommy, to 18 months on corruption charges. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTIONS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Post-election
developments. Opponents threatened a general strike that would shut
down schools, offices and all institutions until Slobodan Milosevic
recognized their election victory. Montenegro and the Serbian
Orthodox Church were reported to have recognized Vojislav
Kostunica's victory. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSTUNICA (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Should Vojislav
Kostunica take office as Yugoslavia's new president, he wants to
help shape a country with a different sense of itself and its place
in the world, less isolated and neurotic, a normal European nation
with a good dose of skepticism toward American foreign-policy
goals. Yugoslavia needs to redefine itself, he explained in a
series of conversations. And Serbia needs to confront its own past.
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK-EURO (Copenhagen, Denmark) _ Exit polls from Thursday's
vote showed that the Danes were moving toward rejecting the euro.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEBATE (Austin, Texas) _ It is impossible to know which
incarnation of George W. Bush will show up at the first debate
between Bush and Vice President Al Gore in Boston next week. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FDA-ABORTION-PILL (Undated) _ In what abortion rights supporters
hailed as a major victory, the Food and Drug Administration
announced Thursday that it had approved the marketing of an
abortion-inducing pill, the first alternative to surgical abortion
approved in the United States. The pill will be available for sale
in about four weeks, its maker said. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-INSURE (Washington) _ The number of Americans without
health insurance declined substantially last year, to 42.6 million,
reversing a 12-year trend. The number of uninsured had been growing
steadily by more than a million a year. It fell by 1.7 million in
1999, mostly because of an increase in coverage provided by
employers _ and perhaps because of a new program for children. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
