<SLUG> BC-FOAM27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Physicist ponders cosmos in cappuccino
 &HT;    By Joe Earle
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Sidney Perkowitz stared into his cappuccino one
morning a few years ago, inspiration bubbled up.
</P>
<P>
   Perkowitz, a white-bearded Emory University physicist and
science writer, was struck by the form of the foam in his cup, so
much so that he launched a three-year survey of frothy things.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after digesting lots of research and more than a few
beverages, he's able to draw physical parallels between the head on
a beer and the structure of the universe, a souffle and top-secret
stuff inside spy satellites. He lays out his foamy connections in
the book ``Universal Foam: From Cappuccino to the Cosmos'' (Walker
and Co., $24).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just great to have some meringue or drink a beer and
think it represents some kind of cosmic pattern,'' the 61-year-old
Perkowitz said one recent afternoon in his office at Emory.
</P>
<P>
   Foam, he maintains, is strange stuff. Shaving cream, frothy
seawater on the beach, dishwashing suds _ it acts like nothing
else, posing physicists with unsolved math problems.
</P>
<P>
   Foam, he says ``is an everyday object that is mysterious.'' It's
taken a scientist who finds the fun in physics to plumb that
mystery. ``He's certainly not just your typical physicist,''
Phillip Schewe, a senior science writer at the American Institute
of Physics, says of Perkowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Brooklyn of Polish immigrants, Perkowitz grew up on
Coney Island. He remembers living in an apartment beneath the
parachute jump ride, about a block from the roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he's written magazine articles on why
scientists dress so badly (a mixture of naivete and arrogance),
what happens when voice-recognition software hears poetry (``In
Xanadu did Kubla Khan'' becomes ``In salmon do did mobile bond'')
and how novelist E.M. Forster might have reacted to the Internet
(poorly).
</P>
<P>
   He started looking into the physics of foam with the idea of
doing another magazine article. But his frothy subject carried so
many possibilities that it led to a book that largely was written,
he says, while sipping froth-topped concoctions at his favorite
Atlanta coffee shop.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he also learned how to make a better cup of
cappuccino. The secret, he says, is in the foam.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Earle writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
