u s BC-OLY-VOL-WOMEN-NYT &LR;      09-28 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VOL-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 5 SETS, THE RUSSIANS END THE UPSTART AMERICANS' RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SHAW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ A U.S. women's volleyball team that arrived
here little known and lowly rated took Russia to a fifth game
Thursday night for the right to play for the Olympic gold medal.
But the U.S. squad, seeded 10th in a 12-nation field, finally lost
to the second-seeded Russians in a tough 90-minute semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, who won, 25-15, 23-25, 25-15, 26-28, 15-8, will
face Cuba, the defending two-time Olympic champion, for the gold
medal. The Cubans beat third-seeded Brazil, 27-29, 25-19, 21-25,
25-19, 15-9, in the other semifinal. The United States and Brazil
will play for the bronze medal on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the U.S. team repeatedly battled back from huge
deficits against the more experienced Russians. After trailing,
19-13, in the fourth set, the Americans won a dramatic series of
set points to take the game, 28-26. In the fifth set, the Russians,
led by their twin towers, 6-foot-4-inch Yelena Godina and 6-3
Yevgeniya Artamanova, finally pulled away from the Americans. From
7-7 in the final game, Russia won eight of the last nine points of
the match. Godina finished with 28 kills and Artamanova had 26,
Lyubov Chachkova added 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic veterans Danielle Scott, 27, and Tara Cross-Battle,
32, and Logan Tom, a 19-year-old newcomer, were the mainstays of
the U.S. attack. Scott had a team-high 21 kills and Tom 15. While
most of the Americans said they were disappointed with Thursday
night's outcome, they took solace in their strong showing in the
tournament. They upset fourth-seeded China in four sets and edged
fifth-seeded South Korea in a thrilling five-set quarterfinal
Wednesday. In that comeback, the Americans rallied from a 12-9
deficit in the fifth set, winning four straight points to gain a
lead they never relinquished. And Thursday night they gave the
Russians a stiffer challenge than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team manager, Robert Gambardella, put its Olympic
performance in perspective. ``Everybody said we'd finish 10th
here,'' he said. ``Instead, this team has made history. Some
players have very little international experience and yet they made
the semis and the playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott looked forward to playing again. ``The Russians have been
an exceptional team for a long time, but we had a chance to win
tonight,'' she said. ``A lot of people didn't think we could get
this far. And we are not through yet. We still have a chance for
bronze against Brazil on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   And Cuba has a chance for an unprecedented third straight
volleyball gold thanks to the victory over Brazil. Cuba raced away
from Brazil in the deciding set Thursday night with a series of
spectacular 60 mph spikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuba-Brazil match had the feel of a gold medal showdown.
Traditional regional rivals with similar aggressive styles, the two
teams had clashed after Cuba's heated five-game semifinal victory
in Atlanta in 1996. In that match, players sniped at one another
during play and the tension boiled over during the post-match
handshake at the net. They slapped each other and scuffled again at
the tunnel leading to the locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   They were well-behaved Thursday night, although the Cuban
blocker Regla Torres glared at the Brazilians from across the net.
``I think there were problems, but those problems are nonexistent
now,'' said the Cuban captain, Regla Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil displayed marginally better form than Cuba going into
Thursday night's match, winning all five of its games in a week of
preliminaries. In those games, Brazil accumulated 395 points to its
opponents' 272, including a low-gear defeat of the U.S. team in
four sets. Cuba lost only to Russia in the round-robin
eliminations.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the 6-3 Torres, Cuba never trailed in the deciding fifth
game Thursday night, taking some drama out of the finish. ``It was
a hard game and both teams were very nervous,'' said Martenis
Costa, a Cuban attacker. ``We are used to winning and when we got
even with Brazil in the fourth set we felt confident we could
win.''
</P>
<P>
