   MLK-GRANITE _ At Stone Mountain it's hard to get a piece of the
rock _ even for a civil rights hero. But designers of the Martin
Luther King Jr. National Memorial, to be built in 2003 among the
cherry trees in the nation's Capitol want to erect a dramatic
entrance there made of Stone Mountain granite. Lotsa luck.It's not
a problem with the symbolism, in fact, there are probably dozens of
quarries and stone masonries in Georgia that would jump for the
job. It's just that Stone Mountain granite, the really pure stuff,
is hard to come by. (Smith, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-MUSIC _ SAN DIEGO _ Napster goes back to court Monday,
trying to convince a panel of judges to let it stay in business and
keep what is now the world's fastest-growing Internet software
application going. But regardless of the outcome of the case and
others like it, profound changes are already rippling through the
music industry. Musicians are already bypassing record companies to
go straight to listeners. Record labels are scrambing to figure out
how the Internet works so they can reconnect to customers. And
listeners are continuing to find free music even without Napster
and other programs. A look at how the business of making,
distributing and buying music has already changed _ and will change
in the future. (Keefe, Cox News Service)
