<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMSOC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWEGIANS DO WHAT US DIDN'T THINK POSSIBLE: WIN   GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The Norwegians were still in shock from watching
Tiffeny Milbrett leap skyward and yank the Olympic gold medal from
their necks just before the referee blew the final whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our day,'' coach Per-Mathias Hagmo assured his charges
as they loosened their legs for overtime. ``We will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they did Thursday night at Sydney Football Stadium, as
substitute Dagny Mellgren pounced on a loose ball that had
ricocheted off her arm and slammed it home in the 102d minute for a
3-2 victory that ended the US soccer team's global reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' said Norwegian defender Gro Espeseth, after
her teammates had rallied to hand the stunned Americans their first
loss in a world-level tournament in five years. ``It's a magical
moment, that's all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   For the US players, who were wandering numbed and tearful around
the pitch as their exuberant rivals did a victory lap, it was the
end of an era for a group who'd owned the planet since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Half a dozen of them _ Brandi Chastain, Joy Fawcett, Julie
Foudy, Mia Hamm, Kristine Lilly, Carla Overbeck _ played on the
team that won the inaugural World Cup in 1991. Few, if any, are
likely to stick around for the next Cup in 2003 or the next
Olympics in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Last Roundup, and for most of the night it seemed
they would go out the way they came in nine years ago _ as
champions. The Americans hadn't lost a global match since the
Norwegians beat them in the 1995 Cup semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   They were unbeaten in the 1996 Olympics, knocking out Norway in
the semis. They were unbeaten in last year's Cup, beating the
Chinese on penalty kicks in the final. And they were unbeaten here,
starting off with a 2-0 knockout of the Norwegians that easily
could have been 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   When Hamm walked into the box Thursday, strolled along the back
line, and tapped the ball to Milbrett for a gimme in the fifth
minute, it appeared the US was headed for a goalfest. ``I thought,
oh, no, not again,'' said Espeseth. ``Why should they win again and
again and again?''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans spent almost the entire first half in the
Norwegian end, just missing another goal in the 29th minute when
Foudy's header off a deflection dinged the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Had it gone in, the Norwegians might have come unglued. Instead,
they went to the dressing room reborn after Espeseth outleaped
defender Kate Sobrero and headed in Hege Riise's corner kick a
minute before intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Americans were having the better of it as the second
half wore on. They had two lovely chances seconds apart in the 61st
minute, after a four-touch rat-a-tat in the area set up a blast by
Lilly that keeper Bente Nordby knocked down, leaving a rebound that
Foudy knocked back to Lilly for another shot, which defender Goeril
Kringen headed away diving across the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegians were sitting back now, waiting for a long-ball
counter that might catch the Americans upfield. It came in the 78th
minute, and as keeper Siri Mullinix came charging off the line to
punch out the ball, Ragnhild Gulbrandsen outjumped Fawcett and
headed the ball past Mullinix and into the open goal.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rookie mistake by Mullinix, who had replaced Briana
Scurry this year after being cut from the Cup squad, and it looked
to have doomed the Americans as the minutes ticked down. But they
weren't playing that way. ``No chance this team is ever going to
give up,'' said coach April Heinrichs, ``until they tell us to get
off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the clock ran out, there were still a couple of
minutes of stoppage time. ``Two minutes is plenty,'' Heinrichs
said. Plenty of time for Hamm to run down the right side and loft a
cross for Milbrett, who leaped over three red jerseys and headed in
the equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably one of my finest goals ever,'' said Milbrett. ``I
never score a goal like that. I'm 5-2. Definitely a dream goal.''
</P>
<P>
   And a horror for the Norwegians, who were less than 20 seconds
from the gold medal when the ball went in. ``It was terrible when
Tiffy scored,'' Espeseth said.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't the end, only overtime. And here the Norwegians
had an edge in youth and freshness. Heinrichs had gone to her bench
only once, putting in Cindy Parlow as a third striker in the 69th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the Americans would be tired in the end,'' said Hagmo,
who inserted the 22-year-old Mellgren in the 83d minute and
Christine Boe Jensen for overtime. ``We had fresh legs to put
against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans could never mount another rush. ``We just couldn't
step it up when we needed to,'' said Milbrett. The Norwegians
launched another long ball, this one from Riise from just inside
midfield _ and this one was fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett headed it out, but the ball bounced off Mellgren's left
arm and back toward the US goal. Mellgren dashed between Fawcett
and Sobrero and fired a shot that went under Mullinix's
outstretched hand. ``She got a finger on it,'' said Heinrichs.
``From my angle, I thought she just pushed it wide.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so. The Norwegians, who'd never won a team gold medal at a
Summer Games, mobbed Mellgren and each other. ``It's so much like a
dream,'' said Gulbrandsen. ``I didn't think it would end up like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the Americans, who didn't know what a silver medal
looked like. ``You have to applaud Norway,'' said Foudy. ``They're
a class team. We have tremendous respect for them and what they've
done this whole decade.''
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegians are the only team in the world that has a winning
record against the Americans. When they play, as they have 30 times
in the last 13 years, the difference is usually one goal. ``I hate
parity,'' Foudy said. ``Who wants parity?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
