<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MERCY FROM THE SISTERS SLEDGEHAMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Venus pauses at the milky stripe, the baseline,
sensing, ``This is our moment. Me and Serena.''
</P>
<P>
   Then her left hand lifts and releases the yellow ball skyward.
For an instant it hangs in the air, like a mini-moon, before her
right arm and racket snap at it, jetting it on a diagonal, a rubber
missile whirring at 108 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Serena, at the net, has just advised Big Sister to ``Serve an
ace!'' giggling, ``that's the way to end it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like an ace,'' Venus says to herself . . . but Kristie
Boogert somehow gets her racket on it to loft a desperate lob.
Moving beneath it, Serena peers at the ball in its descent and
decides not to let it live another instant, not even to let it
bounce. With a mighty overhead swipe, she crunches the concluding
shot of the 2000 Olympics, tennis precinct.
</P>
<P>
   As the ball, mistreated to the end of its usefulness by a
sisterly combination, bounds beyond the dazed Netherlands team,
Boogert and Miriam Oremans, Venus and Serena Williams joyously fall
into each other's arms and 10,000 onlookers applaud a historic
performance: siblings in concert digging gold from asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   If this had been a prizefight, a humane referee would have
stopped it after the first 20 minutes and seven games. But it was
an Olympic final, and the battering had to go on for another 29
minutes until the Sisters Sledgehammer had mauled the Dutchwomen,
6-1, 6-1, Thursday and Little Sister Serena was caught up in the
gold rush. No Olympic final since 1896 had been more one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   As the 3 1/2-hour warm-up act for the Sisters, Yevgeny
Kafelnikov was the first Russian to win gold, beating young German
Tommy Haas, 7-6 (7-4), 3-6, 6-2, 4-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia, a gold medal means more than Wimbledon or anything
else in tennis,'' said Kafelnikov. ``At 3-3 in the fifth I said to
myself, `You will never forgive yourself if you don't win it.' Gold
pulled me through.'' Starling Haas, No. 49, was delighted with
``unexpected silver.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours before, Venus had not been quite so
destructive in dancing down the yellow brick road in a country the
citizenry calls Oz. She needed 58 minutes to work over the
18-year-old Russian, Elena Dementieva, 6-2, 6-4, and scale the
victory podium for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will be even better to win one with Serena,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   US coach Billie Jean King said, ``Venus means it. They are
closer than any sisters I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it had been Venus who kept Serena out of King's
singles lineup by beating Little Sister in their emotional
Wimbledon semifinal. The three singles entrants were selected by
the computer then, and a victory for Serena would have shoved her
ahead of Monica Seles, who copped the bronze Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange being at a tournament and just playing doubles,''
Serena had said. But she wasn't along for the ride or to caddy for
Big Sister, who has fulfilled their father's prophecy of becoming
the planetary leading lady. Even if the computer is behind on that
subject, still listing Martina Hingis and Lindsay Davenport ahead
of Venus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working hard to do my part so Venus and I can get it done.
We've been learning a lot about doubles from Billie Jean and Zina
(Garrison, assistant coach.)''
</P>
<P>
   They have a lot more to learn, which is fortunate for the
opposition _ colleagues nevertheless intimidated and endangered
just by being in the same rectangle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been like two people playing singles instead of one
doubles team,'' said Serena, aware of their deficiencies, which
they overcome anyway with power, speed, and combativeness.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a work in progress it's Venus and Serena, so
raw, yet so rampaging. This was merely their 23d pro tournament _
and seventh title (three of them majors) _ winning 62 of 73
matches, the last 22 straight. Although out of position most of the
time, they lost but one set.
</P>
<P>
   King laughs, ``They'll get it. They're coachable. I'd say that
as a doubles team they're up to about 50 percent of potential. At
singles, Venus is 75 percent, Serena 65 percent. Wait'll they start
coming in more and volleying. And they will.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' she said, shaking her head, ``I don't know how long
they'll stay interested. I hope it's a long time, to see what they
can accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena, who turned 19 Wednesday, bubbles, ``We want to make a
Grand Slam in doubles. That's our next goal.'' Only one female team
has done that: Martina Navratilova and Pam Shriver in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what's happened to me,'' said Venus, ``is a miracle. I
look back to April when I hadn't played in months, and to be here
now with two gold medals and the rest (Wimbledon and US Open
titles) . . . it is hard for me to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   She was in the grip of tendinitis of the wrists, and her papa,
Richard Williams, was saying she should retire. Whether he was
trying to rouse her or was looking for a headline, the fact is that
Venus reappeared. But uncertainly. She split her first four
matches, got to the quarters of the French Open in early June, and
hasn't lost since. Unbeaten in 32 starts, six tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Winning 11 matches, singles and doubles, in 10 days, she became
the second woman to seize gold in singles and doubles, duplicating
Helen Wills Moody's 1924 feat. Moody's sidekick was her 37-year-old
mentor, Bostonian Hazel Wightman. Venus worried ``only that I might
pull a muscle or something, but we have good trainers and
therapists. Gotta lose someday, I suppose. Everybody does.''
</P>
<P>
   As Serena knocks off the last point, King leaps from her seat,
recalling her first glimpse of Venus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 10 years ago. I was giving a clinic at the courts named
for me in Long Beach (Calif.), and her mom brought this skinny
10-year-old who was already taller than me. I told her she reminded
me of the great Althea Gibson, who had been my heroine. It's been
wonderful to watch her, and Serena, bloom.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, the pioneering black champion of the US Open and
Wimbledon in 1957 who today is a reclusive 72-year-old, follows
what the sisters are doing and is really pleased, King said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sisters had made a 10-day trek, preceding the climb up
Olympus, seem a lark. Nobody was in their league. ``It is nice
playing for your country. Fantastic,'' said Serena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked so hard for this. The anthem, the roses, the medals
. . . I'd seen it on TV. But to happen to us . . . you want to hold
on to that. It might never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus beamed: ``To be up there beside my sister, my best friend,
was very, very good. It only lasts a minute but it was our
moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
