u s BC-OLY-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-28 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARION JONES BREEZES TO MORE GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Never, ever forget: There is a Them and an Us. Male,
female, makes no difference.
</P>
<P>
   We cheer for Them and admire Them and just plain marvel at Them
because they do what we can't, and never could, do. They do not
think like Us. They are not subject to the same pressures as Us.
Most of the time, they won't even acknowledge familiarity with the
word.
</P>
<P>
   So for Marion Jones there never was an issue. The world could
think whatever it wanted about her husband and his doping problems
and how they might affect public opinion of her. C.J. Hunter wasn't
going to run that 200-meter race. She was.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us just started training this year,'' she reminded Us
after demolishing the 200-meter field Thursday night to win her
second Olympic gold medal. ``This has been a dream of mine for a
lot of years, so to let one event in your life, as dramatic as it
might be, ruin that wouldn't be worth it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The race itself was a joke. The whole evening was a Marion Jones
showcase. She sashayed her way into the finals, and, once there,
pretty much embarrassed the other seven, breezing to victory in
21.84 seconds. Her margin of victory over second-place finisher
Pauline Davis-Thompson of the Bahamas was .43 seconds, the largest
gap between first and second place in this race since Australia's
Marjorie Jackson breezed home ahead of Holland's Bertha Brouwer in
Helsinki 12 Olympiads ago.
</P>
<P>
   If this were Greco-Roman wrestling, the race would have been
called three-quarters of the way through on the basis of ``grand
superiority.'' It if were Olympic baseball, they would have invoked
the ``10-run mercy rule.'' If Dick Vitale were doing the
play-by-play, he would have been screaming, ``Hey Pauline! Better
get a TO, Bay-bee!''
</P>
<P>
   The race was hardly worth analysis. She started well, came
blasting off the curve, and ran away from everybody. You could have
fit a city bus between her and the delightful Davis-Thompson, who
won her first Olympic individual medal in her fifth Olympics and
then charmed the world's media at the press conference. For the
34-year-old Bahamian, this silver was the equivalent of a gold. She
had no illusions about the possibility of defeating the greatest
woman sprinter alive.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did anyone else in the field. Down there in sixth place was
Australia's Melinda Gainsford-Taylor, who didn't get a medal but
had the thrill a day earlier of finishing ahead of a loping Jones
in a preliminary heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was good fun,'' she gushed. ``Marion was slowing down,
and I thought, `What the hell, I might as well win in my hometown.'
They gave me a photo of the finish, and I'll take it home and frame
it and tell my kids 20 years from now that mommy ran against her,
and I helped push her.''
</P>
<P>
   Though admitting that for her it's really a belt-notch,
``two-down-and-three-to-go'' affair, Jones did profess to a certain
amount of excitement over what she's already accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first Olympics,'' she pointed out. ``The other day
was the first time I actually touched a gold medal. This is the
second time I've actually touched a gold medal. It means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But the goal remained five. Barely 15 hours after winning the
200, she was due at the track to help her relay team qualify in the
4 x 100 relay. There were serious questions about the Americans'
viability in that event. Then her focus would have to shift to
Friday evening's long jump. While no one doubted the US's
capability of qualifying in the 4 x 100, there were almost
undoubtedly going to be serious questions about their actual
chances of winning it. So it was possible she would go into the
long jump aware that the gold estimate might have to be scaled
down.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she allows negative thoughts to distract her, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep asking me about the relays, but I'm just taking it
day by day,'' she said. ``I'm just focusing on the long jump. I've
heard different things about the relays, but right now I'm
confident the US is going to be fine in the relays.''
</P>
<P>
   She was positively bubbly when discussing her chances in the
long jump, where she is all about raw talent, as opposed to
technique. Winning the long jump was always going to be a stretch _
in everyone else's mind, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident,'' she said. ``It was a great thrill for me to
go out and qualify on the first jump. That's not something I
normally do. I hope that this time tomorrow night you guys will be
talking about how well I jumped.''
</P>
<P>
   She says these things in a pleasant, matter-of-fact way,
antagonizing no one. In fact, perhaps the most amazing thing about
Marion Jones is that she has managed to win all these races and
make all this money and receive all this notoriety without having
the rest of her competitors wanting to drop her off a 10-story
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's incredible,'' saluted Gainsford-Taylor. ``She really is
an awesome athlete. I have a lot of respect for her. I admire her.
I've been out on the international circuit for 10 years, and I have
never met anyone any nicer. She's refreshing. There's such a thing
as a bad winner. She's a very good winner.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not a remotely normal human being, so don't even think
about telling your kids to eat their vegetables and say their
prayers and run their laps and think they might even remotely grow
up to be anything like her.
</P>
<P>
   Your kids and mine will always be one of Us. She is one of Them,
and even among Them, she is a higher order of being. Enjoy her. She
has been placed here to entertain us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
