<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JOAN-ALLEN-IN-THE-CONTENDER-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXUAL POLITICS: JOAN ALLEN TACKLES `THE CONTENDER' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 ART NOTE: Includes two color slides and black-and-white photos of
Joan Allen in scenes from ``The Contender.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 c.2000 Ivor Davis 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    In her latest film, ``The Contender,'' Joan Allen plays a
senator nominated to fill an unexpired vice-presidential term. At
her confirmation hearings she has difficulty being taken seriously,
despite her obvious qualifications for the job.
 &HT;    Allen knows the feeling.
 &HT;    After all, even with back-to-back Oscar nominations to her
credit, she had to fight for her role in ``The Contender,'' which
will open nationwide on Oct. 13.
 &HT;    ``Several studios were prepared to spend $30 million on the
movie,'' says Allen, who was Oscar-nominated for ``Nixon'' (l995)
and ``The Crucible'' (l996), ``but they didn't want me attached.
They preferred Michelle Pfeiffer, Meryl Streep or Sigourney
Weaver.''
 &HT;    The low-key Allen lacks the box-office razzmatazz of a Pfeiffer
or a Weaver, so she got the part only because writer/director Rod
Lurie kept his promise to her, even though it forced him to sign on
with Dreamworks and work with a budget of less than $10 million.
 &HT;    The resulting film casts Allen as Senator Laine Hanson, with
Jeff Bridges as the flamboyant president and a barely recognizable
Gary Oldman as a sleazy congressman who, in an effort to derail
Hanson's nomination, dredges up allegations of a sexual scandal
which makes the Monica Lewinsky saga seem like a Sunday-school
picnic.
 &HT;    The central premise of the movie is a tough sell, to say the
least: The whole thing rides on the idea that a female nominee
would refuse to respond to charges that, during her long-ago
college days, she took part in sexual orgies _ even though she had
proof that the charges were false _ because she believed on
principle that one's private life has no place in politics.
 &HT;    The concept strains credibility, to put it mildly, but Allen is
such a solid actress that she manages to give it a semblance of
plausibility. Rarely has her innate believability, that quality of
unflashy, determinedly unglamorous ordinariness, worked more to her
advantage.
 &HT;    The irony, of course, is that it's exactly that quality which
has so far kept her from the studios' A-list. Her performances as a
distraught Pat Nixon in ``Nixon,'' as a wife accused of witchcraft
in ``The Crucible,'' as a stressed-out wife and mother in the 1970s
drama ``The Ice Storm'' (1998) and as a frustrated housewife in the
elaborate fantasy ``Pleasantville'' (1998) have charmed audiences
and critics alike, but the sense of realism she lends her roles
obscures the impressive acting chops it takes to make them
possible.
 &HT;    That may be about to change, however. Besides ``The Contender,''
Allen has another film already in the can, a drama filmed last year
and based loosely on the assassination of real-life Irish
journalist Veronica Guerin. They are her first films as a star,
rather than as a supportive co-star or a member of an ensemble.
 &HT;    ``It's called `When the Sky Falls,''' Allen says of the Guerin
biopic. ``She's called Sinead Hamilton in the film, and I had
finished it at the beginning of June.
 &HT;    ''`Contender' started in August,'' she adds, ``so I was glad to
have had that starring experience under my belt, (to know) what
it's like to have to go to work every day _ because, when you're
supporting, you have four or five days off in between. When you're
carrying a movie, you have to work a lot harder.''
 &HT;    Not that she's complaining, of course. Both roles are the kind
actresses kill for. The role of Senator Hanson was even written
expressly for her.
 &HT;    ``It's never happened to me before,'' she says with a laugh,
``and it probably won't happen again. But at least it happened this
time.''
 &HT;    When Lurie, then a film critic for Los Angeles Magazine, met
Allen at a critics-award event and told her that he was planning to
write a role for her, her reaction was a somewhat skeptical ``Oh,
great.''
 &HT;    But when she saw the script, the actress understood how well it
suited her.
 &HT;    ``The issue of privacy is very big with me,'' says Allen, who is
married to fellow actor Peter Friedman and has a year-old daughter,
Sadie. ``I'm a very private person, and I could relate to that
aspect of Laine's character a lot. Beyond that, there was a certain
strength or calm that I project, that I have naturally.
 &HT;    ``But I think the big difference is I'd never be able to respond
the way Laine did,'' Allen says, ``to stick to what she was able to
stick to and withstand that kind of constant assault. I'd
crumble.''
 &HT;    Or so she says _ the background of the 5-foot-10-inch, rail-thin
actress suggests that she doesn't crumble easily. Born of solid
Midwestern stock, she grew up in the small town of Rochelle, Ill. _
population 8,000 _ and, though she says she was desperately shy,
discovered acting when she failed to make the cheerleading squad.
 &HT;    ``I really treasure having had that experience,'' Allen says.
``It was a really grounded, simple way to grow up, the Midwest.
There's nothing very gushy about (Midwesterners). People are pretty
straightforward. People are kind of quiet _ you don't always know
what they're thinking.''
 &HT;    She attended Eastern Illinois University in Charleston, where
her friend John Malkovich introduced her to a new theater he had
gotten involved in. That theater wound up relocating to Chicago and
becoming the famous Steppenwolf, with Allen along for the ride as
of its second year.
 &HT;    ``John asked me if I wanted to do a play the summer between my
junior and senior year,'' she recalls. ``I went back reluctantly to
school for my senior year, and when I graduated I had a place to
act immediately.''
 &HT;    The big city was a shock after Rochelle, and she got an even
bigger one later on, when she moved to New York to pursue a stage
career which peaked with a Tony Award as Best Actress for ``Burn
This'' (1988) and a second nomination for ``The Heidi Chronicles''
(1989).
 &HT;    But she says that Rochelle is still what keeps her grounded.
Besides, her life in New York is scarcely the glitzy existence of a
movie star.
 &HT;    ``I walk around, I take the subway. I get recognized
occasionally, but I blend in a lot,'' Allen says. ``People will go,
`Did I go to high school with you? Did you grow up in Tucson?' I
get questions like that a lot _ they can't quite place my face.''
 &HT;    In an industry in which stars often complain about the glare of
the spotlight, Allen says that it's perfectly easy to avoid, at
least on her level.
 &HT;    ``I don't seek it out, for one thing,'' she says. ``Some people
like that aspect of the business. I choose not to live in Los
Angeles. I don't socialize. I support movies I'm involved with and
I'll go to events surrounding them, but I don't go out much to
premieres and things like that.
 &HT;    ``I'm not very visible, so I think people forget about me,''
Allen concludes. ``I don't really come to mind as somebody to want
to say much of anything about.''
 &HT;    That may change, given ``The Contender,'' ``When the Sky Falls''
and a TNT television miniseries, ``The Mist of Avalon,'' which
offers Allen the chance to play her first all-stops-out villain.
Due next year, it's a Camelot drama told from the women's point of
view, co-starring Anjelica Huston and Julianna Margulies. Allen
freely admits to chewing some scenery.
 &HT;    ``It was a blast,'' she says. ``I'm even more villainous than in
the book. I try to take over Camelot and kill Anjelica Huston with
a dagger. I cast evil spells.
 &HT;    ``Every day was like being on the playground,'' she says with a
laugh. ``We would just giggle. I had to do this spell where I had a
bird wing and was spitting in the fire, trying to cast a spell so
that Guinevere would remain barren and my sons would inherit the
throne of Camelot.
 &HT;    ``I really enjoyed that.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Contender,'' consult the
official Web site at www.thecontender-thefilm.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
