<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG FACES CONTEST WITH THE CLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Cancer couldn't knock him off his bike, at least not
for long. Then, about 10 days before he was to arrive here, ready
to hunker over his handlebars and fix his gaze on winning his first
Olympic medal, Lance Armstrong slammed headfirst into an oncoming
car, leaving him with a shattered helmet, crumpled bike, and
cracked vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   But what's a crack in the spine when the oncologists,
chemotherapists, an army of lab techs, and oceans of anxiety are
fading images in your rearview mirror?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just part of my job,'' said Armstrong, who has been pedaling
long enough now that he dismisses these unexpected road hazards the
way a cross-country truck driver factors in weather delays.
``Crashes are a part of what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The more important, more rewarding, and usually more successful
part of what Amstrong does will play out Saturday on the roads
around Olympus. The 29-year-old from Austin, Texas, who four years
ago was diagnosed with testicular cancer, will compete in the
Olympic cycling time trials, what amounts to a three-lap drag race
of some 29 miles (46.8 kilometers).
</P>
<P>
   The two-time Tour de France winner, who has conquered bigger
opponents in recent weeks and years, has only the clock to conquer
this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one country _ I think it's Italy _ where the old
wives' tale about the cat is that he has more than nine lives,''
said Armstrong. ``I think the cat has something like 12 or 13
lives. So, I hope I'm an Italian cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was his typically grinding, persistent self Wednesday
when he made his 2000 debut on the road of the Rings, the grueling
148-mile road race. However, unlike the last two summers in the
hills and valleys of Provence, where he won consecutive Tours,
Armstrong finished 13th. He was well off the winning pace set by
longtime German rival Jan Ullrich, and was also behind fellow Yank
George Hincapie (eighth).
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, it was harder than I thought it would be,'' said
Armstrong, who didn't consider himself among the favorites headed
into the race. ``I waited too long (to make a charge). But that's
the way races go.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the time trials will be almost a sprint. Every 90
seconds a racer leaves the starting line, sent charging around a
loop of some 10 miles that must be circled three times. The
hard-charging Armstrong figures he has a better crack at making the
medal stand in this event.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, there was only one reason to come, and that's to
win,'' he said. ``I've been (to the Olympics) twice before, so I
didn't need to come for a vacation. I'd never been to Australia. I
see it's a really nice place for vacation, but it's not the reason
I came.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter where he is, no matter how long the course or how big
the prize money, Armstrong races as much these days to celebrate
his recovery from cancer. By his example, he hopes he has
reaffirmed that hard work, determination, and a will to survive can
be transferred from the winding road to the often more arduous
hallways of hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I don't wake up every day thinking that I want
to be an inspiration to somebody,'' he said. ``All I do is live my
life. When I had the illness, I fought the illness and I was
committed to getting better and leading a normal life _ to
returning to a life _ and I try to exemplify that even today, even
though it has been four years since my diagnosis. I think it is
better if I don't try too hard to be an inspiration; you just live
your life the way you want to live it, and if that is inspirational
to someone else, then that is perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration wasn't the first thing that came to Armstrong's mind
the day he rounded the blind curve in Nice, France (where he now
lives with his wife and child), and barreled into the oncoming car.
Just behind was Team USA member Tyler Hamilton, from Marblehead,
Mass., who steered wide of the collision and pointed his bike for a
more welcoming nearby ditch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he hit the car . . . I assumed the worst,'' said
Hamilton, ``because the impact _ it was an amazing impact _ and it
was loud, so loud. I saw Lance lying there. I didn't think the
outcome was too good. If you saw his bike, you wouldn't believe the
shape he is in now.''
</P>
<P>
   The oncoming car was going too fast. Armstrong, trying to
maximize his speed, was hugging too much to the inside curve. When
all came to a standstill, Armstrong realized both parties were at
fault. And he needed medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   The cyclists used the driver's cell phone to call Armstrong's
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could just give you an idea how quiet these roads are,''
said Armstrong. ``After the accident . . . we waited an hour and a
half for my wife to come and pick us up _ and she was the next car
to come by. It was just bad luck, in the wrong place at the right
time. It could have been a lot worse, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Assessing potential catastrophe has become a familiar part of
the landscape for Armstrong. The cancer could have been worse. If
not for his helmet, and a little bit of luck, he figures the crash
could have finished what the cancer had started.
</P>
<P>
   But he's here, still pumping his legs like pistons, climbing
hills, still racing by all demons and dents. A dogged Texan in an
Italian cat's clothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
