<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIGHT-DELAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AIRLINE EXECUTIVES WARN CONGRESS ABOUT FLIGHT DELAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of American Airlines, Donald J. Carty,
warned Thursday that flight delays will worsen unless Congress
intervenes to limit the burgeoning number of flights at major
airports.
</P>
<P>
   Carty said an unprecedented demand for air travel is prompting
competing airlines to schedule too many morning and evening flights
in places such as New York, Los Angeles and Boston. The result:
delays, cancellations and lost baggage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should authorize a discussion among airlines to prompt
them to cut back on flights at peak hours until airport capacity
expands, he said. Anti-trust law bars such meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has got to give or the bad situation that exists is
going to deteriorate,'' Carty told the aviation subcommittee of the
House Transportation and Infrastructure panel. ``We need to be
using our airspace differently.''
</P>
<P>
   More runways and more airports also are needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick W. Smith, chairman and CEO of FEDEX Corp., said the
federal government needs to limit the number of flights at hub
airports at peak hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think this summer was bad,'' Smith said, ``next summer
is going to make this one look like a picnic.''
</P>
<P>
   Complaints from irate fliers skyrocketed this past summer as
travelers faced the worst summer travel in years. In July, 30
percent of major airline flights were delayed, compared to a
typical late rate of 20 percent, according to the Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just damn near came to a halt this summer,'' complained
Rep. Steven T. Kuykendall, R-Calif., a member of the panel. ``
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the Transportation and
Infrastructure panel, said Congress is expected to vote next week
to provide $40 billion over three years to expand airports and
modernize air traffic control equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of the reason we have these delays is we don't have
an air traffic control system that enables us to fly safely in bad
weather,'' Schuster said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney E. Slater, secretary of the U.S. Department of
Transportation, told the panel that ``unacceptable airline delays
and cancellations'' were triggered this summer by record-level
passenger demand, bad weather, inoperable runways and aircraft
equipment problems.
</P>
<P>
   He said part of the solution is to send more planes to smaller
airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we need some additional capacity at major airports,
but we can make better use of regional airports,'' Slater said.
</P>
<P>
   Jane F. Garvey, administrator of the Federal Aviation
Administration, which oversees the air traffic control system, said
in an interview that ``there is no silver bullet,'' to stop flight
delays.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey said the solution involves better scheduling at airports,
new technology and use of niche airports just for cargo flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the hubs that can solve this,'' Garvey said.
``You've got to have a network.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter A. DeFazio, D-Ore., blamed the airlines for delays
and said the carriers should be barred from scheduling too many
flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines are driving this and they are driving it in a way
that has cost billions of dollars of delays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif., a member of the panel, said in an
interview that the answer is state-of-the-art air traffic control
and weather monitoring equipment and better communication to
passengers who are left in the dark when planes are delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to be pushing information on people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John R. Thune, R-S.D., said one reason airline passengers
get so frustrated is they ``believe a lot of the time they are not
getting the straight scoop.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Johnny Isakson, R-Ga., suggested that the Federal Aviation
Administration place message boards in airports informing
passengers of weather delays before they have checked luggage and
gone through security.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
