 For Release FRIDAY AMs, September 29, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
budgeted graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or
 &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLYSITE-PROTESTS (Jerusalem) _ Helmeted Israeli riot police
fired rubber bullets at hundreds of Palestinian stone-throwers at a
Jerusalem holy site revered by both Muslims and Jews and hotly
contested in Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. The spark is a visit
by hawkish Israeli opposition leader Ariel Sharon, who wants to
show that Israel is sovereign over the disputed site. By Charles M.
Sennott. &UR;  &LR; 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN (Green Bay, Wis.) _ Duelling over a theme that could
well determine the election, George W. Bush and Al Gore each pledge
to nurture the booming economy while casting the other as a
wasteful spender who cannot be trusted with the federal budget. By
Anne E. Kornblut and Glen Johnson. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PILL-REACTION (Undated) _ Abortion rights groups cheer the
approval of RU-486, which followed a 12-year battle to bring it to
the United States. Restrictions placed on the pill might still make
it difficult for some women, particularly those in the Bible Belt,
to get the pill confidentially. By Raja Mishra. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   PILL-POLITICS (Washington) _ Approval of the sale of the
abortion pill RU-486 will have far-reaching social and political
repercussions. By Mary Leonard. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCH-SAFETY (Undated) _ Federal research safety chief,
laying out his goals for the first time, says he will not back off
on enforcement but will focus on preventing harm to research
subjects by professionalizing the oversight system. By Alice
Dembner. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOB-INDICTMENT (Boston) _ Backed up by a stack of recently
unearthed bodies, federal prosecutors charge fugitive mobster
Whitey Bulger with murder for the first time. His sidekick, Stevie
Flemmi, is charged along with him in 10 of the 18 killings. The
indictment also names former FBI agent John Connolly, who used
Bulger and Flemmi as informants. By Shelley Murphy and Ralph
Ranalli. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   MOB-FBI (Boston) _ Bringing down the murderous Mafia was so
important that cutting deals with more benign gangsters like Bulger
and Flemmi was an unsavory necessity for the FBI. But who were the
really bad guys? By Ralph Ranalli. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRESSURE (Prague) _ As police clash with protesters, a
different kind of conflict is brewing at the IMF and World Bank
meetings _ a battle over the price of oil. By Brian Whitmore. 1000
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ARMSTRONG (Sydney) _ The more important, more rewarding, and
usually more successful part of what Amstrong does will play out
Saturday on the roads around Olympus. By Kevin Paul Dupont. 930
words.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WOMSOC (Sydney) _ Norwegians deal the US women's soccer team
the one fate it never expected: a defeat. By John Powers. 1000
words.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RYAN-COLUMN (Sydney) _ For Marion Jones there never was an
issue. The world could think whatever it wanted about her husband.
C.J. Hunter wasn't going to run that 200-meter race. She was. By
Bob Ryan. 990 words.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-COLLINS-COLUMN (Sydney) _ Venus pauses at the milky stripe,
the baseline, sensing, ``This is our moment. Me and Serena.'' By
Bud Collins. 1170 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5421 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l bc-DIGITAL-L.A.     09-28 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-L.A.-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT; 
B92: TRUE DEFENDERS OF THE FREE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
bc-DIGITAL-L.A.
cc,78p3  (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   For more than a decade, the radio station-turned-opposition
media conglomerate known as B92 has battled Serbian strongman
Slobodan Milosevic and his Yugoslavian government, pushing for an
end to the ultra-nationalist policies that helped fuel the ethnic
cleansing of Bosnia, Croatia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Milosevic apparently losing in last week's
presidential elections, B92 may finally find some peace of its own.
At least that's the hope of Gordan Paunovic, the organization's
new-media director, who was recently in Los Angeles for the Digital
Coast Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all looking forward to the day when we have a normal
political climate, and not wars,'' Paunovic said.
</P>
<P>
   For 11 years, what started as a ragtag operation with an expired
temporary broadcasting permit and a '50s-era transmitter has grown
into a network of radio stations, a Web site (www.freeb92.com),
record company and more.
</P>
<P>
   For this election, ``the opposition used the Internet to educate
people to prevent manipulations on the day of the election,''
Paunovic said. ``There is no way Milosevic can win legally.
Milosevic is going to lose. The question is how.''
</P>
<P>
   The station's Web site had an entire section devoted to the
elections, making it easy for people to check whether they're
actually registered to vote, and in what town, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   It's only the latest noble effort by an organization that has
labored since 1989 to present ``unbiased, uncensored news unshaped
by the government,'' Paunovic said. ``We were really the first ones
in Yugoslavia to do that. And we got a tremendous response.''
</P>
<P>
   As unlikely as the organization's beginnings were, it started
with great hope as communism crumbled in Eastern Europe in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, two years later, war came and all the hopes were gone,''
Paunovic said.
</P>
<P>
   The brutal ethnic conflicts of the next several years, fostered
by the pan-Serbian ambitions of the Milosevic regime, put B92 in a
difficult legal position, because the police could legally have
shut them down for broadcasting with an expired permit. But it
didn't happen, at least not immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got signs that the government was not very happy with what
we were doing,'' Paunovic said. ``But at that time they still
wanted to present themselves as open to free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the station was shut down in 1991 when it reported
on street clashes between anti-war protesters and police. When
protests then shifted to reopening the station, government
negotiators agreed, provided the station stopped broadcasting news
coverage, which it did temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, with the Dayton Peace Accords in place and
international trade sanctions lifted, B92 started the region's
first Internet service provider, in part to maintain contacts with
its network of correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet company ``promoted human rights, freedom of speech,
anti-war and peace activities. We gave free Net access to
practically everyone who believed the same as we did,'' Paunovic
said. ``The Internet is the last stand for freedom in the
Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, B92 was shut down again, and then its signal was
jammed. Fortunately, the station was just about to begin Webcasting
through Real Networks, instructing the few people with Net access
to print out B92 news reports for neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The station was shut again briefly when it reported the NATO
bombing was about to start. More recently and devastatingly, many
of B92's assets in Serbia were turned over to a
government-controlled entity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing seemingly everything, the organization soldiered
on, launching Radio Free 92 in May of last year. The Web site at
www.freeb92.net has no important assets based in Serbia, to protect
against further shutdowns and seizures. It also has begun a network
of stations just outside of Serbia. Asked why B92's workers
continue on despite years of government hassles, Paunovic shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our life,'' Paunovic said. ``It's not the money. We're
not underpaid, because the country as a whole is in such trouble.
But compared to the state-run media, it's nothing, it's peanuts.
But it's a huge passion.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
