<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Sept. 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   After a cold dawn with areas of frost and valley fog, abundant
sunshine will bathe the Northeast and Middle Atlantic states.
Despite the sunshine, afternoon temperatures will be several
degrees below normal.
</P>
<P>
   Variable clouds and showers will linger over Florida as gusty
breezes from the east draw moisture inland. Farther north, sunshine
will be plentiful in the Southeast. The afternoon will be warm with
comfortable humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Warm winds from the southwest will deliver unseasonable warmth
from the Plains into the northern Mississippi Valley and Great
Lakes states. Sunshine will be ample in these regions.
</P>
<P>
   Patchy clouds and showers will occur near the central Rockies,
although most of the interior West will be warm and dry. Meanwhile,
clouds and periods of rain will arrive in western Washington.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FROST ABOVE FREEZING &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast early Friday and Saturday, the first frosts of
autumn will occur in some locations where the temperature remains
above freezing. Official thermometers are placed five feet above
the ground. On a clear and calm night when the winds are light, the
air at the ground cools rapidly as it radiates energy to space. As
the night goes on, the layer of cold air gets deeper, but the
coldest, and as a result the densest, air hugs the ground. The
difference between the temperature near the ground and the official
air temperature can often be more than 5 degrees Fahrenheit.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
