</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BIGBROTHER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: IN `BIG BROTHER' FORMAT, NICE IS NOT ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Skedded as TV-WEEKEND)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching ``Big Brother'' has been as exciting as watching
vegetables grow. More precisely, it has been as exciting as
watching people put together a jigsaw puzzle, one of the many inane
tasks assigned to the 10 contestants who agreed to live in a house
for three months with cameras on them 24 hours a day. You may be
wondering why producers would even imagine that seeing people set
up dominoes or ride a stationary bike would create dynamic
television, but it turns out that such stupid human tricks are not
to blame for the show's failure.
</P>
<P>
   Similar tasks have been used in the 10 other versions of ``Big
Brother'' around the world, and they have still become hits as the
franchise has spread from the Netherlands through Germany to Spain.
What's wrong with us? Or is the United States the only ``Big
Brother'' to get things right, philosophically, even if that
philosophy has meant stultifying television?
</P>
<P>
   The major difference between our ``Big Brother'' and the others
is bland niceness. Other countries' contestants sniped at one
another, had sex, created drama. The Americans acted as if they
were in some celibate, selfless commune and just happened to be
wearing body mikes. They are walking, talking symbols of the
sensitive, Oprah-ization of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's live, hourlong finale (8 p.m. on CBS) will reveal which
of the three remaining contestants has won $500,000. (The others
were tossed out, one by one, by viewers who phoned in votes at 99
cents a call.) But the truer cultural revelation has been shaping
up for weeks. The CBS ``Big Brother'' veered away from sensational
chair-tossing television and displayed how Americans want to think
of ourselves _ good-natured and noncompetitive _ which is not
necessarily what we really are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' should have been the ultimate in living life for
the camera, with a half-hour of filmed excerpts five nights a week,
an hourlong live show weekly and 24-hour Web casts presenting what
the television versions did not. Every other week, contestants
voted on which two (or more) of them would be nominated for
expulsion; that meant they had to play to each other. But they also
had to play to the television audience. The potential for mind
games, poses and strategies makes ``Survivor'' look like a day at
the circus.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Big Brother'' is the anti-``Survivor,'' and its weaker
ratings are just the start. It is a commercial disappointment. CBS
has tried to spin this by noting how much ``Big Brother'' ratings
have improved over last summer's programs, but last summer CBS
presented reruns, not this hugely hyped event.
</P>
<P>
   The casting was timid; people in the European houses were on the
average younger and more daring. Then there was the dreadful
editing. Viewers were often dropped into the middle of confusing
conversations, then could spend excruciating minutes watching
someone nail up letters spelling ``Happy Anniversary'' and watching
someone else correct his spelling.
</P>
<P>
   These failures hurt, but the real problem was the group's sense
of community. Viewers of ``Survivor'' loved its intrigue, as
Richard Hatch plotted his success. The cast members of ``Big
Brother'' think strategy is a dirty word; they say that ``the
experience,'' as they so sensitively call it, is more important
than money.
</P>
<P>
   BLANDNESS PAID OFF
</P>
<P>
   Voters in the audiences seem to have bought this psychobabble.
The most confrontational contestants were the first to go, starting
with Will. The only black man in the group, he determinedly stirred
up intense conversations about race. The manipulative and
self-absorbed Jordan, a former stripper, went next. The most
successful contestants used blandness as protective cover. (Whether
it was calculated or because they couldn't help it, we may never
know).
</P>
<P>
   The producers will reveal little about the voters, except to say
they form a small percentage of total viewers. Whether the voters
are typical or not, they have placed two of the most agreeable
personalities among the three finalists, all of them men in their
20s.
</P>
<P>
   Josh, originally cast as the womanizer, has turned out to be
meek. It was news on the Web this week when two members of the
Italian ``Big Brother'' had sex. In England, after a flirty woman
called Mel was voted out, that Web site wrote, ``Sex kitten's
memory lives on.'' Here the attitude seems to be, ``No sex, please,
we're CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, Josh almost kissed Brittany, the sometimes pink-haired,
sometimes green-haired self-proclaimed virgin. ``The reason I don't
want to kiss you is because I like you,'' he said, saving himself
for a meeting with her outside the house. This sincere
self-restraint can't be what the producers hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   Another finalist is Curtis, a law school graduate whose every
comment is followed by a big infectious laugh that saves him from
ever seeming harsh. The producers tried to stir up trouble. In the
so-called Red Room, where contestants talk directly to the camera
and name their candidates for expulsion (out of earshot of their
housemates), the disembodied voice of Big Brother asked, ``Are you
nominating Josh because he's competition for you?'' Curtis said,
``I hope not.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the earnest Cassandra (voted out three weeks ago) was
asked a similar question about whether she was strategizing, she
stomped out of the Red Room and said, ``I'm so insulted.'' A common
refrain in the group was, ``I'd nominate myself if I could.''
</P>
<P>
   A REBELLION THAT FIZZLED
</P>
<P>
   The only finalist who has been direct about wanting to win the
contest is Eddie, a straightforward New Yorker who lost a leg to
cancer when he was a boy. ``As much as they say it may be about the
`experience,' it's about money,'' he told the Red Room camera. But
with the slightest nudge he agreed when his self-abnegating
housemates suggested a mass walkout.
</P>
<P>
   That loony attempt at rebellion isn't up there with the Boston
Tea Party, but it was the series' high point. For a day or so it
was satisfying to watch as the producers nearly lost control of
their show. The revolt was started by George, a roofer in his 40s,
who seemed like a sane family man at first. Soon, he was letting
Brittany dye his hair green, and Jamie, a would-be actress who won
the Miss Washington USA pageant, try out her makeup on him. George
inexplicably wore a toga on the night he was voted out; like so
many of his attempts at humor, the get-up was baffling.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
