<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5434 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ONLINE-MUSIC-0929-COX     09-28 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-MUSIC-0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROPOSED LAW COULD HELP BELEAGUERED ONLINE MUSIC COMPANIES
 &HT;    EDs: This story does not carry a dateline
 &HT;    By BOB KEEFE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bill filed this week in the U.S. House could make the world a
much easier place to do business for some beleaguered online music
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Music Owners' Listening Rights Act of 2000, the bill
would allow companies to store and transmit music over the Internet
to users anywhere in the world without violating copyright laws _
as long as the listener could prove they had already purchased the
music.
</P>
<P>
   A listener who wants to hear their entire CD collection while
traveling or at their office, for example, could do so without
taking their CDs with them simply by logging on to an online music
site.
</P>
<P>
   The bill gets at the crux of a lawsuit filed by the recording
industry against online music pioneer MP3.com Inc. Three weeks ago,
a federal judge ruled that MP3.com willfully violated copyrights
held by Universal Music Group, setting the stage for what could be
$118 million or more in damages. Universal claims that MP3.com
illegally made digital copies of its CDs and then let users who
could supposedly prove they own the CDs access them anywhere
through its ``My.MP3.com'' service.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va., who sponsored the bill, said he did so
because he thinks current copyright laws don't adequately address
services like MP3.com's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are facets of copyright laws that were written for an
earlier era that apply very awkwardly in the Internet era,'' said
Boucher, co-chair of the Internet Caucus, a group of lawmakers who
focus on technology issues. ``They shackle the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   A Universal spokesman did not return a reporter's phone call
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to members of Congress, leaders of groups
representing record labels, movie companies and musicians urged
them not to pass the bill because it would deprive artists of
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said that wasn't the cause, however, because Internet
listeners would have to prove they already bought a piece of music
before they could listen online.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of MP3.com, the copyright owners have already been
paid,'' when the listener bought the CD, he said. ``They don't show
a loss, but MP3.com can't go forward with its business.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other record labels have already settled copyright cases
with MP3.com. Universal is working on a service similar to
MP3.com's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the ulterior motive of Universal is to sue
(MP3.com) out of business so they can have the business all to
themselves,'' Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com on Thursday started what it calls a ``Million Email
March'' asking users to urge Congress to support the bill. Its
introduction also is proof that MP3.com's newly hired lobbying team
in Washington is working. In introducing the bill, Boucher cited a
survey paid for and provided by MP3.com that shows that more than
70 percent of frequent Internet users support business models such
as MP3.com's.
</P>
<P>
   With only about two weeks left in the current Congress, it's
highly unlikely that lawmakers will take any action on the bill
this year. But Boucher said when Congress reconvenes in January,
he'll re-introduce it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I introduced it now just to begin the conversation and to
educate the members of Congress that there are ... provisions in
the current copyright law that will impede the growth of the
Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And while the bill won't likely help MP3.com with its short-term
legal battles _ a federal judge in November is expected to
determine damages in the Universal Music lawsuit _ it could make a
big difference when MP3.com appeals the case, as it has said it
will do.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsoring the bill, HR5275, are Reps. Richard Burr, R-N.C.,
Ray LaHood, R-Ill. and Fred Upton, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Keefe is the San Diego-based West Coast correspondent for
Cox Newspapers. He may be e-mailed at: bkeefe(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Read the bill at
www.house.gov/boucher/docs/molra-leg
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
