<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-2NDTAKE-NY     09-28 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: was baffling.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last month, George misread the fine print in the contestants'
contract with ``Big Brother,'' and decided that if the remaining
six members walked out together they would share the prize money.
(The runner-up gets $100,000 and the third-place finisher $50,000.)
He was convinced that this was the secret intent of the producers
all along, the hidden message those European ``Big Brother'' houses
had failed to get: teamwork and brotherhood. He even convinced
Eddie to go along. The rebellion collapsed when the producers
explained that no one would get anything if they all walked out.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget that they all walked in because they were
willing to trade their privacy for the possibility of fame and
$500,000. Still, it's easy to see why this misguided idea of unity
appealed to them. They had been isolated from contact with the
outside world for two months; they had become increasingly
suspicious of the producers; they were intensely aware of the
cameras. Brittany, interviewed on the show after she had left the
house, explained how conscious everyone had been of the producers'
attention. ``Once you say something they think is important, you'd
hear `Whrrr,''' as the hidden camera zoomed in.
</P>
<P>
   UNANSWERED QUESTIONS
</P>
<P>
   How much of the contestants all-for-one attitude was genuine?
How much was smart posturing for each other and the public? How
much was the delusional result of having been in captivity?
</P>
<P>
   They're not letting on. The recently expelled contestants have
continued to gush about their terrific ``experience.'' Jordan has
griped that the editing made her look bad, but she was sent home so
early it's impossible to separate her bitterness from sour grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disappointment of this ``Big Brother,'' CBS may try
another, this time with a more volatile cast. Americans can create
reality television in a livelier way. MTV's ``Real World'' loads a
house with young people raging with hormones and curiosity, and
actually sends them out of the house. This season's cast lived in
New Orleans and produced a public-access television show.
</P>
<P>
   The success of confrontational reality shows exposes the gap
between our noblest self-image and our mischievous delight in
others' conflicts. What the public says it wants and what it
watches are two different things. If viewers had been voting on
``Survivor,'' Richard, who was at the bottom of popularity polls,
might have been voted off first. That would have been the
``correct'' choice, proving how good-natured we are and how we
admire straightforwardness.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Big Brother'' contestants have turned this attitude to
their advantage, but their determination to be likable may have
been short-sighted. Jamie, who was tossed out only three days ago,
brooded recently when a plane flew over the yard trailing the
message that she was ``two-faced.'' Her housemates assured her they
didn't believe it. (Despite many suspicions, the producers say that
neither they nor CBS had anything to do with the many banners flown
over the house. An early one read: ``Big Brother is worse than you
think. Get out now.'')
</P>
<P>
   MONEY AND CELEBRITY
</P>
<P>
   But in England's ``Big Brother,'' Craig, a builder who went on
to win, dramatically confronted Nick, a stockbroker, across the
kitchen table. ``How can you be so two-faced?'' Craig asked,
challenging Nick after he had been caught lying about passing notes
and trying to orchestrate the nominations (a violation of the ``Big
Brother'' rules). Nasty Nick, as he was called by the English
tabloids, had done worse than that. He had concocted a sob story
that his wife had been tragically killed in a car crash. The
producers kicked him out for cheating, but he went on to sell his
story to a tabloid for as much money as the ``Big Brother'' grand
prize, and become the most famous character on the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' after all, is a game show about money and
celebrity. The Americans' togetherness quietly undermined the
show's crass, humans-on-display tone, but it didn't change the
world. When they get out, they have to face a harsh reality; in
their isolation, they seem to have thought that a huge audience has
been paying attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
