<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0929-COX     09-28 2222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore switches focus to prosperity
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore switched his focus today from pummeling George W. Bush
on Medicare and began casting the election as a choice between
prosperity and ``a massive tax on America's potential,'' pitching
debt reduction as his economic priority. Paying down the national
debt in 12 years, as he hopes to do, would eliminate interest
payments that form essentially the government's third largest
program behind Social Security and defense, Gore told the Brookings
Institution in Washington. He said Bush's across-the-board tax cuts
would disproportionately benefit the wealthy, giving ``too much to
too few at the expense of too many.'' By taking money from programs
and debt reduction, he said, Bush would tax America's potential.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH FOCUSING ON SPENDING AND ENERGY
</P>
<P>
   Seeking political points on the economy, George W. Bush painted
Al Gore today as a big spender who would bring back the era of
expansive government and threaten prosperity. He challenged Gore to
forswear raising taxes to bolster Social Security. ``If the vice
president gets elected, the era of big government being over is
over,'' Bush said. So, too, he said, ``could be our prosperity.''
Bush leveled his attack in Green Bay, Wis. On Friday, he is to make
an energy policy speech in Saginaw, Mich., calling for increased
domestic production, more energy assistance for low-income
households, and a tougher foreign policy toward oil producing
allies.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN: BUSH `DECEPTIVE' ON DRUG PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman, flanked by longtime congressional colleagues,
accused Republicans today of ``downright deceptive'' claims about
their plans for drug coverage for senior citizens. Standing on the
Capitol steps, Lieberman said the plan backed by George W. Bush
would ``leave behind more than half of all senior citizens who have
coverage today.'' By contrast, he said, Al Gore and the Democrats
want to offer protection under Medicare to ``every single senior
citizen and person with disability in the country.'' Lieberman's
appearance at the Capitol as Gore's running mate, with his
limousine parked a few feet away, underscored his new status after
12 years as a rank-and-file senator from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   OIL MONEY GREASES THE COFFERS
</P>
<P>
   Alongside a few friends from the oil industry, Dick Cheney
helped raise $8 million for Republican Senate candidates and blamed
the Clinton administration for a lack of leadership that he says
has left the United States without an energy policy. Big oil and
other special interests came through Wednesday night at the 6th
annual Senate Majority Celebration, where 1,400 supporters paid at
least $1,500 each to dine on mustard-and-herb crusted beef and
Pacific salmon with sun-dried-tomatoes _ and toast GOP leadership.
The National Republican Senatorial Committee said the money will
fatten a campaign bank account that stood at $22.8 million as of
Aug. 31, just short of the $24.7 million balance of the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH'S DEFENSE SPENDING PLAN SMALLER
</P>
<P>
   Top military leaders have appeared before Congress to underscore
their need for more money, more personnel and more modern equipment
to keep pace with the increased number of missions since the end of
the Cold War. George W. Bush has repeatedly charged that the
military is ill-prepared for combat, but proposes increasing
defense spending by less than half what Al Gore wants. Bush says he
would spend $45 billion extra on the military in the next decade,
while Gore would says he'd spend $100 billion during the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   NADER ON LETTERMAN TONIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader gets his turn on David Letterman's late-night show
tonight, capping a week in which he's drawn thousands to rallies in
Minneapolis and Seattle. Yet, despite attracting large crowds and
breaking into the talk-show milieu, the Green Party candidate has
been sliding in the polls and is no closer to being included in
debates. But Nader has scheduled another super rally Sunday at the
Fleet Center in Boston to press for entrance into the first debate
on Tuesday, even though a bipartisan commission reaffirmed this
week that he failed to meet the criteria set for inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   GORE AGREES TO CONDITIONAL SOFT MONEY BAN
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has agreed to swear off soft money for the rest of the
campaign _ on the condition that George W. Bush does the same. Gore
accepted a challenge from Sens. John McCain (R-Ariz.) and Russ
Feingold (D-Wis.) to all candidates in the 2000 election to forego
the unregulated contributions. But he made clear that he was not
agreeing to unilateral disarmament. Even before Gore agreed to the
deal, Bush said he would ``probably not'' sign to such an
agreement, because the vice president wasn't trustworthy enough to
stick to it. Said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer: ``Governor Bush
looks forward to working with Senators McCain and Feingold after
his election to pass meaningful campaign-finance reforms including
a ban on corporate and union soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   GOING WEST FOR THE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton is on a three-day fund-raising trip outside New
York. She started in Oklahoma City, where her host, Michael Turpen,
was a former state attorney general who came under scrutiny in one
of the fund-raising investigations involving her husband's
re-election. She then held an event in Las Vegas on Wednesday
night. She's to be in Los Angeles today and Friday. Her opponent,
Rick Lazio, has criticized her for relying heavily on contributions
from Hollywood celebrities, a traditional fund-raising source for
Democrats, and at first, her aides would not disclose the names of
sponsors of the California events. They later acknowledged that one
host would be Cher. The others include the financier Marvin Davis
and his wife, Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   NEW DEBT REDUCTION PLAN FROM HILLARY
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, supported by ex-Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
and billionaire investor Warren Buffet, pledged to protect the
federal budget surplus from Republican ``tax schemes'' by proposing
legislation to limit tax cuts and new spending. Clinton proposed
mandatory debt-reduction caps that would make it more difficult for
Congress to use expected budget surpluses for cutting taxes or
paying for new programs. Her plan is similar in general terms to
the one proposed by Al Gore, but goes further by setting aside more
money for debt reduction and imposing legislative hurdles for
making exceptions. Her New York Senate opponent, Rick Lazio,
suggested that Clinton's policy proposals would leave little of the
surplus left to apply toward reducing the debt.
</P>
<P>
   BIG FUND-RAISING PUSH BY GORE
</P>
<P>
   Election Day is now less than six weeks off, and fund-raising is
more frenetic than ever. On Wednesday night, Al Gore raised more
than $3.5 million for the Democratic National Committee, bringing
his total take for the party in the last 16 days to nearly $25
million and his total take since January to more than $65 million.
Gore attended two events, starting with a reception at a downtown
Washington hotel for the Women's Leadership Forum. More than 800
people, paying $125 each, contributed about $500,000. He then took
his motorcade to a dinner at the Washington home of Sen. Jay
Rockefeller (D-W.Va.), where about 300 people, paying a minimum of
$5,000 each, contributed more than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   A WEEKEND OF DEBATE PREPPING
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore will return to Florida this weekend to prepare for the
first presidential debate with George W. Bush _ and soak up some
important media attention in that key battleground state. The
primary purpose for the trip to the Mote Marine Laboratory on
Longboat Key near Sarasota is to practice for the televised
showdown Tuesday in Boston. But the Saturday-through-Monday visit
also will provide the fringe benefit of press coverage in a region
of the state dominated by senior voters, a key voting bloc Gore
must reach if he is to beat Bush in Florida. On the other side,
Bush spokesman Tucker Eskew said the Texas governor will split
preparation time this weekend between his offices in Austin and his
ranch Crawford, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS' CHEERLEADER-IN-CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   A successful rally in Connecticut was a vivid demonstration of
how President Clinton may turn out to be the Democrats' secret
weapon in the battle for control of the House. While keeping a
relatively low profile in the presidential campaign, Clinton is
taking an increasingly active role in assisting congressional
Democrats regain the power they lost under his watch. Rep. James
Maloney, a Democrat waging a close race for a third term in his
southern Connecticut district, had hoped to turn out 1,500 people
for a recent rally in Danbury. But with Clinton's name as a draw,
more than 3,500 people flooded an outdoor amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH THE ELDER STUMPS IN DELAWARE
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush invoked images of the Persian Gulf
War and President Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky while
stumping for Republican candidates in Delaware, including his
presidential candidate son, George W., and five-term Sen. William
Roth. Bush questioned the Clinton-Gore administration's overseas
military policies and said his son would have handled the war much
as he did. He also said George W. would ``restore honor and
decency'' to the White House. Bush was in Delaware for a
fund-raiser at the home of Charles Cawley, chairman of credit card
giant MBNA Corp.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN HELP FROM A TV PRESIDENT
</P>
<P>
   In overwhelmingly Republican Utah, Democrats have to tread
carefully. In the 1st Congressional District, Kathleen
McConkie-Collinwood is bringing in the president on Saturday to
help her sagging efforts against the Republican incumbent, Rep.
James Hansen. Oh, not the real president; Utah residents don't
especially like President Clinton. Her guest is Martin Sheen, the
actor who plays a president on ``The West Wing'' the popular NBC
television series.
</P>
<P>
   THE OFTEN CONFLICTING POLLS
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gallup's daily poll of likely voters nationwide
showed Al Gore on top by as much as 10 points, while the bipartisan
Battleground poll had George W. Bush ahead by as much as 6 points.
Ten days ago, Newsweek put Gore ahead among likely voters by a
whopping 14 points; Sunday it reported that his lead has withered
to 2. But maybe that's wrong, since the aforementioned Gallup poll
now has Bush ahead by 3. Pollsters tried to explain the phenomenon,
but the explanations may not provide a lot of comfort. Pollsters
can't agree on the best way to identify the people who are most
likely to vote, and so they develop their own methods. In the words
of David Moore, senior editor of the Gallup poll: ``You can't
assume that all the methods are good. You just don't know. It's
part of the wizardry of polling.''
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS, DEMOCRATS USE WEB DIFFERENTLY
</P>
<P>
   More Republicans than Democrats surf the Web, and members of the
two political parties differ markedly in their surfing habits,
Internet audience tracker Media Metrix Inc. said today. Media
Metrix reported that registered Republicans represent 36.8 percent
of U.S. Internet users, outnumbering registered Democrats, who
represent 27.9 percent. The remaining 36.8 percent were affiliated
with other parties or not registered. The researchers also found
that members of the two major parties display distinct patterns in
the kinds of Web sites they visit, tending to confirm the
stereotypes: Republicans are more interested in money; the
Democrats in the environment.
</P>
<P>
   DAILY POLL OF PRESIDENTIAL RACE
</P>
<P>
   Reuters news agency and cable channel MSNBC will sponsor a daily
tracking poll of the presidential election, beginning Friday and
running through Election Day on Nov. 7. The poll, conducted by John
Zogby International, will survey 400 likely voters each day to
produce a rolling three-day average of 1,200 likely voters. This is
believed to be the largest sample planned for a daily tracking poll
in the presidential race. The poll will be released early each
morning by both Reuters and MSNBC. The results will be used
throughout the day on MSNBC as well as on NBC's ``Today,''
``Nightly News with Tom Brokaw,'' and ``Meet the Press with Tim
Russert.'' The results also also be available on MSNBC.com and on
Reuters.com.
</P>
<P>
   MAJORITY FOUND UNCOMFORTABLE WITH ONLINE VOTING
</P>
<P>
   Americans have mixed feelings about online voting and the Web as
a source for political and election information according to a
recent nationwide survey conducted by Rasmussen Research, an
independent international polling firm. Both Internet and
non-internet users cited election fraud and privacy concerns as
reasons against online voting, and expressed concern about the
trustworthiness of candidate Web sites. Some 51 percent said voters
should not be permitted to cast their ballots for president and
other elected officials via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
