<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5444 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ABORTION-DRUG29-COX     09-28 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-DRUG29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FDA approves new abortion drug
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the Food and Drug Administration officially approved on
the use of RU-486 Thursday, hundreds of Atlanta women have already
taken the abortion pill to end their early pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   The Feminist Women's Health Center has been conducting clinical
trials for the drug, also known by the chemical name of
mifepristone, since 1994, according to Lindy Wood, the clinical
trial site coordinator. She said most of the nearly 500 women who
tried RU-486 thought it a better alternative to more traditional
surgical abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very successful, with the greatest advantage being
women liked the privacy of it _ that they could be in their home,
near their own bathroom,'' she said. ``That the experience became
less clinical, felt more natural and a far more personal
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wood said, almost 96 percent of the women said they
would recommend it to others.
</P>
<P>
   That angers anti-abortion forces, who have rallied to keep the
U.S. ban against the pill in place for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, abortion has become not a medical necessity, but a form
of birth control,'' said Jen Wilson, spokeswoman for Georgia Right
to Life Committee Inc., based in Atlanta. ``The Clinton-Gore
administration has now decided it's okay to hand out abortion pills
like candy.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse, anti-abortion advocates fear that women will think of
this a ``quick and easy'' way of ending a pregnancy, when it is
not.
</P>
<P>
   Where a surgical abortion can take a few minutes, ``medical
abortion'' induced by the drug takes days, and in a few cases,
weeks. Also, one in 20 women who try medical abortion will need to
have a surgical abortion because the pills did not work.
</P>
<P>
   Under the FDA ruling, doctors should be able to receive
mifespristone _ a little white pill, no bigger than a tablet of
aspirin _ within a month.
</P>
<P>
   Once taken, the drug causes the lining of the uterus to break
down. A few days later, the woman takes another drug, misoprostol,
either orally or through vaginal inserts. This causes the uterus to
contract, expelling the embryo.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is about 95 percent effective, and most women
experience cramps similar to a difficult period, according to the
National Abortion Federation, an abortion rights organization that
licenses clinics and abortion providers.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of bleeding often is greater than with surgical
abortions, with many women passing large blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   The pills _ and the required ultrasounds, check-ups and lab work
_ cost about the same as a traditional surgical abortion: between
$300 and $400. Abortion rights advocates expect, however, that cost
to go up since Danco Group, a women's pharmaceutical company, has
an exclusive license to manufacture, market and distribute the drug
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And insurers have yet to weigh in on whether drug, which will be
under the new brand name of Mifeprex, will be covered in
traditional plans. Abortion rights advocates expect that insurance
companies that already cover abortions will cover this new option.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid administrators will have to evaluate whether the
health-care program for the poor should include the pill as part of
its health care coverage of low-income women, said Joyce Goldberg,
spokeswoman for the Georgia Department of Medical Assistance. Now,
the government health care plan for the poor only pays for an
abortion if the pregnancy is a result of incest or rape or
endangers the life of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   And any new drug has to go through an internal review process
before it can be approved for Medicaid use, which would include
RU-486. And although a Kaiser Family Foundation survey shows that
about half of obstetric/gynecology doctors in nation would be
willing to prescribe the drug, the Food and Drug Administration has
placed restrictions on which doctors will be able to administer the
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new regulations, mifepristone will probably be handled
mostly by doctors specializing in obstetrics and gynecology.
Specifically, the drug can only be distributed to doctors trained
to diagnose the duration of pregnancy and to detect ectopic, or
tubal, pregnancies, because those women cannot receive
mifepristone.
</P>
<P>
   And the FDA restricted mifepristone's use to doctors who can
operate in case a surgical abortion is needed to finish the job or
in cases of severe bleeding _ or to doctors who have made advance
arrangements for a surgeon to provide such care to their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Such requirements probably will not prevent most metro Atlanta
patients from seeking a medical abortion, but may make it difficult
for women in rural areas to obtain the pills, according to Dr.
Andrew Toledo, a board member of the Georgia Obstetrics/Gynecology
Society, specializing in reproductive endocrinology.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been a negative perception about anything
having to do with abortion and right-to-life issues (in rural
areas),'' said Toledo, who specializes in infertility at
Reproductive Biology Associates Inc. and will not be using the drug
because of the nature of his practice. ``And most doctors (in rural
areas) simply aren't going to be comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, however, that the problem of access for poor, rural
women will continue to exist, according to Kay Scott, Planned
Parenthood of Georgia's president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Probably 85 percent of the abortions in the state are provided
in the metro Atlanta area, she said. And often, low-income women
travel by bus to Atlanta to have a surgical abortion, because they
don't have access to such services in their hometown, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of such issues, it is unlikely whether the use of RU-486
will exceed the number of surgical abortions in the near future,
experts said. At the Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta, for
example, about 500 women have been involved in clinical trials that
occurred between 1994 and 1995, and again starting in 1998. In the
meantime, the clinic averages between 50 to 75 surgical abortions a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly is not going to replace surgical abortions,''
said Wood. ``But it does give women one more option.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RU-486 is not a drug you can purchase at a pharmacy. You must
have a doctor prescribe it and administer it. The doctor must be
able to diagnose pregnancies and either be able to perform surgery
if necessary or arrange surgical back-up.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RU-486 is not the same as the ``morning after pill.'' Such
emergency contraception pills must be taken within 72 hours of
unprotected intercourse. They contain levonorgestrel and ethinyl
estradiol or levonorgestrel alone, and work the same way as birth
control pills: They delay or inhibit ovulation or fertilization.
They do not cause an abortion and do not interfere with an existing
pregnancy. RU-486 can be used for an abortion up to 49 days from a
woman's last menstrual period and it works by causing the uterus to
shed the lining and embryo.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RU-486 was first approved in 1988 in France, where it was
developed by the pharmaceutical firm Roussel-Uclaf. It was banned
in the United States until the Clinton administration, in one of
its first actions, asked the FDA in 1993 to re-examine its ban.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
