<HEADLINE>
TAE KWON DO: LOPEZ TAKES GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story has been shorted) 
 By WALTER BARRANGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Patience and a penalty point helped propel
Steven Lopez of Sugarland, Texas, to a tae &UR;  &LR; kwon &UR;  &LR; do gold medal
Thursday night, 1-0. Lopez faced Sin Joon Sik of South Korea for
the gold medal in the 68-kilogram (150-pound) class, after
defeating three opponents by a combined 10-1. The 6-foot-2-inch
Lopez used a six-inch height advantage to keep Sin backing away and
risking penalties for lack of aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that sooner or later they were going to give him
penalty points,'' Lopez said. When a penalty point was deducted,
Lopez said, a further complication developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I landed a foot kick, but the crowd was too loud,'' Lopez
said. With the judges unable to hear the sound of his kicks against
Sin's protective gear, the best strategy became patience. Lopez
said that he left his chest open to attack, hoping that Sin's right
kick would leave an opening for a return blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a trap, and he fell for it,'' Lopez said. With about a
minute left in the final round and the match scoreless, Sin tried
the kick and Lopez countered to score the winning point.
</P>
<P>
   Under tae &UR;  &LR; kwon &UR;  &LR; do rules, the point total was recorded as 1-1,
but the penalty deduction meant a decision for Lopez, 1-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-DIV-NYT &LR;      09-28 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DIV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE RETAIN DOMINANCE IN DIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL BRINK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Two systems for developing divers were on
display at the Olympic Park Aquatic Center here Thursday night, and
the results were as defining as Fu Mingxia's nearly flawless
technique.
</P>
<P>
   Fu won the women's 3-meter springboard title by surpassing her
Chinese teammate, Guo Jingjing, on the final two dives. With the
victory, she joined two Americans, Greg Louganis and Pat McCormick,
as the only divers to win four Olympic gold medals, and she became
the first female diver to win five career medals. She also
continued the Chinese dominance that has accounted for eight medals
so far in this diving competition.
</P>
<P>
   The two-woman duel between Fu and Guo underscored the efficiency
of a state system for identifying potential stars at a young age.
Fu was a world champion at age 12, and was 13 when she won the
platform gold at the Barcelona Games in 1992. Now 22, and back from
temporary retirement, she is a mentor and tutor, as well as
inspiration to a new generation. That includes Guo, an 18-year-old,
who said Fu ``looks after all the young divers.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the women left behind Thursday night were two U.S. divers,
Jenny Keim of Miami, who was eighth, and Michelle Davison, who
finished 12th and last. They are products of a U.S. system that
runs up against social and familial boundaries that inhibit
excessive training regimens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese and their system put a lot of miles on their
kids,'' said Tim O'Brien, a U.S. assistant coach. ``They're so well
trained and disciplined. Our kids are training three, four hours a
day. Theirs train eight. The Chinese teach them beginning at age 7
or 8. For the most part, people in our country have resisted going
in this direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Davison, a 20-year-old out of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., said she
would not want to go to such extremes for a sport she pursued
because of her passion for it. ``It's such a different society,''
she said of the Chinese. ``To them, diving is their livelihood. In
the States there are so many other things.'' That's also true for
Keim, who plans to be in law school by the time the 2004 Summer
Games are held in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Americans couldn't help being impressed by Fu and the
Chinese, for their consistency of effort and technique. ``They
always look the same,'' Keim said. ``I don't really understand
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Developing a stronger grass-roots program has been a priority of
Bill Walker, who was elected in 1998 as president of U.S. Diving.
Among the initiatives are a Future Champions Program, more regional
training centers and a possible national training center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to plant some roots,'' Davison said, ``and in eight,
10, 12 years, we'll be up there.''
</P>
<P>
   After sweeping the women's golds in 1996, Fu retired and entered
college in Beijing. But she returned in July 1998, citing her love
for the sport and concern that she was ``getting fat.'' Thursday
night, at 106 pounds, she stayed close to Guo for three rounds,
then edged ahead of her by just more than one point on the fourth.
On the final dive, Guo faltered on a inward 2 1/2 somersault, and
Fu locked up the gold with a clean entry on a reverse 1 1/2
somersault with 2 1/2 twists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I have a lot of gold medals, but I don't consider myself
special,'' she said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
