<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-PEARL-HARBOR-HNS &LR;      09-28 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARL-HARBOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONGRESS POISED TO EXONERATE PEARL HARBOR COMMANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHARLES J. LEWIS and ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly 60 years after Japan bombed Pearl Harbor,
Congress was poised Thursday to posthumously exonerate the military
officers who were blamed for the disaster because U.S. forces were
caught unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation, nearing final action in Congress, praises Rear Adm.
Husband E. Kimmel and Army Maj. Gen. Walter C. Short as
``professional and competent'' and asks President Clinton to
promote them to the highest ranks they held before being forced out
of the military in the wake of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,400 people were killed in the attack on Dec. 7,
1941, the worst military disaster in U.S. history. The United
States declared war against Japan the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel and Short were relieved of their commands and found
guilty of ``dereliction of duty'' for not being prepared for the
attack. Kimmel, the Navy commander at Pearl Harbor, and Short, the
Army chief, were removed from their commands and sent into
retirement. Both men reverted to their previous ranks as two-star
officers in accordance with military rules at the time, though
Kimmel had been a full admiral with four stars and Short had been a
lieutenant general, with three stars.
</P>
<P>
   Short died in 1949 and Kimmel died in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of World War II, Congress and President Harry S.
Truman enacted legislation that allowed all officers to retire that
the highest ranks they had attained during the war. However, the
law made an exception for Kimmel and Short.
</P>
<P>
   According to the pending legislation, the catastrophic U.S.
losses at Pearl Harbor ``were not the result of dereliction'' of
duty on the part of either man. Promoting them, it says, is
essential in order to rehabilitate their reputations.
</P>
<P>
   To do otherwise ``serves only to perpetuate the myth that the
senior commanders in Hawaii were derelict in their duty and
responsible for the success of the attack on Pearl Harbor, and is a
distinct and unacceptable expression of dishonor toward two of the
finest officers who have served in the Armed Forces of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The exoneration is contained in the annual budget authorization
bill for the Defense Department. Both the House and Senate have
approved the exoneration of Kimmel and Short and the bill is now in
a Senate-House conference committee to iron out differences over
such issues as the number and types of weapons to be purchased.
Because both chambers voted for the Pearl Harbor provision, it is
almost certain to be included in the final version expected to win
final passage before Congress adjourns for the year.
</P>
<P>
   According to the legislation, Kimmel and Short were excellent
military commanders. Each ``performed his duties competently and
professionally, and, therefore, the losses incurred by the United
States in the attacks on the naval base at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii,
and other targets on the island of Oahu, Hawaii, on Dec. 7, 1941,
were not a result of dereliction in the performance of those duties
.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers assert that blame doesn't rest with Kimmel and
Short but with a bureaucratic military chain of command that
neglected to pass along key intelligence information. The officers
``were not provided necessary and critical intelligence that was
available, that foretold of war with Japan, that warned of imminent
attack, and that would have alerted them to prepare for the
attack,'' the lawmakers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The exoneration is in line with a historical tendency of
Congress to be less harsh with Kimmel and Short. Following
extensive hearings after the war, a joint House-Senate committee
concluded in 1946 that Kimmel and Short were guilty of ``errors of
judgment and not derelictions of duty.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest congressional action was hailed by Edward K. Kimmel,
the youngest of three sons of Husband Kimmel, and a leader in the
ongoing campaign to exonerate his father.
</P>
<P>
   The exoneration would be ``very significant,'' Kimmel said, but
noted that it is up to Clinton to actually take the step of
nominating both officers for promotion. ``Only the president can
make this happen because he is plenary over the military, he's the
command-in-chief,'' Kimmel said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel, 79, a retired lawyer for the DuPont Co. in Wilmington,
Del., praised Sens. Joseph Biden, D-Del., William Roth, R-Del.,
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., for getting
the exoneration language in the authorization bill. He said he was
counting on them to urge Clinton to follow through.
</P>
<P>
   The exoneration was also praised by Edward Beach, a retired Navy
captain and a long-time supporter of the Kimmel family's crusade on
behalf of Husband Kimmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the official exoneration of Kimmel and Short,'' said
Beach, the author in 1995 of ``Scapegoats,'' a defense of the two
commanders. ``They already have been exonerated in public opinion.
Now this action means they are officially `not guilty.' History
will have to take note. This is the final point.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, University of Pittsburgh historian Donald M.
Goldstein expressed outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is rewriting history,'' said Goldstein, a co-author of
the 1981 best-selling Pearl Harbor history, ``At Dawn We Slept.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel and Short were not the only people responsible for the
disaster, Goldstein said, ``but they nevertheless should have been
better prepared. I'm sorry but they really bungled it. I can't
understand how (Congress) can rewrite history with a bill. The
bottom line is that they were caught unprepared.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the Pearl Harbor commanders had received an
official ``war warning'' message from Washington on Nov. 27, 1941,
that predicted a possible Japanese attack at any minute. Kimmel and
Short later testified that they assumed other U.S. military
commanders in the Pacific _ including Gen. Douglas MacArthur in the
Philippines _ were the primary target for the warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kimmel and Short had enough information and should have been
ready, despite all of the stuff going on in Washington,'' Goldstein
said, adding that the debate over culpability for Pearl Harbor will
go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pearl Harbor never dies and we will never see the end of it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The view that top leaders in Washington shared in the guilt was
embodied in a 1995 Pentagon study of Pearl Harbor commissioned by
Edwin Dorn, then the undersecretary of defense, in response to a
request by Thurmond, then chairman of the Senate Armed Service
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Dorn report concluded that Kimmel and Short shouldn't be
singled out for blame because key Washington officials contributed
to the disaster by withholding valuable intelligence from Kimmel
and Short and by sending confused messages to the Pearl Harbor
commanders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Charles J. Lewis and Eric Rosenberg can be reached at
202-298-6920.)
</P>
