<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: A DEVOTION TO JAPANESE ART IS REQUITED 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE CHARLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rene Scholten came to love Japanese art through a
circuitous route. On a trip to Japan while working as a software
consultant, Scholten, who is Dutch, purchased an inexpensive
woodblock print. Then he saw a fine 1929 print by Torii Kotondo of
a beautiful woman applying powder. Completely seduced, he bought
it.
</P>
<P>
   When an art dealer friend said he wanted to quit, Scholten took
over his shop in The Hague. Business expanded, and so did the
gallery; Scholten left his high-tech life and became a partner in
Hotei Publishing, expanding its list of books on Japanese art.
</P>
<P>
   His most recent venture is Scholten Japanese Art in Manhattan,
which he opened two weeks ago with the help of two respected
experts, Katherine Martin and Rosemary Bandini. Its first show
focuses on the art of the Edo period in Japan (1603-1867).
Intricate netsuke, the fanciful toggles that delighted the Japanese
gentry for whom they were carved, are suspended in illuminated
plastic cubes, as are shimmering lacquer boxes, better suited to
holding admiration and wonder than more substantial stuff. On the
walls are prints by some of the great masters: Suzuki Harunobu,
Katsukawa Shuncho, Kitagawa Utamaro and Utagawa Hiroshige. Scholten
spent $10 million to convert three floors of the town house at 63
East 66th St., and it shows.
</P>
<P>
   Woodblock prints known as ukiyo-e have been the portal into
Japanese art for many Westerners, including Monet, whose collection
can be seen at his home-museum in Giverny, and van Gogh, who copied
two of Hiroshige's prints, most famously ``Ohashi Bridge.'' The
fragile colored prints were also favorites of Frank Lloyd Wright;
an exhibition of his collection and his architecture in Japan will
be at the Japan Society in March. The allure has not faded. A
recent woodblock show at the Asian Art Museum in San Francisco drew
more than 80,000 visitors. ``They have an immense following,'' said
its director, Emily Sano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone can collect Monet, but they can collect prints,''
said Martin, the Scholten gallery's managing director. ``Here are
artists at a turning point. They are creating totally new abstract
images, taking proportion and perspective and color and playing
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The prints lead the viewer into the floating world ukiyo, a
Buddhist concept for the sad and transitory nature of the material
world. Edo artists transformed the idea into the transitory world
of pleasure, a demimonde of geisha and parties, actors and theater.
</P>
<P>
   The high-flying Edo era was a boom period. Like present-day New
York, Edo (now Tokyo) was  &UR; the &LR;  center of commerce and trade.
Merchants flush with money from a new economy sought to spend it on
pleasure and more pleasure. Ukiyo-e put the spotlight on this
self-indulgent, glamorous world, immortalizing the day's most
sought-after courtesans, the season's most popular Kabuki actors.
``The beauties were Edo's supermodels, the actors its rock stars,''
Martin said. ``The prints were the Edo period's color TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The prints were major productions. Publishers hired artists who
drew images that were then carved into wood blocks (sometimes a
dozen or more for one print) by a master engraver. The blocks were
given to a printer who worked under the publisher and the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Although publicly scorned by the higher-caste samurai, the
burgeoning merchant class collected the prints as passionately as
later generations would collect posters and baseball cards. Some
artists became almost as famous as their subjects. Utamaro, who
worked at the end of the 18th century, was the Richard Avedon of
Edo. Known for his innovative close-ups of the beauties of the day,
he at once idealized them and captured, through simple elegant
lines, their emotions and personalities. (His ``Mirror of
Courtesans of the Green Houses'' is for sale at Scholten for
$25,000.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There were thousands of images and varying levels of prints,
ranging from cheap ephemera to mica-ground prints for the
wealthy,'' said Sebastian Izzard, a dealer who has just opened a
new space at 42 E. 76th St., Manhattan. Many were lost to fire or
ruined by water. In the Meiji period, when the Japanese turned
their eyes to the West, some were actually used for packing.``We
have no real idea of how many have survived,'' said Izzard, who
worked at Christie's for 17 years. ``What we do know is that there
are many `sleeping prints' stored away. Whenever a fine `unique'
print is sold for a high price at auction, another surfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Scholten's aims is to make the gallery a focus for
Japanese art: a library on the third floor will be open to
students, scholars and collectors, and Martin plans a series of
lectures next year. (Information and appointments: 212-585-0474.)
``We want to develop collectors,'' Scholten said. ``And you can
only really do that through a gallery.''
</P>
<P>
   George Mann, a collector from Chicago, agreed: ``It's one thing
to see a print on a wall at a museum, and quite another to hold it
and examine it. An even larger barrier is psychological. You can't
own a museum print. A print in a gallery is much more seductive.''
</P>
<P>
   The novice has much to learn. A print of the famed Ohashi bridge
by Hiroshige can sell for anywhere from several hundred dollars to
tens of thousands. In a recent auction at Christie's an early
impression went for $52,875; at Scholten, another fine impression
costs $75,000. At issue is the quality and condition of the print.
Often an early edition will command the highest price: the artist
was there supervising the printer, making sure the proper colors
were used. In later editions, when the artist was off creating new
images, a printer might take shortcuts, using less expensive
pigments.
</P>
<P>
   But the first impression does not always command the highest
price. Sometimes a coterie of patrons commissioned a deluxe edition
printed on special paper with special pigments. Or the publisher or
artist decided to edit the print to make it more salable or
attractive. The first prints of Hiroshige's ``Ohashi,'' for
example, are sometimes known as ``Two Boats''; in later editions
two boats in the background were etched out to make the print more
aesthetically appealing. Popular works could be printed and
reprinted until the block became so worn that the impressions were
virtually unreadable. The title of Hiroshige's series ``100 Views
of Edo'' was actually changed to ``100 Views of Tokyo.'' ``The name
of the city changed in 1868, 10 years after the print was made,''
Izzard said. ``The condition of the blocks had to be pretty
rough.''
</P>
<P>
   The prints are as ephemeral as their subjects, soon fading in
direct light. Improperly stored, they become food for worms and
insects. Today most serious collectors keep prints in acid-free
paper in boxes, taking them out to look at or to hang on a wall,
for only a brief time, behind protective glass.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for ukiyo-e are driven by fashion, just as they were in
the Edo period. Although a popular image in excellent condition
would be out of reach for most (an actor print by Sharaku just sold
at Christie's for $280,000), there are still many prints in fine
condition available for as little as $3,000 or $4,000. ``You might
not be able to afford a fine print of `Ohashi,''' Martin said.
``But there are excellent prints from the same series that you
could buy for $3,000. The market, today as in the past, is driven
by changing tastes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
