<P>
   HEALTH-INSURANCE _ WASHINGTON Nearly 2 million previously
uninsured Americans gained health-care coverage last year, the
first time in 12 years that the number of people without health
insurance dropped. Analysts point to the country's low jobless rate
and broader health coverage plans by employers as contributing to
the turnaround. Still, the number of uninsured Americans,
particularly among the poor, remained high. The number of people
without health insurance declined by 1.7 million between 1998 and
1999, from 44.3 million to 42.6 million. (Holmes, Cox News
Service). 25.
