   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   WEBMD _ WebMD Corp., the biggest Internet company linking
insurers, doctors and patients, will cut 1,100 jobs as it
eliminates overlap resulting from acquisitions. WebMD will take a
pretax charge of $35 million to $45 million in the third quarter,
the company said in a press release. WebMD has said it would close
offices, spend less on marketing and technology and cut jobs and
products to get rid of duplications. (Miller, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   HMO _ Last year health care costs rose about 7 percent
nationwide. This year, double-digit increases are forecast. The
main reason this is happening is that managed care companies
charged less than the market value for years, as they competed for
contracts and market share. But in 1998, that changed. Companies
decided they wanted to turn a profit and the skyrocketing cost of
prescription drugs and lower government reimbursements cut into the
bottom line. But while state government and UT workers are facing
higher co-pays this year for their health insurance, other
companies -- notably in the high tech area -- aren't passing along
costs. We'll look at what companies are doing about rising health
care costs, what it means for employees and what's on the horizon.
40-50 (Bahadur, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
