<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5468 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUSKIN-CENTENARY-NYT &LR;      09-28 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSKIN-CENTENARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: HIGH PRIEST OF A BOUNDLESS ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   By GRACE GLUECK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Much has been made of John Ruskin (1819-1900) this
year, and not without a reason. It is the centenary of the death of
this artist, art and architectural critic extraordinaire, social
reformer, polymath lecturer, first official professor of art in
England (at Oxford University) and an admirer of little girls whose
mismarriage to a full-grown woman ended in disaster.
</P>
<P>
   So far in 2000, there has been a big Ruskin show at the Tate
Britain in London, another at the Yale Center for British Art and a
third at the Grolier Club in New York, as well as the publication
of ``John Ruskin: The Later Years,'' the second and last volume of
a biography by Tim Hilton (Yale University Press).
</P>
<P>
   Now the Morgan Library has mounted its own show of Ruskiniana,
``Ruskin's Italy, Ruskin's England,'' a biographical assemblage of
133 objects: letters, manuscripts, photographs, drawings, paintings
_ including several self-portraits _ and artifacts. They were mined
entirely from the Morgan's own Ruskin collection, proclaimed by the
library to be one of the world's most comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Ruskin's Italy, Ruskin's England'' can't exactly be
described as an art show, it has a number of paintings and drawings
by Ruskin himself as well as by the British artists J.M.W. Turner,
John Constable and the Pre-Raphaelites John Everett Millais,
William Holman Hunt, Edward Burne-Jones, Dante Gabriel Rossetti and
others in the Ruskin pantheon.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Ruskin's illustrious and influential career lay a
troubled life. He was the only child of wealthy and zealously
religious parents who refused to let go of him. (When he enrolled
at Oxford, his mother took up residence near the university.) His
disastrous marriage left him a lonely bachelor subject to fits of
unrequited love for little girls. He was also beset by bouts of
mental illness. In the end, this brilliant and privileged man died
in the care of relatives, and in his last decade he rarely spoke.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Ruskin's genius that this show celebrates: the
enormous energies as a writer, critic, artist, educator and
reformist that made him a giant of the Victorian age whose
published works ran to 39 volumes. He set new standards for
criticism, looking to art for morality, spirituality and a
reflection of nature's truth. His early interest in the work of
Turner inspired the eloquent if sometimes longwinded meditations on
art and architecture that began with his first book, the
five-volume ``Modern Painters'' (1843-1860).
</P>
<P>
   The meditations continued in ``The Seven Lamps of Architecture''
(1849), a paean to medieval architecture as the true expression of
national values, which established Ruskin as a leader in the Gothic
Revival movement. And in ``The Stones of Venice'' (1851-53) he
extolled Venetian Gothic architecture as reflecting national and
domestic integrity, as opposed to the ``corrupt'' Venetian
Renaissance that succeeded it. The books established him as the
most influential art critic and theorist of the age.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition starts with Ruskin's family and childhood. Early
on he showed signs of his polymath talents: he collected minerals,
wrote poetry, and at the age of 10 composed a book of ``Amusing
Characters for Children,'' for which he drew color illustrations
copied from George Cruikshank's drawings for ``Grimms' Fairy
Tales.'' Also on view are 18 sermons he wrote between ages 13 and
15 on the first five books of the Bible, hand-bound into five thin
booklets.
</P>
<P>
   Among the show's highlights are a number of Ruskin's detailed
drawings and quick sketches for ``The Seven Lamps of
Architecture.'' He never regarded his drawings as art but as useful
notes. Still, his precise and elegant draftsmanship is nothing
short of beautiful, exemplified in a meticulously shaded rendering
of the stone balls surrounded by flowing leaves that adorn part of
the central gate of St. Mark's in Venice. ``It looks as if its
leaves had been sensitive, and had risen and shut themselves into a
bud at some sudden touch, and would presently fall back again into
their wild flow,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he was preparing ``The Stones of Venice,'' Ruskin's
marriage (in 1848) to Euphemia Gray, the daughter of a business
acquaintance of his father, was falling apart. Holograph letters
from ``Effie'' to her parents detail the main causes: too much
interference from Ruskin's parents, his absorption in his work and
his sexual indifference, not to say disdain. In 1854 the marriage
was annulled, and the next year she wed Millais, the painter, until
then a close Ruskin friend.
</P>
<P>
   Also touched on is Ruskin's famous rejection of Whistler's
``Nocturne in Black and Gold: The Falling Rocket,'' offered at the
Grosvenor Gallery in 1877 for 200 guineas. ``I have seen, and
heard, much of Cockney impudence before now,'' Ruskin wrote, ``but
never expected to hear a coxcomb ask 200 guineas for flinging a pot
of paint in the public's face.''
</P>
<P>
   Whistler sued, winning only a farthing in damages, and was
bankrupted by the court costs. But posterity has declared in his
favor. Shown here are a copy of his 1878 book, ``Whistler vs.
Ruskin: Art and Art Critics,'' and a holograph letter of 1878 from
Burne-Jones to Ruskin about the former's court appearance in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The show touches on many other aspects of Ruskin's life and
career, including his work as a social reformer and
environmentalist who he pushed for a minimum wage, pensions and
nationalized education and his pathetic infatuation with a
10-year-old girl named Rose La Touche, whom he met when he was 39
and tried to reach by spiritualism after her early death.
</P>
<P>
   The end of Ruskin's life is sadly sketched out in notes made by
him during periods of mental collapse. ``Worst horror I ever
knew,'' is the terse comment in one of them. His working career
ended in 1889, and there is a terrible photograph of him, vacant of
expression and much diminished physically, as he slumps on a bench
next to the robust female cousin who took care of him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he left behind much to commemorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruskin's Italy, Ruskin's England'' is at the Morgan Library,
29 East 36th Street, Manhattan, (212) 685-0610, through Jan. 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
