<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-BIOGRAPHY-LIF     09-28 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-BIOGRAPHY-LIFEGAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIFEGAME': YOUR STORY, TRANSFORMED ON THE SPOT INTO THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 (Eds: This was originally scheduled as BC-BIOGRAPHY-THEATER) 
By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The odds are you have never heard of the star of
``Lifegame,'' the piquant, oddly touching new offering from the
ever-resourceful Improbable Theater. Certainly, I had never heard
of one Nancy Rosenthal, who on the night I caught the show held the
stage of the Jane Street Theater with a commanding, radiant
centeredness. I would recommend that you go see the charismatic
Rosenthal, a self-described ``stay-at-home Mom'' of 45, except that
her run ended the night it began. The stars of ``Lifegame'' are
stars for only two hours.
</P>
<P>
   This latest work from the young British troupe that turned
Scotch tape into ectoplasm in ``70 Hill Lane,'' the real-life
haunted-house drama that was their maiden outing in New York, is
now turning instant biography into instant, multiform theater. The
show is based riskily on the classic premises that everyone has a
story to tell and that no examined life is truly boring.
</P>
<P>
   Each evening, a preselected volunteer (not drawn from that
night's audience) is brought onstage and asked basic biographical
questions by a single, mercifully tactful interviewer (who changes
nightly). This is conducted rather in the manner of a television
talk show, though not of the confrontational sort. The volunteer's
answers are quickly _ sometimes even simultaneously _ turned into
vignettes by the company's seven-member ensemble. This is your
life, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lifegame,'' which was created by Keith Johnstone and has been
previously seen in London and San Diego, sounds like the kind of
performance that you would attend only at gunpoint and then spend
staring at your shoes. After all, the potential for disaster, of
both the humiliating and the boring varieties, is large. Anyway,
haven't we had enough of ordinary people doing psychological (and
sometimes literal) stripteases on daytime television?
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a glowing gentleness about ``Lifegame,'' a
curiosity coupled with respect, that keeps it a healthy distance
from a tabloid sensibility. It is made clear from the beginning
that the guests control the direction of the evening: they can
provide and withhold information as they see fit. As the show
progresses, the effect is less Jerry Springer than Federico Fellini
_ that is, as in the later, warmer memory films of Fellini, like
``Amarcord,'' or its American cousin, Woody Allen's ``Radio Days.''
</P>
<P>
   As in those movies, basic recollections of childhood are given
an exaggerated life that combines comic flourish with deep
wistfulness. Rosenthal, for example, had to give only a few
particulars of her child's eye view of her mother _ as a glamorous
looking woman who served food in a Brooklyn school cafeteria _ for
three ensemble members to assemble an immediate vision of boys
lining up to have their plates filled by a ladle-wielding femme
fatale. ``The boys were crazy about her,'' said Rosenthal, nodding
at the scene before her.
</P>
<P>
   The most commonplace recollections are often the most
inspirational for the seven-member company: Rosenthal's description
of turning down a date in junior high school became a musical set
piece with an impromptu ballad of teen-age angst and an ice-skating
puppet. A passing reference to a troubled love affair turned into a
hilarious five-second portrait of the reckless boyfriend who fast
became history. Extemporaneous music, from keyboard and sax,
floated in counterpoint, providing the soundtrack that every life
begs for.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it takes a fair amount of questioning to arrive at an
incident the performers can ride to interpretive heights. A couple
of vignettes died on the vine. Yet longeurs are few and usually
overridden by the combined feelings of suspense and good will one
feels for the people onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Each night, the visiting subject of ``Lifegame'' chooses an
alter ego among the performers. Guests may also participate as
actors if they choose. Rosenthal chose to and was remarkably
effective at playing her own grandmother and a nun schoolteacher
who sang the prepositions as a mnemonic device. She also recounted
a most tangled tale of courtship with the man who would become her
husband that left the others on stage open-mouthed and temporarily
silenced.
</P>
<P>
   This was either lucky or unlucky for the troupe, depending on
your point of view, since Rosenthal often upstaged the
professionals without ever seeming to try. It is telling that the
company appeared entirely comfortable with the situation, even
shaping the material so the evening would end logically with the
reappearance of the popular singing nun as embodied by Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``Lifegame'' so appealing is the clear sense that its
performers are there not to show off their obvious talents but to
provide a frame for others. It is as selfless-seeming a slice of
show business as I have ever witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   The show is nearly impossible to review in any conventional way,
since its tone and shape depend entirely upon its volunteer guest
star. But from my single experience of ``Lifegame,'' I can attest
that I was far more engrossed by the story of the protracted,
conflicted romance of Rosenthal and her husband-to-be than I have
ever been by chronicles of Bruce and Demi or Gwyneth and Ben.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LIFEGAME'  &QL; 
Created by Keith Johnstone; artistic direction and design by Phelim
McDermott, Lee Simpson and Julian Crouch; lighting by Colin
Grenfell; production stage manager, Jason Scott Eagan; general
management, EGS; production supervisor, Rob Conover. The Improbable
Theater Production presented by David Stone, Markley/Skipper, Nina
Essman and Julian Schlossberg. At the Jane Street Theater in
Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WITH: Niall Ashdown, Angela Clerkin, Guy Dartnell, Stella Duffy,
Phelim McDermott, Toby Park and Lee Simpson.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
