<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-TECHNICAL-ILLUSTRATOR     09-28 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNICAL-ILLUSTRATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHITECT'S ILLUSTRATIONS SIMPLY AND ELOQUENTLY EXPLAIN `BUILDING
BIG' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN LELAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An automobile piston, as anyone who has read David
Macaulay's 1988 best seller, ``The Way Things Work,'' can tell you,
is a simple reciprocating pump that operates on the principle of .
. . well, it would be a lot easier to explain using one of the
witty illustrations that fill Macaulay's books and television
programs.
</P>
<P>
   You could blow a gasket trying to explain some of the principles
that Macaulay, an author and illustrator, distills into simple,
illuminating images.
</P>
<P>
   Under a heavy sky in Brooklyn earlier this week, Macaulay, 53,
was at it again, pointing up at the maze of beams and cables
supporting the Brooklyn Bridge and talking about force. The
vertical cables, he explained, suspend the roadway from above,
while the diagonal cables fight wind sheer by . . . frankly, here
again it would help to call upon one of his eloquent sketches,
which combine the technical insight of a draftsman's drawings with
the chatty unpretentiousness of children's book illustrations. They
make long stories short and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge is one of the massive engineering projects Macaulay
seeks to demystify in his new book, ``Building Big'' (Houghton
Mifflin, $30), and in a five-part public television series of the
same name that begins on Tuesday. ``Building Big,'' whether book or
television program, comes stuffed with his illustrations,
explaining civil works of daunting complexity in simple,
comprehensible images and transforming physical principles into
engaging narratives. Along the way, the project examines the
confluence of ambition, risk and vision that has shaped the growth
of modern cities and the lives of the people who inhabit them.
</P>
<P>
   An architect by training, Macaulay has made a career of
explaining the mechanics of the commonplace fixtures of modern
life: the toasters, cathedrals, mills, ships and other engineering
feats whose inner lives often pass unexamined. The most popular of
Macaulay's books, ``The Way Things Work,'' has sold 2.5 million
copies, plus another 500,000 for a later version, updated as ``The
New Way Things Work,'' which adds explanations of things like CD
players and the computer mouse. In all his work, he focuses on the
bones of design, treating the visible surfaces as the obligatory
neat endings to more interesting hidden depths.
</P>
<P>
   At the Brooklyn waterfront, raising his voice to compete with
the wind and the traffic noise, Macaulay found he had a lot of
explaining to do. Imposing, homely edifices towered all around,
monumental constructions of steel and concrete encrusted with
layers of soot. Macaulay could not have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love process,'' he said, ``and these structures are all
about process. They're autobiographical. If you look closely at
them, they describe their origins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Building Big'' is Macaulay's way of letting those
autobiographies speak. Divided into five segments _ tunnels, dams,
skyscrapers, bridges and domes _ the project took him from the
Aswan High Dam in Egypt to the bowels of the Holland Tunnel.
Combining social history with engineering basics, the book and
series examine the forces of ego as well as those of tension and
compression, and the ways those forces conspire to create the
alternatively inspiring and oppressive cityscapes in which modern
urban residents live and work.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Building Big'' marvels at the scale and daring of its
huge edifices, Macaulay and his producers are careful to note the
consequences of the underlying ambitions. Some dams, particularly
in the Pacific Northwest, have prevented salmon from swimming
upstream to their spawning grounds, contributing to the extinction
of as many as 100 salmon species; 500 workers died building the
Aswan Dam. Big structures have big impacts on the environments
around them.
</P>
<P>
   But Macaulay reserves his harshest criticisms for skyscrapers,
whose rise he traces from the stone towers erected by feuding clans
in San Gimignano, in Tuscany, to the ugly glass boxes of the
International style that lurch upward with little regard for the
other buildings around them or the people slumped inside. The
modern city, he says, is dehumanized by architecture that fails its
narrative function.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a skyscraper says something about how it works, it engages
you,'' he said. ``If it's just a box, you're held back,'' reducing
a building to ``a storage system for the people inside.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own home life, Macaulay has sought a smaller scale. With
his wife and two young children, he lives in an 1848 Gothic revival
house in the coastal town of Bristol, R.I., and makes his studio
above a nearby shipbuilding museum. The house has required
extensive renovation over the years, and Macaulay, following the
pull of his curiosity, has busied himself with plaster and molding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bigger on the destruction end, tearing down a bathroom,''
he said, than putting it all together again. ``I leave that to the
contractor.'' But for an illustrator who specializes in pulling
things apart, such demolition provides another way to tell the
story of a building.
</P>
<P>
   The most harrowing story in ``Building Big,'' a segment that
appears in the television series but not in the book, raises the
prospect of destruction on a much larger scale. During the
construction of the Citicorp Center in Manhattan, contractors cut
costs by bolting together a series of joints, rather than welding
them. A small change, but as engineers realized during
construction, it left the building unable to withstand punishing
winds. As Hurricane Ella approached in 1962, city officials met
secretly with the Red Cross to discuss plans for evacuating
Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Ella, fortunately, turned out to sea, and welders secured the
construction. But the lesson remains at the core of ``Building
Big'': every desire for bigness comes with human costs, often
reducible to formulas. Macaulay makes these formulas easy to
understand, and all the more brutal in their clarity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
