<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-REVIEW-HIRST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DAMIEN HIRST'S UNIVERSE, GLASS AND STEEL MEET PILLS AND PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERTA SMITH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Contrary to rumors that the young British artist
Damien Hirst has forsaken art for the business of advertising or
restaurant running, he seems to have gone into overproduction. His
third solo show in New York, which inaugurates the palatial
redesign of the Gagosian Gallery in Chelsea, is an extravaganza of
paintings and room-size vitrine sculptures, including two that have
been outfitted as gynecological examination rooms and then filled
with water and fish, to great Surrealistic effect.
</P>
<P>
   Walking through this museum-size show, which can sometimes seem
about twice too big, it is irresistible to wonder, first, which
cost more, the renovation of the gallery or the production of the
works on view, and, second, what Hirst would have done had he not
had so much money at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   To a certain extent the ends justify the means. This is a strong
show, far more coherent than the jumble of work Hirst presented in
his previous Gagosian effort. There are undeniable duds. I would
avoid anything with Ping-Pong balls, bobbing or stationary; also
the pair of shrouded faux cadavers titled ``Adam and Eve.'' And the
giant anatomical figure made of painted bronze in the front gallery
might as well be a kiosk pointing the way to other works.
</P>
<P>
   Still, so long as the fish remain healthy, this exhibition shows
Hirst moving beyond the dead animals and putrefying flesh that
catapulted him to fame while clarifying and enriching the grandiose
themes of his art: life and death and their complex, sometimes
oppressive relationship to science and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   This show presents what might be called the Damien Hirst
Universe. It is a big, shiny place with gigantic graph-paper grids
printed on many of the walls; pale dot paintings; expanses of
gleaming glass, mirror and stainless steel; and scores of pristine,
beautifully presented objects _ elements that frequently coalesce
into moments of clarity and beauty and something approximating
wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Row upon row of shiny medical instruments occupy one wall
vitrine along with two skeletons, separately coffered. In another,
the handmade, actual-size models of 8,000 pills are laid out like
gems on thin metal shelves. ``Trinity'' consists of three towering
wall cabinets whose brightly colored anatomical mannequins and
models of organs and limbs gaily deconstruct the human body.
</P>
<P>
   In the best works, Hirst brings the visual and mental, the
material and the literary, into perfect balance. One shiny vitrine
presents the artificial skeletons of two dozen small mammals, all
perfect and white with their miraculous engineering everywhere
apparent; it is as wonderful to look at them as structures as it is
to identify the animals (several dogs and cats) and to find one's
reverence encapsulated in the work's title, ``Something Solid
Beneath the Surface of Several Things Wise and Wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   The displays confirm that Hirst has raided every postwar art
movement from Minimalism to Pop to Super Realism to Neo-Geo. His
main feat is the appropriation of the Minimalist box. His vitrines
and, now, vitrines-within-vitrines are crucial in the way they
encase, monumentalize and aestheticize his tableaux and create a
needed sense of distance for the viewer. And despite his
Neo-Geo-like use of store-bought commodities, this show also
reminds us that his work is so sincere, and even sweet at times,
that it should be called post-postmodern.
</P>
<P>
   Hirst's main objective seems to be to get us to look at the
wonders and horrors of natural life and to realize not only that
they are often the same thing, but also that both have been
intensified by man's pursuit of knowledge. Another objective may be
to simply prepare us for the inevitable: decline and death. It is
somehow comforting to be introduced to all those medical
instruments in the guise of art. The next time many of us see them,
they may be being applied to our own bodies.
</P>
<P>
   He is interested in both sides of any position. In ``A Way of
Seeing,'' he creates a comforting image of a scientist as bohemian
and as seer: a meticulously real life-size sculpture inside a
double vitrine depicts a man with a ponytail who is wearing a lab
coat and jeans as he sits at a desk staring into a microscope,
surrounded by a strip of sandy, carefree beach.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the pitfalls of progress are also in evidence. In ``Looking
Forward to the Total and Absolute Suppression of Pain,'' a walk-in
vitrine where the use of clear and mirrored glass may bring to mind
the work of Dan Graham, four television monitors, installed at
hospital-room height, blast the viewer with nonstop commercials for
painkillers.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments when Hirst's pursuit of accessibility rolls
over into obviousness, as in the segmented vitrine filled with
plump garbage bags and room fresheners where the punch line is
``Stop Me B4 I Kill Again,'' scrawled on the tarnished mirror of an
old wardrobe. And the way these works fit together and play against
one another can make you wonder how some of them will stand on
their own. But on the whole this exhibition gives New York a sense
of Hirst as an artist with big, life-affirming messages to get
across, determined to do so without preaching, and in terms as
close to purely visual as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
