<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MORRIS-TALK0929-COX     09-28 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORRIS-TALK0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Clinton strategist assesses Internet potential
 &HT;    By David Brown
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Ohio _ Well-known political strategist and commentator
Dick Morris focused on the future power of the Internet on
Wednesday night at Miami University. Morris was on campus as part
of the Miami University Lecture Series. Following his lecture at
Hall Auditorium about the Internet and an extended question and
answer session that delved into a variety of political topics,
Morris continued to entertain questions for more than an hour at a
</P>
<P>
   reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the cusp of gigantic change,'' said Morris, who is
president of the nonpartisan Web site Vote.com. ``And it all comes
about as a result of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, chief strategist for President Clinton's 1996
re-election campaign, said the most important aspect of the
Internet is that it eliminates cost and obstacles to communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's free, it's instant, and it's global,'' Morris said,
adding that the Thomas Jefferson model of democracy could be
possible through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson once said, in 1793, ``I subscribe to the principle,
that the will of the majority honestly expressed should give law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas Jefferson would have loved the Internet,'' Morris said.
``The logistical reasons Thomas Jefferson's ideals failed are no
longer valid. But now that we can have it, should we have it?''
</P>
<P>
   Morris said he sees a future where referendums will play a much
larger role in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, people will have more and more control over the
institutions that govern them,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the digital divide locking out the poor who have no
computers and the elderly who don't know how to use computers,
Morris said in two or three years Internet access will come via
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, there's no more digital divide,'' Morris said.
``Everyone watches TV.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Morris, television viewing is going down while
Internet usage is up. He sees that trend continuing and politicians
adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are like lions. When the antelope migrate, so do
the lions,'' Morris said. ``When people leave TV to go to the
Internet, the politicians will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   He said political and candidate sites will have to be
continually updated and interesting to lure viewers _ and potential
voters. Morris said if he were running the presidential campaign of
either Al Gore or
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, he would have targeted Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 123 million e-addresses right now,'' Morris said.
``If I were running a campaign, I would have given away anything to
get you to give me your e-mail address.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the touch of a button could send out positive
information on his candidate to those 123 million people. A spike
in the polls would surely follow, and the opposition would have to
launch an ad campaign. At that point, Morris said he could then
launch something negative against the opponent, and 123 million
people would receive it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, my finger would defeat his money and my
candidate would win the election,'' Morris said, illustrating the
power of the Internet and the reason big money won't be as
important in future campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
