<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW HOME FOR OLD MASTERS; GIFT TO NEW MUSEUM; JASPER JOHNS IN
HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (Inside Art) 
(ATT: Okla., Texas, N.Y.) 
 By   CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A major gift has transformed the University of Oklahoma into a
repository of Impressionist and Post-Impressionist paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Clara Weitzenhoffer, an art collector and longtime arts
supporter who died in July, bequeathed her collection of 33 works,
including 22 paintings and 11 works on paper by van Gogh, Degas,
Gauguin and Monet. It is the largest collection of French
Impressionist art ever given to a public American university.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was formed in the 1950s and '60s by Weitzenhoffer
and her husband, Aaron, a founder of the Davon Oil Co. who died in
1960. They lived in Oklahoma City and La Jolla, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Weitzenhoffer also gave the university her collection of 17th-
and 18th-century furniture and decorative objects. The total gift
is valued at more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Both the art and objects will eventually be on display in a new
$10 million addition to the university Museum of Art in Norman,
Okla. The addition, which is being designed by the Washington
architect Hugh Newell Jacobsen, will not be completed for several
years, but the collection will be displayed at the Museum of Art
from Nov. 14 through Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   David L. Boren, former Oklahoma governor and senator and the
president of the university, said that he met Weitzenhoffer through
her son, A. Max Weitzenhoffer, a theater producer and university
alumnus, and that her son played a role in the gift. The highlights
include a van Gogh portrait (circa 1886-88) of Alexander Reid, a
British art dealer and painter; Gauguin's ``Copenhagen'' (1886), a
snowy street scene, in muted tones; Pissarro's ``Shepherdess
Bringing In the Sheep'' (1886); and Monet's ``Riverbank at
Lavacourt'' (1879).
</P>
<P>
   ``Norman will become a destination,'' Boren said. ``We had
100,000 visitors in the first week when we opened our Natural
History Museum this spring.'' Since 1994 the university has been
working to improve its arts complex. The campus now has a new $16
million concert hall and the Charles M. Russell Center for the
Study of Art of the American West.
</P>
<P>
   BIG GIFT TO NEW MUSEUM
</P>
<P>
   Corporations are becoming more creative about their art
collections. An example is Altoids, the maker of ``the curiously
strong mints.'' A subsidiary of Philip Morris, Altoids has been
quietly putting together a collection of works by emerging artists
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   This week it announced that it had donated the entire collection
of some 70 works to the New Museum of Contemporary Art in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   The collection, amassed with the help of a panel of arts
professionals, features artworks by visual artists working in the
United States, with each piece acquired for less than $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Each year Altoids has presented its new acquisitions in a tour
of five or six cities, including New York, Chicago and Miami. But
the company decided it needed a permanent home for its growing
collection where the public could view the artworks on a regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   The donation is the first corporate gift to the New Museum as
well as the biggest collection it has received.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at a lot of places,'' said Andrew Burke, brand
manager of Altoids. ``But the New Museum, we felt, was the best for
trying to recognize these great artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The gift includes works by artists including Laylah Ali, D.L.
Alvarez, Jessica Craig-Martin, Sam Durant Barry McGee and Dario
Robleto. It is conservatively valued at $175,000, Altoids said
</P>
<P>
   The works will go on view at the museum from Jan. 12 to 28.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER JOHNS IN HOUSTON
</P>
<P>
   With the completion of its new $50 million building designed by
the architect Jose Rafael Moneo, the Museum of Fine Arts in Houston
is focusing on expanding its collection. It has made progress in
strengthening its photography holdings and is now turning its
attention to contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   Among its latest acquisitions are Jasper Johns' ``Untitled (Red
Yellow Blue)'' painting from 1984, six related etchings and a
lithograph. The painting, which experts value from $12 million to
$15 million, was purchased from the artist with funds from the
Brown Foundation in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought Johns' `Ventriloquist' in 1984 from Leo Castelli and
we have the related prints and drawings,'' said Peter C. Marzio,
the museum's director. ``So we contacted Jasper Johns and said we
wanted not just a paintings but work that showed its beginnings and
its afterlife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Untitled (Red Yellow Blue)'' consists of three panels divided
into horizontal sections and incorporates many of the artist's
familiar motifs: stenciled letters, imprints of the artist's hand
and a handkerchief suspended from two nails (in homage to the
19th-century American trompe l'oeil painter John Frederick Peto).
</P>
<P>
   The works will go on view toward the end of October, Marzio
said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
