<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GREEK-VICTORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A HELLAS OF A WIN FOR GREECE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ For the first time in, oh, 2,000 years or
so, a Greek athlete has won a gold medal at 200 meters in the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the Greeks staged Olympic Games that are considered
Ancient today.
</P>
<P>
   But never in the history of the Modern Olympics has a Greek
athlete won a gold medal in the 200-meter dash. Or any medal, for
that matter.
</P>
<P>
   History was made Thursday night at Stadium Australia when
Konstantinos Kenteris shocked the sprinting world by winning the
200 in 20.09 seconds over a field of more accomplished dashmen.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenteris deserved his stunning victory as he came from a
meter behind in the last 80 meters of the race to post a time of
20.09 seconds, a new national record for the country that calls
itself Hellas.
</P>
<P>
   Hellas of a win, Konstantinos. In fact, the last Olympic track
and field medal won by a Greek man was also named Konstantinos. In
the long-discontinued standing long jump, Konstantinos Tsiklitras
won the gold medal in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it was the slowest winning time in an Olympic
Games since Moscow in 1980, when Pietro Mennea of Italy ran 20.19
for the gold. Not having men like Michael Johnson, Maurice Greene
or Frankie Fredericks in the race will do that for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the moment I stepped into this country I realized the
others didn't have anything better than me,'' the 27-year-old
Kenteris said. ``I knew I had a chance, especially as there were
five black runners and I was the only white.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the wonders of Olympic translation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that I've won,'' Kenteris said. ``I didn't
come here to lose, I came here to win. I said Konstan the Greek
would win.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's about time, Konnie. See you in Athens in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Campbell of Great Britain came across the finish in 20.14
for the silver medal. Just as he had in Atlanta in 1996, Ato Boldon
of Trinidad and Tobago got the bronze medal in 20.20, a significant
accomplishment considering he ran from the island of lane eight.
</P>
<P>
   Just how different Sydney 2000 was different from Atlanta 1996
was reflected in the comparative times. Michael Johnson's run for
the ages in Atlanta with his astonishing time of 19.32. Fredericks
of Namibia ran 19.68 for the silver and Boldon the Bronze came
through in 19.80.
</P>
<P>
   And where were the Americans, who had won the last four gold
medals in the Olympic 200? Still running for the finish line, or so
it would appear from the dreadful form posted by the callow duo of
Coby Miller and John Capel.
</P>
<P>
   Miller finished seventh in 20.35. Even worse was Capel, who ran
a personal best 19.85 to win the Olympic Trials race in Sacramento
that featured Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene sprawled on the
track in agony with hamstring cramps.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, while an obscure Greek made history, Capel
finished last in 20.49.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
