<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5498 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-DEBATES-$ADV01-HNS &LR;      09-28 1749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH-GORE DEBATES MAY BE `THE WHOLE BALLGAME' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Millions of voters will get a chance to see
Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush in a live,
unscripted showdown Tuesday night when the presidential contenders
square-off in the first of three debates that could sway the
outcome of the closest presidential election in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the 52-year-old vice president, and Bush, the 54-year-old
governor of Texas, will be trying to sell themselves to voters as
the best man to succeed President Clinton when he leaves office in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from staking out competing policy positions, the
candidates are hoping to portray themselves as attractive
personalities and smart leaders. Bush hopes to steel his aw-shucks
appeal with the detailed knowledge required of a president. Gore is
looking to connect with voters by toning down his lofty
policy-laden discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The three debates offer the candidates a total of 4 hours and 30
minutes of free, unfiltered prime time television time to reach
millions of TV viewers drawn to an OK-Corral format that can spark
memorable one-liners and disastrous gaffes _ and serve as grist for
chit chat at the office water cooler for days afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kirk, the former Democratic chairman who co-chairs the
unofficial bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates, likens
the debates to subjecting candidates to ``job interviews with the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk adds: ``The debates help voters decide if they want this
guy in their homes on their television sets for the next four
years. This is as real as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the University of
Virginia, says the looming debates ``will be the whole ball game''
_ as decisive as the encounters in 1960, 1976 and 1980 that gave
challengers the momentum to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a veteran of five nationally televised presidential
campaign debates, says the encounters ``give voters the best chance
they can get to take the measure of a person under some fire.''
Clinton added in an interview for the Public Broadcasting System's
``Debating Our Destiny'' project: The debates ``show whether you
can understand a situation in a hurry and respond to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-Gore debate on Tuesday at 9 p.m. EDT takes place in
Boston at the University of Massachusetts adjacent to the John F.
Kennedy presidential library, with the candidates standing behind
lecterns.
</P>
<P>
   Their vice presidential running mates, Republican Dick Cheney
and Democrat Joe Lieberman, debate Thursday at Centre College in
Danville, Ky., seated with a moderator.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore meet again on Oct. 11 at Wake Forest University in
Winston-Salem, N.C., in a talk-show style format, seated
side-by-side with a moderator. The candidates last week for a
debate on Oct. 17 at Washington University in St. Louis, Mo., for a
town hall-style meeting fielding questions from citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Each presidential debate is 90 minutes long and will be anchored
by Jim Lehrer of PBS.
</P>
<P>
   The ground rules permit the candidates to take notes during
their exchanges, but not to bring anything into the hall, such as
crib sheets or props that can be used to challenge their rival.
Video excerpts from the debate cannot be used by the rival campaign
for campaign ads but political parties and independent political
organizations are free to harvest the moments of triumph or
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite candidates' pre-debate jockeying to lower expectations
for their own performance and raise the bar for their rival, Gore
and Bush head into the debates with formidable reputations for
staging stunts, blunting rivals' parries and recovering from snafus
on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a veteran of three presidential campaigns and 24 years in
the House, Senate and vice presidency, has repeatedly demonstrated
his knack for the political jugular during debates, including
during the battle for the Democratic presidential nomination
against former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Gore dramatically challenged Bradley's vote as a senator against
federal disaster relief for flooded farmers during a debate before
the Iowa caucuses in January, by introducing an Iowa farmer in the
audience who suffered flood damage on 300 acres in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you vote against the disaster relief for Chris
Peterson when he and thousands of other farmers here in Iowa needed
it after those '93 floods?'' Gore demanded of Bradley in the
debate's most dramatic moment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has demonstrated an ability to recover from debate
mistakes, backpedaling quickly during the Democratic presidential
primaries after telling voters in a campaign debate with Bradley in
New Hampshire that he would impose a ``litmus test'' requiring
prospective appointees to the Joint Chiefs of Staff to fully
support allowing homosexuals to serve openly in the nation's armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Gore quelled a political firestorm two days later by saying that
he would only require military officers to carry out his policies
as president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore showed in his 1992 debate with then-Vice President Dan
Quayle that he can thrust and parry, as well. When Quayle insisted
that Clinton had ``trouble telling the truth,'' Gore snapped back
with a rejoinder reminding voters of President George Bush's
flip-flop on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush, in case you've forgotten Dan, said, `Read my
lips, no new taxes,'' Gore injected.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato says that Gore should ``make his policy points without
being arrogant or appearing school-marmish.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican presidential nominee defeated by
the Clinton-Gore ticket, said in a PBS interview that Gore has to
fight the same tendency to dote on specifics that he had as a
senator-turned-nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're running for president _ they don't need to know how the
watch is made,'' Dole advised. ``Just tell them what time it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, saying he views the encounter as ``a great opportunity to
explain my vision for the country,'' says his tight race with ``a
sitting vice president with the economy pretty good and the world
at peace indicates I have got a very good chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush may have the least experience in government of any
presidential candidate since retired Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower ran
in 1952. But the son of the former president won his shot at the
presidency in the first place by besting silver-tongued Texas Gov.
Ann Richards in a gubernatorial upset in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, an ex-oil field entrepreneur and baseball team owner,
tangled effectively during the GOP presidential primaries with his
most durable rival, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a master of 17 years
of give-and-take in the House and Senate. Bush surprised McCain and
threw the ex-Navy fighter pilot on the defensive during a campaign
debate in the South Carolina primary by wielding a negative
campaign leaflet sponsored by the McCain campaign that had appeared
on a voter's windshield after McCain promised to end negative
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato says that Bush must appear presidential and in command of
policy details to combat some voters' concerns that the Yale- and
Harvard-educated multimillionaire is ``not bright enough or quick
enough on his feet to serve as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabato adds: ``People will be looking to see whether he is truly
articulate and knowledgeable _ or grammatically challenged as he
has been on some occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said one mistake he hopes to avoid is glancing at his watch
as his father did impatiently during the three-way presidential
debate in 1992. As the GOP nominee put it: ``I'm not going to be
looking at my watch, I can assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   Former President George H.W. Bush recalled that moment in an
interview for the PBS documentary. ``It took a little incident like
that to show that I was, you know, out of it,'' the former
president recalled. ``They made a huge thing out of that.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 80 million Americans are expected to view the first
debate, Kirk said, down from the record of 98 million who viewed
the final presidential debate in 1992 but above the 66.4 million
who viewed the first nationally televised presidential debate in
1960 between then-Vice President Richard M. Nixon and Sen. John F.
Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The major broadcast and cable television networks will broadcast
the Tuesday night debate, with the exception of NBC and Fox which
have opted out of national broadcast coverage, citing other
broadcast commitments.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dole, like other presidential and vice presidential candidates
who have endured laser-like scrutiny during the 18 presidential and
five vice presidential nationally televised debates since 1960,
knows the dangers of words gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, known at the time as an acerbic Kansan, dealt his ticket a
blow in 1976 when, as the GOP vice presidential nominee, he charged
that 1.7 million Americans had been killed ``in Democrat wars in
this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Then-President Gerald Ford committed a gaffe of his own in a
1976 debate with former Georgia Gov. Jimmy Carter, insisting in the
midst of the Soviet Union's Cold War control of Eastern Europe that
``there is no Soviet domination of Eastern Europe and there never
will be under a Ford administration.'' The Ford-Dole ticket lost.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Mondale, the former vice president who carried the
Democrats' banner in 1984, paid the price for a triumphant one
liner by his rival. Then-President Ronald Reagan, 73 and the oldest
person to serve as president, had appeared flustered at points
during the first Reagan-Mondale debate.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second showdown, Reagan was affable, relaxed and in
command. When questioned about his earlier performance and the
impact of age, Reagan quipped: ``I want you to know I will not make
age an issue of this campaign. I am not going to exploit for
political purposes my opponent's youth and inexperience.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondale, in his interview for the PBS special, said he knew his
campaign was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked off and I was almost certain the campaign was over _
and it was,'' Mondale recalled. Reagan carried every state against
Mondale except the challenger's native Minnesota and the District
of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
