<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5499 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-HUMMER0929-COX     09-28 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HUMMER0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even in defeat, U.S. team a winner
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ World Cup heroine Brandi Chastain has a message for
those who might get a little excited over one excruciating Olympic
loss, maybe try to turn it into a sad farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Aw, keep your shirt on.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain knighted the Americans' 3-2 sudden-death gold medal
loss to Norway as the best women's soccer game she's ever played a
part in. Divorcing oneself from the result, it would be impossible
not to get swept up in the tension and the violent back-and-forth.
``I can hardly wait to watch the video of this one. This was a game
you could enjoy as a fan,'' the world's most reasonable silver
medalist said.
</P>
<P>
   The role of Chastain this night was played by Dagny Mellgren.
But unlike the poor man's strip tease that took place when Chastain
booted the deciding shootout goal in the '99 World Cup, Mellgren
remained in uniform after her winning boot. No matter the signs
sprouting around the Sydney Football Stadium with the highly
un-Olympian message, ``Show Us Your Sports Bra.''
</P>
<P>
   Resulting was a scene that would have once been thought
oxymoronic _ delirious Norwegians
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps a jumping-off place for the team that invented
women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   It's still difficult to believe that the now-familiar crew of
Hamm and Chastain, Foudy and Milbrett, did not defend the Olympic
gold won in Athens. You invest so much in giving women's soccer an
identity, the least you should expect in return is to win
everything in sight before dissolving.
</P>
<P>
   And dissolve this group inevitably will. Mia Hamm and Kristine
Lilly made their debuts with the U.S. team when they were 15 and
16, and it has been 13 hard years of campaigning since. Michelle
Akers has retired, Chastain and Joy Fawcett are 32. A generation of
pioneers is passing.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, a women's professional soccer league is on the way, but
there'll not be another major international gathering until the
2003 World Cup. The personality of the U.S. team is bound to change
before then.
</P>
<P>
   Putting this bunch in perspective, grandly, was coach April
Heinrichs: ``It would be the equivalent of having Johan Cruyff,
Franz Beckenbauer, George Best and Pele all on the same team, the
same 10 years. No coach will ever have that again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd need a book to explain it, more than a quick answer or
sound bite,'' Heinrichs said. ``They carried the flag for a lot of
women's sports, not just soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   The night was all set up for them to deliver one last,
devastating jolt. Trailing 2-1, Tiffeny Milbrett headed in her
second goal of the night in the very last second of stoppage time.
On to sudden-death extra time. Could another shootout and some
victory display featuring feather boas be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   But this was the one opponent capable of ruining a good time.
Even as the U.S. had beaten the Norwegians 2-0 earlier in the
Olympic competition, it was wary. Norway was the only team to ever
take down the Americans in a major international competition (the
'95 World Cup). The Norsewomen were not intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12th minute of overtime, Mellgren struck. It could have
been called a hand ball and no goal as the high pass to the front
of the U.S. net appeared to bounce off Mellgren's arm before her
soft shot got through goalkeeper Siri Mullinix. When it wasn't, the
Americans didn't cuss and spit and pull out their hair, another
reason to honor them.
</P>
<P>
   The critical eye saw Norwegian goalkeeper Bente Nordby outplay
Mullinix (who faced only three shots on goal, stopping none of
them). It saw the Norwegian defense come up large and the U.S.
waste too many opportunities. It saw so much energy expended in
getting that last-second goal that there was little left for
overtime. Nothing left but shock.
</P>
<P>
   The more deliberate eye saw a team proud of what it has done and
eagerly seeking heirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost games before in my life,'' Chastain said.
``Ultimately, I don't see us as losers. This team has done more for
this sport than anyone can imagine. That seems like a winner to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
