<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran, mechanics settle on new contract
 &HT;    By Nancy Fonti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AirTran Airways and its mechanics' union settled on a
new contract Thursday, three days before the current pact would
become amendable.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's 350 mechanics and inspectors, who are represented
by the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, must ratify the
five-year agreement and will vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran and the Teamsters came to an agreement quickly
considering that in the airline industry talks between companies
and workers often drag on for years before a pact is reached.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups had informally negotiated since spring.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when the airline was forced to cancel flights, the
company suggested that employees frustrated with talks were causing
a work slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very close to agreeing on the contract last week and
then we had a couple of delays,'' said AirTran Marketing Director
Tad Hutcheson. ``We're extremely pleased with this contract ... we
believe the aircraft mechanics and inspectors will overwhelmingly
ratify it.''
</P>
<P>
   AirTran said the contract calls for higher wages, benefits and
better job security but declined to release details. Teamsters
officials could not be reached Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first contract renewal for AirTran and its
mechanics. The pilots' contract, which becomes amendable in April,
will be negotiated next.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
