<HEADER>
A5503 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-28 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THERE'S MORE TO IT THAN KISSING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If it weren't all so darn patronizing, we female
voters might actually feel spoiled.
</P>
<P>
   Much political talk these days has turned to ways of wooing
women's votes. It echoes the mood in the so-called ``year of the
woman'' in 1992 in which more women were sought after. They won
more congressional seats that year than in the previous 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Their victory reflected a pent-up fury at Republican policies of
the prior decade _ policies that many women felt pandered to male
interests and repressed females' economic and legal progress.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later voters responded to modified GOP rhetoric by
pushing many female politicians back into the familiar also-ran
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   In the current campaign do we think anything will really change
for most of us when this election is over? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   The two major candidates are treating us again like some
monolithic female army marching in lock-step in response to
programmed political strategies that they think move us, but not
men.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying truth here, however, is that we still aren't
taken seriously. And it's partly our own fault.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that after the Democratic convention women swung to
Vice President Al Gore because of his passionate smooch with wife
Tipper and then swung back last week to Gov. George W. Bush because
of his televised peck on Oprah Winfrey's cheek. That's what polls
seem to suggest.
</P>
<P>
   A visible touch of humanity never hurts a public figure, but the
idea that symbolic or social kissing is what matters most to women
is silly.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have been appearing on daytime and late-night TV
chat shows popular with stay-at-home folks. The theory is that
candidates who want to spend their days running the country must
identify with homemakers who spend their days running the vacuum
cleaner. Neither Gore nor Bush has yet produced a cookie recipe but
Bush has talked about his love of peanut butter sandwiches and Gore
jokes that a union song was his mother's lullaby to him when he was
a baby.
</P>
<P>
   This television frivolity is meant to be a bonding experience
that will result in votes on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush have gaggles of advisers trying to understand
women, whom both candidates, in their own campaigns, treat as a
strange species to be allowed only in small numbers into their
inner circles. They've got tokens, but not much else.
</P>
<P>
   The polls are shifting rapidly. So today's figures may not track
tomorrow. But at the moment a Los Angeles Times national poll shows
Bush with a 22-point advantage among men while Gore has a 6-point
advantage among women.
</P>
<P>
   The gender gap in which women generally favor Democrats over
Republicans opened in the 1980 campaign, in which Ronald Reagan
concentrated on the getting male vote with macho-oriented policies
that left women out. He did everything but go to a wrestling match.
</P>
<P>
   The imbalance has varied through subsequent presidential
campaigns, but the Democrats have consistently done better with
women than the Republicans, and they, in turn, have consistently
done better with men.
</P>
<P>
   Current surveys indicate that married women prefer Bush to Gore
and unmarried women prefer Gore to Bush. There are several theories
as to why this is so, but mostly it has to do with economics.
</P>
<P>
   Married women tend to have higher income and feel more secure.
They tend to be less sympathetic toward paying taxes for federal
social programs. Single or divorced women are more inclined toward
Democratic-backed initiatives such as a hike in the minimum wage,
day-care tax credits, family leave and support programs for
low-income elderly people.
</P>
<P>
   In appealing for female votes, Gore opts heavily for
family-oriented policy arguments, stressing those issues that
resonate with many women: gun control, abortion choice, aid for
college tuition, help for underfunded public schools, protection of
Medicare and new prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has problems with many women on the issues because he
opposes most gun control and abortion and favors plans to partially
privatize Social Security and provide taxpayer-paid vouchers to
parents to enable them to abandon bad public schools.
</P>
<P>
   He seldom talks about abortion and softens his education
language to avoid the word ``vouchers,'' talking instead about
discipline and instilling moral values.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also says that ``women are very discerning people. They are
going to ask the question, `What is the person's heart like?'''
</P>
<P>
   No, governor, this will never do. We're not choosing a lifetime
soul-mate with a heart full of love. We're picking a president,
heaven help us.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to ask, ``What are the person's policies like? Will
they help us or hurt us?'' And that's what men are going to ask
too.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e       09-28 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NONPROFIT-THEATER-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING A THEATRICAL SEASON, MONTH BY MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is late morning on a muggy day in August. Most of
New York City seems to be rushing to appointments or toiling in
air-conditioned offices. But in a cramped, dusty East Village space
on 13th Street, four people who make their lives working in the
theater are talking about a hat.
</P>
<P>
   This is a costume meeting for the Classic Stage Company's
production of ``I Will Bear Witness,'' a one-man adaptation of the
diaries of Victor Klemperer. ``Witness'' is one of four productions
that make up the company's current season, and this meeting is one
of the countless, painstaking rituals of preparation that the
company has gone through over the last several months to make it
all come together.
</P>
<P>
   A nonprofit theater's season planning is a craft all its own,
one of mundane logistical maneuvering as well as lofty creative
ambition; of sleepless-night angst and pride-swelling triumph; of
big-picture matters like building audiences and details as precise
as choosing a hat. It's a balancing act of egos, schedules, budgets
and creative visions. The process is happening at theaters all over
the country and at many in New York, but it formally begins in
earnest in the spring and ends in the fall. The planning is
conducted at many levels, depending on an institution's finances.
It almost always involves a deep and consuming commitment of
passion and time.
</P>
<P>
   At the 33-year-old Classic Stage Company, which has an operating
budget of $1.3 million and is on a par with off-Broadway companies
like the Atlantic and the Vineyard, the first offering of this
season, ``Texts for Nothing,'' started previews Wednesday and opens
on Oct. 15. It is a one-man performance of prose pieces by Samuel
Beckett featuring and directed by Bill Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   After that is ``Race'' by Ferdinand Bruckner, about the effects
of the Nazis' election on a group of medical students in Germany in
1933. This will be performed in repertory in February and March
with ``I Will Bear Witness,'' which was adapted for the stage by
Karen Malpede and George Bartenieff and will be performed by
Bartenieff.
</P>
<P>
   These will be followed by ``In the Penal Colony,'' a
music-theater work by Philip Glass based on Kafka's story, which
will run in June and July.
</P>
<P>
   Watching this theater company create its season over the last
six months offers a window into not only the running of a small
nonprofit institution but also the making of art.
</P>
<P>
   MARCH
</P>
<P>
   When Barry Edelstein, 35, was selected to be the artistic
director of the Classic Stage Company in 1998, one of first things
he did was call artists he had worked with in the past to say,
essentially, ``I'm running this theater now; come work with me.''
The first of them was Irwin, perhaps best known for his performance
with David Shiner in the hit Broadway show ``Fool Moon.'' Irwin had
performed a version of ``Texts,'' developed by Joseph Chaikin, in
1991 at the Public Theater. He wanted to go a little further with
the Beckett play, in which he brings his clowning skills to
portraying a tramplike figure searching for his place in the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, everything looks like a go: scheduling has been
worked out, and the theater has agreed to Irwin's idea of building
a large hillside with water and real dirt. Doug Stein will design
the set. The one sticking point is getting the rights to the
material from the Beckett estate, famously zealous in controlling
the staging of the playwright's works.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin has had an exchange of letters with Beckett's nephew,
Edward, in which Beckett has expressed some reservations about the
project. In particular, he is opposed to any changes, and Irwin had
hoped to perform 5 of the 13 original texts with a few minor
excisions for pacing. This is nail-biting time; will Irwin get the
green light or won't he?
</P>
<P>
   It looks promising, but projects do sometimes fall through. In
just a few weeks, Classic Stage's original choice for its fourth
slot, an adaptation of Ovid's ``Metamorphoses,'' which takes place
in a giant swimming pool, will evaporate because of scheduling
problems with the director, Mary Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing material, Edelstein says, several considerations are
at work. First of all is scheduling. That includes questions like
``Is so-and-so free then?'' and ``Who's going to come downtown in
May to see a play about the Nazis?'' But more important is the
composition of a season. Classic Stage's mission is to present
classics for contemporary American audiences, which means rewriting
and reimagining works that already exist. The company's last two
seasons have included ``Naked,'' by Luigi Pirandello; Beckett's
``Waiting for Godot''; and ``The Misanthrope'' by Moliere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes my job exciting,'' Edelstein says. ``You're
dealing at an incredibly abstract level with big philosophical
questions: What is a classic? How does time intervene to change a
piece of art? Then you have to find a community of artists who have
perspective on that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to talk about is the deep inner heart of the
play _ the way men and women relate, the way that power works, the
questions that are at the heart of what the drama is talking
about,'' Edelstein continues. ``You can slap a three-piece suit on
Hamlet; does that make a contemporary work? I don't think so. Yes,
these plays survive across time. But aspects of these plays don't,
and when they don't you learn that society has changed. So thinking
about a play from 400 years ago, you have an opportunity to think
about our world.'' (MORE)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   APRIL
</P>
<P>
   In planning a season, a theater also has ticket sales to
consider, and featuring stars can help get people in the door. In
the two seasons that Edelstein has been at Classic Stage, the
company has featured Uma Thurman, Mira Sorvino and John Turturro.
But he is frustrated because some people now associate Classic
Stage with celebrities. ``Those are the ones that generate
attention,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy is to cast the best actor for the part,'' he
adds. ``Of course, it's also to explore exciting people we think
audiences are going to want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars also matter to Beth Emelson, 34, Edelstein's partner as
the company's producing director, because she is concerned with
building Classic Stage's audiences. ``Beth's challenge to me,''
Edelstein says, ``was, `Give me two names people know in each
season brochure.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whether because of big names or because they simply like the
shows, more and more people are coming to Classic Stage these days.
In the last two years, the theater's membership has increased to
1,200 from 224. Classic Stage members _ who tend to be between the
ages of 25 and 45 _ pay $25 a year and see any play for $20.
</P>
<P>
   Growth is important to the company because more money will allow
for more shows with longer runs and larger casts. This year the
theater's operating budget has grown to $1.3 million from $500,000.
Emelson and Edelstein concluded their first year at the company
with a surplus of $250,000, which was used to help pay off an
eight-year debt of about $100,000, to increase the staff to seven
from three, to buy computers and to upgrade dressing rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Without an advertising budget, Classic Stage has to be creative
about getting the word out. Emelson devotes much of her time to
reaching out to the Union Square neighborhood. She makes contact
with colleges in the area like New York University, the New School
and Baruch College, puts up posters in dormitories, gets material
about the theater into orientation packets and speaks to professors
about incorporating Classic Stage productions into the curriculum.
This season, for example, Emelson has been talking to the German
department at New York University about organizing a conference
around Holocaust drama in connection with ``Race'' and ``Witness.''
``It's a wasted opportunity if we don't,'' Emelson says.
</P>
<P>
   Other Classic Stage efforts include special student matinees for
high school students; a program called Classic Stages/New Visions
that presents new works on classic themes; Saturday symposiums at
which scholars talk about topics related to a current Classic Stage
play; and Tuesday Talks, at which the actors and designers meet
with the audience after a show.
</P>
<P>
   In April the company started a Web site, www.classicstage.org.
MAY
</P>
<P>
   Construction is about to begin. For the 33 years that Classic
Stage has occupied a former stable on East 13th Street, no
productions have been mounted in the summer because the theater had
no air-conditioning and the heat was too much for audiences to
bear. (Legend has it that during one season that ran into June,
Turturro was forced to perform Brecht in a full-length leather coat
on a 115-degree day and that the theater's board members had to
spritz the audience.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to an $850,000 capital campaign that is also paying
for a new lobby, renovated bathrooms and a raised ceiling, the
theater will have not only central air but also central heat. In
the past the theater used two gigantic gas blowers that were so
loud they could be used only before performances and at
intermission. While it may seem to most like an incidental upgrade,
to the theater it is a seismic change; whereas Classic Stage
functions 12 months of the year, it has been able to earn money
only during seven _ from October through April. Now the theater
will be able to produce shows year-round _ renting the space out to
others as well as producing its own _ and its directors can hardly
contain their excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly it's a brand-new day in terms of what the calendar
looks like,'' Emelson says. ``Up till now, a key resource in
planning the season was the Farmer's Almanac _ what's it going to
be like outside? And those days, happily, are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Classic Stage was founded by Christopher Martin, who was
followed as artistic director by Carey Perloff, then David
Esbjornson. In June 1998, Edelstein heard that the position was
open, threw his hat into the ring and got the job.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein, born and reared in Fairlawn, N.J., is a cerebral man
with wire-rimmed glasses. He majored in drama at Tufts University,
where he started directing, and on graduating in 1986 won a Rhodes
Scholarship and earned a master's in philosophy from Oxford
University, where he specialized in Shakespeare. After another year
in London, Edelstein came to New York, worked at the Public Theater
under Joseph Papp, taught Shakespearean acting at Juilliard and
began directing. He eventually built a career as a freelance
director _ working at Williamstown Theater Festival, the Roundabout
Theater Company and the Public _ and he continues to direct plays.
He did ``Julius Caesar'' in Central Park this summer and will do
``Race,'' which he also adapted, at Classic Stage.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein says he wanted to run a theater because he was
interested in having more control over his career. ``This is a
place where I can do work I believe in on my own terms,'' he says.
``I have a home now.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Emelson both call their partnership strong, saying they
consult on every decision, from the color of the lobby to how many
season brochures to print and how best to approach a certain actor.
</P>
<P>
   Emelson, who radiates warmth and organization, is from
California, Pa., the daughter of arts educators. She moved to New
York City 14 years ago to attend NYU, where she earned a degree in
arts administration and theater management. Then came work at the
Public, the Brooklyn Academy of Music and Lincoln Center Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain satisfaction in selling tickets and raising
money _ that's part of the job, that's what's expected,'' Emelson
says. ``But the part I most enjoy is working with writers and
directors.'' June
</P>
<P>
   With the Ovid play now off the schedule, Classic Stage is
casting about for a production to fill its final slot. The company
has had a reading of Neal Bell's play ``Monster,'' an adaptation of
Mary Shelley's ``Frankenstein.'' Another possibility is ``In the
Penal Colony,'' a new music-theater piece by Philip Glass, directed
by JoAnne Akalaitis, with scenery by John Conklin and lighting by
Jennifer Tipton _ what Edelstein calls a ``dream team of the
avant-garde theater.'' The production is being staged first at A
Contemporary Theater in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Stage decides to go with the latter, excited to present
the production's New York premiere and relieved that the season is
finally set, though a bit nervous about pulling off something so
ambitious. The show requires a live quintet _ which may turn out to
be imported from Europe _ two opera singers and three actors.
``Nobody else in his right mind would try to do it,'' Edelstein
says.
</P>
<P>
   What Edelstein is not worried about at this point is the fact
that the season as a whole is looking grim, with two Holocaust
plays and an opera about capital punishment coming on the heels of
Beckett. Edelstein says he simply needs to feel good about each
individual project _ and he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own philosophy is, in New York the whole notion of season
planning is different,'' he says. ``In a city where you're the one
major professional theater and there are five smaller theaters,
then I think you know your 20,000 subscribers are going to see your
entire season and in that case a pu pu platter is a good idea _ a
little of this, a little of that. In New York, people don't
experience theater in a seasonal way. You have members who see
everything, and we do. But they are a relatively small proportion
of our audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Edelstein says, he is not concerned with how the plays
he selects relate to one another; he doesn't plan a season around a
theme or any other common thread. ``There are people who regard
season planning as a curatorial activity,'' he says. ``They've got
to have these five plays dealing with war, or one play for every
decade of the 20th century. Our view of this season is, `Let's get
great projects, each one of which is a legitimate response to our
mission.'''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
