<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AIR-DELAYS-0929-COX     09-28 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-DELAYS-0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AVIATION OFFICIALS REASSURE CONGRESS THEY ARE WORKING TO EASE
CONGESTION
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories
 &HT;    By KAVITA KUMAR
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a summer of frustrating delays, aviation
officials reassured members of Congress on Thursday they are
working to alleviate the congestion at the nation's busiest
airports.
</P>
<P>
   While the situation of the past few months _ the worst in five
years _ can be mostly attributed to bad weather and airline labor
disputes, officials said the delays passengers have experienced are
part of a larger problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weather simply exacerbates the problems that airports are
already experiencing in terms of congestion,'' said Benjamin
DeCosta, general manager of Atlanta's Hartsfield, widely regarded
as the world's busiest airport. He was testifying before a House
Transportation and Infrastructure subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more travelers take to the nation's skies every year
because of the robust economy, airports are straining to
accommodate the increased demand on their runways. And air traffic
controllers are struggling to efficiently guide planes through
increasingly crowded skies.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) forecasts that airline
passenger traffic will more than double in the next ten years. That
translates to as much as 70 percent of projected traffic growth at
the nation's 30 largest airports.
</P>
<P>
   One of the keys to reducing delays at Hartsfield, DeCosta said,
is its $5.4 billion expansion project which includes plans for a
fifth runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had the fifth runway today, our average time of delay
would be cut in half,'' DeCosta said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Johnny Isakson, R-Ga., asked that FAA officials work with
Hartsfield to help get the runway approved as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will definitely work with you to help you,'' responded
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, who also testified.
</P>
<P>
   But building new runways, which often are opposed by local
communities or are challenged on environmental grounds, is not a
panacea to the problem of air traffic delays, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And, it takes years for new runways to materialize. Hartsfield's
fifth runway isn't due for completion until 2005, DeCosta said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to focus on the short-term and on less controversial
things now,'' said FAA Administrator Jane Garvey. ``So we're
looking for those things _ the low-lying fruits, if you will _ that
can help us in the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   Slater said the FAA is using more advanced technologies to
modernize the air traffic control system which he said ``will
improve the controllers' ability to manage increasing levels of
traffic.'' The agency hopes to ease congestion by routing more U.S.
flights through Canadian airspace and by using lower altitude
routes which Garvey likened to ``opening up a new highway''.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has also identified the top seven choke points _
including Atlanta _ and has developed routes, approaches and
procedures to reduce congestion in those areas.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduling more flights during non-peak hours and offering
financial incentives to passengers for those flights were some
other solutions thrown out Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Slater seemed unwilling to start regulating how airlines
schedule their flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken an approach where we bring airlines and heads of
airports together to deal with overbooking,'' he said. ``We wish to
do it in a way that recognizes all the benefits that have come from
a deregulated industry'' where the federal government has eased its
control over scheduling and routes.
</P>
<P>
   DeCosta said Hartsfield has worked with Delta to modify its
flight schedule. More flights are now scheduled during the non-peak
hours in the early morning and late evening, he said. But it's
still unclear what sort of an impact this shuffling has had on
delays at Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury's still out on that one,'' DeCosta said.
</P>
<P>
   Kavita Kumar's e-mail address is kkumar(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NON-PROFIT-ART-3RDTAK     09-28 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NON-PROFIT-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
   NEW YORK: our mission. ''' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JULY
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting on ``Texts'' at the theater, amid the scaffolding
and rubble of renovation, Irwin says he is optimistic about getting
the necessary approval from Edward Beckett. ``I think we're in good
shape,'' he says. ``I think I see my way clear to sending him
something he will say yes to.'' Irwin is also clearly excited about
the prose pieces from the original book, ``Stories and Texts for
Nothing,'' that he has selected. ``Like the continent of Africa,''
he says. ``The more I read them, the deeper I can go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His respect for you as an artist is so profound that he's
going to say yes,'' Edelstein predicts hopefully. Later in the
month Beckett faxes Classic Stage permission to go ahead, but Irwin
ultimately decides to perform the pieces without any cuts.
</P>
<P>
   They discuss the blurb about the play that will appear in the
brochure. Irwin worries that it promises too much in the way of
humor and suggests ``a drier tone.'' Edelstein says he has a drier
version but adds that the idea is to get people to come. ``The
preference has been to do a zippier version in the season
brochure,'' he explains. ``I'm stressing witty because our season
is Nazis and capital punishment. The comedy highlight is Samuel
Beckett.''
</P>
<P>
   Appreciating this, Irwin nevertheless persists. ``I would
hate,'' he says, ``to set up a false expectation.''
</P>
<P>
   The blurb ends up being toned down.
</P>
<P>
   They go on to discuss costume designers. Will one be too busy
because she is also doing a Broadway show? Another knows period
costumes well, another has done Woody Allen films. ``You should
meet them,'' Edelstein advises Irwin, ``and make the call.'' Irwin
later decides on Anita Yavich.
</P>
<P>
   Then they talk about sound designers. Is this one ``too
composery''? And stage managers. Is that one tough enough or too
nice?
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Texts'' is a one-man show, Irwin _ whose work
includes unorthodox physical techniques _ is interested in
exploring the possibility of featuring a second set of hands that
resemble his own. This idea is later eliminated, but for now the
creative people worry about getting someone to take the job. ``I
couldn't get a 50-year-old man to play Julius Caesar,'' Edelstein
quips. ``I don't know how we're going to get a 50-year-old guy to
play a hand for half the money.''
</P>
<P>
   AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   George Bartenieff discovered the brown fedora in a bin at the
Barneys warehouse sale, and he is proud of the find; it is just
right, he says, to help capture the painful transformation of his
character, Victor Klemperer in ``I Will Bear Witness,'' from a
distinguished scholar to just another downtrodden Jew suffering
through the Holocaust with a yellow star sewn into his coat over
his heart. ``A professor in his society was at the top of the
rung,'' Bartenieff explains at the costume meeting in the temporary
offices the company is using while the theater is being renovated.
``Even if he went into a grocer, they would call him professor.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Classic Stage's production team gathers to talk
nitty-gritty numbers. In addition to Edelstein and Emelson, those
present are Angela Wendt, the costume designer for ``Race'' and
``Witness''; Rachel M. Tischler, the theater's new general manager;
and Ian Tresselt, production manager.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt asks what her budget will be for the two shows. ``The
whopping sum of $9,000 for both,'' Tischler reports. But Wendt, who
designed ``Rent'' on Broadway, doesn't blink. Somehow, actors,
directors and designers who work in the big time are also willing
to lend their talents to a theater like Classic Stage for
considerably less than their normal fees. Edelstein and Emelson
often say it's because they make up in personal attention what they
can't offer in compensation. But the creative people say it's
because they simply go where the good work is.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most exciting forays I've every made,''
Irwin says. ``And it's as well supported here as it could be
anywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mortgage,'' Irwin adds, ``will have to be paid by some
other kind of work.''
</P>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Classic Stage to give a progress report to its
board. A table eeeeeeeeefor the evening meeting has been set up in
the lobby _ with hard hats as a humorous centerpiece. Emelson,
typically covered with sawdust of late, is wearing high heels and
pearls. Although ``Texts'' is to start performances in just a week
and power tools are still whirring in the background, she seems
typically upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the eternal optimist of Beth Emelson ends up
coming into play,'' she says. ``I really feel it's going to all get
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at this point hasn't been easy. Emelson and Edelstein
have been putting in 14-hour days, 7 days a week. The schedule does
not promise to get much lighter; both try to be in the lobby to
greet people at nearly every performance. ``It's important for an
audience not to perceive the theater as faceless,'' Edelstein says.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is also on to raise money; this is the time of year
that theaters make their big push to find financing. Emelson says
she has sent out 130 proposals and letters seeking support from
government agencies, corporations and individuals. In the first few
months of running the theater, Emelson and Edelstein met ``with
anybody who would open the door,'' she says. ``We were out there
all the time with our dog-and-pony show.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they have established some reliable donors, but they never
stop worrying about money and would like to build up a considerable
cash reserve ``so the panic moments don't shake the place quite as
much as they can,'' Edelstein says.
</P>
<P>
   It is working on projects like Irwin's, he explains, that makes
all this worthwhile. ``Watching Bill is an incredible treat,''
Edelstein says. ``That's why I got into this, to be around artists
like that. You watch him step onto that mountain and you can't
believe your eyes. All the rest _ waiting for permits to come,
sweating out the cash flow _ recedes far into the background when
Bill Irwin does some crazy move with his shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein says there is no shortage of things to be nervous
about: Will the renovation be finished? Will the season stick? Will
people buy tickets? Will critics like the shows? Will audiences
show up? ``There's always something to keep you awake at night, to
turn your hair gray,'' says Edelstein, whose hair does seem to be
looking a little grayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sleeping because I'd much rather be awake,'' he adds.
``I love what I do when I wake up in the morning. So who needs to
sleep? I'd rather be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this is a moment for Classic Stage that happens to be
full of promise, when all the pieces seem as if they might actually
have fallen into place. ``What a relief, we've got a season,''
Edelstein says. ``And there you go _ we're finished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
