<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5509 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-TITANS-REVIEW-HN     09-28 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TITANS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``REMEMBER THE TITANS'' MAY BE THE MOST MOVING AND ENTERTAINING
MOVIE SO FAR THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
``Remember the Titans'' is set in the early 1970s, but perhaps
because it deals with race and football _ those eternal verities _
it feels as up-to-the-minute as this week's game. Some things never
change.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This would seem to contradict the point of this rousing movie,
which is all (begin ital) about (end ital) change, but really it
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   By turns hilarious, moving and action-filled, ``Titans'' is
based on a true story of the struggle surrounding a white high
school team absorbing its first black players. Its true subject,
however, is transcendence, the way personal struggle can transform
society. That the movie feels less like history than current events
doesn't invalidate its premise. It doesn't pretend change is easy;
it never says it's not an ongoing struggle.
</P>
<P>
   To speak of this movie in sociological terms is to do it a
disservice, though. Make no mistake: ``Titans'' rocks. It marries
the verve and fireworks of a popcorn movie with serious social
drama. When is the last time Hollywood made such a shrewdly crafted
tale that turned a subject so potentially dull and polarizing into
a rollicking good time?
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from getting snubbed at the Oscars for his dynamite
performance as a real-life boxer in ``Hurricane,'' Denzel
Washington is no less impressive here without beard, shaved head
and boxer's body in a human-scale role.
</P>
<P>
   He is Herman Boone, a high school football coach from North
Carolina who gets appointed assistant coach in the racially
explosive school district in Alexandria, Va. The black and the
white high schools have just been merged, and against a backdrop of
protests and rioting, he becomes an unwitting political pawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the answer to your prayers,'' he tells black
supporters. ``I'm not the savior, Jesus Christ, Martin Luther King
or the Easter Bunny. I'm just a football coach.''
</P>
<P>
   But first-time screenwriter Gregory Allen Howard was smart
enough to see that in the boiling cauldron of racial integration,
in this town in his native Virginia, football (begin ital) was (end
ital) the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The sports-as-metaphor notion is nothing new. What schoolkid
hasn't been drilled on how competition builds character and
prepares one for life, yadda, yadda? But the filmmakers were
rigorous in constructing this football program to act as stand-in
for society at large. It might be obvious, but it works.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly, Boone is named head coach over the much-loved Bill
Yoast (Will Patton). White players and assistant coaches
predictably rebel. The majority white school board only hired Boone
to appease angry blacks; now they're setting him up to fail.
</P>
<P>
   But as he says at a particularly low point late in the story:
``I'm a winner. I win.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone might be a tad too proud, but he's no fool. To save the
program, he asks Yoast to stay on as assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Determined that his players work together to forge a winning
team, he drives them, mercilessly, relentlessly. Watching this, you
can't help but ask whether this sort of social engineering can
work. Aren't some things beyond the scope of legislation or edict?
</P>
<P>
   What the real-life Boone found, and the movie shows us, is only
the love of the game could get his players to transcend their
differences and animosities. They hated each other's music and
everything else, but when they focused on football the rest fell
away.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is produced by Jerry Bruckheimer, who specializes in
loud, fast-paced, brain-dead action movies such as ``Armageddon''
and ``Gone in Sixty Seconds.'' He's made more serious films, too,
but the formulaic social commentary of his ``Dangerous Minds''
doesn't prepare one for ``Titans.'' It's slick Hollywood product,
all right, but it also may be the most moving and entertaining
movie so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Director Boaz Yakin and Howard have carefully weighted the moral
balance _ the movie is never black and white even though the
conflict is. The film establishes a symmetry between Boone and
Yoast by giving them corresponding scenes early in the movie, but
it never loses sight of what is just. It doesn't make the mistake
of making obstinacy seem noble.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the townspeople opposed to Boone are out-and-out racists
and easy villains, and the movie doesn't stint on portraying them
as such. Yoast, though, is a decent person caught up in difficult
times. We understand his resentment, and even when we wish he were
more understanding, we don't hate him.
</P>
<P>
   For years, movies like this distorted stories about race by
making white people the focus, even when the black side would be
more compelling. Washington is unquestionably the star of this
movie, and it's right that his Herman Boone is the focus. But
despite wavering moments, he is a solid rock. Dramatically
speaking, it is Patton's character that undergoes the more profound
change.
</P>
<P>
   Yoast is a victim here, every bit as much as the black people
who have been locked out of jobs and opportunity. Boone
acknowledges as much when he at first turns down the head coach
job. He'd been passed over too many times on account of race to be
party to it now, he says. He takes the job out of duty, because his
community demands it.
</P>
<P>
   Yoast, a church deacon, must overcome his anger and resist the
temptation to hate. His emotional growth over the course of the
movie, and that of the black and white teen-age players, is what
gives this film its heart.
</P>
<P>
   The most vividly drawn white players are angry and threatened,
and they keep lashing out at the folks they feel are taking over
their school and their team. They never become an undifferentiated
mass, though. The script introduces us to other players, whites new
to the area who don't have the same racial baggage and so are able
to relate to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers also are careful to balance the heavy moments
with humor and to balance that with football action.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics might dismiss this as just another fairy tale about a
subject rich filmmakers know nothing about. But while Hollywood
conventions do sometimes slip into view and the uplift at times
becomes strained, the story feels like it was built upon a bedrock
of truth.
</P>
<P>
   The racial brotherhood at the end seems too good to be true, but
it's hard to scoff when you're all choked up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Remember the Titans'' &QL; 
Starring: Denzel Washington, Will Patton &QL; 
Director: Boaz Yakin &QL; 
Screenwriter: Gregory Allen Howard &QL; 
Rating: PG for thematic elements and some language &QL; 
Running time: 113 min. &QL; 
Grade: A &QL; 
X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
