<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-NYT &LR;      09-28 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 5 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following games will be played this week in the National
Football League:
</P>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK (SUNDAY 4 P.M.)
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (3-1) at Washington (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers lose to the Jets, and all of a sudden Tampa Bay
is the Cincinnati Bengals. Everyone relax. The Buccaneers are still
a Super Bowl-caliber team. Still, they will have a difficult time
at Washington because the Redskins are feeling more confident these
days. Linebacker LaVar Arrington gets the start, and he will make
some plays, as will quarterback Brad Johnson. But this is a bad
week to play Tampa Bay. The players are angry, especially the
defense, and feel they have something to prove.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Buccaneers, 20-12
</P>
<P>
   1 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore (3-1) at Cleveland (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   Coming into this season, many throughout the league felt that
quarterback Tony Banks was the weak link of this team. Banks is
changing people's minds quickly. He has won 7 of his past 9 starts,
and has been a mature, patient leader the team respects. The
defense of the Ravens is finally coming around after a rough start.
Overall it has not allowed a 100-yard rusher in the past 21 games _
tops in the conference. This year Baltimore has allowed a
league-low 5 redzone trips.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Ravens, 28-6
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (1-3) at Carolina (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   The smart, yet cold-hearted, thing to do with a Cowboys offense
that is completely melting down would be to bench quarterback Troy
Aikman and start backup Randall Cunningham. Aikman is a champion
and future Hall of Famer, and he deserves respect, but the harsh
truth is the offense flows better with Cunningham at the helm.
Carolina, after a disappointing start, is due for a breakout game.
This is the week it happens.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Panthers, 21-13
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis (2-1) at Buffalo (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   After the pasting quarterback Peyton Manning and the Colts put
on a pretty good Jacksonville team, the Colts made a major
statement to the rest of the league: The Rams and Buccaneers are
good, but so are we. They would make an even bigger statement by
traveling to Buffalo and beating the Bills, which will be
difficult, but will happen, mainly because Buffalo doesn't have the
offense to keep up with Indianapolis. The game will be extremely
close because Buffalo has good corners and speedy linebackers and
has won 8 of 9 at home against the AFC East. But the feeling now is
that Indianapolis is on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Colts, 16-13
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (3-0) at Detroit (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   Rookie quarterback Daunte Culpepper is for real. So are the
Vikings. The offense is clicking as usual, but it is the defense
that is the surprise. Minnesota is allowing 300.3 yards per game.
No, the Vikings aren't the Buccaneers, but that number is down from
373.7 yards a game through three games last season. The Vikings'
defense keeps the Lions in check. Minnesota Coach Dennis Green
getting a three-year contract extension gives the Vikings an
emotional edge.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Vikings, 28-21
</P>
<P>
   Giants (3-1) at Tennessee (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   On the surface this looks like a loss for the Giants. Tennessee
has won three in a row and 8 of the last 10 games. Quarterback
Steve McNair has almost fully recovered from a bruised sternum and
running back Eddie George is one of the most intimidating offensive
players in football. But here is why the Giants will win. Tennessee
makes its living running the ball, and the Giants have enough
quickness, and toughness, on defense to slow down George. And the
Giants' weakest link, its secondary, won't be challenged by a
passing offense where the tight end is the leading receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Giants, 15-13
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (0-3) at Jacksonville (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh quarterback Kent Graham is hurting all over, dealing
with all kinds of sore body parts, so expect to see backup Kordell
Stewart at some point in the game. The Steelers will take advantage
of the Jaguars' cornerbacks, playing the worst pass defense in the
conference. But Jacksonville is dominant at home and prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Jaguars, 28-12
</P>
<P>
   San Diego (0-4) at St. Louis (4-0)
</P>
<P>
   The numbers St. Louis is putting up are stunning. The offense
has scored 30-plus points 10 straight games. The Rams have scored
160 points and are on pace for 640, which would shatter the league
record set by Minnesota in 1998 by 84 points. Quarterback Kurt
Warner has thrown for four consecutive 300-yard games. With all due
respect to the Chargers and their good little defense, the team has
no chance against that kind of firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Rams, 35-16
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY 4 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Miami (3-1) at Cincinnati (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   At 63, Cincinnati interim coach Dick LeBeau is the oldest rookie
head coach in 30 years. Unfortunately for LeBeau there is no time
to celebrate. He has a lot of work to do with a Bengals team that
is in total disarray after the resignation of coach Bruce Coslet.
Miami has allowed just 22 total points while Cincinnati has scored
a total of only 7. This game is ugly, ugly, ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Dolphins, 25-6
</P>
<P>
   New England (0-4) at Denver (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   Denver quarterback Brian Griese has postponed possible shoulder
surgery until the end of the season, and that is good news for the
Broncos. That is, if the shoulder holds up. His backup, Gus
Frerotte, is far below average. If Griese plays the entire game,
Denver wins. If not, the Patriots get a much-needed victory.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Broncos, 22-14
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (1-2) at San Francisco (1-3)
</P>
<P>
   49ers wide receiver Terrell Owens says he was praying when he
twice ran to midfield last week after scoring touchdowns. Lame
excuse. Owens' hot-dogging overshadowed two things. First, San
Francisco quarterback Jeff Garcia is playing well, and has four,
multi-touchdown games in his past five, and has a passer rating of
100.6, second in the conference. And Owens has three touchdowns in
his past two games.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: 49ers, 28-17
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (0-4) at Green Bay (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the Bears is that they don't know what they
want do offensively. The scheme sometimes resembles that of a
Division 1-AA college-lots of misdirection and trick plays. In
other words, it is a pubescent West Coast offense. Whatever
happened to just running the football up the middle? In eight
career home games against Chicago, Packers quarterback Brett Favre
has averaged a 97.3 passer rating and owns a 6-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Packers, 20-13
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (2-2) at Philadelphia (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   Yawn. The Falcons will run the ball until Jamal Anderson can't
run any more, and then see lots of Eagles running back Duce Staley.
The Eagles have the better defense. That's why they win.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Eagles, 21-14
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (2-2) at Kansas City (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   It is always difficult to win at Arrowhead Stadium. The Chiefs
are still euphoric after their sizzling victory at Denver last
week. Kansas City quarterback Elvis Grbac, 11-6 as a starter
against division opponents, is playing well now. He's the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Chiefs, 18-10
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
