<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LOCKERBIE-TRIAL-(TRIM     09-28 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-TRIAL-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LOCKERBIE CASE, DEFENSE TRIES DISCREDITING LIBYAN TURNCOAT AND
FBI AGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands _ The testimony of a Libyan double-agent
considered the star witness in the Lockerbie trial ended Thursday
after defense lawyers accused him of being not only a liar, but
also a black-market currency dealer and an opportunist hoping for
the $4 million reward offered by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But his closing morning on the witness stand was somewhat
overshadowed later in the day by a set of odd and hostile exchanges
between the defense and an agent of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI agent, Harold Hendershot, has been part of the Lockerbie
case since the early days, watching search teams pick up pieces of
Pan Am 103 on the Scottish moors. He was called Thursday by the
prosecution, apparently to bolster details of testimony given by
Abdul Majid Giaka, the Libyan turncoat who had just been subjected
to two days of withering cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   For the first few minutes, Hendershot explained how, in an
interview aboard an American warship off the Mediterranean island
of Malta in July 1991, Giaka claimed he saw the defendants, Abdel
Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, in late 1988. They
were carrying a brown Samsonite suitcase through customs at the
Malta airport, Giaka said.
</P>
<P>
   The point is important because the defense asserts that Giaka
made up the incident in 1991 in a bid to get the FBI to adopt him
as a protected witness. Investigators believe that the bomb that
blew up Pan Am 103, killing 270 people, was in a brown plastic
suitcase checked in as unaccompanied luggage in Malta.
</P>
<P>
   Hendershot said he remembered that Giaka was ``very general''
about the date in his July 1991 interview, saying he had seen the
suitcase sometime between October and December 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Giaka later became more specific, claiming to remember the exact
date and giving other details about the day.
</P>
<P>
   But when the defense began to cross-examine Hendershot, he
became vague about details of his own investigation. He even
answered that he did not remember whether one suspect he tried to
interview had spit in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Defense's questioning of Hendershot, shifted focus away from the
Libyans. The defense's theory is that Pan Am 103 was blown up by a
Palestinian terrorist cell based in Germany working with another in
Sweden. Scottish investigators have said the German group was their
prime suspects for many months, until attention shifted to the
Libyans.
</P>
<P>
   The defense attorneys, William Taylor and Richard Keen, asked
Hendershot about a trip he took to Sweden in 1989 to investigate
the Palestinian group led by Mohammed Abu Talb, who was in prison
there for other bombings. He confirmed that he had asked the
Swedish police to get a warrant to search Talb's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   But Hendershot repeatedly answered ``I don't recall'' to
questions about the contents of Talb's apartment: whether it
contained disassembled clocks and watches and barometric devices _
all potential bomb triggers; whether it contained clothing made in
Malta, as clothing wrapped around the Lockerbie bomb was; or
whether it contained a calendar with a circle around the date of
the bombing, Dec. 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Keen voiced skepticism about Hendershot's vague recollection and
the agent's contention that he had not taken any notes during the
search.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that unusual,'' Keen asked, ``for an FBI agent to attend
a search and not take notes?''
</P>
<P>
   Hendershot replied that notes might not be taken when the search
was in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   As for Giaka's cross-examination, Keen asked him at one point to
explain why he had told the CIA that he had been reduced to black
market currency trading to support his family.
</P>
<P>
   Giaka denied both having traded on the black market and denied
having told the agency that he had. When challenged with a CIA
cable noting their record, Giaka delved into a long explanation of
private currency trades in Malta and Libya, and said he had made
them, but that he didn't considered it black market trading because
he did not charge inflated commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyan, who as a protected witness arrived guarded by U.S.
marshals in a small motorcade that struggled to evade
photographers, left the courthouse in midafternoon Thursday and
presumably returned to the United States, though a court spokesman
declined to confirm that.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clare Connelly, a criminal law professor who heads the
University of Glasgow's team observing the trial, said Giaka's
three days of testimony had been problematic.
</P>
<P>
   The defense had ``dented his credibility'' by making him seem
motivated by a desire for money and American citizenship, she said,
``but whether that would result in obliterating all his evidence is
dependent on how the judges respond.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she believed it to be premature to theorize that the
prosecution's case was discredited, which was the characterization
provided Tuesday by Prof. Robert Black at the University of
Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The trial has been sparsely attended for weeks, but the public
gallery was fairly full this week with families of the victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
