<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-IDENTITY-THEFT-0929-C     09-28 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDENTITY-THEFT-0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE PANEL APPROVES BILL TO BAN SALE OF SOCIAL SECURITY NUMBERS
 &HT;    By MEGAN K. DOYLE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to reduce identity theft, a House
committee voted unanimously Thursday to prohibit the sale of Social
Security numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., a Republican from
Fort Lauderdale, Fla., would make it illegal to sell or purchase
Social Security numbers, which are commonly sold by financial and
credit institutions. It also would ban the use of these numbers on
driver's licenses, government checks, employer identification cards
and military ID cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This number was never intended for use as a national
identifier,'' said Rep. Gerald Kleczka, D-Wis., a co-sponsor of the
bill. ``We need to stop that use _ I call it an abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The result of a bipartisan effort to reduce fraud and identity
theft, the bill sailed through the House Ways and Means Committee
with little debate, but it must also pass the Commerce and Banking
committees before reaching the House floor. Congress is scheduled
to adjourn next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have literally developed a culture of dependence on the
Social Security number,'' Shaw said. ``Someone who steals your
Social Security number can literally steal your identity.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 60,000 allegations of identity theft were reported to
the Social Security Administration last year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, members of the Federal Trade Commission told a Senate
committee that identity theft is on the rise. Commissioners noted
that 400 claims of identity theft a week were reported to their
toll-free hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force Col. John Stevens and his wife, Mary, of
Maryland are an example of this growing problem. They testified
before the House Social Security subcommittee in July to urge
passage of the bill. In 1997, they discovered that their Social
Security numbers had been used to open 33 fraudulent credit card
and other accounts which were used to run up more than $113,000 in
charges, thus ruining their credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody over 65 years of age and all members of the armed
forces are very vulnerable, because when you retire you get a
Medicare number that is your Social Security number plus a
letter,'' Stevens said at a news conference Thursday. ``That
Medicare number isn't always protected. It goes through so many
hands. And the Social Security number opens the gate to
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would impose criminal penalties against
individuals who misuse Social Security numbers and organizations
that misuse the Social Security benefits of their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 6. 5 million Social Security recipients have their
benefits paid to organizations that help manage their benefits,
Shaw said. Organizations that misuses this money would face
liability for the misused benefits, increased fines, and
disqualification as a fiduciary service.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Doyle may be e-mailed at: mdoyle(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-430&AMP;A     09-28 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCOMING MEXICAN PRESIDENT PLANS INQUIRIES ON PAST ATROCITIES AND
CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM WEINER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ If history is written by the winners, Mexico may
be in for a major rewrite.
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Vicente Fox has promised to create a
``transparency commission'' when he takes office nine weeks from
now. It could be a window into a panorama of secrets, a political
Pandora's box
</P>
<P>
   If opened, it could destroy the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, known as the PRI, which ruled Mexico for 71 years and
controlled the flow of information, the archives of the state and
the official version of history.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the first man to defeat the PRI for the presidency, has
said that the commission, which would have to be approved by
Congress, would ``make an accounting of the past.'' Much must be
accounted for: Many chapters of the official version are false or
full of holes, historians and politicians say.
</P>
<P>
   They say the commission would have to confront Mexico's biggest
unsolved mysteries, like:
</P>
<P>
   _ What became of billions of dollars spent bailing out banks in
1995? Was the killing of the ruling party's presidential candidate
in 1994 a political assassination?
</P>
<P>
   _ Who murdered many of the ruling party's most dangerous
opponents during the 1970s and 1980s?
</P>
<P>
   _ Who gave the orders to shoot to kill hundreds of unarmed
demonstrators _ a massacre that the leaders of the era still deny
ever happened _ 10 days before the 1968 Mexico City Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   These are dangerous questions, for Mexico as well as for the
PRI. ``There are truths which can kill a nation,'' the French
author and diplomat Jean Giraudoux once said. And the truth might
implicate a generation of past leaders _ including some former
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Fox will have the strength to do this,'' said
Lorenzo Meyer, a prominent political history professor. ``You have
to open up thousands of closets, and each probably has more than
one skeleton in it. It would be an encyclopedia of horror, of power
that answered to no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's advisers say that they cannot build public trust in
government if the past remains a minefield of secrets and lies. If
public opinion counts for something in Mexico _ and, increasingly,
it does _ digging up these skeletons would be a popular
undertaking, they believe.
</P>
<P>
   The transparency commission would be ``made up of citizens
chosen by Congress who represent all sectors of society,'' who
would ``carry out the investigations and present them to
Congress,'' said Adolfo Aguilar Zinser, a top adviser to Fox. Much
about the idea remains unclear, including whether the citizens
could subpoena witnesses or demand documents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said that the power to rewrite the past must be in the hands
of Congress, ``because an investigation by the executive branch
lends itself to politicization and witch hunts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Society,'' he said, ``wants the past examined, but within
these limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Those promises may not be enough for the old ruling party.
Rafael Segovia, a political science professor and longtime PRI
leader, said: ``Frankly, if I were Fox, I wouldn't do it. If he
really wanted to seek justice, he would have to accuse thousands of
people of crimes. But that is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI was ``the perfect dictatorship'' _ with democratic
trappings, but ``suppressing by all means, including the worst,
whatever criticism may threaten its perpetuation in power,'' the
Peruvian writer Mario Vargas Llosa said a decade ago. That included
the Oct. 2, 1968, massacre of demonstrators in the Tlatelolco
neighborhood of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Though witnesses say 300 or more people died and more than 1,000
were wounded, the government never gave an accurate account of what
happened. Government-printed history books erased the event. Luis
Echeverria Alvarez, then interior minister, later president from
1970 to 1976, has long been suspected of having a hand in the
killings and the coverup, but has never responded, beyond admitting
in a rambling and evasive interview by a congressional committee in
1998 that the demonstrators were ``sons and daughters of workers,
farmers and unemployed people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hector Aguilar Camin, a writer who led the failed effort to
include Tlatelolco in the official histories, doubts that the
transparency commission would have the strength to exhume the
truth. ``It's got no teeth,'' he said. ``It's more of a politically
motivated idea to satisfy partisans who want to see the government
clean house once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Tlatelolco the last event of its kind. Kidnappings and
killings of dozens of real and imagined enemies of the state
continued during and after the Cold War, at the hands of military
and intelligence forces. The 1990s saw several massacres of men,
women and children in the poorest regions of Mexico, where
``military personnel and police continued to commit serious human
rights abuses,'' the State Department said in February.
</P>
<P>
   But one killing above all fires popular imagination in Mexico:
the slaying of Luis Donaldo Colosio, the PRI's presidential
candidate, in 1994. Like the official investigation into the
assassination of President John F. Kennedy in 1963, the
government's lone-gunman theory in the Colosio case satisfies
almost no one.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the killing, a special prosecutor, Miguel Montes
Garcia, said seven suspects ``carried out a concerted action'' to
assassinate Colosio. The investigation then became lost in the
labyrinth of Mexico's justice system, which has often proved
incapable of doing justice.
</P>
<P>
   The financial system is a maze, too. The nation's banking laws
protect not only the privacy of deposits, but also the secrecy of
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of dollars spent bailing out banks after the peso
plummeted in 1994 are suspected to have benefited thousands of
politically wired businessmen, whose bad debts will be paid by
taxpayers. An independent auditor hired by Congress, Michael
Mackey, found 3,300 such loans, totaling $7.8 billion, to the rich
and powerful, according to opposition lawmakers who hired a
computer hacker to dig up the data in late July.
</P>
<P>
   And the PRI, one of the world's great political machines until
its defeat in the July elections, used the national treasury as a
private purse for decades _ ``a small group in control of all
political and economic power at the cost of the impoverishment of
the citizenry,'' as Fox's party, National Action, said during the
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But two big barriers stand in the way of the transparency
commission. First, the PRI still controls a plurality of seats in
Congress and could block or hobble the commission.
</P>
<P>
   And even if a search for the truth begins, the records of the
past may not remain.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when the PRI lost its majority in the lower
house of Congress, opposition politicians eagerly went looking for
the legislative archives. They were gone. The only thing that
remained on the shelves was an old encyclopedia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1853EDT &QL; 
