<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      09-28 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deconstructing Deneuve
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Catherine Deneuve is a little tired. It's been a
long day, interview after interview. So much talking. She reaches
into her purse, pulls out a sweetener pellet and drops it with a
plink into the fresh cappuccino that has just been delivered to her
hotel suite, the dregs of an ice-cold espresso pushed aside. She
makes eye contact, that breathtakingly perfect, porcelain face
leaning forward to take a good, solid pull on a thin, elegant
cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult, these long days of interviews,'' she
said. ``You are always talking about the same film, over and over.
And yet you must go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Deneuve, perhaps the most famous actress in French film history,
has taken to dividing her time between lavish period epics and
small quirky independent films. None, however, have been quite as
quirky as the one that took her to Beverly Hills for this long day
of interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Her role as a factory worker in Lars von Trier's ``Dancer in the
Dark'' began, she said, when she saw the director's ``Breaking the
Waves'' several years ago and wrote him a letter. He wrote back,
they talked about working together and, eventually, he offered her
a role in this dark, downbeat drama _ part musical, part suicide
note _ that won the top prize at Cannes this year and opened the
New York Film Festival this month to intensely mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   She loves the film, she said. She is very proud to be a part of
it. But it is also clear that she would be happy to talk about
something else for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that I am watching too many films these days at home,''
she said. ``I much prefer to go to the cinema. There, where it is
dark and the screen is so large, you can more focus your attention.
At home, your attention can wander. And there is the sound, which I
find is often the most important part of a film.''
</P>
<P>
   She is often shocked, she says, by the poor quality of the
prints and the sound systems in the Left Bank cinemas that she
frequents. ``Often, I will leave them a note to complain or even
demand to talk to the manager,'' Deneuve said.
</P>
<P>
   On today's filmmakers: ``They are not quite like the directors
from before, they are a different sort.''
</P>
<P>
   This is spoken with clear authority. Deneuve has worked with
Francois Truffaut, Luis Bunuel, Jacques Demy, so many others, and
she vividly remembers an age, now lost, of imposing, intellectual
filmmakers. The directors today, they are a different sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think the new directors are as interested in the
storytelling as the older directors were,'' she said. ``To them, it
is more often always about emotion. Not the emotion of the
characters on the screen, but the emotion in the audience. They are
always trying to play on the emotion in the audience, to make them
scared or happy or frightened, all the time. I think perhaps I
would prefer a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience and `Titans'
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Allen Howard had just about given up, figuring he was
never going to make it as a film writer. ``When you hear no that
much, you just begin to think, `I guess they're right,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After several years writing for sitcoms and dreaming of a career
in movies, Howard thought a change of venue might help. He moved
away from Los Angeles, which he says he hates, and settled in
Alexandria, Va., near enough to Washington to provide some urban
sizzle but suburban enough to meet the slower, more comfortable
life he craved.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, he could write from there as easily as from West
Hollywood. But he was never able to make anything stick, he said,
and was within inches of giving it all up and going back to school
to get a teaching certificate. Then one day when he asked his
neighbors why their corner of Alexandria seemed to be so much more
happily integrated than any other part of the Washington area, they
told him it was because of a high school football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia is second only to Texas in their fanaticism over high
school football,'' Howard said. Two decades ago the city decided to
merge two high schools, one that was predominantly black and one
that was predominantly white. But when it came time to choose the
head football coach for the new school, the administrators decided
to go with a black coach, stunning the white community. And
Howard's resulting film, ``Remember the Titans,'' with Denzel
Washington playing the black coach, opens around the country
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project was rejected by everybody, and I mean
everybody,'' Howard said. ``I was turned down by every financing
entity in the movie business.'' Then, one day, it fell into the
hands of Jerry Bruckheimer Films, best known for big-budget action
blockbusters but interested in starting up a new division for
smaller films. ``And now, 18 months later, it's a movie,'' Howard
said. ``I'm still getting used to the idea. Really, after having
the idea rejected in so many places, all I really wanted was to get
the project into development somewhere. But now it's a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   An Intimidating Father
</P>
<P>
   Jay Roach said he always envisioned ``Meet the Parents'' as a
certain kind of movie, something along the lines of David Lynch's
``Eraserhead'' or Martin Scorsese's ``After Hours'' _ a movie in
which an innocent man is drawn gradually deeper into a Kafkaesque
nightmare that is partly, but only partly, of his own making. ``I
always saw it as an anxiety dream,'' Roach said.
</P>
<P>
   Roach, best known for directing the two ``Austin Powers''
comedies, said he had some trouble getting studio bosses to see him
at the helm of a more character-driven comedy like ``Meet the
Parents,'' which opens on Oct. 6. And it was only after Steven
Spielberg had briefly flirted with the idea of directing the
project and Jim Carrey had considered starring in it that it came
back to Roach and Ben Stiller, the star Roach said he had always
envisioned in the lead role. Not long after, Robert De Niro
expressed an interest in playing the future father-in-law. ``We
always knew it would be somebody kind of scary,'' Roach said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to have the hero engage in a string of small, white
lies intended to ease his introduction to his future in-laws, only
to have them grow and gradually ensnare him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always saw it as having this universal quality,'' Roach
said. ``It's something that almost everyone has to go through,
meeting your future spouse's parents. You're trying too hard,
making stupid jokes, maybe bringing an inappropriate present, and
you're previsualizing disaster at every step. Which, of course,
only helps make it happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
