<SLUG> BC-TV-THATSLIFE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-LIST CAST GIVES `THAT'S LIFE' A LIFT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN HODGES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle  
The premise of CBS' ``That's Life'' isn't entirely new. Heather
Paige Kent plays a late-blooming college freshman just as Rhea
Perlman did on ``Pearl,'' which bombed a few seasons ago.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's life on television, though _ and this show has a lot more
going for it than ``Pearl'' ever did.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot airing Sunday is good enough to bring you back next
Saturday, when the show moves into its regular time slot.
</P>
<P>
   The mob from ``The Sopranos'' would feel right at home in
``That's Life's'' New Jersey neighborhood, but the members of this
loud and fractious Italian-American family are anything but Mafia
hitmen. They're hard-working blue-collar, all for one and one for
all.
</P>
<P>
   Except at times like now.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia DeLucca (Kent) is the guest of honor at a bridal shower,
where the bride is having second thoughts. Lydia's 32 years old,
and after an eight-year engagement, she's about about to marry Lou
Buttafucco (Sonny Marinelli), a lout she doesn't even love, much
less respect.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia has a dream. Since she was a little girl, she's dreamed of
going to college and making something of herself. Instead, she's
had 58 crummy jobs _ now she's a bartender _ and she's saved every
cent she's made, waiting to spend it on her wedding. If and when
Lou ever stopped dragging his feet at setting the date.
</P>
<P>
   She's told her thick-headed groom-to-be what she wants to do,
but he doesn't get it. ``You'll go back to school, graduate at 36,
go to work, and then quit to have kids and resent them,'' he wails.
So now he doesn't get her, either. The bride-to-be bolts.
</P>
<P>
   But when Lydia dumps Lou and announces she's using her bridal
dowry to pay her way through college, her family thinks she's lost
it. They close ranks on the side of the guy she's jilted.
</P>
<P>
   Casting counts here. ``That's Life'' sometimes looks better than
it is, and not just because Kent is a most appealing actress. Her
backup family is A-list, with Ellen Burstyn and Paul Sorvino
playing Ma and Pa, Dolly and Frank DeLucca, and Keith Dillon as her
playful policeman brother, Paul.
</P>
<P>
   The only ones on Lydia's side are Bob, her shadowy barfly
confidante, and her well-cast best friends, Debi Mazur as
neighborhood beauty salon queen Jackie O'Grady, and Kristin Bauer
as Candy Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia's first day on campus is as disastrous as the hairdo that
pal Jackie creates for her to impress her new classmates.
</P>
<P>
   First, Lydia's wreck of a car gives up the ghost, and then Dr.
Victor Leski (Paul Firth), the esteemed professor of her first
class, Human Behavior 101, turns out to be the drunk she had to
throw out of her bar the previous night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its deja vu premise, ``That's Life'' goes into this TV
life with a fair number of promising moments. What's not to like,
if the scripts can manage to come up to this solid cast, and Kent's
considerable charisma?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``That's Life'' &QL; 
7 p.m. Sunday &QL; 
CBS &QL; 
Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
