<SLUG> BC-FILM-DARKDAYS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DARK DAYS' PUTS FACES ON UNDERGROUND HOMELESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
The closing credits to ``Dark Days,'' the remarkable, sad, funny,
tough, vivid, new documentary about life for the homeless in New
York's subways, includes an unusual credit. Amtrak is listed among
the entities thanked for providing shelter to the filmmaking crew.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This only makes sense once you learn that the crew lived in the
subway tunnels while making the movie. The British-born Marc Singer
moved into those dank caverns and lived three months, getting to
know the inhabitants, before he even broached the subject of making
a film.
</P>
<P>
   Once he did, the movie _ his first _ became a collaborative
effort. His entire crew, from electricians to sound recorders,
consisted of original tunnel dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   The film's power resides in Singer's steadfast dedication to
honestly chronicling the lives of the people who lived underground.
So intense is his gaze that his subjects almost instantly are
pulled from the faceless horde of ``the homeless'' and become real.
</P>
<P>
   The black and white images are searing and brutal. Men descend
through holes in the ground like rats to reach garbage-strewn
shanty towns. Repeatedly, Singer cuts away to show the vermin that
live alongside them, competing for food and space.
</P>
<P>
   These men _ the movie focuses on only one woman _ are desperate
souls who have gone underground out of necessity. They find it
safer than sleeping in parks or alleys where they might be
attacked. As one man says, explaining why the filthy and
dangerous-looking tunnels are a refuge: ``Anybody in their right
minds be scared to come down here.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some of the folks we meet aren't in their right
minds. Tommy, a young man who says he left home in his teens to
escape an abusive environment, says most of the people down there
are drug addicts. Others have mental problems.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their problems, they have made for themselves a largely
self-sufficient community. They've built their houses from scrap
wood and furnished them with furniture, lamps, rugs and television
sets they've scavenged from above-ground dumps. They get power by
tapping into underground electric lines. We see a chess set in one
home. Another has a pen where a man keeps dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You adjust,'' says Greg, a loquacious man who scratches out a
living by scavenging in trash cans and selling what he finds. He's
lived in the tunnels for five years. ``You'd be surprised what the
human mind and the human body can adjust to.''
</P>
<P>
   The amazing thing about this documentary is how normal so many
of the lives are, even though they are lived in extraordinary
circumstances. The stories of how some of them got there will break
your heart.
</P>
<P>
   While Singer was making his documentary, Amtrak decided to evict
the homeless and remove their makeshift community. This provides a
dramatic framework late in the movie. The subway dwellers first vow
to resist but eventually agree to move out when an advocacy group
manages to get them subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   To see these people cleaned up and living in clean apartments,
no trace remaining of their former lives, is to realize how fine
the line is between ``us'' and ``them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were dark days,'' Gregg says. ``Real dark. At the time
it didn't bother me at all, but now that I've had time to sit back
and think about it, I wonder how I could do that. How'd I let
myself go down like that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' says Ralph, a former crack addict who looks and
sounds a bit like actor John Malkovich, ``it was like it never
happened at all. It was like a nightmare, and I woke up from it,
and I'm staying awake.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Dark Days'' &QL; 
Director: Marc Singer &QL; 
Rating: Not rated &QL; 
Grade: A &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
