<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5547 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     09-28 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   ``ALMOST FAMOUS,'' starring Patrick Fugit, Billy Crudup, Kate
Hudson and Philip Seymour Hoffman. Written and directed by Cameron
Crowe (R, 120 minutes). Crowe's loose, affectionate look back on
his earlier career as a teen-age rock journalist overflows with
wonderful performances and memorable moments. Fugit brings the
perfect balance of intelligence and innocence to the role of
William Miller, a San Diego teen-ager who takes to the road with a
scruffy band called Stillwater, on assignment for Rolling Stone.
``Almost Famous'' isn't perfect _ it lacks a necessary dimension of
demonic sleaze _ but Crowe's smart, compassionate writing, and the
performances of Crudup, Hudson, Jason Lee and Frances McDormand
(among many others) make it hum (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``BRING IT ON,'' starring Kirsten Dunst, Jesse Bradford and
Eliza Dushku. Directed by Peyton Reed (PG-13, 110 minutes). Even
though it does feature young women bouncing around in skimpy
outfits, this cheerleader comedy, directed with giddy, sometimes
sloppy pep-rally intensity by Reed from a brisk, slangy script by
Jessica Bendinger, is more than a low-minded appeal to male
lechery. Though bound by the conventions of the sports movie and
the teen-age romantic comedy, ``Bring It On'' has a fine satirical
edge, and at least glances at some serious issues of race and
sexuality. It's also a vehicle for the vibrant comic talents of
Dunst, ably supported by Bradford as her cute, nonconformist love
interest, and Dushku as his sister (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE CELL,'' starring Jennifer Lopez, Vincent D'Onofrio and
Vince Vaughn. Directed by Tarsem Singh (R, 110 minutes). A serial
killer named Stargher ( D'Onofrio) who abducts women and imprisons
them in a Plexiglas cell that slowly fills with water has a seizure
and goes into a coma. His latest victim is trapped in his cell, and
she has to be found before the automated torture takes her life. An
FBI agent ( Vaughn) talks a child psychologist ( Lopez) into using
an experimental technique to enter the killer's subconscious.
Singh's talents haven't quite jelled into storytelling yet. He
folds this tale over and over on itself, working with a script that
blends elements of ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' ``Manhunter,''
``The Matrix,'' ``Seven,'' ``Dreamscape'' and ``Spellbound'' with
the stop-motion animation of the brothers Quay (``Street of
Crocodiles''), the moody photography of Matt Mahurin, the paintings
of Francis Bacon and so many other things that there's no there
there (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``DANCER IN THE DARK,'' starring Bjork and Catherine Deneuve.
Directed by Lars von Trier (R, 134 minutes). von Trier's new
musical, shot in raw, jumpy digital video, is a fascinating
exercise in brutality, mitigated by the otherworldy charisma (and
the music) of the Icelandic pop star Bjork. As Selma, a Czech
immigrant factory worker going blind in the early 1960s in
Washington State (the film was shot in Sweden), Bjork seems to be
inventing a whole new style of film acting, and her performance is
miraculous. von Trier, continuing his campaign to rescue the art of
film from complacency and convention, follows Selma's utter
annihilation with sadistic relish. ``Dancer in the Dark'' is both
stupefyingly bad and utterly overpowering; it can elicit, sometimes
within a single scene, a gasp of rapture and a spasm of revulsion.
Come to the theater prepared, with a handkerchief in one hand and a
rotten tomato in the other (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``DUETS'' starring Huey Lewis, Gwyneth Paltrow, Maria Bello,
Andre Braugher, Scott Speedman and Paul Giamatti. Directed by Bruce
Paltrow (R, 113 minutes). Paltrow's musical follows the adventures
of six lost souls looking for salvation in the demimonde of
competitive karaoke. The movie is a mess, lurching from dark satire
to soapy melodrama and punctuated with squirmingly earnest
renditions of songs like ``Bette Davis Eyes'' and ``Hit Me With
Your Best Shot.'' But ``Duets'' has its moments of brilliance, and
a certain reckless integrity. The ensemble cast features Lewis and
Paltrow, the director's daughter, but they're overshadowed by
Giamatti's over-the-top performance as an alienated businessman.
This is a very bad movie, but from time to time you catch glimpses
of a very good movie trapped inside, struggling to get out (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``GOYA IN BORDEAUX,'' starring Francisco Rabal, Jose Coronado,
Dafne Fernandez and Maribel Verdu. Written and directed by Carlos
Saura (R, 94 minutes). There's nothing subtle about Saura's
splashy, sensuous biographical montage of the great Spanish artist
Francisco Goya, whom the movie portrays as an 18th-century raging
bull. Crammed with surreal imagery that quotes from his paintings,
the movie is a series of deathbed flashbacks, many of them
recollections of his passion for the fiery Dutchess of Alba.
Gorgeously lighted and photographed by Vittorio Storaro (Stephen
Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``NURSE BETTY,'' starring Morgan Freeman, Renee Zellweger, Chris
Rock and Greg Kinnear. Directed by Neil LaBute (R, 112 minutes).
Alternately hilarious, poignant and gory, this modern fairy tale,
which follows an aspiring nurse ( Zellweger) suffering from
traumatic amnesia to Los Angeles to win the love of her favorite
soap-opera character, is a contemporary ``Wizard of Oz.'' Hollywood
is the Emerald City. Kinnear is the self-centered actor who plays
her heart's desire on television. Freeman and Rock are a sadly
introspective hit man and his hotheaded protege who follow her
across the country with intention to do harm. This may be the
deepest and funniest American comedy since David O. Russell's
``Flirting With Disaster'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE ORIGINAL KINGS OF COMEDY,'' starring Steve Harvey, D.L.
Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer and Bernie Mac. Directed by Spike
Lee (R, 117 minutes). Filmed before a live audience on two nights
in February in Charlotte, N.C., the self-proclaimed Kings of Comedy
swagger across the stage, urban legends in resplendent outfits.
Until a couple of years ago the comedians' exposure was limited
mostly to cable television. Here their comedy gives audiences that
have never seen anything like it a hilarious window on a new world.
They display their chops when they talk about family, specifically
African-American family with roots in the South (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``SOLAS,'' starring Maria Galiana and Ana Fernandez. Written and
directed by Benito Zambrano (not rated, 98 minutes). When a simple
Spanish woman ( Galiana) makes a rare journey to the city to be
with her husband, who is having surgery, she stays with her
embittered, alcoholic daughter ( Fernandez) who works for a
cleaning service. Galiana's eloquent, utterly unsentimental
portrayal of a woman who expects little of life is an
extraordinarily moving portrait of unconditional love gradually
working its wonders (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
