<HEADER>
A5548 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-PERUVIAN-BO     09-28 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PERUVIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRICE OF REFUGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE CLINTON administration's covert pressure on Panama to grant
asylum to Peru's fleeing intelligence boss, Vladimiro Montesinos,
recalls the bad old days of the Cold War, when blood-drenched
tyrants flying the flag of anticommunism could count on Uncle Sam
to procure them a safe haven in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Jimmy Carter sent the shah of Iran in 1979, at a
time when multitudes had taken to the streets of Tehran, demanding
that the shah be repatriated to pay for the crimes of his secret
police. Panama was also the destination of Haiti's uniformed
despot, General Raoul Cedras and of exiled Guatemalan general Jorge
Serrano Elias, wanted for the massacres of native people in
Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   To recollect this tradition of parking exiled thugs in Panama is
to recognize why Peruvians and Panamanians alike are so angry about
Washington's role in aiding Montesinos to escape from justice back
home.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvians yearning for the rule of law see Uncle Sam playing a
familiar cynical game above their heads. Panamanians eager for
authentic independence have reason to perceive Washington's demand
for a favor as one more humiliating example of Panama's abject
fealty to the North Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Since the administration has acknowledged that Montesinos, the
iron fist of Alberto Fujimori's discredited regime in Peru, had a
privileged relationship with the Central Intelligence Agency, it is
safe to assume that he owes his safe haven in Panama to a
double-barreled blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   The more evident of the two was the rumored threat of a coup in
Peru, a prospect made all the more plausible because Montesinos
over the years had placed his proteges in positions of power within
the military.
</P>
<P>
   Much as the administration and its collaborators in the
Organization of American States might have argued that impunity for
Montesinos was a necessary price to pay for the flowering of true
democracy in Peru, the unspoken argument for saving his skin was
that he might otherwise reveal exactly how much Washington knew _
and tolerated _ of the torture, murder, and corruption Peru
suffered under Fujimori's rule.
</P>
<P>
   If the administration is going to protect Montesinos in Panama _
or wherever he may ultimately find asylum _ to promote democracy in
Peru, then the least it can demand of Fujimori is that he step
aside immediately and permit free and fair elections soon.
</P>
<P>
   In light of American protection of Montesinos, Fujimori should
also be told to release Lori Berenson, the American convicted by a
military tribunal on the preposterous charge of being a leader of a
terrorist group in Peru. Washington's realpolitik in Latin American
should be leavened with a touch of justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
