<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     09-28 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: wonders (Holden.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``SPACE COWBOYS,'' starring Clint Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones,
Donald Sutherland and James Garner (PG-13, 105 minutes). Directed
by Eastwood. The second half of Eastwood's new movie is a pleasant
reworking of the standard trouble-in-space movie, with Eastwood
himself leading a heroic team of astronauts that also includes
Jones, Sutherland and Garner. But the first half, which consists of
the comic tough-old-guy interplay among these four sublime actors,
is a boisterous, easygoing tribute to manhood and maturity.
Sutherland and Jones are in especially fine form, as are Marcia Gay
Harden, playing a NASA engineer, and James Cromwell as (once again)
the villainous bureaucrat who tries to deny the old-timers their
shot at celestial glory (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``SUNSHINE,'' starring Ralph Fiennes, Rachel Weisz, Jennifer
Ehle, Rosemary Harris and James Frian. Directed by Istvan Szabo (R,
180 minutes). In Szabo's tale of 20th-century Hungarian history,
Fiennes plays three members of a wealthy Jewish Budapest family _
grandfather, father and son _ who endure the corruption of the
Austro-Hungarian Empire, the viciousness of Fascism and the
brutality of Communism. Fiennes' performances and those of Ehle and
Harris (playing the same character at different stages of life)
help save the film from melodramatic excess. Even though much of
the story is crudely told, ``Sunshine'' is a serious, humane and
thought-provoking attempt to make sense of complicated and painful
historical experiences (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE TAO OF STEVE,'' starring Donal Logue and Greer Goodman.
Directed by Jenniphr Goodman (R, 87 minutes). The ``Steve'' in the
title refers to the spiritual embodiment of cool as exemplified by
Steve McQueen, Steve McGarrett (``Hawaii Five-O'') and Steve Austin
(``The Six Million Dollar Man''), a goal to which the blobby and
amiable Dex aspires. In this light-as-a-marshmallow romantic
comedy, Dex ( Logue) has lined up quotes from Heidegger, Thomas
Aquinas and ``Don Giovanni'' to rationalize his aimless
pleasure-seeking in this rather aimless movie. Logue's performance
as a nice-guy player _ his weight doesn't keep him from scoring
with the ladies _ makes the movie glide. Dex has a cherub's glee
over what he gets away with. The movie becomes a lot less
interesting when it rolls around to the inevitable quest for a
steady relationship with a woman ( Goodman) whose feelings were
trampled in Dex's compulsive fox hunting. ``Tao'' can't redeem the
moves to its predictable end, but its protagonist has a great time
getting there (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE WATCHER,'' starring Keanu Reeves, James Spader and Marisa
Tomei. Directed by Joe Charbanic (R, 93 minutes). Reeves
enunciates, Spader frets and Tomei just looks tired in this
pretentious, incoherent compilation of serial-killer cliches and
warmed-over MTV-style visual flourishes. Reeves is a sadistic,
diabolically intelligent strangler, Spader the F.B.I. agent whose
psychic torment is the killer's real turn-on and Tomei is the
agent's kindly therapist (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE WAY OF THE GUN,'' starring Ryan Phillippe, Benicio Del
Toro and Juliette Lewis. Written and directed by Christopher
McQuarrie (R, 120 minutes). This film feels like a more violent and
grim version of a Coen brothers film; it could be Quentin
Tarantino's ``Raising Arizona.'' Its lead characters are small-time
criminals who tend to speak in ambitious and hilariously orotund
turns of phrase. The two, um, heroes, while visiting a sperm bank,
hatch a plan to kidnap a young woman doing surrogate-mother duty
for a wealthy couple. ``Gun'' is a stylish and intelligent film
noir built around the feelings adults have about babies, with a
birth and a lengthy gunfight and standoff (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``WOMAN ON TOP,'' starring Penelope Cruz, Murilo Benicio and
Harold Perrineau Jr. Directed by Fina Torres (R, 85 minutes). It
makes sense that the delectable Cruz would play a chef. This
romantic comedy uses an amusing conceit, that she needs a magic
spell to so enchant men that they wouldn't bother to look down at
their plates _ a case in which magic is as redundant as giving the
lethal boxer Roy Jones Jr. a third fist. Cruz flees Brazil and her
philandering husband in order to go to San Francisco. There, she
becomes the host of a cooking show, where she delights the local
male population and sambas waft in the background. Negligible but
diverting (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
