<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANDING WOMEN'S CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE FOOD AND DRUG Administration's overdue approval of the early
abortion pill RU-486 does not signal an end to the abortion wars,
even though it will make the wrenching choice of whether to have an
abortion more private and more accessible for many women. Medical
abortion, through the use of the drug mifepristone, should never
displace the option of surgical abortion, just as no abortion
should ever displace careful family planning and contraception.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was approved in France over 10 years ago, mifepristone
has been the object of fierce attack by the antiabortion movement,
precisely because it takes politics out of the abortion equation
and extends choices to women in remote areas where clinics have
been shut down or where they are under attack by protesting
zealots. Thanks to the steady chipping away of reproductive rights
by prolife forces since abortion became legal here in 1973, fully
86 percent of the counties in the United States have no abortion
providers today.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, since 1995 the pill has been quietly tested in
clinical trials by the Planned Parenthood Federation without
incident, including by some 200 women here in Boston. It has been
found a safe, effective, and noninvasive alternative to surgical
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA was frustratingly slow to grant its approval, but when
it finally did Thursday it was without most of the restrictions
women's health advocates had feared. The drug will be dispensed
only by a physician, but it will not have to be in a hospital.
There will be no registry of providers and patients, which would
have been a chilling requirement. And pharmacies will not be
distributing the drug, which removes the possibility of drugstore
boycotts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, medical abortion is not for every woman. It will require
three visits to doctor's offices over two weeks, and it can be
painful and disruptive, since it mimics spontaneous miscarriage. It
can only be administered through the first 49 days of pregnancy.
Other abortion options and, most important, easy access to
contraception for women of all ages, must be continued.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's action also opens the way for more FDA study of other
applications for mifepristone. The Institute of Medicine believes
it may be useful in treating ovarian cancer, endometriosis,
glaucoma, and breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Few drugs have suffered so much political interference when they
show promise for so much progress. It is a good day for science
over politics when American women can finally get the benefit of
medical advances that have been available in other countries for
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
