<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blacking Out The Body Parts
</P>
<P>
   It may not be down in writing but censorious fig leaves placed
over genitals probably weren't what the Danish filmmaker Lars von
Trier had in mind five years ago when he formulated his so-called
Vow of Chastity, the set of stringent movie-making rules known as
Dogma 95.
</P>
<P>
   von Trier, whose ``Dancer in the Dark'' opened the New York Film
Festival last week, seeks to purge the frills and tricks and
anything else remotely Hollywood from the process. Presumably, that
would include the requirements of the Motion Picture Association of
America's rating system, which mandates that genitalia be covered
if a film is to receive an R instead of an NC-17.
</P>
<P>
   And covered they are in von Trier's ``Idiots,'' which will be
released on Tuesday by USA Home Entertainment. To get the R before
short theater runs in New York and Los Angeles, USA Films added
black patches when and where required in the movie, which follows a
commune of well-to-do Nordic layabouts who wander about irritating
the bourgeoisie by acting as if they are mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   Often a video is released in R and unrated or NC-17 versions,
but not in this case. The black squares remain in the one and only
``Idiots,'' still rated R. A spokeswoman for USA said that there
was no consumer interest in an unrated version.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say what's more idiotic,'' A.O. Scott wrote in
The New York Times, ``a director who treats his audience like
uptight prigs in need of a gratuitous shock, or an industry
organization that treats filmgoers like children.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Double Scare
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rocky Horror Picture Show'' is one of two big new
re-issues for Tuesday. The midnight staple is 25 years old, ripe
for a commemorative tape and two-disc DVD from Fox with soundtracks
enough to let one shout along with the mobs in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   The other film is ``Rosemary's Baby'' (1968). ``It opens like a
Doris Day movie; that was the whole point,'' says the production
designer Richard Sylbert on a new DVD and tape from Paramount.
Having completed ``Dance of the Vampires'' (a k a ``Pardon Me but
Your Teeth Are in My Neck'') the year before, Roman Polanski, the
director, says he was looking away from horror and more toward
making a skiing movie _ Robert Redford in ``Downhill Racer,''
perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Redford was considered for the role of Guy Woodhouse in
``Rosemary's Baby'' before Polanski decided that a harder, darker
New York type like John Cassevetes would better portray the
ambitious actor who accepts Satan's help with his career in return
for letting the devil father his child.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning Rosemary was envisioned as a ``milk-fed
American girl,'' far from the gaunt young woman portrayed by Mia
Farrow. Polanski says that when he first read the script, adapted
from Ira Levin's novel, he thought it was a soap opera. The film
still has a remarkably sunny look. ``The great horror film without
any horror in it,'' Sylbert says.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   East-West
</P>
<P>
   Lured home by promises of Soviet citizenship, Russian emigres
returned after World War II only to be caught in a Stalinist purge
that led them to death and disaster. Aleksei Golovine and his
rebellious French wife, Marie (Oleg Menchikov and Sandrine
Bonnaire), are spared because he is a doctor who decides that his
own good behavior is the best way to protect his family. With its
old-fashioned American big-movie feeling, Regis Wargnier's moving
film, A.O. Scott wrote in The New York Times, ``may justly be
faulted for dissolving the horrors of history in the catharsis of
melodrama, but it also uses the resources of melodrama to shed
light on forgotten history.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $29.95. 115 minutes.
French and Russian with English subtitles. PG-13. Release date:
Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   U-571
</P>
<P>
   A damaged German submarine carrying a coveted code machine is
forced to the surface, whereupon the device is captured by the
Americans. But never count the Germans out underwater. One dirty
trick deserves many others as the American crew, led by an untested
young officer (Matthew McConaughey), battles to stay watertight
while the director, Jonathan Mostow, ``does an impressive job of
moving his cameras around very cramped spaces and uncomfortably
close to his actors'' (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   -2000. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $26.98. 120 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gould's Secret
</P>
<P>
   Ian Holm is ferociously front and center as the title character
in Stanley Tucci's otherwise rather somnolent film adapted from
Joseph Mitchell's New Yorker profiles of 1942 and 1964, ``Professor
Sea Gull'' and ``Joe Gould's Secret.'' An unstable Harvard
graduate, Gould came to New York in 1916 and started panhandling
while supposedly beginning his masterwork, the million-word-plus
``Oral History of Our Time.'' Or so he maintained during raucous
decades being the Greenwich Village character twice examined by
Mitchell, played credibly by Tucci. But lacking dramatic tension,
the film settles for being an atmospheric biography of someone's
most unforgettable character. ``It could have been so much more''
(Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   -2000. USA. $56.49; DVD, $24.95. 108 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   Final Destination
</P>
<P>
   About to take off with his classmates on a senior trip to Paris,
Alex Browning (Devon Sawa) has a strong enough premonition of
disaster to rear up from his seat and demand to be taken off the
plane, which explodes on takeoff. For the rest of the film, he and
several other survivors try to stay ahead of the grim reaper who,
having been cheated once is now picking them off one by one in a
series of bizarre accidents. ``But even by the crude standards of
teen-age horror, `Final Destination' is dramatically flat''
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   -2000. New Line. $117.30; DVD, $24.95. 110 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE PALLISERS. When it came to prolificacy, the Victorian
novelist Anthony Trollope outdistanced Dickens. Here we have the
first eight episodes of Simon Raven's adaptation of Trollope's six
``political'' novels, rendered in 26 parts for the BBC and
broadcast on PBS during the '70s. The aging, unwed Duke of Omnium
(Roland Culver) needs an heir. Should he take a young wife or leave
the job to his newphew, Plantagenet Palliser (Philip Latham), and
his bride, Lady Glencora (Susan Hampshire)? 1977. Acorn. $79.95,
four cassettes, DVD, $79.95, four discs. 400 minutes. Information:
(800) 999-0212.
</P>
<P>
   CAT ON A HOT TIN TIN ROOF, THE CAFETERIA and A MATTER OF
PRINCIPLE. In the first of three PBS American Playhouse
productions, Tommy Lee Jones, Jessica Lange, Rip Torn and Kim
Stanley star in Tennessee Williams' ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof'' (144
minutes). Bob Dishy portrays a refugee infatuated with a Holocaust
survivor (Zohra Lampert) in Isaac Bashevis Singer's ``Cafeteria''
(53 minutes). In John D. Weaver's ``Matter of Principle'' (56
minutes), Alan Arkin and Barbara Dana play a cantankerous West
Virginia scrooge and his wife. Monterey Media. $19.95 each.
Information: (800) 424-2593.
</P>
<P>
   DOO WOP 50. Fifty minutes of hits from the '50s and '60s are
performed by the Platters, the Skyliners, Johnny Maestro and the
Brooklyn Bridge and the Capris. 2000. Rhino. Two cassettes, $19.98
each; DVD, $29.99. 150 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
