<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-SUHARTO-NYT     09-28 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-SUHARTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE AGAINST FORMER INDONESIAN LEADER   IS DISMISSED 
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ An Indonesian court dismissed the
government's corruption case against former President Suharto on
Thursday after court-appointed doctors declared him medically unfit
to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling immediately touched off violent clashes outside the
auditorium where the trial was being conducted between hundreds of
supporters and opponents of Suharto, whose 32-year rule ended in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   As two busloads of his defenders arrived, anti-Suharto student
demonstrators pelted them with rocks. The police said that one
Suharto supporter was beaten to death and two were severely
injured, and that a bus was set on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling, even though it may be legally correct, sends the
wrong message to the average person: that there's still no justice
in Indonesia,'' said Indira Samego, a political analyst. ``It says
that politics in Indonesia are still run by the same old forces,
and that's what people are going to believe until the government
proves otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a major setback for Indonesia's democratically
elected government, which sought to bring the ailing 79-year-old
Suharto to justice for human rights abuses. The government had also
charged him with embezzling $590 million from state charities while
in office.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors testified on Thursday that he had suffered three
strokes last year that left him unable to understand or answer
complex questions. One doctor said Suharto had the communications
skills of ``a kindergartner'' and took up to a minute to answer
basic inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Marzuki Darusman expressed deep disappointment
with the court's ruling, saying the justice system had failed the
people. ``The thing that we aimed for, which was to truly obtain
justice for the people, was not achieved,'' said Darusman, who had
insisted Suharto was well enough to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they would appeal the decision, but they
acknowledged that Suharto's declining health made it unlikely they
would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The corruption case was more than a reckoning with the former
president and his cronies for enriching themselves at public
expense. It was seen as a litmus test for restoring the rule of law
and a sense of equality to Indonesia, where corruption permeated
nearly every aspect of society under Suharto's government.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, along with his six children, is believed to have stolen
billions of dollars through a broad network of deals in which his
family made money from almost every sector of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The justice ministry on Thursday ordered the detention of
Suharto's youngest son, Hutomo Mandala Putra, who is known as Tommy
Suharto, after the Supreme Court overturned a lower court decision
and sentenced him to an 18-month prison term for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Suharto has been in the public eye since President
Abdurrahman Wahid first ordered him arrested on Sept. 15 after a
spate of bomb explosions in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   As word of the decision not to prosecute the former president
spread, hundreds of protesters converged on his house in central
Jakarta, where they were met by dozens of police officers who fired
tear gas and plastic bullets into the stone-wielding crowds. The
situation remained tense Thursday evening as large numbers of
officers were brought into the capital to maintain order. Many
people expressed fear of increasing violence in the aftermath of
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Suharto had been under house arrest for more than four
months during the legal and judicial gyrations of the government's
case. His lawyers and doctors had repeatedly said he was too sick
to attend the trial. But government physicians maintained that he
was capable of understanding the case against him.
</P>
<P>
   After he refused to appear for two earlier court sessions,
judges ordered an independent checkup, which was released on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For the new administration of Wahid, losing the case could not
have come at a worse time. Indonesia, with the fourth-largest
population, is struggling to forge a new democracy despite a weak
economy, political infighting and growing sectarian violence that
has killed thousands and displaced hundreds of thousands more.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, who was elected in October in the country's first
contested election, and Darusman are now under pressure to show
that they can bring Indonesia's former regime to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government doesn't do something to make up for the loss
of the Suharto case, it will handicap the entire process of
political and economic reforms, especially the sense of enforcing
law and order,'' said Teten Masduki, coordinator for Indonesia
Corruption Watch. ``Like it or not, despite the good that he might
have done for the country, Suharto remains the focus of people's
hatred.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
