<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5562 &Cx1f; ttj-z
b w BC-ABORTION-PILL-HNS &LR;      09-28 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-PILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ABORTION FOES ASSAIL ABORTION PILL'S APPROVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER A. DLOUHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Anti-abortion leaders condemned the Food and Drug
Administration for its decision Thursday to allow RU-486, the
abortion pill, to be sold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is unprecedented.'' said Rep. Tom Coburn,
R-Okla., a physician who says he has delivered 3,500 babies in his
career and 400 while in Congress. ``Never before has the FDA
approved a drug intended to kill people.''
</P>
<P>
   The obstetrician said the FDA ``bowed to the political pressure
of the abortion lobby and the White House and approved the drug
with inadequate patient protections.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidates split over the wisdom of the FDA's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush criticized the
decision, saying the abortion pill ``will make abortions more and
more common, rather than more and more rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic candidate Al Gore said the FDA's decision wasn't
political but ``about the health and safety of American women and a
woman's fundamental right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., called for Senate hearings into the
FDA's approval process. Coburn vowed to introduce legislation that
could block the drug. However, it appeared unlikely there would be
any action until next year because Congress is rushing to adjourn
early next month.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes claim the long-term effects of Mifeprex aren't
known. ``This unprecedented act of turning women into guinea pigs
is a payoff by the Clinton administration to the abortion
radicals,'' said Gary Bauer, president of American Values _ a
conservative advocacy group _ and one-time aspirant for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Approving a drug that we know kills one person and may harm a
second just shows how wedded the Clinton administration is to the
abortion lobby,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights advocates hailed the FDA's approval of RU-486 as
a step that will revolutionize abortions in America, by making the
procedure more private and accessible to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mifepristone's approval is one of the most significant
advances in women's reproductive health that we have seen in
decades,'' said Kate Michelman, president of NARAL. ``Its approval
is yet another milestone on the long road to women's reproductive
freedom and equality in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., a leader among congressional
advocates of abortion rights, said RU-486 ``provides a method that
avoids invasive surgery. Today is a day that women should remember
because their health and their choices are finally being
respected.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA limited the use of the RU-486 abortion pill to pregnant
women within 49 days of their last menstrual period. The drug,
which has the chemical name mifepristone and will be marketed in
the United States as Mifeprex, could be available within a month.
The pill has been available in France for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The abortion pill is actually three separate pills, each
containing 200 milligrams of mifepristone. The woman takes all
three pills at the same time. The pills block progesterone, a
hormone essential for maintaining pregnancy. Without progesterone,
a woman's uterine lining thins, preventing an embryo from receiving
nourishment, remaining implanted and growing.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, she takes two other pills _ each containing 200
milligrams of misoprostol. This drug induces uterine contractions
to expel the embryo.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA approval requires that the drugs can only be prescribed
by physicians qualified to determine the age of a patient's
pregnancy and detect ectopic, or tubal, pregnancies. In those
instances, the FDA said, the pills cannot be used because usage
could cause complications.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FDA, physicians who prescribe the drug must
also be able to provide or arrange for ``surgical solutions'' in
cases of incomplete abortion or severe bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Women should return for a follow-up visit 14 days after taking
the second set of pills.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA cautioned that chemical abortions can cause painful
cramping and bleeding, which typically last between nine and 16
days. One in every 100 women might experience bleeding so severe it
requires a surgical procedure, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The pills fail to work in about 5 to 8 percent of women,
requiring surgical abortions to complete the process, according to
the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the abortion pill say the complications are less
severe than those with surgical abortions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; story can end here. Optional material follows. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been approved in France since 1988 and has been
used since 1992 by women in England, Sweden and France, Mifeprex
has only been available to American women through limited clinical
trials.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, President Clinton directed the FDA to start clinical
trials on the drug and later was instrumental in urging Roussel
Uclaf to donate U.S. patent rights to the not-for-profit Population
Council.
</P>
<P>
   The Population Council had trouble finding a manufacturer for
the drug because potential makers feared public criticism from
abortion foes. The council, a not-for-profit New York-based
organization that supports population control, eventually selected
Danco Laboratories, a New York start-up company, to develop the
drug.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the FDA said mifepristone was safe and effective, but
approval was delayed after the original U.S. manufacturer of the
drug dropped out. The approval process was further delayed because
Danco Laboratories _ the new manufacturer _ had to meet federal
manufacturing and labeling requirements.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
