<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-0929     09-28 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NUMBER OF AMERICANS WITHOUT HEALTH INSURANCE DROPS
 &HT;    With HEALTH-INSURANCE-DATA, for a box/chart, which has moved.
 &HT;    ATTN TEXAS EDS: Your state tops the list in the proportion of
uninsured.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly 2 million Americans, half of them children,
obtained health-care coverage last year, the first time in 12 years
that the number of people without health insurance dropped, the
Census Bureau says in a report to be released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The country's low jobless rate and broader health-care coverage
offered by employers contributed to the turnaround. The number of
people without health insurance declined by 1.7 million between
1998 and 1999, from 44.3 million to 42.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The number of uninsured children fell by more than 1 million to
10 million, from 15.4 percent to 13.9 percent of all children, its
lowest level since 1995. About 567,000 poor children gained health
insurance in 1999, stemming in part from a Clinton administration
push to increase government health-care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the number of uninsured Americans, particularly among the
working poor, remained high. About 15 of every 100 Americans
remained without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gains last year, the number of uninsured has
increased by nearly 8 million since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a morning drizzle after a prolonged drought,'' Ron
Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a non-profit consumer
advocacy group on health-case issues, said of the 1999 decline in
the number of uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Young adults and immigrants were the least likely to have
coverage. Minorities were less likely than whites to have
insurance, though coverage increased across all racial and ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Texas topped the list of states with the highest share of
uninsured, 24.1 percent when statistically averaged from 1997 to
1999. Minnesota had the lowest rate of uninsured people, 8.8
percent of its population without coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans _ 63 percent _ were covered by a health insurance
plan linked to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driving force behind this improvement was an increase in
the likelihood of people having employment-based health
insurance,'' said Robert Mills, author of the Census Bureau report.
</P>
<P>
   However, analysts said two vulnerable groups remained worrisome:
low-income working people not eligible for Medicaid or other
government-subsidized health care coverage and young adults unable
to obtain or afford coverage from their employers.
</P>
<P>
   One of every three people in poverty was not covered by a health
plan in 1999, virtually unchanged from the previous year. While
Medicaid covered 12.9 million poor people during at least part of
1999, another 10.4 million people below the poverty line had no
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Only 71 percent of young adults, ages 18-24, had health
insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton took office in 1993 pledging health insurance
for all Americans. In the next five years, the ranks of the
uninsured grew by more than 4.5 million as administration efforts
to convince Congress to approve a comprehensive health care
proposal failed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   However, Congress and the White House have agreed over the years
on a string of incremental measures to expand coverage. Overall,
about one of every four Americans has some form of government
insurance through Medicaid, Medicare or other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Health care and the uninsured has been a major issue in the
presidential election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Al Gore would expand the federal Children's Health
Insurance Program and provide tax credits for low-income families
and the elderly. Republican George W. Bush has proposed a $2,000
refundable health credit for low-income families not covered by
Medicaid or an employers' health plan to be able to purchase their
own insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have promised to make health insurance more
affordable for small businesses who cover their employees. Most new
jobs are created by small businesses, which are less likely to
offer employee health benefits because of the high cost of
insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The non-profit Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation has been
studying uninsured families since 1995 and finds that many forego
medical care or wait until a health condition makes it absolutely
necessary to seek treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we see so visibly is that the uninsured are working
families living on the edge _ a major illness or accident can push
them over the edge,'' said Diane Rowland, executive director of the
Kaiser Commission on Medicaid and the Uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau's figures are based on its annual population
survey of 50,000 American households.
</P>
<P>
   Among other findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lower-income Americans were less likely to have health
insurance. About 24 percent of households with annual incomes of
less than $25,000 had no health insurance. (The poverty line is
defined as an income of $17,029 for a family of four and $13,290
for a family of three). About 8 percent of households with incomes
of $75,000 or more were without coverage. But overall, coverage
rates increased for households with incomes of less than $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whites were much more likely than minorities to be covered by
health insurance. One of every three Hispanics, or 33.4 percent,
was without health insurance compared to 11 percent for
non-Hispanic whites. About 21 percent of African Americans and
Asian Americans were not covered.
</P>
<P>
   _ Workers at large companies were twice as likely to have health
insurance than those employed by small businesses. About 31 percent
of workers at firms with 25 or fewer employers had coverage while
at companies with 1,000 or more employees, 68 percent of workers
had health insurance. (The estimates do not account for employees
that may be covered by another family members job-based insurance
policy).
</P>
<P>
   _ The share of population without health insurance fell in 15
states _ Arizona, Arkansas, California, Connecticut, Iowa, Maine,
Massachusetts, Mississippi, Missouri, New Jersey, New York, North
Dakota, Rhode Island, Tennessee and Texas. Meanwhile, eight states
saw an increase in the proportion of uninsured: Hawaii, Illinois,
Louisiana, Nevada, New Mexico, Vermont, Washington and Wisconsin.
The results are based on statistical comparisons of two-year
averages from from each state for 1997-98 and 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes may be e-mailed at: chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
