<HEADLINE>
LYNCH CASHES IN SOME FIDELITY SHARES FOR $53 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fidelity Investments legend Peter Lynch has sold a
slice of his shares in the privately held mutual fund giant for $53
million, according to a regulatory filing.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch sold 60,566 shares _ more than 1 percent of the shares in
Fidelity's parent company, FMR Corp. _ between Dec. 1, 1998, and
Aug. 31, 2000, according to the filing. He received $9 million in
cash and a promissory note for $44 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that Lynch, 56, sold the stock as part of a
planned compensation arrangement, under which executives hold
Fidelity shares for a certain number of years and agree to sell
them back to the company on a specified date.
</P>
<P>
   They reap gains on the shares based on the growth of Fidelity's
value.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity shares cannot be held by outsiders. The company's
chairman, Edward ``Ned'' Johnson III, his daughter, Abigail, and
their families own 49 percent of the voting shares.
</P>
<P>
   Other top executives, including Lynch, also hold voting shares.
</P>
<P>
   Nonvoting shares are held by a broader group of managers.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch's shares were sold through the Peter S. Lynch Revocable
Trust, as first reported by InvestorForce.com. The sale was
revealed in a proxy statement for one of Fidelity's cash reserve
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity declined to comment on Lynch's sale. A spokeswoman said
there was no change in Lynch's role with the firm, where he is vice
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch became famous for running Fidelity's flagship Magellan
fund for 13 years, until May 1990, and for delivering huge returns
to shareholders. He has since been featured nationally in a
Fidelity advertising campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
