</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-SINGAPORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS AWAIT SINGAPORE AIRLINES' BIG PURCHASE OF BIGGEST PLANES 
</HEADLINE>
   By WAYNE ARNOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ The battle between Boeing and Airbus Industrie for
the future of large-scale jetliners could reach a decisive point on
Friday when Singapore Airlines, the profitable and prestigious
Asian carrier more famous for its flight attendants than its
financial muscle, announces a plan to buy new aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus and Boeing have been courting Singapore Airlines for
months in hopes of winning its endorsement of their rival visions
of a new superjumbo aircraft capable of carrying at least 500
passengers halfway around the world without refueling.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus is struggling to generate enough orders to justify
production of its 550-seat A3XX. Boeing has countered with a
stretched version of its familiar 747 jumbo. Singapore Airlines has
said it will announce its choice by the end of next month, but
industry executives were speculating that it would do so at a
Friday news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has remained silent on just what purchase it will
announce. Even the two rival manufacturers will not be told until
shortly before the announcement. Singapore Airlines is also in the
market for smaller midrange jets to replace 15 older Airbus
A310-300s it now uses across southern Asia. Whatever purchases the
carrier announces, ``it's going to be a big order,'' said Rick
Clements, a Singapore Airlines spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing 15 midrange aircraft could represent billions of
dollars in new orders and might indicate whether Singapore Airlines
is consolidating its fleet toward a single manufacturer to cut
costs, as are many other carriers.
</P>
<P>
   But a decision on the superjumbo would send a powerful signal
about the future of air travel.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is only Asia's seventh-largest airline, Singapore
Airlines is regarded as an industry bellwether. Profitable despite
offering a premium service and one of the industry's youngest
fleets, Singapore Airlines heralded its global ambitions last year
when it announced it would pay nearly $1 billion for 49 percent of
Virgin Atlantic, which is controlled by Richard Branson.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier is considering buying as many as a dozen superjumbo
aircraft, according to some people in the industry. A giant order
in and of itself, the carrier's choice could influence a debate
that has so far centered on whether airlines need larger planes to
fly farther, or smaller planes to fly more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's 747 has been the biggest jetliner for the last 30
years, and is still the only aircraft capable of carrying more than
400 passengers. Airbus hopes to end the jumbo's reign this year by
building the A3XX, which it envisions as an airborne cruise ship,
complete with a casino and gym.
</P>
<P>
   An order from Singapore Airlines would be crucial: Airbus needs
at least 40 orders by some estimates to justify the $11 billion
cost of producing its new behemoth. So far, it has orders for 22
A3XXs from Air France, Emirates Airlines and the International
Lease Finance Corp. Singapore Airlines' biggest competitor, Qantas
of Australia, is also considering a purchase of the aircraft, said
Sean Lee, regional communications director of Airbus in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing says the market for such huge airships is not big enough
to justify making them. It has opted for tweaking the 747 to
satisfy customers who need more than 500 seats per flight and
concentrating on its 380-seat 777's for those airlines that want to
fly to more destinations.
</P>
</TEXT>
