</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-KILLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GROUPS CALL ON CONGRESS TO APPROVE HATE CRIMES LAW FOR GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Hilary Shelton is CQ)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Religious leaders and civil rights advocates urged
Congress Thursday to pass a hate crimes bill following the shooting
rampage last week in a Roanoke, Va., gay bar by a gunman who
announced he was there to ``waste some faggots.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a park across the street from the White House, some
150 people called on House and Senate negotiators to approve
legislation that would extend special federal protections to gays
and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has the power to stand up and do something,'' said
the Rev. Neff Powell, bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of
Southwestern Virginia. ``How many more of our citizens must be
beaten and killed,'' he said, referring to the killing of Danny Lee
Overstreet in Roanoke.
</P>
<P>
   Overstreet, 43, was killed and six people were wounded last
Friday when a gunman opened fire in the bar.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Ronald Edward Gay, 54, told the police he was upset
that his last name made him the brunt of homosexual jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Candace Shultis, an avowedly gay minister at a
Washington church, said ``we are gathered here today to say that
enough is enough that hate is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Sapperstein, director of the Washington-based
Religious Action Center of Reform Judaism, said the legislation is
essential to stopping future hate crimes. It ``is not simply
feel-good legislation,'' he said. ``It will make a real difference
to Americans whose safety is continually threatened because of
their identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Shelton, director of the Washington branch of the NAACP,
said lawmakers should approve ``sane and sensible hate crimes laws
to prevent this from ever happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved the hate crimes legislation as an amendment
to the annual military spending bill. The House expressed support,
but in a non-binding resolution. House and Senate conferees are
hashing out the voluminous defense bill, which typically deals with
the numbers of weapons to be purchased and military research and
development.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles S. Robb, D-Va., who supports the measure and is a
member of the Armed Services Committee, said it was not certain
that the hate crimes measure would be approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not by any means a done deal,'' Robb told the crowd
across from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would expand the existing federal hate crimes
law to cover crimes motivated by sexual orientation, gender or
disability. The current law encompasses crimes in which the
victim's race, religion or national origin are the motivation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill would give states the latitude to ask the
federal government for help investigating and prosecuting hate
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who supports the legislation, has accused
Republican leaders in Congress of blocking the legislation for
political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know what the deal is here,'' Clinton said earlier this
week. ``The Republican majority does not want a bill that
explicitly provides hate crimes protections for gay Americans. And
I think they think it will split their base.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
eric &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
