<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5573 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ARCH-MARION0929-C     09-28 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARCH-MARION0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drugs, sex and scandal - Welcome to the Olympics
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ On a night where she won her second gold medal, her
disgraced husband was banished to the stands and her own reputation
came under question, Marion Jones was handed a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered Olympic star turned out to be nothing but a
warm-up act for the two women who shared the medal stand with her,
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   For that, Jones just may owe them her Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Pauline Davis-Thompson and Susanthika Jayasinghe _ who finished
second and third in the 200 meters _ did for Jones what the
ratings-conscious NBC apologists, her own public relations hacks,
Johnny Cochran and Nike could not.
</P>
<P>
   The pair drew the attention away from the American sprinter, so
much so that both Jones and the hundreds of international media who
had muscled into a post-race press gathering could only sit back
and get led on an unexpected, wild ride of race, sex, drugs and a
red sports bra.
</P>
<P>
   If you want Olympic scandal, the revelation of positive drug
tests by Jones' husband _ shotputter C.J. Hunter _ barely hold a
candle to the drug dilemma of Jayasinghe.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how she felt about winning a bronze medal for her native
Sri Lanka, the 24-year-old sprinter _ using the English she knew _
shocked the crowd:
</P>
<P>
   ``They stopped my training, I couldn't eat, couldn't sleep. They
gave me a terrible time. When I go back October 2 with my bronze
medal, they will be sad.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sri Lanka, she used to be known as ``The Dazzling Gazelle.''
After winning a silver medal in the 200 meters at the 1997 World
Championships in Athens, Greece, she returned home, where
newspapers proclaimed she had ``showered the motherland with glory
and honor.''
</P>
<P>
   That all changed when she tested positive for nandolene _ the
same steroid an International Olympic Committee official said
Hunter tested positive for four times this year _ and she was
condemned by the government and press. Although cleared of all
charges after a legal fight, she is still labeled a drug cheat by
many at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem started because the sports minister wanted sex
from me and I refused,'' Jayasinghe said once she stepped away from
the microphones. ``After that I was called for a drug test. But
they did not seal the sample. I asked them to sign a letter saying
it was not sealed. They kept refusing. I knew there would be
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thy did something to it. I am a clean girl, but it took me a
long time to prove it. They damaged my character . . . That's why I
moved to Los Angeles last year with no money, no sponsor.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she continues to run for Sri Lanka, she shrugged:
``What am I to do? You find me another country and I'll go.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jayasinghe had begun her tale on stage, Jones sat there
wide-eyed . . . and forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The American star only had to answer a few questions about her
husband, whose Olympics credential had been lifted by the United
States Olympic Committee. Instead of spending the night in the
athletes' area of Olympic Stadium _ as he had Saturday night when
his wife won the 100 meters just as easily as the 200 _ he sat in
the grandstands, a couple of rows from the track, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   When Jones made her victory lap _ after clocking a 21.84 to
Davis Thompson's 22.27 and Jayasinghe's 22.28 _ she stopped and
went into the seats, where she gave her husband two quick kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned about him later, she said: ``He has been a good
supporter through my whole quest for five. Just because this came
up, he's not going to hide in his apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested the revelations of Hunter's failed drug
tests had become an almost unmanageable burden, Jones disagreed:
</P>
<P>
   ``What went on the past couple of days could suddenly have
swayed me, but it didn't. I've been dreaming about this for years
and to let one event in my life _ as dramatic as it might be _ stop
me wouldn't be worth it. I think about all the days my mom drove 4
and 5 hours to take me to a track meet. I think of the days my
brother picked me to be on his hide-and-seek team. I wasn't going
to let one event ruin all that. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether her own reputation now was besmirched, she shook
her head: ``People who know me, who support me, who coach me know
that I am a clean athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis-Thompson then took over center stage and Jones didn't
argue. Instead of enduring a stressful grilling, she would be able
to relax on the eve of Friday's long jump competition, the one solo
event in which she seems vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being on guard, Jones soon was laughing as she
listened to the outspoken, 34-year old Bahamian, who is competing
in her fifth Olympics and had just won her first individual medal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she had thought about on the medal stand, Davis
Thompson first mentioned her deceased father and then, out of
nowhere, the sister of her high school coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when I was about 14, I was what you call heavy-busted and
had a big butt,'' she said. ``(The coach's sister) was sitting in
the stands at a meet in Jamaica when she heard other coaches say,
'That girl will never amount to anything as a runner because of her
chest.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day we drove all over Jamaica until she found me one
of those old- style sports bras. She got me a hideous color _ it
was red _ and I had to strap myself in it. She told me I had to
wear it day and night. I slept in it. I never ever took it off.''
</P>
<P>
   As she went into more candid detail, she soon had the whole room
laughing. ``Anyway,'' she said, 'it worked because here I am
today.''
</P>
<P>
   She told one story after another. On first meeting Cathy
Freeman, the Aboriginal Australian who has become her close friend,
she said: ``The first thing I asked her was, 'Girl, just what color
are you?'''
</P>
<P>
   As she talked of her pride in representing the Bahamas _ ``A
little country of just 275,000,'' _ she laid down the gauntlet to
Jones, whom she'll face again in the 400 meter relay: ``In 1996, we
won the Olympic silver medal. In 1999, we took the world
championships. We put three Bahaman girls in the 100 meter finals
here. We are still the underdog, but we love it. It will just make
our victory a little sweeter, Marion. We are going to give you one
hell of a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in private, Davis-Thompson offered the real challenge of
the Games:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disillusioned with my sport now. A lot of today's
athletes are taking drugs because they want fame and glory now.
They don't want to pay the price, don't want to persevere. It's for
the love of money and it has to be now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't realize they're hurting their own bodies and
killing our sport. It most definitely is endangering the Olympics.
We need to clean up our sport. I think one strike and you are out.
No second chances. You know what you are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when I heard about Ben Johnson (testing positive at the
1988 Olympics) I cried. With Merlene Ottey, I cried, too. But when
I heard about C.J., I didn't cry. I think it's because I'm finally
numb.
</P>
<P>
   ``In private athletes talk about who they think is cheating and
who is not. I've never confronted the ones I think are cheating,
but I've given them that look. It says, 'Shame. . . shame. . .
shame. It says I'm disgusted in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis-Thompson continued to hold court well into the night.
Although Jones was long gone, something she said earlier rang true.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about her Olympic experience, she said she had lay awake
many nights dreaming about what it would be like. But those dreams,
she said, couldn't compare to the reality.
</P>
<P>
   From the Opening Ceremonies to stepping out into the massive
sold-out stadium to going to seeing other competitions and meeting
the athletes, she said she'd been struck by one thing:
</P>
<P>
   ``All this seems so much bigger than one person.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night it was.
</P>
<P>
   And because of it, Marion Jones' Olympic Games may have been
saved.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
