<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TITANS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL HARMONY MESSAGE LOOMS LARGE IN `TITANS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sad fact about most Hollywood movies that pay lip service to
racial harmony these days is that, overall, they convey the exact
opposite message, telling us the races are very different indeed
and we have a great deal to fear from one another.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about Denzel Washington's new movie, ``Remember
the Titans,'' is that _ unlike so many of his films (``Malcolm X,''
``The Hurricane'') _ it really does communicate an optimistic sense
that race is irrelevant and we can all live happily ever after
together.
</P>
<P>
   It's essentially a remake of the milestone 1971 TV-movie,
``Brian's Song,'' which told the true story of the friendship that
developed between two professional football players _ a bigoted
white Southern and a Northern black _ when they were forced to room
together on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the same year as ``Brian's Song'' and also based on a
true story, the football team here is the first squad produced by a
newly integrated Virginia high school, commanded by a hard-as-nails
black coach (Washington) who got his job thanks to affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the film fast-forwards through the inevitable locker
room race-baiting scenes as the boys learn to trust one another and
become friends rather quickly. The bulk of the movie deals with
conflict between the now racially harmonious team and its larger
Southern community.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, ``Remember the Titans'' is pretty much your standard
``Rocky''-style competition movie, with some gripping gridiron
moments and some agreeable rise-to-the-occasion heroics but no real
surprises on its way to the big, fourth-quarter finish for the
state championship.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the film was made for super-producer Jerry
Bruckheimer's new low-budget unit, it has an over-produced quality
about it, and, I suspect, exaggerates the Jim Crow mentality of
Alexandria, Va., in 1971 _ more than 15 years after the birth of
the Civil Rights Movement.
</P>
<P>
   But the script is very good in convincingly portraying the way
the teammates learn to trust one another, overcome their prejudices
and even laugh at the absurdity of racism. And director Boaz Yakin
(``A Price Above Rubies'') keeps the sentimentality in check,
filling his scenes with a succession of small, deft touches that
bring the film to life.
</P>
<P>
   The adult stars are subordinated to the team ensemble, but Will
Patton is just right as the white coach who gets his consciousness
raised, and Washington is even better as a complex, ambitious,
never completely sympathetic character who is a big step away from
the one-note martyrs he's been playing lately.
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBER THE TITANS
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Boaz Yakin
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Gregory Allen Howard
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Denzel Washington, Will Patton, Wood Harris, Kip Pardue
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: Rated PG-13 for racism scenes
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5575 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-CAPEL0929-COX     09-28 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CAPEL0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'The all-or-nothing agony of John Capel'
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ John Capel, the man who quit Steve
Spurrier's Florida football team in April to work full time on
winning an Olympic gold medal, believed he had the perfect game
plan for Thursday night's wide-open 200-meter final.
</P>
<P>
   Then he fumbled the snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing to Tennessee up there on a missed field goal in
overtime in front of 100,000 people, that's about the only thing I
can compare it to,'' said Capel, who wasn't comfortable in the
starting blocks and was rocking back when the starter's gun
sounded.
</P>
<P>
   Lose to Tennessee, no matter how humiliating the experience, and
there's always a chance to get it right next September. Guess wrong
at the Olympics and there are four years of frustration to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Capel, who ran fastest in the semifinal but finished dead last
when the medals were on the line, rushed to see a replay of the
race. He wanted to see if there should have been a second chance,
to see if the recall starter blew it by failing to see Capel's
movement and failing to signal a false start in response.
</P>
<P>
   Thus convinced, the open-field sensation Spurrier calls John
John returned to a small gaggle of Florida-based reporters and
talked his way all the way into the next Olympics. Konstantinos
Kenteris of Greece may have shocked the world by winning the
200-meter gold medal in 20.09 seconds, but Capel made certain that
he too would be noticed. Here is where the track world gets a load
of Trash Talk 101, college football style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys that beat me in that race,'' said Capel, ``they
will never beat me again. Ever. What they ran tonight, I jog.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly, but Capel did have time to look back twice in
his semifinal to see if Ato Boldon or anybody else was coming up on
him. They weren't, and the preacher's kid from Brooksville, a small
town north and east of Tampa, coasted home in 20.10. That was
three-tenths faster than his second-round time and 39-hundredths
faster than his first round. Capel was building toward something
big, all right, perhaps as big as the 19.85 he ran to win the U.S.
Olympic Trials in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ran in one of the slowest 200 meters ever at the
Olympics,'' said Capel, ``and I lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell it like it is, Johnny. This was the slowest gold-medal time
since the U.S.-boycotted Moscow Olympics in 1980, and Capel did
waste a beautiful opportunity. Remember, Michael Johnson and
Maurice Greene weren't in this race. They both went down with
injuries during the Olympic Trials final that Capel won so handily
at Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I win every 200-meter race until the next Olympics, I
will not step on a football field,'' said Capel, who until this
moment had planned to re-enroll at Florida in January and return to
the Gators as a running back and kick returner in the fall of 2001.
``It's pitiful. I ran a stupid race. I will not step onto a
football field until I win the 2004 gold medal, and I promise you I
will win that 200 meters.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Wells, manager of Capel's professional track career,
raised an eyebrow at that one. He was a sprinter, too, long ago at
Arizona State. He understands the mentality, the challenge of
training month after month at the risk of a 20-second flameout.
Capel's anger, he said, was troublesome because it is so
uncharacteristic.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics have a way of doing that, coaxing tears and tirades
from the most stoic of athletes. It's the infrequency of it all,
the four-year gap between a runner in his prime and a dreamer lost
in a world where mulligans are always honored and justice always
prevails.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is a competitor,'' Wells said. ``He doesn't ever want to
lose, but to lose on a technical point, it's real tough for him. He
had a chance to definitely get the gold medal. If the recall
starter is doing his job properly, it should have been restarted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a sprinter. I've been caught like that, too. Boom,
everybody's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone to glory, and leaving you in a cloud of disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Capel, 21 and good to go with the Gators for a couple more
seasons, may rethink his decision on football once the adrenaline
drops back to a manageable level. What he said 10 minutes after
Thursday's race, however, that won't change. It's what he believes.
It's what he knows to be true, that the flags of Greece and Great
Britain and Trinidad and Tobago shouldn't be flying over an Olympic
sprint medal ceremony, and that the two representatives of the
U.S., Coby Miller and John Capel, shouldn't be the last two
stragglers to cross the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson's catty comment on the morning of the race, a
prediction to reporters that Capel wouldn't medal, may have been
based on something like this, something that comes from
inexperience in monumental meets like this.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's Capel's fault for not being ready to fly at the one
moment, perhaps in his entire lifetime, that the sky was the limit.
Can't blame that on anybody else. But there has to be some kind of
psychological safety net for one who falls so far, so fast. Lousy
officiating, that's the alibi that's most common to the players and
the fans of college football.
</P>
<P>
   Had Capel been back at Knoxville with the Gators a few weeks
back instead of running track in Sydney, he would have heard it
coming from the Tennessee throng, 110,000 strong and in complete
agreement that Florida beat their Vols on a bad call.
</P>
<P>
   That same number of passionate sports fans watched Thursday's
Olympic track meet with a more discerning eye and a broader
perspective. They had the effervescent Marion Jones to watch and a
long jump competition to figure out and Marla Runyan, a legally
blind 1,500-meter runner, to wish and hope around the track. And,
hey, if some mystery guy from Greece is running for the finish line
ahead of all the 200-meter favorites, that was something to cheer
about, too.
</P>
<P>
   They don't share the tunnel vision of the individual Olympian,
the all-or-nothing agony of John Capel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like crap,'' he said. ``I should have been on the medal
stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until they get instant replay at the Olympics. Not until a
sprinter can call timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
