<HEADER>
A5578 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     09-28 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOUND, BUT ANNOYING, IDEA
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As someone who is always looking for ways to annoy people
without actually being there, I was thrilled to read about a New
Zealand man who has recorded 64 minutes of lawnmower noise.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Reuters story, Geoff Marsland was looking for a
way to get back at inconsiderate neighbors who partied late into
the night, presumably without inviting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you do is you get up at 7 o'clock in the morning, put the
lawnmowing CD on and go out to a cafe,'' Marsland said.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners get to enjoy general lawnmower sounds along with the
occasional sound of the grass-catcher being emptied and stones
hitting the blades.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the guy who used to fire up his dragster at 2 o'clock
in the morning, I have had considerate neighbors, by which I mean
neighbors whose idea of ``partying'' is falling asleep in front of
the TV before South Park comes on. The only reason I would put the
lawnmowing CD on at 7 in the morning would be to fool my neighbors
into thinking I was actually cutting the grass. It might work once
or twice, but I'm betting they would eventually catch on,
especially if the grass grew high enough to obscure the house.
</P>
<P>
   But I think Marsland is on to something with this pre-recorded
noise business. His previous album, titled ``Urban Assault,''
featured motorcycle noise, car alarms and, most inspired of all, a
baby crying.
</P>
<P>
   I am betting that the rate of teen pregnancy _ and the rate of
pregnancy for all age groups, for that matter _ would go way down
if people were made to sit in a room and listen to a squalling
infant for 64 minutes. You wouldn't have to worry about another
Baby Boom threatening Social Security or taxing our elderly care
facilities; in fact, the only problem might be handling all the
requests for sterilizations.
</P>
<P>
   A pre-recorded CD would come in handy during those times when
you would rather be someplace else. Take Little League baseball
games, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   These games can be torturously slow to the point it can take
several days to complete a single inning. Instead of sitting there
for hours on the hard bleachers waiting for the pitcher to throw a
strike, why not play a CD while you go home for a much-needed nap?
</P>
<P>
   Pre-recorded comments could include: ``Good eye!,'' ``You'll get
'em next time,'' ``Way to wait for your pitch,'' ``Just play
catch'' and, of course, ``Keep your head in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   (Given the violent behavior of certain Little League parents
lately, you might want to record the sound of a police siren, just
in case.)
</P>
<P>
   Holiday gatherings can be uncomfortable for some, but not if a
CD player is taking your place. Pre-recorded comments could
include: ``So, I see you've put on weight,'' ``Did I tell you that
my daughter just graduated from medical school?,'' ``We used to
live in an old house like this,'' ``That's not meat, is it?,''
``Mind if I smoke a cigar?'' and, of course, ``You don't mind if we
stay over for a few days?''
</P>
<P>
   Given the vague, uninspiring content of their campaign speeches,
the two major presidential candidates may as well convey their
messages via CD. It would consist of a 64-minute repetition of the
words, ``Trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   And we voters could listen via CD, too. The only difference
would be that ours would consist of 64 minutes of snoring.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
