<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5579 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-VENUS0929-COX     09-28 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VENUS0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams duo take the Olympic doubles title
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Steffi Graf had a Golden Grand Slam year in 1988,
winning all four of tennis' major events plus an Olympic gold
medal, but she didn't get to share the experience with anyone.
Venus Williams, winner of Wimbledon and the U.S. Open earlier this
summer and singles champion of the Sydney Games, won the Olympic
doubles title with sister Serena Thursday afternoon and had so much
fun in the process that a new Grand slam agenda may be in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the world's best players will compete in the 2004
Athens Olympics, which may conflict with the U.S. Open, Venus said,
``Oh, yeah, I tend to think so. Most of us players hold the
Olympics high. Four years is a long ways to go, but I hope that
everyone will make the effort to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when Lindsay Davenport won the gold medal at
Atlanta, Venus was 16 and just beginning to test the WTA tour with
limited success. Serena, 14 at the time, wasn't quite ready to turn
pro. Today they are the hottest names in tennis, both individually
and as a pair. Thursday's 6-1, 6-1 crushing of the Dutch team of
Kristie Boogert and Miriam Oremans was the 22nd straight doubles
victory for the Williams sisters, Southern California girls who
live now in Palm Beach Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   They won five matches in Sydney and were pushed to a third set
only once, when Russia's Elena Likhovtseva and Anastasia Mysinka
won the opening set of a second-round match but got steamrolled
6-2, 6-3 thereafter. And all this happened in Venus' spare time.
</P>
<P>
   Her top priority was winning the singles gold, a six-match
mission that included three-set wins over Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario
and Monica Seles and concluded Wednesday with a 6-2, 6-4 win over
Russia's Elena Dementieva in the title match. Venus is the first
woman since American tennis legend Helen Wills Moody in 1924 to win
gold in singles and doubles at the same Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is very strong,'' Dementieva said. ``One year ago she just
had a very good serve and a few shots. Now she's doing
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And quickly, too. Venus and Serena won the Wimbledon doubles
gold-medal match in 49 minutes. It took Venus just six minutes more
to win the gold-medal singles match the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's five-set men's gold-medal singles match, which went
on before the Williamses, was won by Russia's Yevgeny Kafelnikov
over Germany's Tommy Haas in three hours and 34 minutes. That meant
IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch couldn't stay long enough to
present the medals, but the Williams sisters didn't need that to
thoroughly enjoy the ceremony and the joyous conclusion of a
harried summer schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very happy moment for me actually to watch Venus win,
and to have the same opportunity today, it was great,'' said
Serena, who experienced this situation in reverse at the 1999 U.S.
Open by winning the singles title and teaming with Venus to win the
doubles. ``We went out there prepared and we came out gold
medalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that preparation was an intense practice session on a
side court while the men's singles match dragged on inside the main
tennis stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to this match really serious,'' Venus said. ``We
practiced for an hour and 10 minutes to warm up, which is very
unusual for us. We practice all types of doubles drills. Then when
we went out there, we went for every point. We really, really
focused and it really paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Venus and Serena are not the first set of sisters
to represent the U.S. in Olympic tennis. Marion and Georgina Jones
both played in the 1900 Paris Games, with Marion winning the silver
medal in singles.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, U.S. players have swept every Olympic medal
available to women. Jennifer Capriati won the singles gold in 1992
and Davenport won in 1996. The team of Mary Joe Fernandez and Gigi
Fernandez, not related, won the doubles gold each year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
