<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-TIMEWARNER-440     09-28 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-TIMEWARNER-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS CALLED LIKELY TO BLOCK ONE TIME-WARNER DEAL, APPROVE
ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ European antitrust regulators plan to block
Time Warner's joint venture with the British music conglomerate EMI
Group but are much closer to approving Time Warner's $135 billion
merger with America Online, people close to the talks said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Monti, the European antitrust commissioner, issued
recommendations on both deals on Wednesday in a closed meeting with
antitrust regulators from individual European countries, these
people said.
</P>
<P>
   European officials said Thursday that neither Monti nor most of
the national competition regulators were satisfied with EMI's
proposed concessions, which include selling a few of its small
record labels as well as the logistical operations that physically
distribute music products around Europe.
</P>
<P>
   European officials object that a deal between EMI and Time
Warner would reduce the number of worldwide music distributors to
four from five, and they are pushing for divestitures that the
companies are loath to offer.
</P>
<P>
   But they are increasingly comfortable with Time Warner's
acquisition by America Online, especially if Time Warner abandons
the EMI venture. That, European officials say, would reduce
anxieties that America Online could use its new power in the music
business to cement its dominance in online services.
</P>
<P>
   One national regulator, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said the AOL merger could win approval fairly easily if Time Warner
either makes big new concessions on EMI or abandons the deal
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the problems with the EMI deal were resolved either way,
then that would remove the major impediment'' to approval of the
AOL merger, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   That view was echoed, at least implicitly, by German competition
regulators. Ulf Boege, head of Germany's cartel office and a member
of the advisory group that met on Wednesday with Monti, has
publicly warned that the EMI deal would severely restrict
competition in the music industry. By contrast, Boege has been
silent about the Time Warner merger with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's spokesman in New York, Edward Adler, broadly
acknowledged Thursday that the company's prospects for approval of
its deal with AOL looked good while those for the EMI deal were
more problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding America Online, Adler said that discussions with the
European Commission were ``nearing an end''' and that ``we are
confident they will be concluded successfully.'' But regarding EMI,
Adler said only that ``the process is continuing and is
constructive.'' The U.S. Federal Trade Commission is also reviewing
the EMI deal, but it has not issued an opinion yet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even though both Time Warner and America Online are U.S.
companies, the European Commission has the right to block their
proposed merger because the companies conduct more than 250 million
euros a year of business in European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
   If the European Commission does approve the AOL-Time Warner
combination, the deal still faces tough scrutiny from regulators at
two federal agencies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the FTC have hinted that they would move to block
the deal unless the companies agree to a broad range of rules
intended to foster competition, including opening Time Warner's
high-speed Internet cable lines to rival Internet service providers
on nondiscriminatory terms.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at the FTC have also been examining whether the proposed
merger would lead to AOL moving away from using high-speed
telephone lines, as one company memorandum suggested. America
Online executives have denied that would be part of their strategy,
but the FTC is exploring whether to impose conditions requiring
AOL, the world's largest Internet service provider, to continue to
make use of high-speed telephone lines as well as Time Warner's
cable network.
</P>
<P>
   At the Federal Communications Commission, officials announced
Thursday that they had begun a proceeding to determine whether to
issue industrywide rules to force all high-speed Internet companies
to open their lines to rival service providers on equal terms.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the commission's decision to invite comments
from the industry over the so-called open access rules had been
prompted by conflicting court opinions on the subject and did not
necessarily mean that new rules would be issued.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also said that final decisions about whether to
impose new rules would not be made by the FCC until sometime next
year. By then, the agency is likely to have several new
commissioners and possibly a different chairman, making it
impossible to predict whether the agency intends to take action.
</P>
<P>
   The officials emphasized that the decision to invite comments
about possible new rules had no effect on the review of the
proposed merger of America Online and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of those companies have said that they would
volunteer to keep their cable systems open to rivals, but that it
would be unfair for the government to impose such conditions on
them without also imposing them on other cable companies, like
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Under its rules, the European Commission must decide on the EMI
deal by Oct. 18 and on the America Online merger by Oct. 24. But
both the companies and their opponents have already submitted their
comments and proposed compromises, and European officials are
widely expected to reach a decision much sooner than the official
deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner and EMI executives said they had not given up hope
of winning approval for their deal, but the difficulties will be
hard to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Under the European Commission's rules, companies are supposed to
offer their proposed ``remedies'' no later than one month before
the deadline for a final decision. That deadline passed last week.
And while there is room for bargaining, companies are not supposed
to submit entirely new proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the companies do propose new compromises, both Time
Warner and EMI appear reluctant to give up major record labels in
order to win approval.
</P>
<P>
   It was precisely the union of Warner Music's strength in the
United States with EMI's base in Europe that made the joint venture
attractive to them.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry rivals of Time Warner, notably at Walt Disney Co.,
are still lobbying hard for Brussels to reject both the EMI and
America Online deals.
</P>
<P>
   One critic called AOL's proposed remedies a ``joke,'' saying
they provided no assurances of open access for rivals to its
network. Disney officials have argued that they want guarantees of
open access, without any discrimination in terms of pricing or
technical conditions, for independent suppliers of entertainment
and information as well as simply independent Internet service
providers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
