<HEADER>
A5581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-HOLYSITE-PROTESTS-BOS     09-28 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLYSITE-PROTESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI POLICE STRUGGLE TO CONTROL RIOTERS AT HOLY SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli riot police Thursday fired rubber bullets at
hundreds of Palestinian rock-throwers at a site holy to both
Muslims and Jews and squarely in the way of an Israeli-Palestinian
peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The clash immediately followed the visit of Israel's hard-line
opposition leader, Ariel Sharon, to the 30-acre shrine known to
Muslims as the Noble Sanctuary and to Jews as the Temple Mount.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leaders said the visit by Sharon, one of the Israeli
leaders most reviled in the Arab world and a vehement opponent of
any concessions on Jerusalem, was a clear provocation. Palestinians
shouted, ``Murderer, get out!'' as Sharon, backed by about 1,000
Israeli troops, passed the ancient stone ramparts of the compound
in Jerusalem's Old City.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing black Ray Ban sunglasses and surrounded by security
guards and soldiers, Sharon smiled as he greeted reporters outside
the compound, even as the first round of gunshots cracked in the
air and rioting ignited inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here with a message of peace. . . . I came here to the
holiest place for the Jewish people to see what happens here,''
Sharon said, explaining that the visit was intended to demonstrate
Israeli sovereignty over the site.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat called Sharon's visit ``very
dangerous'' and said that Arab and Islamic nations should ``move
very fast'' in protecting the shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Near the West Bank town of Ramallah, about 200 Palestinian
university students reacted to Sharon's visit by clashing with
Israeli troops and carrying a banner that read, ``Jerusalem is the
capital of Palestine. Sharon get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli supporters of the peace process characterized as a
dangerous stunt Sharon's expedition to what Jews call the Temple
Mount, where the Temples of Solomon and Herod once stood and which
today is the most sacred site in Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   They said it was aimed at increasing Sharon's visibility as
leader of the Likud Party at a time when the party's former leader,
deposed prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu, was cleared of
corruption charges and poised to regain party leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Likud has vowed to topple the fragile One Israel coalition
government of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and call for early
elections, largely in reaction to concessions Barak has made to
find a formula to share sovereignty over Jerusalem, which both
Israelis and Palestinians claim as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been in stalemate over the
issue of Jerusalem, and specifically over who will have sovereignty
of the site holy to both faiths. Currently, Muslim clerics have
autonomy in administering the site, and Israeli police assert
control over security.
</P>
<P>
   The rival claims to the site are often couched in apocalyptic
rhetoric by religious extremists, and the holy shrine has been the
site of deadly clashes. In 1996, about 80 people, most of them
Palestinians, were killed in riots after the Netanyahu government
opened an archeological tunnel under the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our holy place,'' Sharon said Thursday. ``There will
be problems if Jerusalem is divided as the prime minister wants.
Many problems will be caused here.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Sharon used the phrase, ``The Temple Mount is in
our hands,'' a reference to the legendary words of the late Israeli
army officer Motta Gur when Israeli paratroopers captured
Jerusalem's Old City in the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sharon even finished his appearance before the television
crews, the first Israeli soldier to be wounded in the violence was
rushed out on a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the brief clash, 12 Israeli riot police were
slightly wounded and two were seriously wounded. At least three
Palestinians were wounded. Four other Palestinians, including two
senior government officials, were beaten with police batons.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, who describes himself as ``not religious,'' wore a blue
knitted kippa, or Jewish prayer cap, Thursday when he visited the
Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   As Sharon visited, dozens of religious Jews wearing prayer
shawls surrounded him and cheered before the massive Herodian stone
wall that is all that remains of the Second Temple, destroyed by
the Romans in AD 70.
</P>
<P>
   But Chaim Meiselman, 21, an ultra Orthodox Yeshiva student,
expressed a view common among many religious Jews that it is
forbidden for Jews who are not ``ritually pure'' to enter the
Temple Mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even during the time of the Temple, only the high priests were
permitted inside the courtyard,'' explained Meiselman, as he
watched the TV cameras swarming around Sharon. ``He is not a
religious Jew. I don't know what kind of Jew he thinks he is. It is
good that he shows he has a feeling for how important this site is
for the Jewish people, but he has to remember that it is against
Jewish law to enter the compound.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
