<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-POSTCRD-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTCARD FROM THE GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   G'day from Australia &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Day 14 at the Olympics and journalists and volunteers alike are
starting to exhibit as much energy as the notoriously somnolent
koala. I read somewhere that koalas sleep as much as 20 hours a
day. That would be a good week's worth of rest for the Olympic
family.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell the torrid pace is starting to take its toll on
people. A friend of mine fell asleep in the boarding area of the
Sydney airport. He made his flight only because gate agents rang
his cellular phone and then followed the sound of the ringing to
his slumped person.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend sat down on a bench amid a couple hundred
thousand revelers at Sydney Olympic Park to read a newspaper and a
half-hour later woke himself up snoring.
</P>
<P>
   It's a marathon, but there's no pacing yourself. Not when the
world's best athletes are at your feet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catch ya' later, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karen Crouse
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
