<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5583 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-BEAUTIFUL-SPI &LR;      09-28 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BEAUTIFUL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIELD'S DEBUT NOT `BEAUTIFUL,' BUT HAS A NICE PERSONALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beauty pageants have been around for a long time and Hollywood
has done its best to expose their dark comedic side in such films
as ``Smile,'' ``Miss Firecracker'' and ``Drop Dead Gorgeous.''
</P>
<P>
   First-time director Sally Field takes a more intimate slant,
chronicling the journey of Mona Hibbard (Minnie Driver), an
ambitious, self-absorbed young woman who believes she'll find
acceptance and love by becoming a pageant queen. Instead, Mona
finds respect by facing up to the responsibility of parenting her
neglected, illegitimate daughter, Vanessa (Hallie Kate Eisenberg).
</P>
<P>
   For her entire life, Mona _ cast aside by her mother and stepdad
_ has wanted to be a beauty pageant winner and will stop at nothing
to achieve her goal. She's burned bridges in every county enroute
to the prestigious Miss American Miss contest and even fobbed
Vanessa off on her loyal best friend, Ruby (Joey Lauren Adams), to
raise because the pageant won't allow a candidate to be a mother.
She must be a perfect icon in order to be deemed ``beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful'' takes some risks because it presents a drastically
extreme character who is largely unlikable and asks us to go along
with her on her voyage. And Driver dives into the part, chewing up
the scenery along the way.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Beautiful'' doesn't have the complexity of a classic
anti-heroine film and the script by Jon Bernstein is often clunky
and excruciatingly unsubtle.
</P>
<P>
   Some subplots involving the angelic Ruby grind and sputter;
they're essentially creaky mechanisms designed to eliminate the
character for a block of screen time. Too, we're left wondering if
Mona isn't similarly stranded, shedding one archaic fantasy for
another by acknowledging the inevitable maternal instinct as well
as the desire to be a beauty queen.
</P>
<P>
   All these oversights are obvious by the time Mona realizes she's
not sure if she ``wants to be a role model for thousands of little
girls or just a role model for one little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful,'' for all Field's sturdy, no-nonsense direction and
Driver's brutality, suffers because of these lapses. It's a better
film when it keeps its heart in cold storage and shows what drives
a woman to compete against her peers. In the end, dark comedy
drives the film, but it's overwhelmed by a desire to be liked,
really liked.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTIFUL
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Sally Field
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Jon Bernstein
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Minnie Driver, Joey Lauren Adams, Hallie Kate Eisenberg,
Kathleen Turner
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 112 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: PG-13 for language
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
