<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIERCE-STABBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACK ON CELTICS STAR CAST IN CONTRASTING LIGHT AT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Was it a brutal attack on a helpless victim, set upon
by men who cut him with glass, pinned him to a pool table, and
knifed him repeatedly?
</P>
<P>
   Or was it instead a barroom brawl that went too far, with the
inevitable flying bottles, fists flailing in both directions,
followed by a botched investigation leading to the wrong suspect?
</P>
<P>
   As Boston Celtics forward Paul Pierce walked out of a hospital
Thursday, a prosecutor and a defense attorney offered starkly
different images of the stabbing that left Pierce with numerous
wounds moments after he showed up at a Theater District nightclub
in the early morning hours Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In describing a vicious, unprovoked attack on Pierce,
prosecutors offered no motive to explain what prompted the three
suspects to attack Pierce, a star player for the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happened inside the second-floor poolroom of the
Buzz Club/Europa, one thing seemed evident as two of the suspects
faced a judge in Boston Municipal Court: The Pierce matter is
unfolding unlike any ordinary assault case, heightened by Pierce's
celebrity, and clouded by old tensions between police and a rap
group often associated with Boston's gangland past.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the two men turned themselves in to police, Trevor
Watson and Tony Hurston turned their backs to news cameras in
Boston Municipal Court.
</P>
<P>
   Both Watson, 34, and Hurston, 31, pleaded not guilty to charges
of assault and battery with a dangerous weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Hurston, who was met by police at Logan Airport Wednesday night,
allegedly struck Pierce in the face with a bottle. Watson, who
surrendered at a downtown police station Wednesday night, is
charged with stabbing Pierce in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   A third man, William Ragland, also accused of taking part in the
stabbing, is still at large and wanted by police.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Watson nor Hurston are members of Made Men, a three-man
group with its own record label and a financial stake in a leading
national hip-hop magazine, The Source.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hurston found himself represented by Made Men's attorney,
John Swomley.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, Swomley has said that whatever the actions of
Made Men associates _ real or self-styled _ none of rap group's
three members was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he extended that innocence to include Hurston, a Made
Men associate and close friend of the group's frontman Raymond
``Raydog'' Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``He denies any involvement,'' Swomley said of Hurston, who has
no criminal record but had an outstanding warrant for speeding and
driving without a proper license.
</P>
<P>
   While Hurston was at the club that night, Swomley said, his
client got up and left as soon as he saw the commotion near the
pool table. He also said Hurston did not know Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Trading sharp words with the prosecutor in the case, Swomley
accused police of targeting the group without cause and compiling
photographs of anyone in their entourage.
</P>
<P>
   And he raised questions about how police used photo arrays to
identify his client as the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would bet dollars to Dunkin' Donuts that (police) took
anyone and everyone associated with Made Men and showed their
photographs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors sought $50,000 cash bail for Hurston, Swomley
said the amount did not fit the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this wasn't a Boston Celtic, (the bail) would be $5,000,
not $50,000,'' Swomley said.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Raymond Dougan set bail for both Watson and Hurston at
$15,000 cash.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing for a higher bail, Assistant District Attorney John
Pappas laid out a scenario of a vicious, unprovoked attack against
Pierce just moments after he stepped into the Buzz Club/Europa with
two friends in for an after-party.
</P>
<P>
   As Pierce stood with his back to the bar, facing two pool tables
and talking to a woman, Pappas said, Jurston approached Pierce,
hooked his arm, and struck him in the head, sending the player
falling to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Once Pierce was down, Pappas said, Hurston bashed him across the
face with a bottle, escalating an attack that later drew in Ragland
and Watson, the two accused stabbers.
</P>
<P>
   Grabbing Pierce around the neck from behind, Pappas said, Watson
and Ragland stabbed Pierce at least nine times in the back, face
and neck, with one cut going seven inches deep.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the stabbing, Watson was under supervisory
release from a 1995 conviction as a felon in possession of a
firearm. He will now face a judge in US District Court in Boston
for violating federal probation. He could return to federal prison
and serve up to two years before serving any time if convicted in
Pierce's stabbing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
