<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5589 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-28 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: NO APPEAL OVER TWINS
</P>
<P>
   The parents of 7-week-old twins joined at the pelvis have
decided not to appeal a Court of Appeal decision giving doctors
permission to separate the infants in an operation that will
sacrifice the life of one to save the other. The couple, from the
island of Gozo, near Malta, had argued that their Catholic faith
compelled them to let nature take its course although it meant the
probable death of both children. But their lawyer said that after
two court decisions against them, ``they feel they have done the
best they can for both daughters.''
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: UNITED AGAINST NEO-NAZIS
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the main political parties united in calls to combat
right-wing extremism, which has led to a wave of neo-Nazi violence
against foreigners. The Bundestag president, Wolfgang Thierse, said
such attacks were an assault on a democratic society's values, and
should not be regarded just as a problem in eastern Germany. A
government working group is considering the possibility of banning
the neo-Nazi National Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: 5 KURDS SLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Security forces reported killing five Kurdish rebels in fighting
in the southeast part of the country, bringing the death toll among
separatists to 10 in a week. Fighting between the Kurdistan
Workers' Party and the military has eased since last year when
Abdullah Ocalan, the jailed Kurdish leader, told his troops to put
down their weapons. But the military has pressed on in smaller
operations against Kurds in southeast Turkey and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: 5 CHARGED IN FERRY SINKING
</P>
<P>
   Charges of manslaughter have been brought against the captain
and four crew members of a ferry that rammed a marked reef near the
Aegean island of Paros on Tuesday, killing at least 66 people. The
charges follow accounts by survivors that the ferry was on
auto-pilot as the captain and senior crew members watched a soccer
match on television.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: PEDOPHILIA ARRESTS
</P>
<P>
   Eight people were arrested on charges of selling child
pornography on the Internet, while the police said they are
investigating 1,700 people suspected of buying sexually graphic and
violent videos featuring children. The pedophilia scare turned into
a media scandal after two channels of RAI, the state-controlled
network, showed clips from the videos on the evening news. After a
debate in Parliament on the issue, five RAI journalists said they
would quit, including two editors in chief.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: EMBARGO WEAKENED
</P>
<P>
   With flights from Western Europe, the Middle East and Russia
arriving almost daily in Baghdad, the Iraqi deputy prime minister,
Tariq Aziz, said decade-old sanctions against Iraq were collapsing.
``The embargo has become odious and all people call for its
removal,'' he said in Baghdad. Jordan, France and Russia have sent
planes to Iraq, saying there never really was an air embargo,
despite contrary assertions by Washington. Iceland and Yemen are
also planning flights. THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: DRUG CZAR'S JAILING UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   A court upheld the 71-year prison sentence on Jesus Gutierrez
Rebollo, a former head of the National Institute to Combat Drugs
who was convicted on drug and weapons charges. Rebollo was arrested
in 1997 after prosecutors found he had received gifts, payments and
real estate from leaders of one of Mexico's most ruthless drug
cartels. He also faces charges of abuse of authority.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA: COCA PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   President Hugo Banzer canceled a trip to Japan in order to deal
with rising protests by coca farmers, who are blocking roads across
the country. The protests, which have already caused estimated
losses of $100 million, are in support of demands that the military
remove troops from the country's principal area of coca
cultivation.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOROCCO: TALKS ON WESTERN SAHARA
</P>
<P>
   Morocco and the Polisario Front began direct peace talks in
Berlin over the disputed territory of Western Sahara. The main
sticking point is the carrying out of a long-delayed U.N. peace
plan that calls for a referendum to decide whether the former
Spanish colony should be incorporated into Morocco, which controls
most of the territory, or become independent, as called for by the
Polisario Front.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: MEAT BARRED
</P>
<P>
   Responding to an outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease among
livestock at two farms in the KwaZulu Natal Province, Botswana,
Namibia, Singapore and Mauritius have banned imports of South
African meat. Officials said they were destroying about 3,500
animals to stop the spread of the disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
