<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ADVISORS0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta hero to advise Gore on debate issues
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ Rescue hero Matt Moseley of the Atlanta Fire
Department is adding another skill to his resume: presidential
debate coach.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley, who carried a crane operator to safety last year in a
daring rescue, has been asked by Vice President Al Gore's campaign
to help Gore prepare for his upcoming debates with Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley, 31, is one of 12 ``ordinary Americans'' who Gore hopes
will give him advice about issues that probably will come up during
the debates, the first of which is scheduled for Tuesday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Moseley will fly to Sarasota, Fla., where Gore will
be holed up with his family and advisers preparing for the debates.
He'll meet with Gore on Sunday and Monday, and attend the Boston
debate as one of Gore's guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a surprise,'' Moseley said Thursday. ``It's
quite a step. You have to stretch your legs out for a step that
long, but hopefully I'll be able to offer up some advice which he
will be able to take into consideration, which I'm sure he will.
He's obviously wanting to listen to the regular people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Harvard-educated son of a Tennessee senator, has at
times struggled to portray himself as a sympathetic leader in touch
with average Americans. The campaign's selection of a dozen
citizens to supplement the paid advice Gore gets from a team of
Washington advisers is Gore's latest attempt to project a populist
image.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley struck up an acquaintance with Gore on April 12, 1999,
the day he dangled from a helicopter and rescued Ivers Sims from
atop a construction crane next to the burning Fulton Bag and Cotton
Mill in Atlanta's Cabbagetown. Gore, who watched the rescue on CNN,
called Moseley to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley met Gore a month and a half later when the vice
president visited Georgia. Last month, Moseley was one of several
law enforcement officers and firefighters recognized at the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Since he got the call from the Gore campaign, Moseley said he
has been asking around the firehouse _ Atlanta's Squad 4 _ for any
issues that he should bring up with the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare reform, Medicare, Medicaid and the budget deficit topped
the list, he said. In addition to that, Moseley said, he wants to
bring up gun control, an issue about which he has mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really that much in favor of it, but I'm not against
it, either,'' he said. ``I do think there needs to be some reform
in the laws, because I don't believe the ones on the books now are
that effective.'' On Thursday, Moseley was scrambling to find
colleagues who could trade work days with him so he could make the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not every day that you get asked by a presidential
candidate to give an opinion on issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
