<HEADER>
A5594 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MOB-FBI-BOS &LR;      09-28 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-FBI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW OFFICERS QUESTION FBI'S RELATIONS WITH MOBSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For decades, FBI and Justice Department officials
likened the Italian-America Mafia to a national cancer that had to
be eradicated at any cost. But for many in law enforcement, the
mind-numbing number of murders attributed Thursday to gangsters
James ``Whitey'' Bulger and Stephen Flemmi suggests that -- at
least in Boston -- the cure was worse than the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi and Bulger, who for years informed on their Mafia rivals
as part of the FBI's controversial, ultra-secret Top Echelon
informant program, were charged with committing 18 murders between
them and ordering three others, most while the two Winter Hill Gang
leaders were working as FBI informants. Some of their victims were
fellow informants in a position to incriminate them.
</P>
<P>
   As the two gangsters were helping the FBI make cases against
their Mafia competitors, prosecutors charge that they were killing
at a frightening pace. Even officials who have long defended the
use of hardened criminals as informants say the scope of these new
murder allegations shock the conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally unheard of,'' said Oliver ``Buck'' Revell, a
former FBI Executive Assistant Director and number two official at
the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald K. Stern called the indictment ``a deep stain
on the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were at least as bad and at least as violent as the
Mafia,'' Stern said. ``Certainly, based on what we now know, it was
a horrible mistake for these guys to be used as informants.''
</P>
<P>
   According to longtime prosecutors and defense attorneys who have
worked on organized crime cases, members of the Patriarca crime
family, New England's Mafia franchise, were charged with as many as
a dozen murders during the years that Bulger and Flemmi were
members of the FBI's Top Echelon program -- a half- dozen less than
Bulger and Flemmi are charged with committing.
</P>
<P>
   But some officials caution against a strict numerical comparison
because there has been a more complete accounting of the Winter
Hill Gang's crimes because two of its top associates, Kevin Weeks
and John Martorano, are cooperating with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the murders believed to have been committed by Patriarca
family members are still unsolved, making an accurate estimate
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many officials, including Stern, are now pronouncing
the two groups equally deadly, a remarkable admission, they say,
given the fact that the Mafia was targeted and villified while
Bulger and Flemmi were coddled and allegedly protected by their FBI
handlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cure was worse than the illness,'' said one former Boston
FBI agent who was against using Bulger and Flemmi as informants.
``Evidence is showing that, giving them a pass was not a good
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Both groups, court records show, were equally capable of
sadistic cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that Bulger and Flemmi tortured legendary
burglar Arthur ``Bucky'' Barrett by pulling his teeth one by one to
learn where he kept his loot, before killing him.
</P>
<P>
   Angelo ``Hole in the Head'' Patrizzi, meanwhile, was allegedly
hogtied by Patriarca family soldiers in such a manner that he
slowly strangled himself to death while locked in the trunk of a
car.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a difference, the former Boston agent said, it was
that the Mafia's murders were more predictable, more based on the
code of the underworld, than Bulger and Flemmi's.
</P>
<P>
   Patrizzi had vowed revenge for his brother's killing and was
perceived as a threat. Legendary hitman Joseph Barboza was killed
by Patriarca family captain Joseph ``J.R.'' Russo for working with
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger and Flemmi, on the other hand, appear to have been
``emboldened'' and ``enabled'' by their relationship with the FBI
and killed seemingly without regard to underworld taboos, the
former agent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They became almost serial murderers,'' the former agent said.
``That is the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Among their alleged victims were Flemmi's girlfriend, Debra
Davis, and Deborah Hussey, the daughter of Flemmi's longtime
companion.
</P>
<P>
   Some relatives of Bulger and Flemmi's alleged victims say they
believe the FBI bears equal responsibility for their deaths.
Several families have said they plan to file wrongful death claims
against the FBI in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys they took down in the North End are 10 times the
men these rats were,'' said Davis' brother, Victor. ``Taking down
the Italian mob in Boston was more important than my sister's
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
