<HEADER>
A5596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-28 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Rhymes With Tweak?
</P>
<P>
   Confirming rumors that first emerged online, the producers of
``Seussical'' said Thursday that the director and choreographer Rob
Marshall will be brought in to help doctor the highly anticipated
musical.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse two-sentence statement the producers said: ``Rob
Marshall will be joining the `Seussical' rehearsals to lend an
additional pair of eyes to the show. We're glad to have him with
us.'' Frank Galati will remain the director.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes after several weeks of heavy tinkering
with the show, inspired by Dr. Seuss, which retreated to New York
on Sunday after a bumpy monthlong tryout in Boston. In recent weeks
the show's costume designer has been replaced, blocking and lyrics
have been dropped and added, and the first Broadway preview was
pushed back three days, to Oct. 18. The producers have sought a
positive spin, saying no musical is born wart-free and pointing to
the show's early sales (some $4.5 million).
</P>
<P>
   News of Marshall's involvement first leaked through a theater
Web site, Broadway.com. Marshall, whose credits include the recent
revivals of ``Cabaret,'' ``She Loves Me'' and ``Damn Yankees,''
joins his sister on the creative team of ``Seussical''; Kathleen
Marshall is the show's choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   Young British Anguish
</P>
<P>
   Between plays like Jez Butterworth's ``Mojo'' and Mark
Ravenhill's ``Shopping and ...,'' New York stages in recent years
have been awash in the angst of young British playwrights. Now
comes news of two more imports from two of Britain's most touted _
and twisted _ young talents.
</P>
<P>
   Second things first. Beginning in late January audiences will
see the return of Martin McDonagh, who has already had three major
productions in New York, most famously ``The Beauty Queen of
Leenane,'' the tale of a wretched old woman and her impulsively
homicidal daughter. (A stove poker was involved.)
</P>
<P>
   That play, which won four Tony awards on Broadway, was the first
of three that McDonagh, a 30-year-old Londoner, set in the soggy _
and fictional _ Irish town of Leenane. In 1999 he returned to New
York with ``The Lonesome West,'' the trilogy's third segment, which
followed the lives of two brothers at war in a dank room. It fared
less well with critics but featured one of the greatest demolitions
of a stove in stage history. (A gun was involved.)
</P>
<P>
   Now the Roundabout Theater Company has announced it will produce
the second installment of the Leenane Trilogy: ``A Skull in
Connemara,'' which, like its predecessors, promises lots of dark
humor and a felony or two. (No weapons have been announced.) The
play had its U.S. debut at A Contemporary Theater in Seattle in
July. The New York production, at the Gramercy Theater, will
include much of Seattle's creative team, including the director
Gordon Edelstein.
</P>
<P>
   Several months before McDonagh's return, another British
playwright will make a posthumous debut under more somber
circumstances. She is Sarah Kane, the onetime enfant terrible of
the British theater whose short career ended last year when she
committed suicide in a London hospital. She was 28.
</P>
<P>
   Kane scandalized and electrified audiences in London in 1995
with her first play, ``Blasted,'' the story of a tabloid journalist
who lures a mentally retarded girl into his home. Kane followed
that work with several other provocative scripts, including ``4:48
Psychosis,'' her final play. Its subject? Despair.
</P>
<P>
   A small Greenwich Village theater, the Axis Company, will stage
the U.S. premiere of one of Kane's most highly praised plays,
``Crave'' (1997), the story of four voices warring for an
individual's soul. One of those voices may sound familiar to fans
of 1980s-era pop: Deborah Harry, the lead singer of Blondie, will
play one of Kane's troubled spirits. Performances are scheduled to
begin on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Aged, That Aquarius
</P>
<P>
   Three months after taking over as artistic director of Encores!,
the annual concert series at City Center, Jack Viertel is ready to
announce his productions for next spring. He's not sure of the
order or the directors, but considering the nature of one of his
choices, that's cool, man.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``Hair,'' the seminal 1968 anti-war musical, which ran
1,750 performances on Broadway and set the standard for nudity long
before ``The Full Monty.'' (No word if Encores! will re-create the
original, um, mise-en-scene.)
</P>
<P>
   Also on tap this season are two earlier gems, including ``A
Connecticut Yankee,'' the 1927 Rodgers and Hart tale (revised in
1943) about a bumbling bachelor who suddenly finds himself at play
in King Arthur's Court (or so he believes).
</P>
<P>
   And finally there's ``Bloomer Girl,'' with music by Harold Arlen
and lyrics by E.Y. Harburg, from 1944. The musical is the story of
an irrepressible suffragette, played by Celeste Holm in the
original. No word yet on who might fill the bloomers this time
around, but Holm herself is busy, and at City Center, no less. She
is to join Joanne Woodward, Edward Herrmann and Alec Baldwin in a
reading of ``Arsenic and Old Lace,'' the inaugural production of
the new Voices! series, on Nov. 11.
</P>
<P>
   `Slightly Ragged Writer'
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's is the final performance of ``Middle Finger,'' a
little-noticed production by a prolific young writer with some big
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   He is Han Ong, who won a MacArthur Foundation ``genius'' grant
worth $200,000 in 1997 at the ripe old age of 29. Ong, the author
of three dozen plays, says that while the award was a ``huge
shock,'' it has done little to enhance his name recognition. ``I
think I received a sum total of zero offers,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   His current effort, at the Blue Heron Arts Centerin Manhattan,
is produced by Ma-Yi, a company devoted to work about and by
Filipino-Americans, and tells the story of two young men suffering
through puberty.
</P>
<P>
   And while not much attention has been paid, Ong isn't
discouraged; his next play will be produced by Ma-Yi in the spring,
around the time that his first novel is published. ``I'm a prolific
but slightly ragged writer,'' he said. ``I can't imagine spending a
year on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
