<SLUG> BC-LIBERIANS-EXTENSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON EXTENDS LIBERIANS' STAY IN US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton Thursday authorized a one-year extension
that will allow Liberian refugees to stay in the US until next
October _ hours before they would've become illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-hour save brought a sigh of relief to Liberians, many
of whom had received letters notifying them that they would be
losing their jobs Friday. But many view it as a Band-Aid approach,
and the wounds will be reopened again next year at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are grateful to the president for giving us another
extention but, you know, people cannot spend their whole lifetime
living on extensions,'' said Torli Krua, president of the Liberian
Community Association of Massachusetts. ``Life is short.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 Liberians have been living in the US since
civil war broke out in their West African country Christmas eve,
1989. An estimated 4,000 of them live in New England. Though the
war ended in 1997, the country, and the region, remains unstable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has determined that voluntarily returning
Liberian refugees at this time could lead to further instability in
their country or in the region,'' said P.J. Crowley, a spokesman
for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley added that Clinton would welcome legislation that would
allow Liberians to remain as US residents. The only way to solve
the problem permanently would be for Congress to pass a law
allowing Liberians to adjust from their Deferred Enforced Departure
status.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island Senator Jack Reed has sponsored such a bill, which
he is hoping will pass before the end of the session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
Q2483 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-REZULIN-DEATHS-NNS &LR;      09-28 2659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REZULIN-DEATHS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DRUG LINKED TO 63 DEATHS WAS FAST-TRACKED DESPITE WARNINGS 
 &HT;     
</HEADLINE>
   
 &HT;     First of two articles  &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 27, 2000, is available as a
``separate buy.'' For information about purchasing the article,
contact DEBRA WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at
732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;     Art Advisory: With four photos, of Jose Francisco Cara (NNS1),
John Gueriguian (NNS2), Chuck Rand with photo (NNS3) and Chuck Rand
at gravesite (NNS4); for information about purchasing art call
202-383-7824 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     With a sidebar, `REZULIN-COMPANY' 
 &HT;     Optional trim to 2,350 words 
 &HT;     By DAVID WAHLBERG 
 &HT;     c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ Chuck Rand was sipping his morning coffee at
the only restaurant in his tiny Illinois hometown when the owner
said Rand's wife was on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck, I need you,'' is all Eleanor Rand managed to say.
</P>
<P>
   He rushed home to find his wife of 38 years sprawled on her
favorite reclining chair _ her eyes rolled back, vomit covering her
blouse.
</P>
<P>
   He took her to the hospital, where doctors said nearly half of
her liver looked like it had been through a shredder. It was April
1998, nine months after she started taking the drug Rezulin for her
diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Rand watched as doctors drained fluid from his wife's abdomen,
bloated by her dysfunctional liver. He helped her eat, bathe and
roll over in bed, until she got so big he couldn't roll her
anymore. He stayed by her side as her other organs _ kidneys,
heart, lungs _ also started failing. She died in May 1999 at age
58.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a sledgehammer hitting me upside the head,'' said
Rand, also 58, who has sued Parke-Davis, which developed Rezulin in
Ann Arbor. ``I wish they would have to see what it was like to go
through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Rand was one of at least 63 people nationwide whose
deaths have been linked to Rezulin, with some doctors saying the
figure could be 10 times higher. Many more patients had to undergo
liver transplants or be placed on waiting lists, possibly meaning
that thousands were injured.
</P>
<P>
   In March, three years after the drug went on the market and two
years after the first death was reported, Parke-Davis withdrew
Rezulin at the federal Food and Drug Administration's request.
About 1.9 million people had taken it, bringing in nearly $2
billion in sales. Typically it costs about $500 million to bring a
drug to market.
</P>
<P>
   Parke-Davis is a division of Warner-Lambert Co., which this year
merged with Pfizer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Ann Arbor News reviewed thousands of documents obtained
under the Freedom of Information Act and interviewed key figures
involved in Rezulin's approval. The newspaper's three-month
investigation found that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Rezulin was granted fast approval despite warnings about liver
dangers from some FDA staff members.
</P>
<P>
   _ The first FDA medical officer assigned to Rezulin was removed
from the case at Parke-Davis' request after he recommended that the
drug not be approved.
</P>
<P>
   _ An FDA doctors committee that recommended approval of Rezulin
was not told about all the data showing potential liver problems.
The company's presentation to the committee omitted key parts of
the data, but the company said it gave all the information to the
FDA staff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Parke-Davis and the FDA were reluctant to pull Rezulin from
the market even in the face of mounting evidence that it
contributed to deaths and liver problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ At least two members of the FDA doctors committee and a key
National Institutes of Health doctor were paid consultants of
Parke-Davis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Johns Hopkins University Hospital, one of the nation's
foremost medical centers, never placed Rezulin on its list of
approved drugs due to concerns about liver problems _ even though
the FDA had approved it.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors say the story of Rezulin, one of at least eight
drugs pulled off the market in the past three years, illustrates
broader issues of drug safety.
</P>
<P>
   While all drugs come with side effects, the FDA has no formula
for deciding if a drug is too risky to approve or whether it should
be pulled off the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many mistakes in such a short period of time raises the
question of whether the FDA has allowed the pharmaceutical industry
to gain too much influence,'' said Thomas Moore, a George
Washington University health policy analyst and long-time FDA
observer.
</P>
<P>
   It is buyer beware, said Dr. Jose Francisco Cara, a children's
diabetes specialist at Henry Ford Hospital in Detroit who sat on an
FDA panel that approved Rezulin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you use any drug, you really should be thinking about
the benefits and risks of the medication,'' Cara said. ``If you
don't, you're following the Pied Piper and ultimately getting
yourself into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer officials denied repeated interview requests, but have
said in the past that Rezulin helped hundreds of thousands of
people. Like all diabetes drugs, Rezulin presented risks as well as
benefits, the company said, adding that it gave appropriate
warnings of Rezulin's risks.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   As FDA-appointed doctors gathered around a Bethesda, Md.,
conference table in December 1996 to decide whether to approve
Rezulin, they talked about possible side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Enlargement of the heart. Weight gain. Cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Little was said about liver problems, except that a few research
patients had high liver enzyme levels, a warning sign of possible
liver failure. One of them had jaundice, a yellowing of the skin
that signals liver trouble, according to the meeting minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors, assembled as an FDA advisory committee, didn't
learn that 2 percent of 2,500 study patients had liver enzymes
three times higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't learn that 24 patients had to stop taking Rezulin
because of liver problems _ five of them with liver enzymes 30
times too high, two with jaundice.
</P>
<P>
   They also didn't learn that Rezulin's first FDA medical
reviewer, who was concerned about liver problems, was pulled off
the case after recommending that Rezulin not be approved.
</P>
<P>
   The committee meeting came less than five months after
Parke-Davis submitted its Rezulin application to the FDA. Most drug
reviews take at least a year. But Rezulin was on a ``fast track''
process of no more than six months, meant to bring cutting-edge
drugs to patients quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The ``fast track'' concept began in the mid-1990s following
pressure from Congress, which was responding to patients with AIDS
and other diseases. They argued that the FDA took too long to get
life-saving drugs to dying people.
</P>
<P>
   FDA's Dr. Alexander Fleming opened the December 1996 meeting by
explaining that Rezulin was slated for quick approval because it
offered a new approach to treating Type II diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The disease, affecting some 15 million U.S. adults, can cause
heart problems, kidney damage, blindness and death. Rezulin worked
by allowing the body to make better use of the insulin it has,
instead of trying (as other drugs do) to get the pancreas to
produce more insulin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should explain why we are here earlier than might
otherwise be the case,'' Fleming told the committee. ``Does this
mean that we lower the bar at the same time? Let's be clear about
this: absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   A team of Parke-Davis officials told the committee that Rezulin
had kept blood sugar levels under control during trials, so much so
that many patients were able to reduce or even stop daily insulin
injections. The lower blood sugar levels would result in fewer
complications from diabetes, Parke-Davis promised.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Randall Whitcomb, a Parke-Davis clinical research director,
was in charge of delivering bad news about Rezulin. Heart
enlargement and cancer were possible side effects. Fourteen
patients in one study had slightly elevated liver enzymes,
including one with jaundice. But the enzymes returned to normal
after the patients stopped taking the drug, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Research patients who took a sugar pill instead of Rezulin had
the same rate of liver problems as those taking the drug, Whitcomb
said, moving on to other topics.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, the FDA's staff member in charge of giving the
committee all salient information on Rezulin, didn't mention liver
enzymes in his presentation. He only briefly noted some liver
tumors in female lab mice.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming did say that the FDA generally likes to have more than
twice as much patient data as Parke-Davis had submitted before
approving a drug.
</P>
<P>
   After the committee voted unanimously to support Rezulin, FDA
staff followed suit, as it usually does, by approving the drug on
Jan. 29, 1997. It hit the market that March.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't the FDA doctors hear all the information about liver
problems at the December 1996 meeting?
</P>
<P>
   In a statement to The Ann Arbor News, Parke-Davis officials said
they notified FDA staff of all the data.
</P>
<P>
   One FDA staff member said the agency got the data but may not
have sorted it out completely before the meeting because it was
buried in stacks of documents. The company, he said, should have
highlighted the data.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my knowledge there is no basis for an assertion that
Parke-Davis withheld information,'' said the staff member, who was
closely involved in the case but who would speak only on condition
his name not be used. ``On the other hand, putting a few pieces of
paper (about the liver problems) in an application that has several
hundred volumes is only doing what is required.''
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen, the Ralph Nader consumer advocate group, filed a
petition with the FDA in July 1998 asking that Rezulin be taken off
the market. Last March, just before the drug was withdrawn, the
group requested criminal prosecution of Parke-Davis for covering up
liver data. According to Public Citizen, that spawned an FDA
investigation into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bradbard of the FDA said she couldn't confirm or deny such
an investigation. There has been no criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   At least one FDA official seemed to be aware of enough data to
warrant rejection of Rezulin.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Gueriguian was the first FDA medical officer assigned
to Rezulin. In 1996, he recommended against approving it, he said
in a recent interview. ``There was a very high probability for
severe liver toxicity,'' Gueriguian said.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed skepticism to Parke-Davis officials during a
September 1996 meeting. Shortly thereafter, Parke-Davis complained
to the FDA that Gueriguian had acted inappropriately during the
meeting by using offensive language.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA removed him from the case and any other dealings with
Parke-Davis. He retired in 1998 and now works as a drug industry
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept everything they say about my behavior,'' Gueriguian
said. ``But that has nothing to do with the fact that this drug is
toxic to the liver ... . There must be hundreds, more probably
thousands, who have died _ and tens of thousands severely
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Gueriguian would not discuss specifics of the liver data that
convinced him the drug wasn't safe. But when asked why he drew
attention to the data while other FDA staff apparently downplayed
it or didn't see it, he responded: ``I'm competent and honest.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Rezulin-related death was made public in October 1997.
By the early months of 1999, the death toll had reached 33, despite
three label changes suggesting more blood tests and meant to
prevent more liver injury. Members of Congress started asking tough
questions. Doctors started wondering if they should pull patients
off the drug.
</P>
<P>
   On March 26, 1999, the FDA took the unusual step of convening
the advisory committee a second time to discuss Rezulin. The
doctors met again in Bethesda.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission: to decide whether to expand Rezulin's use,
require more warnings or take the drug off the market.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Rezulin opponents spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   Moore told the committee that Rezulin's benefits paled before
its risks, especially since there were several other diabetes drugs
on the market. ``We are gambling with people's lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vincent Pearson, a Johns Hopkins University pharmacist, said
doctors at his hospital had never accepted Rezulin into their
approved list of drugs. ``We were all acutely aware of the liver
toxicity that was associated with the product,'' Pearson said.
</P>
<P>
   The most incriminating remarks came from someone within the FDA
itself, when epidemiologist David Graham recommended that Rezulin
be pulled from the market.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy presentation, he said that only 15 percent of
Rezulin patients had been properly monitored by their doctors with
blood tests, despite the repeated warnings. He said the reported
deaths and liver problems likely amounted to only about 10 percent
of what was actually occurring.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said one in 1,800 patients on Rezulin likely were
experiencing liver failure. Since about 1.9 million people
eventually took the drug, that translates to a prediction of about
1,000 liver failures.
</P>
<P>
   Parke-Davis officials responded with plenty of
counter-arguments. They said reports of jaundice had dropped
following the label changes. Factors other than Rezulin contributed
to some patients' liver damage; one man who developed jaundice had
consumed 12 beers daily for 20 years. Using a different formula
than Graham's, they said the rate of liver failure was only one in
45,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Parke-Davis representatives also presented a doctor survey
saying 82 percent of patients were properly monitored.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors voted 11-1 to keep Rezulin on the market, and the
FDA made a fourth label change, again requiring more frequent blood
tests.
</P>
<P>
   It would be another year before the FDA would request that
Parke-Davis withdraw the drug.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1999, less than two months after that vote, Eleanor Rand
died, ending her quiet life in the pastoral farmland of Latham,
Ill., a whistlestop of 400 people between Decatur and Springfield,
the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Rand developed diabetes in the mid-1970s. Her daily
insulin shots didn't control her blood sugar very well, and she
sometimes nearly slipped into diabetic comas.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, her doctor spoke highly of a new pill, Rezulin.
She started on it right away.
</P>
<P>
   The drug worked wonders for her blood sugar. But after several
months, she grew tired and couldn't walk from her recliner to the
kitchen without stopping to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Rand was concerned, so he took her in for a blood test to
check liver enzymes. Her levels were normal.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month later, she placed the terrified call to him at
the restaurant and had the vomiting episode that sent her to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   She was in such bad shape, doctors said she wouldn't survive a
liver transplant. About all they could do was drain fluid through
her groin to counteract the bloating. At first, the draining
procedures were scheduled every four months. But the fluid kept
building up. The procedures had to be repeated more frequently.
Finally, they were being done every week, with the last one coming
the day after Mother's Day and containing both clear fluid and
blood.
</P>
<P>
   She died a day later.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Rand still hears his wife's voice calling for help in the
middle of the night. Well over a year after her death, he still
begins many sentences with ``We.''
</P>
<P>
   At least once a month _ sometimes weekly _ he drives an hour to
Mattoon, to the cemetery where Eleanor Rand is buried. Five
generations of his family are there.
</P>
<P>
   When nobody is looking, he sits on her gravestone and weeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very emotional person,'' he said. ``If I have to go into
court and testify, I don't know if I'll be able to handle it. But
Parke-Davis has to know what they did to us.''
</P>
<P>
   JL END WAHLBERG
</P>
<P>
   (David Wahlberg is a staff writer for the Ann Arbor (Mich.)
News)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
