<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS &LR;      09-28 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH SET TO ROLL OUT ENERGY PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Capitalizing public anxiety over rising fuel prices, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush plans Friday to unveil an energy policy that calls
for new government policies to encourage oil exploration and
refining.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to outline steps to speed up construction of
refineries that process oil. The rise in gas prices, the Bush
campaign says, is partly attributable to the nation's oil
refineries running at virtually full throttle.
</P>
<P>
   He will deliver the speech in Saginaw, Mich., one of several
Midwestern states crucial to Republican hopes of retaking the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also will call for greater incentives to increase oil
exploration and drilling. And he will argue that because he and his
running mate, former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, have worked in
the oil business, they have the expertise necessary to pressure
oil-producing nations to boost output.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candidate has used fuel prices to
hammer Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said President Clinton's recent decision _ at Gore's
urging _ to release up to 30 million barrels from the strategic
petroleum reserve was a political move calculated to divert
attention from what he has called a faulty energy policy. The
reserve was created to provide oil in the event of an energy
emergency or military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   One energy policy historian questioned whether government
efforts to spur production would yield more oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good politics because the issue is worrying people,''
said Allen Matusow, a history professor at Rice University in
Houston. But ultimately ``the best policy is no policy. In time,
high prices will stimulate exploration if the government will stay
the heck out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Higher prices at the pump have coincided with higher poll
numbers for Bush. The Texas governor had trailed Gore since the
Democratic National Convention in mid-August, where Gore fine-tuned
a populist message, casting himself as the candidate of the people
and Bush as the candidate of the rich. But over the past two weeks
Bush has caught up with Gore and even taken a narrow lead in some
polls.
</P>
<P>
   At Voter.com Battleground 2000 poll released Thursday showed
Bush ahead of Gore 39 percent to 35 percent. The poll of 1,000
likely voters from Sept. 21 to Sept. 26 had a margin of error of
3.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   But a CNN/USA Today/Gallup tracking poll, released Thursday,
showed Bush and Gore both at 46 percent. The same poll on Wednesday
gave Bush a two-percentage-point advantage, 46-44 percent. That's
dead even in statistical terms.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Lindsey, Bush's senior economic adviser, told the
Washington Post that high oil prices represent the Bush campaign's
``best issue right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, the author of ``Earth in the Balance,'' intends to
pump the energy issue for what he thinks its worth Friday as the
walks the nature trails at the Audubon Naturalist Society in Chevy
Chase, Md., just outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's running mate, Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman, is
scheduled to speak on air pollution in Houston in an effort to link
Bush to polluters. Houston is now ranked as one of the nation's
most polluted cities.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's energy plan is built around tax breaks and incentives
that would reduce foreign-oil dependency through fuel-efficient
cars, buses and trucks; energy-saving manufacturing and power
plants; and turning production of pollution-preventing devices into
a growth industry.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail last week, Gore called Bush and Cheney the
``big oil dream ticket.'' His advisers are gambling that by
highlighting an energy policy focused on increased oil exploration
and refining, Bush will give Gore more populist ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail Thursday, Gore and Bush traded shots over
who has the best plan to guide the economy into the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vice president gets elected, the era of big government
being over is over,'' Bush said in Green Bay, Wis., another
Midwestern state crucial to his victory strategy on the electoral
map.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``is proposing the largest increase in federal spending in
35 years _ since the presidency of Lyndon Baines Johnson,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to undercut Gore's economic plan at a time when the
economy continues to be robust, Bush ticked off new federal
programs, hiring and regulations proposed by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this could amount to over $2 trillion in bigger government
in 10 years _ costing about $20,000 on average for every household
in America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At a speech at the Brookings Institution in Washington, Gore
reiterated his call to pay down the national debt in 12 years,
saying it would eliminate interest payments that represent the
government's third largest program behind Social Security and
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty days from now, prosperity itself will be on the
ballot,'' Gore said. He said Bush's $1.3 billion tax cut would
disproportionately benefit the wealthy, giving ``too much to too
few at the expense of too many.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
