<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REZULIN-COMPANY-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PFIZER STATES ITS CASE 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   
 &HT;     With `REZULIN-DEATHS,' first of two articles  &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 28, 2000, is available as a
``separate buy.'' For information about purchasing the article,
contact DEBRA WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at
732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;     Art Advisory: With four photos, of Jose Francisco Cara (NNS1),
John Gueriguian (NNS2), Chuck Rand with photo (NNS3) and Chuck Rand
at gravesite (NNS4); for information about purchasing art call
202-383-7824 
 &HT;    
 &HT;      c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ Officials at Pfizer Inc. denied repeated
requests to be interviewed for this series. But in response to
certified letters from The Ann Arbor News outlining the main
allegations raised in the stories, Pfizer issued a three-page
statement. Parke-Davis, as a division of Warner-Lambert, became
part of Pfizer when the latter two companies merged this year.
</P>
<P>
   The statement didn't directly respond to some of the
allegations, but it touched on several points.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Rezulin's review by FDA, Warner-Lambert disclosed the
risk of adverse liver events to the FDA, to the FDA Advisory
Committee, and to the medical community, based on the clinical
study research data before the drug was commercially marketed,''
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several months after marketing of the drug began,
Warner-Lambert received reports of severe adverse liver events,
including acute liver failure leading to transplant and death,
which had not occurred during the clinical testing of the drug.
These post-marketing adverse event reports were timely disclosed to
the FDA, and the Rezulin label was revised to reflect the new
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the statement:
</P>
<P>
   _ Monitoring: The company relied on drug label changes calling
for more blood test monitoring to keep Rezulin on the market
because that allowed physicians to detect an important warning
sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liver-function monitoring afforded this opportunity,
potentially enabling a physician to direct the patient to
discontinue Rezulin to stop the progression of, and reverse, an
incipient injury. ... Dozens of other FDA-approved drugs are also
labeled with recommendations that patients taking those therapies
have periodic liver-enzyme monitoring.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rezulin's withdrawal: Parke-Davis kept Rezulin on the market,
even after growing reports of deaths, because the FDA advisory
committee in March 1999 recommended that it stay on the market,
saying the benefits still outweighed the risks.
</P>
<P>
   But by March 21 of this year, two other similar drugs _ Avandia
and Actos _ had been approved, with fewer side effects. So Rezulin
was withdrawn. ``Just as Rezulin's introduction in January 1997
represented an advance over previously available therapies, it now
appeared that the newer drugs may have superseded Rezulin.''
</P>
<P>
   JL END
</P>
</TEXT>
