<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PILL-REACTION-BOS &LR;      09-28 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILL-REACTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPROVAL OF ABORTION PILL BRINGS MIXED REACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Security at abortion clinics and federal offices across the
nation was heightened Thursday in the wake of the US Food and Drug
Administration's approval of the abortion pill RU-486, a decision
that ends a tumultuous decade-long political struggle over the
drug.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's green light marks a milestone in
reproductive health, giving women, for the first time, a
widely-available abortion option that takes the procedure out of
the operating room and into the quiet of the doctor's office. The
drug is expected to be available to women within a month.
</P>
<P>
   RU-486, quite simply, makes abortion a more private affair, with
the expulsion of the embryo most likely occurring in a woman's
home. This transformation of what is certainly an emotional
procedure, was seized upon by both sides, with pro-abortion
advocates hailing it as the most significant abortion rights
triumph since Roe v. Wade, while anti-abortion activists decried
the pill as an easily-wielded tool of infanticide.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also drew into stark contrast the abortion
positions of the two candidates running for president, as Vice
President Al Gore quickly expressed his support for the FDA's
decision, while Texas Governor George W. Bush denounced it.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, FDA commissioner Dr. Jane E. Henney said, the
decision was removed from the political swirl and based on a
rigorous set of scientific and safety considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FDA's review and approval of this drug has adhered
strictly to our legal mandate and mission as a science-based public
health regulatory agency,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the RU-486's 12-year journey has been an intensely political
one, with numerous stops and starts, as US drug companies
unanimously refused to manufacture the controversial pill. Instead,
an international abortion rights group, the Population Council,
teamed with a small New York drug company, Danco Laboratories LLC,
to make the proposal that won the FDA over.
</P>
<P>
   RU-486 became available in France in 1988, and in much of
Western Europe, China and Israel since then, but did not stand a
chance on these shores until President Clinton lifted the
Reagan-Bush ban on importation of the drug from abroad. This paved
the way for clinical testing, which led to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   RU-486, also called mifepristone, can be used by women up to the
49th day of pregnancy, and involves three visits to a physician's
office over a two-week period. The drug can be prescribed by
obstetricians and gynecologists, as well as any physician with the
training to properly diagnose pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   The studies presented to the FDA showed RU-486 is about 95
percent effective in causing abortions. A small percentage of women
suffered side effects of bleeding, cramping, nausea and diarrhea.
One percent of the women tested suffered from serious bleeding that
required hospitalization. The FDA will require any doctor that
prescribes the drug to have ready access to a hospital surgery
room.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the official announcement broke, phone calls, faxes
and e-mails flew from both sides of the abortion divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting for this for a long time. This is a
historic moment. It's comparable to the arrival of birth control
pills 40 years ago,'' said Dianne Luby, president and CEO of
Planned Parenthood of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the political spectrum was Ted Furton, an
member of the National Catholic Bioethics Center in Boston, which
helps local clergy sort through ethical dilemmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hardening of the heart, further callousness toward the
unborn,'' he said. ``The fact that it can be done in the privacy of
one's home is a terrible thing. The home is the place of newborns,
the place of life, the place of family. This negates all those
values.''
</P>
<P>
   But while political activists debated the merits of the FDA's
decision, doctors across the country prepared for a significant
change in their practices. About 1 million women seek surgical
abortions annually but, with the availability of RU-486, women's
health experts expect this to drop, as women begin opting for the
less-intrusive option of the abortion pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely will suggest it to my patients,'' said Dr.
Fredric Frigoletto, chief of obstetrics at Massachusetts General
Hospital. ``From the point of view of patient privacy, it is a
distinct improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Women who request RU-486 will first have to sign a form
indicating they understand its risks. Then they will be given three
200 mg tablets. The drug blocks the secretion of the hormone
progesterone, which prepares the lining of the uterus for a
fertilized egg. It is possible this alone will cause an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   If not, at a second visit three days later, women will be
prescribed another already-available drug, misoprostol. It causes
contractions, eventually expelling the embryo within several days.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a third follow-up visit within nine days is required.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this requires a certain kind of patient, one who is able
to recognize pregnancy early, and one who can access the system,''
said Frigoletto.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that women without health insurance and non-English
speakers will be less likely to request, and successfully complete,
a RU-486 abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Frigoletto, and most pro-abortion activists interviewed, were
pleased with the FDA conditions placed on RU-486. During
negotiations between the FDA and Danco, the manufacturer, the
agency had considered only allowing abortion doctors in suburban or
urban areas to prescribe the pill, said people familiar with the
negotiations. Danco and others wanted RU-486 available outside of
abortion clinics, which are often the site of noisy, occasionally
violent, protests. Thursday, the FDA granted them this, allowing
not only abortion doctors, but hospital-based obstetricians and
gynecologists, as well as properly-training primary care doctors,
to prescribe RU-486.
</P>
<P>
   These doctors will purchase the drug directly from Danco. The
emergence of this somewhat secretive company was a key development
in RU-486's journey through the approval process. Though Clinton
opened the door for the drug's entry into the US, no pharmaceutical
company would touch the controversial pill. So the pill's champions
were unable to demonstrate to the FDA that they could reliably
produce the drug, a key component in getting the agency's seal of
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The French company that developed RU-486, Roussel-Uclaf, sold
the rights to the drug to the Population Council in 1995. But they
struggled to find a manufacturer. Finally, they helped found Danco,
which is run by a former executive from drug giant Merck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Clinical tests were initiated. Those, combined with numerous
studies from France, convinced the FDA, in 1996, to declare the
drug basically safe. But they wanted more detail on the
manufacturing and distribution process. This was dramatically
complicated by the political controversy surrounding RU-486, which
had come to be known as the ``morning after'' abortion pill.
</P>
<P>
   These complications intruded into negotiations right down to the
wire, said people familiar with them.
</P>
<P>
   Danco will market RU-486 as Mifeprex, and has spent over a
million dollars preparing a marketing strategy and training
programs for doctor, said the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We and our partners in the women's health community have
worked long and hard for this day,'' said Dr. Richard Hausknecht,
Danco's medical director. ``I am excited and very proud to be part
of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
