<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-EDUCATION-ELECTION-HN     09-28 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE AND BUSH RUN NECK AND NECK ON EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Education, as teachers say, may be the ticket to a
brighter future, and for Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore, it could be the key to the White House door.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are knocking themselves out trying to one-up the
other on the issue, which, along with health care and Social
Security, tops the list of voters' concerns in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats traditionally have had an advantage on education, but
Bush's five-year record of overhauling schools in Texas has helped
make him competitive with Gore on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush's proposals, which would dramatically boost
Washington's oversight of classroom academic quality as well inject
more federal aid into local school districts, represent a sharp
break with Republican orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Just four years ago Bob Dole, the GOP presidential candidate,
ran on a platform of abolishing the Department of Education and
leaving education totally in the hands of state and local
officials.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail last week, Bush said proudly that
disadvantaged minority students in Texas have closed the learning
gap with white students during his years as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Amy Wilkens, principal partner at the nonpartisan
Education Trust here, says, ``It takes some political courage to be
a Republican candidate and say `I'm concerned about minority kids.'
This isn't a backdoor agenda for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore would spend much more on education, and he
fundamentally differs with Bush on how best to improve public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the vice president would expand elementary and
secondary spending by $115 billion over 10 years. Bush would boost
such spending $47.6 billion over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years of the Clinton-Gore administration have produced an
``education recession'' during which the test-score gap between
white and minority youth has widened, Bush charges. Gore replies
that Bush's tax cuts would yield their own ``education recession,''
forcing Washington to cut education spending 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Gore and Bush seek the same destination: high
academic standards and student achievement plus standardized tests
to measure progress. But they are polar opposites on the
controversial idea of vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would create nationally the system of school requirements,
rewards and punishments that he champions in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He would require states to measure student achievement through
standardized tests, with sanctions for states and school districts
that don't measure up. The most prominent sanctions are vouchers,
which would enable parents of children in failing schools to seek
alternatives, including private religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, backed by teachers' unions, opposes vouchers. He contends
they could ultimately destroy public schools and that such federal
aid to religious schools would be unconstitutional. In Gore's plan,
failing schools would be shut down and reopened under new
principals and new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush, states would have to test children in every grade
from three through eight. Under Gore, states would be required to
administer a national test _ the National Assessment of Education
Progress _ to children in 4th, 8th and 12th grades. Both would make
federal education aid contingent on showing test-score progress.
</P>
<P>
   In a Bush administration, states would have to develop
curriculum standards in science, history, reading and math.
</P>
<P>
   Now, states must have standards only for reading and math.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also wants to guarantee high educational
standards and student progress through testing, but he dismisses
Bush's proposal by saying that much of it is already in place,
thanks to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has given states and school districts $460
million a year to put standards and testing in place, according to
Michael Cohen, an assistant secretary of education.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in campaign speeches Bush emphasizes local control of
schools and pledges to consolidate 60 federal education programs
into five.
</P>
<P>
   Some education experts see a contradiction in the Bush approach.
Jack Jennings, director of the nonpartisan Center for Education
Policy here, says, ``What Bush is proposing is a logical next step
to improve American schools, but he's not calling it what it is,''
that is, a big federal program.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's defenders say he is trying to balance Washington's role
with local control. Colorado's Republican governor, Bill Owens, a
longtime friend of Bush, told reporters recently, ``There have to
be some strings attached to the billions of dollars the federal
government spends. To have no strings attached would be fiscally
imprudent.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens of the Education Trust said that under Bush, Washington
would not dictate to states on how to run schools. According to
her, ``Bush (in essence) is saying, `This is the goal. I'm holding
you accountable. Achieve it however you want to.'''
</P>
<P>
   In other areas of education:
</P>
<P>
   _Gore would raise salaries, recruit a million new teachers over
10 years and test all of them to make sure they meet national
standards. Bush does not set a numerical goal for additional
teachers but would give states money to ensure teacher quality. He
would also boost funding to recruit former military personnel into
the teaching profession.
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not advocate teacher testing or pay raises. But he
would allow teachers to deduct out-of-pocket classroom expenditures
from their taxes. Both candidates would expand a federal
loan-forgiveness program to attract college science and math majors
to public school teaching.
</P>
<P>
   _Guided in part by his wife Laura, a former teacher and
librarian, Bush proposes a ``reading first'' program to ensure that
disadvantaged children can read by third grade.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says the government's Head Start program for pre-school
children does little to prepare children for school. He would shift
it from the Department of Health and Human Services to the
Department of Education to focus the program more on teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Gore does not specifically address reading, but his education
plan would make preschool available to all four-year-old children
and raise the number of spaces allotted to three-year-olds. On Head
Start, Gore says it began putting more emphasis on school
preparation two years ago when Congress re-authorized the program.
</P>
<P>
   _Through federal grants and interest-free loans, Gore would
repair and rebuild schools. Bush dismisses that idea, charging that
Gore is focused on ``bricks and mortars'' while he, Bush, is
concentrating on the quality of education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Both candidates stress school discipline, safety and moral
values. Both would require states to issue safety and discipline
report cards so that parents could judge the schools their children
attend.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
