<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday Sept. 29, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   ALLEN-MICROSOFT (Seattle) _ Paul Allen, the billionaire
co-founder of Microsoft Corp., will step down from the software
giant's board at its annual meeting on November 9, Microsoft said
in a federal filing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Richman. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TRUDEAU-OBIT (Undated) _ Former Canadian Prime Minister Pierre
Trudeau, a provocative political figure who fought separatism in
his country, died Thursday in his Montreal home at the age of 80.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TITANS (Undated) _ The best thing about Denzel Washington's
new movie, ``Remember the Titans,'' is that _ unlike so many of his
films (``Malcolm X,'' ``The Hurricane'') _ it really does
communicate an optimistic sense that race is irrelevant and we can
all live happily ever after together.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BEAUTIFUL (Undated) _ ``Beautiful,'' for all Sally Field's
sturdy, no-nonsense direction and Minnie Driver's brutality,
suffers from some problems. In the end, dark comedy drives the
film, but it's overwhelmed by a desire to be liked, really liked.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GIRLFIGHT (Undated) _ Its punch may stem from a feminine
perspective but don't underrate the visceral wallop packed by
``Girlfight,'' a first feature from Karyn Kusama. It teems with an
impatient, explosive energy that's so full of attitude that
Sundance Film Festival audiences lavished it with a best directing
honor and a shared Grand Jury Prize.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
