<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Sept. 29. The night supervisor for The New York
Times News Service is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: 888-346-9867 or
212-556-1927; e-mail: lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story: 3-column hed
</P>
<P>
   FDA-ABORTION-PILL (Undated) _ In what abortion-rights supporters
hailed as a major victory, the Food and Drug Administration
announced Thursday that it had approved the marketing of an
abortion-inducing pill, the first alternative to surgical abortion
approved in the United States. The pill will be available for sale
in about four weeks, its maker said. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-PILL-REACT (Washington) _ Abortion-rights supporters
celebrated a victory Thursday with the FDA's approval of the
abortion pill RU-486, but they acknowledged that it could be an
exceedingly fragile one. At the same time, abortion opponents
denounced the administration and the FDA for furthering ``a culture
of death'' and vowed to keep fighting, legislatively and
politically. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   Photo refer:
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-UNREST (Jerusalem) _ Tightly guarded by an Israeli
security cordon, Ariel Sharon, the right-wing Israeli opposition
leader, led a group of Israeli legislators onto the bitterly
contested Temple Mount today to assert Jewish claims there, setting
off a stone-throwing clash that left several Palestinians and more
than two dozen policemen injured. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTIONS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Yugoslavia's democratic
opposition thinks it has a president in Vojislav Kostunica, but it
also has a problem: how to get the incumbent, President Slobodan
Milosevic, out of power. The problem is more than technical:
Milosevic shows no signs of wanting to go. So Kostunica and the 18
party leaders who support him decided Thursday night to call a
rally for Friday in Belgrade's Square of the Republic, where they
will ask the people of Yugoslavia to perform ``any act of civil
disobedience they have at their disposal'' until Milosevic leaves
office, said Zarko Korac, a party leader. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICH-CAMPAIGN (Pontiac, Mich.) _ On Feb. 22, Gov. George W. Bush
lost the Michigan Republican primary to Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, thanks to a notably poor showing among independents,
moderates and women. Seven months later, in this same pivotal Great
Lakes state, he is again having trouble attracting independents,
moderates and women in his race against Vice President Al Gore. The
race is close here, with Gore very narrowly ahead. By R.W. Apple
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK-EURO (Copenhagen, Denmark) _ Denmark rejected the euro
on Thursday, undermining Europe's common currency and efforts to
intensify the European political integration championed by France
and Germany. In the first popular test for the euro, introduced
last year without such democratic consultation in 11 states of the
15-member European Union, Danes voted to preserve the krone. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   GORE-DEBATE (Washington) _ One of the fixtures of the 2000
campaign has been the candidates' efforts to connect themselves and
their policy proposals with everyday people. George W. Bush has his
tax families, who gladly tell how much money they will save under
his tax-cut proposal; Al Gore spends the night at the homes of
local teachers before spending the next day in their schools. But
the vice president is about to take the approach to another, much
higher, level. In the next day or so, he will transport a dozen
people from all corners of the country to Sarasota, Fla., to
participate in his debate preparation. They will then travel to
Boston to be in the audience. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
