<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
Q2485 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-REZULIN-WARNINGS-NNS &LR;      09-28 2206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REZULIN-WARNINGS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LABEL UPDATES ON DRUG FAILED TO PROTECT USERS 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   
 &HT;     Last of two articles  &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 28, 2000, is available as a
``separate buy.'' For information about purchasing the article,
contact DEBRA WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at
732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;     Art Advisory: With photo of diabetes patient Val Snyder (NNS5);
for information about purchasing art call 202-383-7824 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Optional trim to 1,900 words 
 &HT;     By DAVID WAHLBERG 
 &HT;     c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ When Parke-Davis and federal Food and Drug
Administration officials were faced with a growing number of deaths
linked to the diabetes drug Rezulin, they turned to the same
solution four times.
</P>
<P>
   Tweak the fine print on the drug's label by suggesting more
blood tests, they said, and liver injuries would be prevented. They
also sent letters to doctors recommending the tests.
</P>
<P>
   But physicians don't pay much attention to such warnings,
leaving patients largely responsible for themselves, some experts
say. At least 63 deaths were linked to Rezulin during its three
years on the market. The drug was developed by Parke-Davis of Ann
Arbor, which then was a division of Warner-Lambert and is now part
of Pfizer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will guarantee you that the number of patients who read the
labels is probably 0.01 percent,'' said Dr. Jose Francisco Cara, a
physician at Henry Ford Hospital in Detroit who was on the FDA
advisory committee that reviewed Rezulin. ``For doctors, it might
be 0.02 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors read the side effects on a drug's initial label, but
they're too busy to closely scrutinize follow-up warnings, said Dr.
Doug Greene, the former head of diabetes research at the University
of Michigan who sat on the FDA advisory committee before Rezulin
was approved.
</P>
<P>
   ```Dear Doctor' letters don't work,'' Greene said. ``It's always
more difficult to change physician behavior after a drug is
launched.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, Parke-Davis should have been more aggressive in
warning doctors and patients about liver problems, Greene said. The
company should have developed public service announcements or
bought ads to announce the warnings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Moore, a George Washington University health policy
analyst who closely observes the FDA, called the label changes the
most shocking aspect of the Rezulin case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was virtually a charade,'' Moore said. ``An essential
safety precaution was a total illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Pfizer and the former Parke-Davis denied repeated
interview requests for this story. But Pfizer issued a statement
saying Parke-Davis appropriately warned of Rezulin's risks.
</P>
<P>
   Blood tests were important because they were the only way for
doctors to detect high liver enzyme levels, a warning sign of
possible liver failure. Other clues include symptoms such as
nausea, stomach pain and jaundice, but they often appear too late
for the liver to be saved.
</P>
<P>
   When Rezulin was approved in January 1997, no blood tests were
required. In the nine months following the first patient death
report in October 1997, Parke-Davis and the FDA made three label
changes, each requiring more frequent blood tests. The labels were
lengthy, in fine print and full of complicated medical jargon.
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile death in May 1998 of a high school teacher from
East St. Louis, Ill., escalated the debate about labels and blood
tests. Audrey LaRue Jones, 55, didn't have diabetes. But she
enrolled in a diabetes prevention trial led by the National
Institutes of Health, taking Rezulin to help gather data that might
help diabetics like her son.
</P>
<P>
   Jones received frequent blood tests, as the FDA had ordered. But
her liver failed anyway, suggesting that monitoring couldn't
prevent all casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of Jones' death, the FDA in March 1999 took the
unusual step of convening its physician advisory committee a second
time to discuss Rezulin. The group had met in December 1996 to
approve the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Parke-Davis officials told the committee that 97 percent of
patients were getting liver enzyme blood tests before starting
Rezulin and 82 percent were receiving monthly blood tests while on
the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be expected to further ... decrease the incidence
of liver-related death and transplant,'' Dr. Mark Pierce of
Parke-Davis told the committee, according to minutes of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But David Graham, a top FDA epidemiologist, said only 15 percent
of patients were receiving the appropriate blood tests.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Graham said, the blood tests sometimes weren't
catching high liver enzymes early enough. He told of one patient
who tested normal just before traveling to Italy on vacation. After
becoming nauseous on the trip, the patient returned to the United
States. Five days later, his liver shut down. He had a liver
transplant but died _ less than 15 days after his normal readings.
</P>
<P>
   Another patient's blood test showed high liver enzymes, so her
doctor took her off Rezulin. But her enzymes continued to soar, and
she too had to get a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Saul Genuth, an FDA committee member, seemed to agree that
blood tests weren't working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think logistically there's no monitoring scheme that can be
dictated from above that will be carried out perfectly enough to
prevent liver deaths earlier,'' he said during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But Parke-Davis and the FDA responded by issuing a fourth label
change that increased blood tests once again.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Zimmerman, a diabetes specialist at the Mayo Clinic
and a past president of the American Diabetes Association, said in
an interview that the government should have taken more action
after that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should have been some thought at the FDA of requiring
monitoring, not just suggesting it,'' Zimmerman said. Pharmacists
could have been forced to ask patients for evidence of monthly
blood tests before refilling prescriptions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Bell, a diabetes doctor at the University of Alabama
at Birmingham, said the FDA should have withdrawn Rezulin at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there were several cases where monitoring didn't stop
it,'' Bell said. ``They had enough information then.''
</P>
<P>
   Another question surrounding Rezulin is whether it really was a
breakthrough drug. Its purported novelty is why Parke-Davis asked
for, and the FDA granted, a ``fast-track'' approval of six months,
less than half the usual time period.
</P>
<P>
   Rezulin was the first of a new group of diabetes drugs. Two
other drugs in the same class were approved in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   All diabetes medications aim to control blood sugar levels by
balancing the body's production of glucose (or sugar) and insulin,
which breaks down glucose. Because diabetics don't produce enough
insulin, their blood sugar often soars, which can damage vital
organs.
</P>
<P>
   Other drugs on the market prior to Rezulin's approval either
stimulate insulin production by the pancreas, decrease glucose
production by the liver or delay absorption of glucose into the
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Rezulin acted differently by encouraging fat and muscle cells to
better absorb glucose, therefore making the body use insulin more
efficiently. But the result was the same as the other drugs: It
reduced blood sugar levels.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeff Sanfield, a diabetes specialist at St. Joseph Mercy
Hospital in Ann Arbor who helped run a clinical trial of Rezulin,
said the drug didn't live up to its expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a major breakthrough,'' Sanfield said. ``The end
result was disappointing. The clinical effectiveness was modest.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, of Alabama, said Rezulin was no more effective than other
drugs. ``It wasn't as novel as Parke-Davis marketing would have
liked us to believe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But several other diabetes doctors, along with the American
Diabetes Association, told the FDA advisory committee in 1999 that
Rezulin allowed many diabetics to control blood sugar better than
before.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven Edelman said he successfully treated 500 diabetics
with Rezulin at the Veterans Affairs Medical Center in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't buy this drug back from these individuals because it
has helped them to achieve and maintain control over their diabetes
where previously it was not possible despite intensive efforts,''
Edelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the doctors who gave positive testimonials to the FDA
advisory committee were paid consultants for Parke-Davis, raising
conflict-of-interest questions that also apply to some FDA
committee members and National Institutes of Health officials.
</P>
<P>
   No rules ban doctors who speak before the FDA committee from
accepting money from drug companies. But it's clear that at least
one FDA committee member, who is not known to have received money,
was influenced more by the testimonials than by FDA staff who
wanted Rezulin pulled off the market.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1999 meeting, at which the committee voted to keep
Rezulin on pharmacy shelves, Dr. Robert Kreisberg, a committee
member from Birmingham, Ala., said: ``I'm going to rely very
heavily on valued colleagues who practice and take care of patients
with diabetes on a day-in and day-out basis. I think this
information is as valuable or more valuable than the theoretic
issues that have been brought up here (by FDA staff).''
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent Rezulin decision makers also had financial ties
to Parke-Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the FDA advisory committee met in 1999, the FDA
appointed two physicians to the panel who had served on the
education council of the National Diabetes Education Initiative,
which is partly funded by Parke-Davis.
</P>
<P>
   One of those doctors didn't attend the meeting. The other, who
voted to keep the drug on the market, was one of four people on the
12-member panel who received an FDA waiver allowing them to vote.
That means each had potential conflicts of interest that FDA
administrators deemed not serious enough to prohibit participation.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA will not say what the conflicts were, said spokeswoman
Laura Bradbard, citing privacy laws. One of the four doctors who
received a waiver was Henry Bone, a Detroit physician who chaired
the committee and also voted for Rezulin. He declined an interview
request.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the man who reigned over the NIH diabetes
prevention trial in which the East St. Louis teacher died also was
a paid consultant for Parke-Davis. Dr. Richard Eastman accepted
money for two years from the company and its affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   He and Dr. Jerrold Olefsy, who also helped oversee the NIH
trial, were investigated for potential conflicts of interest by the
inspector general's office of the federal Department of Health and
Human Services. But the investigators found no evidence of criminal
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   While some criticize the potential conflicts, others say it is
common for government pharmaceutical advisers to have ties to the
drug industry. Such people often hone and apply expertise by
working with drug companies on studies and seminars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you began to exclude everybody in a certain field who had
at any time been a consultant or a speaker for a pharmaceutical
company, you would lose the ability to find qualified members,''
said Greene, the former Michigan diabetes research director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experts are sought after by the agency and the companies.
It's a fact of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rezulin story illustrates the many struggles faced by the
FDA when weighing the risks and benefits of any drug, said Cara,
the Henry Ford doctor who was on the FDA advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make `guesstimates' of the pros and cons of the
medication long-term, when all we have is short-term data to base a
decision on. That's the balance the FDA is always trying to come to
grips with.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jules Hirsch, a retired professor at Rockefeller University
in New York who also sat on the FDA panel, said the short-term data
often don't reflect the eventual real-world experience of a drug.
Research patients are screened so they don't use other medications
that might cause cross reactions, for example, while everyday
patients may be popping over-the-counter pills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The few thousand people in well-controlled trials are not
necessarily a cross-section of the American public,'' Hirsch said.
So some side effects aren't discovered until after a drug is
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't the FDA require longer clinical trials, with more
patient data?
</P>
<P>
   It would be cost-prohibitive, Cara said. A recent 10-year NIH
diabetes trial cost $177 million, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can a drug company be responsible for a study like that?
We wouldn't have any drugs being submitted for approval.''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Cara said, he wouldn't have recommended fast-track
approval for Rezulin. ``When you do fast-track, there are always
going to be situations when you can make mistakes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't think the fast-track concept should be dropped,
because it's important to get real breakthrough drugs to high-risk
patients quickly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   PH END WAHLBERG
</P>
<P>
   (David Wahlberg is a staff writer for the Ann Arbor (Mich.)
News)
</P>
</TEXT>
