u f BC-WEBMD0929-COX     09-28 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMD to cut 1,100 `redundancy' jobs
 &HT;    By Andy Miller and Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of Atlanta-based WebMD soared 24 percent
Thursday after the company announced it will cut 1,100 jobs and
take a pretax charge of up to $45 million to streamline operations
after a flurry of acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts, representing about 20 percent of WebMD's work
force, will be completed by the end of 2001. WebMD, which is trying
to link doctors, patients and health insurers online, expects
annualized savings of about $250 million from its integration plan
by the fourth quarter of 2001. The company will also consolidate
offices and reduce marketing and promotional expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The job redundancies have resulted from WebMD's rapid
acquisition pace _ nine deals in 10 months. With mergers this month
involving Medical Manager, CareInsite and OnHealth, WebMD jumped to
6,000 employees from about 3,000, said co-Chief Executive Jeff
Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got tremendous redundancy as a result of our recent
acquisitions,'' said Arnold. ``We've got multiple sales forces,
multiple legal, finance and HR departments. The cuts are going to
be pretty much across the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said the company is ``realizing the synergies of moving
the companies together so we can get profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD lost $518 million, or $2.64 a share, during the three
months that ended June 30. Arnold said the company is on track to
become profitable in 2001, however, and that annual revenue will
approach $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD's corporate headquarters is in Atlanta, and the company
has 600 employees here. Arnold would not say how many of those jobs
will be eliminated. The company still plans to consolidate its five
Atlanta locations.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold shares the CEO title with Martin Wygod, who was chairman
of Medical Manager and CareInsite.
</P>
<P>
   The pretax charge of $35 million to $45 million will be taken in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's announcement of 100 job cuts is part of the 1,100
reduction. Laid-off workers will get severance packages and job
placement counseling, the company said. WebMD will also divest its
plastics and filtration technologies subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Shares rose $2.75 Thursday to $14 on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Sean Wieland of Prudential Securities linked the stock
jump to ``management fulfilling its commitment to the Street, to
cut costs and reduce redundancies.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD's medical management system, which handles day-to-day
transactions in physicians' offices, may soon provide a financial
breakthrough for the company, Wieland said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst James Kumpel of Raymond James said Wygod's presence at
WebMD ``has provided a sense of relief to investors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern previously was that it was a very unfocused
company, making announcements in any number of fields,'' Kumpel
said. ``Marty is introducing a regimen and a discipline and focus
that wasn't there before.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kumpel added: ``This doesn't necessarily mean that there's
smooth sailing ahead. The company is recognizing the realities of
the marketplace'' _ that hospitals and doctors don't react that
quickly to change.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
