u a BC-SCI-BREAST-CANCER-405     09-28 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAST-CANCER-405&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY BREAST CANCER PATIENTS HAVE BEEN UNDERTREATED, SAYS STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)   By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A third of American women who had lumpectomies or other
breast-conserving operations for early-stage breast cancer from
1990 to 1995 did not get other needed treatments, a new study says.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the women did not get radiation or
lymph-node biopsies, both called for by standard treatment
guidelines. Such incomplete treatment can double a patient's risk
that the cancer will come back, and it is of particular concern
because more and more women are having lumpectomy instead of
mastectomy, said Dr. Ann Butler Nattinger, a professor of medicine
at the Medical College of Wisconsin in Milwaukee and lead author of
the study, which is being published Friday in The Lancet.
</P>
<P>
   Nattinger's study, based on the records of nearly 145,000 women
treated from 1983 to 1995, did not explain why the recommended
procedures were sometimes skipped. Nattinger said she could only
guess the reasons, and suggested that some doctors might not know
the treatment guidelines, or might disagree with them or disregard
them in certain cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is that there is a real possibility of
undertreating at least some of these women,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The current recommendations for treating early-stage breast
cancer, issued by the National Institutes of Health in 1990, call
for either mastectomy or breast-conserving surgery like lumpectomy.
But neither procedure is sufficient by itself. Both operations are
supposed to include lymph node biopsies, to see if the cancer has
spread and the patient needs chemotherapy. Women who have
mastectomy usually do not need radiation, but lumpectomy, even for
tiny tumors, is supposed to be followed by radiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breast conserving surgery is a more complicated treatment,''
Nattinger said. ``But if you're going to do a more complicated
therapy, you've got to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the best way for patients to protect themselves was to
learn as much as possible about breast cancer, seek second opinions
and get their treatment from a team of doctors that included
specialists in radiation and chemotherapy as well as surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   Nattinger and her colleagues based their conclusions on medical
records of 144,759 women 30 and older from around the United States
who were treated for early breast cancer from 1983 to 1995. The
data were taken from a registry of cancer patients created by the
National Cancer Institute, and showed the patients' diagnoses and
treatments given.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In 1983, only about 15 percent of patients had breast-conserving
surgery, while the rest had mastectomy. By 1995, 50 percent had
breast-conserving procedures. The proportion who also had radiation
and lymph-node biopsy increased over time, but by 1995, 35 percent
still lacked one or both of the additional procedures.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers at the National Cancer Institute, which provided
the raw data for the study, questioned the findings and said that
their own analysis of the numbers, not yet published, indicated
that far fewer women were missing out on needed treatments and that
the percentage of women receiving them was actually increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rachel Ballard-Barbash, associate director of applied
research in the division of cancer control and population science
at the cancer institute, said, ``There have been substantial
improvements in appropriate therapy, but there is still room for
further improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballard-Barbash said she thought 35 percent might be too high
because women in the study were counted as having received
radiation only if they got it within three months of their surgery.
But some may have received it later, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nattinger and other researchers said that it was not realistic
to expect 100 percent adherence to any set of medical guidelines,
and that in some cases there might be legitimate reasons to chart a
different course. In particular, they said, for very elderly
patients, especially those with other illnesses, the odds of living
long enough to worry about a recurrence of breast cancer might not
be high enough to justify the pain and inconvenience of radiation
and lymph node biopsies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Patrick Borgen, a breast cancer surgeon at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York, who was not involved in
the research, called Nattinger's study a wake-up call. ``It's such
an important national snapshot,'' he said. ``This type of exercise,
taking a look at what we are actually doing as a nation, treating a
disease that's a huge health problem, is valuable and important. We
need to try to do it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Borgen said the study confirmed his personal observation that
many patients got incomplete treatment. He said he saw women
``every week, all the time,'' who had received incorrect therapy at
other hospitals. ``It's very common,'' he said, adding that many
sought second opinions after talking to other patients or joining
support groups and discovering they were the only one in the room
who had not been given radiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy is when they come in because they have a
recurrence, and you find out they had no radiation, no lymph node
dissection and therefore they didn't get chemotherapy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
