<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DEBATE-LEHRER-1001-CO     09-28 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-LEHRER-1001-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOW-KEYED JIM LEHRER TO MODERATE HIGH-POWERED PRESIDENTIAL
DEBATES
 &HT;    Advance for Sunday, Oct. 1
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the 1960s, Walter Cronkite was known as ``the
most trusted man in America'' _ a reputation rooted largely in the
evenhandedness he brought to the anchor desk at CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Jim Lehrer to moderate all three presidential
debates this year suggests that the low-keyed PBS news anchor may
have taken on that same role _ if not in all of America, then at
least in the political realm of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer, after all, has only a fraction of the TV audience
Cronkite once commanded when the Big Three networks were the Only
Three networks and held the attention of nearly all viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer'' reaches about 3.1 million
viewers each evening. Oprah Winfrey, by comparison, has an audience
of 22 million each afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And outside of politics and journalism, Lehrer is hardly known:
he hasn't shown up yet on a poll of most admired or most trusted
Americans as has, again, Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be the secret of Lehrer's success. And certainly it
is the reason behind his selection by the Commission on
Presidential Debates to moderate the three face-to-face meetings of
presidential rivals Al Gore and George Bush this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted someone who is not going to be competing with the
candidates from the point of star quality or trying to show how
smart they are vis a vis the candidates,'' Frank Farenkopf Jr., the
commission's co-chairman and a former chair of the Republican
National Committee, said in an interview. ``We wanted someone who
has the ability and the manner to go after the issues, but not in
such a way that they are trying to show up the candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   And that someone, in the judgment of the debate commission, is
Lehrer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch 'NewsHour' and there's no spin, no in-your-face and
some of the snideness you might get on other outlets,'' Paul Kirk,
the former Democratic National Committee chief who shares the
debate commission chairmanship with Farenkopf, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   He is, in fact, what New York University communications
professor Todd Gitlin calls ``the anti-Russert,'' a reference to
NBC ``Meet The Press'' host Tim Russert, a lawyer by training and
former political adviser who often turns the spotlight on himself
with his aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's debate, Lehrer has unprecedented authority to
direct the flow of the debate between Gore and Bush. He has sole
responsibility for the questions in the first two debates _ the
third debate will feature questions from voters as well Lehrer _
and he is free to follow up on any remarks by the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty awesome responsibility for one person,'' said
Kirk.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Lehrer is the new Walter Cronkite is open to debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others have to make that judgment,'' said Lester M. Crystal,
Lehrer's longtime executive producer at ``NewsHour.'' ``But
clearly, Jim Lehrer is highly trusted as a journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Lehrer is good, though hardly the god he is now heralded
as being,'' said Larry Sabato, a politics and media expert at the
University of Virginia. ``If he were, maybe more Americans would
watch the sparsely seen 'NewsHour'.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer is, in many ways, an anachronism in today's broadcast
journalism, which promotes attitude as much as accuracy, edginess
as much as evenhandedness. He avoids opinions and biases to the
extreme: he hasn't even voted since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   A one-time chain smoker, Lehrer gave up cigarettes after a heart
attack and bypass surgery in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at 66, he professes journalistic ideals that, by today's
standards, seem almost quaint: he refuses to use anonymous sources
or unattributed quotes; he carefully separates opinion and analysis
from straight news stories; and he assumes there is at least one
other side or version to every story.
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer declined all requests for interviews this past week,
devoting his extra time to preparing for the first presidential
debate, set for this Tuesday at the University of Massachusetts in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But his comments about his craft have been remarkably similar
over the years, underscoring his reputation as hard-working,
diligent, productive, questioning, sometimes droll, and perhaps
sober to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not an entertainer,'' he has declared on more than one
occasion. And after the commission announced his selection as
debate moderator last month, he told The Boston Globe: ``I really
don't have any politics. I love politics. I admire the people who
put themselves on the line. But I never take a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Five nights a week for the last 25 years, Lehrer has been
interviewing politicians and world leaders in Washington, first on
``The Robert McNeil Report,'' then ``The MacNeil-Lehrer Hour'' and,
since McNeil's retirement in 1995, ``The NewsHour with Jim
Lehrer.''
</P>
<P>
   His questions are often considered ``soft'' _ that is, polite,
by news show standards. But the questions are also open-ended,
focused and short. ``The longer the question, the easier it is to
evade,'' Lehrer reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer was born in Wichita, Kan., and spent much of his
childhood in the state. His family moved to San Antonio, Texas,
when he was a teenager. His father worked for a bus company, and
today, Lehrer's office in suburban Virginia is decorated with bus
company logos and terminal signs.
</P>
<P>
   After the University of Missouri and a stint in the Marines, he
landed a job writing obituaries at The Dallas Morning News.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be like Ernest Hemingway,'' he told the Pittsburgh
Post-Gazette last spring. ``I wanted to write stories, and
Hemingway said if you want to do that, got get a job as a
newspaperman.''
</P>
<P>
   But like Hemingway, Lehrer did not settle for the who, what,
when, where, how and why of daily journalism. He also wrote
fiction. And in 1970, while working as city editor for the
now-defunct Dallas Times Herald, he wrote a novel, ``Viva Max!'',
which became a Peter Ustinov movie.
</P>
<P>
   He quit his job at the paper to write fiction full time, but
then took part-time job at the Dallas public TV station. Two years
later, he and his wife, novelist Kate Lehrer, and their three
daughters moved to Washington just in time for the Watergate
scandal, which led to the rewriting of many of the rules of
journalism, most notably the use of unidentified sources.
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer continues to write fiction. He published his eleventh
novel this year, ``The Special Prisoner,'' a yarn about Japanese
atrocities during World War II that poses the question of whether
homicide is ever justifiable.
</P>
<P>
   His 1995 novel, ``The Last Debate,'' is about a conspiracy in
which journalists use unsubstantiated charges of child and spousal
abuse to destroy a presidential candidate during a live TV debate.
It grew out of Lehrer's experience moderating one of the three
presidential debates in 1992 and one in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer also moderated the two debates between President Clinton
and former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, the Republican
challenger, in 1996. And despite strict rules governing the
debates, he succeeded in gently breaking some in order to make the
debate more free flowing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at one point, Lehrer was temporarily stymied by the
no follow-up rules Clinton and Dole had set. So, Lehrer asked a
follow-up disguised as a new question: ``Mr. President, the senator
mentioned drugs. He suggested that you are _ you bear some
responsibility for the rise in drug use of teen-agers in the United
States. Is he right?''
</P>
<P>
   As the sole question in this year's debates, Lehrer has great
latitude to direct the flow and content of the events. But it's
unlikely he will exploit his powerful role to make himself the
center of attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more important to Jim Lehrer than to get the
information from the candidates and to the audience,'' said
Crystal. ``And there's nothing less important to Jim Lehrer than to
show off Jim Lehrer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard may be e-mailed at: ScottS(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
