<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5617 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ROSH-LIEBERMAN-BOS &LR;      09-28 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSH-LIEBERMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN A HOT TOPIC AS ROSH HASHANA BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rabbi Daniel Judson will be eating his words this weekend, and
perhaps he should be eating his yarmulke.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, Judson stood before his congregation and
scoffed at the leaked list of potential Democratic vice
presidential candidates, predicting that Vice President Al Gore
could not choose Senator Joseph I. Lieberman to be his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said there would be no way they would nominate Lieberman,
and I actually said I would eat my `kippah' if they did,'' Judson
said, using the Hebrew word for skullcap. ``Almost every member of
my congregation agreed with me.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, as Jews gather to celebrate Rosh Hashana, Judson
will again be before his congregation in Canton, Mass., but this
time he'll be seeking to draw moral and historical lessons from
Lieberman's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Judson, like rabbis in synagogues across the nation, will be
addressing the same fundamental questions: What does Lieberman's
nomination and his public and proud proclamation of his faith mean
for American Jews?
</P>
<P>
   Not since Egypt and Syria invaded Israel on Yom Kippur of 1973
has there been such broad consensus about what to talk about in
synagogues during the High Holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost impossible for a modern rabbi not to address this
during the High Holiday season, because it has become clear that it
is an epochal event in American Jewish history,'' said Rabbi Noam
E. Marans of Temple Israel in Ridgewood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Judson, rabbi at Temple Beth David in Canton, will suggest that
the positive reaction to Lieberman's nomination reflects a decline
in anti-Semitism in the United States, while the apparent
acceptance of his religiosity offers an opportunity for American
Jews to rethink their views on public expressions of Jewishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``My question is, `How come the Jews thought there was no way
they were going to do it, but the Democrats did it?' '' Judson
said. ``We have overestimated the level of anti-Semitism in this
country, and we need to re-evaluate our sense of where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Many rabbis will be focusing on Lieberman's religiosity, which
runs counter to a secular trend in American Jewish life.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one at this level of possible power has been as Jewish as
this Jew,'' Marans said. ``Does his role-modelling break the
stereotype that somehow Jews who are completely immersed in their
Judaism are at a disadvantage in climbing the secular mountain?''
</P>
<P>
   Most rabbis will be combining those themes, suggesting that the
Lieberman nomination is a chance to reflect on the attitudes of
America generally, and American Jews in particular, toward Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our wider society is expressing more than a passing curiosity
in traditions that an un-identified Jew had long since dismissed as
antiquated and irrelevant,'' said Rabbi William Hamilton of
Congregation Kehillath Israel in Brookline, Mass. ``All of a sudden
America seems to respect the Jewish way, so what's an un-identified
Jew to do?''
</P>
<P>
   One of Lieberman's own rabbis, Barry Freundel of Kesher Israel
in Washington, will also choose this theme, saying ``he (Lieberman)
challenges those who assume Jews can't really be comfortable in
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The High Holidays _ Rosh Hashana, which marks the start of a new
year in the Jewish calendar, and Yom Kippur, which is the day on
which Jews atone for sins against one another and against God _ are
the most stressful points of a rabbi's year, because many more
people show up at synagogue to mark those holidays than on any
other occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like Christians come for Christmas and maybe for Easter,
Jews tend to come for the High Holidays,'' said Rabbi Ruth Alpers,
a professor of practical rabbinics at Hebrew Union College, the
seminary for Reform rabbis. ``In many congregations, High Holidays
are the one chance rabbis have to reach the most number of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbis often agonize about High Holiday sermon topics, with some
attending workshops for ideas, or waiting until the last minute to
choose from a number of alternative speeches they have prepared.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, ``Gore took care of all of us rabbis by
selecting Senator Lieberman,'' said Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   In numerous interviews about their sermons, rabbis repeatedly
compared Lieberman to baseball players Hank Greenberg and Sandy
Koufax, both of whom drew attention for their refusal to play ball
on Jewish holidays. Lieberman has refused to to campaign on the
Jewish sabbath, and he is taking time away from his campaign this
weekend to celebrate Rosh Hashana at his synagogue in New Haven and
next weekend to mark Yom Kippur, most likely at his synagogue in
the Georgetown section of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But rabbis said the nomination of Lieberman is the first truly
American event to be of such broad interest in the diverse Jewish
community, which previously has coalesced largely around issues
involving Israel. (Many rabbis this year will also give sermons
that touch on the Middle East peace talks, and some will touch on
topics from ``Survivor,'' a hit television show, to ``Jew vs.
Jew,'' a new book on Jewish factionalism in the United States.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all rabbis will be talking about Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, home of Republican presidential nominee George W.
Bush, Rabbi Steven Folberg of Congregation Beth Israel and Rabbi
Martin J. Pasternak of Congregation Agudas Achim will both be
talking about other subjects. Bush has close ties to the Jewish
community in Austin, where some leading Republicans are Jewish and
where Bush has been known to show up at a Passover seder on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reason is I'm not really sure that there's an
ultimate religious message in Lieberman's candidacy that is weighty
enough for these days in which people are hungering for a spiritual
message and at a time when I have the largest audience of the
year,'' Pasternak said. ``But my second reason is that I'm in
Austin, Texas, and I've got Republicans out there (in the
congregation). I don't want to endanger my status with them as a
rabbi, so that they might feel uncomfortable with me or not come to
me because politics is such an emotional issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
