<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COMPUTERS-NORRIS-COLU     09-28 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE DOUR EARNINGS REPORTS MAY SIGNAL HIGH TECH'S PARTY IS FINALLY
OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computers have driven this economy to the longest expansion
ever. Computer stocks have racked up some of the biggest gains of
the bull market.
</P>
<P>
   But all good things must end someday, and the signs are growing
that the end may be here. September has been a horrid month for
computer-stock investors. If the growth of the computer industry is
slowing, as seems to be happening, that has significant
implications for corporate profits and for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of alarm had not spread very far on Wall Street before
Thursday night, although bad news from Apple may change that.
Intel, the dominant maker of personal computer chips, is down 41
percent this month since its disclosure that revenue is running
well below forecast. But much of the commentary on Intel focused
not on the implications for the industry, but on explaining away
the price drop. Some said that the market would have reacted more
calmly if Intel had quietly prepared analysts, but that it was
prevented from doing so by a new regulation of the Securities and
Exchange Commission barring selective disclosure _ a rule not yet
in effect, as it happens.
</P>
<P>
   Such analysis insults investors and analysts, who are presumed
to be able to handle bad news only if it is whispered rather than
announced. And it overlooks the fact that many computer-related
stocks have declined. Apple, for example, was down 12 percent this
month before its bad news came out _ sending it down 45 percent
more in after-hours trading. Microsoft rallied briefly after the
Supreme Court decided not to hear the company's antitrust appeal
immediately, but the shares soon fell to their lowest level since
November 1998. (Microsoft, which went public in 1986, had never
before traded at a 22-month low.)
</P>
<P>
   Greg Jensen of Bridgewater Associates, a money management firm,
notes that movements in computer-stock prices have been a leading
indicator of trends in computer-equipment orders. ``These stocks
are now pointing to a big slowdown in computer investment,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   If that indication is accurate _ and the government's durable
goods figures make it clear that growth in computer orders is
slowing sharply _ then slower economic growth is likely. Much of
the growth in recent years has reflected the surge of investment in
computer equipment.
</P>
<P>
   That investment has been even more important to corporate
profits because money spent on computers counts as revenue for the
seller _ thus raising profits _ but is treated as an investment by
the buyer, thereby not harming that company's immediate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Why the slowdown? Many companies accelerated their spending in
recent years to replace computers rather than deal with year-2000
issues in the older equipment. Spending for Internet-related
strategies remains strong _ EMC, the biggest company in data
storage, is still setting new highs _ but other areas are
weakening.
</P>
<P>
   At the low end _ the home and small-business markets _ computers
may be starting to resemble cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody says things are slowing, maybe you wait a year to
buy a new auto, or a new computer,'' said Robert Barbera, the chief
economist of Hoenig &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Slower growth for computers does not spell doom for the economy,
or for the companies involved. But it does call into question the
high multiples that computer stocks have come to enjoy. Even now,
Intel trades for 33 times historic earnings. That is double the
multiple it fetched a few years ago _ and four times that of
General Motors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
