u s BC-OLY-VOLLEY0929-COX     09-28 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VOLLEY0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Russians knock U.S. out of gold-medal contention
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The improbable run by the U.S. women's volleyball team
ended in the Olympic semifinals Thursday when Russia proved too
tall an order.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian players averaged about 6-foot-3 at the net and
looked like street performers on stilts. They were overpowering on
serves and blocked effectively to win 25-15, 23-25, 25-15, 26-28,
15-8 after the United States fought off two match points in the
fourth set.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some moments of greatness,'' said U.S. player Kerri
Walsh. ``Our comeback in Game 4 was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The final set was tied at 7 before the Russians closed out the
match at the Sydney Entertainment Centre. Saturday, Russia will
play Cuba, the dominant team for the past decade, for the gold,
while the United States will play Brazil for the bronze. Brazil
defeated the U.S. in four sets during group play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to win the match, but it didn't happen,'' said
Tara Cross-Battle, 32, one of two remaining members of the 1996
Olympic team, which placed seventh. ``A lot of people didn't think
we would get this far, but we knew that we could.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. players upset South Korea in five sets to gain a
semifinal berth, then had to readjust their game to the Russians,
who formed a virtual iron curtain at the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team came here kind of unknown, but they knew what they
came here to do,'' said coach Mick Haley. ``And once we got into
the medal round, it became very clear to all the players that the
gold medal was the thing they cherished the most. You could see by
their fighting spirit that they did not give up at any point in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the team will be upset if it doesn't come away with a
medal. ``No one wants to lose the last match,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Haley, ``We came here to win a gold medal. There's not
much difference between fourth and eighth.''
</P>
<P>
   His counterpart, Nikolai Karpol, has coached the Russians for 20
years and is compared to Bobby Knight for his fiery temperament.
When he yelled at one player, an American spectator called out,
``Awww, leave her alone,'' and other members of the crowd booed.
</P>
<P>
   Karpol's daughter Nadia is engaged to marry U.S. assistant coach
Jeri Estes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Maybe your dad will give you an early wedding
present,' '' said Robert Gambardella, director of the U.S. program.
``He's an intense guy. As much as he hollers at them, he really
loves the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team couldn't match the Russians' experience, as 10 of
the 12 were newcomers to the Olympics. Danielle Scott, the other
'96 veteran, will turn 28 Sunday. She doesn't regret sticking
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I gave up too much coming back. . . . a little
taxing on the body,'' she said, ``but I think it was worth it. And
I'm not finished yet. I have one more match to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
