<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.29.00
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   _ Unable to boogie, K-Tel leaves Nasdaq
</P>
<P>
   _ Garden.com cutting 30% of work force
</P>
<P>
   _ China auctions Web sites, names
</P>
<P>
   _ AccessAtlanta.com, Vindigo cook up deal
</P>
<P>
   _ Ford dealers join Web sales effort
</P>
<P>
   SOUR NOTE FOR K-TEL: Music retailer K-Tel International, a once
high-flying Internet stock that has since been grounded, has been
delisted by Nasdaq for failing to meet minimum requirements to
trade on the exchange. The company, which is known for its
repackaging of hits from the '70s and '80s (remember ``Play That
Funky Music''?), also said fourth-quarter revenue dropped and
losses widened. It partly blamed an ``excess inventory'' of
cassette tapes. K-Tel is now outsourcing a large part of its
e-commerce sales to Amazon.com to reduce overhead. Visitors to its
site _ www.ktel.com _ still can order custom CDs and get digital
downloads. In late 1998, K-Tel soared as high as $12.56 as day
traders snapped up shares but dumped them after investor euphoria
waned. The stock now trades at around 63 cents.
</P>
<P>
   GROWING PAINS: Garden.com plans to cut 30 percent of its work
force, or 93 jobs, as it joins a growing number of dot.coms that
are trying to cut expenses in the face of increased competition for
Internet dollars. At the same time, the company is launching a new
business division called Trellis, and it is teaming with Lowes
Companies Inc. to leverage Trellis' supply chain technology to
generate more retail and e-commerce business.
</P>
<P>
   WEB AUCTION IN CHINA: China will hold its first auction of
Internet companies, domain names and Web sites today, although
foreign investors aren't invited. The company is expected to have
50 million Internet users in five years. But many existing Net
companies are floundering. ``It has become almost impossible for
medium and small Web sites to sell shares to the public, and
mergers and acquisitions are good ways for them,'' Li Wenming, the
deputy secretary-general of the China Internet Web Site Auction
Committee, told Bloomberg News. The sites to be auctioned include
scrap-metal dealerships, flower suppliers and chat rooms for AIDS
patients.
</P>
<P>
   DINNER ANYONE? AccessAtlanta.com is teaming up with Vindigo, a
company that develops personal navigation software for hand-held
digital devices like Palms, to deliver information on the best
places to dine in metro Atlanta. Users will be able to search
restaurants by categories, name, distance and cost. They can also
indicate their current location on a Palm, or where they're going,
and get reviews, directions and details on popular eateries.
AccessAtlanta.com is owned and operated by Cox Interactive Media,
which is owned by Cox Enterprises Inc. Cox Enterprises also owns
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   FORD AT FINGERTIPS: Ford said 78 percent of its eligible member
dealers have agreed to participate in FordDirect.com, which will
sell cars and trucks online at the prices dealers pay. The Ford
dealers council said 3,194 of the 4,080 eligible dealers in the
United States, who account for 90 percent of Ford sales, have
committed to participating in FordDirect.com. The first online site
is expected to be running in California next month.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   WELL-CONNECTED: Gartner Group researchers say San Francisco can
call itself the country's top Internet market. A study shows 73% of
the city's population accessed the Web in the past 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   HOT/COLD NET STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com Inc. (PCLN), up 10% at $11.88. The travel site
rebounded after plunging 51 percent because it said it will fall
short of third-quarter sales estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Inc. (YHOO), up 6% at $95.69. Investors returned to the
stock after sending it down 19 percent over the last three sessions
because of revenue concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Exodus Communications (EXDS), down 8% at $41.12. The manager of
Web sites for businesses agreed to buy Global Crossing Ltd.'s
GlobalCenter Inc. unit for $6.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE: 09.29.00
</P>
<P>
   SITES
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon Net browser now available
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo of America and MediaBrowser Inc. have launched a
Pokemon Internet browser. Users can surf the Pokemon Gold and
Silver Official game site, Pokemon Stadium game site, Pokemon
Trading Card game site, and Pokemon Snap game site. The browser is
available free for downloading.
</P>
<P>
   www.pokemon.com
</P>
