<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-PILL (Washington) _ Anti-abortion leaders condemn the
Food and Drug Administration for its decision to allow RU-486, the
abortion pill, to be sold in the United States. ``This decision is
unprecedented.'' said Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a physician who
says he has delivered 3,500 babies in his career and 400 while in
Congress. ``Never before has the FDA approved a drug intended to
kill people.'' By JENNIFER A. DLOUHY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FLIGHT-DELAYS (Washington) _ American Airlines Chairman Donald
J. Carty warns a House panel that air traffic delays will worsen
next year unless Congress intervenes to limit the burgeoning number
of flights at major airports. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-KILLING (Washington) _ Religious leaders and civil rights
advocates urge Congress to pass a hate crimes bill following the
shooting death last week in a Roanoke, Va., gay bar by a gunman who
announced he was there to ``waste fags.'' By ERIC ROSENBERG.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PEARL-HARBOR (Washington) _ Congress appears poised to exonerate
the U.S. commanders at Pearl Harbor at the time of the surprise
Japanese attack on Dec. 7, 1941. Legislation approved by both the
House and Senate would absolve Rear Adm. Husband Kimmel and Maj.
Gen. Walter Short of blame for the disaster, saying both officers
were ``professional and competent.'' By CHARLES J. LEWIS and ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP _ Capitalizing public anxiety over rising fuel
prices, Texas Gov. George W. Bush plans to unveil an energy policy
that calls for new government policies to encourage oil exploration
and refining. In a speech to be delivered in the battleground state
of Michigan, Bush is expected to outline steps to speed up
construction of refineries that process oil. By DAN FREEDMAN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BUSH (Undated) _ Before taking a break from the campaign
trail to prepare for upcoming debates, Republican George W. Bush
and Democrat Al Gore stake out traditional party territory. Bush
says the big surplus merits a big tax cut. Gore brags about the
good economy and says it provides the opportunity to shore up
Medicare and Social Security. By PATTY REINERT and CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The myth is now frozen that the way
to woo female voters is to master the art of the smooch and chatter
about silly things like peanut butter sandwiches, as Al Gore and
George W. Bush are doing. The myth is as misleading as it is
patronizing. Women don't vote for president solely out of emotion
any more than men vote entirely by intellect. All the political
talk about how to get the female vote is just that _ talk. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES (Washington) _ Millions of voters will get a chance to
see Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush in a live,
unscripted showdown Tuesday night when the presidential contenders
square-off in the first of three debates that could sway the
outcome of the closest presidential election in 20 years. By
STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-ELECTION (Washington) _ Al Gore and George W. Bush are
knocking themselves out trying to one-up the other on education, an
issue at the top of voters' concerns. Each would dramatically boost
federal education spending, and each has a plan to raise student
achievement, but they are polar opposites on the controversial idea
of vouchers. We compare and contrast the two candidates' plans. By
DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PREVIEW (Washington) _ After tackling such volatile issues
as gay rights and late-term abortion in its last term, the Supreme
Court starts a new session Monday with a wide-ranging docket of
cases involving police searches, immigration law, high-school
athletes, migrating birds and smog. By MARK HELM.
</P>
