<SLUG> BC-OLY-HOOPM0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Team USA used to being a target
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ They're as good as it gets in Olympic basketball, and
yet the U.S. men's team feels it can get better. Better play,
better results, better reaction.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Team USA continues its assault on the gold
medal. In dismantling Russia 85-70 Thursday, the United States
advanced to the semifinals Friday against Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that America won by only nine points the first time
the teams met a week ago _ and the aggressiveness with which
opponents have attacked the overwhelming favorites _ another
challenging, if not difficult, outing is expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for a lot of marbles, so teams are coming at us,''
said guard Vince Carter, who had 15 points and six rebounds against
the Russians. ``We're about winning, too, so we're coming right
back at them. We don't care who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way many feel about the Americans. Kevin Garnett (16
points, 11 rebounds) listened to a fan heckle him all game. When it
was over, Garnett said, he threw the man a towel in a spirit of
sportsmanship. ``And he spat on it and threw it back,'' Garnett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the feelings many fans have expressed about America's
team. Not all the time, but enough to let the players know they
must be their own support system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an NBA game, we see hecklers and get booed on the road,''
Carter said. ``So we're used to it. In this case, it's the Goliath
thing. They want to see us knocked off.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia was in a position to pull the upset, trailing just 46-41
at halftime. But, as usual, the United States' depth, talent and
defense won out. Which, of course, prompted boos from the SuperDome
crowd as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what the fans think,'' Carter said. ``I'm not
playing for the fans. I'm playing for the gold. We're not playing
to impress the fans. We're playing to impress ourselves. I could
score 50 points and they would still boo. So we just have to take
care of our own business.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Seattle's Gary Payton: ``We don't care about them booing
us. They boo us, but then we get a dunk and they cheer. They're
wishy-washy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the less-than-warm reception and the shaky starts to
games, the United States has handled business quite well. And it
has managed its emotions admirably, too, for opponents have taken
to grabbing, clutching, holding, pulling and bumping even more than
expected for international play.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the first half Thursday, Carter was undercut by
Russia's Zakhar Pachoutine, which touched off some strong emotions.
Carter, Gary Payton and Antonio McDyess had to be restrained from
taking on Pachoutine and his brother, Evgueni.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deliberately undercut me,'' Carter said. ``I don't care if
you play hard. But there was no call to low-bridge me. Whenever
that happens, I can't go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The American players are mindful not to sound like whiners.
``We're not asking for any breaks,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   But they are keenly aware that teams open games strongly and
with a purpose. ``We can't get frustrated,'' Payton said. ``And I
don't think we are. I mean, we've got two more games and it's gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're coming out too relaxed, and that's because of the
young guys. They are hyped and running around instead of being
poised and coming hard. If we come out at the start the way we do
the second half, we win by 30. . . . And we'd probably get booed
for that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
