<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTES0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three left for U.S. in boxing semifinals
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For U.S. boxers once heralded as the best since the
five-gold team of 1976, it's now this simple: three remaining shots
at gold, and at the chance to salvage some respectability in the
new order of world amateur boxing.
</P>
<P>
   If Jermain Taylor, Rocky Juarez and Ricardo Williams don't win
on Friday, the United States will go home without any boxing gold
for the first time since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team hasn't lived up to my expectations,'' USA Boxing
president Gary Toney said.
</P>
<P>
   That thought could easily be echoed by Cuban boxing officials,
though they tend to keep such things to themselves. Five Cuban
losses in a row between the quarterfinals and semifinals stunned
boxing's dominant power the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Cubans still beat Americans, as Clarence Vinson found out
Thursday when Guillermo Rigondeaux snapped the Cuban losing streak
with a dominating win over Vinson in the 119-pound semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get these type of things in boxing,'' said Vinson, who
will take a bronze medal home to Washington. ``He was just a better
fighter today.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams gets the last U.S. chance to beat a Cuban when he faces
Diogenes Luna in the 139-pound semifinal Friday. American boxers
are 0-2 against Cuba in Sydney and 2-10 overall in the last three
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The other Americans fighting to get into gold medal finals are
the hard-hitting Taylor at 156 pounds and Juarez at 125 pounds.
Taylor faces Yermakhan Ibraimov of Kasakstan, while Juarez fights
Russia's Kamil Dzamalutdinov.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can get a couple of them through to the finals,''
U.S. coach Tom Mustin said. ``Maybe we'll get all three of them.''
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING
</P>
<P>
   KOLAT ELIMINATED
</P>
<P>
   Cary Kolat can beat the wrestlers. What he can't seem to beat is
the system in international wrestling that permits the slightest
dispute or error to alter a match result.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Kolat, who can't seem to win for losing in off-the-mat
decisions, won 3-1 Thursday over former world champion Mohammad
Talaei of Iran, but the result was protested, then Kolat lost the
rematch 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Kolat, long one of the United States' best amateur wrestlers,
later pinned Ramil Islamov of Uzbekistan in 5:52 at 138 3/4 pounds
(63 kg). However, Talaei won by injury forfeit over Islamov to win
the three-man pool, advance to Friday's quarterfinals and oust
Kolat.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in four years a Kolat victory in a
world-level championship was stripped by protest.
</P>
<P>
   In amateur wrestling, no wrestler leaves the mat secure in
victory. Any loser can dispute a match on any technical point, and
all he needs is a sympathetic arbitrator to order a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Slay of the United States, for example, upset Olympic
champion Bouvaissa Saitiev of Russia at 167 1/2 pounds (76 kg)
Thursday, but was nervous about the outcome until Saitiev's protest
was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, and I've never liked it, that a point can be
awarded on the mat and allowed to stand, and somebody goes into a
back room and changes it,'' U.S. coach Bruce Barnett said.
</P>
<P>
   TAEKWONDO
</P>
<P>
   BREAKTHROUGH FOR U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Lopez won the United States' first gold medal in the
Olympics' newest official sport, just as he knew someday would.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like I visualized,'' said Lopez, competing at 150
pounds (68 kg). ``It's just as perfect as I had imagined and
dreamt.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez got into the sport because his family was into it. His
older brother, Jean, who is also now his coach, was on the national
team with Steven in 1994 and 1996. His younger brother, Mark, was
on the team with him last year.
</P>
<P>
   After being scored on only once in his first three bouts, Lopez
had to come from behind in the final round of the title match to
defeat South Korean Sin Joon-sik.
</P>
<P>
   MEN'S TENNIS
</P>
<P>
   KAFELNIKOV TRIUMPHANT
</P>
<P>
   With a marathon performance and a jubilant heave of his racket,
Yevgeny Kafelnikov capped a stellar month for Russian tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov outlasted Tommy Haas of Germany 7-6 (4), 3-6, 6-2,
4-6, 6-3 for the gold medal in men's singles, then celebrated by
tossing his racket 15 rows into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``To add a gold medal to my career, it's absolutely fantastic,''
Kafelnikov said.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Russian Elena Dementieva won the silver in women's
singles. Less than three weeks ago, Russian Marat Safin beat Pete
Sampras to win the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``My country is taking over in tennis,'' Kafelnikov said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE TENNIS
</P>
<P>
   DOKIC OUT FOR AUSSIES?
</P>
<P>
   Upset over news reports that focus on her father's temper,
17-year-old star Jelena Dokic has vowed never to play for Australia
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph reported that Dokic was angry over an
article in the Australian Tennis magazine that suggested her
father, Damir Dokic, needed psychological help to control his
temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to speak to my Fed Cup captain Lesley Bowrey . . .
and tell her I don't want to play for Australia again,'' said
Dokic, who lost to Monica Seles in the bronze-medal match. ``I
don't care what people say and do to my poppa _ the bond between
us, my mother and (brother) Savo, no one can break.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Dokic's father was banned from women's
tennis, both as a coach and as a spectator. He also was denied
Olympic accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions came after he was tossed out of both Wimbledon and
the U.S. Open this year following confrontations with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   TRACK AND FIELD
</P>
<P>
   PEREC `CRACKED'
</P>
<P>
   French star Marie-Jose Perec, who fled before her planned
400-meter showdown with Cathy Freeman, says fear overwhelmed her
dream of obtaining a third gold medal and she ``cracked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed the most important rendezvous I ever had with
myself,'' she told the French sports daily L'Equipe. ``I cracked
when I shouldn't have cracked.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
