<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-NEWSPAPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY SELLS LOCAL NEWSPAPER UNIT TO BOSTON HERALD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dramatically altering the Massachusetts media landscape
and widening his publishing battle with The Boston Globe, Boston
Herald publisher Patrick J. Purcell announced an agreement Thursday
to purchase the Fidelity Investments stable of more than 100 local
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative deal for Community Newspaper Co. (CNC) ends
Fidelity's rocky 10-year experiment in community journalism. It
also teams the urban-oriented Herald with CNC's suburban papers
shortly after the Globe's parent company, The New York Times Co.,
purchased the Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette and as the Globe itself
is expanding its suburban coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it certainly will extend the (newspaper) battle,''
said Purcell during a teleconference announcing the sale. ``This is
an extraordinary revenue generating opportunity. . . . I think it
will make the Herald combination a much more effective competitor.
Let the battle be joined.''
</P>
<P>
   Globe publisher Richard H. Gilman responded that ``I'm not
surprised that they've done this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither company was in a particularly favorable competitive
situation,'' Gilman said. ``We will continue our plans to serve our
readers and advertisers even better than we do today.''
</P>
<P>
   If the sale, expected to close by Nov. 1, goes through, Purcell
will acquire CNC's Eastern Massachusetts stable of 88 weeklies,
four dailies, 15 so-called shoppers devoted largely to advertising,
some specialty publications, and the Town Online Web operation.
</P>
<P>
   CNC, with about 1,200 employees, reports a total weekly
circulation of slightly under 600,000. The combined daily
circulation of the Herald and CNC daily papers would be about
325,000.
</P>
<P>
   While Thursday's agreement was a well-kept secret, it was not a
complete surprise. In recent years, Fidelity had been the subject
of frequent sale rumors, many of them involving MediaNews Group
president William Dean Singleton as a potential buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell has been actively pursuing other acquisition
opportunities, most recently making a serious bid for The Patriot
Ledger of Quincy and The Brockton Enterprise, which were suddenly
pulled off the market last week. Since its pursuit of the Ledger,
the Herald has employed several internal belt-tightening measures.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Purcell said that ``I've been talking to various folks
at Fidelity for a long time about coming together.'' Those talks
``became really serious in the summer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The principals declined to discuss a sale price, with Purcell
simply stating that the ``financing is in place.'' That led to
speculation about whether the Herald had won a bargain basement
deal for an operation that Fidelity may have come to view as a
corporate liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I ever believed it would sell as a package was at
bottom-fishing prices,'' said Jack Authelet, a newspaper
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper analyst John Morton characterized the purchase as a
``very intelligent strategy.'' But Morton added that ``a more
interesting question is about how he's financing it'' and joked
that perhaps former Herald owner Rupert Murdoch was lurking in the
shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the initial reaction to Thursday's announcement was
upbeat. ``It sure makes sense for Pat, because he's going to
combine his strength in the city with superb demographics in the
suburbs, which gives him a compelling story,'' said Russel
Pergament, who sold his Tab newspaper chain to CNC in 1992 and
later became a vice chairman of that company. ``And it will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elfers, the retired CNC chairman who initially convinced
Fidelity boss Ned Johnson to invest in community newspapers, said:
``I have some wistfulness and I also have some joy. I think this is
an outstanding marriage between two strong, locally owned
franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his plans for personnel and synergy between the
two operations, Purcell indicated that it was too early to know
many of those answers. ``We need to get in there and better
understand'' the CNC structure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The question hanging over Thursday's announcement was not only
whether Purcell could reap financial rewards from his purchase, but
whether he could act as an effective steward for scores of small
community papers with intimate ties to their readers.
</P>
<P>
   The sale ``bodes well for journalism in general in the Boston
area,'' said Robert Keough, the editor of CommonWealth magazine,
who recently moderated a forum on community journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of community journalism,'' he said, the question is
whether the ``Herald is in a position to carry out an oversight
over what essentially are a million little newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's tenure had its share of rough patches. Founded in
1991, CNC patched together various local chains in the hope of
creating a muscular newspaper empire that combined the best aspects
of localism and chainwide clout.
</P>
<P>
   But early on, there was a revolving door of top executives and
frustrating bureaucratic inertia. By the mid-1990s, CNC had
invested approximately $100 million in the enterprise and still not
turned a profit. One observer compared the undertaking to ``a major
motion picture, many years in the making.''
</P>
<P>
   CNC is widely believed to have been operating in the black for
the last several years, but that has also been accompanied by a
number of cost-cutting measures. Editors were stretched thinner
during a 1999 restructuring, and the company announced the
elimination of about 150 positions earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   At the public forum moderated by Keough and sponsored by the the
MassInc think tank, CNC executive editor Mary Jo Meisner was
besieged by angry questions from audience members complaining about
CNC's cutbacks and the quality of their local papers.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Johnson ``wanted to do something positive, he wanted
something of civic value, and he put his money where his mouth
is,'' said Pergament. ``A few bucks later, he's decided, I think
wisely, to step out of the arena and to defer to someone who
understands the newspapers organically.''
</P>
<P>
   Said analyst Morton: ``It may be that Fidelity may have made
some mistakes in alienating some of thse communities. ``But the key
here (for Purcell) is advertising presence.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does the Herald succeed where Fidelity struggled?
Observers say Purcell will need to develop strategies for combined
advertising packages, that there are likely to be some sharing of
reporting resources, and that he needs to be acutely aware, more
aware than his predecessors, of the sensitive bond between a
community and its neighborhood paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have to make some smart business decisions, no
doubt about that,'' said Authelet, who has been a sometime critic
of CNC.
</P>
<P>
   But the key is for Purcell to ``just put the responsibility back
in the hands of people at the local papers who can do the job,'' he
said. ``Every reader in CNC land should be rejoicing tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
