<HEADER>
A5632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-FIRESTONE0929-COX     09-28 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRESTONE0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A small-town David verses big corporate Goliaths
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATESBORO, Ga. _ It's not likely Rowe Brogdon instilled fear in
the corporate hearts of Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. and the Ford
Motor Co. in 1998 when he filed a $21 million wrongful-death
lawsuit on behalf of a Florida couple whose son died in a car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon, after all, is an affable, small-town, South Georgia
lawyer who cut his lawyerly teeth on car-crash cases. Nobody
dismisses Brogdon today.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate giants settled the lawsuit right before trial was
set to begin _ much to Brogdon's satisfaction, although he would
not disclose terms. Brogdon, 46, and the tire-building
whistle-blower he discovered helped lead to Bridgestone/Firestone's
recall of 6.5 million tires.
</P>
<P>
   And, tire company documents that Brogdon fought hard to uncover
show that tires made at a plant in Wilson, N.C., prompted more
customer complaints of tread separations between 1990 and 1995 than
tires manufactured at any other Firestone plant. A U.S. District
Court judge in Brunswick ordered the documents unsealed this week.
They seem to contradict the company's earlier claims that its
problems were confined to its Decatur, Ill., plant.
</P>
<P>
   It also shifts the focus of the faulty-tire investigation from
the Midwest to the South. Georgia _ Brunswick and Statesboro, in
particular _ are in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see my role as being a lawyer prosecuting a successful case
involving a defective product,'' Brogdon said in an interview this
week. ``It's exhilarating to see things ideally happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim and Michael Van Etten's son Daniel died in March 1997 when
his Ford Explorer blew a tire and crashed on I-95 in Camden County.
Daniel, a 19-year-old scholarship football player returning to West
Virginia University, was thrown from the car. The blown tire was a
Firestone radial ATX, like millions of others now being
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met Kim Van Etten, she told me they picked the
wrong mother's son to kill,'' Brogdon recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon had successfully sued the Cooper Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. after
a 1993 blow-out near Claxton led to a man's ``catastrophic'' head
injury. Brogdon's reputation as a tire expert for product liability
cases was building. Brogdon compiled incidents nationwide of tire
blowouts involving Firestone/Bridgestone tires. He received
documents from the tire company which showed Brogdon where the
faulty tire was manufactured _ Wilson, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon needed more, though, somebody with inside information.
He found Alan Hogan. It wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1998, Brogdon wrote 10 or so members of the
American Trial Lawyers Association in Wilson wondering if they'd
ever had clients who'd worked at the massive tire company. Brogdon
got lucky and found one employee, but he'd worked in shipping, not
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he had a friend who was willing to talk who made tires and
had tremendous knowledge of the manufacturing process,'' Brogdon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon flew to Raleigh the next morning, rented a car and drove
to the Holiday Inn Express in Wilson to meet Hogan. He discovered
Hogan, who'd worked at the plant during the early and mid-1990s,
had a ``tremendous background in engineering and an understanding
of the tire-building process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning I knew I had his attention, when he learned
somebody had been killed,'' Brogdon recalled. ``When I showed him
pictures of the tire he said, 'I can tell you exactly why that tire
came apart.' `` Firestone/Bridgestone's attorneys deposed Hogan on
March 31, 1999. He told them the plant had a ``chronic problem with
the tire separations.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys asked: ``You talked earlier about when you saw the
Van Etten tire that you thought there was something wrong with it,
that it occurred at the plant. What was it that you thought was
wrong . . .?''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan replied: ``The way the two belts came apart.'' He said he
saw ``clear indications'' that sections of the tire were
inadequately joined.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the Brunswick trial in August 1999,
Firestone/Bridgestone and Ford settled with Brogdon, his partner
James Franklin, and the Van Ettens. But the game was only half
over.
</P>
<P>
   KHOU-TV in Houston learned of Hogan's testimony. A reporter flew
the next day to interview Hogan. Officials with the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration saw Warner's report and the
tire recall soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I learned about the recall, the first two people I called
were Kim Van Etten and Alan Hogan,'' Brogdon said. ``We just shared
a feeling that the case had a much greater worth than any monetary
amount ever received.''
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon is set to go out on his own Monday. His new office is a
few blocks off the courthouse square, evidence of the distance he
has traveled, literally and figuratively, from his earlier
product-liability days.
</P>
<P>
   But Brogdon still keeps in touch with the Van Ettens and Hogan.
He represents Hogan, who claims ``intentional and malicious
interference of his business by Firestone'' as a result of Hogan's
public comments against his former employer.
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon is also fielding inquiries from a couple of clients
considering lawsuits against Firestone/Bridgestone. He relishes the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-level litigation against major corporations is extremely
challenging,'' he said. ``It's a game of cat and mouse and,
unfortunately, you're the mouse. What you have to do, though,
through tenaciousness and persistence is fight, fight, fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
