<HEADER>
A5635 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-FIRE-LAWSUIT0929-COX     09-28 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-LAWSUIT0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyer: Tire builder's testimony backed
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Court documents unsealed in Brunswick validate key
testimony by a former Firestone tire builder whose allegations of
quality control problems at the company's North Carolina factory
eventually led to a massive recall, a Georgia lawyer said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adjustment or warranty data confirms and corroborates the
testimony of Alan Hogan,'' Statesboro, Ga., lawyer Rowe Brogdon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, 33, is a former Firestone employee in Wilson, N.C., whose
pre-trial testimony in a wrongful death lawsuit exposed problems at
the factory. Hogan's revelations led to subsequent news reports,
prompting Bridgestone/Firestone's recall of 6.5 million tires.
</P>
<P>
   Brogdon brought the wrongful death lawsuit and now represents
Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   Adjustment data is information compiled by tire companies to
document how many tires were returned to retailers by unsatisfied
customers, and why refunds or exchanges were granted.
</P>
<P>
   The newly disclosed information, compiled by plaintiffs' expert
witness Dennis Carlson, shows that between 1990 and 1995, tread
separation was cited in 66.4 percent of the tires returned for
refunds at the Wilson facility; tread separation was cited in 59.6
percent for returns of tires made at all Firestone plants. This
data was revealed in four sets of Firestone documents unsealed
Wednesday by U.S. District Judge Anthony Alaimo of Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   Alaimo also ordered the unsealing of even more Firestone
documents, but the judge postponed their release, giving the
tiremaker a week to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public interest is legitimate because the tire tread
separation defect concerns the health and safety of the public _
interests of the highest order,'' Alaimo wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone may appeal part of Alaimo's ruling,
spokeswoman Anne Conrad said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also strongly disputes Carlson's conclusions, Conrad
said, adding that Wilson's adjustment data is ``equal to or better
than'' all other plants. Of the more than 2.3 million tires
produced at Wilson between 1991 and 1995, only 0.13 percent had a
tread separation adjustment, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``For these people to make a claim that there are problems with
the Wilson tire, that's absurd,'' Conrad said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration is
investigating the Aug. 9 recall of the ATX, ATX II and Wilderness
AT tires. Bridgestone/Firestone has recalled all ATX tires but only
Wilderness tires made in Decatur, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Ford Motor Co. said it will give buyers of future
versions of its Explorer sports-utility vehicles a choice of tires
from three different companies. Customers will be able to pick
tires from Michelin &AMP; Cie. and Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co., as well
as Bridgestone/Firestone, for the 2002 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
