u i BC-ISRAEL-RIOT-HNS &LR;      09-28 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-RIOT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS RIOT AS ISRAELI LAWMAKERS VISIT RELIGIOUS SITE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Angry Palestinians rioted Thursday in Jerusalem and
the West Bank following a tour by Israeli opposition leader Ariel
Sharon to the religious shrine that stands at the heart of the
Arab-Israeli dispute.
</P>
<P>
   At least five demonstrators were injured in Ramallah, 15 miles
north of Jerusalem, when Palestinian stone-throwers confronted
Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Similar unrest in Jerusalem left at least a dozen Palestinians
and several Israeli soldiers wounded. The clashes flared after
Sharon and six fellow Likud lawmakers marched onto the site that
Jews call Temple Mount and Muslims the Haram al-Sharif, or the
Noble Sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's delegation stayed for about 20 minutes while dozens of
Palestinians lobbed rocks and bottles toward them. Hundreds of
Israeli police, on hand to provide security, responded by clubbing
and firing rubber bullets at the stone throwers.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing melee, at least two Palestinians were injured
when they were hit in the face by rubber bullets. Two soldiers,
slightly injured, were whisked away on stretchers. Israeli
officials said 25 troops suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the violence, Sharon announced upon leaving that he
had come on a mission of good will. ``I came here with a message of
peace,'' he told reporters. ``I am very sorry that people were
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``What provocation is there when Jews come to
visit the place with a message of peace?''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's critics, however, blasted the retired general for what
they said was a poorly timed visit designed to provoke violent
confrontations over the site. Many Palestinians were angered by the
visit because it carried political significance to a sacred Islamic
site that they believe should be subject solely to Muslim
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Jews believe the site is where King Solomon built the first of
two temples some 3,000 years ago. It is Judaism's holiest shrine.
For Arabs, it is the third-holiest place of Islam. Muslims believe
the Prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven from there, which now is
the site of two mosques, Al Aqsa and Dome of the Rock.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the site has been at the epicenter of the
Israeli-Palestinian dispute. Both sides demand control over it as
part of any peace deal. Neither has shown an inclination, in public
at least, to accept a compromise on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Camp David summit collapsed in July, Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat has stuck to his public demand for Arab
sovereignty over the site. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has
refused to budge. The impasse has led to a variety of suggested
solutions, including sharing sovereignty over the city or agreeing
to a partial deal that would leave its future undecided.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Barak was quoted as suggesting that Jerusalem and
al-Quds, the Arabic name for Jerusalem, could be capitals for the
Israelis and Palestinians. ``It will be Jerusalem and Al-Quds, one
next to the other, as two capitals,'' he was quoted by the
Jerusalem Post.
</P>
<P>
   Against this political backdrop, Sharon's ascent to the shrine
appeared designed to highlight Israel's current hold over the site,
captured in the 1967 Middle East war, while placing Barak in the
awkward position of seeming too willing to concede it to the
Palestinians in return for a peace.
</P>
<P>
   To Palestinian leaders, many of whom confronted Sharon at the
shrine Thursday, the visit seemed calculated to provoke an angry
response.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to Palestinian television in Gaza, Arafat termed the
visit ``very dangerous'' and called on Muslim nations to ``move
very fast'' to protect the Muslim shrines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dangerous process conducted by Sharon against
Islamic sacred places,'' the Palestinian leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Announced more than a day in advance, Sharon's tour attracted
Palestinian warnings of violence and calls for strikes, and allowed
plenty of time for the Palestinian leadership to organize angry
protests.
</P>
<P>
   The tour followed a day of violence in the Gaza Strip, in which
a roadside bomb planted near a Jewish settlement detonated as an
army convoy passed by, injuring two soldiers. One later died from
his wounds.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, several Arab Israeli members of the Knesset,
Israel's parliament, stood with the protesters during the Sharon
visit and declared shortly after he left that the Likud leader had
deliberately caused a bloody confrontation. Some said the police
had beaten them with clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to see more blood and to see more killing,'' Abdel
Malik Dahamsheh, an Israeli-Arab lawmaker, said of Sharon as he
walked down from the mount. ``He wants to kill the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Tibi, another Arab member of the Knesset, added: ``They
should be kept away from this place. They are responsible for any
violence that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, a 33-year-old Jewish man from Maryland who refused
to give his name heckled the lawmakers. ``Go away! We don't want
you here,'' he yelled. ``Go back to Mecca!''
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, the legislators chanted ``Al-Aqsa is Palestinian.''
That is the name of one of the mosques at the site.
</P>
<P>
   On the plaza below, a group of about a dozen Jews tried to
out-shout them, chanting, ``Here is the Temple Mount.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
