u w BC-PERU-FUJIMORI-HNS &LR;      09-28 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-FUJIMORI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERU PRESIDENT VISITS WASHINGTON TO SEEK U.S. SUPPORT 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL HEDGES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Embattled Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori paid
a surprise visit to Washington Thursday in an effort to gain
backing during a tumultuous time in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived so suddenly that U.S. officials were caught
flat-footed when asked when and with whom he'd meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that has come up rather quickly,'' said
State Department Spokesman Philip Reeker at an afternoon briefing.
``It wasn't something we were anticipating as we put together
schedules for the week or even for the days ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori met with the secretary-general of the Organization of
American States, Cesar Gaviria, for about 45 minutes at OAS
headquarters Thursday evening but had no comment afterwards. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The State Department arranged a meeting with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright for Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said U.S. officials plan to emphasize the Clinton
administration's support for a peaceful and democratic transition
of power and ``for the continuation of OAS dialogue that has been
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Andean nation has been rocked by fears of a military coup
following an announcement by Fujimori earlier this month that he
will step down next spring after new elections. The fears were
heightened Thursday when a member of the Peruvian Congress charged
that the military was trying to force lawmakers into a plot to
provoke a coup. But Reeker said the administration had no knowledge
of an imminent coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peruvian armed forces issued a statement last (Wednesday)
night denying outright rumors of army-led efforts to organize a
coup. And I think that statement very much reaffirms the support
previously voiced by the military in Peru for maintaining
constitutional order, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent forced departure to Panama of Fujimori's disgraced
former spy chief, Vladimiro Montesinos, after charges arose that he
bribed a legislator failed to calm jitters that the nation's
fragile democracy was faltering.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos had strong support inside the Peruvian army, fueling
rumors that he was instigating a coup.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell Fleischer, a senior associate at the Center for Strategic
and International Studies in Washington, said Fujimori was visiting
Washington in hopes of securing support from the OAS and the State
Department, both of which have been critical of him since he was
elected for an unprecedented third term in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess he is shopping around for international backing
for his plans to hold elections next year,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   One senior congressional analyst said Fujimori's sudden visit
may be intended to gain the backing of the United States and the
OAS as he prepares to ``portray himself, ironically, as the savior
of Peruvian democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Under this theory, Fujimori is taking advantage of, and perhaps
even heightening, speculation in Peru that former spy chief
Montesinos is working to set up a military coup.
</P>
<P>
   That speculation has grown following unsubstantiated reports
that Montesinos backers inside the military were replacing junior
officers viewed as not loyal to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our read is that a coup is very doubtful at this point,'' said
the congressional expert. ``There would be very little support for
it in Latin America beyond (Cuban President Fidel) Castro and maybe
(Venezuelan President Hugo) Chavez.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lima, many people inside and outside of government believe
that a coup is not a possibility. One expert, retired Gen. Daniel
Mora, said the military command would destroy itself it it tried to
take power.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a clear leader and cohesion in the ranks for
a coup to happen, and both conditions are missing,'' Mora said.
``Two other conditions, popular support and international
acquiescence, are also absent. It wouldn't work and the generals
know this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori may have surmised that his sudden departure to the
United States could create jitters in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   He would then tell U.S. and OAS officials that he needed their
strong, explicit backing in order to calm the volatile situation.
</P>
<P>
   If he secured that backing, Fujimori could then return to Peru
clearly in charge, and would have bought time until the new
election he has promised for next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said, ``That is a plausible scenario. He may well be
telling people in Washington that a smooth, successful transition
to democracy is up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lima, opposition politicians ended a two-week boycott of
Congress Thursday. Lawmakers unanimously passed a law eliminating
the intelligence service, which was headed by Montesinos. The law
calls for the service to be deactivated beginning in 15 days and
set up an oversight board that includes civilian participation.
</P>
<P>
   When the votes were counted the chamber exploded in applause,
with representatives from both sides of the aisle congratulating
themselves for working together.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
