<SLUG> BC-FILM-GIRLFIGHT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ A KNOCKOUT IN `GIRLFIGHT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Its punch may stem from a feminine perspective but don't
underrate the visceral wallop packed by ``Girlfight,'' a first
feature from Karyn Kusama.
</P>
<P>
   It teems with an impatient, explosive energy that's so full of
attitude that Sundance Film Festival audiences lavished it with a
best directing honor and a shared Grand Jury Prize. Subsequent
showings at the Seattle International Film Festival and Cannes
garnered additional enthusiasm for the film.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why. Kusama tells the rugged story of Diana
Guzman (Michelle Rodriguez), a young woman who takes up boxing as
an escape from life in Brooklyn's housing projects and finds
self-respect and acceptance in a male-dominated world.
</P>
<P>
   The film could easily have stumbled under the weight of a
million cliches and too-familiar ``Rocky'' references, but
``Girlfight'' is a genre-twisting surprise. It's more akin to
recent European boxing films _ ``The Boxer'' and ``247'' _ that see
the sport as a way out of poverty and didn't impossibly or
unrealistically stack the odds against their young protagonist's
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, there is a deeper emotional weight to the material
_ as it invites us to actually invest more than the mindless ``good
vs. evil'' theme that so many movies warrant these days.
</P>
<P>
   Diana isn't just an angry kid out to beat up the bad guys. She's
confused but brave and she's tired of taking heat from her abusive
father (Paul Calderon). When she picks up her little brother, Tiny
(Ray Santiago), from the gym, where he's been sent to learn to
fight, Diana realizes this is a place where she feels comfortable
and secure. And after convincing seasoned coach Hector (Jaime
Tirelli) that she has the right stuff to become a formidable
presence in the ring, he agrees to help her train, in secret.
</P>
<P>
   Their alliance gives the high school girl a sense of balance in
her disordered, formerly dead-end life. And a friendship with a
promising young boxer (Santiago Douglas) instills her with the
determination to get out of her rut and to face her familial demons
with pride and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Kusama found her Diana in an open casting call after exhausting
other options. In Rodriguez, whom the director calls ``a wild
card'' who ``burns up the screen and holds it by sheer presence,''
she's made a real find.
</P>
<P>
   GIRLFIGHT
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/WRITER: Karyn Kusama
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Michelle Rodriguez, Jaime Tirelli, Paul Calderon, Santiago
Douglas
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: R for language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
