<HEADER>
A5642 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CANADA-TRUDEAU-BOS &LR;      09-28 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TRUDEAU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLISH EX-CANADA PREMIER PIERRE TRUDEAU, 80, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Pierre Elliott Trudeau, who for 16 years as Canada's
prime minister electrified the country and captured world attention
with his aristocratic style, fierce intelligence, and dashing good
looks, died Thursday, age 80.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Broadcasting Corp. reported the cause of death as
``complications'' resulting from prostate cancer and Parkinson's
disease. He had been in frail health since a bout of pnuemonia in
January, although until July he walked daily to his downtown law
office in his hometown of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of mourners gathered outside Trudeau's landmark art
deco mansion on the slopes of Mount Royal as word of his death
spread through the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierre Trudeau, the embodiment of the dream of a just society,
has left us,'' Prime Minister Jean Chretien told the grieving
nation. ``He is gone but his unfinished work remains _ our country,
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Easily the most famous and controversial Canadian leader of this
century, Trudeau's legacy _ like that of John F. Kennedy, the
American president to whom he was most frequently compared _ is
more one of style than substance.
</P>
<P>
   But the left-leaning leader presided over the restoration of the
Canada's Constitution from Britain and the creation of the
country's Charter of Rights and Freedoms, equivalent to the United
States Bill of Rights. Against tremendous opposition in English
Canada, he pushed the country into enshrining French, the tongue of
his native Quebec, as the country's second official language,
giving it the same legal status as English.
</P>
<P>
   Most controversially, during the ``October Crisis'' of 1970, as
separatist terrorists exploded bombs and murdered officials in
Quebec, Trudeau imposed the War Measures Act, ordering troops into
the province and suspending civil liberties. The dramatic action
won him the undying hatred of many French Quebecers, although
repeated polls show that English Canadians consider him to be the
greatest politician in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
   In supporting federal bills that made divorce easier and relaxed
laws on abortion and homosexuality _ positions that were also
deeply unpopular in predominantly Roman Catholic Quebec _ Trudeau
came up with one of his most famous phrases: ``The state has no
place in the bedrooms of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   All through his long occupation of the top political post, from
1968 to 1979 and again from 1980 to 1984, he projected a charisma
not seen before or since in a nation whose leaders are typically as
drab and dreary as the Canadian winterscape. The late Marshall
McLuhan, the media guru and Trudeau confidant, described the former
prime minister as the ideal candidate for the television age _ cool
and cerebral with ``the perfect mask.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was Trudeau's extraordinary popularity that he occasionally
had to run to escape shrieking legions of female fans.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau's political life was mainly a progression of triumph to
triumph. But his final years were marked by searing personal
tragedy. In 1998, his 23-year-old son Michel was killed in a freak
cross-country skiiing accident, swept into a British Columbia lake
by an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   The loss savaged Trudeau; virtually overnight he was transformed
from a vigorous elder statesman to a seemingly broken man.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement that surrounded Trudeau's ascent to the
leadership of Canada was called ``Trudeaumania,'' and the prime
minister, with his jaunty black beret and red rose boutonniere,
only added to the mystique when in 1971, age 52, he walked down the
aisle with Margaret Sinclair, a 22-year-old flower child whom he
courted in a sizzling romance that had started on the beaches of
Tahiti three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Trudeau's major policies, from massive deficit spending
on ambitious federal social projects to disengagement from the
United States, have largely been reversed since he stepped down
from the leadership for the last time in 1984. His rather haughty
anti-Americanism never sat too well even with his supporters, and
the free trade policies embraced by his successors have moved the
country ever closer into the American economic embrace from which
he sought to lead the country.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau once told an American audience: ``Living next to you is
like sleeping with an elephant. No matter how friendly and
even-tempered the beast, one is affected by every twitch and
grunt.''
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, Trudeau is best remembered for his tough stand
against Quebec's separatist movement as well as for ``patriating''
the Canadian Constitution from Britain _ in effect, making Canada's
federal laws and Charter of Rights and Freedoms, equivalent of the
US Bill of Rights, truly Canadian for the first time. He also
pushed the country into accepting official bilingualism, giving
French equal legal status with the English dominating all of the 10
provinces and three territories except Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Trudeau, despite his French Quebecois heritage,
remains as widely despised in Quebec as he is beloved in English
Canada. Separatist passions still burn in Quebec, and Trudeau is
bitterly recalled in La Belle Province as the hardliner who imposed
martial law on Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   In recent poll, Canadian newspaper editors overwhelming picked
Trudeau as the country's ``newsmaker of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his popularity, Trudeau was an aloof and often arrogant
man; he was known to respond to hecklers with an upraised middle
finger. Even one of his sons spoke of him as distant and
obsessively private. ``I guess he had a kind of lonely life,''
Sacha, 25, told the CBC late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Born Oct. 18, 1919, Trudeau was raised a child of privilege
among the French- and English upper crust in this most cosmopolitan
of Canadian cities. He was the middle of three children, and
received his early education in Jesuit schools.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated with honors in 1943 from the University of Montreal
_ Quebec's most elite French language university _ with a law
degree and three years later earned a degree in political economics
from Harvard. He also studied economics, politics and law at the
London School of Economics and the Ecole des sciences politiques in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   He taught constitutional law at the University of Montreal, and
his leftist writings and association with intellectuals soon
brought him to the attention of the Liberal Party. He first won
election to Parliament in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   As prime minister, he captivated the imagination of the world,
but also presided over a hyper-inflated economy and soaring
unemployment, partly the fruit of his socialist-leaning governmnet
with its emphasis on big government and expensive social programs.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau's marriage to Margaret collapsed in 1977. He later dated
Barbra Streisand and actress Margot Kidder. At age 71, he fathered
a daughter, Sarah Elisabeth, with his last wife, Deborah Coyne,
then 37, a marriage that also ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   When Trudeau finally resigned as prime minister in 1984, these
were his typically enigmatic farewll words: ``It seemed like a good
day to have a last day. ... I went out to see if there were any
signs of my destiny in the sky. But there weren't; there was
nothing but snowflakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TITAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     09-28 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REMEMBER THE TITANS': NOT SUBTLE BUT EFFECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's striking how many of the images that capture America's
struggle to overcome its legacy of racism come from the world of
sports. Think of Jesse Owens at the 1936 Olympics, Jackie Robinson
stealing home, Arthur Ashe triumphing at Wimbledon, Tiger Woods
winning his first major tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're black or white, these moments are likely to put a
lump in your throat and inspire a justified swelling of civic
pride. On the playing field, at least, our better selves can
triumph over our baser instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the Titans,'' based upon a less well-known episode in
the racial history of U.S. sports _ the integration of a
high-school football team in Alexandria, Va., in 1971 _ does an
awful lot of swelling.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of movie in which every big speech or heartfelt
moment _ and aside from a handful of tense showdowns at the line of
scrimmage, there's not much else to see _ is washed in on the flood
tide of a thousand violins. (Trevor Rabin's score, poured over the
action like ketchup, is mitigated a bit by the obligatory
classic-rock song selection. It was nice to hear Leon Russell's
version of ``A Hard Rain's a-Gonna Fall,'' but I think I've heard
``Spirit in the Sky'' enough for one lifetime.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the Titans'' is not a subtle picture: Toward the end,
a black player comes to visit his white teammate _ at first his
bitter rival, now his bosom friend _ in the hospital. The nurse
tries to shoo him away. ``Only kin is allowed,'' she says. ``Can't
you see that's my brother?'' the bedridden warrior replies. All
together now, ``He's got the whole world, in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But football is not a subtle game, and if ``Remember the
Titans'' is corny, it's unabashedly, even generously so. Directed
by Boaz Yakin from a screenplay by Gregory Allen Howard, the film
tells the true story of the T.C. Williams High School Titans in
broad, accessible shorthand.
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington plays Herman Boone, who becomes the Titans'
head coach by fiat of the Alexandria school board, which has also
required the desegregation of Williams' team. Boone's predecessor,
Bill Yoast (Will Patton), one winning season away from election to
the Virginia Football Hall of Fame, swallows his pride, and brushes
off the outrage of many of the town's prominent whites, to stay on
as Boone's assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the two men gradually mutates from
hostile suspicion to grudging respect to loyalty and trust, an
evolution mirrored by the players. The first, and strongest, part
of the movie takes place at a preseason camp, where, under Boone's
relentless drill-sergeant discipline (``This is not a democracy,''
he bellows. ``This is a dictatorship. I am the law.''), they meld
into a cohesive fighting unit.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the scenes _ a locker-room dozens session, in which the
players achieve solidarity by insulting one another's mothers _
feel a bit phony, but Yakin uses the physical intensity of the
sport as a way of telegraphing the changing emotional texture of
the team. Brutal tackles and errant punches have a way of turning
into the hugs and handshakes of genuine camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much male bonding going on here,'' says Petey, the
Titans' cocky running back (Donald Faison). Yes, indeed. Even by
sports movie standards, there aren't a lot of women on the scene.
Boone's wife (Nicole Ari Parker) barely speaks, and white women
show up principally as opponents of the transracial bonding that
comes relatively easily to the football players.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bertier (Ryan Hurst), the white team captain whose initial
resistance to playing alongside blacks does not survive camp, must
contend with the stubborn bigotry of his mother and his girlfriend.
On the first day back at school, the students are greeted by an
angry white mob, including protesters carrying signs that say
``Mothers Against Busing.'' The strongest female presence is
Yoast's perky, blond-ringleted daughter Sheryl (Hayden Penettier),
whose passion for the sport is even more rabid than her dad's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the Titans'' was produced by Jerry Bruckheimer, whose
recent pictures include action blockbusters like ``Armageddon,''
``Bad Boys'' and ''The Rock,'' and it provides the emotional
equivalent to those movies' visceral thrills. Yakin leaps from one
big payoff to the next, and paints his characters in vivid,
cartoonish colors. There's the fat white guy who's too goofy to be
racist (Ethan Suplee); the beefy black guy who sings, jokes and
dispenses inspiration (Earl C. Poitier); and the golden-haired
hippie, a transplant from Southern California, with a throwing arm
that's also pure gold (Kip Pardue).
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the younger members of the cast form a loose, funny,
heartfelt ensemble; Hurst and Wood Harris, as his rival and comrade
Julius Campbell, are especially fine. Washington and Patton are
strong, complex enough presences to make up for the script's
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   The football played by the Titans and their opponents is the
old-fashioned, up-the-middle kind, yielding low final scores and
bruised and muddy players. ``Remember the Titans'' is similarly
solid; its satisfactions are time-tested, a little worn but
nonetheless durable.
</P>
<P>
   The football sequences themselves are in the usual slamming,
grunting Dolby, and if they don't quite shake your molars loose,
the way Oliver Stone's ``Any Given Sunday'' did, you may put a hand
to your chest from time to time to see if your ribs are still in
place. If a heart beats inside those ribs, you'll also find a lump
in your throat and an overwhelming urge to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBER THE TITANS
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Boaz Yakin; written by Gregory Allen Howard;
director of photography, Philippe Rousselot; edited by Michael
Tronick; music by Trevor Rabin; production designer, Deborah Evans;
produced by Jerry Bruckheimer and Chad Oman; released by Walt
Disney Pictures/Jerry Bruckheimer Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Denzel Washington (Coach Boone), Will Patton (Coach
Yoast), Wood Harris (Big Ju), Ryan Hurst (Gary Bertier), Donald
Faison (Petey), Craig Kirkwood (Rev), Ethan Suplee (Lewis Lastik),
Earl C. Poitier (Blue Stanton), Kip Pardue (Sunshine), Hayden
Panettiere (Sheryl Yoast) and Nicole Ari Parker (Carol Boone).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 113 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the Titans'' is rated PG (Parental guidance
suggested). It includes some salty football-coach lingo and some
rough gridiron action.
</P>
</TEXT>
