<SLUG> BC-BIAS-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON FIRM NAMED IN RACIAL BIAS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Pa.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keane Inc., a Boston-based information technology company,
subjected its black employees in Philadelphia to racial
discrimination and harassment, the US Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission alleged in a lawsuit filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also accuses Keane of retaliating against employees who
complained and says that one employee was subjected to a racially
offensive Ku Klux Klan drawing while on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in federal court in Boston, also claims the
employee, Michael Randolph, 43, of Atlanta, was called names and
assigned to less lucrative accounts due to his race.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph is no longer with Keane.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Vale, vice president of Keane, a leading IT services firm
that does about $1 billion worth of business annually, said Keane
is regarded as ``a good company, a fair company'' and that it will
contest the suit vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can not comment on the specifics of the complaint because
we have not seen the complaint,'' Vale said. ``However, I can tell
you that we are very distressed that the EEOC seems to believe we
discriminate. We are aware, in general, of some of the EEOC's
allegations _ and we believe they have no merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Vale said he did not know how many minorities Keane employs.
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC's complaint did not spell out how many employees in
addition to Randolph were allegedly affected.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Bissell, an EEOC supervisory attorney, said the agency
sued after investigating a complaint from Randolph. The EEOC took
depositions from other employees who worked at Keane over the last
three years and claimed they had not been treated fairly, Bissell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We determined . . . there was cause to believe laws were
violated, but we were unable to resolve the case in conciliation
meetings,'' Bissell said. ``We are hoping this lawsuit will act as
a deterrent and send a message to other employers.''
</P>
<P>
   Since September 1997, the suit alleges, Keane has discriminated
against blacks by permitting racial epithets, assigning them fewer
accounts, and issuing their paychecks late.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks unspecified financial penalties and back pay.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Randolph said he was an account executive at Keane
from July 1998 to January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three things drove me to leave,'' he said, ``and one was a KKK
drawing that was on a white board during my employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suggested to them that they take one of those K's down or
put another one up, because I found it offensive. But the person
whose office the drawing was in said I was being overly sensitive,
and so did his boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Randolph also alleges that a lucrative account was taken away
from him. ``I was told the client did not want to work with a black
man, and that I was better suited for accounts in inner-city
Philadelphia, as opposed to suburban accounts. After that, a series
of accounts were taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Randolph, a graduate of the University of Delaware, is now a
self-employed computer marketing consultant in Altanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2011EDT &QL; 
