<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUNYAN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNYAN CONTINUES TO SURPRISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ It's terribly tiring racing one 1,500
meters, much less three in four days. If there's a silver lining
behind all that sweat, it's that runners have plenty of time to
work out the kinks in their race strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Marla Runyan went out much too slowly in the Olympic heats of
the 1,500 Wednesday and was the second-to-last runner to advance to
the semifinal. Having learned her lesson, the Camarillo High
graduate set the early pace Thursday in a field that included her
U.S. teammate and gold-medal contender Suzy Favor-Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Favor-Hamilton passed her midway through the race and four other
runners caught Runyan on the last curve. When she finished sixth in
4-minutes, 06.14 seconds, Runyan was sure her Olympic experience
was over.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old started down the snaking line of international
television reporters, leaving a Frenchman to deliver the good news:
Nobody in the second semifinal surpassed Runyan's time, which was a
.3-second improvement over her third-place effort from the U.S.
Trials in July.
</P>
<P>
   So Runyan will run once more, in Saturday's 12-woman final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky I got to the semifinal. Now I'm lucky to get to the
final,'' Runyan said. ``I'm so excited. I'm just going to run my
heart out and enjoy running against the best in the world. I'll
have to run fast; otherwise you'll never see me in the camera
frame.''
</P>
<P>
   While Runyan was talking, competitors from the men's and women's
Olympic exhibition wheelchair races rolled by her in the mixed
zone. Runyan felt right at home, having starred at the Paralympics
in 1996 as a legally blind athlete.
</P>
<P>
   A degenerative eye disease has narrowed her vision to 20/300 in
the left eye and 20/400 in the right eye. Runyan is the first
Paralympian to make the quantum leap to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to feel pressure about that,'' Runyan said, ``and
then I thought about it and turned it around. It's not pressure,
it's an opportunity. I have the opportunity to show kids all over
the world who are losing their vision what life can be like. I hope
parents out there will say, `I'm going to let my child be whatever
she wants to be.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The people who are so focused on her vision are missing the
really neat story, in Runyan's humble opinion. Runyan wanted to be
an Olympic heptathlete, but after placing 10th at the 1996 U.S.
Trials on the strength of a terrific 800 meters, she decided to
concentrate on middle-distance running.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really crazy, isn't it?'' Runyan said. ``I'm really glad
I'm not throwing the shot put anymore. To go from being a
heptathlete to an Olympic finalist in the 1,500, I think, is a
pretty amazing story in itself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0367 </DOCNO>
