<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GROPES FOR THE RIGHT STRATEGY IN MICHIGAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ Last Feb. 22, Gov. George W. Bush lost the
Michigan Republican primary to Sen. John McCain of Arizona, thanks
to a notably poor showing among independents, moderates and women.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months later, in this same pivotal Great Lakes state, he
is again having trouble attracting independents, moderates and
women in his race against Vice President Al Gore. The race is close
here, with Gore very narrowly ahead. Demographically very similar
to the United States as a whole, Michigan has seen a Bush lead, a
Gore bounce and now a bit of a Bush comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Bush arrived in the state for a pair of fund raisers
Thursday night in Oakland County, just north of Detroit, and an
appearance Friday in Saginaw, he was still searching for ways to
ratchet his campaign up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Republicans have plenty of suggestions to offer him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to cloak himself in McCain in this state,'' said
Jerry Roe, a former executive director of the state GOP, who backed
McCain in the primary. ``The moderates and the independents were
terribly disappointed when he chose Dick Cheney for vice president.
A town hall meeting with McCain, maybe two, in crucial counties
like Macomb and Oakland, might do the trick.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican officials think Bush should carry the fight
more directly to the vice president by attacking him as a threat to
the auto industry, which is still Michigan's lifeblood (although
much of the action has switched from the Big Three automakers to
dozens of small, innovative engineering outfits along the
expressways fanning out from Detroit.)
</P>
<P>
   Anything that cut into Gore's union support here would be
invaluable to the Texan. Almost a third of Michigan's likely voters
live in union households, and Gore leads among them by 55 percent
to 28 percent, according to a New York Times/CBS News poll of 1,145
registered voters between Sept. 22 and 25. Bush leads among
non-union voters.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which had a margin of sampling error of three
percentage points, showed Gore ahead by seven points among all
registered voters, but only four points ahead, 45-41, among likely
voters. And if the numbers are adjusted to account for past turnout
patterns, the race is even.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ballenger, who publishes ``Inside Michigan Politics,'' a
highly regarded newsletter, said that Bush's ``character'' campaign
against Gore had failed, and that the focus of the campaign had
switched to issues. On the most important ones, he asserted, the
vice president has the advantage, with ``a more understandable
prescription-drugs plan and a tax plan that's selling because it
helps pay down the deficit and puts more resources into the kind of
programs that people here want.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, interviews with voters in the state suggest,
Gore has been damaged by a tendency to exaggerate or even to
fabricate, and his staunch advocacy of protecting the environment
can cut both ways.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Earth in the Balance'' Gore described the internal
combustion engine as ``a mortal threat to the security of every
nation _ more clearly than that of any military enemy we are again
likely to confront.'' Sensing a big opening for Bush, Rusty Hills,
the Michigan Republican chairman, who is a close associate of Gov.
John Engler, said on Wednesday: ``That is just plain nutty. If we
can tell every autoworker Gore said that, we can win this
election.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to do so would be in television commercials, but 35
percent of Michigan voters, the Times/CBS poll shows, already view
Bush's ads as negative, compared with 21 percent who view Gore's as
negative. Probably not coincidentally, 48 percent said the vice
president's commercials had given them an improved image of him,
while only 32 percent thought better of Bush after watching his
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   As in a half-dozen other states, voters here have been
completely immersed in the campaign, though the effect is not yet
clear. Well over three-quarters of the respondents in the polls
said they had seen commercials for the presidential nominees _ a
surprisingly high figure more than five weeks from Election Day _
and the news is jam-packed with politics. Yet four out of ten of
each man's backers expressed reservations about their vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheer volume of advertising, back to back, day after day,
the constant political palaver, may have reached some kind of limit
of influence,'' said Hugh McDiarmid, political columnist for The
Detroit Free Press. ``It may be a wash. At any rate, nothing is
producing any marked changes so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this kind of situation, I think the debates could count a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   David W. Rohde, a political scientist at Michigan State
University in East Lansing, argued that this election differs from
many in the last two decades in its fluidity. In 1980, with an
unpopular incumbent, Jimmy Carter, the result was more or less
foreordained, he said, as it was again in 1996, with a popular
incumbent, Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he said, ``with no incumbent and both candidates
relatively moderate in relation to their parties, you get the
feeling that nothing is locked in for the 10 percent that drifts
back and forth _ exactly the kind of race where the outcome could
be affected by a dramatic event like the debates, especially the
first one.''
</P>
<P>
   That will take place next Tuesday in Boston, with two more
later.
</P>
<P>
   The uncommitted and uncertain voters in this state tend to be
ticket-splitters, a phenomenon evident as long ago as 1964, when
President Johnson, a Democrat, carried the state by a million
votes, while George Romney, a Republican, was winning the
governor's race by 300,000 votes. So local politicians would not be
even slightly surprised to see Gore and Sen. Spencer Abraham, a
Republican, pulling off the same trick in November.
</P>
<P>
   But in other respects Michigan has changed radically. The state
is no longer singing the Rust Belt blues, and its population, 9.3
million in 1990, is now approaching 10 million. Both its politics
and its economy, long static, have entered a dynamic era, marked by
widespread innovation and reform.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
