<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAHAL COULD LEAD AMERICAN REVOLUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time when only Michael Andretti and Jimmy Vasser have
full-time rides in CART, is it any wonder there are no American
drivers competing in Formula One?
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, does Bernie Ecclestone's ``Flying Circus''
actually need an All-American boy to ensure F1's continued success
at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway?
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the enthusiastic, record-setting crowd that attended
the inaugural SAP United States Grand Prix on Sunday, the answer to
the latter is a resounding no. Drivers at both ends of the grid _
from double world champions Michael Schumacher of Germany and Mika
Hakkinen of Finland to backmarkers Pedro de la Rosa of Spain and
Gaston Mazzacane of Argentina _ seemed genuinely stunned by their
receptions in Indy, home to American oval-track racing and its
larger-than-anything heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the lack of an American driver in F1 was a topic that
took on a life of its own at the Speedway. Michael Andretti's
aborted 1993 season with Team McLaren remains the last shot given
an American. Andretti blew it, but there were extenuating
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Recall that Andretti was teamed with Brazil's Ayrton Senna, a
three-time world champion and arguably the best F1 driver ever.
Suffice it to say that team orders were not going to be an issue
for Ron Dennis, McLaren's team principal.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many seasoned F1 observers still maintain that Andretti's
refusal to move from Nazareth, Pa., to England was a mistake, one
that effectively cast him as a rent-a-driver in the eyes of the men
who regularly toiled over their cars.
</P>
<P>
   But Dennis said Mikey's biggest fault simply may have been lousy
timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no driver that's going to climb into F1 and be an
immediate success story,'' Dennis said. ``When Michael came to our
team, it was at a time when we had the most sophisticated Formula
One car ever made. We were reprogramming the suspension several
times in every corner, an extremely complex process to optimize the
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to learn the circuits, learn to drive the car, and in
the end it was quite a handful for him. And it was, indeed, very
difficult for him to come to terms with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Time has taken the sting out of Andretti's failure to emulate
father Mario, the 1978 F1 world driving champion. And events of the
last week indicate that Europe's freeze on even considering
Americans is beginning to thaw.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's decision to hire Bobby Rahal, the Championship Auto
Racing Teams' interim president and chief executive officer, to
lead the company's Jaguar Racing program for the next three years
looms as a potentially huge break for an American aspiring to get
noticed by F1's powerbrokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep, I'd like to see an American driver make it in the
big-time,'' said Neil Ressler, chairman and current CEO of Jaguar
Racing, and like Rahal, a native of Ohio. ``I think in the
foreseeable future that will require that that American driver go
compete in Europe. That's the competition, those are the venues
that produce world champion drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ressler noted that Jag Racing includes a Formula Three team,
with two empty seats for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we develop our Formula Three program, we'll give Americans
_ maybe even this year _ a crack at it to see whether they can get
started,'' Ressler said. ``I've asked Bobby to think about whether
we would want to test an American driver among the collection.
We're going to try to hold a seat, at least one seat, in the open
test. If an American comes in and is best, he gets the drive.
That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ressler warned, however, that the journey into F1 for any
American likely will take two years. Five years might prove to be
more realistic. Whatever, some current F1 stars are curious to see
how it all turns out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's different,'' said Hakkinen, referring to the
Andretti episode. ``And if one driver makes a mistake, you don't
want to say every driver makes a mistake. But American drivers ...
they need to change their way of life, the mentality, the
preparation to be in grand prix racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Irishman Eddie Irvine, lead driver at Jaguar, said it is easy
for talented Americans to race and live quite comfortably in the
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is big enough to be its own self-contained thing,''
Irvine said. ``But whatever way the sport is organized here, they
ain't coming up through. There's got to be good guys here.
Americans are good at every sport there is, so there must be good
drivers here, as well.''
SPOTLIGHT ON...
Labonte rolling toward Cup title
With a minimum of fuss, native Texan Bobby Labonte is barreling
toward his first NASCAR Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   His fifth-place finish in Dover, Del., on Sunday allowed Labonte
to open a 249-point lead over seven-time Cup champion Dale
Earnhardt with seven races remaining. Labonte, younger brother of
two-time Cup champion Terry Labonte, took over the top spot with a
second-place finish at the California Speedway on April 30.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte has posted an amazing 15 top-five and 19 top-10 finishes
in 27 starts in the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac Grand Prix.
If Labonte finishes sixth or better in each of the remaining races,
he will clinch the championship regardless of any other driver's
performance. Five of the remaining seven events will be contested
on tracks visited earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Those venues, with Labonte's finish first time around:
Martinsville Speedway, 12th; Lowe's Motor Speedway, second;
Talladega Superspeedway, 21st; North Carolina Speedway, first;
Atlanta Motor Speedway, second.
</P>
<P>
   True to his roots, Labonte said the toughest thing he has had to
deal with lately are the never-ending questions about this title
quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, I haven't really seen a whole lot different,
to be honest with you,'' said Labonte, who drives for car owner Joe
Gibbs. ``It's just what you want to make out of it. I haven't made
anything out of it, other than that it's a whole lot better leading
than it is running second because it's more exciting. You're
focused more on one thing than on other things maybe. Trying to
play catch-up, you've got to think of a lot of things as you're
trying to proceed forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's me personally. Not everybody has the same comment. But
this is a lot more fun. I've enjoyed it. I don't think it's been
any big deal. Not saying it won't change because it probably will.
But so far I can't say that I've seen anything that's been harder,
been more difficult or been frustrating or challenging or anything.
It's been focus, focus, focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs said he likes the mindset of this team, in that it is
being rewarded for its hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the last two years it's pretty much been the
same,'' said Gibbs, recalling that Labonte finished second to
reigning champion Dale Jarrett by 201 points in 1999. ``We realize
that you only get opportunities like this every now and then. You
only get a driver that is at his peak for so many years, and the
team and everything to go around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it started last year. That was the first time we could
seriously say that we raced for a championship. We could win races
and everything, but to seriously be a championship contender _ that
came last year. We always look at each week saying, `Is there
something we can do to improve the team? Is there anybody we can
add? Is there any way we can make ourselves a better race team?'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been going on for the last two years.''
PIT STOPS CART invades Houston The most closely contested driver's
title chase in the 22-year history of the Championship Auto Racing
Teams is scheduled to resume on the streets of Houston this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Only 19 points separate leader Gil de Ferran from sixth-place
Kenny Brack after 17 events heading to the 1.527-mile temporary
street circuit set up for the Texaco/Havoline Grand Prix of
Houston. A maximum of 66 points are available in the remaining
three events in Houston, Australia and at Fontana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tracy, the defending race champion, is fourth overall with
122 points, 15 behind De Ferran. With 20 points available for a
victory, Tracy could take the lead with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Dario Franchitti, Tracy's teammate, won the inaugural Houston
race in 1998. Tracy led 85 of 100 laps last year to continue the
domination for Team KOOL Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``The engineers have hit on a setup for the street circuits, and
we've won Houston two years in a row,'' said Tracy, a three-time
winner this season. ``I intend to do everything I can to make it
three.'' Ray staying put Plano's Greg Ray says some driving
opportunities outside the Indy Racing Northern Light Series have
crossed his path lately. But Ray is planning to return to Team
Menard in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm signed and ready to go,'' said Ray, the 1999 series
champion who failed to duplicate his dominating form this year.
``There's still a lot of interesting opportunities that are arising
late in the season, and I don't think you never say never. But I
would say my plans are pretty well focused on staying with Menard
for the next several years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray is in the second year of a five-year contract with
Wisconsin-based businessman John Menard, with each subsequent year
an option. The team suffered a shake-up when Thomas Knapp, Ray's
longtime friend and Menard's team manager, left the organization in
early August. Knapp has been replaced by Mitch Davis, formerly of
Team Purex.
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Davis tested for two days, including a full-race
simulation, at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth last week in
preparation for the season-ending Excite 500 on Oct. 15. Mosley
seeks one more FIA president Max Mosley is planning to seek a third
four-year term when his current term ends in October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that would definitely be it,'' Mosley said at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway, site of the inaugural SAP United
States Grand Prix. ``At the end of that term, I would be 65. That
is quite a good time to stop. It's all right to go into the
driver's briefing when they are old enough to be your children, but
not your grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent criticism directed at Mosley by Formula One
powerbrokers Ron Dennis of McLaren/Mercedes and Frank Williams of
BMW Williams, Mosley apparently has no fear of being voted out of
office by the FIA's 123-member countries. Woods mark milestone
Currently celebrating their 50th season in stock-car racing, the
Wood Brothers will field a car for the 1,000th time in NASCAR's top
series during the NAPA AutoCare 500 at Martinsville Speedway on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the occasion, Elliott Sadler's No. 21 Citgo Ford Taurus
will feature a solid red paint scheme in honor of team founder Glen
Wood. Based in Stuart, Va., Wood Brothers Racing has won 96 NASCAR
races. The last word ``We started racing in 1950 with a car we
bought for $50. We put No. 50 on the side of the car because it
just seemed like the right thing to do. Now, here we are 50 years
later.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Glen Wood, NASCAR pioneer, on the team's 1,000th start Sunday
