<HEADER>
A5666 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MICH-CAMPAIGN-ART-2ND     09-28 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-CAMPAIGN-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PONTIAC, Mich.: and reform. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The change is particularly noticeable here in the belt of
suburbs, exurbs and edge cities north of Detroit. Macomb County is
no longer dominated by the party-switching Democrats who helped
Ronald Reagan win a majority of the union vote in 1984, and Oakland
County, the state's second largest, after Wayne (Detroit), is no
longer as automatically Republican as it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fate in Michigan may well depend on how he does in Macomb
and Oakland, both of which were carried by his father in 1988 and
1992. Former Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas lost both, and Michigan, four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sander Levin, a Democrat whose district includes parts of
both counties, said he thought that Gore had ``managed to hack his
way through most of the thicket of negative Clinton associations,
like Monica and Whitewater, which has allowed prosperity to pop
through as the leading issue.'' In his area, he said, ``virtually
everything has gotten better for most people, though not everyone,
over the last eight years, from better schools to better race
relations to considerably better pay and conditions on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, Levin said, only 10 percent of the
children in Macomb County went to college, and their parents felt
left out of the American success story. Now, more than half get
degrees, he said, and their parents ``have joined the rest of us in
the scramble of middle-income life.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. William G. Milliken, a moderate Republican, said he
thought that despite Bush's promise of ``compassionate
conservatism,'' Bush was having trouble fitting into the pattern of
economic conservatism and moderation on social issues that seems to
succeed best in the suburbs. Specifically, Milliken mentioned as
problems Bush's opposition to campaign finance reform, as espoused
by McCain, and his steadfast opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Engler ran Bush's campaign against McCain, promising to erect a
firewall against the insurgent. He and the wall were torched. Now
he is once again at the helm, with assistance from Warren K.
Erdman, a former aide to Sen. Christopher S. Bond of Missouri, who
was sent into the state when Bush began slipping. But this time,
Engler's profile is lower.
</P>
<P>
   Rohde of Michigan State said the best the governor could do for
Bush in any event was ``some small influence on the Republican
turnout, roughly equal to the impact of the labor unions on the
other side.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Bush has promised larger public roles for, and better
coordination with, Republican governors in two neighboring Midwest
states _ Tommy G. Thompson of Wisconsin and Bob Taft of Ohio. But
so far at least, there has been no evidence that he is planning to
push Engler out front.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush doesn't want to turn this into another referendum
on a controversial governor,'' said Ballenger, the newsletter
publisher, ``and pull the independents out to cast protest votes
for Al Gore in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, a ballot proposal that would legalize the use of state
funds for private and parochial schools through a system of
vouchers has complicated the Michigan situation for the national
Republican ticket. Engler opposes vouchers, which has split
Republican ranks wide open; Elisabeth DeVos, who strongly supports
them, resigned as the state party chairman in order to back the
campaign for the ballot initiative, which is known as Proposal 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS poll shows 2-1 backing for vouchers. Private
schools were explicitly prohibited from using them in a 1970
amendment to the state constitution. Television campaigns, pro and
con, are just beginning, but the Roman Catholic church, under
Cardinal Adam Maida of Detroit, is said to have set aside $1.5
million to support the proposal. Hundreds of thousands of yard
signs have already been ordered by opponents of the proposal, so it
seems inevitable that the issue will soon loom large in voters'
minds.
</P>
<P>
   But Dick Cheney did not even mention the subject in a speech in
nearby Troy on Wednesday, and Bush, an eager advocate of vouchers,
was not expected to use the ``v-word'' here either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
