<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIMINATE-OIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spot budget story OIL-PRESSURE (f) will not move in
tonight's Boston Globe file.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WEST-WING-1001-COX     09-28 1833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-WING-1001-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR NBC'S ``WEST WING,'' ART ISN'T FAR FROM REALITY
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (e)
entertainment categories
 &HT;    Advance for release Sunday, Oct. 1
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He's one of the best known media figures in the
nation, but that didn't cut any ice with a local judge when Joe
Lockhart showed up for jury duty earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Learning that the case would likely last three months, the
normally unflappable Lockhart struggled for a tactful way to say
that he couldn't take that much time away from his job as White
House press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a lawyer in the case approached the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge, he's C.J.,'' the attorney explained, as the judge
suddenly nodded knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, 'Oh, I get it,''' Lockhart recalled, explaining how
the mere mention of C.J. Cregg, the fictional White House press
secretary in the popular television series ``West Wing,'' cleared
up matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got me off the hook,'' shrugged Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   In a company town whose business is politics, it's often hard to
tell where real life ends and theater begins.
</P>
<P>
   The line has become even more blurred for White House staffers,
though, in the year since NBC's ``West Wing'' took the airwaves by
storm, popularizing a bevy of fictional characters whose real-life
counterparts find much to admire, and even envy, about the
television versions of their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a much harder job,'' Lockhart, a former television
news producer, joked in a comparison to actress Allison Janney, who
plays Cregg in the ``West Wing'' cast. ``I can't believe she got
the Emmy.''
</P>
<P>
   Janney's Emmy for best supporting actress in a television drama
series was one of nine of the coveted awards ``West Wing'' won
Sept. 10 for its debut season last year.
</P>
<P>
   Its special two-hour season premiere airs Wednesday night. It
picks up on an episode that closed last season amid the terrifying
mayhem of an attack on the presidential entourage by skinheads with
pistols.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional assault takes place as ``West Wing'' President
Josiah Bartlet exits a town hall-style meeting with college
students at the Newseum in Rosslyn, Va., just across the Potomac
River from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers will learn Wednesday night the answer to the question
left hanging in the season finale _ who got shot, a matter of
widespread speculation in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Toby,'' suggested one White House staffer, speaking on
the kind of background basis ordinarily reserved for inside gossip
on the status of high-stakes congressional battles, senior staff
changes or forward-leaning news on President Clinton's future
travel plans.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Richard Schiff received an Emmy nominated for his
portrayal of Toby Ziegler, the bleary-eyed but brilliant
communications director on the ``West Wing'' staff.
</P>
<P>
   The real life White House communications director, Loretta
Ucelli, cut the striking figure of a starlet the other day,
standing quietly in the shadows as her boss, President Clinton,
faced the cameras in an auditorium in the Old Executive Office
Building, where the bulk of the White House senior staff actually
works.
</P>
<P>
   Polite yet professional, Ucelli is a far cry from the
perpetually rumpled and easily agitated Ziegler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have some similarities,'' though, she said. ``We're both
big Yankee fans.''
</P>
<P>
   White House staffers generally describe Ucelli's job as less
knee-jerk political than Zeigler's character. But again, Ucelli
finds much in common with her television counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy who has to step back a bit and take a look at an
issue that's coming down the pike, and that's similar for me,''
Ucelli said.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the fast and often unpredictable pace of White
House life reflected in ``West Wing'' strikes too close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president just walked in,'' real life White House
speechwriter Josh Gottheimer also likened by some to Zeigler's
character interjects during a quick phone interview. ``Can I call
you back?''
</P>
<P>
   The star of ``West Wing,'' veteran actor Martin Sheen, plays
Bartlet, a New Hampshire Democrat descended from a signer of the
Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Smart, funny and decisive, Bartlet's character has much in
common with the real thing _ President Clinton _ but Sheen has said
he's modeled the role more after former President Jimmy Carter, a
move reflected in the lofty moral posture Bartlet often assumes on
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlet's close, almost fatherly relationship with his personal
aide, Charlie Young, played by the actor Dule Hill, is largely on
target, said Kris Engskov, who spent seven years as a White House
assistant, including two and a half as Clinton's personal aide.
</P>
<P>
   Around a year ago, in fact, Hill and Engskov met over a brunch
arranged by Dee Dee Myers, Clinton's one-time press secretary and
now a consultant to ``West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked a lot about the job and how a young person in that
job would operate around some of the people I had to operate
around,'' said Engskov, who left the White House last summer to
work for a venture capital company in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put a lot of thought into the role,'' said Engskov. ``He's
kind of fascinated by the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, in fact, Hill arranged with his current White
House counterpart, presidential aide Doug Band, for an insider's
tour of Air Force One, while Clinton was in Los Angeles for some
political fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy,'' Hill told reporters after touring the world's
most famous plane, sitting in the president's chair and copping a
small signature box of M&AMP;Ms given out aboard the presidential
aircraft. ``I can't believe I was actually on the real Air Force
One.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hill's character appears to have been closely modeled on
Engskov, there is one striking difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He dates the president's daughter on the show. I always
thought that was a bad idea, partly for job security reasons,''
said Engskov, whose cool blue eyes and boyish good looks helped
endear him to some members of the White House staff, though he
regarded First Daughter Chelsea as strictly off limits.
</P>
<P>
   Chief of Staff John Podesta has much in common with his ``West
Wing'' counterpart, Leo McGarry, played by actor John Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the television Chief of Staff, Podesta is a close
political confidant to Clinton and is the man in charge of keeping
the real West Wing characters in some semblance of orbit, while
keeping the president in touch with the pulse of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The template, though, only goes so far.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer plays a straight-talking, combat-hardened manager who is
fiercely loyal to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta has a no-nonsense side to him _ he's even given his
split personality a name, his ``evil twin, Skippy'' _ and he's not
afraid to take his tough side public, as he did two weeks ago in
threatening Japan with sanctions for its seasonal whale hunts.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta favors, though, a more playful air and a mischievous
sense of humor, taking particular delight in lampooning his
Republican foes.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, for instance, Chief of Staff Podesta led his
office team for a three-mile morning road race near the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Team Podesta was ready to suit up in T-shirts that had the words
``The Lame Ducks'' air-brushed across the back. The day before the
race, though, The New York Times broke the story about the
subliminal message _ ``Rats'' _ flashing ominously across the
screen of a campaign ad by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing the moment, Podesta pulled his joggers' uniforms and
sent them back to the shop, where a skillful artisan sprayed a line
through ``The Lame Ducks'' and wrote underneath, ``The Rat Pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ``West Wing'' characters lack a precise White House
analog.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Bradley Whiteford, for example, plays the ruthlessly
calculating political tactician Josh Lyman, youthful deputy chief
of staff.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Podesta has two deputies _ Maria Echaveste and
Stephen Ricchetti _ both of whom spend more time on policy missions
than pouncing at the political jugular.
</P>
<P>
   Other ``West Wing'' characters are something like hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Rob Lowe, for instance, plays deputy communications
director Sam Seaborn.
</P>
<P>
   His character is likened by many White House staffers to two
people.
</P>
<P>
   One is former political strategist Doug Sosnik, a diminutive
senior aide who stuck so close to Clinton over the course of his
impeachment travails that the White House press corps nicknamed him
``Mini Me''. The other is Sidney Blumenthal, the elegant confidant
of First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton who has played a key role in
helping to manage the White House image and message machinery that
seeks to cast the Clintons in the best possible public light.
</P>
<P>
   White House staffers tend to watch ``West Wing'' when they're in
town and able to get home by its 9 p.m. air time _ which isn't
often for many of them. And, not surprisingly, they generally
approve of the favorable light in which their characters are cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had made C.J. a clown, people would think I'm a
clown,'' said Lockhart. ``But she's smart, she's plugged in and she
tries to get it right, and, what's the most realistic thing, she
doesn't always get it right, because that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart concedes, though, that issues seldom get worked out
with the dispatch portrayed on the television show. Few viewers
would tune in, he said, if the script mimicked reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot slower and a lot uglier,'' in the White House, he
said. ``And I mean that literally and figuratively. The people are
a lot slower and a lot uglier.''
</P>
<P>
   What White House staffers like most about ``West Wing'' is the
positive image it portrays of public servants in earnest pursuit of
the public good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really as glamorous as the TV show, but we like
working here because we feel that there is generally a sense of
purpose to the place,'' said Lockhart's deputy, Jake Siewert, who
stages his own debut this week as Clinton's press secretary,
replacing Lockhart, who left the White House on Friday to look for
work in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Siewert rises to stretch his lanky frame as much as possible in
the closet-like hovel that deputy White House spokesmen use as an
office behind the press briefing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their offices are a lot nicer,'' Siewert said of the ``West
Wing'' set.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Buddy, the president's three-year-old chocolate
Labrador Retriever, wandered down to Siewert's office and scrounged
outside his office door, much like reporters often do, in search of
scraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they don't have a dog,'' Jake said, pausing for a moment's
reflection. ``They should have a dog. It could make a good plot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans can be reached by e-mail at: Bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
