<P>
   Actor Rob Lowe, for instance, plays deputy communications
director Sam Seaborn.
</P>
<P>
   His character is likened by many White House staffers to two
people.
</P>
<P>
   One is former political strategist Doug Sosnik, a diminutive
senior aide who stuck so close to Clinton over the course of his
impeachment travails that the White House press corps nicknamed him
``Mini Me''. The other is Sidney Blumenthal, the elegant confidant
of First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton who has played a key role in
helping to manage the White House image and message machinery that
seeks to cast the Clintons in the best possible public light.
</P>
<P>
   White House staffers tend to watch ``West Wing'' when they're in
town and able to get home by its 9 p.m. air time _ which isn't
often for many of them. And, not surprisingly, they generally
approve of the favorable light in which their characters are cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had made C.J. a clown, people would think I'm a
clown,'' said Lockhart. ``But she's smart, she's plugged in and she
tries to get it right, and, what's the most realistic thing, she
doesn't always get it right, because that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart concedes, though, that issues seldom get worked out
with the dispatch portrayed on the television show. Few viewers
would tune in, he said, if the script mimicked reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot slower and a lot uglier,'' in the White House, he
said. ``And I mean that literally and figuratively. The people are
a lot slower and a lot uglier.''
</P>
<P>
   What White House staffers like most about ``West Wing'' is the
positive image it portrays of public servants in earnest pursuit of
the public good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really as glamorous as the TV show, but we like
working here because we feel that there is generally a sense of
purpose to the place,'' said Lockhart's deputy, Jake Siewert, who
stages his own debut this week as Clinton's press secretary,
replacing Lockhart, who left the White House on Friday to look for
work in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Siewert rises to stretch his lanky frame as much as possible in
the closet-like hovel that deputy White House spokesmen use as an
office behind the press briefing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their offices are a lot nicer,'' Siewert said of the ``West
Wing'' set.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Buddy, the president's three-year-old chocolate
Labrador Retriever, wandered down to Siewert's office and scrounged
outside his office door, much like reporters often do, in search of
scraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they don't have a dog,'' Jake said, pausing for a moment's
reflection. ``They should have a dog. It could make a good plot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans can be reached by e-mail at: Bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
