<HEADER>
A5674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MASS-MOBSTER-INDICT-(     09-28 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-MOBSTER-INDICT-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INDICTS FOR MURDERS A MOBSTER IT PROTECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Federal prosecutors unsealed an indictment Thursday
charging Boston's most infamous, and elusive, mobster and his
longtime associate with involvement in the deaths of 21 people
between them _ from rivals to strangers in the wrong place at the
wrong time to their own girlfriends _ in ``a reign of intimidation
and murder that spanned some 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, said U.S. Attorney Donald K. Stern, the main
defendant, James ``Whitey'' Bulger, had never been charged with
murder, though he was indicted on racketeering charges in 1995. But
in the course of a long and complex investigation, Stern said,
``Layer upon layer of myth, fear and protection have been stripped
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that protection came from the FBI. Bulger, 71, and his
longtime associate, Stephen J. Flemmi, 66, were ``top-echelon
informants'' from the early 1970s through the mid-1990s, the agency
has acknowledged, and helped vanquish the local arm of La Cosa
Nostra. Also charged in the indictment is Kevin P. O'Neil, another
associate of Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, prosecutors now say, was that while the FBI was
protecting Bulger, Flemmi and their Irish-dominated mob from other
law enforcement agencies to keep their information coming, the two
men were committing crimes as frightening as anything their Italian
rivals might have contemplated. The case has raised serious
questions about the often-murky relationships between law
enforcement officials and criminal informers.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi is in prison awaiting trial since 1995 on racketeering
charges. The relationship between Flemmi, Bulger and the FBI
emerged in Flemmi's pre-trial motions, because he has argued that
the FBI promised him and Bulger immunity for any crimes short of
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger has been on the run since 1995, and is considered one of
the most wanted men in America, with $250,000 offered for his
capture. The authorities say he may be using the name of Mark
Shapeton. He is believed to be traveling with his girlfriend,
Catherine Greig, who was reportedly seen in January in Fountain
Valley, Calif., having her hair done.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A bit more than a year ago, the outlook for prosecutors appeared
bleak, and critics said they might not be able to make their case
against Flemmi and Bulger stand up. But Stern said Thursday that
they had made great progress, in particular by making deals with
associates of Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, at least two associates, John Martorano, a
confessed hit man, and Kevin Weeks, who has been described as
Bulger's top lieutenant, have been given deals for crimes of their
own in exchange for information. With it, the authorities unearthed
five bodies of victims that they are now charging Bulger and Flemmi
with murdering. Thursday, excavation was still under way as
authorities searched for a body in the Boston suburb of Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's indictment charged Bulger and Flemmi with committing
a pattern of violence meant to protect their criminal dealings.
Their crimes ranged, prosecutors said, from murdering potential
witnesses against them to corrupting law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also says that the two killed their girlfriends
because they thought their knowledge posed a threat; other victims
were killed, the indictment charges, to gain control of their
business, to eliminate rivals, and, in one case, out of revenge for
losing a fight. It also accuses them of drug-trafficking,
extortion, money laundering and more.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said Thursday that the crimes in the indictment were not
eligible for the death penalty in Massachusetts and the federal
system, but that prosecutors would seek life in prison for both
men.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth J. Fishman, Flemmi's lawyer, said he could not comment
because he had not yet discussed the indictment with his client.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more damaging accusations surface about Bulger,
officials acknowledge that the FBI's protection of him looks worse
and worse. The case had already prompted sweeping internal
investigations of the bureau's Boston branch and a months-long
policy review by the Justice Department, which has moved to tighten
its rules for handling such informers.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, prosecutors also indicted a retired FBI agent,
John J. Connolly Jr., accusing him of racketeering and, in
particular, of warning Bulger of his impending arrest in time for
him to escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
