<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5678 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ABORTION-PILL-REACT-N     09-28 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-PILL-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA DECISION ON ABORTION PILL OPENS A RIFT BETWEEN PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (with FDA-ABORTION-PILL) 
 By ROBIN TONER     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Abortion rights supporters celebrated a long-sought
victory on Thursday, with the Food and Drug Administration's
approval of the abortion pill RU-486, but acknowledged that it
could be an exceedingly fragile one.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents denounced the administration and the agency
for pushing through a drug ``that will take lives instead of saving
them,'' as Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., put it. They vowed to keep
fighting, legislatively and politically.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed on one thing: the drug agency's ruling
highlights the stakes for November's election, with stark
differences between the two parties on the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this is a sweet victory, it could be short-lived if we
elect an anti-choice president,'' said Kate Michelman, president of
the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, which
has endorsed Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts, chairman of the House Republican Conference and
an abortion opponent, declared in a statement that he was confident
that a new administration ``with moral leadership and a commitment
to the family will reverse this Clinton-Gore decision.'' He
asserted, ``Do-it-yourself abortion has no place in a civilized
society.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Capitol Hill on Thursday, other
anti-abortion legislators, including Hutchinson, called for
committee hearings on what they described as the FDA's
``questionable approval process in regard to RU-486.'' Sen. Sam
Brownback, R-Kan., asserted that the FDA's decision ``was pushed by
politics and not by health,'' while Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J.,
described the drug as ``baby poison.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years RU-486 has been a symbol of the differences
between the two parties on abortion _ President George Bush blocked
its importation; President Clinton lifted that ban just days after
taking office. The reaction from the presidential candidates on
Thursday, while brief and careful, highlighted those differences
anew.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush issued a statement declaring that he
believed the FDA's decision was `'wrong,'' and feared that it would
make abortions ``more and more common, rather than more and more
rare.'' He added, ``As president, I will work to build a culture
that respects life.'' Bush supports a ban on abortion except in
cases of rape, incest, or when the life of a woman is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   When asked specifically what Bush would do about the FDA action,
a spokesman, Scott McClellan, responded: ``It appears the president
does not have the authority to order drugs off the market. As
president, he would order a careful review to ensure that the FDA
considered all the risks and did not do this as a result of
political pressure from the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore issued a statement declaring that he was
``pleased'' with the FDA's decision. ``Today's decision is not
about politics, but the health and safety of American women and a
woman's fundamental right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration, meanwhile, dismissed the notion that the FDA
acted because of political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   For all the political furor on Thursday, it was not clear how
much it would push the abortion issue into a campaign debate that,
until now, has been dominated by the concerns of moderate swing
voters, like health care, Medicare and education.
</P>
<P>
   But Geoffrey Garin, a Democratic pollster, argued that it could
make a difference with ``independent and Republican-leaning women
who are pro-choice,'' who ``might feel perfectly comfortable with
Bush on a whole host of other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting that battle for the center, opponents of abortion
focused much of their fire on Thursday on the FDA's approval
process, the dangers they asserted the drug would present to women,
and the notion that it will increase the number of abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of RU-486 have long hoped that it would, eventually,
make abortion far more accessible, private and harder to target by
opponents. The struggles so long centered on the nation's abortion
clinics would, some of these advocates suggested, slowly fade as
the abortion pill took hold.
</P>
<P>
   David Garrow, a historian of the abortion rights movement and a
professor at Emory University, argued that while FDA's decision was
a victory for abortion rights, ``people in the past have perhaps
created an exaggerated climate of expectations for RU-486.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted, for example, that many women may not want the multiple
doctor visits that RU-486 entails, and thus still choose surgical
abortions. Moreover, he added, many women may not discover their
pregnancy and decide to abort it early enough to use the abortion
pill.
</P>
<P>
   As for a waning of the political struggle, there were few signs
of that on Thursday, at least in the short term. Rep. Tom Coburn,
R-Okla., who has tried to block RU-486 in the past, declared that
Thursday's announcement was unprecedented: ``Never before has the
FDA approved a drug intended to kill people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, at a news conference of Democratic women from the
House, Rep. Lynn Woolsey of California declared of the FDA action,
``It's about time!'' and added that the decision ``has taken women
further away from the back alleys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Hutchinson of Arkansas reflected, ``The idea that it so
normalizes the process that it's no longer a question, I don't
think that's going to happen. The human life issue is too important
to too many people; it's going to continue to be a divisive and
very front-burner issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
