<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News about the net: 09.29.00
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris and John Druckenmiller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Debating the Web impact of `Big Brother'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HBO to get ant's-eye view of undiscovered films
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Trippy movie site a `Dream' in the making
</P>
<P>
   HITS &AMP; MISSES: Tonight's ``Big Brother'' finale could be one of
the Web's great events or a bust. It depends on whom you ask. ``I
think this show will be a benchmark for convergence,'' says Regina
Lewis, the show's on-the-air online adviser, referring to the
cross-pollination between the CBS show and America Online, the
Internet service provider that has carried the program's 24/7 Web
site. Adds David Card, an analyst with Internet research firm
Jupiter Communications: ``This is a show that is perfectly tuned to
the Internet. If you're really interested in watching those boring
guests, you can watch them all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   The stats: AOL and CBS won't project how many will watch the
finale on the Web, but Nielsen/NetRatings reports that the number
of unique visitors since the show's July 5 premiere topped 9.4
million through Wednesday. Other stats:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bigbrother2000.com was the top new site in July, with more
than 4.2 million visitors, reports Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Traffic dropped to 2.3 million in August.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Visitors averaged 12 minutes at the site in August.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The unofficial site, www.bigbrotherblows.com, has had fewer
than 100,000 visitors each day, compared with 400,000 daily
visitors to the survivorsucks.com parody site.
</P>
<P>
   Euro versions: Paul Sims, who maintains the ``Brother'' parody
site, says the CBS-AOL experiment hasn't lived up to its potential
or the hype. ``This was a reality show that needs more reality in
terms of what they were showing on the Internet,'' Sims says. The
original Dutch and German versions had more access to the inner
workings of the housebound contestants, he says, adding, ``On the
American version, they quashed interactivity. They tried to be `Big
Brother' in the house and on the Net as well.''
</P>
<P>
   www.bigbrother2000.com
</P>
<P>
   www.bigbrotherblows.com
</P>
<P>
   PEEKABOO: HBO has a new first-look deal with anteye.com that
allows the cable company exclusive access to the talent and
concepts that feed anteye's ``virtual studio engine.'' Anteye
harvests film and video material from undiscovered filmmakers.
Since launching in March, anteye has received more than 1,000
submissions. Says Chris Albrecht, president of HBO Original
Programming: ``HBO will now get the first look at some of the Web's
hottest filmmakers.''
</P>
<P>
   www.anteye.com
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF SITE: Take a trip to the site for the upcoming movie
``Requiem for a Dream'' and you may wonder if you've stumbled into
Wonderland or Oz. This is not your usual movie promotional Web
site, but then ``Requiem'' director Darren Aronofsky isn't your
usual filmmaker. What's there: Mixes of movie scenes, excerpts from
the book and sound bites is an upbeat, somewhat confusing scene.
But when you try to interact, colors fade, error messages pop up
and you're directed into weird places. If you don't know any
better, you'll think there's something wrong with your computer.
The site, says Artisan, the movie's distributor, is meant to be an
extended mind trip that mirrors the characters' quest for happiness
and their ultimate disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   www.requiemforadream.com
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
