<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-AIDS-CONFERENCE0929-C     09-28 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-CONFERENCE0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tackling HIV/AIDS' grip on black women
 &HT;    By Gracie Bonds Staples
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She struggles to put her fear into words, but Mardis
Andrews knows perhaps better than anyone what the AIDS epidemic
means to her and her children, an 11-year-old daughter and a baby
not yet born.
</P>
<P>
   Death and dying tumble up out of a familiar dark place as she
remembers the funerals of her only sister, Angela, and her
daughter's father, Tyrone Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone was the first to go, then Angela six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She takes a deep breath as if still in disbelief and confides
that in addition to the medicines she takes to fight off the AIDS
virus, she must take an additional pill for depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm in a world different from everybody else,''
the 33-year-old Atlanta mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Mardis Andrews isn't. She has never been.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, 82 percent of women with AIDS are African-American,
just like her. And African-American children represent 62 percent
of all new HIV/AIDS cases in the United States, just like her
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   CHILLING COMPARISON TO AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   But if these numbers are lost on Andrews, they weigh heavy on
the 3,300 representatives from HIV/AIDS advocacy groups and service
providers who are expected to meet here next week for the U.S.
Conference on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   People like Pandora Singleton, executive director of Project
Azuka in Savannah, and Nyrobi Moss, resident manager and social
services coordinator of SisterLove Inc. in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   They know that Georgia has the eighth-highest number of AIDS
cases in the United States; that African-American women account for
54 percent of all new HIV/AIDS cases in the United States; and that
here in Georgia, AIDS is the leading cause of death for
African-American women ages 20 to 44.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one word that comes to mind is devastating,'' said
Singleton, who is also treasurer for the National Minority AIDS
Council and co-chairwoman of the Georgia host committee for the
AIDS conference. ``This is what I remember Africa looking like
before the epidemic took hold there. I see people dying in the
prime of their lives, so we're losing valuable and needed skills.
Children are being orphaned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we're extending people's lives, I would like us to
be more proactive, especially with young women. We can't cure AIDS,
but we can work on trying to stop it from spreading.''
</P>
<P>
   This is but part of the message Singleton hopes to get out at
the four-day conference, which will convene Sunday and run through
Wednesday at the Hyatt Regency downtown. The conference, sponsored
by the National Minority AIDS Council, will feature daily plenary
sessions on everything from housing to fund-raising to nutrition to
public safety to prevention and treatment research.
</P>
<P>
   Special guests will include Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell; Sandra
Thurman, presidential envoy for AIDS Cooperation; and U.S. Surgeon
General David Satcher.
</P>
<P>
   OUTREACH TARGETS MINORITIES
</P>
<P>
   Satcher has made educating, motivating and mobilizing minority
communities his theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans and Hispanics make up well over 50 percent
of new people with full-blown AIDS,'' he said in a telephone
interview last week from Dallas, where he had spent the morning at
a conference of the American Academy of Physicians. ``Among people
with new HIV infections, African-Americans alone make up over 60
percent, and people under 15 make up over half of the new HIV
infections. So it's becoming more heterosexual, it's involving more
women.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, Satcher said, new strategies are needed to reach
these communities, especially people of color.
</P>
<P>
   He said that while there has been some progress noted in slowing
the spread of the disease _ from 150,000 new infections a year in
1988 to about 40,000 a year today _ getting from today's numbers to
zero is the tough part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not seen an epidemic like this before in recorded
history,'' Satcher said. ``Many of the people being infected today
won't know, unless they are tested, that they are infected, because
there are no symptoms for at least 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   This is often true especially for women of color, said Moss,
citing poverty and drugs as major culprits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us can't afford to give much attention to preventative
health care,'' she said. ``Our families come first, especially with
African-American women. We don't go to the doctor until we're
bleeding and dying or pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews was two months pregnant with her 11-year-old when she
discovered she was HIV-positive. In the beginning, she said, she
was in denial about her HIV status. When she realized she had
passed it on to her daughter, ``I was hurt. I felt guilt. Scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has tried to give her daughter as much support
as she can and teach her to take care of herself as best she can.
``I know she lives off of my support,'' she said, ``because I live
off of hers.''
</P>
<P>
   The new pregnancy was unplanned, but an abortion was out of the
question. And so each day she takes a combination of three
medicines, including AZT, to prevent the transmission of the deadly
virus to her unborn child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just pray and have faith that this baby won't be positive,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, sometimes Andrews is depressed about her life, especially
about relationships. She doubts she'll ever have a husband, and she
worries what might become of her children if she becomes no longer
able to care for them or dies.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP IS LABOR OF LOVE
</P>
<P>
   Singleton said Andrews' story is typical of many she has heard
since starting Project Azuka 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual to have a family with more than one person
infected with the AIDS virus, sometimes a mother and child,
sometimes a husband and wife, sometimes cousins or aunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some families where there may be two or three sisters
infected,'' she said. ``It's kind of why our organization even came
into existence.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Singleton was doing testing for the public health
department in prenatal clinics and discovered there were no
gender-specific services for women or their families.
</P>
<P>
   She resigned her job and started Project Azuka, which serves
about 2,100 women annually.
</P>
<P>
   She admits she thought she would be in the unemployment line by
now, not looking to retire with the epidemic on her heels. But
Singleton's hopeful all of it will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 21-year-old daughter,'' she said, ``and I want her to
be able to live in a world without AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Conference on AIDS: www.nmac.org/usca2000/default.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
