<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-REPLAY0929-COX     09-28 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REPLAY0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coaches: Let's take a look
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's still September and already a number of games
have been decided on questionable calls. As a result, the hottest
topic is whether college football should follow the pros and use
instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, many of the aggrieved coaches are for it.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Phillip Fulmer saw his football team lose on a
catch/non-catch call in Florida's 27-23 win Sept. 16 in Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer complained to the SEC about the call. ``I don't know all
the ramifications of having replay, but after some of the recent
things that have happened, I would be for researching it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama coach Mike DuBose was grousing Sunday after a pair of
calls in Arkansas' final drive helped beat the Crimson Tide 28-21.
In one case, the drive was kept alive by a late defensive holding
call DuBose thought was questionable. In another, Arkansas had 12
men on the field on a key third down.
</P>
<P>
   After two missed calls late in a 35-31 loss to Michigan
Saturday, Illinois coach Ron Turner asked the NCAA to consider
instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   Turner got some surprising support from a coach considered to be
a traditionalist. ``I think it's certainly worth discussing,'' Penn
State's Joe Paterno said. ``You're going to get some bad calls, but
you hate to see a bunch of kids who have played so hard lose a game
because the officials blew a call _ not that they do it on
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much pressure on the coaches and kids,'' Texas
coach Mack Brown said. ``There's too much at stake. There's too
much pressure on officials to not make sure the call was right. I
think that would help the officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bobby Gaston, the SEC supervisor of officials, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a perfectionist and so are my guys,'' Gaston said. ``First
and foremost, they want to get the call right. If the technology is
there to help, they'd be for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Money is why it probably won't happen. The budgets of athletics
department are stretched tight. An instant-replay system like that
of the NFL for each of the nation's 115 Division I-A football
stadiums would have to be outfitted with a minimum of eight cameras
wired into video equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some schools would have those kind of resources, but many do
not,'' ACC commissioner John Swofford said. ``And unless you can do
it for every (I-A) team, you can't do it at all. It simply isn't
practical.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing worse than having no instant-replay system would
be to have one that didn't cover all the angles, Gaston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not getting the coverage you want, then you'd be
trying to make a decision without the right information or the
right look at the play,'' he said. ``That would be bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all coaches are for instant replay. ``You're going to have
calls that go for you and calls that go against you,'' Ohio State's
John Cooper said. ``That's part of college football. Officials are
just like coaches and players. Most of the time they are right, but
they make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people are concerned that college play already is too slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got games lasting too long as it is,'' Swofford said.
``I think what we have to do is accept that there are going to be
some bad calls. There is a human element to the game. I don't think
it helps college football to move in the direction of the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
