<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Asian champions play a different style
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The road to the women's basketball gold medal game has
been rougher than expected for the United States, which meets South
Korea in the semifinals Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans outlasted Slovakia 58-43 Wednesday in the
quarterfinals after shooting only 40 percent in a rugged encounter.
Now they face a Korean team that got within a respectable 14 points
of them in their Olympic pool opener Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The reigning Asian champions upset European power France in the
quarterfinals to match their best showing n world competition. The
Koreans, less physical but better outside shooters than the other
teams still in contention, mesmerized the French with backdoor cuts
and surprisingly easy moves to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that we played them once,'' U.S. coach Nell Fortner
said, ``because their style is different than anyone else in this
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other semifinal Friday, Australia meets Brazil, which
upset gold-medal threat Russia in the quarterfinals. Australia beat
Brazil 81-70 when the teams met in pool play.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
