<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-SAUCE-RELIGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA STORES DROP A SAUCE OVER MAKER'S RACIST WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The sauce itself is an act of defiance: a
thick, yellow mustardy glaze that dares to call itself a barbecue
sauce despite its utter lack of tomatoes. South Carolinians are
among the only humans known to allow it upon their meat.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the racial notions of its maker, not its formula,
that led to the banishment of Maurice's All Natural Gourmet Blend
BBQ Sauce from the grocery shelves of six major retailers in the
Southeast in the last two weeks. The sauce, like the huge
Confederate battle flag that flies over its manufacturer's
headquarters, has become a redolent symbol of the change in the
attitudes in the South, a change that infuriates the sauce's
namesake.
</P>
<P>
   With a white sport coat to match his hair and mustache, Maurice
Bessinger even looks like the South of the 1950s, a time when he
was a forceful advocate for segregation, and at quiet moments he
seems almost wistful for a time when he could state plainly his
feelings about race without suffering financially for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say my restaurant never served blacks, but that's just
not true,'' he said, sitting in the headquarters office of
Maurice's Piggy Park, a chain of restaurants that has come to
define South Carolina barbecue. ``We just served them on a
segregated basis, like every other restaurant did. What the blacks
didn't realize was that they got the best food, because their
dining room was actually in the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bessinger spent much of the 1950s and '60s attacking
race-mixing, running the National Association for the Preservation
of White People and refusing to let blacks into his main dining
room, long after most other restaurants had given in. The Supreme
Court eventually forced him to comply with the law.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, he became a born-again Christian and said he
put aside his notions of racial superiority. He set up a religious
mission next to his main restaurant, in West Columbia, and began
distributing tracts that combined his love of the Confederacy with
his religious beliefs, and it is those tracts that have now landed
him in trouble. The one attracting most attention is entitled
``Biblical View of Slavery,'' by John Weaver, a Baptist minister
from Fitzgerald, Ga., and argues that slavery is not inherently
evil because it is permitted in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let anyone try to load you with guilt and say you need
to make reparations for what your forefathers did,'' says the
tract, which is on sale for $1 at the restaurant, alongside Bibles
and Confederate memorabilia. ``No! What our forefathers did was not
evil in and of itself. That doesn't mean that some of our
forefathers did not act evilly, wickedly themselves, and if they
did, they are responsible for their own sins.
</P>
<P>
   The pamphlet also argues that many African slaves ``blessed the
Lord'' for allowing them to be enslaved, because their life in
slavery was better than in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   These ideas came to light last month when they were printed by
John Monk, a columnist at The State, Columbia's daily newspaper.
Bessinger had already been in the news for lowering the American
flag over his headquarters and replacing it with the state and
Confederate battle flags after the State Legislature voted to
remove its Confederate flag from the Capitol dome.
</P>
<P>
   These events led the stores _ including Winn-Dixie, Bi-Lo,
Kroger and Wal-Mart _ to stop selling Bessinger's immensely popular
condiment and boxes of his frozen barbecued pork. The stores have
apparently decided that the number of Southerners likely to be
offended by Bessinger's beliefs is now greater than the mustard and
Confederate traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   Bessinger's business activities ``are unacceptable to us as a
company and to many of our customers,'' said a statement issued by
Bi-Lo Supermarkets, which has 286 stores in the South and is based
in Mauldin, S.C. ``We believe that removing his products from Bi-Lo
stores will reinforce our belief in the dignity of each individual
who shops with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Other stores cited similar reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Bessinger said that more than 40 percent of his business came
from retail sales of his sauce and packaged barbecue, and warned of
layoffs among his 250 employees if he cannot distribute his
products. He says his religious rights are being violated, though
he acknowledged that the stores had a right to choose which
products to sell, and he said that the South Carolina Chamber of
Commerce had organized a politically correct conspiracy against
him. (The chamber, which was active in getting the flag removed
from the Capitol dome, denied a similar role in the sauce's
disappearance.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not pro-slavery,'' he said, ``but no man on earth can
make me deny what the Bible says about slavery. The stores are just
yielding to outside pressure from people who want to destroy the
Constitution and remake America to fit their globalism strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The only notable defender of Bessinger so far has been Pat
Buchanan, whose presidential campaign has established its state
headquarters in the Piggy Park building.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from the building, in the Food Lion grocery
store, there is a wide empty space on the barbecue-sauce shelf that
was once filled by Carolina Gold, as Bessinger sauce is sometimes
known. Eddie Miles, the store manager, said dozens of people had
complained about the missing sauce, but only a few on ideological
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most of them even know about it,'' he said.
``They just like the sauce. You know, it's the only one that has
mustard in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
