<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SHARKS:  &LR; Jim Beck cautiously entered the shark cage in the chilly
waters surrounding this desolate marine outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old electrician had driven through the night from
his home in Southern California for this chance to get up close and
personal with one of the most fearsome predators on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to dive with a great white,'' Beck had
explained earlier, during the predawn, two-hour boat ride from
Alameda. ``It's one of the most beautiful, graceful fishes in the
ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   He gazed into the murky green sea surrounding the aluminum cage.
Visibility was limited to about 15 feet. A huge great white shark
could have been just yards away _ watching, calculating _ and Beck
wouldn't have known.
</P>
<P>
   The minutes ticked by, punctuated only by the hissing sound of
the regulator as Beck took long swallows of compressed air. He saw
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Beck's frustrating experience last week underlines the unique
challenge of marketing nature as a tourist attraction. The simple
fact is this: Nature doesn't always cooperate.  &UR; By David Lazarus &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; NETWORTH:  &LR; Telecom-equipment stocks busted out of their slump
yesterday and rallied the overall market after a Sanford Bernstein
analyst issued a gloom-and-doom report on the sector.
</P>
<P>
   After falling for six straight sessions, the S&AMP;P Communication
Equipment index _ which includes Cisco, Lucent and Nortel _ jumped
4 percent yesterday, more than any other S&AMP;P sector index.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst called it a classic case of ``sell on the rumor, buy
on the news.''  &UR; By Kathleen Pender &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
