<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANK WILLS, 52, WATCHMAN WHO FOILED WATERGATE BREAK-IN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., S.C.)   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Wills, the night watchman who discovered the 1972
Watergate burglary that ultimately led to the resignation of
President Richard M. Nixon, died Sept. 27. He was 52.
</P>
<P>
   Wills, who struggled with celebrity and joblessness after being
hailed as hero, died at University Hospital in Augusta, Ga. Friends
told The Augusta Chronicle that he had suffered from a brain tumor.
He lived in North Augusta, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Wills, a 24-year-old security guard at the Watergate office
building, was working the midnight shift on June 17, 1972. He
discovered tape over a lock on a basement door. Thinking that an
employee had left it there to make getting in and out easier, he
removed it.
</P>
<P>
   On another inspection round, he found the lock taped over again,
and called the police. They locked the doors, turned off the
elevators, and started checking darkened offices. About 2 a.m., at
the sixth floor headquarters of the Democratic National Committee,
they found five men: Bernard L. Barker, Virgilio Gonzales, Eugenio
Martinez, James W. McCord Jr. and Frank Sturgis.
</P>
<P>
   As Wills put it in a 1997 interview with The Florida
Times-Union, ``When we turned the lights on, one person, then two
persons, then three persons came out, and on down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   They five men were arrested for what Ronald L. Ziegler, Nixon's
press secretary, tried to dismiss as a ``second-rate burglary.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House saw to their being paid hush money. But after
the men were convicted before U.S. District Judge John. J. Sirica
the following January, McCord began talking to prosecutors and told
them that Nixon's campaign committee, the Committee for the
Re-Election of the President, had been behind the burglary.
</P>
<P>
   When White House tapes made it clear that Nixon had played a
central role in the cover-up attempt, and he was faced with
impeachment and conviction, he resigned on Aug. 9, 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Wills had quit his job soon after the event, believing he did
not get the raise he deserved. As the cover-up was unraveling in
1974, he made a little money talking about his historic moment, but
his appearances cost him jobs because he was away from work. Most
of the jobs paid not much more than minimum wage, although Wills
did better than that when he played himself in the 1976 movie about
Nixon's downfall, ``All the President's Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Wills was convicted of shoplifting in 1983. For some years he
worked for Dick Gregory, the comedian, who was promoting a diet
product, and lived in the Bahamas. He moved back to North Augusta
in 1990 to care for his mother, who died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a daughter, Angel Brown of Aiken, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by The Washington Star-News on the day Nixon
resigned, Wills said, ``We treat the president like a king, when he
should be a man for all the people.'' He complained that in Nixon's
resignation speech the night before, the president had failed to
describe his role in the cover-up. ``I think he should have been a
little more specific,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee gave Wills an award that fall,
and Robert S. Strauss, its chairman, said he had played ``a unique
role in the history of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most eloquent description of his role came when Rep.
James Mann, D-S.C., casting a difficult vote for impeachment on the
House Judiciary Committee, said on July 29, 1974: ``If there is no
accountability, another president will feel free to do as he
chooses. But the next time, there may be no watchman in the
night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2059EDT &QL; 
