<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5689 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-PREVIEW-$ADV01-     09-28 1607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PREVIEW-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLICE POWER, ENVIRONMENT, SPEECH ISSUES TOP COURT'S DOCKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After tackling such volatile issues as gay rights
and late-term abortion during its last session, the Supreme Court
opens a new season Monday with far-reaching but less dramatic cases
involving police power, the environment and free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was the fireworks, once-in-a-decade kind of term,
whereas this time around the court has slowed things down and is
looking at less controversial issues,'' says John Roberts Jr., a
Supreme Court expert here.
</P>
<P>
   But he notes that the court still has time to add high-profile
cases. The court docket now has 47 cases. Typically, it ends up
with around 75.
</P>
<P>
   As its term begins, the court itself has become a major
political issue. Since the next president will likely nominate two
to four justices, whoever wins in November could shape the court,
now beginning its 15th year under Chief Justice William Rehnquist,
for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   Four cases focusing on police power lead the current docket.
Julie O'Sullivan, a Georgetown University law professor, says they
``may not have high visibility, but for most people, they may have
more of an impact'' than some of last term's hot-button cases.
``They may burden the law-abiding, as well as the law-breaking,''
she explains.
</P>
<P>
   In one case from Lago Vista, Texas, Gail Atwater was driving her
two children home from soccer practice in 1997 when a toy fell off
their pickup truck. Atwater then drove slowly around the
neighborhood, letting the children stand on the seat to look out
the window for it.
</P>
<P>
   When a police car passed her truck, Atwater said later, she knew
she was going to get a ticket for failing to buckle the youngsters'
seatbelts. What she didn't expect was that the police would
handcuff her in front of the children and search her vehicle.
Although they found only soccer equipment, the officers took
Atwater to the local police station, where she was booked,
photographed and put into a holding cell. She later paid a $50
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Atwater filed a federal lawsuit against the city, attacking its
policy allowing such searches after minor traffic violations. A
federal judge ruled for the city, but the 5th Circuit Court of
Appeals overruled the decision, saying the search policy was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here concerns everyone because it looks at how far
can police go after picking someone up for something minor, which
sooner or later happens to most people,'' says Steven R. Shapiro,
national legal director of the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   In an Indianapolis case, the court will look at the use of
police roadblocks on city streets in which an officer checks
licenses and registration while a drug-sniffing dog walks around
the stopped cars in search of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled against the checkpoints,
saying they were not designed to ensure highway safety, which would
have made them legal, but were used as ``a pretext for a dragnet
search for criminals.''The Supreme Court in 1990 upheld
drunken-driving roadblocks as a legal method of removing hazardous
drivers from the roads, but lower courts have disagreed about the
constitutionality of drug roadblocks, which seek to detect illegal
trafficking, not drug-using drivers.
</P>
<P>
   In another case under the Fourth Amendment's ban on
``unreasonable searches and seizures,'' the court will examine the
controversial practice of prosecuting pregnant women who use drugs
or engage in other practices that might endanger their babies. The
court will review the policy of a Charleston, S.C., city hospital
that allows tests of pregnant patients suspected of drug use and
then turns the results over to police if they test positive.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the practice, ruling
that the health problems caused by maternal drug use outweighed the
intrusion suffered by the women whose urine was tested for drugs
without their consent.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the justices will go high-tech when they consider
whether Florence, Ore., police needed a search warrant before using
a thermal-imaging device to detect heat patterns inside a house.
</P>
<P>
   The imaging device has become popular with police trying to
detect indoor marijuana-growing operations that use high-intensity
lights to speed the plants' growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court also will wade into environmental issues in
two cases that will test the constitutional limits of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   The first involves the Environmental Protection Agency's
adoption in 1997 of tough new rules on smog-causing ozone and soot
under the 1990 Clean Air Act. The regulations, which would have
thrown hundreds of urban counties out of compliance, were
challenged by a coalition of industry representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia ruled that the EPA had acted unconstitutionally in
imposing sweeping air-quality standards for those pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   In the case, the Supreme Court also will consider whether the
government must take costs into account as well as benefits to
society before it sets national air quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   The other environmental case stems from an effort by the U.S.
Army Corps of Engineers to prevent 24 communities near Chicago from
dumping garbage into a proposed landfill. The area now has inland
waters that are home to blue herons and other migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the Corps has
jurisdiction over the area and may protect it under the federal
government's authority to regulate interstate commerce. The court
said the wetlands area contributes to the economy because many
out-of-state travelers drive there each year to hunt and view the
birds.
</P>
<P>
   In a First Amendment free-speech case, the justices will decide
whether people may be sued for disclosing the contents of telephone
calls that were illegally intercepted and recorded by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilkes-Barre, Penn., case is expected to help define the
balance between the First Amendment rights of Americans to
disseminate information and state and federal wiretapping laws
aimed at preventing people from intercepting private conversations.
</P>
<P>
   The case involve a tape recording made illegally of a cell phone
conversation that was later given to radio station WILK, which
broadcast it repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   The case could have an important impact on the press because
news reporters sometimes use information that may have been
obtained by third parties through questionable means.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision could also affect a lawsuit brought by Rep.
John A. Boehner, R-Ohio, against Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, a Florida couple illegally taped a cell phone
conversation in which then House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Boehner and
other Republican leaders were heard discussing matters related to
an ethics case against Gingrich. The couple gave the tape to
McDermott, who passed it on to the House ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   Several news organizations published transcripts of the
conversations. A U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia later ruled that the Boehner suit could go forward.
</P>
<P>
   In another case with First Amendment implications, the justices
will examine a voter-initiated amendment to the Missouri
Constitution that required the state's 11-member congressional
delegation to either support a term-limits amendment to the U.S.
Constitution or be labeled on future ballots as having
``disregarded voters' instruction on term limits.''
</P>
<P>
   The 8th Circuit Court of Appeals found the law to be a form of
government-compelled speech that violates the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   In a Tennessee case, the justices will examine whether a state
high school association can bar coaches at private schools from
recruiting athletes from public schools.
</P>
<P>
   A federal district court ruled that the association's policy
violated the coaches' First Amendment rights to free speech.
However, the 6th Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati reversed
the district court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In another case involving athletes, the justices will decide if
the Professional Golf Association violated the Americans with
Disabilities Act when it barred Casey Martin _ a partially disabled
golfer _ from riding a cart during tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals rejected the PGA argument that
all tournament golfers must play by the same rules, which includes
walking about five miles a day on sometimes hilly courses.
</P>
<P>
   The high court will also explore a distinction in federal
immigration law between out-of-wedlock children born overseas to
American mothers and those born to American fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, a child born to an unmarried American mother is
considered a U.S. citizen at birth. But a child whose mother is a
foreign national and whose father is an American is considered a
noncitizen. For the child to become a citizen, the American father
must formally acknowledge paternity before the child is 18 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves a 31-year-old man born in Vietnam and raised
by his American father, who never asked the government to make him
a citizen. Now the son faces deportation to Vietnam after being
convicted on an assault charge. The father challenged the statute,
saying it violates the constitutional requirement that laws treat
men and women equally.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
