u i BC-DENMARK-EURO(TRIM)-NY     09-28 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENMARK-EURO(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENMARK'S REJECTION OF EURO MAY SIGNAL DEEPER DISCONTENT WITH
INTEGRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark _ Denmark voted Thursday not to join
Europe's common currency, the euro, undermining an already fragile
monetary experiment and disdaining the rapid European political
integration championed by France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In the first popular test for the euro, introduced last year
without such democratic consultation in 11 nations of the 15-member
European Union, Danes voted to preserve the krone rather than join
Europe's ambitious experiment with a common currency.
</P>
<P>
   Final results showed about 53 percent of the electorate
rejecting the euro, with about 47 percent in favor. The result was
a blow to Social Democratic Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen,
who campaigned vigorously with a message that Danes should accept
the euro or face isolation.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection appeared to contain an ominous warning to European
leaders that they may have raced ahead of their electorates in
adopting the euro, pressing for the political cooperation needed to
support it, and talking of European federalism.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``democratic deficit'' is now heard often in
discussions of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am generally pro-European, but I voted no to register my
protest at the lack of democratic openness in the way a united
Europe is being built,'' said Ebbe Kloevedal Reich, a writer, as he
stood in the misty rain in Copenhagen on Thursday. ``It is simply
not a democratic process at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote may reflect a broad political trend in European
countries toward the rediscovery of national identity and away from
Europeanism, at least as currently envisioned. Pia Kjaersgaard, a
nationalist Danish leader, has been a leader of the campaign
against the euro, and will now likely find her political position
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the day Thursday the euro traded at about 88 cents
to the dollar, slipping only slightly after the vote to about 87.5
cents in New York trading.
</P>
<P>
   This relative stability reflected several factors: the rejection
by Danes had already been factored in by many currency traders,
plus the limited size of Denmark's economy and recent European
Central Bank intervention that has demonstrated that monetary
authorities will not let the currency slip much below this level.
</P>
<P>
   But just 21 months ago, at its introduction, the euro bought
$1.17 and the Danish rejection suggested that the currency's
chronic weakness is not about to end.
</P>
<P>
   Confronting such weakness may require the support of something
as big as a federal government spanning the European Union, but the
Danes, among others, have shown that many Europeans do not want
that _ at least for now. A tension seems certain to persist between
a common currency and the absence of common fiscal and other
policies to support it.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of Britain and Sweden joining the euro seems less
likely after Denmark's vote. And the absence of Britain's
participation in the euro is particularly discomfiting to European
monetary authorities, given the size and strength of that country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a no from the Danes, there would certainly be a loss of
confidence in the euro,'' said Klaus-Dieter Kuehbacher, a member of
the governing council of the German Bundesbank, before the final
results were announced. He suggested that further intervention by
the European Central Bank to stabilize the euro was possible.
</P>
<P>
   However, a sharp fall in the euro's value appears unlikely in
part because it has begun to hurt the earnings of large American
corporations in Europe. Sales in euros now translate into fewer
dollars. The Federal Reserve has joined the European Union in
supporting the euro and a consensus regarding it's value appears to
exist.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The euro was always a political project, adopted in haste soon
after German unification a decade ago as a means to tie a united
Germany forever to its European neighbors and advance the vision of
a United States of Europe held dear by Germany's former chancellor,
Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   It is this vision, imposed from above and without a voice that
that seem to be a concern for many of the 375 million residents in
the European Union's member countries worried about the loss of
national identity and national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   One of those Danes voicing concern Thursday was Louisa Jacobsen,
a lawyer who said she had favored European integration in the past.
But recent developments _ particularly the imposition by 14
European Union governments of sanctions on Austria for including
Jorg Haider's rightist Freedom Party in a governing coalition _
have angered her, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in Austria was a scandal, and that it why I
voted no,'' she said, clearly troubled, like many Danes, by the
idea that ``Europe'' could punish a small country for its
democratic choice. ``We need a break, a pause, in a process of
integration that is going much too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian sanctions were lifted earlier this month, but not
before damage had been done to the pro-euro campaign in Denmark, a
nation of 5.3 million people. This small nation has long been
divided over European integration, and swing voters like Jacobsen
have proven decisive on such votes.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a combination of the rightist nationalism of
Kjaersgaard and a wide range of anxieties over the future of
Denmark's welfare state and the nature of democracy in a united
Europe clearly coalesced to produce the rejection. This combination
outweighed the solidly pro-euro sentiments of Denmark's business
community.
</P>
<P>
   The governing Social Democrats, by far the largest party with 35
percent of the vote, were unable to deliver their voters to the
pro-euro cause because of widespread concern among them that
pressure for lower taxes from European monetary authorities would
eventually make Denmark's comprehensive welfare state unaffordable.
</P>
<P>
   Tax cuts and deregulation are favored by the European Central
Bank to spur pan-European economic growth to a point where it can
begin to compete with the vigorous American economy, making the
euro more attractive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
