<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5691 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SHARKS-SFCHRON &LR;      09-28 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NATURE CALLS THE SHOTS WHEN CHASING GREAT WHITE SHARKS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARALLON ISLANDS, Calif. _ Jim Beck cautiously entered the shark
cage in the chilly waters surrounding this desolate marine outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old electrician had driven through the night from
his home in Southern California for this chance to get up close and
personal with one of the most fearsome predators on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to dive with a great white,'' Beck had
explained earlier, during the predawn, two-hour boat ride from
Alameda, Calif. ``It's one of the most beautiful, graceful fishes
in the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   He gazed into the murky green sea surrounding the aluminum cage.
Visibility was limited to about 15 feet. A huge great white shark
could have been just yards away _ watching, calculating _ and Beck
wouldn't have known.
</P>
<P>
   The minutes ticked by, punctuated only by the hissing sound of
the regulator as Beck took long swallows of compressed air. He saw
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Beck's frustrating experience last week underlines the unique
challenge of marketing nature as a tourist attraction. The simple
fact is this: Nature doesn't always cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that's wonderful about wilderness is its
unpredictability,'' said Josh Nowlis, a senior scientist at the
Center for Marine Conservation in San Francisco. ``We can't expect
nature to provide guaranteed results on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a challenge faced by all those who seek to bring people
and creatures into contact, from whale-watching services to African
safari organizers.
</P>
<P>
   It also raises ethical questions about how far an entrepreneur
can or should go to facilitate close encounters with the wild
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of great white sharks, there are just three places
in the world where intrepid divers can tour known feeding grounds _
Australia, South Africa and the Farallons, located about 25 miles
west of the Golden Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   September and October are when the Farallons teem with dozens of
great whites, which come in search of the elephant seals and sea
lions that frequent the area.
</P>
<P>
   While commercial divers and charters have been visiting the
rocky islands for years, only one company offers shark-watching
tours for the general public: Alameda's Golden Gate Expeditions,
established last year by Lawrence Groth, a longtime diver and
marine-services worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see great whites,'' he said, explaining why he
invested more than $100,000 in a specially equipped boat and
establishing his own firm. ``And I think other people should see
them, too. It's an incredible creature, and it's right here in our
backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   He can take up to six passengers aboard his 32-foot vessel, the
Patriot. Each pays either $400 for weekday outings or $450 for
weekends, with typical trips lasting from 6 a.m. to 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Groth, who spends the remainder of the year working on a variety
of commercial vessels, makes clear up front that he cannot
guarantee the appearance of any sharks. But that doesn't deter
those for whom even the possibility of a great white sighting is
cause for excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Pesch, a 37-year-old fire captain, flew in from Arizona for
the experience. ``It's the thrill of a lifetime,'' he said. ``If I
see a white . . .''
</P>
<P>
   His voice trailed off, as if mere words could not capture the
full splendor of such an idea.
</P>
<P>
   For many divers, confronting a great white shark, even from the
confines of a shark cage, is the Holy Grail of their sport. The
creature commands that much respect.
</P>
<P>
   The great white _ Carcharodon carcharias to shark aficionados _
can grow to more than 20 feet in length and weigh upwards of 7,000
pounds. Its ancestry as one of the ocean's most potent predators _
only killer whales and people are as deadly _ dates back 300
million years.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the film ``Jaws,'' great whites are seen by many as
the serial killers of the sea (not to mention the only predators
that attack to their own universally recognized theme music).
</P>
<P>
   In reality, fatal attacks on humans are relatively rare,
occurring only about once or twce a year worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fascination with these carnivores persists.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, two surfers in Australia were killed by great
whites along the same stretch of coast on consecutive days _ the
first time this has happened in more than 20 years, the BBC
reported.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving at the Farallons, Groth and his dive master, Gary
Rose, tossed a pair of decoys from the stern of the boat. Each
consisted of a piece of a surfboard-size plywood covered with foam
rubber, and, according to Groth, looked distinctly from beneath the
waves like sea lions sunning on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Just a half hour later, as Beck and the other divers were
readying their gear, a flash of gray fins churned the water as a
great white went for one of the floats. In a blink of an eye, it
was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see that?'' Groth shouted. ``A 12-footer! Easily a
12-footer!''
</P>
<P>
   Beck was inside the shark cage just moments afterward, peering
intently into the gloom. But the shark had apparently decided that
a foam-rubber decoy is not as tasty as the real thing and had
departed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' Beck said as he emerged, dripping and shivering,
from the 56-degree water almost an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   His chagrin was partially the result of a decision by Groth not
to use ``chum'' _ buckets of blood and meat dumped into the water _
to lure sharks in close. Chumming is a common practice among
great-white tour operators in Australia and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Groth said he chummed last year at the Farallons and ran afoul
of environmentalists, who said that he was messing with the natural
feeding behavior of great whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of that,'' he said, ``it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Groth said he gets the same results using decoys. Others,
however, note that while a decoy may initially attract a shark, it
won't keep the creature coming back for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't use blood, you won't see sharks,'' said a worker
at a Bay Area dive shop who asked to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do shark watching without any chumming, the odds are
certainly against you,'' agreed Doreen Moser, assistant director of
education for the Marine Mammal Center in Sausalito.
</P>
<P>
   But she said Groth was correct not to do it. ``The key thing
with any ecotourism is not to do anything that could affect the
animal's behavior,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Pyle, a biologist who has conducted research at the
Farallons for the past 20 years, said even foam rubber decoys can
influence a shark's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Given his choice, Pyle said all shark-watching tours of the
islands would be banned. ``They interfere with our research,'' Pyle
said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Fear of Chum
</P>
<P>
   But such a ban is unlikely. Shark watchers can claim the same
rights as the numerous whale watchers who visit the area.
</P>
<P>
   A more pressing concern for some is if other entrepreneurs get
into the game, competition could intensify among shark-watching
tours of the Farallons.
</P>
<P>
   Burr Heneman, former executive director of the Point Reyes Bird
Observatory, which has jurisdiction over the waters surrounding the
islands, said he worries that such a situation would compel boat
owners to increase viewing chances by resorting to chum.
</P>
<P>
   The concern, in essence, is that, like wild bears at Yosemite,
great whites would alter their behavior to accommodate the presence
of humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best place on the planet to study white sharks,''
Heneman said. ``Chumming makes you part of the picture, and it
really throws off the research.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, caveat emptor rules the day for those who pony up
hundreds of dollars for a chance to see sharks at the Farallons.
After that one fleeting glimpse in the morning, the passengers of
the Patriot saw nary a fin for their remaining eight hours at the
islands.
</P>
<P>
   Beck said he was satisfied with having gotten at least a brief
peek at a great white. But Pesch could barely hide his
disappointment that he had so little to show for his trip out from
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the pair missed the big show by just one day.
Groth said that during his next outing to the islands, a 15-foot
shark took a bite out of one of the decoys, and an 18-footer
attacked and ate an elephant seal not far from the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' he said. ``A big, bloody mess.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as shark watching goes, it doesn't get much better than
that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Lazarus at dlazarus(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
