<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-28 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: UNDER THE VOLCANO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Foreign Affairs)  
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELES CITY, Philippines _ So you get home tonight and you get
on AOL and you have a question about your bill or a technical
glitch. You go to the AOL help section and get online with an AOL
helper, who walks you through your problem, using e-mail back and
forth. Do you know who you're talking to? You're talking to a
Filipino techie working in AOL's back office, which, thanks to a
fiber-optic cable under the Pacific, is now located here at the
former Clark Air Base outside Manila, beneath the Mount Pinatubo
volcano.
</P>
<P>
   The AOL member-services center in the Philippines employs 900
young Filipino techies, who, working on computers in three
eight-hour shifts, now handle about 90 percent of the 600,000
online billing and technical questions that pour into AOL each
month. ``I got this member online one day,'' said Christine Dizon,
one of many Filipino AOL techies I interviewed here, ``and she
asked me: `Where are you?' And I said, `I'm in the Philippines.'
And she said, `You're kidding me, right?' I told her, `No, I'm
really in the Philippines.' Sometimes people ask if we're machines.
We tell them no, we're alive and kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   It was interesting to visit the two-year-old AOL Philippine
center on the same day that in Prague, Czech Republic, a rogues'
gallery of communists, anarchists, protectionist unions and
over-fed Yuppies out for their 1960s fix were denouncing
globalization and trying to turn the World Bank-IMF meetings into a
molotov cocktail party. Because this AOL call center, one of many
sprouting in the Philippines, is also globalization, and, for 900
young Filipinos, it's their salvation.
</P>
<P>
   There is a long waiting list for jobs here, which pay about
triple the local minimum wage, and come with a 10-kilo bag of rice
twice a month, plus health care and one meal a day. The Filipinos
here also get free Internet phone and Web access, which many use
for hours after work because they don't have home phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are afraid of globalization because they fear
being exploited,'' said Romer Recabar, an AOL techie, ``but what
they are missing is that we can use this as a chance to learn. We
have the technical know-how here, but AOL is bringing us the
knowledge and resources we need to compete, and if we don't compete
we perish. ... My parents have a family business, but I work here
so I can bring what I learn from an international company like AOL
to our family business.''
</P>
<P>
   If AOL were not here, said Judith Jane Lyons, one of the
thousands of tech grads produced by Filipino colleges each year,
``I would probably be unemployed or underemployed,'' because the
number of good tech jobs is limited, so many end up working as
clerks or in a factory, if they're lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a job for almost a year before I got in
here,'' said Jojo Echo. ``I have two brothers and one sister. My
father is not living, so I am the breadwinner. My mom is so happy
on payday, because I give her almost half my salary.''
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine the pride it produces in young Filipino techies
to know they are explaining to Americans and the world how to
operate AOL services. There are only two American AOL managers
here. All the other managers have been developed from the Filipino
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people ask me where I work,'' said Soc Bautista, who has
risen to training manager, ``and I tell them `AOL,' they say: `Wow!
Really?' The pride it gives is immense. Our families share in the
pride. Our families say, `My kid works for AOL. ...' This gives us
the opportunity as a Third World country to improve and be at par
(with others).''
</P>
<P>
   The AOL call center here is but one example of a simple truth _
that the best hope for alleviating poverty around the world is
through more globalization, not less, and by encouraging
governments to put in place the market-friendly policies,
institutions and environmental protections that will attract global
investment and jobs. The idea peddled by the Prague protesters that
choking off this process will help the world's poor is sheer
lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the people who should be saying that loudly, such
as the World Bank head, James Wolfensohn, have become intimidated
by the anti-globalization mob, whose only plan is to keep poor
people poor. Think of the glib, moronic sign held up by protesters
in Prague: ``Make Love, Not Trade.'' Very funny _ unless trade and
foreign investment are your only lifelines out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Yo, protesters! Come here for a visit _ or get on AOL's help
line and ask the Filipino techies what they think about
globalization. Trust me, they'll give you an earful. Trust me,
you've got mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
