<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-DEBATE-NYT &LR;      09-28 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE INVITES GROUP OF `REGULAR FOLKS' TO HELP HIM PREPARE FOR
DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Vice President Al Gore travels to his debate
preparation camp in Sarasota, Fla., on Saturday, he will be
accompanied by many of the usual campaign suspects _ his chairman,
his media consultant and his message guru. But he also bring along
some very unusual _ and unsuspecting _ advisers he picked up on the
campaign trail, like Erin K. Conner, a 14-year-old freshman at
Belleville West High School in Belleville, Ill., and Joyce E.
Martin, a 76-year-old retiree from Clearwater, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   At considerable expense that some Gore aides do not even want to
think about, Gore has invited 13 ``regular folks'' _ including
Conner's mother, who will chaperone her _ to help him prepare for
one of the pivotal moments in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides say the purpose is for these people, all of whom Gore
has met in campaign appearances, to help brief the vice president
about the concerns of real Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, another purpose, or at least a consequence, is to
provide fodder for newspaper and television stories during the
three days that Gore will be sequestered for mock debates and
strategy meetings. Not coincidentally, almost all of those Gore has
invited come from important swing states where newspapers and
television stations are likely to compile reports about the new
Gore advisers from back home. Three are from Michigan, two are from
Illinois, and others are from Ohio, Pennsylvania, Florida, Georgia,
New Mexico, Maine and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   When the briefings and rehearsals end on Tuesday, Gore's guests
are to accompany him to Boston for that night's nationally
televised debate. Gore aides hope to secure tickets that will allow
them to sit in the debate hall, raising the prospect that Gore will
allude to them during his thrust-and-parry with Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Using audience members as props has become a regular feature of
presidential debates and major speeches like the State of the Union
in recent years, and Gore uses the tactic frequently. In his
acceptance speech at the Democratic National Convention in August,
for example, he illustrated his positions on prescription drug
costs, education and a patient's bill of rights by pointing to
several people who had been planted in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Among those invited to advise Gore this weekend is Winifred
Skinner, a 79-year-old widow from Des Moines, Iowa, who has become
an overnight national celebrity since an encounter with Gore on
Wednesday at a forum on Medicare in Altoona, Iowa. Skinner told
Gore that she has to collect cans on roadsides to make ends meet
because her prescription drugs are so expensive. When Gore asked
how much she raised that way, she charmed him by responding:
``You're not going to tell the government, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner has since been inundated by network television
reporters, making appearances Thursday on NBC's ``Today'' and ABC's
``Good Morning America,'' among other shows. The Gore campaign
offered to fly her to Sarasota and Boston, but she at first
declined because her claustrophobia makes her afraid to fly. The
campaign then offered to drive her to Boston in a Winnebago. She
hesitated because she did not want to leave behind her 6-year-old
toy poodle, Bridget. She was told she could bring the dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the deal breaker,'' said Jeff J. Link, Gore's Iowa
state director, who personally negotiated the arrangement with
Skinner by telephone on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner said that once Bridget was accommodated _ ``she's the
only family I've got'' _ she began to get excited about her trip.
``I've never been that far east,'' she said. ``And I was a debater
in high school, so I love debates.'' She also said she planned to
sell some cans she has accumulated to provide spending money for
her trip. ``I'm no moocher,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The sessions in Sarasota will be held at the Mote Marine
Laboratory, an 11-acre research and conference center where Gore
also prepared for his 1996 vice presidential debate. William M.
Daley, Gore's campaign chairman and the former commerce secretary,
said on Thursday that the special guests would help Gore stay
focused on the debate's audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates tend to stay fairly secluded when preparing for
debates,'' he said. ``It is a rarefied atmosphere of policy
briefings, debate rehearsals and briefing books. The presence of
these special guests is an opportunity for us all to remember
what's really important in this election.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's guests are demographically diverse. Short biographies
distributed on Thursday by the Gore campaign point out that Joseph
Austin, a construction worker from Albuquerque, N.M., is Hispanic
and Joseph Dulin, a school principal from Ann Arbor, Mich., is an
African-American. Most of those invited were notified earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the invitees, like Donald Jalbert of Lewiston, Maine,
and Claudia Amboyer of Shelby Township, Mich., are teachers who
Gore met while staying at their homes during his various campaign
``school days.'' Conner, the 14-year-old student, caught his
attention when she introduced him during an appearance at her
school on Sept. 11. The retired Martin met the vice president on
Monday during a discussion with him about Medicare that preceded a
speech he gave in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's doctor had wanted to charge her $450 for a recent
office visit to examine an ailing wrist but accepted a $125
Medicare payment instead, she told Gore. ``If I didn't have
Medicare I'd have been out of luck,'' she said on Thursday. ``I'd
have been sitting here suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ``guest'' will be Atlanta firefighter Matt Moseley,
himself something of a celebrity since the day last year when he
dangled from a helicopter to rescue a construction worker trapped
by a raging fire. Gore called Moseley shortly after the rescue and
then met him during a trip to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley said he had been surveying colleagues at his firehouse
and other friends about the subjects they would like him to raise
with Gore. His topics so far: prescription drug coverage,
education, gun control, tax cuts and welfare reform. ``It will be
an honor to go,'' he said, ``and pretty reassuring that the person
running to be leader of the free world would want to talk to what I
would call real people in preparing for this debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one was more stunned to be asked, however, than
Connor, who is four years shy of voting age. ``I couldn't believe
it,'' she said. ``But I think he knows that teen-agers like myself
are going to be the leaders of tomorrow and without our input we
may not like the society that he forms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
