A5703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCI-GLOBAL-CLIMATE-NY     09-28 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GLOBAL-CLIMATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS DOUBT PROGRESS ON GLOBAL WARMING PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Ind.)   By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several Republican senators expressed strong
concerns Thursday that talks to flesh out details of a global
warming treaty signed by the Clinton administration in 1998 would
never produce a document the Senate will approve.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as Frank E. Loy, undersecretary of state for
global affairs, spoke at a joint hearing of the Senate Foreign
Relations and Energy and Natural Resources committees in which he
staunchly defended efforts to transform the treaty, the Kyoto
Protocol, from a broad commitment to stem global emissions of
heat-trapping greenhouse gases into a detailed, enforceable plan.
</P>
<P>
   The protocol calls for the United States and other
industrialized countries to start by 2008 reducing emissions of
greenhouse gases like carbon dioxide, which comes mainly from
burning coal and oil. More than 150 countries have signed the
protocol, but it has not been ratified by any of the world's
industrial powers.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations will resume in November in The Hague, Netherlands,
on a variety of points, including defining ways for wealthy
countries to get credit toward emissions targets by paying for
projects in developing countries that help prevent releases of
greenhouse gases as those economies grow.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank H. Murkowski, R-Alaska, chairman of the energy
committee, said important aspects of the treaty were far from the
goals the Senate set in a resolution 1997, before the accord was
adopted at a Kyoto meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It would still be an unfair burden on the U.S. economy,
Murkowski said, by forcing cuts in the use of coal and oil. And, he
added, there appeared to be no requirement for developing countries
to limit future emissions. That was a specific demand of in the
Senate resolution, which passed on a 95-0 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developing nations basically get a free ride,'' Murkowski
said. ``The protocol only punishes developed countries with high
energy prices and reduced economic productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Loy, the chief negotiator for the United States in recent rounds
of climate talks, said the agreement was not, and would not _ even
after further talks _ be a complete or perfect solution to global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, it is an essential start, providing relatively
cheap insurance against harm if scientists' predictions of the
consequences of a warming climate prove correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we act now, the insurance premium will be far more
reasonable than if we delay and hope the problem will simply go
away,'' Loy said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that there were signs that China and India, along with
other developing countries, were moving toward reducing their use
of coal or changing other practices in ways that would limit their
contribution to the greenhouse problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., said there were signs in his state
that farmers would support a treaty if they got financial credits
for sopping up carbon dioxide through certain farming methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any solution until a large number of Americans see
this is in their self-interest,'' Lugar said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BEAUTIFUL-FILM-REVIEW     09-28 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTIFUL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEAUTIFUL': THE MAKING OF A MISS CONGENIALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Beauty may be only skin deep, but ugly is to the bone,'' the
queen of the thunderously intoned wisecrack, Tallulah Bankhead, is
reputed to have said on the subject of appearances. But if we are
to believe ``Beautiful,'' a clumsy satire of the world of beauty
pageants, most of those involved in that world are spiritually ugly
to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Take the movie's ruthless hard-boiled antiheroine, Mona Hibbard
(Minnie Driver), a cutthroat competitor who exhibits not the
tiniest stirrings of conscience or affection for any other human
being until she has a sappy, unconvincing revelation near the end
of the film.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of Mona's notorious pranks are the stunt she pulls on a
contestant who has stolen her talent routine of twirling a flaming
baton while singing ``A Bicycle Built for Two.'' Just before her
rival goes onstage, Mona slips some glue on the baton. When the
flaming instrument sticks to the hand of the panicked contestant,
Mona just happens to be standing by with a fire extinguisher to
save the day and further humiliate her, covering her in a thick
blanket of foam.
</P>
<P>
   In another farcical moment Mona, who has recently been crowned
Miss Illinois and is desperate for photo opportunities, rushes to
the aid of a woman who has gone into labor in a supermarket.
Instructing her young daughter Vanessa (Hallie Kate Eisenberg) to
keep snapping pictures, she offers an impromptu serenade of ``The
Wind Beneath My Wings'' before loading the poor woman onto a
shopping cart and wheeling her to a hospital while Vanessa follows
dutifully snapping away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful'' is at its most promising when it satirically
scratches the eyes out of its subject, although these farcical bits
are executed with a haranguing insistence that flattens much of
their humor. Responsibility for the movie's relentless shrillness
belongs both to Sally Field, who is making her insecure
feature-film debut as a director, and to Driver, who is woefully
miscast as Mona.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying a woman who grew up in a shack in Illinois with gross
redneck caricatures for parents, Driver strives determinedly to
carry off a role that at odd moments suggests a worst-nightmare
parody of Kathie Lee Gifford. But the higher Mona rises on the
pageant circuit, the more unbelievable her ascent becomes. For
Driver, although striking looking, is simply too old for the role
and utterly lacking in the sleek, airbrushed perkiness of the
typical American beauty contestant. Her features are irregular, her
smiles less than star bright, and the aura she exudes, even when
plastering on a fake, toothy grin, can only be described as dark
and heavy.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay by Jon Bernstein rides on an implausible soap
opera conceit more appropriate to a vintage Bette Davis weepie than
to a contemporary satire. Early in her career Mona has a child who
her saintly best friend, Ruby (Joey Lauren Adams), agrees to call
her own. Mona, Ruby and Vanessa (who doesn't know the truth) live
together until Ruby, who works as a nurse in an old-age home, is
wrongfully accused of helping a patient commit suicide and thrown
in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Mona is forced to be a mother to the little girl who
loathes her for very good reasons. She ends up taking the child
with her to the finals of a Miss America-like competition in
Southern California, where a vindictive, nosy television reporter
(Leslie Stefanson) plans to expose her as a single mother and
disqualify her from the pageant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful'' wants to make a statement about sexism and beauty
pageants with their phony humanitarianism, bogus talent shows and
superficial values. But the movie is so nasty to its mostly female
characters that it feels harshly misogynist. The sole angel among
these screeching harpies is Ruby. Heaven knows why she puts up with
Mona, who treats her like a doormat.
</P>
<P>
   Stylistically ``Beautiful'' teeters from a noisy sitcom (only
one step removed from ``The Beverly Hillbillies''), to brickbat
satire until it collapses in a pool of redemptive mush as Mona
belatedly and unconvincingly discovers her maternal instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned). It
includes profanity and off-color jokes.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:  &QL; 
`BEAUTIFUL' Directed by Sally Field; written by Jon Bernstein;
director of photography, Robert Yeoman; edited by Debra
Neil-Fischer; music by John Frizzell; production designer, Charles
Breen; produced by John Bertolli and B.J. Rack; released by
Destination Films. Running time: 112 minutes. This film is rated
PG-13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WITH: Minnie Driver (Mona), Joey Lauren Adams (Ruby), Leslie
Stefanson (Joyce Parkins), Bridgette L. Wilson (Lorna Larkin),
Kathleen Turner (Verna Chickle) and Hallie Kate Eisenberg
(Vanessa).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
