<HEADER>
A5708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HEALTH-INSURE-ART-NYT     09-28 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INSURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF INSURED AMERICANS UP FOR THE FIRST TIME IN MORE THAN A
DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After rising for 11 years, the number of Americans
without health insurance declined last year, to 42.6 million, a
reduction of 1.7 million from 1998, the Census Bureau reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of people without insurance also declined for the
first time since 1987 _ to 15.5 percent in 1999, from 16.3 percent
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The robust economy and an expansion of government programs
contributed to the decline, economists and health policy experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   With the unemployment rate at 4.1 percent, a 30-year low, many
employers have found that they must offer health insurance to
attract and retain workers. In addition, low-income people are
receiving coverage from government programs created or expanded in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Mills, a statistician at the Census Bureau, said,
``The driving force behind this improvement was an increase in the
likelihood of people having employment-based health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of people with health insurance through their
employers rose last year by 3.4 million, to 172 million. This
change accounted for 85 percent of the increase in the number of
people with health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   For children, as for the population as a whole, coverage
increased last year. The number of uninsured children declined to
10 million last year, from 11.1 million in 1998. The proportion of
children without coverage declined as well, to 13.9 percent from
15.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton welcomed the new data, saying: ``I am
extremely pleased with today's announcement. I believe it validates
our health care and economic policies.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of uninsured is still nearly 3 million higher than
when Clinton took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Since Congress rejected his proposal for universal health
insurance in 1994, Clinton has been advocating smaller steps to
expand coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau said that government programs, including
Medicaid and the new Children's Health Insurance Program, had
helped increase coverage among poor children and youngsters with
family incomes just above the poverty level ($13,290 for a family
of three).
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the bureau said, in the last year, there was no
change in the proportion of the population (24 percent) covered by
government health insurance programs.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people without insurance rose by an average of
more than a million a year from 1987 to 1998. The trend puzzled and
frustrated health care experts because it persisted in a strong
economy with low unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, the number of Americans with
employer-sponsored health insurance has been creeping up. But the
changes received little notice because they coincided with the
erosion of other types of coverage. For example, millions of
low-income people, including former welfare recipients, were losing
Medicaid. That erosion stopped last year. The number of people
covered by Medicaid held steady around 28 million, the Census
Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   Genevieve M. Kenney, an economist at the Urban Institute here,
said, ``The percentage of poor children without coverage has
dropped back to where it was in 1996,'' the year Congress passed a
landmark law limiting access to welfare.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, many employers have seen their health
insurance premiums rise by 10 percent to 30 percent, mainly because
of increased spending on prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald F. Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a
consumer group, said: ``The new Census Bureau numbers are welcome
news, but no cause for celebration. It's like a morning drizzle
after a prolonged drought.''
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the Census Bureau made these points:
</P>
<P>
   _ More than one-fifth of all poor children, and nearly one-third
of all poor people, are still uninsured. Nearly half of poor people
who worked full-time last year were uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   _ Households making less than $50,000 accounted for almost all
of the increase in insurance coverage. Among those with incomes of
$50,000 or more, there was no change in the proportion having
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hispanic people were more likely to be uninsured than any
other major racial or ethnic group. About 33 percent of Hispanic
people, 21.2 percent of blacks, 20.8 percent of Asian-Americans and
11 percent of non-Hispanic whites were uninsured last year.
</P>
<P>
   To compare states, the Census Bureau suggested using three-year
averages of data from 1997 to 1999. By this measure, the proportion
of people without health insurance ranged from a high of 24.1
percent in Texas to a low of 8.8 percent in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, New Mexico, California and Louisiana also had high
proportions of people without insurance. The comparable figures
were low for Rhode Island, Hawaii and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of people without health insurance was slightly
above the national average in New York, where 17.1 percent were
uninsured. The figures were below the national average in
Connecticut (11.5 percent) and New Jersey (15.4 percent).
</P>
</TEXT>
