<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-KOSTUNICA-NYT &LR;      09-28 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-KOSTUNICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC'S RIVAL OFFERS A NEW VISION OF SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Should Vojislav Kostunica take office as
Yugoslavia's new president, he wants, he says, to help shape a
country with a different sense of itself and its place in the
world, less isolated and neurotic, a normal European nation with a
good dose of skepticism toward U.S. foreign-policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of conversations in recent weeks, before and after
what he and his supporters insist was his victory in elections last
Sunday, Kostunica has outlined a vision that reads broadly like
this:
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia needs to redefine itself, with its republics, Serbia
and Montenegro, working out a new relationship if they can. It also
needs to work within the U.N. Security Council resolution governing
Kosovo to find a way to allow Serbs to return there with security,
within a democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, he said that Serbia needed to confront its own
past, especially in the last decade of Yugoslavia's civil wars.
Such a self-examination, he said, has been blocked so far both by
the incumbency of Slobodan Milosevic, who helped start those wars,
and by the nature of the regime that Milosevic built: a Communist
base infused by nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica (pronounced kosh-TOON-eet-zah), a 56-year-old
constitutional lawyer, said he would favor a form of state ``truth
commission'' of independent historians and experts to examine the
crimes and victims of all the parties to the Yugoslav wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a war in the former Yugoslavia, and we must try to
face the results and consequences of this war one way or another,''
he said. ``We must look at everything.''
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Kostunica traveled with a small retinue
all over Serbia, criticizing the socialist regime of Milosevic,
which he said had distorted the country's interests. His choice for
a national anthem is the Serbian one from the 19th century, he
often mentions God in his speeches, and he is proud of his family's
bourgeois and anti-Communist traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, nationalism is a natural state of mind, to be one who
belongs to a nation,'' he said. Such national feeling _ which might
be called patriotism elsewhere _ is not much different than that
felt by the British or the French, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   In his criticism of the United States and its policies, there is
more than a touch of the continental European view _ often
articulated by the French _ that the ``hyperpower'' of the United
States, with its enormous wealth and capacities, is often
unconscious and unheeding of the dignity and interests of other
nations. And Americans, he has said, often presume that what they
define as good is good for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``But being Serbian and European doesn't mean being
anti-American,'' Kostunica said. ``I have no stereotypes and
prejudices. What concerns me is state interests and policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica, who translated the Federalist Papers into
Serbo-Croatian in 1981, does see the Hague Tribunal on war crimes
in the former Yugoslavia as ``an instrument of American policy and
not of international law.'' He criticizes the tribunal for refusing
to examine possible war crimes by NATO leaders for the bombing of
civilian targets here (as both Amnesty International and Human
Rights Watch also believe). And he has said that he will not turn
Milosevic, indicted last year over alleged war crimes in Kosovo,
over to the Hague for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica refuses to be explicit now over whether he would turn
over Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic, the two Bosnian Serb
leaders indicted by the tribunal. They might be the price for what
Kostunica wants: a reentry into European institutions like the
Council of Europe and the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe, and the restoration of Yugoslavia as a respected member
of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech this week celebrating his apparent victory over
Milosevic, Kostunica spoke of showing the world ``that we are
worthy of the tremendous historic task, worthy of our ancestors,
worthy of our history.''
</P>
<P>
   He also speaks of the Serbian nation and of its historical
tragedies, of the enormous number of Serbian refugees inside
Serbia, of the need to help ``Serb brothers'' in the Bosnian Serb
republic, but with the clear acknowledgment that they live in a
different state, in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   And he says bluntly: ``Those who think that Serbia cannot exist
as a nation without Kosovo are wrong.'' Kosovo, like Jerusalem, he
said, ``is one of those problems without a solution, that must be
managed,'' even if it goes against ``the American view that every
problem can be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Nenad Stefanovic, a journalist for Vreme, an independent weekly,
said that Kostunica supported the Bosnian Serbs in the 1992-95
Bosnian war and _ like many Serbs _ backed their right to secede
from a Bosnia governed by Muslims and Croats. However, Kostunica
rejected the brutal expulsion and slaying of non-Serbs and never
supported paramilitary troops. ``He was a nationalist concerned for
the fate of his nation, but never against other nations,''
Stefanovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoran Djindjic of the Democratic Party, regards Kostunica's
politics as traditionalist and even primitive, but without the
murderous and malignant nationalism manipulated by those, like
Milosevic and the late Croatian leader Franjo Tudjman, who led
Yugoslavia into disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica, Djindjic said, ``is a necessary bridge'' between the
politics of the past and a more modern European future.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kostunica is a strong advocate of the rule of law, of an
independent judiciary, of a free press and university, and of
constitutional agreements binding states.
</P>
<P>
   After NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia last year, Kostunica said,
``I've realized that my views can be a normal, authentic policy
that suits most of the people in Serbia,'' and not just the
democratic opposition, from which he keeps a certain distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``And suddenly I find this new policy of mine is respected
abroad,'' he said this week, grinning _ ``by Europeans more, the
Americans less, but even there with some understanding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
