<SLUG> BC-E-COLUMN0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.29.00
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   _ IOC seeks to protect Olympics' cyber future
</P>
<P>
   _ Olympic reputation unscathed by drug scandals
</P>
<P>
   IOC TOO LATE: The International Olympic Committee is waging what
many believe to be a futile corporate war in an attempt to protect
the word ``Olympic.'' The IOC has hired a British firm to monitor _
and then legally hound _ any Internet sites using ``Olympic'' in
their addresses. So far, 1,800 sites have been told to cease and
desist, and the IOC has filed suit in federal court in the United
States to protect the O-word and its five-ring symbol. ``Technology
has completely overtaken the IOC,'' Ioannis Synodinos, an official
with the Athens 2004 Summer Games, told the San Jose Mercury News.
``The Internet is a huge invasion, and the IOC is trying to stop
it, but it can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee also now forbids Olympic athletes from writing
Internet diaries on their own Web sites or for their hometown
newspapers. Many Olympians have built their own sites _ aided in
Sydney, oddly enough, by official Olympic sponsor IBM _ but they
are prohibited from selling their diaries to any publication during
the Games. ``Maybe in 2004 but definitely in 2008, that will be the
first real Internet Olympics,'' says Synodinos. ``People will have
their PCs and they will watch the Olympics in the toilet _ or
anywhere else they want to. Billions of people can use a PC and you
can't deny it. It will be like radio. You won't be able to deny its
use.''
</P>
<P>
   SURVEY SAYS: Call it hypocrisy. While 98 percent believe that
the use of performance enhancing drugs is unethical only 7 percent
believe the problem has reached epidemic proportions at the Olympic
Games. So despite the recent rash of drug-use allegations, most
Americans have a favorable opinion of Olympic athletes. ``Americans
believe that steroid use is a big problem, but they feel it is more
of an international problem than an American one,'' said J. Nadine
Gelberg, Director of Harris Interactive's Sports and Entertainment
Practice, which conducted the survey.
</P>
<P>
   www.harrisinteractive.com
</P>
<P>
   DOWN UNDER DIARY
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson on the apparent false start that was not called
against American John Capel in the 200 meter finals:
</P>
<P>
   ``John Capel was robbed. He false-started, and it should have
been called back. Once a runner gets in the set position, he can't
move. Capel moved, and it wasn't called back. By the time the gun
went off, he was rocking back, trying to get back to a set
position. He was totally off balance. It's very unfortunate because
I believe he would have been the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   www.nbcolympics.com
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE 09.29.00
</P>
<P>
   SITES
</P>
<P>
   GRIGORIEVA VAULTS INTO AUSSIE POPULARITY
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, she moved from Russia to Australia. In her new
Olympic sport _ women's pole vaulting _ the new Australian
national, Tatiana Grigorieva, has become one of her country's most
searched for athletes on the Web after earning a silver medal. Find
photos, recipes, articles, a diary, upcoming events and more on the
comely Grigorieva's official site.
</P>
<P>
   www.tatiana.com.au
</P>
<P>
   EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   MODERATED CHAT: Discuss what you think about the 2000 Games, who
your favorite athletes are, and what your favorite sport is.
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. at www.sportsline.com
</P>
