<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5712 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-LONG0929-COX     09-28 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LONG0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pedroso edges Taurima; Americans shut out for first time
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ With apologies to Carl Lewis, Jesse Owens and Co.,
American long-jumping had never suffered a night quite like this.
Never before had U.S. long jumpers been shut out of a medal at the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough that Cuban favorite Ivan Pedroso walked off with
the gold medal that Lewis had claimed at the past four Olympics.
But the only American good enough to make the final proved to be
Dwight Phillips, a relative greenhorn in the event who finished
eighth overall.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, as he stood shaking his head, world record-holder
Mike Powell offered his coaching services to get the Americans up
to speed. Maybe he'd even come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to steer some of these guys who are in the CBA
(Continental Basketball Association) to the long jump,'' Powell
said. ``I'll teach them how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the gnashing of teeth inside the Olympic Stadium,
silver medalist Jai Taurima wandered by, an unlit filtered
cigarette in his right hand, a lighter in the other. The Aussie
enjoys pack-a-day habit and isn't afraid to down a few cold
Fosters.
</P>
<P>
   It was Taurima who created a mini-stink leading up to the Games,
dismissing the ``dark'' American jumpers as a ``bunch of
dribblers'' and suggesting they collectively don't perform well in
chilly weather, or on foreign soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these guys write (trash) about me,'' said Taurima, his
medal hanging around his neck. ``Look who is laughing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he regretted his earlier remarks, Taurima said, ``No
comment.''
</P>
<P>
   How about the nicotine habit?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just like all the other guys,'' he said. ``The long jump
is a pretty easy event to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The extroverted Taurima resembles radio shock-jock Howard Stern
with his scraggly dark hair and sunglasses. He has a handful of
tattoos, including a big S for Superman (``I think I can fly'') on
his left biceps.
</P>
<P>
   On his home stage, Taurima used the energy of the crowd to
almost steal gold from Pedroso, a three-time world champion. The
Aussie had three leads during the competition before Pedroso nailed
his winning mark on his sixth and final jump.
</P>
<P>
   Pedroso was bothered by a hamstring injury in Atlanta in 1996,
barely made the final and finished 12th. Here, the 28-year-old
Cuban won with an effort of 28 feet, 3/4-inch, just ahead of
Taurima's personal-best 27-10 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a competitor,'' Pedroso said. ``I know it is not over
until the last jump. It'd been my dream to win this medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips finished eighth with a best of 26-5 1/2, fouling on
four of his six jumps. He's considered one of the top young jumpers
after recently shifting his focus from sprinting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my best,'' Phillips said. ``I'm disappointed I didn't
win an Olympic medal, but I plan to be back in four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the Americans must wait to make Taurima eat his
words.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
