<HEADER>
A5713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-TRACK-MAIN0929-CO     09-28 0286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-MAIN0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Final greased for Greece
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ In the men's 200 meters, Greece is the word.
</P>
<P>
   A race left wide open by a hamstring injury epidemic in the U.S.
trials was won Thursday by Konstantinos Kenteris of Greece, hardly
a sprint hotbed.
</P>
<P>
   Kenteris benefited from the absence of Michael Johnson and
Maurice Greene, as well as the belated start by U.S. trials
champion John Capel, to deliver the host nation of the 2004 Games
its fifth and least likely gold medal in Sydney. Americans Coby
Miller and Capel brought up the rear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feared nobody,'' Kenteris said. ``From the moment I stepped
into the country, I realized the others didn't have anything better
than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Capel appeared to. He blasted through his semifinal
heat in 19.85 seconds, easily the best.
</P>
<P>
   But in the blocks for the finals, Capel rocked forward, then
back. As he was in retreat, the starting beep sounded. He ran well
but never recovered from the others' head start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I false-started,'' Capel said to his manager after
the race, meaning he expected the runners to be reset.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was ready to run, no question,'' Charlie Wells said of his
crushed client, a University of Florida dropout this year, where he
played wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Kenteris is a former 400-meter man who coped with injuries
during the mid-'90s, partly caused by one leg being longer than the
other. The only agony he has felt recently is from a sunken ferry
that killed scores this week in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this will relieve some of the pain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
