<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      09-28 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS, SEEING END OF TRYING QUARTER, PUSH MARKETS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reassuring comments by Procter &AMP; Gamble about
earnings helped pull stock prices out of a late-September slide
Thursday as two major gauges posted their biggest advance since May
30 and the Nasdaq market jumped 3.34 percent to regain more than
half the ground lost in the preceding five sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Traders and investors were relieved that an unusually bloody
quarter with many warnings about reduced corporate earnings was
coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the optimism evaporated after the formal 4 p.m.
close when Apple Computer warned that its fourth-quarter earnings
would be below estimates. Shares of Apple, which had climbed $4.56,
to $53.50 during regular hours, plunged more than 24 percent to
around $29.19 in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index gained 122.02 points, to 3,778.32,
narrowed its decline so far this year to 7.15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which is also heavily
weighted with technology issues, gained 31.72 points, or 2.2
percent, to 1,458.29.
</P>
<P>
   For the blue-chip Dow Jones industrial average, which joined the
S&AMP;P in posting its biggest gain since late May, it was Procter &AMP;
Gamble and J.P. Morgan each accounting for more than 30 points of a
surge totaling 195.70 points, or 1.8 percent. At 10,824.06, the Dow
is 5.85 percent lower than at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson, down $1.75, to $93.38, was the biggest drag
on the Dow industrials, with Eastman Kodak, pummeled after warning
of lower profits on Tuesday, losing another $1.19, to $41.31. Of
the 30 Dow stocks, 23 advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Exodus Communications, which agreed to buy Global Crossing's Web
unit, lost $4.13, to $49.13.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems was the most actively traded stock, with 90.5
million shares changing hands. It closed at $59.31, up $2.00, after
trading as low as $54.63.
</P>
<P>
   An analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein cut his rating of the stock
and also that of Nortel Networks. Nortel rose $3.7213, to $63.00.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial stocks were standout gainers, with Lehman
Brothers, Goldman Sachs and J.P. Morgan up more than five points
each after it was announced that Dain Rauscher, up $13, to $92.88,
was being sold to the Royal Bank of Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
