<HEADER>
A5722 &Cx1f; tth-z
u i BC-TRUDEAU-OBIT-SPI &LR;      09-28 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUDEAU-OBIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERRE TRUDEAU DIES AT 80 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Elliott Trudeau, a
provocative political figure who fought French-Canadian separatism,
died Thursday in his Montreal home. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   With the motto ``Reason Over Passion'' hanging above his desk,
Trudeau served as prime minister from 1968 to 1979, and again from
1980 to 1984. After retirement, he continued to decry
``unscrupulous politicians'' advocating independence for his native
Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   An active canoeist and skier _ he climbed Mount Athabasca in the
Canadian Rockies in his 60s _ Trudeau suffered in recent years from
Parkinson's disease and prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Although sometimes unpopular, particularly in Western Canada,
Trudeau grew in stature after retiring to his Montreal law firm
with only occasional forays against separatists and those
advocating so-called ``special status'' for Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the great prime ministers of our country and
there has been an outpouring of respect even among those who
disagreed with him,'' said Iona Campagnolo, a British Columbia
educator who was a cabinet minister under Trudeau.
</P>
<P>
   Former British Columbia Premier Dave Barrett, a political foe of
Trudeau, described him as ``an intellectual giant with a lovely
touch of arrogance. Humility was not his strong suit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He intellectually towered over 98 percent of Canadian
politicians, and for that matter 98 percent of North American
politicians,'' Barrett added.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau was cared for in his final days by his surviving sons
Justin and Sacha, products of his 1971 marriage, at the age of 51,
to 22-year-old Margaret Sinclar of Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The couple later divorced, but two years ago the family was
briefly reunited by tragedy. A third son, Michel, was killed when
swept into an alpine lake by an avalanche while on an early winter
cross-country ski trip to Kokanee Glacier Park in eastern British
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   In a tribute Thursday, President Clinton said Trudeau ``opened a
dynamic new era in Canadian politics and helped establish Canada's
unique imprint on the global stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau was the antithesis of today's ``pander bear''
politicians. He confronted critics and confounded interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I sell the Canadian farmers' wheat?'' Trudeau once
asked an interviewer, a remark that angered the Prairies. When
surrounded by angry striking postal workers in Montreal, Trudeau
rolled down his car window and offered an earthy suggestion
regarding , told them: ``Mangez de la merde!''
</P>
<P>
   At a Liberal Party fund-raising dinner in Vancouver, many in the
audience seethed when he said that British Columbians were hiding
behind their mountains from the problems of their country.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau displayed a sometimes-impudent humor, once performing a
pirouette behind the back of Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember him once standing at the top of a ski run at
Whistler, talking to reporters,'' said Campagnolo. ``He was toying
with them, saying, `Well, you know the quality of snow in British
Columbia is never as good as in Quebec.' He was extremely clever.
His intelligence was always at play.''
</P>
<P>
   A world traveler, human rights advocate and sometime law
professor, Trudeau won election to Canada's House of Commons in
1965.
</P>
<P>
   He burst on the national scene as Justice Minister, advocating
reform of Canada's laws against abortion and homosexuality with the
famous line: ``The state has no place in the bedrooms of the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau was picked as leader of the ruling Liberal Party and
became prime minister in April of 1968, in a campaign described as
``our Camelot'' by Roger Simmons, another former Trudeau cabinet
minister and Canada's consul-general in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Late in that campaign, Trudeau was watching a St. Jean-Baptiste
Day parade in Montreal. Separatist extremists began throwing rocks.
Other dignitaries scattered. Trudeau sat in his seat, staring
straight ahead, as projectiles flew past his head.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau was to lead his party to four election victories, the
last coming in January 1980, nine months after he was briefly
ousted from power. He bounded onto the stage of Ottawa's Chateau
Laurier Hotel, and declared: ``Well, welcome to the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trudeau was our single combat warrior,'' author Richard Gwynn
wrote in his biography, ``The Northern Magus.'' His main
confrontations came with those who would take his native Quebec out
of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   When separatist extremists kidnapped a British diplomat in
October 1970 and killed a provincial cabinet minister they were
holding, Trudeau invoked the War Measures Act. The act suspended
civil liberties and permitted police to detain hundreds of people
without charges. Troops patrolled Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The ``October Crisis'' saw a reporter verbally joust with
Trudeau over how far he would go to preserve law and order. Trudeau
ended the debate with three words: ``Just watch me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Trudeau also gave Canada its own constitution and Charter of
Rights. ``Canada is a much more just society because he was prime
minister,'' Campagnolo said.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau instituted a national policy of bilingualism, requiring
that French as well as English appear in all Canadian government
publications and in packaging. Once, at breakfast, when his then
mother-in-law objected to bilingual packaging, Trudeau told her to
just turn the cereal box around.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau was sometimes impatient with fellow politicians, even
those with whom he shared the cabinet table.
</P>
<P>
   ``He treated you as an equal until you showed him you weren't,''
said Simmons. ``He would test you. He would test you very quickly.
He would always have read his briefing materials. You got one shot.
If you weren't prepared, you never got back in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau fought Quebec separatists, and lampooned those Canadian
politicians who submitted to what he called the ``blackmail'' of
demands that special status for the French-Canadian province be
enshrined in Canada's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his fellow Quebeckers, Trudeau wrote in 1996: ``They
should not look for their `identity' and their `distinctiveness' in
the constitution but rather in their confidence in themselves and
in the full exercise of their rights as citizens equal to all other
citizens of Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Trudeau give any quarter to the ``blue-eyed sheiks'' of
Western Canada who wanted riches at the expense of other provinces.
He enacted a National Energy Program to put strict controls on
domestic oil prices at a time when the world price for oil was
soaring. Oil-rich Alberta howled in protest.
</P>
<P>
   The apex of Trudeau's career as single-combat warrior came in
the 1980 Quebec referendum on a form of succession from Canada. The
separatist forces were led by Quebec Premier Rene Levesque.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, one separatist leader sneered at the prime
minister's middle name _ Elliott _ suggesting that Trudeau was not
a true Quebecker.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau lashed back against the politics of race, noting that
his mother's maiden name was Grace Elliott and proclaiming pride in
his mixed ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum went down to a resounding defeat. At the
campaign's closing rally, Trudeau stood for minutes as the
pro-Canada crowd took up a chant: ``E-l-l-i-o-t-t! E-l-l-i-o-t-t.''
</P>
<P>
   On stage that night was Canada's present prime minister, Jean
Chretien, who said Thursday: ``Pierre Trudeau, the embodiment of
the dream of a just society, has left us. He is gone but his
unfinished work remains _ our country, Canada.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
