<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS NOTES INCREASE IN HEALTH COVERAGE FOR AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By   ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After rising for 11 years, the number of Americans
without health insurance declined last year, to 42.6 million, a
reduction of 1.7 million from 1998, the Census Bureau reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of people without insurance also declined for the
first time since 1987 _ to 15.5 percent in 1999, from 16.3 percent
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The robust economy and an expansion of government programs
contributed to the decline, economists and health policy experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   With the unemployment rate at 4.1 percent, a 30-year low, many
employers have found that they must offer health insurance to
attract and retain workers. In addition, low-income people are
receiving coverage from government programs created or expanded in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Mills, a statistician at the Census Bureau, said,
``The driving force behind this improvement was an increase in the
likelihood of people having employment-based health insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of people with health insurance through their
employers rose last year by 3.4 million, to 172 million. This
change accounted for 85 percent of the increase in the number of
people with health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   For children, as for the population as a whole, coverage
increased last year. The number of uninsured children declined to
10 million last year, from 11.1 million in 1998. The proportion of
children without coverage declined as well, to 13.9 percent from
15.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The number of uninsured is still nearly three million higher
than when President Clinton took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau said that government programs, including
Medicaid and the new Children's Health Insurance Program, had
helped increase coverage among poor children and youngsters with
family incomes just above the poverty level ($13,290 for a family
of three).
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the bureau said, in the last year, there was no
change in the proportion of the population (24 percent) covered by
government health insurance programs.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people without insurance rose by an average of
more than a million a year from 1987 to 1998. The trend puzzled and
frustrated health care experts because it persisted in a strong
economy with low unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald F. Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a
consumer group, said: ``The new Census Bureau numbers are welcome
news, but no cause for celebration. It's like a morning drizzle
after a prolonged drought.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
