<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUNYAN0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Runyan's strategy works to perfection
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Marla Runyan was wandering through Hartsfield
International in 1996, looking for her ride into town. Through her
blurry vision, 20-300 in one eye and 20-400 in another, she spotted
one of those signs held by chauffeurs with a name on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that say Marla Runyan?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   The legally blind 1,500-meter runner, first Paralympian ever to
compete in the able-bodied Games, cannot detect the clock on the
scoreboard, or even the hands on her watch. But Runyan could see
that only five first-heat runners finished in front of her
Thursday, and that was sufficient for a berth in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Nos. 6 and 7 runners in the next heat bettered her time
of 4:06.14, she would have been packing clothes and visual aids and
heading home. But she earned one of two wild-card spots in the cast
of 12 after the five automatic qualifiers from each heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel so fortunate,'' she said. ``A lot of positive
forces are helping me through.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Runyan does not bolt for the lead. She did so Thursday
with a plan in mind. Even if she did not hold on, she hoped a
mid-race kick would quicken the pace enough to give her a strong
time in sixth or seventh place.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan ran the first lap in an outside lane to avoid getting
caught in traffic. She gunned to the lead halfway through, then
began to back up _ all the way to seventh.
</P>
<P>
   A late surge moved her into sixth, and into Saturday's final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I made it,'' she said, grinning broadly. ``I have
nothing to lose in the final.''
</P>
<P>
   Runyan was charged up after seeing some Paralympian pals in a
pair of exhibition wheelchair races sprinkled between the night's
Olympic events. Louise Savage of Australia, winner of the 800
meters on wheels, and Saul Mendoza of Mexico, slickest in the men's
1,500, have trained at the Roosevelt Institute in Warm Springs.
Mendoza lives there most of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan believes she is becoming more acclimated to running with
limited sight. ``Ultimately,'' she said, ``I'm going to surprise a
lot of people (in the 1,500) in the years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Runyan's teammate, Suzy Favor Hamilton, running better than ever
in her third Games, punched in the second-fastest 1,500. Loping
through the darkness in sunglasses, she closed in 4:05.24, behind
only Nouria Merah-Benida of Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
