<HEADER>
A5746 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-DIVE0929-COX     09-28 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DIVE0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hoping to reach height of glory
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Mark Ruiz is afraid of heights.
</P>
<P>
   That's not unusual in the general population _ not everyone
wants to make the Harbour Bridge climb. But Ruiz is a diver, and on
Friday he'll be standing with his toes on the edge of the Olympic
10-meter platform, ready to plunge 33 feet to the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I'm not where I'm going to fall, then I'm all
right,'' Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   On the platform, he's in total control. Ruiz, 21, of Orlando,
and David Pichler, 32, of Fort Lauderdale, are the last chances for
the U.S. men to win a diving medal. They'll compete in prelims and
semifinals Friday, with the finals Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Ruiz went on an amusement park ride in
Orlando with his girlfriend and his stepbrother. ``I couldn't even
look down, I was so scared,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz was originally afraid of the platform, too. He was 14 years
old and remembers crying when he first stood so high over the
water. So how did his coach get him to do it? ``He said, `Either
you do it or you quit,''' said Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't quit. The diver who has been called ``the next Greg
Louganis,'' was born in Toa Alta, Puerto Rico, just outside San
Juan. He and his brother used to swing off trees into a little pond
or accompany their mother, Lydia, to a hotel with a pool. While
their mom gambled in the casino, the kids would splash and dive.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz started taking lessons when he was 4. The family moved to
Miami, back to Puerto Rico, and then to a strange city, Orlando,
when he was 12. Ruiz had fallen in love with Orlando at a training
camp. He begged his mother, who was divorced from Ruiz's father and
struggling financially, to move. She was hesitant, but did it for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I owe everything to her,'' Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother now owns a hair salon in Orlando, and when Ruiz was
younger he'd help sweep up. His father, John, died of a heart
attack just before Mark competed in the 1998 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Ruiz won the Pan American Games on 3-meter
springboard, and was considered a hero when he went back to Puerto
Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the U.S., and I love representing our country,'' said
Ruiz, who decided at age 12 that he would dive for the U.S., ``but
I'm also Puerto Rican.''
</P>
<P>
   On a scale of 1-10, with singer Ricky Martin a 10, Ruiz figures
he'd be a 7 or an 8, ``which is pretty good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's more used to comparisons with Louganis, the greatest diver
ever, and someone who has given him inside tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little more mechanical,'' said Ruiz, who has won 17
national titles. ``I would say Greg was more graceful in the air.
There's never been another diver like Greg. . . . That's what it's
all about in diving, making things look easy and graceful in the
air.''
</P>
<P>
   The back 3 1/2 tuck on platform is Ruiz's signature dive.
</P>
<P>
   On the perfect dive, he said, ``You go in the water and it feels
really smooth, The water just kind of goes really soft on you. I
feel the water hit the palm of my hand, pow , and you just know you
did a good entry.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
