<SLUG> BC-OLY-JONES0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marion Jones wins the 200 meters, giving her two golds with
three events left.
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ What do you call a second gold medal? If you're Marion
Jones, thrown deeper in the spotlight by a drug scandal involving
her husband, it's one word: relief.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the deep-red Olympic Stadium oval is her refuge. No
rumors, no in-your-face questions. Just do what you do best, and
pocket gold.
</P>
<P>
   Running as if scripted in an NBC production truck, Jones
comfortably took the 200-meter gold Thursday to go with an earlier
gold in the 100. Next up is the dicier long-jump final Friday,
followed by two relay medal opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, there was pressure coming to Sydney and
saying I was going for five gold medals,'' Jones said, reflecting.
``Then, of course, what happened the last couple days is not
necessarily pressure, but something that could easily have swayed
my focus. But it didn't, and I'm glad about that.'' Earlier this
week, it was revealed that Jones' husband, shot putter C.J. Hunter,
had tested positive for a performance-enhancing drug. The Sydney
newspapers have played the story to the hilt. Then, the Aussies'
favorite athlete, Cathy Freeman, and countrywoman Melinda
Gainsford-Taylor sprinted into the 200 final against Jones _ though
both finished deep in the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Jones wore a heavy parka in the 90 minutes between the semifinal
and final, spending her time on a nearby warmup track. The trace of
a smile crossed her face when, during introductions for the final,
the PA announcer identified her as: ``from the Bahamas. I beg your
pardon, from the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the distractions seemed to matter as Jones blitzed the
field in a season-best 21.84 seconds. Atlanta resident Pauline
Davis-Thompson, 34, won the silver medal for the Bahamas. Davis, a
five-time Olympian and the oldest runner in the field, finished
nearly five meters behind Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, at least, Jones wouldn't let on if the intense
scrutiny has unnerved her. She was calm and cool on the track. At
race's end, she carried flags of the U.S. and Belize on her victory
lap, just as she had after the 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us just started training this year,'' said Jones,
explaining her singular focus. ``It's been my dream for a lot of
years. All the days of having my mother take me to track meets . .
. So I'm not going to let one event, traumatic as it is, ruin that.
No way, no way.''
</P>
<P>
   The sprints were never thought to be a serious problem, anyway.
How she'll fare in the long jump and relays is anyone's guess, but
Davis-Thompson and Debbie Ferguson, a former University of Georgia
star and fifth in the 200, stand between Jones and another gold in
the 400 relay.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the team from the Bahamas reigning world champs, but
the U.S. squad is in disarray after injuries suffered by Inger
Miller and Gail Devers.
</P>
<P>
   Hyped after her silver-medal run, Davis-Thompson stood by Jones'
side offering coming relief and jabs about the relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it this way, we're the `96 silver medalist and `99
world champions, and we're still the underdog and we love that
spot,'' Davis-Thompson said. ``It's just going to make our victory
sweeter, Marion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody said it was going to be easy,'' Jones responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marion, we're going to give you a helluva race,''
Davis-Thompson said, laughing. ``I know you have a little Caribbean
blood, too, Marion. You're mother being from Belize. So you're like
one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of the 200 was Davis-Thompson, silver medalist in
the 400 at the 1995 world championships. A former training partner
of sprinter Gwen Torrence, she trains in Atlanta with coach Loren
Seagrave.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, she ran a personal-best 10.97 100 earlier this year, and
recently was named athlete of the century for the Bahamas. She was
expected to be a key member of the 400 relay, but few rated her a
medal favorite in the 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never gave up,'' said Davis, a semifinalist at the 1984
Los Angeles Games. ``It's been a very very long road to Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
