<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUMOR0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC dispels rumor of Athens' loss
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The International Olympics Committee, the premier of
New South Wales and the Athens Organizing Committee dismissed
rumors Thursday that Sydney might steal the Games from Athens in
2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athens is absolutely a certainty for 2004,'' said Franklin
Servan-Schreiber, the IOC director of communications. ``We are
impressed by the progress that has been made, and we will work with
them very closely to put on the best Games ever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not get excited about this,'' New South Wales Premier
Bob Carr said. ``No one has offered it to us. No one has asked us.
And we won't be doing 2004.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney's spectacular showing, coupled with the IOC's public
scolding of Athens earlier this year for being ill-prepared, had
prompted speculation that the 2004 Games might be played in Sydney,
or even Seoul, if Athens was not ready in time.
</P>
<P>
   But since the Greek government put Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki
in charge of the Athens committee in July, the IOC seems to have
changed its position.
</P>
<P>
   Said Angelopoulos on Wednesday: ``I don't pay attention to
rumors. I pay attention to facts. The fact is in August, at the
presentation to the IOC, we received comments like, `You are on
track. You have made an excellent job up to now. Of course it is
not easy because you only have four years instead of seven. You
have a new team. We are happy that your prime minister decided his
participation is needed. We are happy that the whole government
seems to understand that. We are with you, and we want you to
organize the best Games.' That is what I get, and nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
