<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOCC0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norway refuses to lose; gets winner in overtime
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The mantra of success for the U.S. women's soccer team
for the past decade has been its unremitting resolve in the clutch.
But the only nation that has shown any ability to match that will
to power over the years proved every bit as durable with the gold
medal on the line.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up a tying goal with seconds to play in the second
half Thursday, Norway could have fallen victim to what the United
States likes to describe as its special mentality for winning.
</P>
<P>
   But a ``golden goal'' by substitute striker Dagny Mellgren 12
minutes into extra time gave the Norwegians a 3-2 victory in front
of 22,848 at the Sydney Football Stadium, shattering the hopes of
an American team aiming for its third consecutive major
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a magic moment, that is all I can say,'' said defender
Gro Espeseth, who scored Norway's first goal a minute before
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that this was our day today. We were not going to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway, which gave up a fifth-minute goal to Tiffeny Milbrett,
who looked unstoppable in the first half, recovered to pull even
right before the intermission. The Scandinavians then hung together
after Milbrett's second strike gave the Americans what appeared to
be the momentum to pull off the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how to win,'' said Milbrett, who scored the dramatic
equalizer at the end of regulation. ``They just have our number.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Norwegians, the victory was the fourth over the
Americans this year, and runs their all-time record against their
venerable rival to 15-13-2. The U.S., winners of Olympic gold in
1996 and the World Cup last year, has been ousted from the only
major tournaments it has lost, including the 1995 World Cup, by
Norway.
</P>
<P>
   After being humiliated 2-0 by the U.S. on Sept. 16 in their
Olympic opener in Melbourne, Norway rebounded with a vengeance,
displaying the kind of counterattacking it used in beating the
Americans twice on home soil in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we are the best team in the world now,'' said outgoing
Norwegian coach Per-Mathias Hogmo. ``We have defeated the United
States four times, China three times and Germany twice this year.''
</P>
<P>
   For an American team completing a remarkable decade of
achievement, this loss surely was an emotional backbreaker. Moments
after Mellgren's clincher, U.S. players looked around the field in
a daze, showing no visible reaction. Whatever tears poured out were
left in the locker room. Nearly 30 minutes after receiving their
runner-up medals, several players emerged to put a good face on
their thwarted dreams. Only one of them, defender Brandi Chastain,
managed a convincing smile with a piece of silver dangling from her
neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people got the best game possible,'' said Chastain,
who wasn't a part of the 1995 World Cup team upset by Norway in the
semifinals. ``We played a great game out there. But you have to
give Norway credit. They scored goals when they needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm, who often has disappeared in the late stages of
tournaments, was superb in the final, teaming up with speedy
Milbrett to terrorize the slow-footed Norwegian defense early. They
created the opening score, and it was Hamm's cross with seconds
remaining in the second half that the 5-foot-2 Milbrett put home,
rising over two Norwegian defenders.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans found no rejuvenation from their rally.
Instead, Norway, which switched from a 4-4-2 to a 4-5-1 formation
to bottle up the U.S. attack after drawing even 1-1 at halftime,
waited for the right time to strike back.
</P>
<P>
   And the U.S. defense, so sturdy during the Olympics, fell apart
when pressed. In the 78th minute, central defender Joy Fawcett
mistimed a cross in the box to Ragnhild Gulbrandsen, who headed the
ball safely in the net as U.S. goalkeeper Siri Mullinix tried to
put up a final line of defense in vain.
</P>
<P>
   In extra time, another long ball, this one to Mellgren from Hege
Riise inside the center circle, bounced off Fawcett's head and onto
the shoulder of Mellgren, who knocked home the shot past a
sprawling Mullinix. U.S. captain Julie Foudy called for a handball,
but Canadian referee Sonia Denoncourt wouldn't hear of it.
</P>
<P>
   The gold medal had changed hands, and the Americans were in the
unusual position of consoling themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said to the players, 'Hold your heads up, you have
nothing to be ashamed of,' `` Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
