<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5754 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-28 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ALL AL AND W., ALL THE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Public Interests) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans are very sophisticated about the relationship between
politics and entertainment. Anybody can tell you that Richard Nixon
blazed the trail in 1968 when he appeared on ``Laugh-In'' and
muttered the show's catch phrase, ``Sock it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the first glimpses of the ``fun'' Nixon the nation
would later come to love.
</P>
<P>
   We know this story because it was an important moment in our
collective cultural history and also because it was the answer to
the first million-dollar question on ``Who Wants to be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nixon moment was one step in the road toward our current
controversy over the amount of time presidential candidates are
spending on television, talking about their families and favorite
foods. The other night you could flip back and forth between Al
Gore on MTV, looking stern at the mere mention of marijuana, and
George W. Bush on CNN, hanging out with Larry King. On NBC, I swear
I saw Dick Cheney mounting the pommel horse.
</P>
<P>
   (Has anybody noticed, by the way, that none of the candidates
have spent much time cheering on our Olympic athletes? This is
particularly disappointing in the case of Bush, who did such a
great job of psyching up the Ryder Cup golf team by reading them a
letter from the commander of the Alamo, vowing ``victory or
death.'' I think I am speaking for all Americans when I say that if
Bush had taken the trouble to read his Alamo letter to the women's
soccer team, they would not have lost to Norway.)
</P>
<P>
   We digress.
</P>
<P>
   Our topic today was whether the candidates are spending too much
time hanging around the softer side of the media, where they do not
have to answer tough questions. The whole debate is truly touching,
since it presumes that when they aren't on ``Oprah,'' Gore and Bush
are at the mercy of bloodthirsty journalists who are forcing them
to finally come clean about the contradictions in their Medicare
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the campaigns are so controlled that it's a challenge
to get much more than the message of the day, and in the case of
Gore, the press conference of every other month. If the TV hosts
think they can pry something surprising out of these guys, more
power to them. David Letterman gave it the old college try when he
demanded to know what Gore thought we should do about global
warming. (Great news! The problem can be solved by new,
job-creating technology.) Winfrey didn't exactly go for the
jugular, but it was still fun to watch the presidential candidates
groveling at the feet of a powerful woman. Gore was in such full
pander mode that when asked to name his favorite cereal, he blurted
out, ``Oprah.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's least threatening interviewer had to be Regis Philbin,
who spent an inordinate amount of time questioning him closely
about what the ``W.'' stands for. (``Walker ... of course, Walker.
... George Walker Bush. ... Yeah, yeah.'') Perhaps Philbin was
worried about all the trouble Bush had earlier in the campaign,
when people asked him about world affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning as TV entertainment has actually been with us since
the 1950s, when people acquired their first television sets and
immediately stopped showing up at political rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Eisenhower saw what was going on and hired a media
consultant, one of whose coups was to persuade CBS to air a
birthday tribute to Mamie Eisenhower in the spring of the 1956
election year, despite the fact that the first lady had actually
been born in late November. Adlai Stevenson, meanwhile, resisted
all attempts to make him more camera-friendly, and turned down an
invitation to appear as the mystery guest on the popular program
``I've Got a Secret.'' This cost Stevenson both valuable exposure
and the opportunity to become immortalized as a 21st-century quiz
show question.
</P>
<P>
   Now the airwaves are full of once and future candidates, and if
this race gets any closer, they'll be moving into the prime-time
lineup:
</P>
<P>
   Sunday _ Dueling centrists Bush and Gore attempt to elbow
Malcolm out of the Middle.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday _ The ``NYPD Blue'' gang gets to escort Gore to a
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Friday _ Bush appears on a special edition of ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire,'' limited to questions about people's middle names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
