<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones the main attraction tonight
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Marion Jones variety hour continues tonight with
her bid for the gold in the women's long jump. This is the last
individual event for Jones and figures to be the toughest one for
her to win. There's also the men's finals in the 1,500 meters and
the pole vault with American Lawrence Johnson in the latter, but
NBC hopes the other eye-grabber will be the men's basketball
semifinal between the U.S. and Lithuania. So far, Craig Sager's
memorable feature on Alonzo Mourning's sojourn from Sydney to Miami
for the birth of his daughter has been the highlight of the men's
basketball coverage in prime time. Perhaps high-flying Vince Carter
will provide a few more tonight. The U.S. women's basketball team,
led by WNBA stars Lisa Leslie and Yolanda Griffith, will be
showcased on NBC's late-night telecast when the semifinal against
South Korea will be shown. MSNBC plans to use the men's
bronze-medal soccer match between Chile and the U.S. as the
linchpin of its coverage, while the women's gold-medal match
between Australia and Argentina will augment the boxing semifinals
on CNBC where U.S. light welterweight Ricardo Williams is the
fighter to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
