<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-DEFENSE0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Dogs defense, gambling less results in fewer big plays
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ During the past three years, Georgia's defense has
offered more versions than Mircrosoft Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who ranked last in the SEC in defense last season,
have had five coordinators in eight years. But former Oklahoma
coach Gary Gibbs, hired in February to replace Kevin Ramsey, has
brought some stability.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday's game at Arkansas, Georgia is ranked second
in the SEC and eighth nationally in total defense, giving up only
235.3 yards per game. The Bulldogs rank first in the SEC against
the pass, allowing 93.7 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played hard,'' Gibbs said. ``We've made some mistakes,
which you are going to have every week, but they are correctable
mistakes. We've gotten a lot of good play from a lot of different
players.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change from last season is that Georgia isn't making
as many big mistakes. Only once in its first three games has the
defense allowed a play from scrimmage of more than 25 yards. Last
season, opponents had six plays of more than 25 yards in the first
three games.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, a defensive coordinator with the Sooners for eight
seasons in the 1980s, has installed a scheme that seems to take
fewer risks. Last season, Georgia's cornerbacks often played
bump-and-run coverage and tried to jam receivers at the line. In 12
games in 1999, Georgia gave up 28 passing plays of more than 25
yards.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the cornerbacks are playing farther back from the
line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know one thing for sure. They are going to be very sound,
very disciplined,'' Arkansas coach Houston Nutt said. ``I don't see
too many home-run balls going against them. That's been the most
impressive thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulldogs have yet to face a passing team as formidable
as the Razorbacks. Arkansas quarterback Robby Hampton is averaging
13.2 yards per completion and has thrown six touchdowns and two
interceptions. Razorbacks receiver Boo Williams leads the SEC with
a 28.8-yard average on 10 catches.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan said Williams, 6 feet 4 and 230 pounds, reminds him of
Auburn's Ronney Daniels, who blistered the Bulldogs for nine
catches and 249 yards in the Tigers' 38-21 victory in Athens last
season. Georgia cornerback Tim Wansley, who is about seven inches
shorter than Williams, will have the daunting task of covering him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe Wansley is one of the most competitive guys
we have here,'' Donnan said. ``He's fearless. He thinks he can do
anything. (But Williams) is a scary guy. We're going to have to
give (Wansley) some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs also has installed a five-man front, a change from
Georgia's 4-3 defense last season. One of the Bulldogs' defensive
ends is more of a down lineman, and outside linebacker Will
Witherspoon creeps to the line next to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's other defensive ends aren't rushing the quarterback as
much, either. The Bulldogs have only six sacks in three games, with
just one interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've still got to play the run first and the pass second,''
defensive end Josh Mallard said. ``Last year, our defense was kind
of like Florida State's, and they just let us run. This year, we've
got to be a little more disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   The new plan seems to be working so far. In the first three
games, Georgia's defense has carried its inconsistent offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we gave up a lot of big plays,'' linebacker Tony
Gilbert said. ``This year, we don't want to give up the big plays.
They can get the yards, just as long as they don't score on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
