<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UNC-RUSSELL0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stepping in for the Heels
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With his credentials from Atlanta's Marist School,
Brandon Russell could have attended Georgia Tech or Georgia on a
football scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against the state schools, but Russell wanted to broaden
his horizons.
</P>
<P>
   The Decatur, Ga., native passed on official visits to either and
chose North Carolina over Stanford and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wanted to get away from Atlanta,'' he said. ``I love
Atlanta; I just wanted something else. I had always heard North
Carolina was a nice place. I had the opportunity to look around,
and I didn't see anything nicer. Chapel Hill impressed me.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision already has proved to be a good one for both
Russell and North Carolina coach Carl Torbush.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday's regionally televised game against Georgia
Tech, Russell is the starting tailback and the Tar Heels' leading
rusher with 178 yards on 50 carries. He also has caught two passes
for 26 yards for the 3-1 Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most pleasant surprise is that Brandon continues to make
improvements at tailback,'' Torbush said. ``His two best games have
been the two previous games. We also had him returning punts and he
did an outstanding job.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell's best work came in the final minutes of Carolina's
comeback win over Marshall Saturday. Behind the blocking of
fullback Anthony Sanders, Russell gained 34 yards on six carries
during the Tar Heels' final 13-play drive, which allowed them to
milk the clock for the victory. He finished with 79 yards on 17
carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In coming up here, I wasn't sure if I was going to play or
redshirt or what,'' Russell said. ``As it turned out, it worked out
for me. To tell the truth, I didn't think I'd be starting. I didn't
think I'd just come up here and step in and start. It wasn't
realistic from my perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell also plans to play outfield for the North Carolina
baseball team, hitting .483 with 11 home runs and 23 stolen bases
as a Marist senior. He was selected by the Florida Marlins for the
Major League Showcase in 1999. That sport almost persuaded him to
stay in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was especially tempting at Georgia with that guy
(second-year coach Ron Polk) who (was) at Mississippi State there.
That was a real draw,'' he said. ``But all three of my final
schools would let me play baseball. I have a passion for both
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   In football, the War Eagles compiled a 51-4 record during his
four years at Marist, where he also played defensive back and
linebacker and blocked eight kicks. But he always flourished on
offense. He gained 1,697 yards, an average of 9.98 yards per carry,
and scored 29 touchdowns as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said hitting a baseball is harder than playing football.
But he has found something harder than both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played golf one time up here,'' he said. ``It was the most
frustrating thing I've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on his history, he will master that one eventually, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
