<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE SAYS QUARTERLY PROFIT WON'T MEET EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Apple Computer said Thursday that its
fourth-quarter earnings would fall far below analysts' estimates
because of weak September sales, an announcement that sent the
company's shares plunging in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've clearly hit a speed bump,'' said Steve Jobs, Apple's
chief executive, adding that before investment gains, Apple would
earn about $110 million rather than the expected $165 million for
the quarter, which ends Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though this slowdown is disappointing,'' Jobs said, ``we have
so many wonderful new products and programs in the pipeline,
including Mac OS X early next year, and remain positive about our
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple says it now expects earnings of 30 to 33 cents a share in
the fourth quarter, well below the consensus estimate of 45 cents,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company
earnings. The company said it expected to report revenues of $1.85
billion to $1.90 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Apple, which is based in Cupertino, Calif., made its
announcement after the close of the market. Apple shares, which had
closed at $53.50, up $4.56 on Nasdaq, dropped as low as $28.25 in
after-hours trading. Apple's last profit warning came a year ago
when the company's results lagged forecasts because of parts
shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Although Apple's loyal user base has often buffered it from the
seasonal swings of the broader personal computer industry, analysts
said the company was not immune to the global slowdown affecting
the business this quarter. Last week, Intel Corp. sent jitters
through the technology sector when it warned of a slow quarter,
which it attributed primarily to a soft market in Europe. Dell
Computer Corp. said in August that second-quarter sales rose more
slowly than expected because of weak demand.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the bigger fear for Apple was whether the
shortfall indicated that the company's much-heralded turnaround _
tied to Jobs' return to the helm and the introduction of the
popular iMac desktop computer _ had run out of gas. For Apple to
continue growing at the pace it had been, it has to claim new
computer users and former PC users for its Macintosh computers,
something it has been doing. Now it is unclear whether the company
can continue to make gains among those users, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time since Steve returned the company to
profitability in the fourth quarter of '97 that they've truly hit a
wall,'' said Charles R. Wolf, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read.
``It's not that its so dramatic a wall, but it is, in my mind, an
ominous one. The scary part is maybe their ability to attract new
users to the Mac platform will be more difficult in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Fred D. Anderson, Apple's chief financial
officer, attributed the expected shortfall to three factors.
``First, we experienced lower-than-expected September sales due to
a business slowdown in all geographies,'' he said. ``Second, our
education sales, which normally peak during September, were lower
than expected. And third, our Power Mac G4 Cube is off to a
slower-than-expected start, resulting in revenues below
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the G4 Cube has won rave reviews for its sleek design,
it appears to be selling primarily to Mac loyalists rather than
winning over new users, analysts said. The slowdown in education
sales, traditionally an Apple stronghold that accounts for about 25
percent of revenues, is particularly troubling, they said, because
it could indicate the loss of market share.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Apple began shipping a public beta test
version of Mac OS X, the new version of its operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the company would provide lower growth targets for
the next quarter and the next fiscal year when it announced final
results on Oct. 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
