<SLUG> BC-OLY-BUZZ0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We were robbed _ really
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As if finishing a disappointing fifth wasn't bad
enough for Atlanta kayaker Scott Shipley last week, he was a crime
victim shortly after going to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Shipley drove back from a party to the house he and teammates
rented at Penrith and went to sleep at 3 a.m. A half-hour later,
team leader Bob Campbell got back and noticed the car was missing.
He went inside and discovered other items gone, such as Shipley's
digital camera and the team VCR and camera. Police received an
anonymous tip and tracked down the stolen car at a house that day.
</P>
<P>
   Three men were arrested. Some of them were wearing clothes
stolen from the house. Unfortunately for Shipley, there was no
medal for the crooks to pilfer.
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDS IN HIGH PLACES
</P>
<P>
   Kay Poe's disastrous day ended on a happier note.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, the gold-medal taekwondo favorite in the
under 49-kg (108-pound) class was ousted in the first round. That
evening, however, she and friend Esther Kim sat at the venue with
IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch, and two IOC members asked to
meet them.
</P>
<P>
   Kim bowed out of the U.S. Trials finals against her injured pal,
which put Poe in the Games. Kim and her father, who coaches both,
are Samaranch's guests at the Games.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY ON, MATES
</P>
<P>
   It's getting to be party time in Sydney as athletes wrap up
competition and start having fun. Aussie swimmer Susie O'Neill
threw a party for teammates and friends at a Bondi beach club.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson celebrated his 34th birthday and his 400-meter
victory with a party at Planet Hollywood. Among the guests were his
wife, Kerri, Prince Albert of Monoco and women's 400 bronze
medalist Katherine Merry. ``I love Syndey,'' Johnson said. ``It's a
great city. Oi, Oi, Oi!''
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN'S VIEW
</P>
<P>
   Pieter van den Hoogenband's upset of Aussie swim star Ian Thorpe
in the 200 meter freestyle will be a focal point of Bud Greenspan's
documentary on the Games. Greenspan said he would also focus on
Cathy Freeman's victory in the 400 meters and the Opening
Ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   AND FINALLY . . .
</P>
<P>
   Scene at the tennis stadium: A woman was standing in the ramp
entrance to a section, breastfreeding her infant. Nearby, a man was
smoking a cigarette. She said, ``Could you move away from the baby,
please? Thank you.'' He complied.
</P>
<P>
   NO WAVING IN THE PRESS BOX
</P>
<P>
   While the ``wave'' is long gone as a crowd favorite at sporting
events in the United States, it remains popular in other countries.
At the Olympic Stadium Tuesday morning, spectators kept a wave
going for several minutes. When it reached the media section and
slowed down, the crowd booed, but fans in the upper deck kept it
alive.
</P>
<P>
   HEY, SOMEONE'S GOT TO DO IT
</P>
<P>
   The places journalist will go to get a story! As a ferry slowly
made its way to Manly, a North Sydney suburb, passengers noticed a
lone boat floating off to one side of the Olympic regatta. The tiny
motorboat was flying a flag that read ``Media.'' There were one
reporter and one photographer aboard, and they looked like they
were enjoying their lunch.
</P>
<P>
   WEBSTER'S THE TOP DOG
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Closing Ceremonies are expected to be a big celebration
for the athletes, with a major party and jam session taking place
on the field of Olympic Stadium. Among the Australian stars
expected to come out that night are singer-dancer Christine Anu,
rock star Jimmy Barnes, country legend Slim Dusty, opera singer
Yvonne Kenny and supermodel Elle Macpherson. But the night will
belong to 13-year-old Nikki Webster. The high-flying girl became an
overnight star at the Sept. 15 Opening Ceremonies. But by all
accounts she's just an ordinary kid who goes to school at McDonald
College in the Sydney suburb of North Stratfield. According to one
local newspaper: ``Her little dog, Star, got to wag his tail
madly'' when she got home from the Olympic spectacle the other
night. Awww.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
