<HEADER>
A5765 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-GREECE0929-COX     09-28 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GREECE0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Athens gets help in push for 2004
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ After a severe scolding from the International Olympic
Committee, the Athens 2004 effort is trying desperately to put its
house in order, and the person leading the effort seems to be
winning the confidence of the IOC and the public.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can salvage the Athens Games, it is believed to be
Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki _ a statuesque and striking
45-year-old with an impeccable political, business and academic
dossier.
</P>
<P>
   Though she was credited with single-handedly winning the Athens
bid in 1993, she remained behind the scenes until four months ago,
when Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis begged her to come to the
rescue of Athens, which appeared in danger of losing the Games. In
April, IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch said Athens faced the
worst organizational crisis he'd seen in his 20-year tenure, and
the Greek government assumed full responsibility for delivering the
Games on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I couldn't say, `I won't assist my country,' '' said
Angelopoulos, who is in Sydney with a team of 130 observers from
Athens. ``What I truly didn't know is that we need all the good
people, all the capable people. It's not the result of one
charismatic person or 10 charismatic persons. The government has to
participate. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``What I can see in Sydney is that they have made a good
coordination. Good people, good Games. It's a very strong effort.
It's a very hard task.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Angelopoulos also gave good marks to the
Atlanta Games and said that Athens will run its torch relay on five
continents _ an unprecedented and ambitious undertaking. She
praised Atlanta's egalitarian torch relay as a model.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we feel is that the Olympic torch really makes people
think about ideals and ideas like friendship, peace, like
tradition,'' she said. ``Like forget about divisions and think
about issues that we can share. It's a unique celebration of
Olympism.''
</P>
<P>
   As the first woman to run an Olympic enterprise, Angelopoulos
says each host city has to put its on stamp on the Olympics.
``Atlanta was different from Barcelona. Sydney was different from
Atlanta. Athens will be different from Sydney,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know (Atlanta bid organizers) Charlie Battle and Billy
Payne. They tried to organize the Games in their American model. I
personally very much liked the Games. And I know that NBC enjoyed
them very much, that they were very good Games. This is what really
counts to me. The masses, the spectators: They enjoyed great Games.
They had a lot of good sports, good results, good records. This is
what counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelopoulos, a former Athens city councilwoman and member of
the Greek Parliament, is married to Greek shipping magnate Theodore
Angelopoulos. She is a lawyer and serves as vice chairwoman of
Harvard University's John F. Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   The Athens organizing committee has been mired in the slow
machinations of Greek politics for the past three years, and the
IOC has expressed serious concerns about venues, transportation,
hotel accommodations and security.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Athens gave a good progress report at an IOC meeting in
Sydney on Sept. 12, it was told to deliver the venues _ now only
about 70 percent complete _ by the end of 2003, four months earlier
than the original deadline. Still to be built are the five venues
for yachting, rowing and canoeing, equestrian, softball and
baseball, and badminton and fencing.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek government has spent $634 million on infrastructure
improvements, including a new road system and subway. It is
spending an additional $981 million for a sports training and
education program throughout the country _ improvements that
Angelopoulos says ``has to do with motivating the country.''
Athens' organizing committee's operating budget is about $1.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Athens is clearly trying to promote itself as an idyllic tourist
destination. The Games will be played in the shadows of the
Acropolis and Mount Olympus, and Greece is a repository of
sun-splashed Aegean islands.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday night's Closing Ceremonies, Sydney will pass the
Olympic flag to Athens, and the Greeks will introduce themselves to
the world in an eight-minute segment set to music by ``Chariots of
Fire'' composer Vangelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first image of Greece that people will have,''
Angelopoulos said. ``It will be a way to show how Greece feels
about the Olympic Games. On the one hand, we promise to have a
state-of-the-arts Games. Athens, we believe, will be good for the
Games. On the other hand, we want to show where the Olympic Games
were born. They have a unique culture, a unique heritage, a unique
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelopoulos also extended an olive branch to Atlanta. She said
that Athens carried no grudges for the loss of the 1996 Centennial
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to win on merit and not by right. Athens was not ready
at the time. Atlanta was.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
