u a BC-OLYMPICS-AD-COLUMN-AR     09-28 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-AD-COLUMN-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SYDNEY OLYMPICS PROTECTING SPONSORS FROM AMBUSH
MARKETERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Photos
NYT19,20 are being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ It has become an urban legend at these
Olympic Games: Security guards are supposedly confiscating bottles
of Pepsi-Cola from visitors at the gates of the Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi, cracked the Sydney Morning Herald, is on the forbidden
list _ along with guns, knives and explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Not true, says the Sydney Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given no instructions for Pepsi to be confiscated,'' Bob
Bowden, a spokesman, said. ``People are allowed to bring food and
drink into the park. We haven't specified what kind of drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the denials, Bowden said the Olympic Committee had been
unable to snuff out the rumor. That may reflect the consensus, both
here and abroad, that Sydney has gone farther than any previous
host city to protect its official sponsors from being ambushed by
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico's archrival, of course, is Coca-Cola, which paid an
estimated $55 million to be a worldwide sponsor of the Olympics.
The company is blanketing Sydney's Olympic Park with red-and-white
umbrellas, lawn chairs and other reminders.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the 1996 Games held in Coke's hometown of Atlanta, Sydney
has kept so-called ambush marketers far from Olympic arenas and
sites. Although nonsponsor companies are visible here, Sydney has
little of the flea-market ambience that made the Atlanta Games a
byword for crass commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've really done a great job,'' said Gary Pluchino, vice
president of Carlson Marketing Group, which works for Olympic
sponsors IBM, Samsung Electronics and Eastman Kodak. ``It's
enormously helpful for these companies, which are using the Games
as a platform around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambush marketing is such a touchy subject because the costs of
an Olympic sponsorship are so high. The International Olympics
Committee's 11 worldwide sponsors plunked down $550 million for the
four years leading up to the Sydney Games, while local sponsors
paid an additional $315 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing better captures the difference between Atlanta and
Sydney than the role played by Nike. In 1996, Nike, the athletic
shoe and apparel maker, was the most aggressive ambush marketer of
the Games _ leasing a parking garage near Centennial Park to
promote its athletes and peddle its products.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Nike is inside the tent, as an Australian sponsor of the
Games. That status has allowed it to plaster its trademark Swoosh
all over Sydney without worrying about protests from other
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Among its showier gestures, Nike has wrapped a skyscraper in
perforated film painted with expansive images of three Australian
athletes who endorse Nike shoes: Cathy Freeman, the sprinter;
Lleyton Hewitt, the tennis player; and Lauren Jackson, a star
player on the women's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expected this to be a huge shift for us, like `You were
the black sheep of the family, and now you're the white sheep,'''
said Martha Ivester, the Olympics marketing director for Nike.
``But the reality is, we're doing the same marketing. People always
expect us to be in-your-face.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk, Nike seems to have mellowed. Four years ago,
it thumbed its nose at the whole concept of sponsorship. ``We don't
sell dreams. We sell shoes,'' declared an eight-page advertising
insert in Sports Illustrated. A television commercial said: ``You
don't win silver. You lose gold.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the tone is softer: Nike's commercials talk
about drawing on one's inner strength to win. The Australian
campaign has Olympic athletes promising to put their lives in order
after the Games.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Like other people at Nike, Ivester seems almost nostalgic for
the insurgent days of Atlanta, when Nike spurned a sponsorship and
still won more attention for its marketing than the officially
sanctioned companies.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ivester is excited about Nike's new status, she said
that the company _ because of its close identification with sports
and its superstar endorsers _ did not need the sponsorship as much
as nonsports companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point of being an event sponsor is to get visibility
for your brand,'' Ivester said. ``The moment Marion Jones steps on
the track wearing our shoes, we get all the visibility you could
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike only signed its deal with the Australian Olympic Committee
last December after its competitor, Reebok, pulled out after a
dispute over the scope of the agreement. By picking up the $5
million contract just nine months before the Games, Nike was able
to dictate its terms.
</P>
<P>
   Nike agreed to design and produce uniforms for the Australian
athletes, but not the 47,000 volunteers who work at the Olympic
Park. The company obtained waivers of an International Olympic
Committee rule that prohibits the use of Olympic athletes in
advertisements during the two weeks of the Games. As part of its
agreement, Nike has also been allowed to build mobile playgrounds
around Sydney that feature Nike products.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the company's promotional efforts were centered on
Nike Park, a flashy complex near Centennial Park that drew crowds
and the envy of less inventive sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Marketing coups like that are all but impossible here because
most of the sporting events are concentrated in the
tightly-controlled Olympic Park at Homebush Bay. Not only is the
park free of ambush advertising, the organizers have bought up most
of the billboards on the surrounding roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly helps to have a new facility that is not
surrounded by buildings on which you can hang big fluorescent
signs,'' Bowden of the organizing committee said. ``You've
basically got to hijack the airspace above the park if you want to
get a marketing message out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Bowden points out, skywriting over Homebush is prohibited
by the Olympic Arrangements Act, a government law that covers
everything from security and parking to airspace. The act permits
the authorities to remove unauthorized advertisements in the
vicinity of the park that are deemed to be ambush marketing.
</P>
<P>
   While it says it has not yanked bottles of Pepsi, the Sydney
organizing committee has let little else slip by. A catering
service in the park was ordered to change the appearance of its
bacon-and-egg roll because it looked suspiciously like an Egg
McMuffin _ McDonald's is a worldwide sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out to ban legitimate marketing,'' Bowden said.
``But we want to protect the investment of our main sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in Sydney, the Olympic committee cannot eradicate every
incidence of ambush marketing. Among sportswear manufacturers, the
Italian company Fila has taken up the mantle of Nike. In 1998, it
leased a replica of Britain's legendary 18th century sailing ship
HMS Bounty, the crew of which mutinied against Capt. William Bligh
on a commission to Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   The ship _ its fluttering foresail emblazoned with the Fila name
_ is tied up at a wharf in Sydney's harbor. The company uses the
ship to wine and dine clients. But its biggest value is as a
floating advertisement: it sits just across the bay from the iconic
Sydney Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   Alessandro De Pestel, Fila's vice president of communication,
said the company spent $2 million on its Sydney marketing campaign.
That compares with $10 million for a full-fledged Australian
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has learned from Nike,'' said De Pestel, as he
relaxed with a double espresso on the Bounty replica's quarter
deck.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Nike has gone easy on Fila, Adidas, and other
nonsponsors that are practicing ambush marketing here. Adidas, for
example, has widely trumpeted its association with Ian Thorpe, the
17-year-old Australian swimmer who won two gold medals. That may be
because Nike is likely to revert to its outsider status in future
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the U.S. probably wouldn't know who Ian Thorpe is if
Adidas hadn't done so much advertising with him,'' Ivester said.
``Does that make us mad? Kind of yes, kind of no.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   There are no mixed feelings between Australia's two airlines,
Qantas Airways and Ansett Australia, owned by Air New Zealand,
which are engaged in the most rancorous battle between a sponsor
and an ambusher. Ansett is the official airline of the Games;
Qantas, the longtime carrier of the Australian Olympic team, was
left out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Television viewers could be forgiven for thinking it was the
other way around. By signing an estimated $8 million deal with
Australia's Seven network, the local broadcaster of the Games,
Qantas has been able to place its commercials around the hottest
events involving Australian athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse for Ansett is the Qantas theme song, ``I
Still Call Australia Home,'' which has become the unofficial anthem
of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   While Ansett has managed to keep the song out of formal Olympic
ceremonies, one of Australia's gymnasts chose it for her floor
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been disappointed with a lot of the ambush activity
undertaken by our competitor,'' said Jane Corbett-Jones, a
spokeswoman for Ansett. ``But we're satisfied that our sponsorship
has met the objectives we originally set out.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Qantas theme song?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that it evokes a lot of sentiment among
Australians,'' Corbett-Jones said. ``One way or another, the song
is going to be played, and there's not a lot we can do it about
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
