<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-SPEND-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOPGAP BUDGET MEASURE APPROVED BY SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate passed a stopgap spending measure
Thursday that will allow the federal government to function through
Oct. 6, seven days after the end of its fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate's 96-0 vote to approve the short-term spending
measure and the House approval of the legislation on Tuesday,
Congress has now given itself more time to debate the remaining 11
spending measures that finance a variety of federal agencies,
including the State Department and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Only two spending bills _ one a $288 billion measure for the
military and another, smaller, bill that provides funds for
military construction _ have been approved by Congress and signed
by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During a lengthy debate in the Senate on the stopgap financing
bill, known as a continuing resolution, Democrats criticized
Republicans for failing to enact the 11 spending measures,
comparing the Republican-controlled legislature with what President
Harry Truman called the ``do nothing'' Congress of 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid that we have now developed an operating procedure
around here that is a disaster,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.
``We end up with no accountability and no control and chaos at the
end. That's where we are today. This is chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Democrats' ire has been directed toward Republican
leaders who have held off presenting for Senate passage three major
spending bills. One finances the Department of Veterans Affairs and
the Department of Housing and Urban Development, another provides
money for the Commerce, Justice and State departments; the third
authorizes the budgets for the Treasury Department and other
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have also expressed anger at a tactic the
Republican leaders had used recently. They had asked the Senate to
vote on a House-Senate conference spending measure for military
construction projects that included the full spending bill for the
Treasury Department, even though the Senate had not debated or
voted on the Treasury measure. The bill was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are poisoning the institutional role of the United States
Senate, rendering it weaker and weaker in influence and
usefulness,'' said Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Republicans said they had to use unorthodox
methods to get spending bills passed because Democrats had been
stalling, attaching amendment after amendment to spending bills to
delay passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the process has broken down,'' said Sen. Robert F.
Bennett, R-Utah. ``If I were to look for a place to place blame,''
he said, ``I would look towards'' the Democratic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the finger-pointing, some lawmakers acknowledge that
one cause of the slow pace is the caution bred by a fear of making
a political mistake at a time when the balance in the House and the
Senate, as well as in the presidential race, rests on a razor's
edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stars are all aligned,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb.
``You are going to elect a new president and both houses are in
play. That doesn't happen often.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even as Congress gave itself some breathing room to work out
agreements between Republicans and Democrats and between Capitol
Hill and the White House, the House moved toward a confrontation
Thursday with the administration about the water flows of the
Missouri River.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 301-117, the House approved a compromise worked out
in a House-Senate conference on a $23.6 billion spending measure
that finances the Department of Energy, including the national
laboratories where nuclear weapons are developed, and a host of
other federal water and energy programs. The Senate is scheduled to
consider the House-Senate conference measure next week.
</P>
<P>
   The energy and water bill, however, also contains an amendment
that halts the Army Corps of Engineers from revising its plan to
manage the upper reaches of the Missouri River.
</P>
<P>
   For years, environmentalists have urged the corps to increase
the springtime Missouri flows, thus providing a more hospitable
habitat for threatened species like the pallid sturgeon and two
endangered birds, the piping plover and the least tern.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed change is opposed by down-river lawmakers in
Missouri like House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, a Democrat,
and Sen. Christopher Bond, a Republican. They say that changing the
water flows of the Missouri in the spring could mean reduced flows
in the river in the late summer. As a result, Bond has argued,
barge operators would have difficulty navigating the river.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists and other Democrats _ including Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, an up-river lawmaker from South Dakota
_ have prevailed upon the administration to veto the measure.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, wrote
a letter declaring that unless the amendment barring the Corps of
Engineers from revising its management of the Missouri was dropped
or substantially modified, ``the president will veto this bill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
