<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUJIMORI LOOKS FOR U.S. SUPPORT TO MOVE PAST CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As tensions deepen for him at home, President
Alberto Fujimori of Peru flew to Washington on Thursday to seek
support from the United States and inter-American countries and
organizations for his plan to transfer power to an elected
successor, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's trip stunned Clinton administration officials, who
last week were acutely worried that he might be ousted by military
officers loyal to his fired intelligence chief, Vladimiro
Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   Those fears eased somewhat after Montesinos took refuge in
Panama. But American officials said that Fujimori's hold on power
remained precarious and that Montesinos remained capable of
influencing events in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Peruvian lawmakers have withdrawn their support from
Fujimori, and an 11th has been expelled from his Peru 2000
coalition since the president announced on Sept. 16 that he would
call elections.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers' departure has cost the autocratic Fujimori his
majority in the congress and confused a political climate that was
for nearly a decade anchored by him and his rarely photographed but
ubiquitous spy chief, Montesinos. The congress did, however, accede
to Fujimori's request to abolish the National Intelligence Service,
which Montesinos led.
</P>
<P>
   In several areas of Peru, a transportation strike gained ground.
The affected zones included the second-largest city, Arequipa.
Dozens of Peruvians were arrested in protests in coastal cities as
demonstrators called for a lower fuel prices, lower unemployment
and Fujimori's immediate departure.
</P>
<P>
   After a round of hurried calls to Washington late Wednesday,
Fujimori arrived and met Cesar Gaviria, the secretary general of
the Organization of American States. Since denouncing Fujimori's
re-election in May as fraudulent, the 34-nation hemispheric forum
has pressed him to hold a new vote. A senior administration
official said Fujimori, after having spurned the OAS for months,
was now seeking its embrace to thwart political or military
challenges at home as he arranged a transition. Fujimori's aides
have indicated that he is considering holding elections in March,
with the inauguration of a president in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coming to the OAS to lift his standing and to show he's
in control,'' the official said. ``It's very gutsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Fujimori's challengers is the democratic opposition, which
includes Alejandro Toledo, the candidate for president who withdrew
from the race in the spring as signs of electoral fraud developed.
</P>
<P>
   There also a small but powerful group of army leaders who owe
their careers to Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fujimori is trapped between the military, which wants
Montesinos back or wants a coup, and the opposition which wants an
immediate transition,'' said Eduardo Gamarra, an Andean expert at
Florida International University.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the army leaders sent menacing signals to bolster
their demand that Montesinos be granted permanent haven in Panama.
Panamanian authorities are considering his request for asylum, a
status that would make it harder to prosecute him for political
extortion, murder and other abuses attributed to him by human
rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   American officials and Gaviria, a former president of Colombia,
had pressed President Mireya Moscoso of Panama to admit Montesinos
in the first place. The officials said it would be up to Peruvian
and Pananamian officials to determine whether he should be
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Montesinos, who reportedly has
vast files on Peruvians, including Fujimori, has long had an
informal relationship with the Central Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori is scheduled to meet with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright on Friday morning. American officials privately said he
appeared determined to protect a mixed legacy. It has weakened
democratic institutions, but it has also neutralized threats posed
by guerrilla groups, fought the narcotics trade and opened up the
Peruvian economy.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the State Department, Philip T. Reeker, said,
``We will, of course, when we do meet with President Fujimori,
emphasize our support for a peaceful, democratic, constitutional
transition of power for the continuation of that OAS dialogue that
has been going on and which we very much supported.''
</P>
</TEXT>
