u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT &LR;      09-28 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRESTONE UNEASY OVER THREATENED CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Bridgestone/Firestone Inc., which is struggling to
cope with the recall of 6.5 million Firestone tires, can chalk up
one more problem: growing uncertainty about who will be running the
company in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Yoichiro Kaizaki, the president of Firestone's parent,
Bridgestone Corp. of Japan, created the uncertainty two weeks ago
by declaring that a management reshuffle was likely at its U.S.
subsidiary, which is based in Nashville. But there has been no
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   There was a flurry of reports in the Japanese media Thursday
that Masatoshi Ono, Firestone's chairman and a protege of Kaizaki,
would be demoted. Bridgestone, based in Tokyo, denied the reports
while repeating that management changes might be coming. Kaizaki
``may be considering a kind of management reshuffle, but nothing
has been decided,'' Ken Kitawaki, Bridgestone's manager of public
relations, said in a telephone call from Nashville, which he is
visiting this week.
</P>
<P>
   Crisis management experts say that promising a shake-up without
taking immediate action is a bad idea because it tends to undercut
the authority and morale of the people who might be losing their
jobs. ``It puts everyone on tenterhooks, because they don't know
what their role is going to be in the future,'' said C.B.
Bhattacharya, an associate professor at Boston University who
specializes in how corporations manage their reputations during
crises.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone is already struggling to preserve its brand in the
face of Congressional hearings and investigations by federal
regulators and the attorneys general of 39 states. Complaints to
regulators have linked the tires to 101 deaths and more than 400
injuries. Almost all of the deaths and injuries have occurred in
Ford Explorer sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion at Firestone came as the tire maker and Ford Motor
Co. also quarreled publicly over the role that Firestone would play
in supplying tires to the next generation of Ford Explorers,
beginning with the 2002 Explorer, which is scheduled to go on sale
in January. Firestone said in a statement Thursday that it ``is
slated to be the sole supplier on the 2002 Ford Explorer when it
launches in 2001,'' and that other tire makers would become
involved later.
</P>
<P>
   But Della DiPietro, a Ford spokeswoman, denied this, saying that
Ford had been working with Michelin as well as Firestone since 1997
to supply tires for the next Explorer, and that Michelin tires
would be available from the beginning. Lynn Mann, a spokeswoman for
Michelin, said ``We're happy to stand behind Ford's announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Firestone said in a statement Thursday night that Michelin would
be providing some tires. Separately, Ford has also said it is
talking to Goodyear about tires for the 2002 Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   In a potentially ominous development for Ford, Blueovalnews.com,
a Web site devoted to news about Ford, plans to announce on Friday
that it will share information with regulators about patterns of
defects in Fords. Blueovalnews is popular with technicians at Ford
dealerships, and Robert Lane, the site's founder, said that the
site would allow technicians and the public to fill out forms
online about vehicle problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said that Blueovalnews had been asked unofficially by
officials at the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to
begin collecting the data. Tim Hurd, a spokesman for the NHTSA,
said the agency had not officially asked the Internet site to
provide information but added that one or more investigators might
have asked it to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Vaughn, a Ford spokesman, said that the site's efforts
were unnecessary because Ford already gathers information from its
dealers and works closely with regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
