u f BC-NASDAQ-TRADING-NYT &LR;      09-28 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-TRADING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ AMENDS PROPOSAL FOR NEW TRADING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Responding to criticism that their plan for a more
centralized system for executing stock trades treated some
investors' orders unfairly, Nasdaq Stock Market officials revised
the proposal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan, which is subject to approval by the Securities and
Exchange Commission, is an attempt to mollify the operators of
electronic communication networks, known as ECNs.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of these networks, which allow investors to meet
without a middleman, had complained that the previous Nasdaq plan
put them at a disadvantage because prices posted by an ECN on the
system would have included the trading fees they charge. Adding
such fees to prices posted by ECNs would have made them less
attractive to other investors looking for the best price on a
Nasdaq stock.
</P>
<P>
   Under the latest plan, Nasdaq will no longer post prices on its
system based on the inclusion of ECN access fees. Nasdaq officials
say the new plan will allow its users to choose which market
participants they want to deal with. ``This is a fair resolution to
this issue,'' Richard G. Ketchum, president of Nasdaq, said. ``It
is hard to argue with letting the market decide.''
</P>
<P>
   The change led one ECN that had been critical of Nasdaq's new
system to support the plan. Kevin Foley, chief executive of
Bloomberg Tradebook, said: ``If implemented along the lines
envisioned, it will be a dramatic enhancement for investors and all
market participants.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials at other networks, including Archipelago ECN,
remain opposed to the Nasdaq plan. Douglas M. Atkin, president of
Instinet, the largest ECN, said that if Nasdaq allowed market
participants to choose whom they do business with in the system,
some investors' orders that should have priority might never be
executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of fixing the problem and saying investors' orders are
not going to be discriminated against, they dismantled price/time
priority by adding something they call choice,'' Atkin said.
``Every other market in the world lets the first person there get
the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The revised proposal did not address the issue of how the Nasdaq
system would display prices offered by competing exchanges, like
the Pacific Stock Exchange. Under the original plan, prices from
these exchanges were set to appear well below the quotations of
other market participants and would thus presumably attract fewer
investors. In announcing its revised plan, Nasdaq acknowledged that
additional work would have to be done to make sure prices posted by
exchanges were treated equally.
</P>
<P>
   Some institutional investors who had criticized Nasdaq's earlier
plan declined to comment on the revision until they could read the
amendment, which Nasdaq officials said would be filed with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell anything from what a press release says,'' said
Harold Bradley, senior vice president at American Century
Investments. ``It's in the details where you get stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
