<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-PATIENT-PROTECT-NYT &LR;      09-28 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENT-PROTECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DIRECTOR PUSHES FOR STRICTER STANDARDS ON EXPERIMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP J. HILTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new head of the federal office that oversees research on
people said the system is flawed and will be revised to increase
protections for human subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Greg Koski, who took over as director of the Office of Human
Research Protections this month, said that because of the
increasing number of experiments involving people, stricter
standards were needed.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he would ask universities to verify that scientists
dealing with human subjects have formal training in ethics. He also
said that the review boards at the universities that approve human
experiments must show they have sufficient staff and expertise to
conduct proper ethical reviews of proposed experiments. In
addition, he is asking the Institute of Medicine at the National
Academy of Sciences to devise a way to measure the performance of
the scientists and boards.
</P>
<P>
   The moves come after a series of lapses in experiments that
Koski said has shaken public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, 18-year-old Jesse Gelsinger of Tucson died in a gene
therapy experiment in Pennsylvania. And during the past two years,
the federal government has shut down human research at eight major
universities and hospitals for failure to abide by the nation's
ethical rules. In addition, 34 universities and hospitals were
cited for similar violations.
</P>
<P>
   Koski said that he hoped that most of the changes could be
carried out by research centers voluntarily. But if they were not,
public sentiment likely would force Congressional action to mandate
such standards, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must move beyond the culture of compliance, to move to a
culture of conscience and responsibility,'' Koski said at a news
conference at his office in Washington on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, there has been no certification or accreditation of
scientists or review boards to make sure they have formal ethics
training. Federal officials do not even know how many review boards
there are in the United States, how many experiments are conducted
on humans, or exactly what qualifications researchers and ethics
reviewers have. Not surprisingly, federal oversight has been
minimal.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Koski said, the certification of scientists and
supervisory boards by universities and medical centers would remain
voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, he said his office has the option of suspending
any program that gets federal funds to carry out research. Research
carried out with private funds is not covered by the system.
</P>
<P>
   Adil E. Shamoo, vice president of Citizens for Responsible Care
and Research, a nonprofit group that has criticized government
supervision of human experiments, said the moves were ``good first
steps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will now depend on how they are carried out, and whether
they can address the weakest link in the system _ that the review
boards themselves are employees of the institutions doing the
experiments. That conflict of interest is the central problem,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
