<P>
   (NYT19) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 28, 2000 --
OLYMPICS-AD-COLUMN-1 -- The International Olympics Committee's 11
worldwide sponsors plunked down $550 million for the four years
leading up to the Sydney Games, while local sponsors paid an
additional $315 million. Among sportswear manufacturers, the
Italian company Fila has taken up the mantle of Nike at the Games
in Sydney. In 1998, it leased a replica of Britain's legendary 18th
century sailing ship H.M.S. Bounty, the crew of which mutinied
against Capt. William Bligh on a commission to Tahiti. The ship,
its fluttering foresail emblazoned with the Fila name, is tied up
at a wharf in Sydney's harbor. (David Frank/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MONTREAL -- Sept. 28, 2000 -- OBIT-TRUDEAU -- Pierre
Elliott Trudeau, the long-serving prime minister of Canada who
successfully defended his vision of federalism and a unified nation
against the aroused forces of Quebec separatism, died Thursday in
Montreal. He was 80. Trudeau had suffered from Parkinson's disease
and prostate cancer and, more recently, pneumonia. Throughout his
career, Trudeau succeeded in altering his country's traditionally
staid and fusty image with atypical flamboyance. He was a dashing
figure who made his countrymen proud that a Canadian was so highly
visible on the world stage. Trudeau during an interview with The
New York Times in 1968. Trudeau walking to work to his law office
in Montreal in October of 1999. (Robert Galbraith/The New York
Times)
</P>
