<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5783 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USCFEA-LADN-(SLAN     09-28 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCFEA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC NEEDS BIG ROAD PRODUCTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sign No. 1 USC is a different team:
</P>
<P>
   During halftime of the Trojans' 34-24 victory over San Jose
State, center Eric Denmon lambasted his teammates in the locker
room for their sloppy efforts. And he had a captive audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always have players speak out, but it only means
something if players want to listen,'' linebacker Zeke Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   Denmon's message, with USC trailing by 12 points, was simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, being down 12 points at halftime, they would have
given up,'' Denmon said. ``I just told the team we're not playing
like we were practicing. Just because we were ranked ninth, that
didn't mean anything. I told them that in so many words.''
</P>
<P>
   Denmon's speech apparently worked, because USC ended up
outscoring San Jose State 22-0 in the fourth quarter to pull out
the comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   It's a major reason the eighth-ranked Trojans (3-0) believe they
are better equipped to handle adversity this season.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Trojans really are a different team, they need to
demonstrate they can win on the road and in a hostile environment,
something they haven't done consistently in the Pacific-10
Conference during coach Paul Hackett's first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   USC will get the chance to clear this barrier when it plays
undefeated Oregon State (3-0) Saturday at Reser Stadium in
Corvallis.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are 3-5 on the road under Hackett, but all three
victories (Washington State twice, Stanford) came against teams
with losing records.
</P>
<P>
   Anytime USC has played a quality opponent, or for that matter, a
team above .500, it has found a way to lose. And usually, the
Trojans were their own biggest enemy, on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, usually only one phase would do well, primarily
the defense was our strength,'' Denmon said. ``There would be a lot
of bickering on the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive stats certainly show an inconsistency on the road.
In USC's Pac-10 road losses under Hackett, the Trojans averaged 18
points per game. In their victories, they averaged 36 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we lost most games was because of mental errors or
mistakes,'' quarterback Carson Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The offense's ineptness usually caused the defense to feel the
strain of trying to hold an opponent down, aware the offense
wouldn't be able to rally from a deficit. Sometimes, worrying about
it too much would backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past couple years, we had a knack for letting the big play
happen against us,'' cornerback Kris Richard said. ``There was a
lack of focus. Not necessarily a lack of emotions, but we had a
big-play syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are optimistic these problems will not resurface in
Corvallis. Even Hackett believes this year's team is better
prepared to handle playing in a small, loud, sold-out stadium that
seats little more than 35,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a different team. The leadership and response in the
fourth quarter is different,'' Hackett said. ``But this game is a
big hump. We've got to get over this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this is only the first Pac-10 game for both teams, the
players realize the stakes are high, particularly as the Trojans
continue to build confidence from their perfect start.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose this one, the whole season will build off that,''
fullback Charlie Landrigan said. ``We can't look ahead to any
games. That's what's bitten us in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Denmon: ``Both teams have a lot to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The loser immediately falls into the back of the pack in the
Rose Bowl race and needs the winner to lose two conference games to
keep its hopes of playing in Pasadena alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will gunning for us,'' Landrigan said. ``Winning there
would be big.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hackett feels good about one thing going into the game, it's
USC's 29-5 victory over Penn State last month in the Kickoff
Classic. While Giants Stadium was a neutral field, the crowd of
more than 78,000 was overwhelmingly pro-Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be a good football team, you have to play
on the road and win,'' Hackett said. ``Now, I feel good about
playing in New York. We went on the road and won. This would have
been our first road game if we hadn't played there.''
</P>
<P>
   There won't be as many fans at Oregon State, but they will be
closer to the field. And many of the Trojans weren't even around
the last time USC played in Corvallis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we haven't experienced,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   But as serious as USC regards the game, that doesn't mean the
Trojans haven't sometimes been lighthearted when pondering the
prospects of playing away from the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of pressure on the road. Traveler won't be
there,'' Denmon joked, referring to USC's horse mascot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
