<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5790 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-ABORTION-GORNEY-     09-28 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-ABORTION-GORNEY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION CHANGES, BUT HOW MUCH? 
</HEADLINE>
  (New York Times OpEd for Friday, Sept. 29, 2000, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By CYNTHIA GORNEY 
 c.2000 New York Times  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The RU-486 announcement yesterday arrived with a lot of emphatic
declarations attached: ``historic moment,'' ``milestone,'' ``most
significant technological advance in women's reproductive health
care since the birth control pill.'' That last characterization was
from Gloria Feldt, president of Planned Parenthood, responding to
the news that the Food and Drug Administration had finally approved
the marketing of what's come to be known as the abortion pill.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare for a confusion of multisyllabic ``m'' words as Historic
Moment arguments get underway. Mifepristone, named RU-486 by the
French company that developed it, is the now-marketable pill that
begins a miscarriage in very early pregnancy. Misoprostol, already
marketed for other uses, is the medication that completes a
pill-induced abortion, when used after the mifepristone.
</P>
<P>
   Two medications, in other words, not one. Two visits to the
doctor, under the most lenient of the current protocols _ maybe
three visits _ and maybe a mandatory ultrasound to confirm the
timing of the pregnancy, which could require a trip to a facility
with an ultrasound machine.
</P>
<P>
   There's drawn-out pain, severe in some cases, less so in others,
but lasting considerably longer than the brief intense pain of most
surgical abortions. And medical abortion promises to be no cheaper
than the surgical alternative, at least at first _ about $300,
according to doctors who have been running this country's clinical
trials.
</P>
<P>
   Which is only to say that women need to remember what is in fact
historic about this moment, what must be kept in perspective, and
how much we have yet to learn about what termination by pill is
going to mean for American abortion practice.
</P>
<P>
   It will change the abortion debate, not because it is a pill but
because it works so early in pregnancy; both sides know that. Both
sides know as well that in theory the pills have the potential to
do what some abortion supporters dreamed of 30 years ago, when New
York became the first of the contiguous states to drop its abortion
restrictions: Termination of pregnancy might now lose its dreadful
stigma, they exulted, and become part of the regular practice of
any doctor who attends to women in their childbearing years.
</P>
<P>
   But of course that is not what happened, and although much has
changed over the last three decades, veterans of the legalization
battles sometimes despair over how much has not. In many
communities the decision to offer terminations still brings on
protests or bomb threats or the cold shoulder at Sunday church
services; surely nobody in New York in 1970 envisioned
circuit-riding doctors with bulletproof vests under their scrubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most physicians don't want to be worried about their safety,''
a St. Petersburg, Fla., obstetrician-gynecologist told a reporter
earlier this month. She thought RU-486 was a fine idea, but she
said she had no plans to begin dispensing it.
</P>
<P>
   Is hers a minority voice? Or are there many thousands like her
out there, kindly disposed toward mifepristone without quite being
ready to hand over the pills and risk the word getting out around
town? Are family practitioners and gynecology training programs
ready to amend their ``We don't teach that here'' stance?
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty more we don't know yet. Is it going to be a good
thing or a bad thing when the first magazine and newspaper ads
offering discount mifepristone-abortion start appearing, like the
ads for cheap laser eye correction? And how long will it take
before somebody is offering cut-rate abortion tablets on the
Internet?
</P>
<P>
   These pills have been studied as thoroughly as any in recent
history, as their many medical defenders have pointed out, and one
conclusion of the studies is the critical importance of timing the
pregnancy correctly and making sure that when the bleeding and
cramping are over, the abortion is complete. That requires a visit
to the doctor. It requires vigilance on the part of the pregnant
woman, and a decision before the eight-week cutoff period.
</P>
<P>
   Then, if she wants an RU-486 abortion without going over to the
local abortion clinic, the woman is going to have to sit down with
her doctor and ask for it.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the popularity of mifepristone in Europe,
and rightly so: more than a half million of these abortions have
taken place there by now. But it is also worth remembering that
even in France, where the pills began, two-thirds of abortion
patients are still opting for suction.
</P>
<P>
   If Americans do take to the new method, and if they are
straightforward about requesting it from their doctors, and if the
dispensing of mifepristone develops enough critical mass so that no
community physician is singled out as the abortion pill doc, then
perhaps we really are looking at a milestone here.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be up to doctors and their patients to decide
together how big a milestone, and just how much of the journey it
marks.
</P>
<P>
   (Cynthia Gorney is the author of ``Articles of Faith: A
Frontline History of the Abortion Wars.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
