<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Europeans Likely to Approve One Time-warner Deal, Reject Another
</P>
<P>
   European antitrust regulators plan to block Time Warner's joint
venture with the British music conglomerate EMI Group, but are much
closer to approving Time Warner's $135 billion merger with America
Online, people close to the talks say. Mario Monti, the European
antitrust commissioner, issued recommendations on both deals on
Wednesday in a closed meeting with antitrust regulators from
individual European countries, these people said.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Warns on Earnings, And Stock Falls After Hours
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer said that its fourth-quarter earnings would fall
far below estimates because of weak September sales. Earnings will
be 30 cents to 33 cents a share in the quarter, below analysts'
forecasts of 45 cents. Shares of Apple, which had closed at $53.50,
up $4.56, dropped as low as $28.25 in after-hours trading. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denmark Decides Not to Adopt Euro
</P>
<P>
   Denmark voted not to join Europe's unified currency, the euro,
undermining a fragile monetary experiment and turning its back on
the rapid European political integration championed by France and
Germany. Results showed 53.1 percent voting against the euro and
46.9 percent in favor. In New York, the euro settled at 88.13
cents, down from 88.30.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G Leads Rebound in Stocks
</P>
<P>
   Reassuring comments by Procter &AMP; Gamble helped lift stocks. The
Dow Jones industrial average rose 195.70 points, or 1.8 percent, to
10,824.06. The Nasdaq composite index gained 122.02 points, or 3.3
percent, to 3,778.32. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained
31.72 points, or 2.2 percent, to 1,458.29.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone Faces Reshuffling at Top
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone, which is recalling 6.5 million tires, is
also facing growing uncertainty about who will run the company.
Yoichiro Kaizaki, the president of Firestone's parent, Bridgestone
Corp. of Japan, created the uncertainty two weeks ago by declaring
that a management reshuffle was likely at its U.S. subsidiary,
which is based in Nashville. But there has been no announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Business Dean Is Stepping Down
</P>
<P>
   Donald P. Jacobs, one of the most influential people in
management education, will step down next spring after a
quarter-century as the dean of Northwestern University's business
school. Jacobs, 73, has served longer than any current major
university president or other business school dean, higher
education experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Less Marketing at Sydney Olympics
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the 1996 Olympic Games held in Coke's hometown of
Atlanta, Sydney, Australia, has kept so-called ambush marketers far
from Olympic arenas and sites. Although nonsponsor companies are
visible here, Sydney has little of the flea-market ambience that
made the Atlanta Games a byword for crass commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   Executives Indicted for Financial Irregularities in Merger
</P>
<P>
   A California federal grand jury indicted two former HBO &AMP; Co.
executives for fraud and conspiracy over accounting irregularities
at the software company before its $12 billion acquisition by
medical products supplier McKesson Inc. Federal officials said the
case represents one of biggest financial crimes ever investigated
by the FBI and the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC Blames Industrialized Nations for High Oil Prices
</P>
<P>
   An OPEC summit concluded Thursday by laying the blame for high
oil prices squarely on industrialized nations and calling debt a
greater barrier to the world's poor than costly fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Delays for Sony's Playstation 2
</P>
<P>
   Sony confirmed that it would fall far short of having a million
Playstation 2 devices ready for sale on Oct. 26. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
