<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TITANS-BOONE0929-COX     09-28 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANS-BOONE0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Patrick Brannan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, D.C. _ When Herman Boone was passed over for a head
coaching position in Williamston, N.C., he did what any coach would
do. He searched for a new job.
</P>
<P>
   Little did Boone know that he was going to find the biggest
challenge of his career. But it also proved to be the most
rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 Boone, a Rocky Mount, N.C. native, became the head
football coach at T.C. Williams High School in Alexandria, Va. The
Alexandria school board was being forced to create more racially
balanced schools. Boone, who is black, was appointed the new head
coach and thereby given the task of trying to unite not only a
football team, but a school and a community. The Titans completed a
perfect season and won the Virginia AAA state championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now the story of the 1971 Titans is hitting the big screen
nationwide today with the opening of ``Remember the Titans.'' The
Walt Disney film was produced by Jerry Bruckheimer, who produced
such films as ``Armageddon,'' ``The Rock'' and ``Con Air.'' It
stars Denzel Washington as Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the films stars were on hand for a gala screening in
Washington, D.C., Tuesday night. With many of the original Titans
in attendance, along with celebrities and dignitaries like
President Clinton, the atmosphere combined a high school reunion
with a Hollywood gala.
</P>
<P>
   It also continued to shine the spotlight on Boone, 64. Who told
the Telegram a year ago when filming began, that he was afraid of
the attention the movie would bring to his family. He still feels
that way today, but he has learned to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a low maintenance family,'' Boone said at the
post-screening party at ESPN Zone restaurant. ``We try to stay out
of the spotlight as much as we can. But this is like a storm that
catches up with you and you can't avoid it. You just have to deal
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone said he coached at a school in Williamston from 1961 to
1969 and won four state championships. But when he was passed over
for a head coaching position when the schools were integrated, he
decided to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that the town wasn't ready for a black coach,''
Boone said. ``And with me assisting the white coach at the white
school, so we couldn't help but win could we? The white coach came
out of East Carolina, a nice guy, a nice kid. He lost his first
eight, won his last two. I go 14-0 and right away I've got to
assist him? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone said he headed to a coaching clinic and was one of the few
black coaches in Eastern North Carolina that filmed his games. He
would bring his films to the clinics and meet with other black
coaches because everything was so segregated.
</P>
<P>
   Boone eventually was hired to be part of the staff of Bill
Yoast, a white coach. But the school board later appointed Boone as
head coach over Yoast, which created even more tension. Not only
did Boone have to find a way to get his players to come together,
he had to start but uniting his own coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Boone found a way to not only unify the team, but eventually the
entire community. Mostly through his determination. Qualities Boone
said he gained while growing up in Rocky Mount.
</P>
<P>
   Boone grew up in the Happy Hill section of Rocky Mount. An area
that stretches west of the railroad tracks, to the Tar River and
down to Raleigh Road. He still has a brother who lives here. Many
friends and family were in Washington for the premier.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell the underprivileged children of Rocky Mount, 'If a
little racked dude who lived over a ditch in the 700 block of Gay
Street, can make it to the top of the world, through hard work, I
mean extremely hard work - the only one in my family of 12 people
that ever thought about college - then they can make it,''' Boone
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though conditions were rough, Boone still speaks fondly of
his childhood. Partly because he said he never knew that things
were tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three rooms with no heat, a fireplace,'' Boone said.
``The spigot froze up in the winter time. We had to save our water,
bathe in tubs. . . . None of my friends in Rocky Mount knew that we
were poor, because as Sam Gray, on of my best friends said to me a
few minutes ago, 'there's love between people of Happy Hill.' They
won't allow you to realize that you're poor. Because we had so much
love.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone was involved in the making of the film. He said he spent
most weekends in Atlanta, where the film was shot, and worked with
Washington to help him mold to the role.
</P>
<P>
   Boone said there wasn't much he had to tell Washington, only
teaching him some of Boone's own football terminology. That's where
Boone says there is a little Rocky Mount flavor in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't have to tell him that much,'' Boone said of
Washington. ``He's a brilliant human being. You just had to tell
him your football vocabulary. So that he could make it authentic.
So of course my wife told him my curse words . . .. Hind parts _
you know what that is - when you say that I guess everybody in the
world will know I'm from Rocky Mount.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone touched and shaped the lives of a community nearly 30
years ago. Now he's hoping that the movie will shapes the lives of
everyone that sees it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it touches a lot of lives,'' Boone said. ``It's a feel
good movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-DEBATE-ART-2TAKE     09-28 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EVOLUTION OF BUSH THE DEBATER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT16,18 were sent to NYT photo clients on Sept
27. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the first debates of the Republican
primaries, Gov. George W. Bush did not have to do much. With six
candidates dividing an hour and a half, no one got more than 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bush filled up even less than that, his diaphanous answers
sometimes ending many seconds before the allotted time. And while
his opponents talked longer and louder during those early December
meetings, few seemed as self-satisfied as the Texas governor. His
lips twisted into an expression quickly branded ``the smirk.''
</P>
<P>
   Within two months, however, he had grafted a layer of
earnestness over any arrogance for his ninth debate, a special
edition of CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' There were just two other
contenders left at that point. But Bush was suddenly a font of
interjections and rebuttals, as if he had to rush to fit in all
that he had to say.
</P>
<P>
   As he approaches his first debate with Vice President Al Gore in
Boston next week, it is impossible to know which incarnation of
Bush will show up.
</P>
<P>
   He and his aides are hoping for the better version, and will
devote much of the weekend to debate preparation. It is their final
push in a process that began last spring, and it is a recognition
both that the campaign is entering a new phase, to be dominated by
the three debates between Bush and Gore, and that these events
represent Bush's best chance to erase any lingering questions about
how serious and seasoned he really is.
</P>
<P>
   But while Gore is a well-known quantity in this arena, a fresh,
thorough review of Bush's 10 debates during the primaries and his
two earlier debates in Texas showed him to be an unpredictable,
uneven performer. At the same time, it revealed someone who,
despite his image in some quarters as an overconfident slacker, can
be capable of significant improvements, important adjustments and
little surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still kind of out on Bush,'' said Greg Mueller,
who was a senior adviser to the publisher Steve Forbes, one of
Bush's former rivals for the Republican presidential nomination.
Mueller was referring to Bush's aptitude for debates, but he said
there was one clear lesson from the primaries: Bush brings weapons
to the battle that should not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among them is his talent for humorous asides, some of
them cleverly self-effacing and some of them clearly spontaneous,
and Bush drew on this with increasing frequency and effectiveness
as he progressed through the rapid-fire series of debates last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   At his fourth one, in early January, he was asked: ``Would you
take an expression like `What would Jesus do?' into the Oval
Office?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would take an expression into the Oval Office of `Dear God,
help me,''' Bush answered, without missing a beat.
</P>
<P>
   When Gary Bauer, another rival, muttered that the same thought
would go through his head if Bush were president, Bush again found
a fast and fitting retort.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't very Christian of you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also, in the same forum, mispronounced ``obfuscate,''
even though he was following his habit of edging up slowly to
multisyllable clusters of consonants, as if pondering dangerous
potholes on his oratorical highway.
</P>
<P>
   That error demonstrated one of his debate liabilities: A
wobbliness (and sometimes wackiness) with words that was present
even during the Larry King performance, when Bush signaled his
commitment to a growing economy by saying, ``We ought to make the
pie higher.''
</P>
<P>
   His debates to date form a fairly apt metaphor for his candidacy
and, really, for his political identity.
</P>
<P>
   At his worst, Bush came across as cocky, tongue-tied and only
glibly engaged with the nuts and bolts of the matters at hand. At
his best, he projected a genuineness of belief, buoyancy of spirit
and affability of character that trumped any of his opponents'
charms.
</P>
<P>
   At all times, he leaned _ arguably a few inches further than
other candidates do _ on transparently scripted, broad statements
about his principles and qualifications, no matter what he had been
asked.
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable example was his answer, during a December
debate in Phoenix, to a question about what he had learned from a
biography of former Secretary of State Dean Acheson that he had
previously said he was reading. Bush simply reverted to
foreign-policy lines from his stump speeches.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But his aides and advisers are not talking much these days about
that balance sheet of strengths and weaknesses; they are too busy
building Gore into the most fearsome forensic gladiator in the
empire.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews, one of them called the vice president
``the most effective and lethal debater in modern presidential
politics.'' Several others said that Bush would be lucky simply to
remain upright in the face of Gore's onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   The name of this game is the management of expectations, and
Bush's associates played it perfectly in 1994, when he was running
for Texas governor against a quick-witted incumbent, Ann Richards.
</P>
<P>
   A recent look at the sole Bush-Richards debate that year left
little doubt that she was funnier, more agile with facts, and more
authoritative. And some of Bush's canned goods verged on hokey, as
when he concluded his final remarks by abruptly quoting a song:
``Texas, our Texas, all hail the mighty state.''
</P>
<P>
   But he had never previously engaged in a formal debate, so the
fact that he stood his ground and stated his platform succinctly,
clearly and sometimes even forcefully impressed many skeptical
observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thought he won,'' said Bill Miller, a political
strategist in Austin, who has worked for both Democrats and
Republicans. ``But nobody said, `Gee, Richards just wiped the floor
with this guy,' so he came out of it well.'' Several weeks later,
he defeated Richards in the election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers are now trying to create a similar dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   They can and will tell anyone who asks that since 1984, Gore has
debated about 45 times. They can and will recite chapter and verse
of a long article about Gore's evolution as a debater in the July
issue of Atlantic Monthly, the cover of which depicted the vice
president as a political vampire.
</P>
<P>
   But many of Bush's advisers acknowledge that behind the scenes,
Bush has been practicing and practicing, to a degree that is not
wholly characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   During the primaries, for example, he did not bother with a
single mock debate. For the general election, he began such
rehearsals about four months ago, several advisers said. In May, he
sat with aides in the governor's mansion in Austin and watched a
videotape, edited by the campaign's chief media adviser, Mark
McKinnon, that included scenes from Gore's debates as well as high
points from past presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In early June, he and Sen. Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, the
stand-in for Gore, actually stood at lecterns in a room at the Bush
family compound in Kennebunkport, Maine. It was a scenario repeated
over subsequent months, with Stuart Stevens, another media adviser
with the campaign, acting as a moderator.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, at Bush's ranch near Waco, he and Gregg will
hold a timed rehearsal at the same late hour as Tuesday's event, a
dry run that will test him past his usual bedtime. They may do a
second rehearsal on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers said that one goal of all this work has been to brief
Bush thoroughly on the details of Gore's record and proposals. But
another goal has been simply to make sure that Bush goes into
Tuesday's debate feeling as comfortable as possible, because that
often dictates whether he seems clipped or convivial, herky-jerky
or fluid.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts said that the way he showcases his
personality will be a key to his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``His forte is not speed or specificity,'' noted Roderick P.
Hart, a University of Texas professor of communication and
government who has observed Bush through the years. ``But contrary
to popular reports, he's an intelligent man.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hart said, ``he has some of that genial quality
that President Reagan had in debates.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The debates during the primaries bear out that assessment. Some
of Bush's best moments came when he finally relaxed enough to
unleash a playful streak that made him seem accessible and smart
and accomplished other goals as well.
</P>
<P>
   In late January, during his eighth debate, he responded to
several of Forbes' attacks on his Texas record by saying, ``So many
half stories, so little time.'' It was the kind of Reaganesque,
``there-you-go-again'' line that is certain to be trotted out on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the last debate, on March 2, he drew laughter
and applause when he answered a question about his familiarity with
the Internet by saying that he ``e-mailed my mother the other
day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me to stand straight, by the way, when I was at your
debate,'' he added. It was a quick, self-effacing and humorous way
to work his family connections.
</P>
<P>
   But this was also the debate in which Bush went a laugh too far,
chuckling when one of his questioners mentioned that some death row
convicts in Texas had had lawyers who slept during their trials.
</P>
<P>
   A more persistent trait of Bush's responses was his tendency to
talk about foreign policy in the most general, well-worn terms.
When King asked him about the appropriate occasions for military
force, Bush lapsed into a kind of mantra.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's in our national strategic interest,'' Bush said.
``The Far East is in our national strategic interest. Our own
hemisphere is in our national strategic interests. The Middle East,
protecting Israel, is in our national security interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, to many observers, was much safer than it was
illuminating.
</P>
</TEXT>
