<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0470 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEBATE-ADVANCE1001-CO     09-28 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-ADVANCE1001-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 1.
 &HT;    Candidates prepare for the debatesBy Ken Herman and Scott
Shepard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For Al Gore, the problem is great expectations.
For George W. Bush, the hurdle, as it's been since day one, is
proving he is presidential material.
</P>
<P>
   So far, months of campaigning and millions of dollars of
political spending have produced a dead heat. The tie-breaking
process begins Tuesday night in Boston when Bush and Gore go
lectern to lectern in the first of three debates that will move
crucial undecided voters one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of the debates, the American people get the
information they need to make an informed decision on Nov. 7,''
said Paul G. Kirk Jr., a co-chairman of the Commission on
Presidential Debates that sponsors the events.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, both candidates retreated to familiar ground for
final preparation sessions. The goals are the same, but the
challenges differ for the two candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is a natural-born killer when it comes to debates,'' said
GOP strategist Scott Reed, who is not affiliated with the Bush
campaign, but is part of the Republican effort to set a high bar
for Gore to clear.
</P>
<P>
   For GOP nominee Bush, who has spent more than a year offering
programs and policies, the hurdle is the same one he faced on June
1999 when he flew to Iowa (on a plane dubbed ``Great
Expectations'') to announce his candidacy: Is this guy presidential
material?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has got to convey something more than warmth and charm,''
said Wayne Fields, a political rhetoric expert at Washington
University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Fields' campus will host the third presidential debate on Oct.
17. Round two is set for Oct. 11 in Winston-Salem, N.C. Vice
presidential nominees Joe Lieberman and Dick Cheney square off
Thursday night in Danville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Bush went home for the weekend and Gore headed to Florida to
prepare for the Tuesday meeting at the University of Massachusetts
at Boston. At his ranch in Crawford, west of Waco, Bush is working
with a team of aides and New Hampshire Sen. Judd Gregg, who is
playing Gore in the mock debates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore brought a small entourage to Longboat Key, near Sarasota,
where he will practice at the Mote Marine Laboratory, a private,
nonprofit research and education facility. In addition to debate
prep, the trip to Florida gave Gore several days of high-profile
publicity in a key state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used the facility as the headquarters for preparation
for his 1996 vice presidential debate against GOP nominee Jack
Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore entourage in Florida this weekend includes wife Tipper,
daughter Karenna Gore Schiff, brother-in-law Frank Hunger and a
handful of top aides. Among those is Clinton adviser Bruce Reed,
who has taken a leave of absence from his White House chores to
help Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also invited 12 ``ordinary citizens'' from around the
nation to join him in Florida to offer their input.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not complicated,'' Gore campaign chairman Bill Daley said
of the pre-debate process. ``You try to guess at the subject areas,
the three or four that will come up in each'' debate.
</P>
<P>
   A key member of Team Gore is Paul Begala, a Texan and longtime
Clinton-Gore aide who is spending the weekend playing Bush. Begala
got the gig after former U.S. Rep. Tom Downey of New York, who had
been playing Bush, received a package including a videotape of Bush
debate preparation sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Downey turned the tape over to the FBI, which is still
investigating how it got to him, and dropped off the debate prep
team.
</P>
<P>
   Begala relishes his role as Bush, who, like Begala, is known to
occasionally crack wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that very appealing. He is a bit of a wiseacre and I am
too, I like that about him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Begala is the author of a recent book analyzing Bush's
effectiveness in Texas. It's called ``Is Our Children Learning?''a
campaign-trail malapropism coined by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a very different world view than I do. He was born rich
and he is going to be rich and he is going to die rich,'' said
Begala, who has managed to turn politics into a buck or two.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to spin a spinner, so Begala isn't buying the Bush
campaign's attempt to set low expectations (a curious effort on
behalf of a candidate who makes his points about raising education
standards by discussing ``the soft bigotry of low expectations.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has done a masterful job of spinning
expectations,'' said Begala. ``That's one of the reasons he beat
Ann Richards and he beat John McCain. It would be very, very
foolish to underestimate him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, political rhetoric expert Rita Whillock said Bush's
burden of proof is to show he is up to the top job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has got to come across as a CEO,'' said Whillock, a
professor of public affairs at Southern Methodist University.
``That's his credentials for office. He just doesn't have the
policy wonk information.''
</P>
<P>
   A top Bush aide said a successful night for his boss would be
showing that he can ``stand toe to toe'' with Gore, a debater whose
actual talents can't possibly match the reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, aware of the great expectations, told reporters last week,
``I don't have an overconfident bone in my body.'' He recalled
Bush's performance, rated by many at the time as adequate, in his
1994 gubernatorial race debate against then-Gov. Ann Richards, then
the reigning queen of political rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was supposed to be slaughtered in that,'' Gore said,
aw-shucksing his own vaunted talents. ``She's certainly a better
debater than I am. She's got a very quick wit and silver tongue and
is just smart as a whip, and he beat her in that debate, so put
that in your formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, calmly confident in the face of the pre-debate chatter
about Gore, is taking the low-key approach to what he knows will be
a high-key deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view it as a great opportunity to explain my vision for the
country,'' he said last week on ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, which included a Wednesday night return
to Austin for debate preparation, Bush summed it up this way,
``Either you're ready or you're not read.'' And he believes he is.
</P>
<P>
   It's a more even-up assessment than offered during the summer by
Karl Rove, Bush's top strategist, who, facetiously but to make a
point, called Gore ``the world's most pre-eminent debater, a man
who is more proficient at hand-to-hand debate combat than anybody
the world has ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pre-debate setting of odds and expectations,
University of Kansas communications professor Diana Carlin says
voters tend to ignore the hype and watch with a discerning eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewers are measuring a combination of things,'' said Carlin,
a member of the Commission on Presidential Debates. ``This is the
only time you have them in the same place, the only time you can
really get them to compare, if the questions are asked the right
way. I equate it to a job interview. It's part job interview, but
it's also part test of how they handle the pressure, how they
relate to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
