<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ACCOUNTING-FRAUD-700(     09-28 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-FRAUD-700(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO EXECUTIVES INDICTED IN $9 BILLION FRAUD SCAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX BERENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two former top executives of a Georgia medical software company
were indicted on Thursday, accused of costing investors more than
$9 billion in one of the largest financial frauds in American
history.
</P>
<P>
   As co-presidents of HBO &AMP; Co. for most of 1998, Albert J.
Bergonzi and Jay P. Gilbertson used sham deals and bad accounting
to inflate the company's revenue and earnings by hundreds of
millions of dollars, according to federal prosecutors in San
Francisco, who announced the indictments. If convicted, the two men
each face up to 10 years in jail and a $1 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   HBO &AMP; Co. was acquired by McKesson, a distributor of
prescription drugs based in San Francisco, in January 1999 for $14
billion. When the merged McKesson HBO announced that its auditors
had discovered fraud in April 1999, its shares fell almost 50
percent in one day, leaving investors $9 billion poorer. McKesson
HBO stock has yet to recover.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment comes as the Securities and Exchange Commission
steps up efforts to work more closely with federal prosecutors in
cases of serious financial wrongdoing. Over the last two years,
Richard Walker, the SEC's director of enforcement, has visited U.S.
attorneys in several cities to offer the commission's help to
prosecutors interested in filing financial fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping cases like this will send a message to corporate
boardrooms and suites that they actually could go to jail for
this,'' said Leslie Caldwell, chief of securities fraud for the
U.S. attorney's office in San Francisco. ``This isn't just managing
your numbers or tweaking accounts here and there. This is putting
your whole company at risk, and if you do that, there are going to
be serious consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Bergonzi and Gilbertson denied the criminal charges,
as well as a related civil complaint filed by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Dominick A. DeRosa, a former HBO vice president, agreed to pay
more than $411,000 to settle an SEC complaint against him in the
case. DeRosa was not charged in the criminal case, and Caldwell
said DeRosa was cooperating with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's fast growth in sales and profits made it a favorite of
investors throughout the 1990s. Its stock rose more than a
hundredfold between October 1990 and October 1998, when HBO agreed
to be acquired by McKesson, the largest distributor of prescription
drugs in the United States. At the time, the two companies had a
combined market value of more than $23 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But when the merged McKesson HBO announced in April 1999 that
its auditors had discovered fraud at HBO during a routine annual
review, McKesson HBO shares fell to $34 from $65 in a single day.
HBO McKesson stock rose 38 cents, to close at $30.50 on Thursday,
giving the company a market value of less than $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Bergonzi and Gilbertson, desperate to ensure
that HBO would meet or beat analysts' expectations for sales and
profits, used several schemes to inflate the company's results.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout 1998, they allowed more than a dozen hospitals to buy
HBO software or services with conditional ``side letters'' that
allowed the hospitals to back out of the deals, according to the
indictment. Then they hid the side letters from auditors and
reported those sales as complete, violating accounting rules. In at
least one case, a hospital canceled a purchase HBO had booked,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   To further bolster its results, HBO also agreed to huge sham
sales with two other large computer companies, according to the
indictment. On Sept. 28, 1998, two days before the end of HBO's
quarter and just weeks before HBO and McKesson agreed to merge, the
two men agreed to buy $73.8 million in software from Computer
Associates, supposedly for resale, according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Computer Associates of Long Island, a maker of
software used by big companies, bought $30 million in HBO software,
also supposedly for resale.
</P>
<P>
   To make the deals seem separate, the men ``split the transaction
into separate contracts, neither of which made any reference to the
other,'' the indictment asserts. In the two years since it bought
HBO's software, Computer Associates ``has neither made use of nor
distributed any of the $30 million in HBOC software products,''
according to the indictment. Similarly, HBO had sold only a
fraction of the $74 million in Computer Associates software it
bought.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1999, McKesson HBO and Data General, a computer
hardware maker based in Massachusetts, agreed to a similar deal,
prosecutors said. It was that deal that eventually led to the fraud
discovery, when Data General disclosed to auditors that what
appeared to be a simple $20 million purchase of HBO's software had
a side agreement that essentially ensured that Data General would
never have to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The frauds increased HBO's revenue by $230 million, or more than
20 percent, in the final three quarters of 1999, according to the
indictment. Profits were overstated by $170 million, or nearly 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson left HBO in November 1998 to become the president of
WebMD, an Internet health care company. He resigned from WebMD in
June 1999 after McKesson HBO said it had discovered the fraud.
McKesson HBO fired Bergonzi and other former top HBO executives in
June 1999. A McKesson spokesman said on Thursday that only one
former HBO executive is now among the top 20 executives of the
merged company, and that that person joined HBO only in December
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell and SEC officials said that the investigation was
continuing and that more complaints or charges might be filed.
Charles McCall, the former chairman of HBO, has not been charged
with wrongdoing in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell said McKesson HBO was unlikely to be charged with fraud
because the company immediately began an investigation when it
discovered the problems and told the public and the authorities
promptly. ``The company basically did the right thing when they
discovered there was a fraud,'' Caldwell said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
