<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE PRAISE FOR CLINTON GOES A LONG WAY FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT12 and NYT14 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ After more than a year of trying to hang
President Clinton around Vice President Al Gore's neck, Gov. George
W. Bush took the opposite tack on Thursday, saying that the main
problem with Gore was that he was not enough like his boss.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to workers at a manufacturing plant here, Bush
tacitly praised Clinton's past calls for an end to ``big
government'' and said that Gore was not heeding them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the vice president had ``cast his lot with the old
Democratic party'' in proposing a new level of federal spending and
regulation that, Bush said, would endanger the country's current
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president was seated right behind Bill Clinton at the
State of the Union when the president declared, `The era of big
government is over,''' Bush said, referring to Clinton's address in
January 1996. ``Apparently, the message never took.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent seemed interested in `reinventing government,'''
Bush said, alluding to one of Gore's signature phrases. ``Now he
seems interested only in expanding it. For him, big government has
never really been dead. It's simply been biding its time, waiting
for its next chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Those comments made up some of the sharpened language that Bush
unveiled on Thursday to make the case that electing Gore might mean
a return to ``the old ways of tax and spend.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressing the point, Bush called on Gore to make an unequivocal
promise that he would never raise the payroll taxes for Social
Security to keep the entitlement program financially solvent. Bush
has made that pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The references to Clinton revealed a fresh tactic in Bush's
intrinsically difficult quest to persuade Americans that they
should unseat an incumbent administration during a period of
unparalleled prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was essentially saying that electing Gore would not be like
re-electing Clinton, because Gore was less protege than dissident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is proposing the largest increase in federal spending in 35
years, since the presidency of Lyndon Baines Johnson,'' Bush said.
``The vice president's spending plan proposes three times more in
new spending than Bill Clinton proposed in 1992. If the vice
president gets elected, the era of big government being over is
over. And so, too, I fear, could be our prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   In casting Gore as financially profligate and trying to plant
fears that he might raise taxes, Bush sounded much like his father
did in 1988, when then-Vice President George Bush waged a
successful campaign for the presidency against Michael Dukakis,
then the governor of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not use the word ``liberal,'' which was the tag his
father placed on Dukakis at the time. But that was clearly what the
Texas governor meant. And what he intended was to persuade voters
that prosperity was a potentially fragile thing and that Gore was
not its surest protector but its direst threat, someone who would
not use the projected federal surpluses in the right way.
</P>
<P>
   Bush began an attempt to take the issue of prosperity at least
partly away from Gore this week when he warned that the vice
president was not taking the necessary steps to end an ``education
recession'' that imperiled the American economy down the line.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he warned that too much new government spending
could have the same effect. He said that his own proposal for a
sweeping tax cut of $1.3 trillion over 10 years was, in fact, ``an
insurance policy against an economic slowdown or a recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, called
Bush's assessments ``absolutely laughable.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that Gore's 10-year budget plan called for
higher expenditures in ``education, health care, Medicare and the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hattaway said that Gore's proposal for an estimated $500
billion in tax cuts over 10 years _ less than half the size of
Bush's _ made that spending affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Bush's pledge not to raise payroll taxes for Social
Security, Hattaway said, ``Did he say, `Read my lips'? The last
time a Bush made a silly pledge like that, he broke it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway said Gore would not be making a similar vow, because
the vice president had already outlined a plan for safeguarding
Social Security that did not involve a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Bush mentioned Clinton twice _ and twice flattered him in
comparison with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Bush had loudly rued the possibility of ``four more
years of Clinton-Gore'' and implied that the vice president was a
participant in an administration that, in Bush's view, was guilty
of serious ethical lapses, divisive partisanship and failed
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, Bush described Gore as an entirely different
kind of politician from Clinton, one who had ``left the vital
center of American politics.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
