<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY TO TAKE ON DIAZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ His rematch with Oscar De La Hoya on hold
indefinitely, Shane Mosley is moving on but not avoiding a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The WBC welterweight champion will make the first defense of his
title Nov. 4 in New York against Antonio Diaz _ a junior
welterweight contender from Coachella who has won his past 25
fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a credible fighter,'' Mosley said, ``a great fighter. He
has great counter-punching skills, he's consistent. He has a Julio
Cesar Chavez look., strong, great chin, durable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think I'm too fast for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz (33-2, with 24 knockouts) IS a credible fighter.
</P>
<P>
   He has proved he's all the things Mosley (35-0, 32 KOs) said he
is. In two recent fights, he was tougher than two tough opponents,
stopping Ivan Robinson in April and outpointing Mickey Ward in
August.
</P>
<P>
   A significant question is weight: Diaz will be fighting at 147
pounds for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonio is a big boy,'' said Lee Espinoza, his manager. ``He's
been having a lot of problems trying to make weight. He weighs 164
pounds right now.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, from whom Mosley took the title in June, is in the
picture. The former champion said he wants to fight early next year
in spite of an ugly contractual dispute with promoter Bob Arum and
would like to fight Mosley in May.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Mosley, who stands to make $10 million-plus
against De La Hoya (compared to $3 million against Diaz).
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Oscar's ready, I'll be ready,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
