<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SAYS BUSH TAX PLAN THREATENS PROSPERITY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore said Thursday that
``prosperity itself will be on the ballot'' on Nov. 7 and then
repeatedly portrayed Gov. George W. Bush's proposed income tax cut
as a serious threat to the country's economic health.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not tax relief,'' Gore said of his Republican rival's
$1.3 trillion tax reduction plan. ``That's a massive tax on
America's potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his comments in a notably brief speech to a group of
scholars and staff members at the Brookings Institution, one of
Washington's most prominent research organizations. It is a
nonpartisan group that conducts research on a broad range of
domestic and foreign policy topics.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president made no new proposals during his address,
which he read somewhat impassively from a teleprompter while
standing at a lectern. But he did introduce new language, and aides
said the speech, like other Gore addresses this week, was designed
as something of a test drive for Gore's first debate with Bush,
which is set for Tuesday night in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, viewers can expect to hear a vigorous
assault on Bush's tax cut plan. Gore attacked the Bush plan five
times in his 13-minute address. The candidates' disparate
approaches to tax cuts provide perhaps the clearest distinction in
this year's campaign, and Gore has long maintained that the
Republican plan risks a return to heavy deficits.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush proposal would reduce all income tax rates, double the
child credit, provide a break for married couples, repeal the
federal estate tax and expand the deductibility of charitable
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   It would reduce federal revenue by $1.3 trillion in the nine
years starting 2002 and would use $1.6 trillion of the federal
surplus because of increased interest costs that the government
would incur if the surplus is used for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus is projected by the Congressional Budget Office to
be $4.3 trillion during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, by contrast, opposes any across-the-board reduction in tax
rates. He has proposed a $500 billion array of targeted tax cuts
and credits aimed at providing relief for the middle class. They
would include financial breaks intended to encourage retirement
savings and to make college tuition, health insurance and child
care more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would spend more than Bush on education and health care,
and he would devote significant sums to paying down the national
debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consider this fact,'' Gore said of Bush's proposal. ``The
other side's plan gives more in tax cuts to the wealthiest 1
percent _ $667 billion of the surplus _ than all the new money they
would invest in education, health care, prescription drugs and the
national defense combined.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I believe in smart investments for the future, not
massive tax cuts for the few that could bring us back into
deficit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
