<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW WRINKLES IN CHINA-WTO APPLICATION
</P>
<P>
   China's effort to gain admission to the World Trade Organization
has encountered new problems, undercutting the chances that the
country can join by the end of the year. China's top negotiator,
Long Yongtu, denied speculation of a deadlock, but the WTO
negotiating group chairman issued a statement calling for a
``fundamental re-examination of negotiating positions in capitals''
before any new session takes place. Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S.
trade representative, has asked for a meeting with China's premier,
Zhu Rongji, but no date has been set, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   FREESERVE POSTS LOSS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Freeserve, the leading provider of Internet access in
Britain, fell 3 percent to 235 pence, or about $3.31, after it said
first-quarter losses had nearly doubled to 15.5 million pounds, or
about $19 million, as spending on advertising and new services
increased. Revenue grew more than three-fold to 14.6 million
pounds, and the number of registered users grew to 2 million,
compared with 1.4 million a year ago. Freeserve, which is 80
percent owned by Dixons, the British consumer electronics retailer,
has been unsuccessful in its attempts to find a buyer even as other
Internet service providers have rushed to consolidate. Tiscali SpA
and Germany's T-Online International AG, which have made
acquisitions to expand and cut costs, now have more than 6 million
users each. Freeserve also is facing stiff competition from United
States Internet companies Yahoo and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   PARTNERSHIP ON WIRELESS COMMUNICATIONS
</P>
<P>
   In a deal to help speed the development of in-car electronic
services, Ford Motor Co. and Peugeot Citroen of France announced
that they would form an alliance to cooperate in automotive design
and the development of wireless services like cell phone and
Internet access and entertainment channels. The companies expect to
formally seal the deal by the end of the year. In August, Ford
formed a joint venture with Qualcomm Inc., called Wingcast, to
equip its cars for wireless services. The deal is the latest
example of a spreading web of cooperation agreements in the car
industry. Ford and Citroen recently announced an agreement to
cooperate in the development of diesel engines.
</P>
<P>
   STRONG RESULTS AT FRENCH CONGLOMERATE
</P>
<P>
   The French media company Lagardere, best known for its
publishing division and magazines, reported a 36.4 percent increase
in first-half operating income, to 263 million euros, or $232
million, as revenue increased to 5.9 billion euros from 5.8 billion
a year earlier. Net profit soared almost sixfold, to 788 million
euros largely on a one-time exceptional gain of 1.1 billion euros
related to the sale this year of an Internet service provider, Club
Internet, to Deutsche Telekom, and of the publisher Grolier Inc. to
Scholastic Corp. To focus on the media, Lagardere this year also
entered an alliance with Canal Plus, a European pay-for-view
television company.
</P>
<P>
   UNILEVER-BESTFOODS DEAL APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission said it had approved the $24.3 billion
acquisition of the U.S. foods company Bestfoods by Unilever PLC,
the Anglo-Dutch food and consumer goods conglomerate. Under the
European Commission's condition for approval, Unilever must shed
brands and businesses worth $440 million in annual sales. Unilever
said it had agreed to shed overlapping businesses such as its Oxo
bouillon cubes and Bestfood's Lesieur mayonnaise products in
France. The Federal Trade Commission in the United States has
approved the deal.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA BANK EXPANDS SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   Canada's largest Royal Bank of Canada, has agreed to buy Dain
Rauscher Corp. of Minneapolis, a retail brokerage and investment
banker, for $1.456 billion. At $95 a share, the offer is 19 percent
above Dain Rauscher's trading price Wednesday on the New York Stock
Exchange. Royal Bank chairman John Cleghorn said the acquisition
will provide ``an established U.S. presence and a platform for
growth.'' In June, the bank bought the insurance businesses of
Liberty Corp. of Greenville, S.C., and indicated it wants to
develop cross-marketing of banking, insurance and brokerage
services that are not yet permitted in Canada. The latest
transaction requires approval from regulatory agencies and
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL WINS CHINA, TAIWAN DEALS
</P>
<P>
   Canada's Nortel Networks Corp. has won two contracts worth $525
million to build wireless telephone systems in China and Taiwan.
One contract, worth $250 million, is for 1,900 new base stations
for cellular phone and Internet transmission for Chunghwa Telecom
in Taiwan. Chunghwa has given Nortel, which is based in Brampton,
Ontario, $900 million worth of orders since 1994. The second, $275
million contract is with Zhejiang Unicom in China to install
infrastructure and software for wireless Internet services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
