<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY SELLS NEWSPAPERS TO BOSTON HERALD OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The owner of The Boston Herald is purchasing Community Newspaper
Co., a group of four daily and 88 weekly newspapers in the Boston
suburbs, from Fidelity Capital, the new business and venture
capital arm of Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives Patrick J. Purcell, the owner of Herald Media
Inc., a regional platform from which to compete with The Boston
Globe, particularly in the wealthy suburbs west of the city. The
Globe is owned by The New York Times Co., which earlier this year
completed its purchase of The Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette, which
is Massachusetts' third-largest newspaper, for $295 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Telegram &AMP; Gazette circulates in many of the same western
suburbs where Community Newspapers owns weeklies. The biggest of
the four daily newspapers, The MetroWest Daily News, is published
in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Thursday, Purcell declared, ``Let the
battle begin.''
</P>
<P>
   In the six and a half years since he bought The Herald _ which
has a daily circulation of 266,000 _ from his former employer,
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., Purcell has impressed industry
analysts and New England newspaper executives with his ability to
keep The Herald profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The same observers say that Fidelity struggled to get consistent
returns on its investment in the newspapers and niche publications
that serve 140 communities in eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, Fidelity has not operated these newspapers well,''
said Steven Barlow, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   William B. Ketter, the former editor of The Patriot Ledger in
Quincy, Mass., who is now chairman of Boston University's
journalism department, said: ``I think Fidelity has found that the
newspaper business is a very difficult business. They tried the
concept of 100 little mice trying to be an elephant, and they
realized that it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Purcell, operating from a strong base in Boston, may be able
to find economies and combinations that enhance The Herald's reach
and profitability, while increasing the margins of the community
newspapers, which have a combined circulation of about 900,000. ``I
think the purchase of the Fidelity papers by The Herald moves them
up a significant notch in competition with The Globe,'' Ketter
added.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell said Thursday that ``this is an extraordinary
revenue-generating opportunity.'' He added that ``the ability to
generate ad revenue in this combination is enormous.'' He also
noted that his was by far the biggest community newspaper operation
in a single region.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two other companies have pursued a similar strategy. Pulitzer
Inc., the owner of The St. Louis Post-Dispatch, this summer paid
$165 million for Suburban Journals of Greater St. Louis, including
38 newspapers and some niche publications. Hollinger Inc., the
parent of Hollinger International, owns Chicago's No. 2 newspaper,
The Chicago Sun-Times, as well as the suburban Pioneer Press
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the Community Newspaper sale came on the
same day The Globe started its new Thursday GlobeWest section,
serving 35 communities in Boston's western suburbs. The Globe has
also just finished a redesign, and has recently added new editorial
initiatives, including focused weekly business coverage of the
biotechnology industry _ a growing part of the economy of the same
western suburbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
