<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-ELECTIONS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC'S OPPONENTS, CLAIMING VICTORY AT POLLS, WILL PRESS HIM TO
LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to correct name of Radical Party leader in graf 16)  
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Serbia's democratic opposition thinks
that it has a president in Vojislav Kostunica. But it also has a
problem: how to get the incumbent, President Slobodan Milosevic,
out of power.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is more than technical. Milosevic shows no signs of
wanting to go.
</P>
<P>
   So Kostunica and the leaders of 18 parties that support him
decided Thursday night to call a rally for 2 p.m. Friday in
Belgrade's Square of the Republic, where they will ask the people
of Serbia to perform ``any act of civil disobedience they have at
their disposal'' until Milosevic leaves office, Zarko Korac, a
party leader, said after Kostunica and the opposition met Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Talking of rolling strikes, the closing of roads, cinemas,
theaters, shops and schools, Korac said: ``We know it's a high-risk
game, but we know we have no alternative. Through the rigging of
votes, Milosevic is clearly challenging us, and since we are being
pushed into the street, we must accept it. It is Milosevic who has
declared war. We'll start tomorrow and see how we end up and how
far we have to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to some 3,000 people who had gathered spontaneously in
the square Thursday night, Zoran Djindjic and other opposition
party leaders said they would start at 2 p.m. and remain in the
square until Milosevic leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 10 years, we have to show that we are ready to defend
our will and overthrow one regime,'' Djindjic said. Another party
official, Slobodan Orlic, said: ``See you tomorrow at 1400. He can
do nothing to us. He is broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is hoping that his special police, which he has built
up and paid well at the expense of the army, will stand by him in
the face of what could be widespread protests.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's Federal Election Commission, in an announcement
early Thursday morning, confirmed its preliminary results and
declared that Kostunica, while running 10 percentage points ahead
of Milosevic, had failed to win more than 50 percent of the votes
in Sunday's elections, meaning he and Milosevic would have to face
each other in a runoff on Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica and the democratic opposition, backed by the United
States and the European Union, have cried fraud, and say that their
count shows clearly that he won more than 52 percent of the vote
and that there is no need for a second round.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica has ruled out a second round, saying that to
participate would be to accept electoral fraud and betray the votes
of the people. ``If we bargained, then we would acknowledge a lie
instead of the truth,'' he told a huge rally of more than 200,000
people in downtown Belgrade on Wednesday night. ``If we bargained,
we would admit that one man's will is greater than the will of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to boycott has given Milosevic an opportunity.
On Thursday, he met the main officials of his Socialist Party and
those of his allies, and announced that he would run in a second
round _ displaying himself on television for the first time since
Sunday's vote. And if Kostunica does not run, Milosevic may win by
default _ unless the opposition can force him to recognize his
defeat in the meantime, through legal efforts in dubious courts or
through popular pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is clearly buying time. He is hoping to hold his
party, his coalition and his security forces together, while
dividing the opposition _ and the outside world _ with the idea
that a second round is hardly undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   But Kostunica and other opposition leaders believe that a second
round would be a trap, and that Milosevic would have more time to
prepare an enormous vote fraud or to find a pretext to cancel or
annul a second round, and thus remain in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not going to recognize the true results from the first
round and leave office, why should he recognize the results from
round two?'' an opposition leader asked.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Asked in an interview on Wednesday whether he saw risks in his
boycott strategy and might allow Milosevic to remain in power,
Kostunica shrugged. ``I won't exclude that risk,'' he said. ``But
risk is all round us. Living in a country with Slobodan Milosevic
is risky. But he is buying time, and this is something that cannot
last long. People know I won these elections, and why should I
betray them?''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica found moral support Thursday from the Serbian Orthodox
Church, which recognized his election victory and addressed him as
``president elect.'' And the leader of the Radical Party, Vojislav
Seselj, until recently a Milosevic ally, also congratulated
Kostunica on his election, called for a reshuffle of the Serbian
government and the firing of Milosevic's powerful interior
minister, Vlajko Stojiljkovic.
</P>
<P>
   In Montenegro, the anti-Milosevic prime minister, Filip
Vujanovic, also recognized Kostunica as president.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition leaders of the 18 parties met twice Thursday to
discuss strategy, with some leaders more radical than others. They
decided on following two tracks: first, a legal track, which
Kostunica, a constitutional lawyer, insists upon, challenging the
findings of the Federal Election Commission in the courts. The
second track is people power _ popular pressure through a mixture
of rallies, strikes and other demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing except random gatherings Thursday, with a few
thousand people gathering in Belgrade and more substantial
spontaneous rallies in Novi Sad and Cacak. In Gornji Milanovac,
high school students went on strike, saying they would not return
to school until Milosevic left office. In Krusevac, which was a
Socialist town, the local television and radio started showing news
from independent Radio B2-92 and Radio Free Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are angry, but our dilemma is how to organize their
protests without burning people out,'' Korac said. He said leaders
were discussing a mix of protests, rallies, strikes and
encouragements to those allied to Milosevic to abandon a sinking
ship.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica has been reluctant to provide an early provocation to
the police, but he says he believes that in the end the police and
the army will not act against the will of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A general strike in Serbia, suggested early this morning by
Djindjic, the leader of the Democratic Party, is problematic, given
the poverty of people and the high level of unemployment anyway.
But the opposition is discussing general strikes in one city at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster its case before the courts and world opinion, the
opposition says it has clear evidence of fraud, including the
sudden disappearance from the rolls of 600,000 voters, the
inclusion of invalid ballots to lower Kostunica's percentages and
the counting of ballots from polling stations in Kosovo that
apparently never opened.
</P>
<P>
   To the opposition's outrage Thursday night, the election
commission declared that its work for the first round was done,
refused to hear opposition complaints and, in a final statement,
took away four seats from the opposition's totals in the lower
house of the federal Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition efforts to get large numbers of the permanent
government-appointed commissioners to resign apparently failed,
although there were reports that Bojan Pudar, the commission's vice
president, had quit.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said they thought that Milosevic would not
succeed in holding on to power and that his government was already
crumbling. But experts here noted that Milosevic appeared to
encounter no dissent at the meeting of his party's main board or a
second meeting of the leaders of his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, Milosevic can keep power only by killing Serbs,''
a diplomat said. ``But the police and the army know that people
voted for Kostunica, and many of them voted for him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on Thursday urged Milosevic to honor the
results of the election. ``The people of Yugoslavia have spoken
loud and clear in support of democratic change,'' Clinton said in
Washington. ``It is time for Milosevic to heed the call of the Serb
people, step down, and allow a peaceful democratic transition to
take place.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and the European Union, with France in its
revolving presidency, are pressing Russian President Vladimir Putin
to help make Milosevic yield. French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine was in Moscow on Thursday, and there were reports that the
Milosevic government sent copies of its electoral material to
Moscow _ where Milosevic's brother, Borislav, is the Yugoslav
ambassador _ to try to convince Putin that a second round is
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians will evaluate the evidence, and the opposition
has the better evidence,'' a Western official said. ``No one has a
veto over the fact that change will come. There is an opportunity
for the Russians to help this along more quickly and easily and
leave fewer scars in Serbia, to be a player and help other Slavic
peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement, Foreign Minister Igor S. Ivanov said Moscow
``stands firmly for the peoples of Yugoslavia to have full freedom
to express their will without internal or external pressure'' and
urged other nations ``not to allow destabilization of the
situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
