<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN CONTINUES CRITICISM
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman on Thursday accused Republicans of
deceiving voters about the Democratic plan to pay for prescription
drugs, the second time this week he has called them dishonest.
``What Bush and Cheney are saying about our Medicare plan is
downright deceptive,'' Lieberman said, joined by other Democratic
lawmakers on the steps of the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he said Gov. George W. Bush and Dick Cheney had
repeatedly made promises that were contradicted by ``their records
and the details of their plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has proposed adding a prescription drug
benefit to Medicare. Bush has derided the plan as forcing older
people into a government-run health maintenance organization and
has proposed a more limited program.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHER AGAINST BROTHER
</P>
<P>
   Handgun Control Inc. will begin broadcasting television
commercials this weekend that feature the actor Martin Sheen
criticizing Gov. George W. Bush's record on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   In the 30-second commercial, Sheen, who portrays the president
on the television series ``The West Wing,'' sits in front of an
American flag and says: ``Should the next president be the
candidate of the gun lobby? Should he have signed a bill that
allows hidden handguns in churches, hospitals and amusement parks?
Should he be someone of whom the NRA has said, that if he is
elected, they'll be working right out of the Oval Office? That's
Governor Bush's record.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Handgun Control sought Sheen is that his brother
Joseph Estevez did the voice-over for a commercial opposing gun
control produced by a gun industry group, said Joseph Sudbay, the
group's political director. Sudbay said Handgun Control has bought
more than $300,000 in time on stations in Cleveland, Milwaukee and
St. Louis. The commercials have been timed to coincide with the
season premier of ``The West Wing.'' Last season's finale featured
an assassination attempt on Sheen's character.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE TRAVEL LOG
</P>
<P>
   Economic expansion is over if Vice President Al Gore becomes
president, Gov. George W. Bush told supporters in Michigan and
Wisconsin. Gore, in Washington, said as much of Bush. The
candidates continue racking up frequent flier miles, wooing voters
and hacking away at their opponents' credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stats:
</P>
<P>
   Length of the Official Day: Gore, 13{ hours; Bush, 13 hours
</P>
<P>
   States Visited: Gore, 1; Bush, 2
</P>
<P>
   Towns and Cities Visited: Gore, 1; Bush, 2
</P>
<P>
   Events: Gore, 1; Bush, 2
</P>
<P>
   Press Conferences/Press Availability: Gore, 0; Bush, 0
</P>
<P>
   Press Interviews (Includes newspaper and television interviews):
Gore, 5; Bush, 0
</P>
<P>
   Debate preparation: Gore, 1 hour; Bush, 0 hours
</P>
<P>
   Main message: Gore, economics; Bush, economic agenda, budget
comparisons
</P>
