<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CARRIERS TIGHTEN BELTS, IT'S EQUIPMENT-MAKERS WHO'LL HURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHLEEN PENDER  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Telecom-equipment stocks busted out of their
slump yesterday and rallied the overall market after a Sanford
Bernstein analyst issued a gloom-and-doom report on the sector.
</P>
<P>
   After falling for six straight sessions, the S&AMP;P communication
equipment index _ which includes Cisco Systems, Lucent Technologies
and Nortel Networks _ jumped 4 percent yesterday, more than any
other S&AMP;P sector index.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst called it a classic case of ``sell on the rumor, buy
on the news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone heard about this Sanford Bernstein report (Wednesday)
morning'' and started selling telecom-equipment stocks, says Jeff
Wrona, manager of the PBHG Technology &AMP; Communications fund. When
Bernstein analyst Paul Sagawa finally discussed his report in a
conference call yesterday morning, ``they bought them right back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein is known for doing detailed research and is considered
less biased than other Wall Street firms because it doesn't manage
stock and bond deals for the companies it covers. But its analysts
generally don't have the same stature as those from the big
investment banks. And some critics scoffed at Sagawa's gloomy
predictions, saying telecom-service providers always underestimate
how much they'll spend on equipment in the upcoming year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bernstein report predicted a ``sharp decline'' in spending
on equipment for carrying voice and data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our analysis of 59 North American and European
telecommunications carriers leads us to conclude that actual
spending on telecom equipment is likely to show a sharp
deceleration from more than 28 percent growth in 2000 to less than
20 percent growth in 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicts that total capital expenditures _ including
non-equipment outlays such as labor _ will fall 3 percent next year
after rising 31 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even spending on optical and data networking equipment, which
grew an astounding 65 percent this year, will grow only 39 percent
next year, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Given that he expects industry sales to grow less than 20
percent next year, Sagawa can't see how earnings could possibly
meet a consensus growth rate of 29 percent next year. ``In
particular, we are concerned that companies trading at more than 50
times forward earnings will face considerable pressure,'' he
writes.
</P>
<P>
   Sagawa, as expected, downgraded Cisco and Nortel to ``market
perform.'' But Merrill Lynch and Salomon Smith Barney reiterated
their buy ratings on both stocks. Cisco rose $2.13 to $59.88, while
Nortel jumped $2.13 to $61.75.
</P>
<P>
   Sagawa is hardly the first analyst to forecast a slowdown, but
he is more bearish than most.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in telecom equipment providers _ like Cisco, Nortel and
Lucent _ have been slumping for at least a month, ever since it
became clear that many of their customers were in a heap of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom service providers _ ranging from biggies like AT&AMP;T,
Sprint and WorldCom to smaller local-service providers dubbed CLECs
(competitive local exchange carriers) _ have been suffering from
overcapacity, falling prices, financing difficulties and, in some
cases, management problems.
</P>
<P>
   Two CLECs _ GST Telecommunications an ICG Communications _ have
become insolvent and more are headed that way. Some of these
companies are financed by telecom-equipment providers, who stand to
lose an investment as well as a customer.
</P>
<P>
   Sagawa admits that telecom carriers spent way more than they
thought they would on equipment this year, which is one reason for
their current predicament.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't see how they can keep spending at current rates,
given that stock prices for every category of carrier are down
after three years of superior returns, free cash flows have turned
sharply negative and bond yields are up (which makes debt financing
more costly).
</P>
<P>
   No one is expecting spending to continue at current rates, but
some are more bullish than Sagawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happens every year at this time. People get concerned
about capital spending on telecom equipment by the carriers,'' says
Robb Parlanti, co-manager of the Turner Technology fund. ``Service
providers don't want to say, `We're going to spend this much
money,' because that generally hits their stock.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, U.S. carriers projected a 7 percent to 10 percent
increase in spending and ended up spending 36 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   Sagawa says he took that into account when preparing his
projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our survey projects (total spending) to decline 9 percent in
the U.S. and 3 percent worldwide. If we assume the degree of
underestimation is the same (as last year), it equates to 18 to 21
percent growth in the U.S. and 17 to 20 percent worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Parlanti says the market has already discounted a moderate
slowdown in capital spending. ``I'll also say that I think that
Wall Street has a habit of taking things to extreme, on the upside
and the downside.''
</P>
<P>
   He is generally bullish on telecom-equipment stocks but says
they could post further losses in the next 30 days. Many mutual
funds have fiscal years ending in October and they will try to
minimize taxable distributions by selling losers to offset realized
gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next month we'll see the bottom for some of these
stocks. We'll be keeping an eye on Nortel, Corning, Cisco,''
Parlanti says.
</P>
<P>
   He says companies such as Lucent that are focused on older
technologies will fare the worst, because carriers will spend the
most money on newer technologies, primarily fiber optics.
</P>
<P>
   But he also says some of the smaller optics companies that have
one or two products could also get whipsawed. ``There's no doubt in
my mind that this group is still going to be volatile over the next
month or so,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Wrona, of PBHG, says he doesn't think anyone knows how much
telecom carriers will spend next year. And in a way, it doesn't
really matter, he adds. What does matter is the company's specific
products and customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being much more selective in which telecom equipment
companies I own,'' Wrona says. ``The wind is not at the back of a
lot of subsectors of the tech world. You really have to pick and
choose more than you did two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrona says he was buying Ciena and Redback Networks yesterday
and is looking at a couple of upcoming IPOs, including San Jose's
Oplink Communications. ``All of my exposure is in the optics/next
generation area,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sth  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; IPO UPDATE: Oplink is getting a lot of buzz in the IPO world, but
it'll face plenty of competition if it goes public next week as
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Ten companies went public this week and as many as 13 more could
premiere today. ``Underwriters were pushing to get out as many IPOs
as they could before the end of the quarter,'' says Dan McCarthy,
an analyst with IPO.com. The reason: to pump up their third-quarter
underwriting volumes.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine deals were priced last night, which means they'll
begin trading today, and four more were expected to price but could
be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest deal to price last night was Head, the Dutch maker
of tennis racquets and skis. The company priced its IPO at $10 per
share, the bottom of its $10-to-$12 range, but it still managed to
raise $208.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   This week's biggest winner, ironically, was CoSine
Communications, a Redwood City telecom-equipment-maker. It was
priced at $23 per share on Monday and closed Tuesday at $63.06. It
dipped slightly to $58.13 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Underwriters will be looking to see how well the market absorbs
today's new issues. ``Underwriters saw this as a big test week,''
says McCarthy. Depending on what happens today, he says, ``I think
they'll adjust their calendars accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
