<HEADER>
A5854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FAITHLESS-FILM-REVIEW     09-28 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAITHLESS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAITHLESS': IN AN OLD MAN'S REVERIES, THE PAST LIVES ON AS PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's an unsettling thought: The hardest lessons we learn in
life (and maybe the only lessons we truly absorb) are those learned
too late. It is precisely this sense of nagging regret and the
compulsion to comb obsessively through decisions that can't be
undone that haunts the characters in Liv Ullmann's morose and
profound film, ``Faithless.''
</P>
<P>
   For in looking back, there is usually a point at which past
events lose their fluidity. That lingering question of what-if?
evaporates, and the past becomes frozen, at once accessible and out
of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed by the actress and director (it's her fourth full-length
feature) from a late screenplay by Ingmar Bergman, this attenuated
two-and-a-half-hour reflection on marriage, adultery, parenthood
and the casualties of sexual warfare unfolds like a brooding
autobiographical epilogue to Bergman's much stormier 1974
masterpiece, ``Scenes From a Marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   In its tone, style and message, ``Faithless'' is an old man's
movie, paced at a measured hobble, its metaphysical gaze turned as
much toward the sea and the sky as toward the houses on the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Ullmann, a colleague and collaborator of Bergman's for decades,
has absorbed his sensibility and style so thoroughly that
``Faithless'' is more than just a reverent homage to the master. It
feels almost like the product of artificial respiration, as if
Ullmann (who starred in Bergman's ``Persona'' and ``Scenes From a
Marriage'') and Bergman were breathing life into each other in
long, sad exhalations.
</P>
<P>
   As in earlier Bergman films, the great Swedish actor Erland
Josephson is a stand-in for the director. This time around, his
character is a frail, aging film and theater director actually
named Bergman who, while rattling around his office, conjures up
the ghost of Marianne (Lena Endre), an actress he once loved who
has since died and become his muse.
</P>
<P>
   When she appears, he coaxes her into delivering a blow-by-blow
account of her love affair with her husband's best friend, David
(Krister Henriksson), a director who turns out to be the old man's
younger mid-40s self. As she tells the story, most of the events
she recalls are remembered in extended flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing orderly or predictable about the drama in which
Marianne is the prime mover and David, although the initiator of
the affair, the follower. Her husband, Markus (Thomas Hanzon), a
world-famous conductor, and their young daughter Isabelle (Michelle
Gylemo) flit in and out as supporting players who are horribly
damaged by the affair.
</P>
<P>
   As the story unfolds, you expect it to fade out, but it takes
several surprising turns as hidden facts come to light.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most tales of adultery, ``Faithless'' is an emotional
mystery story that never solves (or even tries to solve) an
essential puzzle. Why would a happily married woman jeopardize a
successful marriage by having an affair with her husband's poorer,
less attractive and admittedly unhappy best friend? For David, to
put it bluntly, is no catch. As he warns at the outset of their
affair, he is self-loathing, joyless and pathologically jealous. In
one of the film's ugliest scenes, he coaxes Marianne into revealing
the details of her past sexual adventures, then explodes with
violent jealousy when she's finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faithless'' offers few if any psychological or sexual clues to
explain Marianne's faithlessness. She professes to have a great sex
life with Markus, yet she still gives in to David's casual
suggestion that they sleep together. Is it just curiosity?
Altruism? When Marianne has an opportunity to end this rocky affair
before the roof falls in, she chooses not to. The movie suggests
that major life decisions that can have the most earthshaking,
tragic consequences may ultimately come down to whims.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery is deepened by the film's extraordinary central
performances. With his alarmed watery eyes gazing beseechingly into
the void, Josephson's Bergman is an unforgettable portrait of the
artist as an old man at once tormented by his past and unable to
resist raking over its coals. If he has acquired a certain wisdom
and humility late in life, they have arrived too late to do him any
good, which only adds salt to his wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The only word to describe David, Bergman's self-portrait of his
younger self, is unsparing. In every shot, Henriksson palpably
registers David's inner suffering, as if beneath a surface
joviality he were wincing through his life. Most complicated of all
is Endre's Marianne, a woman who usually knows exactly what she's
feeling but who has no understanding of the forces determining her
behavior. She has the paradoxical quality of having a conscience
but hardly any capacity for self-examination. In the end, you begin
to wonder if this is Bergman's view of the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   Ullmann has filled the movie with references to earlier Bergman
films, especially those in which she appeared. The mirror images of
characters confronting one another echo ``Persona,'' while the
couple's erupting domestic battles recall ``Scenes From a
Marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   The very solemnity of ``Faithless'' reminds us that the
institution of marriage isn't the awesome edifice it used to be,
that our expectations of coupling ``till death do us part'' aren't
as absolute and fearsome as they were in the 1950s and '60s when
Bergman was at his creative peak. As excruciatingly painful as it
is, sexual betrayal in marriage nowadays is less likely to be the
life-or-death, kill-or-be-killed emotional battle that it is for
these characters. The dam of all-powerful monogamy and the
commitments it entails has been seriously breached.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FAITHLESS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Liv Ullmann; written (in Swedish, with English
subtitles) by Ingmar Bergman; director of photography, Jorgen
Persson; edited by Sylvia Ingemarsson; art director, Goran
Wassberg; produced by Kaj Larsen; released by Samuel Goldwyn
Films/Fireworks Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 155 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Therese Brunnander (Petra Holst), Juni Dahr (Margareta),
Stina Ekblad (Eva), Lena Endre (Marianne), Bjorn Granath (Gustav),
Michelle Gylemo (Isabelle), Thomas Hanzon (Markus), Krister
Henriksson (David), Erland Josephson (Bergman), Johan Rabaeus
(Johan), Marie Richardson (Anna Berg), Gertrud Stenung (Martha),
Jan-Olof Strandberg (Axel) and Philip Zanden (Martin Goldman). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
