<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-MICROSOFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL ALLEN LEAVING MICROSOFT BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After increasingly distancing himself from the company
he helped create 25 years ago, Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen will
step down from the company's board of directors next month.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a Mercer Island resident worth an estimated $36 billion,
will become a senior strategy adviser to Microsoft, the company
said in a proxy statement filed after the close of business
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, 47, declined to comment on why he is resigning his post.
In a prepared statement, he wrote, ``Being an active board member
for a dynamic and successful company such as Microsoft is a
time-consuming role and one I have enjoyed for many years. This new
role will enable me to spend my time on technology and products
where I can really make a significant contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen's spokeswoman, Susan Pearson Brown, said Allen is not
leaving for health reasons. After founding Microsoft with Chairman
Bill Gates in 1975, Allen left in 1983 in the midst of a battle
with Hodgkin's disease.
</P>
<P>
   He has been the biggest individual seller of Microsoft shares
this year, unloading shares worth more than $6 billion, according
to the Washington Service, which tracks insider stock sales.
</P>
<P>
   Most onlookers speculated he is departing to focus more closely
on his own extensive investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been pretty involved in his own investments over the past
few years, so I don't know how involved he's been in Microsoft's
board anyhow,'' said Jonathan Geurkink, an analyst with Ragen
MacKenzie Inc. in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's Vulcan Ventures investment arm has a hand in some 140
technology, telecommunications and entertainment companies,
including Egghead Inc., Asymetrix Corp., Starwave Corp. and Virtual
Vision Inc. Allen owns the Seattle Seahawks football team and
Portland Trail Blazers basketball team, and in June opened a $240
million shrine to American music, the Experience Music Project, in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The world's third richest man, Allen currently serves on the
boards of Charter Communications, USA Networks, pop.com, and
DreamWorks SKG.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Allen's reasons, his departure creates the impression
of a company in transition, if not in trouble, one analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft was the 8,000 pound gorilla with the super growth
trajectory, and now the near-term perception will be that
everything isn't quite tight at Microsoft,'' said Gene Munster, an
analyst with U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows a huge drop in Microsoft's stock price, the
departure of key old-guard executives, and multiple antitrust
lawsuits. The stock closed up 69 cents at $61.31 Thursday, and
declined 81 cents in afterhours trading.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has dropped 47 percent this year, making it the
second-worst performer in the Dow Jones Industrial Average. Chief
financial officer Greg Maffei, chief technology officer Nathan
Myhrvold, Windows chief Brad Silverberg, and MSN maven Pete Higgins
all left the company within the past year. Just two weeks ago,
14-year veteran Paul Maritz retired.
</P>
<P>
   A three-year-old federal antitrust suit, along with scores of
private antitrust class actions, continues to dog the company. But
Microsoft did win a victory earlier this week when the Supreme
Court declined to hear its antitrust appeal before lower court
review, sending the appeal to a court where Microsoft has prevailed
twice before on related matters.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said in a prepared release, ``Paul and I have an amazing
friendship that extends back 30 years. I will continue to value his
friendship and counsel in the years ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Gates and Allen together bluffed a tiny Albuquerque
computer company, Model Instrumentation and Telemetry Systems, into
thinking they had created a version of the BASIC language for that
company's 8080-based Altair computer. They then worked day and
night for 8 weeks in a Harvard University computer lab to actually
write it, according to ``Hard Drive,'' a history of Microsoft by
James Wallace and Jim Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed, the company's president offered to make Allen
software director, a position he accepted. He left to work full
time with Gates in November 1977, with a 36 percent share in the
company then called Micro-Soft.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hackborn, a former executive vice president of
Hewlett-Packard, also will leave the board.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said Hackborn will leave his seat to spend more time
on personal and philanthropic pursuits. He stepped down as chairman
of the board of Hewlett-Packard last week but will remain on that
board. He retired from Hewlett-Packard in 1993 as the executive
vice president of the Computer Products Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The departures reduce Microsoft's board to six people. Allen and
Hackborn will not be replaced, Microsoft said.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining board members are David Marquardt, a founding
general partner of August Capital in Menlo Park, Calif.; Ann
McLaughlin, a director of and adviser to numerous educational and
not-for-profit organizations; and William Reed, a Medina resident
who is also a director of PACCAR, Inc., SAFECO Corp., the Seattle
Times Co. and Washington Mutual Savings Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the board are Jon Shirley, another Medina resident who
served as Microsoft's president and chief operating officer from
1983 to 1990; chief executive Steve Ballmer; and Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Wire service material is included in this report
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
