<SLUG> BC-EDIT-YUGO-MILOSEVIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MILOSEVIC'S TRICKERY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Sept. 29:
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic's resounding defeat in Yugoslavia's
presidential elections is being celebrated by large and joyous
crowds around the country. Thursday, Serbia's Orthodox Church
joined most of Yugoslavia's political parties, President Clinton
and leaders across Europe in recognizing the election of the
opposition candidate, Vojislav Kostunica.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, Milosevic himself does not yet seem to have gotten
the message. His allies in the government-controlled election
commission have brazenly shaved just enough votes off Kostunica's
winning margin to call for a runoff vote next month. That insults
democracy and invites political turmoil. The international
community, including Russia, must firmly insist that Milosevic step
aside now.
</P>
<P>
   The most reliable vote count comes from opposition poll watchers
who observed the official ballot tabulation at almost every voting
place in Yugoslavia. Adding up the local tally sheets, each signed
by observers from all major parties, shows Kostunica with a clear
majority of 52.54 percent, enough to avoid a runoff, with only
35.01 percent going to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition count has been endorsed by Washington and leading
European governments. Similar results have been announced by
Yugoslavia's leading independent vote monitoring group and even by
some parties previously allied with Milosevic. But early Thursday
morning the election commission announced a total of 48.96 percent
for Kostunica and 38.62 for Milosevic. Producing those figures
required disqualifying several hundred thousand voters and
dispensing with the legal requirement of reconciling the
commission's numbers with the tally sheet totals compiled by the
opposition. If these cooked numbers are allowed to stand, neither
candidate would have the 50 percent needed for a first-round
victory, forcing an Oct. 8 runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has rightly refused to accept this latest
attempted manipulation by the Milosevic camp. New balloting would
give the beleaguered dictator time to regroup and once more try to
steal victory through systematic vote-rigging and violent
repression. Instead Kostunica has summoned his supporters to the
streets to defend his victory, and plans to call for civil
disobedience. Hundreds of thousands of Yugoslavs have already
rallied in Belgrade and other major cities.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is understandably desperate to cling to power. Out of
office, he might find it harder to avoid eventual trial before an
international war crimes tribunal for his treatment of Kosovo's
Albanians. But he should not be allowed to take Yugoslavia down
with him. An attempt to prolong his rule by further electoral fraud
could produce unrest, even violence, making it difficult for
Yugoslavia to end its economic and political isolation from the
rest of Europe. Russia, which has traditionally seen itself as the
protector of Yugoslavia's people, has thus far stood apart from
European demands for Milosevic's immediate departure. Moscow should
now make clear to him that the Yugoslav people have voted him out
of power and he must yield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
