<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISMISSES PART OF JUSTICE DEPARTMENT'S SUIT AGAINST TOBACCO
INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge threw out part of the government's
suit against the tobacco industry on Thursday, narrowing the
avenues by which the Justice Department can seek billions of
dollars in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Gladys Kessler of U.S. District Court, dismissed two
counts in the Justice Department suit, rejecting theories that the
government could use two statutes enacted 40 years ago to recover
money spent on smoking-related health care. Those statutes empower
the government to seek damages from outside parties it deems
responsible for medical expenses borne by the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   But Kessler declined to throw out two other counts accusing the
industry of operating a ``racketeering enterprise'' and seeking
recovery of ill-gotten gains.
</P>
<P>
   Each side issued a statement saying it was happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to proceeding to trial and holding the tobacco
companies accountable for the fraudulent conduct alleged in this
lawsuit,'' said David Ogden, the assistant attorney general who
heads the Justice Department's Civil Division.
</P>
<P>
   William Ohlemeyer, vice president and associate general counsel
for Philip Morris, one of the defendants in the suit, called
Thursday's ruling ``an important first step in the ultimate
dismissal of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   A government official who spoke on condition he not be named had
this perspective: ``Would we rather have had a one-line ruling
saying that the motion to dismiss is denied? Sure. But this is
still a big lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge said as much in her ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the government's theories of liability have been
limited,'' she wrote, ``the extent of defendants' potential
liability remains, in the estimation of both parties, in the
billions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The government suit was filed last September and sought to use
the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act, the Medical
Care Recovery Act and provisions of the Medicare Secondary Payer
statute to pry money from the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting the government's efforts to use the last two, Kessler
concluded that Congress had not intended those laws to be used the
way the Justice Department sought to employ them.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Medical Care Recovery Act of 1962, she noted
``its total nonenforcement by the Department of Justice for 37 of
those 38 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In ruling that the RICO portion of the suit could proceed, the
judge held that the government had established a sufficient basis
for its claims, ``which is all it must do at this early stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit is the first the government has filed against an entire
industry using the RICO statute. The statute was enacted 30 years
ago to fight organized crime, although federal prosecutors have
more recently used it against businesses and others it contends
have engaged in a pattern of illegal acts.
</P>
<P>
   The government argues such a pattern going back to at least 1953
among the tobacco companies. It accuses them of promoting biased
research, wrongly asserting that nicotine was not addictive and
aiming their products at children.
</P>
<P>
   When the suit was filed last year, Attorney General Janet Reno
accused the companies of engaging in ``a campaign designed to
preserve their enormous profits whatever the cost in human lives,
human suffering and medical resources.''
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry has accused the government of ``politically
correct extortion,'' as Greg Little, a Philip Morris lawyer
characterized it a year ago, and of bullying an entire industry in
a way it has treated no other legal enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is separate from the cases that resulted in settlements
totaling about $246 billion that the tobacco industry reached with
various states in 1998 over smoking-related Medicaid costs for the
poor and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Philip Morris, the defendants are R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co.; the former American Tobacco Co.; the Brown &AMP;
Williamson Tobacco Corp., a division of British American Tobacco
PLC; the Lorillard Tobacco Co.; the Liggett Group; the Council for
Tobacco Research USA Inc.; and the Tobacco Institute Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler rejected a request by the Liggett Group to exempt it
from the racketeering suit on grounds it broke with other tobacco
companies four years ago and settled with several states.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-tobacco groups expressed pleasure at Thursday's ruling. The
Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids said it hoped that Congress would
not succumb to pressure to cut off money to pay for the Justice
Department suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxpayers deserve their day in court to hold the tobacco
companies responsible for their illegal behavior,'' the
organization said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
