<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BACKUPS BATTER MADDUX, JUST FOR THE FUN OF IT
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets are not used to relaxing. Sometimes
they press, sometimes they focus, but not since the end of the 1997
season had the Mets been able to kick back and play ball for the
heck of it. Thursday night, the Mets played a game with absolutely
nothing on the line, and they had no trouble beating the best
pitcher of this generation.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets clinched the National League wild-card berth on
Wednesday, so four everyday players took Thursday night off. Two
other starters are out with minor injuries. A sell-out crowd of
52,134 at Shea Stadium paid to see the Mets' bench try to hit the
Atlanta Braves' Greg Maddux. They left the park happy for the
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   With Maddux trying to win his 20th game and build on a lengthy
scoreless innings streak, the Mets' reserves knocked him out after
five innings, en route to an 8-2 victory. Todd Pratt drove in three
runs, Darryl Hamilton had two hits, Timo Perez scored twice and
Kurt Abbott hit a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than enough support for the right-hander Bobby J.
Jones, who worked eight innings, allowing two runs (one earned) to
improve to 11-6. The strong effort could complicate the Mets'
decision about who will be their fourth starter in the division
series against St. Louis or San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets almost certainly will use four starters; if they do
not, two starters would have to pitch on short rest in a five-game
series. General Manager Steve Phillips, manager Bobby Valentine and
the coaching staff will meet Friday to discuss plans for the
playoff roster and rotation, and they were coy Thursday when asked
for their thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton, Al Leiter and Rick Reed will each get a start, of
course. But Glendon Rusch and Jones can make strong cases for a
turn. Rusch (11-11) has pitched better lately, and Phillips said
recent performance will be a factor in which pitcher starts and
which shifts to the bullpen. But Valentine said Thursday night's
game would not affect his opinion of Jones, a veteran he trusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's a very good pitcher who I think is capable of winning
a game any time of the season,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, whose team was eliminated from playoff contention on
the final day in 1998 and clinched a playoff spot in a one-game
playoff last year, rested shortstop Mike Bordick, catcher Mike
Piazza, third baseman Robin Ventura and first baseman Todd Zeile.
Two outfielders _ Derek Bell (bruised left knee) and Benny Agbayani
(strained right hamstring) _ also sat out.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux came in with 361/3 consecutive scoreless innings, a total
topped only twice in the majors since Orel Hershiser's record
59-inning run in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux worked the first three innings perfectly, needing only 26
pitches to retire the first nine Mets. That brought the streak to
391/3 innings, and with two more scoreless innings, Maddux would
own the longest streak since Hershiser's.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. Timo Perez, who sparked two rallies on
Wednesday, tried to bunt for a hit, but the ball went foul. Maddux
then threw three balls, and Perez took first on Maddux's second
walk in more than 40 innings.
</P>
<P>
   This was a case of a leadoff hitter making things happen.
Agbayani probably will regain the leadoff spot if his strained
right hamstring heals for the playoffs, but Perez is faster, and
his legs paid off here. With Perez running and second baseman Keith
Lockhart covering the bag, Hamilton tapped a slow bouncer to second
for a single.
</P>
<P>
   There were runners at first and third, and after getting a
flyout, Maddux hit Jay Payton with a pitch to load the bases. He
ran the count to 3-0 on Lenny Harris, a .179 career hitter off him,
then got Harris to chop the ball in front of the plate. Maddux was
poised to leap for it _ a Gold Glover, he has perfected the move _
but the ball was well over his head, and shortstop Rafael Furcal
could not barehand it.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreless streak was over, the Mets had tied the game, 1-1,
and on the next pitch they took a 3-1 lead when Todd Pratt lashed a
single to right.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets added a run in the fifth, in another rally generated by
Perez, who walked again, this time with with one out. Hamilton
singled, his seventh hit in 13 at-bats against Maddux, and Edgardo
Alfonzo grounded to short. Furcal's throw was wild, an error, and
Perez scored to put the Mets in front, 4-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
