<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEED OF MOMENTUM, THE YANKEES GET PUMMELED
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The New York Yankees have been so
dominant for so long that even their losing streaks made sense.
They were either unhealthy or unchallenged but always unconcerned
because the Yankees have come to believe in their own ability to
refocus and win any game they absolutely had to win.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   At a time of year when they usually increase their level of
intensity and assume the look of a juggernaut, the Yankees are
being obliterated daily, and they are confused, angry, frustrated.
It is as if baseball's supermen have been robbed of their powers
and they do not know why.
</P>
<P>
   They look helpless, with the playoffs four days away. The Tampa
Bay Devil Rays concluded a three-game sweep of the Yankees here
Thursday night, wiping out Roger Clemens, 11-3, and handing the
Yankees their fourth straight loss, 12th in 15 games and their
sixth defeat by eight or more runs in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, the Yankees managed to inch closer toward the
American League East title because the Toronto Blue Jays were
eliminated in Baltimore, 23-1. One more Yankees victory or Boston
Red Sox defeat would put the Yankees into the postseason next week.
</P>
<P>
   There was no chance George Steinbrenner would participate in
even a muted clinching celebration, however. He has owned the
spotlight in such times during the Yankees' rebirth over the last
five years. But as Tampa Bay whipped his team Thursday night,
Steinbrenner sat near the back of his private box, a silhouette on
television screens, and stalked out before the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   His anger has occasionally boiled over through this strange
season, but he has been relatively sedate the last couple of days.
There is nothing he can do now; the Yankees will either rebound or
their reign will end.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees abandoned their clubhouse quickly Wednesday after
Tampa Bay crushed them, 11-1, a loss variously described by the
players and manager Joe Torre as humiliating, embarrassing,
disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he was disappointed and hung the wreath of defeat on
the pitching. He leans toward the notion that the slump is mostly
the result of poor pitching, given that the Yankees have allowed
114 runs in 15 games, an average of 7.6 runs a game.
</P>
<P>
   Others offered different interpretations. Reliever Mike Stanton
feels that since the Yankees swept the series in Boston three weeks
ago, ``the intensity we had up until that point hasn't been
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton continued: ``I think there was a big exhale once the
Boston series was over. It's like the old parable: You push to row
upstream in a river, and you don't stop rowing once you get to
where you want. You have to keep pushing, and for a short time,
we've stopped rowing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
