u f BC-SONY-PLAYSTATION-NYT &LR;      09-28 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONY-PLAYSTATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONY FACES BIG DELAYS FOR PLAYSTATION 2 SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The North American debut of Sony's new Playstation 2 video
system appears to have become a marketing nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   After days of rumors, Sony confirmed Wednesday that it would
fall far short of meeting its promise to have a million devices
ready for sale on Oct. 26. At least 500,000 consumers Sony had
expected to satisfy immediately _ many of whom had made deposits
with retailers _ will be turned away. Sony blamed shortages of
electronic components, though it offered no details.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that despite Sony's plans to ship 100,000
units a week from the end of October until Christmas, sales of the
$299 device will fall at least 700,000 units below previous
projections for the Christmas season, costing more than $200
million in revenues. And that is not counting lost sales from game
software and compact discs that can be played on Playstation 2, the
first device that lets users play video games, browse the Internet
and play DVD-format discs on one machine.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals asserted that Sony was squandering a huge opportunity in
the $8 billion games industry, where 60 percent of sales come in
the last quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have something under the Christmas tree, `` said
Peter Moore, president and chief operating officer of Sega of
America, which is shifting its $149 Dreamcast video units from
container ships to air freighters to fill what it describes as
soaring demand from retailers frantic to stock up on alternatives
to Playstation. ``Rain checks won't work with kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts were not so sure. While some sales would be
lost, they said, Playstation 2 is such an advance on competing
systems that many serious game players, however annoyed, are likely
to wait until Sony works out its production bottlenecks. While Sega
will certainly experience a measurable boost, they say, Playstation
2 will not face true competition until the fall of 2001, when both
Microsoft and Nintendo are expected to introduce products with
comparable features.
</P>
<P>
   Sony said Wednesday that it would catch up with it previous
production promises by the end of its fiscal year next March 31,
its target date for having sold 10 million Playstation 2 consoles
worldwide. The device was introduced in Japan last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just shifting revenue from the end of this year to
the first three months of 2001,'' said James Lin, an analyst at
Sutro &AMP; Co. ``The impact is minimal once you do the math.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony's stock and shares of game designers like Electronic Arts
and Activision rebounded in heavy trading Thursday from sharp
declines on Wednesday, when rumors about Sony's problems had
swirled through the markets.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's American depository receipts rose $5.06 Thursday, to
$104.44, after falling $9.38 on Wednesday. Electronic Arts rose
$4.94, to $50.13; Activision climbed $1.38, to $14; and THQ rose
$3.44, to $24.50.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's problems represent the latest variation on a familiar
theme this year for electronics consumers and investors. The entire
industry has been hit by shortages of memory chips, displays,
several types of processors and even humdrum components like
capacitors _ tiny devices that cost a few cents but are crucial to
managing power on chips.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, including IBM, Palm and the cellular phone giant
Ericsson, have lost so much production to shortages that it has had
a material impact on earnings. Analysts expect fewer such
announcements in the coming months as many of the shortages are
eased, but several component markets are expected to remain tight
for at least another six months.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's inability to pull together the components needed to
create a huge inventory of Playstation 2 units for rollout
contrasts with the situation at Sega, which ironed out the mass
production kinks that Dreamcast encountered last year and has been
able to build a slight buffer of inventory this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's shortfall, though, is vast even by gaming industry
standards, and many retailers are fuming that they were not warned
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for short supplies is certain to be tense for months,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is how it is distributed among the big versus
the small shops,'' said John-Paul McNealy, a consumer electronics
analyst for Gartner Group in San Jose, Calif. ``We think the Mom
and Pop stores are going to get pinched.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
