<HEADER>
A6035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-ORGAN-MANAGERS-380&AMP;AD     09-28 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-MANAGERS-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY MANAGING DISTRIBUTION OF ORGANS FOR TRANSPLANT RETAINS
CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government on Thursday renewed its
contract with the private organization that runs the nation's organ
transplant system, a move that appears to end two years of bitter
dispute over the limited number of organs are distributed.
</P>
<P>
   After competitive bidding, the contract was again awarded to the
United Network for Organ Sharing, a nonprofit organization based in
Richmond, Va., that had resisted new federal rules requiring organs
to be distributed across broad geographic areas to the sickest
patients first.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year contract explicitly calls for the network to
accept those rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely pleased to have retained this important
contract and thus continue to serve the needs of the more than
71,000 patients awaiting transplants,'' said Walter Graham, the
network's executive director. The contract, he said, affirms the
government's ``continued confidence in our ability.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the contract does not give complete authority to the
organ sharing network.
</P>
<P>
   The network, which has run the transplant system since the
mid-1980s, will continue to maintain the list of patients who are
waiting for new organs and will run the computer system that
matches waiting patients with donated organs.
</P>
<P>
   But federal health officials selected another organization, the
University Renal Research and Education Association of Ann Arbor,
Mich., to run the scientific registry that examines how transplant
patients fare and how changes in organ distribution policy affect
them.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Claude Earl Fox, the administrator of the Health Resources
and Services Administration, the federal Health and Human Services
unit that oversees the transplant system, said he hoped that the
awarding of the contracts would help the government, ``settle the
dust and move forward with the transplant community'' to improve
the quality of care for patients.
</P>
<P>
   He added:``There was absolutely no politics involved. These
contracts were awarded based on merit.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract with the Richmond group is worth $52 million for
three years. About $1.5 million per year will come from taxpayers,
while the rest comes from fees paid by transplant patients or their
insurers. The Michigan group will receive $2.5 million per year
from taxpayers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thursday's decision came one day after Donna Shalala, the
secretary of Health and Human Services, announced she was creating
an advisory committee on organ transplantation to help guide her
though the thicket of medical and ethical issues that come with
regulating the transplants.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the committee, Shalala said it would provide her
with ``top-notch, science-based counsel on transplantation
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the organ sharing network had worked over the summer to
develop new policies for distributing livers, which are in
especially short supply, and that the advisory committee would help
assess those proposals.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 62,000 Americans now waiting for donated
organs, and each year, about 4,000 people die while they wait. As a
result, the dispute over who should receive donated organs is
intense.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when Shalala first proposed revamping the organ sharing
system to force organ sharing across broad geographic regions,
reaction to the proposal was swift and intense.
</P>
<P>
   Under the system that had been in effect since the mid-1980s,
when the organ sharing network got its start, the country was
divided into 11 regions further divided into a total of 62 areas.
Donated organs were first offered to patients within areas. Only if
there was no need locally, were they offered in the larger regions.
</P>
<P>
   Citing great disparities in waiting times for transplants from
region to region, Shalala argued that the old system was unfair and
sought to replace it with one that would break down the old
geographic barriers.
</P>
<P>
   The organ sharing network resisted, however, and soon the debate
moved to Congress, which put the administration's rules on hold
until March of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was not only political, but economic. Small
transplant centers feared that the new rules would put them out of
business by steering organs to larger, big-city hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, transplant surgeons argued bitterly among
themselves. Some states also stepped into the debate, passing
legislation that would prevent organs from being shipped to
neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Thursday's decision, Congress could still step in. The
National Organ Transplant Act, the 1984 law that created the organ
allocation system, expired several years ago and is up for
reauthorization. Congress could use the reauthorization as an
occasion to reshape the system yet again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
