<SLUG> BC-3COM-EXEC-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTICIPATED RESIGNATION OCCURS AT 3COM
</HEADLINE>
  By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The 3Com Corp. said Thursday that Eric Benhamou
had resigned as chief executive, but would remain chairman.
</P>
<P>
   He is being succeeded as chief executive by Bruce Claflin,
3Com's president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou's departure has been anticipated ever since 3Com
successfully spun off its Palm Inc. unit in an initial public
offering in July.
</P>
<P>
   His restructuring of the company showed signs of being on track
on Tuesday, when 3Com reported a first-quarter loss that was
substantially smaller than analysts' estimates. But the company's
future prospects remain cloudy, analysts say, and investors are
wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is my 10th anniversary as chief executive,'' Benhamou
said in a telephone interview, noting that his original commitment
to the board was to run 3Com for 10 years. ``In an industry as
volatile as ours, it's a good discipline to self-regenerate
leadership. I believe Bruce is up to it, and the most qualified
person to lead 3Com through its next phase.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of 3Com rose $1, to $18, in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou presided over a rocky 10 years at 3Com, which once had
a clear opportunity to be the dominant company in computer
networking. Its founder, Robert Metcalfe, invented Ethernet, a
popular technology used for creating office networks of personal
computers, while a researcher at the fabled Xerox PARC. But the
company lost ground early on to Novell Inc., which emphasized
software over hardware, and more recently to Cisco Systems Inc.,
which has been a much more aggressive competitor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 3Com acquired U.S. Robotics Inc., the leading modem
manufacturer, only to watch as the modem market imploded. At the
same time, 3Com's own core product, network adaptor cards for
connecting PCs to Ethernet, became a commodity item with little
profitability. In routers, specialized computers used to direct
traffic over networks, the company was consistently outgunned by
Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately Palm, which had been a nearly overlooked part of the
U.S. Robotics deal, came to be worth more by itself than all of
3Com. So 3Com spun off Palm, and at the same time announced its
withdrawal from the corporate networking equipment business. 3Com
now is focused primarily on broadband and wireless connectivity
devices for consumers and small businesses, and infrastructure
equipment for companies that provide telecommunications and
Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou, 45, appointed Claflin, 48, president and chief
operating officer in 1998. Claflin had previously worked for the
Digital Equipment Corp. and the International Business Machines
Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
