<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6050 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-OLYTRAK-LADN-(SLA     09-28 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYTRAK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARION BY A MILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SYDNEY, Australia _ Once upon a time, the women's Olympic
200-meter dash looked as if it would be taut with drama. That was
before the fairytale unraveled like the plot of a dime-store novel.
</P>
<P>
   When defending Olympic champion Marie-Jose Perec's demons chased
her out of these Summer Games and defending world champion Inger
Miller bowed out with a hamstring pull, the ending of the 200 final
here became as predictable as the guy getting the girl.
</P>
<P>
   As long as she finished, Marion Jones was going to finish first.
The ending was foreshadowed none too subtly in the semifinal
Thursday when the former Thousand Oaks High standout clocked a
22.40 and looked as winded afterward as someone who had just
gathered the newspaper off her front porch.
</P>
<P>
   In the final, a scant two hours later, Jones pulled away from
the field so promptly, her final 80 meters was for all intents and
purposes the start of her victory lap.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was timed in 21.84, a season best. Pauline Davis-Thompson
of the Bahamas edged Susanthika Jayasinghe of Sri Lanka for the
silver, 22.27 to 22.28. Not since Australian Marjorie Jackson's
.5-second victory in the 1952 Olympics in the era of hand-timing
had anyone scored such a clear-cut victory in the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief,'' said Jones, who is 2 for 2 in her historic
quest for five gold medals, having won the 100 meters Saturday.
``I'm here for greater things than two gold medals. In a certain
way I guess I am checking (the events) off the list. But I'm
definitely enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing Jones enjoys more than competing. When she saw
Davis-Thompson's times dropping with every round of the 200, Jones
said she thought to herself, ``OK, it's going to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been thrilling to see Jones battle a healthy
Miller, whose personal best in the event is within .01-second of
Jones' 21.76. And Perec has run a sub-22, so her presence would
have added to the intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Perec weren't the only athletes whose nonappearance
created a theatrical void. Erki Nool of Estonia won the decathlon
in the absence of Dan O'Brien, the defending Olympic decathlon
champion who missed the U.S. Trials with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Konstantinos Kenteris of Greece won the gold medal in the 200-
meter dash in the absence of world-record holder Michael Johnson
and Maurice Greene, both of whom pulled up lame in the final at the
U.S. Trials. Ato Boldon, who ran at UCLA and competes for his
native Trinidad &AMP; Tabogo, finished third in the slowest 200-meter
final since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   And Americans Suzy Favor Hamilton and Camarillo High graduate
Marla Runyan advanced to Saturday's final in the 1500 meters in the
absence of U.S. Trials winner Regina Jacobs, who dropped out of the
Games with a viral infection.
</P>
<P>
   Anymore at the Olympics, it's not finishing first that's the
hardest thing; it's making it to the starting blocks at all.
</P>
<P>
   Jones knows bad things can happen to really good athletes. She
collapsed on the track with back spasms in the semifinals of the
200 meters at last summer's World Championships. So she can be
forgiven for not looking any farther than tonight's long jump final
(she also is scheduled to run in the 400 and 1,600 relays).
</P>
<P>
   That Jones has been able to maintain her keen focus the past few
days in spite of the fallout from her husband C.J. Hunter's
positive test for the banned steroid nandrolone is something of
which she is proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that could have easily swayed my focus, but
it hasn't,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   She simply has worked too hard and dreamed too big to get
distracted now.
</P>
<P>
   ``To let some event in your life, no matter how dramatic it
might be, ruin a dream you've had for a lot of years wouldn't be
worth it at all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For someone who long ago declared her intentions to become the
first track athlete to win five gold medals in a single Olympics,
Jones, 24, is awfully modest. She was quick to dismiss any notion
that she was running against the clock Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in a class by myself,'' she said. Nodding to Davis-
Thompson and Jayasinghe, who flanked her in the interview room,
Jones added, ``These women pushed me. They made me dig deep down.''
</P>
<P>
   From high in the Olympic Stadium stands, it appeared as though
Jones, a red-white-and-blue blur, was the one pushing the others
along to faster times. All seven runners behind her posted
season-best times and Davis-Thompson and Jayasinghe recorded
lifetime bests.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's awesome,'' said another finalist, Melinda Gainsford-
Taylor, who had nipped Jones in a quarterfinal heat Wednesday and
then awakened Thursday to find photos of her first-place finish
stripped across the front pages of the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a clear case of a picture misrepresenting the facts,
Gainsford-Taylor admitted with a giggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just good fun, I think,'' she said after finishing
sixth in the final. ``I knew Marion was shutting down, so I said,
what the hell, it's my hometown, and I passed her.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainsford-Taylor went on to admit she's keeping all of
Thursday's newspapers and probably will have the photo of her
beating Jones framed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that terrible?'' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The female sprint corps isn't exactly known for being an esprit
de corps. Big egos and a small margin of error make for uneasy
alliances; just ask Miller and Jones, who will exchange relay
batons before they do words.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest living female on the planet, Gainsford-Taylor says,
is also the friendliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been running internationally for the last 10 years and
I've never seen someone so friendly,'' Gainsford-Taylor said.
``It's just really refreshing, let's put it that way. I've seen
good winners and bad winners. She's a good winner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
