r s BC-OLY-WOMSOC-LADN-(SLAN     09-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMSOC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWAY EDGES U.S. IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Same excitement. Different result.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's soccer team has a knack for playing dramatic
matches in the grandest of arenas and the Yanks were at it again
Thursday night at the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffeny Milbrett scored her second goal 30 seconds from end time
to forge a stunning tie, but Norway got the decisive goal 12
minutes into overtime to upset the Americans 3-2 in the gold-medal
match at Sydney Football Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will sleep well tonight knowing they did everything they
could to win this game,'' U.S. coach April Heinrichs said of her
players.
</P>
<P>
   After a streak of winning big matches going back to the 1996
Olympics and extending through the 1999 World Cup, the U.S. this
time succumbed to a cool, heady Norwegian team that took advantage
of its limited opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive chance came when U.S. defender Joy Fawcett's
attempted clearance header caromed off Norway forward Dagny
Mellgren and fell to her feet just inside the box. Mellgren bounced
a shot that U.S. keeper Siri Mullinix got a hand on but couldn't
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinix did not have a strong match. She never saw Norway's
first goal, off a corner kick; came off her line in an attempt to
catch a ball that turned into a header and Norway's second goal;
and couldn't get a big-enough piece of a ball within her reach on
the third goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got down on it and I got a piece of it, but I guess it
wasn't enough,'' Mullinix said of the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Julie Foudy refused to consider the idea that Mullinix
cost the U.S. the gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Siri has done a tremendous job for us,'' Foudy said.
``She's been absolutely phenomenal. Without her, we don't even get
to this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans dominated the first half but managed only one
goal. ``Coulda, woulda, shoulda,'' U.S. forward Mia Hamm said of
the missed opportunities. ``It's a little late for that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett banged home a perfect pass by Hamm in the fifth minute
to launch what for a time looked like a replay of the 2-0 U.S.
victory in the opening match of this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have started better,'' Heinrichs said. ``It's a
coach's dream to push the ball around as much as we did, and all
that possession.''
</P>
<P>
   But it yielded only a 1-1 tie at the half when Gro Espeseth
headed in a corner kick in the 41st minute.
</P>
<P>
   Espeseth said Norway had to withstand the early U.S. momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored so early and I said, 'Oh, no, not again,' '' she
said. ``Why should they win again and again and again?''
</P>
<P>
   The game took on a different cast in the second half as Norway
coach Per-Mathias Hagmo packed his midfield with a 4-5-1 formation
to break up the U.S. attack and Norway launched counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
   Ragnhild Gulbrandsen put Norway up 2-1 in the 78th minute when
she headed in a long pass while colliding with Fawcett and Siri
Mullinix near the penalty spot. ``That's my style, going out for
long balls,'' Mullinix said. ``Unfortunately, this time it didn't
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans weren't finished, even as they went into the
second of two minutes of extra time tacked on after the 90th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team never gives up until they're told to leave the
field,'' Heinrichs said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm carried a ball down the right flank and launched a long
cross into the box. It sailed over the head of midfielder Kristine
Lilly but right into the path of Milbrett, who headed it home, a
lightning bolt of a goal that brought the crowd to its feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best goals I've ever scored,'' Milbrett said. ``I
mean, I'm 5-foot-2 so I haven't put in too many with my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps exhausted by its comeback, the U.S. failed to carry
momentum into overtime, and Norway ended things quickly in the
sudden-death format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norway are champions,'' Heinrichs said. ``We have a
deep-deep-seated respect for Norway. Their history, their talent,
their will to find a way to win. We respect that and have for 10
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
