<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN UPSTATE NEW YORK, RICK LAZIO STUMPS TO SHOW HIS CONCERN FOR
REGION'S ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick Lazio Thursday sought to rebut the
perception that he has turned a happy cheek to the economic
suffering upstate, asserting that new jobs are being created while
acknowledging that ``the recovery here has not reached every single
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the Buffalo Rotary Club a week after his opponent in
the Senate race, Hillary Rodham Clinton, told the same group that
Lazio was out of touch, he stuck close to a stance that has
generated some debate upstate and has led even some fellow
Republicans to question his approach.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, noting statistics indicating 11,000 new jobs created in
the region during the last 18 months, said, ``It is symptomatic of
a dynamic economy _ of an economy that's changing, that's flexible,
that's adapting, that in the end that is growing.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I know the recovery here has not reached every
single family. I know there is still a lot of work to do, and I
know that the next senator of New York will need to be a leader of
that effort. But the question is: Do we want to build on our recent
accomplishments or do we want to return to the policies that caused
the recessions in the first place?''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio did not lay out a specific plan aimed at the region,
saying his overall plan to cut taxes and encourage partnerships
between the public and private sectors would stimulate the economy.
He said that he would encourage more high-technology businesses to
settle here, and suggested that the region would benefit from a
high-speed rail link to downstate.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the audience expressed impatience, asking for specifics
on what he would do as senator.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Mills, who would not give his party affiliation but said
he had not decided whom to vote for in November, told Lazio that he
had spent too much time telling the group what ``disqualifies your
opponent rather than what qualifies you.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has spent the past few days emphasizing his tax-cut plan
in speeches, but he no longer assigns a figure to it. When he
unveiled it in a speech last month, he said it would amount to $776
billion over the next decade, but Democrats and news reports
suggested the figure was closer to $1 trillion, putting it in line
with the one proposed byGov. George W. Bush. Lazio's aides have
since conceded that some of the figures he used were outdated,
though he has stood by the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's latest swing through the state, which began Wednesday
and concludes Saturday, is a prelude to a high-energy drive to
secure the upstate vote, his strategists said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the region is traditionally Republican, polls _ both
independent and Lazio's _ suggest that Clinton poses a strong
challenge after heavily campaigning here with the message that the
upstate economy is hurting and that she will focus on fixing it.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's assistants said he would spend time upstate next month,
focusing on potential supporters of Vice President Al Gore who tell
pollsters they are undecided on a choice for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who says they support Gore but are undecided in this
race does not want to vote for Hillary Clinton,'' a Lazio aide
said. ``They are looking for a reason not to vote for Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides said he had been hurt by commercials from Clinton
and her supporters that have hampered his efforts to tell voters
who he is.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has complained that the advertisements have distorted his
record in Congress, and on this trip he has made an effort to
correct what he considers misconceptions, especially regarding
Medicare. Clinton's supporters have run commercials saying that
Lazio voted to cut Medicare by $270 billion: Lazio instead voted to
cut the rate of growth in the program, a position Clinton has also
supported. In his speeches, Lazio has told people not to pay
attention to the advertisements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
