<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COWS-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIBERGLASS HERD IS SENT TO MARKET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind., Colo.)  By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They were rustled in the dead of night and sprayed
with graffiti, saddled by children and derided by critics. And
Thursday night the cows of the city's CowParade New York 2000 did
yeoman's service one more time, raising hundreds of thousands of
dollars for charity.
</P>
<P>
   As featured cows rose up and down on hydraulic lifts in the
ornate hall of Cipriani 42nd Street, a sold-out crowd that had paid
up to $350 per ticket bid enthusiastically, with most of the cows
going for several times their estimates.
</P>
<P>
   By 9:30 p.m., 49 cows had been sold for a total of nearly a
million dollars, with the highest bid of $60,000 going to Adele
Moros' ``Tiffany Cow.'' A cow by the pop artist Peter Max went for
$24,000, as did a cow that unfolds into a real piano. The president
of a chain of Japanese steakhouses, Tony Fujita, bought two cows,
paying $48,000 for ``Lady Cowdiva,'' a ladylike cow seated atop a
Holstein, by Tim Gaydos, and $24,000 for ``La Vie Bovine'' by Matt
Maraffi.
</P>
<P>
   For the auction, a committee selected 75 of the 500 life-size
cows, each sponsored by a corporation, civic group, cultural
institution or other organization, which had been deployed in
public spaces during the summer, with most of them, 480, in
Manhattan. Since Labor Day, the colorful herd has been corralled in
the Helmsley Building on Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the remaining 425 cows, including one that was signed by
the cast of the television show ``Survivor,'' are being sold on
Amazon.com in an auction that began at 12:01 a.m. Friday. Bidding
closes on Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds will benefit charities chosen by the city, including
the City Parks Foundation, God's Love We Deliver, Hale House,
Citymeals-on-Wheels, New Yorkers for Children and the Center for
Arts Education, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   Though each artist began with one of only three fiberglass cow
models (standing, grazing or seated), the designs ranged widely,
from cheesy to conceptual. Among the crowd pleasers was a ``Cowch
Potato'' plopped on a sofa in Grand Central Terminal. On the
head-scratching side, there was ``Ceci n'est pas une vache''
(``this is not a cow,'' a reference to a painting by Rene Magritte,
``Ceci n'est pas une pipe'').
</P>
<P>
   There were cows transformed into slinky-toys, cows covered in
ersatz moola and a cow catching a Frisbee in its mouth. But there
were no sliced cows a la Damien Hirst, the British artist whose
work in ``Sensation,'' at the Brooklyn Museum of Art, caused a stir
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The cows were popular with tourists but derided by many locals,
who pointed out that New York is not the cow town that Chicago, the
first city in the United States to play host to a cow parade, can
claim to be.
</P>
<P>
   Art critics, too, bemoaned what they called the hokey designs
and the hackneyed puns in the titles. (``Moo York'' was used a
dozen times.) Roberta Smith, writing in The New York Times, located
the hoofed creations ``somewhere between a Happening and an art
class at summer camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Such slings and arrows, it seems, placed Pat Smith, a spokesman
for CowParade Holdings, Inc., on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In answer to the question, `Is this really art?''' he wrote to
a reporter, ``we offer representatives from Phillips Auctioneers,
the third-largest auction house in the world, which is lending its
prestige to this event and providing its services at no charge.''
</P>
<P>
   If the past is any guide, CowParade Holdings, the company
responsible for the cow parade, need not have feared negative
appraisals. In Chicago, an auction of 147 cows generated $3.5
million for charity, according to Jerry Elbaum, CowParade's
president. Cows expected to go for $2,000 to $5,000 went for $8,500
to $110,000 (for a cow decorated with the handprints of patients at
a children's hospital).
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey spent $110,000 on three cows. But she had a place
to put them: her Indiana farm. Where, on the other hand, would the
average New York auctiongoer put one of the statues?
</P>
<P>
   Barbi Benton, the actress and singer, hopes to acquire 20 cows
for her 40-acre sculpture garden in Aspen, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Mendell, a senior officer at Chase Manhattan Bank, said
that if he bid successfully on the ``Twin Cowers,'' two cows
modeled after the World Trade Center, he would put them in his
summer house. ``Pound Ridge, New York,'' he said. ``Everybody has a
summer house, don't they?''
</P>
<P>
   A couple from Woodcliff Lake, N.J., said that their $26,000 cow,
``Hugs and Smooches,'' which the artist, Susan Rooney, had covered
with X's and O's, was destined to stand by their pool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
