<DOCNO> NYT20000928.0513 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-28 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6060 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-OLYVOL-LADN-(SLAN     09-28 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYVOL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BEARS UP IN SEMIFINAL LOSS TO RUSSIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ It started off as a mismatch, as the
Russians, with eight players on their women's volleyball roster
taller than the United States' tallest player, were connecting on
one spike after another and blocking every shot that came their
way.
</P>
<P>
   And at the conclusion of the semifinal proceedings Thursday
night, two of the youngest American performers, Logan Tom and Kerri
Walsh, wept. The rest of their teammates were similarly distraught.
</P>
<P>
   Not, mind you, because they were embarrassed by the Russians,
ranked second in the world behind Cuba and undefeated in these
Games. They were downcast because they felt they should have beaten
the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   And, for a tantalizing few moments in the decisive fifth game of
what turned into a thrilling match, it seemed that the ol'
David-Goliath saga would repeat itself as the Americans actually
held a 7-6 lead and had the momentum and the crowd at the Sydney
Entertainment Center solidly on their side.
</P>
<P>
   But then harsh reality set in _ i.e., the Russians' overwhelming
height advantage _ and the gallant Americans finally unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just let it get away,'' said Danielle Scott after the
Russians pulled away in that final game and emerged with a 25-15,
23-25, 25-15, 26-28, 15-8 victory that almost caused their volatile
coach, Nikolai Karpol, a nervous breakdown. ``We're very
disappointed. We wanted to win the gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't come up with the defensive stops in that last
game, and they did,'' said Walsh. ``We had to play a great game to
beat them and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans might not have played extraordinarily well, but
they played with a fierce determination and did something only Cuba
has been able to do in this tournament _ extend the Russians to
five games.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. faced match point twice in the fourth game _ it trailed
at one point 15-9 _ but somehow avoided certain defeat with clutch
shots by Scott and Tom and terrific defensive plays by Scott, Walsh
and Heather Brown.
</P>
<P>
   At this juncture, the crowd, composed of a lot of Brazilian fans
who had watched their team beaten earlier by Cuba, was cheering
loudly for the heavily underdog Americans. And Karpol, sort of a
Russian version of Bobby Knight, was stomping around the sidelines,
screaming at his women for not being able to put away the U.S.
team.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Karpol's eruption, which inspired boos, was
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians had an overwhelming frontline advantage with
6-foot-4 Elena Godina, their best player, 6-3 Evguenia Artamonova
and 6-3 Anastassia Belikova _ they combined for 61 kills _ and four
of their players had powerful jump serves.
</P>
<P>
   They easily should have disposed of an American team that not
only lacked size _ Danielle Scott (a team-high 16 kills) was its
tallest player at 6-2 _ but also offensive cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. women didn't lack resilience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give the Russians credit,'' U.S. coach Mick Haley
said. ``They're good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians are good, but the Americans weren't bad, either,
despite their obvious shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish I would have played a better game,'' said Tara
Cross-Battle, who contributed a couple of big blocks in that tense
fourth game that was decided on a Logan Tom kill. ``. . .Now we
just have to concentrate on winning the bronze medal.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team will play Brazil Saturday for that honor, but,
clearly, the American players thought for a time Thursday night
that they were destined to meet Cuba for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave it our best,'' said Cross-Battle. ``We left our hearts
on the court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-00 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
